[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Introduction"]
[Black "Who this course is for and how it should be studied"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
{ Who is this course for? I expect to have a lot newer players around because the London System is known as an 'easy opening' to start your chess journey with. However, despite its simplicity, the London System can be a deadly weapon at the very top level of chess too, so together with the best engines like Leela and Stockfish @@StartBracket@@and the help of cloud-based super computers@@EndBracket@@ I came up with a bunch of novel ideas to make the London System a very dangerous weapon at all levels.How should this course be studied? The classical method is always reasonable. Taking each chapter one by one and eventually navigating through the whole information is for sure a solid approach. However, there are a few ways which can make the whole process a bit more efficient, based on the rating range that you are in. For the sake of simplicity we are going to split the course into two categories of players: between 0-1800 and 1800+ @@StartBracket@@I think the course could serve very well in Grandmaster practise too@@EndBracket@@.     Plan I @@StartBracket@@0-1800@@EndBracket@@: Mastering Fundamentals ➼ Typical Pawn Structures ➼ Quickstarter Guide ➼ The Chigorin Defense ➼ The Englund Gambit ➼ The Copycat ➼ Typical Tactics ➼ Model Games  In my opinion these are the best chapters to start with because the mentioned theory chapters are played A LOT in this rating range. Once you get a good understanding of these chapters you can move on to the rest of the course, but you have already created a solid foundation and you will be prepared against the most common replies.    Observation: ➼ Of course you will occassionaly run into openings like King's Indian Defense/Dutch/ Benoni, but focusing on those chapters won't be the most efficient strategy for your rating range because the other lines are simply way more popular. I recommend you mainly focus on the short lines recommended in the Quickstarter Guide against these lines @@StartBracket@@this way you won't be completely out of book and won't be that easy for other players to exploit you@@EndBracket@@.    Plan II @@StartBracket@@1800+@@EndBracket@@: ALL Queen's Gambit Declined Chapters ➼ Slav Defense ➼ Copycat ➼ King's Indian Defense/Grunfeld Defense ➼ Queen's Indian Defense ➼ Benoni Defense ➼ Dutch Defense ➼ Typical Tactics ➼ Model Games ➼ Thematic Maneuvers ➼ Typical Endgames    Disclaimer: all chapters are equally important. I put them in order of how often I think you will come across any of these lines.  The course has plenty of model games covered, but in order to really step up your game I highly recommend studying the London games of the following players:    Berkes Ferenc  Kamsky Gata  Nihal Sarin  Grachev Boris  Sedlak Nikola  Gukesh Dommaraju  Sadhwani Raunak  Demchenko Anton  Firouzja Alireza  Carlsen Magnus  Eric Rosen  Tang Andrew. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Introduction"]
[Black "Move order against 1...d5"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3
{ Against 1... d5 this is by far the most accurate move order, even though most new London players start by developing the bishop @@StartBracket@@some strong Grandmasters included@@EndBracket@@. The main point is that against  2.Bf4  , the move  2...c5!  could be annoying because Black has some plans to play with ...f6 instead of the standard ...Nf6! In order to get a better understanding I will just attach two of the most annoying lines:   2.Bf4  c5  3.e3  Nc6  4.c3  This used to be played by Magnus Carlsen around 2016-2017 when the London System was just starting to get played at the very top level. Nowadays Black has many ways to get a reasonable position and I will just mention what I personally find to be the most annoying lines.   @@StartBracket@@  4.Nf3  tries to transpose back into the normal lines after 4...Nf6 5.Nbd2 but Black has an additional plan to play with ...f6!  4...cxd4  5.exd4  Bf5  6.c3  e6  7.Qb3  Qd7  8.Nbd2  f6∞  Threatening to push ...g5 followed by ...h5 ➼ this line is quite problematic. Keep in mind that none of this is possible after 2.Nf3 because Black will have to commit with ...Nf6! @@EndBracket@@  4...Qb6  This became more more and popular recently because Black discovered a new resource.   4...Bf5!?  is another sound setup for Black ➼ focusing on a quick ...Qb6 plan.  5.Nd2  e6  6.Ngf3  Qb6  7.Qb3  c4  8.Qxb6  axb6=  With a pleasant endgame for Black.  5.Qb3  c4  6.Qc2  e5!  This pawn sacrifice is the latest trend!   The direct  6...Bf5  is simply bad after  7.Qxf5  Qxb2  8.Qxd5  Qxa1  9.Qb5!  and White is clearly better because Black's queen is stuck in the corner. The point of sacrificing the pawn with 6...e5 is to avoid Qxd5!  7.dxe5  Bf5∞  With a complicated position after  8.Qc1  g5!?  Notice that  8.Qxf5  Qxb2!  simply wins for Black this time because there is no Qxd5 like after the direct 6...Bf5. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Introduction"]
[Black "Move order against 1...Nf6"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6
{ While there is not such a huge difference between  2.Bf4  and  2.Nf3  , I want to give you a good overview of what the options are for both sides. }
2. Bf4
{ This allows us to meet  2...c5  with  3.e3  ➼ inviting Black to go back into the normal lines.  3.e4!?  could be an interesting way to deal with the quick ...c5!?  but it's not really that thematic nor easy to play for White @@StartBracket@@I only recommend it to more experienced players@@EndBracket@@. Additionally, after 2. Bf4 White has an interesting option to meet  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pppppppp/5n2/8/3P1B2/8/PPP1PPPP/RN1QKBNR b KQkq - 2 2@@EndFEN@@  2...g6  with  3.Nc3!?  because the Jobava London works quite well against the King's Indian/Grunfeld. The Jobava London is not part of this repertoire because we are focusing on the positional setup, but it is an idea for a future update of the course.   If you start with  2.Nf3  , the line  2...c5  3.d5  b5!?  could lead to a pretty complicated game that has nothing to do with the London System @@StartBracket@@which is one of the main reasons that made me recommend 2.Bf4@@EndBracket@@.   To sum things up,  2.Bf4  avoids the crazy ...c5-b5 line ➼ leading to a standard London position, while  2.Nf3  could be a smart choice against players that only go  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  Nf6  2.Bf4  c5  3.e3  Qb6  because this way you can avoid a line that if played well, might lead to a forced draw. }
