{ Welcome to Mastering Fundamentals! This chapter is dedicated to players below 1500 blitz on chess.com. If you are rated above 1500, this chapter could still be useful, but you might already be familiar with most of the concepts @@StartBracket@@you let me know in the comments if that was the case!@@EndBracket@@.   I made a collection of the most important basic concepts that every beginner should understand before doing anything else! What makes this chapter special compared to other 'general improvement books' is that all the positions of interest are coming from the London System ➼ making it easier to apply in your own games.   I recommend you simply read these files and then have a look at the model games that they will link you to. If you have any questions make sure to let me know in the comments and I will clarify as fast as I can. }
1. -- *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Mastering Fundamentals"]
[Black "What is a 'good' bishop?"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Bf4 e6 4. e3 Bd6 5. Nbd2 b6 6. c3 Bxf4 7. exf4 Bb7 8.
Bd3 Nbd7 9. O-O O-O 10. Re1
{ White is slightly better simply due to the fact that the d3-bishop is more active than the b7-bishop, which is restricted by the d5-pawn. We are going to continue by playing Ne5, and then we have an interesting plan to go Qf3, followed by Qh3 with interesting play on the kingside. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Mastering Fundamentals"]
[Black "How to spot and fix a 'bad' bishop"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Bf4 c5 4. e3 Nc6 5. Nbd2 e6 6. c3 Bd6 7. Bg3 O-O 8. Bd3
Re8 9. Ne5 Qc7
{ Black has just played ...Qc7 ➼ putting pressure on the e5-knight. This is a very common position arising from the Queen's Gambit Declined with a quick ...e6, ...Bd6. }
10. f4
{ This is an amazing move that supports the e5-knight. It's simply a 'knightmare' for our opponent because the e5-knight feels like a thorn in Black's position. Although this is the right call, we also have to keep an eye on the potential drawbacks after playing this move which is, in our case, that ➼ the g3-bishop has been restricted!To be honest, technically speaking, we can't really call it a bad bishop since it can be improved, but after discussing this theme with a lot of my students, I realized that a lot of them forget to optimize the g3-bishop ➼ which is quite passive if it remains on the g3-square. }
10... b6 11. O-O { We almost always castle short in these positions. } 11...
Bb7 12. Bh4
{ After this simple move, the dark-squared bishop suddenly becomes very active. This is a classic example of how you can maximize the potential of your pieces by doing simple things, which most beginners miss because they don't have solid fundamentals. A lot of players simply look for concrete lines while they haven't optimized their position with this kind of simple move.   12.Ndf3?!  This is a common mistake that a lot of my students  have made. I guess it looks pretty logical with the idea to play Nxc6 and then put the second knight to e5 ➼ but the issue with this plan is that we are giving Black full control over the e4-square.  12...Ne4⇆  Broadly speaking, this is the issue when playing Ndf3! Black is ready to kick the e5-knight with ...f6 on the next move. When that happens, White generally has no advantage.   12.Qc2?!  This is another common mistake that I see @@StartBracket@@not only in this structure but in general@@EndBracket@@. The queen is simply not ideally placed on c2 because it can be vulnerable to tactics along the c-file, and isn't achieving its full potential due to being behind the bishop. As an alternative, the queen is much better on e2 most of the time  @@StartBracket@@though not in this particular pawn structure@@EndBracket@@.  12...Ne7!  This maneuver is quite problematic for us now. Not to mention Black could have started with 12...c4 as well.  13.Bh4  c4!  Attacking the d3-bishop. Notice that we don't have the typical retreat Bc2 because the queen is misplaced!  14.Be2  Nf5!   With the idea to meet  15.Bxf6  by going  15...Nxe3!  15.Bf2  Be7∞  With ...Nd6 followed by ...Nfe4, and Black is very comfortable. To be honest, I don't really expect your opponents to be aware of this plan @@StartBracket@@unless you are playing a master or someone really well prepared@@EndBracket@@, but it's good to be familiar with these types of ideas. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Mastering Fundamentals"]
[Black "The most important plan against ...d5-lines!"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Bf4 e6 4. e3 Bd6 5. Nbd2 O-O 6. c3 c5 7. Bd3 Qc7 8. Bxd6
Qxd6 9. Ne5
{ This is our main plan against the ...d5 lines. The whole London System game plan against these variations is weighted around the e5-square. If Black manages to take control over the e5-square, that will usually result in an equal game. }
9... b6 { Preparing ...Bb7/Ba6 ideas. } 10. f4
{ The e5-knight is very annoying for Black because there is not an easy way to get rid of it. In order to get a better feeling for these positions, make sure to check out the 'Reversed Stonewall structure' and the model endgame between Carlsen-Sunilduth Lyna, 2020. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Mastering Fundamentals"]
[Black "Knight on the rim is grim"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Bf4 c6 4. e3 Nh5 5. Be5 Nd7 6. c4 e6 7. Nc3 Nxe5 8. dxe5
{ This is a theoretical position that we can get after Black hunts our bishop with ...Nh5! Our last move was important because the e5-pawn is doing a great job ➼ trapping Black's knight on the rim. Generally speaking ➼ the knight on the rim is bad because it controls less squares compared to a 'centrally' placed knight. While the knight on the rim is generally quite passive, it can also be a target, as in our position, where White already has a threat of winning the knight by pushing g4! }
