[White "Mastering Fundamentals"]
[Black "What is a 'backward' pawn?"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 c5 2. d5 e6 3. Nc3 exd5 4. Nxd5 Nf6 5. e4 Nxd5 6. Qxd5 d6 7. Bc4 Qc7 8.
Ne2 Be6 9. Qd3 Bxc4 10. Qxc4 Be7 11. Bf4 O-O 12. O-O Nc6
{ This is a typical position coming from the 1...c5 Benoni. } 13. Rad1
{ White has a long-term initiative thanks to the 'backward' d6-pawn. The backward pawn is named like that because it can't be defended by any other pawns ➼ which makes it an easy target and a long-term weakness. White has a simple plan to double up the rooks on the d-file ➼ with huge pressure on the d6-pawn. }
