Nxf5 exf5 9. c3 O-O 10. Be2 Ne4 11. Nxe4 fxe4 12. Qb3 Qd7 13. O-O Rfd8 14. Rfd1
{ This is a typical structure coming from @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.Nf3  Nf6  3.Bf4  c5  4.e3  Nc6  5.Nbd2  Bf5  6.dxc5!  Black's position is more active compared to the previous case, but the d5-pawn is a juicy target for White because it can't be protected by any other pawns. Still, this version is less bad for Black than the regular 'backward' pawn because Black has more space which can be used to double up the rooks and protect the advanced backward pawn ➼ but we can draw a pretty simple conclusion ➼ White has a target, and Black does not. }
