[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Mastering Fundamentals"]
[Black "Life changing: Recapturing towards the center"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Bf4 c5 4. e3 Nc6 5. Nbd2 e6 6. c3 Bd6 7. Bg3 Bxg3
{ This is a very typical scenario after Black plays ...Bd6! } 8. hxg3
{ This is the right call 99% of the time ➼ opening up the rook with pressure on the kingside. Taking fxg3 is very situational, and it can be good sometimes if you have a rook placed on f1, and then you can go for concrete play. Keep in mind that fxg3 is very risky from a strategical perspective, and you should play it only if you know what you are doing!In order to see how White puts pressure in this structure, make sure to check out the model game between Carlsen-Ghaem Maghami, 2016. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Mastering Fundamentals"]
[Black "The key way to recapture in the center"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Bf4 c5 4. e3 Nc6 5. Nbd2 Bg4 6. c3 cxd4
{ This is a typical situation arising from the QGD without 5...e6. } 7. exd4
{ This is by far the best move, and it leads to an interesting situation because we are breaking a general rule which says that 'we should recapture towards the center.' The problem with  7.cxd4  is that we are getting into a situation where Black's c6-knight is better placed than the d2-knight, and we are vulnerable to ...Rc8-Nb4 ideas, not to mention that it will be very tricky for us to generate any play in that symmetrical structure. Just remember that whenever Black goes ...c5 followed by ...cxd4, we will be capturing exd4 99% of the time.Going cxd4 is very situational, and it can sometimes be interesting, as shown by Kamsky on some occasions in the Queen's Indian, but it's definitely a very tricky decision to make, which I don't think gives us any edge compared to the standard exd4. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Mastering Fundamentals"]
[Black "How to effectively use 'the pin'"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Bf4 Nc6 4. e3 Bf5
{ This is a super common position for the lower-rated games, which has been covered in the 'Chigorin Defense'. }
5. Bb5
{ Using the 'pin!' Black's knight is unable to move which makes it vulnerable. This is a powerful tactical idea that can be used not only against the enemy king, but also against pieces that are more valuable than the pinned one. }
5... e6 { This is Black's most common answer. } 6. Ne5
{ Increasing the pressure on the pinned knight! Black is unable to defend the c6-knight, which shows the potential of the pin. }
