[Black "What are 'doubled pawns' & how to exploit them"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Bf4 c5 4. e3 Nc6 5. Nbd2 Bg4 6. c3 cxd4 7. exd4 e6 8.
Qb3 Qb6 9. Qxb6 axb6 10. Bd3 Nh5
{ This is a typical structure arising after Black reacts to Qb3 by going ...Qb6! Black manages to nullify White's pressure against the b7-pawn, but in return, they have to allow the doubled pawns. These pawns are generally a weakness because they can be easier to target. Moreover, it will be much harder to create a passed pawn. }
11. Bc7
{ Highlighting the weakness of the doubled pawns. Black is unable to protect the b6-pawn. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Mastering Fundamentals"]
[Black "What are 'Tripled Pawns'?"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Bf4 Nc6 4. e3 Bf5 5. Bb5 a6 6. Bxc6+ bxc6 7. c4 dxc4
{ This position can arise from the Chigorin Defense. The tripled pawns are generally a huge weakness because they can't protect each other and will most likely become easy targets. }
8. Qa4
{ After this move, White wins back the pawn while keeping a better position. Keep in mind that after we collect one of the pawns, Black will remain with the 'doubled pawns,' which will be a long-term weakness. }
