[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Mastering Fundamentals"]
[Black "What is a 'hook'? "]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Bf4 Nc6 4. e3 e6 5. Nbd2 Bd6 6. c3 Bxf4 7. exf4 O-O 8.
Bd3 a6 9. Ne5 Nxe5 10. fxe5 Nd7 11. Qh5 g6
{ This is a typical position after White has just played Qh5 ➼ threatening checkmate on h7 and forcing Black to create a weakness. }
12. Qh6
{ White has a big initiative because we can push h4-h5 ➼ taking advantage of the g6-hook. We call the g6-pawn a 'hook' because it gives us the chance to deliver a powerful pawn break. The reason why h4-h5 is so powerful is that Black is unable to stop us from opening up the h-file for the rook.   Imagine we go back two moves, and instead of @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/1ppn1ppp/p3p3/3pP3/3P4/2PB4/PP1N1PPP/R2QK2R w KQ - 1 11@@EndFEN@@  11.Qh5  , we start by pushing  11.h4  directly.  The difference is that even if we get the pawn all the way to h6 ➼ Black is able to dodge the attack by pushing ...g6! This is no longer the case when we have the 'hook!' }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Mastering Fundamentals"]
[Black "Opposite side castling: one simple rule!"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Bf4 c5 4. e3 Nc6 5. Nbd2 e6 6. c3 cxd4 7. exd4 Bd6 8.
Bg3 Bxg3 9. hxg3 Bd7 10. Bd3 Qc7 11. O-O O-O-O 12. Re1 h5
{ It is not very often that we get opposite-side castling in the London System, but it's for sure a very common scenario in general ➼ which you need to be familiar with! }
13. b4
{ When there is opposite castling, it's a race! Every tempo becomes much more valuable, and it is very common to even sacrifice pawns to open up lines faster for the attack. Taking a defensive position can usually be fatal. Imagine this is like two boxers fighting ➼ if one is just taking punches, it normally doesn't end well. That is why we have to strike back and create our own attack. Of course, when our opponent has a huge threat, we can pause and defend against it, but the point is to always have your own threats on the other side of the board. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Mastering Fundamentals"]
[Black "Opposite-coloured bishops middlegame strategy"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4 d5 3. e3 c5 4. Nf3 Nc6 5. Nbd2 Nh5 6. dxc5 Nxf4 7. exf4 Qa5 8.
Bd3 Qxc5 9. O-O g6 10. Nb3 Qd6 11. Qd2 Bg7 12. c3 O-O 13. Rfe1 Bg4 14. Qe3 Bxf3
15. Qxf3 e6
{ We have a typical position coming from the topical variation @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.Nf3  Nf6  3.Bf4  c5  4.e3  Nc6  5.Nbd2  Nh5  . The main factor that we need to notice is the presence of the opposite-colored bishops. }
16. h4
{ This should be the first move that comes to mind, and you can play it instantly! Before you start thinking that this is how Alpha Zero changed chess or some other sophisticated answer, let me make something clear.As mentioned earlier, we have a position with opposite-colored bishops ➼ in this type of middlegame, the side that's attacking will have very good chances to succeed. Imagine we will be opening up the kingside and Black is simply unable to defend on the light squares. In some books, authors go as far as saying that it feels like you are attacking with an extra piece. While there is a bit of truth behind that, I would take a more balanced approach since it really depends on the specific position.Now that you understand this, it becomes very clear why Magnus played 16.h4! and why you should be making such moves instantly. There was simply no other idea to create any play. To see how Magnus builds up the initiative and scores a crushing victory, make sure to check out the model game between Carlsen-Caruana, 2020. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Mastering Fundamentals"]
[Black "What is a 'semi-open' file?"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Bf4 c5 4. e3 Nc6 5. Nbd2 cxd4 6. exd4 Bg4 7. c3 e6 8.
Qb3 Qc8 9. Bd3 Be7 10. O-O O-O 11. Rae1 Bh5 12. Ne5 Nxe5 13. Bxe5 Bg6 14. Bxg6
hxg6 15. f4 Qc6
{ This is a typical position that stems from the QGD without 5...e6. } 16. Re3
{ White is able to rook lift thanks to the semi-open e-file. The semi-open file is almost like an open file, but your opponent has a pawn on it ➼ generally in his camp. Of course, the traditional open files are even better, but semi-open files should not be neglected ➼ especially when there are no open files on the board.Here we have a very good example where White is able to take over the initiative thanks to this rook lift preparing Rh3 ➼ using another semi-open file to generate a dangerous attack against Black's king. }
