[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Mastering Fundamentals"]
[Black "How can 'doubled pawns' be an asset and not a weakness?"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Bf4 Bf5 4. e3 e6 5. Bd3 Bxd3
{ This is a theoretical position arising from the 'Copycat' chapter. } 6. cxd3
{ While the doubled pawns are a weakness more often than not ➼ here we have an example of 'good doubled pawns.' To better grasp that concept, you have to understand that weakness is something that your opponent can attack. If your opponent has no threats, then there is no weakness.   We can think of an extreme example coming from the Modern Defense after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  g6  2.d4  Bg7  3.Nc3  c5  4.dxc5  Bxc3+  5.bxc3  Qa5  6.Qd4  when Black does not have enough attacking resources to regain the pawn, and White is better with the tripled pawns. What does this have to do with our London System? Just remember the golden rule: Any pawn/square/piece is a weakness ONLY if your opponent can attack it.   Coming back to the position after  6.cxd3  ➼  White has an easier game with the 'good doubled pawns' because we can push e4 ➼ grabbing space in the center, and we have very good odds to undouble the pawns and dominate the center as in the model game between Muthaiah-Hakobyan, 2018. }
