[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Mastering Fundamentals"]
[Black "What is an outpost and what makes it so special?"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4 g6 3. Nf3 Bg7 4. c3 O-O 5. Nbd2 d6 6. e4 c5 7. dxc5 dxc5 8. h3
Nc6 9. Qc2 Re8 10. Be2 e5 11. Be3 b6 12. Nc4 Qc7 13. Rd1 Rd8 14. O-O Bb7 15.
Bg5 h6 16. Bxf6 Bxf6 17. Ne3 Bg7
{ This is a typical structure arising from the 'King's Indian Defense' when Black goes for ...c5, and we answer with the typical dxc5 as explained in the theory chapter. }
18. Nd5
{ This is the best knight that you can ever get in chess because:  it's central  it's placed on the outpost   But what is an outpost, and why is it such a big deal at all? An outpost is a square on an open file that is controlled by your pawn, and more importantly ➼ the enemy pawns are unable to attack that square. Most of the time, a piece such as the d5-knight can be more valuable than a rook. What makes it really special as an outpost ➼ is that whenever Black tries to capture the d5-knight, it will create a dangerous passed pawn which turns out to be decisive most of the time. }
