[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Mastering Fundamentals"]
[Black "Two minor pieces or rook & pawn - Which one is better & why?"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 d5 3. Bf4 c5 4. e3 Nc6 5. Nbd2 Qb6 6. dxc5 Qxb2 7. Rb1 Qa3 8.
Bb5 g6 9. Ne5 Qxc5 10. c4 Bg7 11. Qa4 dxc4 12. Bxc4 a6 13. Bxf7+ Kf8 14. Nxc6
Qxc6 15. Qxc6 bxc6 16. Bc4 Nd5 17. Bg3 Be6 18. e4 Nc3 19. Bxe6 Nxb1 20. Nxb1
Bd4 21. Ke2 c5 22. Nd2 Kg7 23. Bd5 Ra7 24. Nc4 Re8 25. Rb1 e6 26. Bc6 Rf8 27.
f3 a5
{ This example doesn't have much to do with the London System itself, but it's one of the first things you need to get a solid understanding of when starting to learn the beautiful game of chess. What is better to have? Two minor pieces or a rook and a pawn. This can be a pretty tricky question to answer because if you do the basic math where a minor piece equals three, a rook equals five, and a pawn one @@StartBracket@@so 3+3=5+1@@EndBracket@@, it might give you the false impression that the situation is equal @@StartBracket@@I know in our case Black doesn't have the extra pawn, but the answer would stay relatively the same@@EndBracket@@. }
28. a4
{ White is just completely winning in this endgame with two minor pieces for the rook because there are no open files for Black's rooks, and the minor pieces are placed on active squares. Another important factor is that White still has a rook. Generally, keeping a pair of rooks on the board when you have two minor pieces against a rook will make it much easier to convert. The reason to keep the rook is simply to control the open file that your opponent needs to activate his rook. The only way to get counterplay if you are the defending side with the rook is to have a passed pawn ➼ having the passed pawn will generally even give the rook a better endgame against the two minor pieces.   Now, if we move the discussion to a middlegame with a lot of pieces on the board, the strength of the minor pieces increases against the rooks. A good example is this line coming from the Jobava London after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  Nf6  2.Bf4  g6  3.Nc3  d5  4.e3  Bg7  5.h4  O-O  6.h5  Nxh5  7.Rxh5  gxh5  8.Qxh5  where White is down an exchange but has a much better position because of the kingside pressure. Black is up material, but the key idea is that the rook needs open files. If there are no open files, the rooks are not very effective, as a rule of thumb. }
*

