28. cxb5 Qb6 29. Nc4 Nxc4 30. Bxc4 Rc8 31. Ra6 Qc5 32. Bd3 d5 33. Bf4 Ne4 34.
Be3 d4 35. Bf4 Nc3 36. Re5 Qb4 37. Qxb4 Bxb4 38. g4 g6 39. Kg2 Rcb8 40. Re1 Rd8
41. Bg5 Rdb8 42. Bf4 Rd8 43. Re5 Rdb8 44. Rc6 Nxb5 45. Rd5 Na7 46. Rc1 Re8
{ This comes from a high-profile game played between Levon Aronian and Magnus Carlsen. The battle took place in the Queen's Indian Defense, and Levon managed to trick Magnus with the powerful bishop pair. }
47. Rb1
{ The position is close to losing for Black objectively speaking because of the 'pinned bishop' and White is simply dominating the whole board ➼ because of the bishop pair in an open position. The bishop pair is a very powerful weapon that can win you a lot of games. If the position is open, the bishop pair really starts to snowball, and in many books, they even go as far as saying that it feels close to being up a pawn. This is definitely the case if the bishops have targets! When we are talking about closed positions, the bishops are still incredibly strong most of the time if they have enough space.   We can think about the Maroczy bind that arises after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.Nf3  Nc6  3.d4  cxd4  4.Nxd4  g6  5.c4  Bg7  6.Be3  Nf6  7.Nc3  d6  8.f3  where the f1-bishop is the 'bad bishop' which defends the good pawns. Many players tend to get this wrong and think that the light-squared bishop is bad because of the pawns being placed on the light squares. That is a good general idea, but we have to keep in mind that White has the extra space and the pawns are also restricting the enemy light-squared bishop!In the game, White managed to convert a nice endgame between Aronian-Carlsen, 2021. }
