[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Mastering Fundamentals"]
[Black "What is an 'isolated' pawn & what are 'pawn islands'?"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "6k1/1pq2pp1/p4nb1/3p3p/PQ1N4/2P2PP1/1P5P/5BK1 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ This is a typical endgame arising from the Carlsbad structure after Black tries to free himself by breaking with ...e5! After this pawn break, Black is left with the 'isolated' pawn on d5, which is a weakness in most endgames. We call it isolated because there are no black pawns on the adjacent files, so the pawn feels a bit lonely, and it is generally a target for White's pieces. In this particular case, the d5-pawn can be named Isolated Queen's Pawn or 'IQP.' You might also see it reffered to as 'isolani'.Generally speaking, this structure is favorable for White, with only two 'pawn islands' against three. We call a 'pawn island' pawns that are next to each other but isolated from the rest. To be more specific, White has two pawn islands:  a4,b2,c3 is one pawn island  f3,g3,h2 is the other pawn island.  Black's position is made of three pawn islands:  a6,b7 is one pawn island  d5 is the isolated pawn  f7,g7,h5 is the other pawn island   Generally speaking, the fewer pawn islands, the better because it will be easier to protect your pawns @@StartBracket@@as they are usually protecting each other, which is not the case for an 'isolated' pawn!@@EndBracket@@. }
1. Nb3
{ This was a great move to start with because White has a direct threat of playing Qc5 that leads to very unpleasant endgames for Black. The knight was well placed on d4, but sometimes we neet to make this kind of move in order to make progress.To see how White managed to convert this position and how you should put pressure on the 'isolated' pawn, make sure to check out the model endgame between Kamsky-Quintiliano Pinto, 2021. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Mastering Fundamentals"]
[Black "What is a 'protected passer'?"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "4r3/1b3pk1/p1r1p1p1/1pPp2Pp/3P1K1P/2PBR3/1P3P2/4R3 b - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

1... Rd8
{ This is an 'equal position' if we are counting the pieces, but White is strategically winning thanks to the good vs. bad bishop, plus having the protected passer on c5. The protected passed pawn is a deadly weapon when it comes to endgames ➼ most of the time giving the possessor a winning king and pawn endgame. This is an incredibly useful tool, because in this type of position when you have the protected passed pawn, you can simply trade all the pieces and win the king and pawn endgame.We can try to imagine this structure with only kings on the board and try to evaluate. Let's say Black has ...Ke7 and White Ke5. The endgames are an easy win because we can sacrifice the 'protected passer' by pushing c6-c7 and after Black goes to stop it with ...Kd7 we can infiltrate on the kingside with Kf6 winning Black's pawns one by one. }
2. Ke5
{ Keep in mind that the king becomes an attacking piece in the endgame and it can play a major role in this type of situation. To see how White converted this position make sure to check out the model endgame between Kovacevic-Sprecic, Tuzla 1981. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Mastering Fundamentals"]
[Black "What is an 'outside passer' & how to win with it"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "6k1/5pp1/4p2p/r2bP3/P1p2P2/2K3P1/1R5P/3B4 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ This is a classic example of an outside passer deciding the game. The main factor in this particular case is that White's king is much more active and can support the a-pawn in its advance. }
1. Rb8+
{ Followed by Kb4 next, White wins easily because we are practically attacking with an extra piece since the king becomes a crucial attacker in the endgame @@StartBracket@@as there are no mating threats anymore@@EndBracket@@.  Now I want you to imagine that we have a king and pawn endgame with the same exact pawn structure, but we place Black's king on c5. @@StartFEN@@8/5pp1/4p2p/2k1P3/P1p2P2/2K3P1/7P/8 w - - 1 1@@EndFEN@@ That is a classic win for White thanks to the 'outside passer.' The key idea which makes this a huge asset in the endgames is that White is able to sacrifice the a-pawn ➼ distracting Black's king this way so we can run faster on the other side of the board, collecting the whole kingside. This is a huge idea in king and pawn endgames because the side which benefits from the outside passer usually has a free win. }
