[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Mastering Fundamentals"]
[Black "How to exploit the king in the middle"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "2r1k1r1/pp2qpp1/2b1pn1p/2ppN3/3P2P1/2P1P1Q1/PP1N1PP1/2R2RK1 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ This is a very important topic to understand because it makes it easier to grasp why it's so important to castle quickly  (especially with Black)  . The king in the middle of the board is usually vulnerable, and experienced players will more often than not take advantage of it immediately. }
1. c4
{ You may be wondering what on earth is White doing? I mean, he played c3 first, and then he goes c4? I don't even understand when to play c3 and when to play c2-c4, and White has just played both in a single game?!These are very natural questions that a London System beginner has, and the answer is a lot simpler than you think. It is not really about literally pushing c4! The key rule to follow in these positions when the enemy king is stuck in the center is that in order to take advantage of it, we need to open up the position ➼ so pushing c4 is only a tool that helps us.For more details, check out the model game between Carlsen-Ghaem Maghami, 2016. }
