[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Chigorin: 2... Nf6 3. Bf4 Nc6 with 4... e6"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3
{ This is the most precise move ➼ avoiding the annoying  2.Bf4  c5!  which gives us some headaches as explained in this informational. }
2... Nf6 3. Bf4 Nc6
{ Going for the Chigorin Defense. This is by far the most popular choice below 1600 blitz on chess.com! People that play this generally don't know that they are playing 'The Chigorin Defense' and they are simply trying to get their pieces developed according to the common sense rules @@StartBracket@@Developing their knights before the bishops@@EndBracket@@. }
4. e3
{ Now Black has a choice between three equally popular plans:   4...Bf5  4...Bg4  4...e6. }
4... e6
{ Locking the light-squared bishop inside the pawn chain. Against this plan ➼ it is less effective to go  5.Bb5  because Black can easily deal with the pin by answering  5...Bd7!  Against this plan I suggest we stick with the standard London System play ➼ and we no longer go for the exploitative approach with Bb5. }
5. Nbd2 Bd6 { Offering the bishop trade ➼ this is Black's most common move. }
6. c3
{ Going for an improved version of the Berkes structure after  6...Bxf4  7.exf4  ➼ because Black has a passive light-squared bishop.   @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/ppp2ppp/2nbpn2/3p4/3P1B2/4PN2/PPPN1PPP/R2QKB1R w KQkq - 2 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Bg3  is a perfectly fine alternative, but it could lead to some unnecessary complications. I prefer  6.c3  because I think it's the simplest and most effective approach. Black now has a choice between:  6... O-O  6...Bxf4. }
6... Bxf4
{ This is by far the most common move for Black. My guess is that lower rated players tend to underestimate this structure thinking that 'the doubled pawns should be weak'. That is true...but only if you can attack them! }
7. exf4 O-O 8. Bd3
{ We could already stop here and claim that White is slightly better with the more active light-squared bishop and Ne5 ideas, but we can go a bit deeper still since I think this line is very popular for players below 1600 blitz on chess.com! }
8... Re8
{ For some reason this is the most popular move in the position according to the statistics. I am really struggling to explain why, since it's not even preparing ...e5-break, but I guess we will just have to refute it! }
9. Ne5
{ With a dominating position for White thanks to the active light-squared bishop and the strong e5-knight. }
