{ Now Black has a choice between three equally popular plans:   4...Bf5  4...Bg4  4...e6. }
4... Bf5 5. Bb5
{ This plan works very well against both 4...Bf5 and 4...Bg4! I want you to clearly understand that the light-squared bishop belongs on d3 in most London System positions and that developing it to b5 is a very situational plan. By going for 5.Bb5 we are trying to exploit the fact that Black has committed with ...Nf6. There are no longer any ...Nge7 ideas to protect the c6-knight after we play Ne5!, like they could do after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.Nf3  Nc6  3.Bf4  Bf5  4.e3  e6  5.Bb5  Bd6  6.Ne5  Nge7!  and Black is safe.Now Black has a choice between two main moves:  5... e6  5...a6. }
5... e6
{ This is the most common move for Black ➼ giving White a close to winning position as early as move six!   If  5...a6  6.Bxc6+!  bxc6  7.c4!  with Qa4 followed by Ne5 White has pressure on the c6-pawn. }
6. Ne5
{ After this move Black lacks a good way to protect the c6-knight. This is the whole point behind 5.Bb5! }
6... Bd6
{ This is Black's most common answer. They usually just give up on the exchange! }
7. Nxc6 bxc6
{ Usually people just give up on the exchange. 1 out of 15 times someone plays  7...Qd7  8.Nxa7!  c6  9.Nxc6  bxc6  10.Bd3  with two extra pawns for White. }
8. Bxc6+
{ Collecting the a8-rook next with a winning position for White thanks to the extra exchange. This motif is incredibly common and I expect you to start a lot of games like this if you are playing below 1600 on chess.com blitz. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Copycat: 2...Bg4"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3
{ This is the most precise move ➼ avoiding the annoying  2.Bf4  c5!  which gives us some headaches as explained in this informational. }
2... Bg4
{ This is a typical mistake made in lower rated games. Black is trying to unbalance White's structure with ...Bxf3 in order to avoid the standard London System gameplay. In terms of popularity ➼ this is as common as 2...c5 @@StartBracket@@The Tarrasch Defense@@EndBracket@@, so we need to be aware of it because I've noticed my students face this move quite regularly. }
3. Ne5
{ This is the key move that a lot of London System beginners are missing! White gets a very dangerous initiative because the enemy light-squared bishop becomes a target. }
3... Bh5 { This move allows White to go for quick kingside play. } 4. g4 Bg6 5.
h4
{ Threatening to push h5 ➼ trapping the g6-bishop! Black does not have a good way to deal with this move. }
5... h6 6. Nxg6 fxg6 7. Qd3
{ Attacking Black's biggest weakness ➼ the g6-pawn! After Black defends, we can continue with Nc3-Bg2 followed by the e4-break. }
