[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "The quick 3...e6/4...Bd6: 5...Bxf4"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3
{ This is the most precise move ➼ avoiding the annoying  2.Bf4  c5!  which gives us some headaches as explained in this informational. }
2... Nf6 3. Bf4 e6 4. e3 Bd6
{ Playing ...Bd6 without ...c5 is a solid approach for Black. The main difference is that 5.Bg3 is no longer such a good move and White has a choice between:  5.Nbd2 @@StartBracket@@going for the Berkes structure@@EndBracket@@  5.Ne5!? @@StartBracket@@going for a double-edged fight@@EndBracket@@. }
5. Nbd2
{ This is the best try for White.  5.Bg3  gives Black a number of interesting tries such as  5...O-O  6.Nbd2  c5  7.c3  Qc7  8.Bd3  Nbd7  followed by ...e5! or  5...O-O  6.Nbd2  b6  7.Bd3  Bb7  8.c3  Ne4  with a very solid position for Black.   5.Ne5  could be an interesting alternative if you want to avoid the Berkes Structure ➼ leading to a double-edged game. }
5... Bxf4
{ This is a solid variation for Black. If played well, this can be pretty annoying, but overall I think this structure is easier to play for White. }
6. exf4 { Entering the Berkes structure! } 6... O-O 7. c3
{ Staying very flexible. This move is played with the idea to meet  7...b6  with  8.h4! }
7... c5
{ This line could equalize if Black plays very precise ➼ otherwise White gets a pleasant position. }
8. dxc5 Qc7
{ This is the trick to regain the pawn. Black is attacking both c5 and f4. } 9.
g3 { This is the standard way to protect the f4-pawn. } 9... Qxc5
{ This is by far the most common move in online chess. } 10. Bd3
{ This is the ideal square for the light-squared bishop in the Berkes structure. }
10... Nc6 11. O-O Bd7 12. Re1 { Activating the rook. } 12... Rfd8 13. Qe2
{ This is the ideal square for the queen in the Berkes structure. } 13... Rac8
14. Rad1
{ With a typical advantage for White in the Berkes structure. We can play Bb1 followed by Nb3-Nbd4, Nf3-Ne5 and ideas to push on the kingside with h4-h5 and g4-g5. White won a smooth game between Moroni,L @@StartBracket@@2564@@EndBracket@@-Morefield,J @@StartBracket@@2300@@EndBracket@@ Chess.com INT 2019. }
