1. d4 d5 2. Nf3
{ This is the most precise move ➼ avoiding the annoying  2.Bf4  c5!  which gives us some headaches as explained in this informational. }
2... Nf6 3. Bf4 c5 4. e3 Nc6 5. Nbd2
{ This is the key move to start with. A common mistake that most of the London System players make is  5.c3  allowing  5...Qb6  with a good version for Black. }
5... Bg4 { This is one of Black's most solid replies. } 6. c3 e6 7. Qb3
{ Attacking the b7-pawn ➼ This is a common theme when Black develops the light-squared bishop in the ...c5 lines. }
7... Qc8
{ This is the main move in OTB. This is the safest square for the queen because  7...Qd7  8.Bb5!  is a bit problematic, and also the endgames arising from the @@StartFEN@@r2qkb1r/pp3ppp/2n1pn2/2pp4/3P1Bb1/1QP1PN2/PP1N1PPP/R3KB1R b KQkq - 1 7@@EndFEN@@  7...Qb6  lines are not very fun to play for Black. }
8. Nh4
{ This was recently implemented by Aronian and Demchenko. This is the most serious attempt to put the ...Bg4-lines under a question mark. White's plan is to advance on the kingside with h3-g4 and win the bishop pair.   An alternative could be  8.h3  followed by g4 which could lead to similar positions, but I prefer 8.Nh4 because it avoids ...Bf5. }
8... Be7 9. h3 Bh5 10. g4 Bg6 11. Nxg6 { Eliminating the bishop. } 11... hxg6
12. Be2
{ We can continue with Kf1-Kg2 and White has pressure on the kingside based on the h4-h5 push. }
