1. d4 d5 2. Nf3
{ This is the most precise move ➼ avoiding the annoying  2.Bf4  c5!  which gives us some headaches as explained in this informational. }
2... Nf6 3. Bf4 c5 4. e3 Nc6 5. Nbd2
{ This is the key move to start with. A common mistake that most of the London System players make is  5.c3  allowing  5...Qb6  with a good version for Black. }
5... Bg4 { This is one of Black's most solid replies. } 6. c3 cxd4
{ This is played in order to transpose back into the Caro Kann. } 7. exd4 e6 8.
Qb3
{ Attacking the b7-pawn and breaking the pin ➼ This is a common theme when Black develops the light-squared bishop in the ...c5 lines. }
8... Qc8 { This is the main move for Black in OTB. } 9. Bd3 Be7 10. O-O
{ Here Black has two main plans:  10...O-O  10...Bh5 @@StartBracket@@delaying ...O-O and intending to play ...Bg6@@EndBracket@@. }
10... O-O 11. Rfe1 { Activating the rook. } 11... Bh5 12. h3
{ This move is evil. The trick is that Black is lacking any useful moves! It is important to notice that  12.Ne5  would have made Black's life easier because they had more obvious moves as answer to that. I am not saying Ne5 is a bad move, I just want you to pay attention to these subtle details because they differentiate a good London player from an average one. }
12... a6 { Threatening to push ...b5! } 13. a4
{ We are literally squeezing Black on both sides of the board. White has the easier game. }
