6... Qxc5
{ This is the safer alternative to the capture on b2, but a bit inferior. } 7.
a3 { Preparing the typical queenside storm with c4-b4! } 7... Bg4
{ This is very common in online chess. Black has a concrete threat of pushing ...e5! }
8. Be2
{ The simplest. First we are breaking the pin, and then we can focus on the typical queenside play. }
8... e6 9. c4
{ It is important to start with this move because  9.b4  Qc3  is very annoying. Next up we are ready to expand further with b4 and White has pressure on the queenside. }
