[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "QGD 5.Nbd2 Qb6 6.dxc5 Qxb2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3
{ This is the most precise move ➼ avoiding the annoying  2.Bf4  c5!  which gives us some headaches as explained in this informational. }
2... Nf6 3. Bf4 c5 4. e3 Nc6 5. Nbd2
{ This is the key move to start with. A common mistake that most of the London System players make is  5.c3  allowing  5...Qb6  with a good version for Black. }
5... Qb6 { This is Black's most direct attempt ➼ attacking both d4 and b2. } 6.
dxc5
{ The point of having started with 5. Nbd2! Black has a choice between:  6...Qxc5  6...Qxb2. }
6... Qxb2
{ The most common move in both OTB and online chess. Before we dive into the action I want to make clear that this line is very unique because we will be getting into a different pawn structure compared to what we have seen so far. While learning this variation try to think about it very specifically and not from a general perspective because we are about to enter some sharp lines. You can think of it as a completely new opening, because the typical static plans are gone and we should guide ourselves with concrete factors in order to succeed. }
7. Rb1
{ The only serious move for White. Now Black has a choice between: 7...Qc3  @@StartBracket@@The Main Line@@EndBracket@@  7...Qa3  7...Qxa2. }
7... Qc3 8. Bb5
{ This is simply a must in order to generate good play as White.   This is a highly disputed line which is covered in great depth in the Queen's Gambit Declined with 5...Qb6, but for now we can just say that White is going to continue with O-O and Ne5 ideas ➼ and in case Black plays ...Qxc5 a typical idea for White is to play c4 followed by Qa4 with pressure on the c6-knight. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Queen's Indian: Mainline with 12...Bf8"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4
{ This is the most flexible move order ➼ making sure that we keep everything in London System territory. For more details about the move order make sure to check out the informational. }
2... e6
{ This move is usually preferred by the Queen's Indian players since Black is most likely going to follow it up by playing either 3... b6 or 3...c5. Going for 3...d5 is of course playable ➼ transposing to the QGD main lines, but less logical because Black could have played the more flexible 2...d5 ➼ putting a pawn in the center while not yet restricting the light-squared bishop. }
3. e3
{ Starting  3.Nf3  is also perfectly playable, but going  3.e3  is the most flexible move for a number of reasons. First and foremost White can now meet the agressive  3...c5  with  4.c3  ➼ preparing to meet  4...Qb6  with  5.Qb3  @@StartBracket@@this move order was played almost exclusively by Grachev and Kamsky@@EndBracket@@.   Another reason is that against  3...b6  White has an aditional option to spice things up by going for the creative  4.Qf3!?  line. Those are some important points to keep in mind, however we won't be using any of those lines in particular in this repertoire!That being said, both moves are playable, but going 3.e3 gives you a bit more room for creativity and that's why I made it our main line. }
3... b6
{ With this move being played, we are now entering Queen's Indian teritory. While ...Bb7 is played almost exclusively, I would like to draw your attention to the fact that Black could also use ...Ba6 as an idea to trade off our powerful light-squared bishop. }
4. Nf3
{ Going for the standard approach. the g1-knight is always placed on f3 in the Classical London System. Even though 4. Qf3 is an interesting line, I am not a huge fan of it because its quite speculative and if Black plays the move order with 3...c5 and later on decides to fianchetto with ...b6, we would have to learn a lot of additional theory.   While  4.Qf3  could surprise some of your opponents, I don't see it as a healthy approach when Black can use a simple move order trick and avoid our whole idea. }
4... Bb7
{ The most standard move and what I expect you to encounter the most. } 5. Nbd2
{ This move is important for a number of reasons. First and foremost, if Black deviates from the standard path @@StartBracket@@5...Be7@@EndBracket@@ by playing  5...d5  , we can simply play  6.c3  Bd6  7.h4!  ➼ transposing back to the quick ...Bd6 lines.   Following Magnus Carlsen's footsteps blindly by playing  5.h3  would give Black the chance to switch and get an improved version after  5...d5!  Of course, that is not the end of the world, but we can no longer get the best version of our setup.   Another reason why I prefer  5.Nbd2  is that  5...Bd6!?  can be met by the standard  6.Bg3! }
5... Be7
{ The standard move. Black is preparing ...O-O and then the most common plan is to go ...c5 followed by ...cxd4 ➼ entering the typical 'Hedgehog Structure'. Besides that, we should not forget about the 'innocent' positional threat of going ...Nh5! }
6. h3
{ This is important because we need to have a square to hide our dark-squared bishop in case of ... Nh5. }
6... O-O 7. Bd3
{ This is the most active place for our light-squared bishop. It normally belongs on this square except when we are dealing with the kingside fianchetto. }
7... c5
{ The only big move in the position since both  7...d5  and  7...d6  are very likely to transpose. }
8. O-O
{ This is the standard way to castle against the Queen's Indian, and also in general. In some positions White can try to play for long castle, but it's very situational. Now Black has a choice between:  8...d6  8...d5  8...cxd4 @@StartBracket@@the main line@@EndBracket@@. }
8... cxd4 9. exd4 d6 10. Re1
{ I find this to be the most useful move. There is nothing wrong with  10.c3  and it might very well transpose. The reason why I made  10.Re1  the main line is that it's the most flexible move, keeping ideas of c2-c4 ➼ using the Kamsky plan. }
10... Nbd7 11. Bh2
{ This is again, not the only move, but the most flexible one. Starting with  11.c3  is perfectly fine, and it might simply transpose. }
11... Re8
{ After this move we have reached the main crossroads. White has a choice between two big ideas:   12.c3 @@StartBracket@@the standard move@@EndBracket@@  12.a4 @@StartBracket@@the Kamsky plan@@EndBracket@@. }
12. c3
{ This is the most common way of playing and the universal approach for White. In order to be a successful London System player, I think this is one of the structures that you should be looking to master. Instead,  12.a4  a6  13.a5  b5  14.c4  is Kamsky's pet line.Now Black has a choice between two main plans:   12...Bf8 @@StartBracket@@the most common plan@@EndBracket@@  12...Nf8 @@StartBracket@@less common, but quite tricky@@EndBracket@@. }
12... Bf8 13. a4
{ Threatening to push a5 with pressure on the queenside. This position is covered in great depth in the Theory Chapter, but for now we can stop and dicuss about White's ideal set-up. The d2-knight goes Nc4-Ne3 @@StartBracket@@from where it's controlling the center and protecting the g2-square@@EndBracket@@, the f3-knight goes Nd2, the d3-bishop goes Bf1 @@StartBracket@@it's simply safer here@@EndBracket@@ and after all of this White is ready to expand on the queenside with b4-c4 and so on. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "KID Mainline: 6...c5"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4
{ This is the most flexible move order ➼ making sure that we keep everything in London System teritory. For more details about the move order make sure to check out the informational. }
2... g6
{ Going for the kingside fianchetto will generally lead to a more dynamic game. Black has a choice between two main openings: The King's Indian Defense The Grunfeld Defense. }
3. Nf3 Bg7 4. c3
{ This is a very underrated move! White is preparing to play Nbd2 followed by e4 if allowed @@StartBracket@@this is why we are not rushing to push e3 like in the most common lines@@EndBracket@@. }
4... O-O 5. Nbd2
{ Threatening to grab space with e4. Black has a choice between:  5...d5 @@StartBracket@@The Grunfeld move@@EndBracket@@  5...d6 @@StartBracket@@The King's Indian move@@EndBracket@@. }
5... d6
{ This is the King's Indian move ➼ allowing White to expand in the center and then trying to create counterplay with the ...e5-break. This is way more popular than 5...d5, but we should be equally well prepared against both!   5...d5  stops White from pushing e4 ➼ this will be the choice of Grunfeld Defense players. }
6. e4 c5 7. dxc5
{ This move might seem a bit odd at first because why wouldn't we keep the pawn center?! In fact, going 7.Be2 is an alternative and we'll most likely transpose to my recommendation against the Old Indian. Now let's address the elephant in the room! Why are the top grandmasters playing 7. dxc5! exclusively?There are a couple of reasons, but the funny one is that there is simply nothing better! Going 7.d5 would lead to a comfortable Benoni for Black and the simple 7.Be2 is interesting but equal with correct play.Now that we have seen what the alternatives are, let's discuss about the pawn structure after 7.dxc5 dxc5 for a bit. Black's main issue is that it's not easy to find a good square for the queen. White can easily develop with Qc2-Be2-short castle-Rfd1 followed by a4-Nc4 with positional play on the queenside. At the same time, it's much trickier for Black to organize their pieces. Throw in h3 at the right moment and it's even worse for them!Of course, this is only a very brief introduction, but for more details check out the 'King's Indian Pawn Structure'. }
7... dxc5 8. h3
{ This is by far the most annoying move to face for Black ➼ making it a nightmare for Black to develop the light-squared bishop because we are stopping ...Bg4-ideas. }
8... Nc6 9. Qc2
{ While  9.Bb5  is a very interesting alternative, I decided to pick this move for the sake of simplicity. }
9... b6
{ This is Black's most common move ➼ trying to solve the issue of the light-squared bishop by placing it on b7. }
10. Be2 Bb7 11. O-O
{ We have arrived at one of the main crossroads for the whole 6...c5 line. Black has a big choice, but none of the following moves seem particularly fun to play:  11...Nh5  11...Rc8  11...Re8  11...Qd7  11...Qc8.  For now we can stop here and say that White can continue most of the times with Rad1-Rfe1 followed by Nc4 and push in the center with e5. }
*

