[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "KID Mainline: 6...Nbd7 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4
{ This is the most flexible move order ➼ making sure that we keep everything in London System teritory. For more details about the move order make sure to check out the informational. }
2... g6
{ Going for the kingside fianchetto will generally lead to a more dynamic game. Black has a choice between two main openings: The King's Indian Defense The Grunfeld Defense. }
3. Nf3 Bg7 4. c3
{ This is a very underrated move! White is preparing to play Nbd2 followed by e4 if allowed @@StartBracket@@this is why we are not rushing to push e3 like in the most common lines@@EndBracket@@. }
4... O-O 5. Nbd2
{ Threatening to grab space with e4. Black has a choice between:  5...d5 @@StartBracket@@The Grunfeld move@@EndBracket@@  5...d6 @@StartBracket@@The King's Indian move@@EndBracket@@. }
5... d6
{ This is the King's Indian move ➼ allowing White to expand in the center and then trying to create counterplay with the ...e5-break. This is way more popular than 5...d5, but we should be equally well prepared against both!   5...d5  stops White from pushing e4 ➼ this will be the choice of Grunfeld Defense players. }
6. e4 Nbd7
{ This is the most common move for Black ➼ preparing the typical ... e5-break! Black's light-squared bishop is blocked by the knight, but this is not the biggest issue since it was lacking a good square on the c8-h3 diagonal. Black will most likely develop the light-squared bishop with ...b6-Bb7 or simply delay it's development and focus on the kingside play with ...e5 followed by ...Nh5-Nf4. }
7. Be2 e5
{ This pawn sacrifice is always a theme for Black ➼ connected with pressure on the e4-pawn. It is not a super popular line, but it's definitely something you should be aware of. }
8. dxe5 dxe5 9. Nxe5
{ Best by test! In case you feel unsure about taking the pawn, you can always play the positional way with  9.Be3  and get an interesting game. }
9... Nxe5 { I find this to be more likely in a practical game. } 10. Bxe5 Re8
11. f4
{ Thanks to this strong move White is able to keep the extra pawn without much compensation for Black. We can simply castle short on the next move with a significant edge. }
*

[Event "?"]
