[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "KID Mainline: 6...Nbd7 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4
{ This is the most flexible move order ➼ making sure that we keep everything in London System teritory. For more details about the move order make sure to check out the informational. }
2... g6
{ Going for the kingside fianchetto will generally lead to a more dynamic game. Black has a choice between two main openings: The King's Indian Defense The Grunfeld Defense. }
3. Nf3 Bg7 4. c3
{ This is a very underrated move! White is preparing to play Nbd2 followed by e4 if allowed @@StartBracket@@this is why we are not rushing to push e3 like in the most common lines@@EndBracket@@. }
4... O-O 5. Nbd2
{ Threatening to grab space with e4. Black has a choice between:  5...d5 @@StartBracket@@The Grunfeld move@@EndBracket@@  5...d6 @@StartBracket@@The King's Indian move@@EndBracket@@. }
5... d6
{ This is the King's Indian move ➼ allowing White to expand in the center and then trying to create counterplay with the ...e5-break. This is way more popular than 5...d5, but we should be equally well prepared against both!   5...d5  stops White from pushing e4 ➼ this will be the choice of Grunfeld Defense players. }
6. e4 Nbd7
{ This is the most common move for Black ➼ preparing the typical ... e5-break! Black's light-squared bishop is blocked by the knight, but this is not the biggest issue since it was lacking a good square on the c8-h3 diagonal. Black will most likely develop the light-squared bishop with ...b6-Bb7 or simply delay it's development and focus on the kingside play with ...e5 followed by ...Nh5-Nf4. }
7. Be2 Re8
{ This is the most common move for Black ➼ preparing the ...e5-break. } 8. h3
{ This is the key reaction that I want you to remember against Black's main idea. Here is the trick to easily memorize it! When ...e5 is played, you want to answer it by playing dxe5 followed by Be3 @@StartBracket@@asuming they take back on e5 with the pawn@@EndBracket@@. That will lead to the main pawn structure for our variation which is explained in the 'Typical Pawn Structures' chapter. }
8... e5
{ The logical follow up after having played ...Re8! Other moves simply don't make much sense. }
9. dxe5
{ This move is very important ➼ otherwise Black will play ...exd4 and the e4-pawn will have to suffer. }
9... dxe5
{ Both  9...dxe5  and  9...Nxe5  are equally good. According to the online database, taking back with the pawn seems to be more frequent, and I am guessing you will get it in 3/4 of your games. }
10. Be3
{ The key retreating square. The bishop is really active on e3 while Black is unable to bother us with any ...Ng4 jumps thanks to the precise 8. h3! This position is deeply analyzed in the Theory Chapter, but for now we can stop here and say that White will always develop with Qc2, most of the times castle short and then push on the queenside with a4-a5. A common reaction to keep in mind is when Black tries ...Nh5-Nf4 you wanna be able to meet that with Re1-Bf1 and simply play around Black's knight. }
