[Black "Grunfeld: 6...c5"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4
{ This is the most flexible move order ➼ making sure that we keep everything in London System teritory. For more details about the move order make sure to check out the informational. }
2... g6 3. Nf3 Bg7 4. c3 O-O 5. Nbd2 d5 6. e3
{ While many players have preffered  6.h3  ➼ countering ...Nh5,  I recommend that we stick with  6.e3  for the following reasons:  6...Nh5 ➼ is not such a bad counter in this version  6...c5 ➼ is the most common move ➼ allowing 7. dxc5!  against 6...Nbd7 & 6...b6 we can use h4-ideas to speed up the kingside play.Now it's Black's turn to make an important decision between:  6...Nh5 @@StartBracket@@rare, but critical@@EndBracket@@  6...Nbd7 @@StartBracket@@very popular@@EndBracket@@  6...Bf5 @@StartBracket@@a bit rare@@EndBracket@@  6...b6 @@StartBracket@@similar to 6...Nbd7@@EndBracket@@  6...c5 @@StartBracket@@most popular in online by far@@EndBracket@@  6...Nc6 @@StartBracket@@rare@@EndBracket@@. }
6... c5
{ This is by far the most common move in online chess even though players in over the board games are mixing it with  6...Nbd7  and  6...b6  . }
7. dxc5
{ Taking on c5 is not the most common theme for our repertoire, but here it works very well. Generally this comes as a big surprise for the Black players. It's pretty tricky to make an accurate guess of how the play could go, but I did my best to add all the natural continuations + what I encountered myself playing this variation. }
7... Nc6 { Creating a big positional threat of ...Nh5! } 8. h3
{ This move is really important ➼ in order to meet ...Nh5 with Bh2! The careless  8.Be2  would give Black very decent compensation after something like  8...Nh5  9.Bg5  h6  10.Bh4  g5  11.Bg3  Nxg3  12.hxg3  e5  13.O-O  f5  with a position where White is still 'slightly better' according to the engine, but from a human perspective it feels easier to play as Black ➼ despite being down a pawn. }
8... Nd7
{ This move has the same plan as ...Re8 @@StartBracket@@to push ...e5@@EndBracket@@, but it just seems inferior to me because Black is struggling to develop. }
9. Nb3 { This is the key move to defend the c5-pawn. } 9... a5 10. a4
{ After this important move Black has a hard time regaining the pawn. Keep in mind that  10...e5  allows  11.Bg5!  and  11...f6?  12.Qxd5+!  wins another pawn for White. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Benoni with 2...d6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 c5 2. d5 d6 3. Nc3
{ This works best ➼ keeping the c4-square available for the knight. } 3... Nf6
4. e4 e6 5. dxe6
{ This move works best no matter what Black will recapture with. The point is to avoid  5.Nf3  exd5  6.exd5  with a symmetrical structure which is known to be slightly better for White, but pretty tricky to execute. }
5... Bxe6
{ This is the most common way for Black to recapture.   5...fxe6  improves Black's control over the center, but they will be vulnerable to e5-ideas ➼ messing up Black's pawn structure.  6.Nf3  already threatens to push e5!  6...Nc6  7.Bf4!  Reinforcing the e5-threat. Black can't really do much about it because 7...e5 would create a huge weakness on d5!  7...Be7  8.e5!  After this key idea White has long term pressure with the better pawn structure.  8...dxe5  9.Qxd8+  Bxd8  10.Nxe5⩲  With a long-term advantage for White because of the isolated e6-pawn. Keep in mind that  10...Bc7  is met by  11.Nd3  with a risk-free game for White. }
6. Nge2
{ Nobody really played this move out of 5000 online games, which is interesting to see because 6.Nge2! is the key move to grab the advantage. White is preparing Nf4 which not only attacks the e6-bishop, but also keeps an eye on the d5-outpost.After Nf4 we can simply continue with Be2 followed by O-O, Be3-Qd2-Rad1 and White has pressure on the backward d6-pawn. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Benoni with 2...d6 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 c5 2. d5 d6 3. Nc3
{ This works best ➼ keeping the c4-square available for the knight. } 3... Nf6
4. e4 g6
{ This is the most common plan for Black ➼ setting-up the kingside fianchetto and then trying to play on the queenside with ...a6-b5! }
5. Nf3 Bg7 6. Bc4
{ There are many ways of playing this position, but I find this one to be the most effective ➼ following a recent game by Grischuk. The main advantage of playing 6.Bc4 is that Black can no longer break with ...e6 which is a typical plan in this Benoni structure.   Initially I was considering to recommend  6.Bb5+  which is known to be a 'clever' move to include, but the main issue is that after  6...Bd7  7.a4  Bxb5  8.axb5  it's not so easy to make progress for White. @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/pp2ppbp/3p1np1/2pP4/4P3/2N2N2/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 2 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Be2  is a very viable alternative, but then Black has an additional option to break with ...e6!? }
6... O-O 7. O-O
{ After this move Black has a choice between three main plans:  7...Bg4  7...Na6  7...a6. }
7... Bg4
{ This is a typical plan for the Benoni structure ➼ trading a pair of minor pieces because Black is lacking space. }
8. h3 { Forcing Black to give up the bishop pair. } 8... Bxf3 9. Qxf3 Nbd7
{ Creating a big positional threat of going ...Ne5 ➼ attacking both the c4-bishop and the f3-queen. }
10. Qd1
{ Returning to the safe square and preparing to meet  10...Ne5  with  11.Be2! }
10... Ne8 { Preparing to play ...Nc7 ➼ supporting the ...b5-push. } 11. Re1
{ Activating the rook and preparing to play Bf1. } 11... Nc7
{ Threatening to play ...a6 followed by ...b5! } 12. a4
{ This move is important ➼ preparing to meet  12...a6  with  13.a5! } 12... Rb8
13. Bg5
{ This is the most active square for the bishop ➼ trying to provoke a weakness with ...h6! Following Grischuk's footsteps. }
13... a6 { Threatening to push ...b5! } 14. a5
{ Making Black's ...b5-break less effective. White is slightly better thanks to the extra space + the bishop pair ➼ but the position remains complicated. For more details check out the model game between Grischuk-Sindarov, 2020. }
*

