[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Typical Pawn Structures"]
[Black "The hedgehog structure"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4 e6 3. Nf3 c5 4. e3 cxd4 5. exd4 Be7 6. Nbd2 O-O 7. h3 b6 8. a4
d6 9. c3 Ba6 10. Bb5 Bb7 11. O-O a6 12. Bd3 Nbd7 13. Re1 Re8 14. Bh2
{ This is the most common position for the Queen's Indian Defense. Usually, we call this the 'Hedgehog structure' because Black's pawns are all on the sixth rank, controlling the fifth rank. The basic plan is very simple, but what makes it harder in these lines ➼ is knowing the specific reaction against Black's concrete plans @@StartBracket@@e.g when they try ...Bc6-b5@@EndBracket@@. For more details about any individual line, I highly advise to check out the Theory Chapter, but before you do that, let's have a look at the common plans for both sides.   Typical plans for Black:  ...Bf8-g6, followed by ...e5 a bit later  ... Nf8-Ng6 @@StartBracket@@usually combined with ...Nd5 and ...Nf4 ideas@@EndBracket@@  ...Bc6-b5 @@StartBracket@@this can be the most annoying one@@EndBracket@@  ...Qc7-Bc6-Qb7 @@StartBracket@@with ...b5 ideas@@EndBracket@@  ...Rc8, followed by ...Qc7-Qb8-Qa8 @@StartBracket@@the slow plan which gives us free play@@EndBracket@@   There are not as many plans for White, but it's important to know the ideal setup:  Nd2 goes via Nc4-Ne3 @@StartBracket@@controlling both the center and protecting the g2-square@@EndBracket@@  Bf1 @@StartBracket@@the bishop is simply safer here since we don't really play for a kingside attack  Nf3 will be well placed after Nd2  Rc1 only if needed to protect the c3-pawn   Once the ideal set-up is reached, the plan is to expand on the queenside with b4-c4, and then we decide how to break based on Black's reaction. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Typical Pawn Structures"]
[Black "The Berkes structure - the modern approach"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Bf4 e6 4. e3 Bd6 5. Nbd2 Bxf4 6. exf4
{ This is one of the most common ways to get the Berkes pawn structure. I decided to name it this way after the legendary Hungarian Grandmaster, who has made a large contribution to the modern theory of the London System. To sum things up, White's position is generally a bit easier to play because we have better control over the e5-square, which will make our typical Ne5 plan even stronger. Something important to keep an eye on is the difference between the light-squared bishops. Generally, if bishops are on the board, White is always slightly better, and if Black manages to trade them off, the game is closer to equal. }
6... O-O 7. c3 b6 8. h4
{ This is the modern version of handling the Berkes structure and my main recommendation for the course. Leela0 came up with this new concept, and there are still very few games played. The first high-profile game featuring this new concept was played between Giri-Vitiugov, 2020 ➼ which gave White a promising position even though the game finished peacefully. }
8... c5 9. h5 Qd6
{ 9...h6  10.Ne5⩲  Threatening to push g4-g5. For more details about this position, make sure to check out the theory chapter. }
10. h6 g6 11. g3
{ After this move, White is slightly better because the enemy king feels vulnerable. At this point, Black can go for two main plans:  simple development  striking in the center. }
11... a5
{ Going for simple development with ...Ba6!   11...cxd4  This is played with the idea of breaking in the center.  12.Nxd4  e5  13.fxe5  Qxe5+  14.Be2  Ba6  15.Kf1  Bxe2+  16.Qxe2  Qxe2+  17.Nxe2⩲  With a slightly better endgame for White because of the isolated pawn. For more details, make sure to check out the model endgame between Nihal,S @@StartBracket@@2648@@EndBracket@@ -Batsiashvili,N @@StartBracket@@2463@@EndBracket@@ Ciutadella de Menorca 2022. }
12. a3 Nc6 13. Bd3 Ba6 14. Qe2 Bxd3 15. Qxd3 cxd4 16. Nxd4 Ne7 17. Kf1
{ With the idea to play Kg2 next instead of O-O because the h1-rook has to protect the h6-pawn. For more details, make sure to check out the very recent model game between Nihal,S @@StartBracket@@2646@@EndBracket@@-Petrosyan,M @@StartBracket@@2638@@EndBracket@@ Jermuk 2022. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Typical Pawn Structures"]
[Black "Doubled d-pawns"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Bf4 Bf5
{ 3...c6  4.e3  Bf5  5.Bd3  Bxd3  6.cxd3  This is another way of getting this structure from our Repertoire. }
4. e3 e6 5. Bd3 Bxd3 6. cxd3
{ Most commonly, we are going to reach this structure after Black plays the symmetrical setup with 3...Bf5 despite the fact that you can also get a similar version against the Slav @@StartBracket@@3...c6-lines@@EndBracket@@. If the pawn structure remains the same, I think we can agree on a simple set of moves for White that pretty much work universally:  short castle followed by Nc3 and Rc1 @@StartBracket@@the move order is not that important@@EndBracket@@  grabbing space in the center with e4-e5  after e4-e5 is completed, we can focus on the kingside with h4-g3-Kg2-h5, and Black will have a choice between allowing us to place the pawn on h6 or to play ...h6 himself, which will create a target for a potential bishop sacrifice after Qd2-Bxh6 with a strong attack.  in some positions, White can start with Nc3 and a quick e4-e5  @@StartBracket@@delaying 0-0@@EndBracket@@ because there will be an additional idea of going h4!?, followed by the surprising rook lift Rh3-Rg3 while the king will be safely placed on f1.    As I was saying, this is only if the pawn structure remains intact, but Black has a few ways to deviate from our main plans. The most important are:  playing ...Bd6 and recapturing with the pawn to d6  going for an early ...c5 getting into a symmetrical pawn structure. }
6... Be7
{ 6...c5  7.Qb3!  Forcing Black to play ...Qb6, otherwise he will be clearly worse.  7...Qb6  8.Qxb6  axb6  9.Bxb8  Rxb8  10.Nc3  This is another case where objectively speaking, Black should be fine, but it just seems much easier to play these positions as White because there are so many ways to improve our position. One aspect that makes this position a bit unpleasant for Black is the fact that our knight will be landing on b5 soon, from where it will be really hard to challenge. Then the king will be super useful in the center after Ke2 while the last piece will be activated via Rhc1.   6...Bd6  7.Qb3!  b6  8.Bxd6  cxd6  This is an important change in the pawn structure that will force White to pick a different path than what you were used to in the first place. The fact that Black has a pawn on d6 now simply makes our e4-e5 push much more inefficient. Therefore we need to adapt.These positions should be objectively close to equal, but there is one little aspect that we can try to exploit, which is the c6-square! Our long-term plan is to castle short, push the pawns to a4-b5, double the rooks on the c-file, and then maneuver the knight with Nc3-Na2-Nb4, from where it will be ready to land on the ideal c6-square.   8...Qxd6  Won't affect the pawn structure, and we can continue in the standard fashion with Nc3-Rc1-short castle-and e4.  9.O-O  O-O  10.Nc3  Nc6  11.Rfc1  Qd7  12.Qa4  Rfc8  13.b4  h6  14.b5  Ne7  15.Qb3  Rc7  16.a4  Rac8  17.Rc2  Kh8  18.Rac1  Kg8  19.Na2  Ng6  20.Nb4  This is the dream scenario for White against the ...cxd6 capture where White has managed to gain full control over the a6-c6 squares. }
7. Nc3 O-O 8. Rc1 c6 9. e4 a5 10. O-O Na6 11. h4 Rc8 12. g3 b6 13. Re1 Re8 14.
e5 Nd7 15. Kg2 b5 16. h5
{ This is how our main plan looks in action! White has managed to get all the useful moves in, while Black played a waiting game, being afraid to commit. Now Black has to decide whether to allow White to push h6 or if he goes ...h6 himself creating a hook on the kingside. }
16... h6
{ 16...a4  17.h6  g6  18.Qd2  We are going to follow that standard strategy of trading the dark-squared bishop, which will make Black's king much weaker, and then a powerful maneuver is Nh2-Ng4, keeping an eye on the f6-square.  18...Nc7  19.Bg5  Nb6  20.Bxe7  Qxe7  White's position looks really nice, and as always, it is very important to not only have a good position but also know exactly how to proceed. In this case, the weakness of the f6-square in particular makes Black's king really vulnerable, and White has a great way to exploit that with the typical Nh2-Ng4 maneuver. }
17. Qd2
{ We are ready to break with g4-g5 next, and Black's king is in a lot of trouble. After that, we can continue the attack with Rh1-h6! }
