[Black "The Berkes structure - the classical approach"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Bf4 e6 4. e3 Bd6 5. Nbd2 Bxf4 6. exf4 O-O 7. c3 b6 8.
Bd3
{ This is the classical version of the Berkes structure ➼ going for O-O. The position is pretty simple to understand if you guide yourself by the following rules:  if Black manages to trade off the bad light-squared bishop ➼ the game is around equal  if Black plays with a passive light-squared bishop ➼ White has free pressure on the kingside with a risk-free advantage. }
8... c5 9. O-O Ba6
{ This is Black's best plan to fight for equality ➼ trading off the bad bishop.   9...Bb7  This is a natural move that leads to an inferior position for Black because White's d3-bishop is simply more active, which ultimately makes White's game easier.  10.Re1  Qd6  11.g3  Nbd7  12.Qe2  Rac8  13.Rad1  Rfe8  14.Ne5⩲  This is a typical example of when White gets free pressure on the kingside thanks to the more active bishop. We can continue with Bb1, followed by pushing on the kingside with h4-h5 and g4-g5. }
10. Bxa6 Nxa6 11. Qe2 Nb8 12. Ne5 Qc7 13. Ndf3 Nc6 14. Rad1 cxd4 15. Nxc6 Qxc6
16. Nxd4 Qc7 17. g3
{ This is a typical example of Black using the ...Ba6 plan ➼ to trade off the bad bishop and get an equal game. Nevertheless, White's position remained 'easier' to play and White went on to win a very instructive endgame. For more details, make sure to check out the model endgame between Grachev,B @@StartBracket@@2619@@EndBracket@@-Matlakov,M @@StartBracket@@2688@@EndBracket@@ Tornelo INT 2021. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Typical Pawn Structures"]
[Black "The reversed Stonewall"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Bf4 c5 4. e3 Nc6 5. Nbd2 e6 6. c3 Bd6 7. Bg3 O-O 8. Bd3
Re8 9. Ne5 Qc7 10. f4 b6
{ This is a typical position coming from the ...c5 & ...Bd6 lines. White is clearly better in this structure if you understand the main concepts. Our biggest advantage is secured by the e5-knight @@StartBracket@@without it, the position would be equal@@EndBracket@@.The d2-knight might seem a bit passive for now, but it's actually really well-placed because it controls the critical e4-square ➼ stopping Black's main source of counterplay which is ...Ne4, followed by ... f6! @@StartBracket@@getting rid of the e5-knight@@EndBracket@@. The d3-bishop is very active ➼ exerting a lot of pressure against the enemy king. The g3-bishop is passive after we push the typical f4, but that is only a temporary issue since most of the time, the bishop can be activated with Bh4!Sometimes White can take a very aggressive approach and play Qf3 followed by O-O-O, but most of the time, the safer plan with O-O, followed by Rf3-Rh3 works better ➼ with good attacking prospects on the kingside. To sum things up, as long as you avoid ...Ne4, White should have a promising position. }
11. Bh4
{ Bringing the bishop back to life. You should strike with this move immediately after the f4 push.   11.Ndf3?  This is a typical mistake that I noticed a lot of my students making. This is because people generally don't know how to build up the initiative in the Reversed Stonewall structure, and they are also unaware of Black's only source of counterplay.  11...Ne4⇆  With ...f6 coming on the next move ➼ Black gets an easy game.   11.O-O  This was an alternative.  11...Bb7  12.Bh4  Using this move order is also perfectly fine.   11.Qc2?  This is another typical mistake for the London System beginners @@StartBracket@@not only in this structure but in general@@EndBracket@@. The queen loses a lot of its potential after being placed on this square. On the one hand, the queen is putting a bit of pressure on the b1-h7 diagonal, but it will be much harder to bring her over to the kingside. On the other hand, the c2-queen is most of the time vulnerable to tactical motifs on the c-file ➼ a classical motif would be something like ...Bb7-Rc8-cxd4-Nb4! }
11... Be7 { Preparing to recapture on f6 with the bishop. } 12. O-O
{ This is what we are gonna be playing most of the time. Castling long is sometimes an option, but very situational. }
12... Bb7
{ We have reached a critical point for our topic. White did the right thing by playing Ne5, followed it up with f4, and even activated the bishop with Bh4, but what now? White has a choice between a few interesting plans:  13.Rf3  13.Qf3  13.Bxf6. }
13. Rf3
{ Generally, this is the most effective plan in most situations ➼ preparing to play Rh3.   13.Bxf6!  This move is best objectively speaking, avoiding any ...Ne4 ideas ➼ as explained in the theory chapter.   13.Qf3  This is played with the idea to go Qh3. It is definitely a viable plan and a typical maneuver that should always be on your radar after White has played Ne5!  13...a6  14.Qh3  Threatening Bxf6 followed by Qxh7+!  14...g6  15.Ndf3→  With Ng5 next ➼ White has pressure on the f7-square. }
13... a6 14. Rh3
{ Creating a direct threat of Bxf6 because the h7-square is vulnerable. White has good attacking prospects on the kingside. }
