1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Bf4 c5 4. e3 Nc6 5. Nbd2 cxd4 6. exd4 Bf5 7. c3 e6 8.
Qb3 Qc8 9. Be2 h6 10. O-O Be7 11. Rfe1 O-O 12. h3 Ne4 13. Nxe4 Bxe4 14. Nd2 Bg6
15. a4
{ This is an improved version for Black because they have managed to take control over the b1-h7 diagonal, and our bishop is sitting on a less active square. In the previous example, we saw White going full attacking mode on the kingside, but here it's no longer the case. All of the action will now that place on the queenside, and White has the following typical ideas:  taking space with a4-a5  Qa4 @@StartBracket@@making room for the b-pawn  push b4  Nb3-Nc5 @@StartBracket@@recapturing with the b-pawn generally, so we can attack the b7-pawn@@EndBracket@@   Black's plans will generally remain the same with ...Rd8-Bd6 ideas and simply trying to stay solid while White attempts to create something on the queenside.   For more details, make sure to check out the model game between Kamsky,G @@StartBracket@@2666@@EndBracket@@-Shirov,A @@StartBracket@@2643@@EndBracket@@ St Petersburg 2018 and Bachmann,A @@StartBracket@@2653@@EndBracket@@-Hong, A @@StartBracket@@2383@@EndBracket@@ Philadelphia 2017. }
