[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Typical Pawn Structures"]
[Black "The Carlsbad with h3-g4"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Bf4 c5 4. e3 Nc6 5. Nbd2 Bg4 6. c3 e6 7. Qb3 Qc8 8. Nh4
Be7 9. h3 Bh5 10. g4 Bg6 11. Nxg6 hxg6 12. Be2
{ This is a typical position arising from the ...c5 & ...Bf5/Bg4 main lines. Most of the time, this will transpose to the Carlsbad structure after Black plays ...cxd4, and we recapture with exd4. Black's position is pretty solid, but White has pressure with the bishop pair and attacking ideas on the kingside with h4-h5.For more details, I highly recommend checking out the Theory Chapter and the model games between Berkes-Nguyen, 2016, and Kravtsiv-Mchedlisvhvili, 2019. For now, I will just introduce you to the main plans available for both sides.   Typical plans for Black:  ...O-O @@StartBracket@@this generally falls under a big attack after h4-h5!@@EndBracket@@  ...Qd7 & ...O-O-O @@StartBracket@@as in the Berkes-Nguyen, 2016@@EndBracket@@  ...a6-b5 @@StartBracket@@as in Kravtsiv-Mchedlisvhvili, 2019@@EndBracket@@  ...Kf8-Kg8 @@StartBracket@@trying to avoid White's attack@@EndBracket@@.  Typical plans for White:  O-O-O @@StartBracket@@when there is no ...cxd4 & ...Nxd4 trick@@EndBracket@@  dxc5 & O-O-O  Kf1-Kg2 with pressure on the kingside after h4-h5 @@StartBracket@@as in Kravtsiv-Mchedlisvhvili, 2019@@EndBracket@@  whenever Black goes ...Bd6, we avoid the trade unless we can win something  always meeting ...cxd4 with exd4! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Typical Pawn Structures"]
[Black "The Chigorin structure"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bf4 Bf5 4. c4 e6
{ 4...dxc4  5.Nc3  Nf6  6.e3  e6  7.Bxc4  Be7  8.O-O  O-O  9.Rc1  a6  10.a3⩲  This is a common structure arising from the ...dxc4 lines, which is simply slightly better for White because we have better control over the center + the enemy c6-knight is a little misplaced. White's main plan is to prepare the e4-push with moves such as Qe2 and Rfd1. Once the e4-push is achieved ➼ White has a solid advantage because all of Black pieces are restricted by our pawn center.The next step in order to make progress after pushing e4 will be to break with d5! because we are opening up the position against the black queen @@StartBracket@@and the other break with e5 would allow ...Nd5 and Black manages to stabilize@@EndBracket@@.Speaking of Black's main plans, we need to first of all point out that their position is worse, so there are not as many interesting ideas as for White. The main plan for Black is to set up a blockade with ...Ne4 ➼ trying to stop White's central expansion. That plan can normally be countered by Nxe4, followed by Nd2 and later on e4 push.Another plan for Black could be ...Nh5 ➼ trying to steal the London bishop. This plan is also not very effective because we can simply play Bg3 and then continue with the typical Qe2-Rfd1, followed by e4. }
5. Nc3 Nf6 6. e3 Be7 7. a3 O-O 8. Rc1 a6 9. cxd5 exd5 10. Bd3 Bxd3 11. Qxd3
{ This is a typical scenario that stems from the Chigorin Defense, which is reminiscent of the Ragozin Defense. Generally, White has steady pressure on the queenside after Na4-Nc5, which will normally be met by ...Bxc5, and we recapture with Rxc5. Black will then just try to stay solid with ...Ne7, followed by ...c6 and play a waiting game, while White can set up the minority attack with b4-a4-b5.Generally speaking, White is the only one pushing with a risk free position ➼ while Black has to come up with a number of accurate decisions before getting a safe position. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Typical Pawn Structures"]
[Black "The King's Indian Defense with the ...e5-break"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4 g6 3. Nf3 Bg7 4. c3 O-O 5. Nbd2 d6 6. e4 Nbd7 7. Be2 Re8 8. h3
e5 9. dxe5 dxe5 10. Be3
{ This is a typical structure arising from the King's Indian Defense. I consider it easier to play as White because the queenside play simply comes more naturally, while Black has to come up with some serious effort to achieve anything on the kingside. Their main ...f5-break will be much harder to achieve, and even when they do, it might create a lot of weaknesses.I have given an overview of the main plans for both sides below, but I strongly encourage you to read the Theory Chapter for more details!  Typical plans for Black:  ...b6-Bb7 @@StartBracket@@finishing development@@EndBracket@@  ...Nh5-Nf4 @@StartBracket@@trying to win the light-squared bishop@@EndBracket@@  ...Nh5-f5 @@StartBracket@@going full attacking mode@@EndBracket@@  ...Bf8-Bc5  @@StartBracket@@trading the bad bishop@@EndBracket@@.  Typical plans for White:  a4 @@StartBracket@@followed by a5 if allowed@@EndBracket@@  always play Qc2 @@StartBracket@@it overprotects e4, and the queen is very safe@@EndBracket@@  Rfe1-Bf1 @@StartBracket@@in case Black has played ...Nf4, we can kick it away with Kh2-g3@@EndBracket@@  Nc4 followed by b4 @@StartBracket@@with pressure on the queenside@@EndBracket@@. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Typical Pawn Structures"]
[Black "The King's Indian Defense with the ...c5-break"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4 g6 3. Nf3 Bg7 4. Nbd2 O-O 5. c3 d6 6. e4 c5 7. dxc5 dxc5 8. h3
Nc6 9. Qc2
{ This thematic symmetrical structure which arises after Black breaks with ...c5 is full of venom! The main reason is that Black won't have an easy time finding a safe square for the queen because the ideal c7-square is covered by the f4-bishop.   Generally speaking, White has very easy play without any risks whatsoever, but I still encourage you to go over the Theory Chapter to find out more about these lines. Here I will just mention the main plans for both sides.   Typical plans for Black:  ...b6-Bb7 @@StartBracket@@followed by ...Qc8-Ba6 most likely@@EndBracket@@  ...Nh5-e5 @@StartBracket@@followed by ...Nf4 most of the time@@EndBracket@@  ...Re8-e5 @@StartBracket@@and potentially ... Nh5-Nf4@@EndBracket@@  ...Nh5-Bh6 @@StartBracket@@in case of Bh2@@EndBracket@@.  Typical plans for White:  Always play Be2  Most of the time O-O  Rad1-Rfe1 @@StartBracket@@placing the rooks on the central files@@EndBracket@@  Nc4 followed by expanding in the center with e5!  when Black plays ...Nf4, we can meet it with Bf1 and play around it  in case of ...e5, we can maneuver around it with Nc4-Ne3-Nd5!  in case of ...a6 ➼ threatening to push ...b5, we play a4! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1) Chigorin Defense"]
[Black "Introduction"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bf4
{ In this chapter, we are going to have a look at the most common opening below 1500 blitz rating on chess.com! If you are fitting in this rating category YOU MUST know this chapter by heart because it gets played almost in every game. We will divide the material into two main categories:  • lines where Black plays ...Nf6  • lines where Black delays ...Nf6  For a better understanding of the main plans for both sides, make sure to check out the Chigorin Structure.  Model games arising from this chapter:  ➡ Landa Konstantin-Balducchi Francois, Ajaccio Blitz 2007  ➡ Malakhatko Vadim-Meyssonnier Patrick, Corsica Rapid 2008 }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1) Chigorin Defense"]
[Black "Chigorin: 3...Bg4 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3
{ This is the most precise move ➼ avoiding the annoying  2.Bf4  c5!  which gives us some headaches as explained in this informational. }
2... Nc6
{ This is the Chigorin Defense ➼ by far the most common reply in beginner games. Please keep in mind that this can be also reached via  2...Nf6  3.Bf4  Nc6  which transposes to an important line of this chapter.To sum things up, we can split the material in two main parts:  lines with ...Nf6 @@StartBracket@@where Bb5 followed by Ne5 works well@@EndBracket@@  lines where Black delays ...Nf6 @@StartBracket@@where c4 is the best plan@@EndBracket@@. }
3. Bf4 Bg4 { Threatening ...Bxf3 ➼ messing up White's pawn structure. } 4. e3
e6
{ Delaying ...Nf6 and keeping open the option of playing with ...Nge7!   Keep in mind that  4...Nf6  transposes to the line 2...Nf6 3. Bf4 Nc6 4.e3 Bg4. }
5. h3
{ This is always a nice move to throw in ➼ forcing Black to decide whether they keep the pin or not. }
5... Bh5
{ Keeping the tension ➼ this is generally the most common way to react for Black.   5...Bxf3  cedes the bishop pair, which is something that we are happy to see. After  6.Qxf3  Bd6  we can stay flexible with  7.c3!  ,  preparing to play Nd2 and then we can decide between Bd3 or the aggressive g4!? The line could continue  7...Nge7  8.Nd2  O-O  9.Bd3⩲  With a slightly better position for White thanks to the bishop pair. Keep in mind that  9...e5  allows a common tactical trick after  10.dxe5  Nxe5  11.Bxe5  Bxe5  12.Bxh7+!  Kxh7  13.Qh5+  Kg8  14.Qxe5  with an extra pawn for White. }
6. c4
{ This is the best way to approach this situation where Black delays ...Nf6! The typical motif for how we play against the Chigorin,  6.Bb5  , does not work very well against this move order because after  6...Bd6  7.g4  Bg6  8.Ne5  Black has the extra option of going  8...Nge7!  and the c6-knight is safe.Now that we understand why Bb5 is no longer effective, let's discuss the most asked question 'When should I play c4 instead of c3?'. This is a super specific question and it really depends on the position, but I will do my best to give you a general idea which should make it easier to decide during the game.Generally, c3 is the way to go in the London because you can combine it with the typical Ne5 plan or the break in the center with e4. However there are some lines that don't allow Ne5 @@StartBracket@@e.g. The Leningrad Dutch@@EndBracket@@ which happens to be the case in this Chigorin line as well, because the f3-knight is pinned ➼ in these lines, playing c3 will generally lead to an equal game because it's hard for White to create superiority on any side. The advantage of pushing c4 is that this way we can create superiority on the queenside and fight for an opening advantage.To sum things up, I would like to mention that going c4 is a double-edged sword ➼ because playing with c3 will generally lead to an equal game in the worst case scenario, but pushing c4 at the wrong time could give White a worse position because White's center could be weaker. Please keep in mind that this is general advice, and you really have to decide based on the concrete factors of your position. }
6... dxc4
{ This avoids White's ideas to expand with c5, but on the other hand releases the tension and gives White an edge in the center. }
7. Bxc4 Bd6 8. Bxd6 { We don't really have much of an alternative! } 8... cxd6
{ Threatening to push ...d5!  8...Qxd6  would lead to a normal position which is slightly better for White after the typical  9.O-O  followed by Nc3 and Rc1. }
9. d5 { Stopping Black from pushing ...d5! } 9... exd5 10. Bxd5
{ We can continue with Nc3 and O-O with a long term advantage thanks to the isolated d6-pawn. }
*

