[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3
{ This is the most precise move ➼ avoiding the annoying  2.Bf4  c5!  which gives us some headaches as explained in this informational. }
2... Nc6
{ This is the Chigorin Defense ➼ by far the most common reply in beginner games. Please keep in mind that this can be also reached via  2...Nf6  3.Bf4  Nc6  which transposes to an important line of this chapter.To sum things up, we can split the material in two main parts:  lines with ...Nf6 @@StartBracket@@where Bb5 followed by Ne5 works well@@EndBracket@@  lines where Black delays ...Nf6 @@StartBracket@@where c4 is the best plan@@EndBracket@@ }
3. Bf4 f6
{ The point of this move is to meet  4.e3  with  4...g5!?  5.Bg3  h5  with interesting play on the kingside. }
4. c4
{ Let's discuss the most asked question: 'When should I play c4 instead of c3?'. This is a super specific question and it really depends on the position, but I will do my best give you a general idea which should make it easier to decide during the game.  Typically c4 works well when the c6-knight is placed in front on the c7-pawn @@StartBracket@@Chigorin Lines@@EndBracket@@. Going c3 is usually the way to go in the London because you can combine it with the typical Ne5 plan or the break in the center with e4. However, there are some lines that don't allow Ne5 @@StartBracket@@e.g. The Leningrad Dutch@@EndBracket@@ where in order to create superiority White needs to use the c4-push.  To sum things up, I would like to mention that going c4 is a double-edged sword ➼ because playing with c3 will generally lead to an equal game in the worst case scenario, but pushing c4 at the wrong time could give White a worse position because White's center could become weak. Please keep in mind that this is general advice, and you really have to decide based on the concrete factors of your position. }
4... e5 { This involves a pawn sacrifice. } 5. cxd5
{ This is best because  5.dxe5  d4!?  would give Black interesting compensation. }
5... Qxd5
{ In case of  5...exf4  6.dxc6  bxc6  we have  7.e4!  Forcing Black to go ...fxe3 ➼ otherwise White keeps a strong center. After  7...fxe3  8.fxe3  Bb4+  9.Nbd2  we can continue with Bc4 and O-O with a better position for White because Black's position is full of weaknesses. }
6. Nc3 { Developing with tempo ➼ attacking Black's queen. } 6... Bb4 7. dxe5
{ Most games will continue with  7...Qxd1+  8.Rxd1  with an extra pawn for White. }
