2... Nc6
{ This is the Chigorin Defense ➼ by far the most common reply in beginner games. Please keep in mind that this can be also reached via  2...Nf6  3.Bf4  Nc6  which transposes to an important line of this chapter.To sum things up, we can split the material in two main parts:  lines with ...Nf6 @@StartBracket@@where Bb5 followed by Ne5 works well@@EndBracket@@  lines where Black delays ...Nf6 @@StartBracket@@where c4 is the best plan@@EndBracket@@. }
3. Bf4 Bf5 4. c4
{ Let's discuss the most asked question 'When should I play c4 instead of c3?'. This is a super specific question and it really depends on the position, but I will do my best to give you a general idea which should make it easier to decide during the game.Generally, c3 is the way to go in the London because you can combine it with the typical Ne5 plan or the break in the center with e4. However there are some lines that don't allow Ne5 @@StartBracket@@e.g. The Leningrad Dutch@@EndBracket@@ which happens to be the case in this Chigorin line as well ➼ in these lines, playing c3 will generally lead to an equal game because it's hard for White to create superiority on any side. The advantage of pushing c4 is that this way we can create superiority on the queenside and fight for an opening advantage.To sum things up, I would like to mention that going c4 is a double-edged sword ➼ because playing with c3 will generally lead to an equal game in the worst case scenario, but pushing c4 at the wrong time could give White a worse position because White's center could be weaker. Please keep in mind that this is general advice, and you really have to decide based on the concrete factors of your position. }
4... e6 5. cxd5
{ I like to start with this move ➼ defining the pawn structure. } 5... exd5 6.
Nc3 Nf6 7. e3
{ Preparing to develop with Bd3 followed by O-O. Black now has a choice between:  7...Be7  7...Bd6  7...Bb4. }
7... Bd6 8. Bg5
{ Threatening Bxf6 followed by Nxd5! A typical mistake that Black makes in this structure is  8...h6  allowing  9.Bxf6  Qxf6  10.Nxd5  with an extra pawn for White. }
8... Be7 9. Bxf6
{ This is a typical trick to win a pawn for White. The point is to play Qb3 next! }
9... Bxf6 10. Qb3
{ Black is unable to defend both b7 and d5 at the same time. } *

