4... dxc4 { This move gives White an edge in the center. } 5. Nc3
{ Threatening to play e4 followed by Bxc4! } 5... Nf6
{ Stopping White from pushing e4. Keep in mind that  5...Nb4  can easily be met by  6.e4!  with a much better position for White. }
6. e3
{ Preparing to take back the pawn with Bxc4.  6...Nb4  is still not a good move for Black in view of  7.Qa4+! }
6... e6 7. Bxc4
{ Preparing O-O. Black has a choice between:  7...Be7  7...Bd6  7...Bb4. } 7...
Bd6 { Offering the bishop trade. } 8. Bg5
{ This move is very annoying for Black! The threat is to meet  8...O-O  with  9.e4!  followed by e5 ➼ winning a piece. }
8... h6
{ This is the most common move in online chess.   Instead,  8...Be7  breaks the pin, but after  9.Bb5!  Black lacks a good way to deal with Bxc6. Following  9...O-O  10.Bxc6  bxc6  11.O-O  ⩲  we can continue with Rc1 and White keeps a small but steady edge thanks to Black's weak pawns on the queenside. }
9. Bxf6 { Going for the piece with e4-e5! } 9... Qxf6 10. e4 Bg4 11. e5
{ Winning a piece despite the fact that Black has a bit of counterplay. } *

