[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1) Chigorin Defense"]
[Black "Chigorin: 2...Nf6 3.Bf4 Nc6 with 4...Bf5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3
{ This is the most precise move ➼ avoiding the annoying  2.Bf4  c5!  which gives us some headaches as explained in this informational. }
2... Nf6 3. Bf4 Nc6
{ Going for the Chigorin Defense. This is by far the most popular choice below 1600 blitz on chess.com! People that play this generally don't know that they are playing 'The Chigorin Defense' and they are simply trying to get their pieces developed according to the common sense rules @@StartBracket@@Developing their knights before the bishops@@EndBracket@@. }
4. e3
{ Now Black has a choice between three equally popular plans:   4...Bf5  4...Bg4  4...e6. }
4... Bf5 5. Bb5
{ This plan works very well against both 4...Bf5 and 4...Bg4! I want you to clearly understand that the light-squared bishop belongs to d3 in most London System positions and that developing it to b5 is a very situational plan. By going for 5.Bb5 we are trying to exploit the fact that Black has committed with ...Nf6. There are no longer any ...Nge7 ideas to protect the c6-knight after we play Ne5!, like they could do after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.Nf3  Nc6  3.Bf4  Bf5  4.e3  e6  5.Bb5  Bd6  6.Ne5  Nge7!  and Black is safe.Now Black has a choice between two main moves:  5... e6  5...a6. }
5... a6 { Attacking White's bishop immediately ➼ avoiding the direct Ne5! } 6.
Bxc6+
{ Going for positional play. This move creates a weakness on c6 ➼ which will become our main target. }
6... bxc6 7. c4
{ Preparing to play Qa4 and in some lines we could make use of the c-file.  7.c3  is much softer and could lead to an equal game if Black finds the precise  7...Qb8!  8.Qa4  Qb5!  and this is only a super specific reason which shows that 7.c4 is better in this case! }
7... dxc4
{ This is the greedy approach, but the tripled pawns can hardly be any good! }
8. Qa4
{ This is the standard way to react. Developing the queen while attacking both c6 and c4. }
8... Qd5 { Trying to defend both pawns and threatening ...Qb5! } 9. Nc3
{ Attacking the queen on d5 and stopping ...Qb5 ideas. After this move White is completely winning. Keep in mind that  9.Bxc7  Qb5!  is only slightly better for White. }
9... Qd7 10. Ne5
{ Attacking Black's queen. We can meet  10...Qe6  with  11.Nxc4  with a winning position because Black's pieces are stuck combined with the ruined pawn structure. }
