4... Bf5 5. Bb5
{ This plan works very well against both 4...Bf5 and 4...Bg4! I want you to clearly understand that the light-squared bishop belongs to d3 in most London System positions and that developing it to b5 is a very situational plan. By going for 5.Bb5 we are trying to exploit the fact that Black has committed with ...Nf6. There are no longer any ...Nge7 ideas to protect the c6-knight after we play Ne5!, like they could do after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.Nf3  Nc6  3.Bf4  Bf5  4.e3  e6  5.Bb5  Bd6  6.Ne5  Nge7!  and Black is safe.Now Black has a choice between two main moves:  5... e6  5...a6. }
5... a6 { Attacking White's bishop immediately ➼ avoiding the direct Ne5! } 6.
Bxc6+
{ Going for positional play. This move creates a weakness on c6 ➼ which will become our main target. }
6... bxc6 7. c4
{ Preparing to play Qa4 and in some lines we could make use of the c-file.  7.c3  is much softer and could lead to an equal game if Black finds the precise  7...Qb8!  8.Qa4  Qb5!  and this is only a super specific reason which shows that 7.c4 is better in this case! }
7... e6
{ This is by far the most common move for Black, but it already leads to a losing position. }
8. Qa4 { Attacking the c6-pawn and Black has no good way to protect it. } 8...
Qd7 9. Ne5 { Attacking both the queen on d7 an the pawn on c6. } 9... Qd6 10.
c5 { Attacking the queen so that we can grab the c6-pawn next with the queen. }
10... Qe7 11. Qxc6+
{ With a free win for White. This is a super common scenario for games below 1600 blitz on chess.com! }
