[Round "?"]
[White "1) Chigorin Defense"]
[Black "Chigorin: 2...Nf6 3.Bf4 Nc6 with 4...e6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3
{ This is the most precise move ➼ avoiding the annoying  2.Bf4  c5!  which gives us some headaches as explained in this informational. }
2... Nf6 3. Bf4 Nc6
{ Going for the Chigorin Defense. This is by far the most popular choice below 1600 blitz on chess.com! People that play this generally don't know that they are playing 'The Chigorin Defense' and they are simply trying to get their pieces developed according to the common sense rules @@StartBracket@@Developing their knights before the bishops@@EndBracket@@. }
4. e3
{ Now Black has a choice between three equally popular plans:   4...Bf5  4...Bg4  4...e6. }
4... e6
{ Locking the light-squared bishop inside the pawn chain. Against this plan ➼ it is less effective to go  5.Bb5  because Black can easily deal with the pin by answering  5...Bd7!  Against this plan I suggest we stick with the standard London System play ➼ and we no longer go for the exploitative approach with Bb5. }
5. Nbd2 Be7 6. c3
{ Preparing to play Bd3 without allowing any annoying ...Nb4 jumps! } 6... O-O
7. Bd3 { Already it's not simple to suggest something for Black. } 7... a6
{ This is the most common move ➼ the logic behind it is to play ...b5-b4. } 8.
Qe2
{ I find this plan to work best. Going  8.Ne5  is also fine, but after  8...Nxe5  9.dxe5  Nd7  I couldn't come up with a super straightforward plan even though White has a great position. For this reason I made 8.Qe2 the main move as I find it easier. I think it's also instructive to highlight the fact that the queen belongs here and not on c2 like most of the London beginners would play. }
8... b5 { Going for the ...b4-push. } 9. e4
{ Threatening to expand in the center with e5! } 9... dxe4 10. Nxe4
{ We can stop here and say that White is slightly better with the extra space in the center and an easy plan to play O-O followed by Rad1 and Ne5.   A common mistake that Black makes here is  10...Nxe4  allowing  11.Qxe4  winning a piece because of the double threat of Qxh7 and Qxc6! }
*

