2... Nf6 3. Bf4 Nc6
{ Going for the Chigorin Defense. This is by far the most popular choice below 1600 blitz on chess.com! People that play this generally don't know that they are playing 'The Chigorin Defense' and they are simply trying to get their pieces developed according to the common sense rules @@StartBracket@@Developing their knights before the bishops@@EndBracket@@. }
4. e3
{ Now Black has a choice between three equally popular plans:   4...Bf5  4...Bg4  4...e6. }
4... e6
{ Locking the light-squared bishop inside the pawn chain. Against this plan ➼ it is less effective to go  5.Bb5  because Black can easily deal with the pin by answering  5...Bd7!  Against this plan I suggest we stick with the standard London System play ➼ and we no longer go for the exploitative approach with Bb5. }
5. Nbd2 Bd6 { Offering the bishop trade ➼ this is Black's most common move. }
6. c3
{ Going for an improved version of the Berkes structure after  6...Bxf4  7.exf4  ➼ because Black has a passive light-squared bishop.   @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/ppp2ppp/2nbpn2/3p4/3P1B2/4PN2/PPPN1PPP/R2QKB1R w KQkq - 2 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Bg3  is a perfectly fine alternative, but it could lead to some unnecessary complications. I prefer  6.c3  because I think it's the simplest and most effective approach. Black now has a choice between:  6... O-O  6...Bxf4. }
6... O-O
{ This is less frequent compared to 6...Bxf4, but it's played by people that have already suffered enough against the improved Berkes structure! }
7. Bd3 Re8
{ This is Black's main plan ➼ they are preparing the ...e5-break! If they can get it, Black has no problems. That's a pretty big 'if', though! }
8. Ne5
{ This move completely shuts down Black's pieces. Just look how pointless the e8-rook is! Black now has a choice between:  8... Bxe5  8...Nd7. }
8... Bxe5 { Getting rid of the e5-knight is a natural thing to do. } 9. dxe5
{ This is the typical way to recapture ➼ hitting the f6-knight and making Black's king weaker overall. }
9... Nd7 { Attacking the e5-pawn. } 10. Nf3 { Protecting the e5-pawn. } 10...
f6
{ This is the most common way for Black to generate some play.  10...Nc5  11.Bc2!  gives White good attacking chances on the kingside with h4 followed by Ng5 ideas. }
11. exf6 Nxf6
{ Threatening to push ...e5! This is the only move because  11...Qxf6  12.Bxc7!  drops a pawn, while @@StartFEN@@r1bqr1k1/pppn2pp/2n1pP2/3p4/5B2/2PBPN2/PP3PPP/R2QK2R b KQ - 0 11@@EndFEN@@  11...gxf6  12.Nh4!  followed by Qh5 gives White a huge attack. }
12. Ne5
{ Stopping Black's only source of counterplay ➼ the ...e5-break! A typical line that proves White's dominance is  12...Nxe5  13.Bxe5  Nd7  14.Qh5  g6  15.Bxg6!  hxg6  16.Qxg6+  Kf8  17.Qg7# }
