[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1) Chigorin Defense"]
[Black "Chigorin: 2...Nf6 3.Bf4 Nc6 with 4...Bg4 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3
{ This is the most precise move ➼ avoiding the annoying  2.Bf4  c5!  which gives us some headaches as explained in this informational. }
2... Nf6 3. Bf4 Nc6
{ Going for the Chigorin Defense. This is by far the most popular choice below 1600 blitz on chess.com! People that play this generally don't know that they are playing 'The Chigorin Defense' and they are simply trying to get their pieces developed according to the common sense rules @@StartBracket@@Developing their knights before the bishops@@EndBracket@@. }
4. e3
{ Now Black has a choice between three equally popular plans:   4...Bf5  4...Bg4  4...e6. }
4... Bg4
{ 4...Nh5  is a rare choice that should be mentioned. We reply  5.Be5  . This move works best with the idea to meet  5...Nxe5  with  6.dxe5!  and Black's h5-knight is stuck on the rim. We will see more of the same concept in later chapters. Here after  @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/ppp1pppp/2n5/3pB2n/3P4/4PN2/PPP2PPP/RN1QKB1R b KQkq - 2 5@@EndFEN@@  5...f6  6.Bg3  Nxg3  7.hxg3⩲  White has a slightly better position thanks to the open h-file. We can meet  7...e5  with  8.dxe5  fxe5  9.Bb5!  when Black is struggling to protect the e5-pawn. }
5. h3
{ Forcing Black to show what he intends to do with the light-squared bishop. They have a choice between:  5...Bh5  5...Bxf3. }
5... Bxf3
{ This is less popular compared to 5...Bh5, but it's still an important line to understand. }
6. Qxf3
{ We could be lazy and claim that White has a better position with the bishop pair. However, I think it's better to dive a bit deeper in this line since it's pretty easy to predict how the game could go. }
6... e6 7. c3 { Preparing to play Nd2 and then we decide. } 7... Bd6
{ 7...Be7  is less active compared to the development to d6. After  8.Nd2  O-O  9.Bd3  a6  10.O-O  ⩲  We will break with e4 and White is slightly better with the extra space and the bishop pair. }
8. Nd2
{ After this flexible move, Black has a choice between:  8...O-O  8...Bxf4. }
8... O-O
{ 8...Bxf4  is Black's most common move.  9.exf4  enters the Berkes structure ➼ limiting Black's counterplay based on ...e5, and after  9...O-O  10.Bd3⩲  White has a slightly better position with bishop against knight and good control over the center. }
9. g4
{ Threatening to push on the kingside with h4 followed by O-O-O. I think the only move that makes sense for Black is to strike in the center. }
9... e5 10. Bg5 { After this move White gets a slightly better endgame. } 10...
h6 11. Bxf6 { The simplest. The computer suggests the funny  11.h4!? } 11...
Qxf6 12. Qxf6 gxf6 13. O-O-O
{ We can continue with Bd3 followed by Rhg1 and Nf1-Ng3. White has some initiative on the kingside based on h4-g5! }
