1. d4 d5 2. Nf3
{ This is the most precise move ➼ avoiding the annoying  2.Bf4  c5!  which gives us some headaches as explained in this informational. }
2... Nf6 3. Bf4 Nc6
{ Going for the Chigorin Defense. This is by far the most popular choice below 1600 blitz on chess.com! People that play this generally don't know that they are playing 'The Chigorin Defense' and they are simply trying to get their pieces developed according to the common sense rules @@StartBracket@@Developing their knights before the bishops@@EndBracket@@. }
4. e3
{ Now Black has a choice between three equally popular plans:   4...Bf5  4...Bg4  4...e6. }
4... Bg4
{ 4...Nh5  is a rare choice that should be mentioned. We reply  5.Be5  . This move works best with the idea to meet  5...Nxe5  with  6.dxe5!  and Black's h5-knight is stuck on the rim. We will see more of the same concept in later chapters. Here after  @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/ppp1pppp/2n5/3pB2n/3P4/4PN2/PPP2PPP/RN1QKB1R b KQkq - 2 5@@EndFEN@@  5...f6  6.Bg3  Nxg3  7.hxg3⩲  White has a slightly better position thanks to the open h-file. We can meet  7...e5  with  8.dxe5  fxe5  9.Bb5!  when Black is struggling to protect the e5-pawn. }
5. h3
{ Forcing Black to show what he intends to do with the light-squared bishop. They have a choice between:  5...Bh5  5...Bxf3. }
5... Bh5 { Keeping the tension ➼ this is Black's most common way to react. } 6.
Bb5
{ This is the best practical try in my opinion. The computer is a big fan of  6.c4  , but from my personal experience combined with my student's feedback,  6.Bb5  works best. I want you to clearly understand that the light-squared bishop belongs to d3 in most London System positions and this is a very situational plan. By going for 6.Bb5 we are trying to exploit the fact that Black has committed to ...Nf6 and there will no longer be ...Nge7 ideas to protect the c6-knight after we play g4 followed by Ne5! like they could do after  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.Nf3  Nc6  3.Bf4  Bf5  4.e3  e6  5.Bb5  Bd6  6.Ne5  Nge7!  and Black is safe.Now Black has a choice between two main moves:  6... e6  6...a6. }
6... e6
{ This is the most common move for Black ➼ preparing ...Bd6 followed by O-O. Little do they know what's coming! }
7. g4
{ Breaking the pin so we can exploit the c6-knight by playing Ne5 on the next move. }
7... Bg6 8. Ne5
{ Many players just don't expect this combination. Black has no comfortable way to defend the c6-knight. }
8... Bd6 9. Nxc6 bxc6
{ This is the most common reply in online chess. People just give up on the exchange generally. }
10. Bxc6+
{ We will collect the a8-rook on the next move ➼ with a winning position for White thanks to the extra material. }
