[White "2) Englund Gambit"]
[Black "Introduction"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 e5 2. dxe5
{ In this chapter, we will be refuting the dubious and somewhat controversial Englund Gambit. This opening is filled with many dirty traps, but as long as you follow my recommendations you will not only avoid a quick loss but also get a winning position from the opening!  The material will be split into two parts:  •  2...Bc5  @@StartBracket@@the Eric Rosen trap@@EndBracket@@  •  2...Nc6  @@StartBracket@@followed by ...Qe7 with the standard lines@@EndBracket@@ }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2) Englund Gambit"]
[Black "Englund: 2...Bc5"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 e5
{ The Englund Gambit ➼ this is the guilty pleasure of all amateurs. We can almost hear Eric Rosen saying 'Oh no, my knight!' when this move appears on the board. Objectively speaking ➼ this opening is just losing, but we already know that 'Black has some tricks'. }
2. dxe5 Bc5
{ This is Eric Rosen's pet line, and I am sure that if you are reading this chapter you already know what Black's idea is... }
3. Nf3 d6 4. Bf4
{ Spoiling Black's fun! This is objectively best ➼ threatening to play exd6 which will create an isolated pawn for Black.  4.exd6  Ne7  @@StartBracket@@'Oh no, my knight!'@@EndBracket@@  5.dxe7  Bxf2+!  6.Kxf2  Qxd1  is something we need to stay away from! }
4... Ne7 5. e3
{ This is the simplest. Closing the g1-a7 diagonal ➼ making sure that there will be no ...Bxf2+ tricks.   5.exd6  is perfectly fine as well. }
5... Nbc6 6. exd6 { Creating the isolated pawn which will be our main target. }
6... cxd6 { Threatening to play ...Qb6 which could be a bit annoying. } 7. c3
{ This is the cleanest! The point is to meet  7...Qb6  with  8.b4!  winning the c5-bishop. }
7... O-O 8. Be2
{ We can continue with O-O followed by Nbd2 with an extra pawn and a better position for White. As a general strategy we should try to exchange as many pieces as possible in order to make the conversion easier, while you can also try to focus on the isolated d6-pawn. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2) Englund Gambit"]
[Black "Englund: 2...Nc6 3.Nf3 d6"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 e5
{ The Englund Gambit ➼ this is the guilty pleasure of all amateurs. We can almost hear Eric Rosen saying 'Oh no, my knight!' when this move appears on the board. Objectively speaking ➼ this opening is just losing, but we already know that 'Black has some tricks'. }
2. dxe5 Nc6 { Attacking the e5-pawn ➼ this is the old school variation. } 3.
Nf3 { Developing the knight while protecting the e5-pawn. } 3... d6
{ Trying to play for positional compensation. This line is way less frequently seen compared to 3... Qe7, but it can be pretty annoying if you relax too early. }
4. Bg5
{ This is the most precise way to counter Black's set-up! After this move it's not easy at all for Black to get his pieces developed. }
4... f6
{ Never play ...f6! Here it's an interesting move, but I just wanted to highlight more that the line is a bit dubious. Black's alternatives don't convince:   4...Be7  allows White to get a winning position without many chances to complicate the game after  5.Bxe7  Qxe7  6.exd6  , creating an isolated pawn which will be our main target. Following  6...cxd6  7.Nc3  @@StartBracket@@ threatening Nd5@@EndBracket@@  7...Nf6  8.e3  O-O  , I prefer  9.Be2±  just to avoid the annoying ...Bg4 pin. Developing to a more active square such as  9.Bd3  is perfectly fine, but from my experience ➼ most of my students are struggling to deal with 9...Bg4 because it can be tricky to unpin.   After  4...Qd7  Black's queen feels really awkward on that square. After  5.exd6  Bxd6  6.Nc3  Black has an interesting try in  6...f6!?  with the idea to place the queen on f7.  7.Bh4!  prepares to trade Black's strong bishop with Bg3, and after  7...Qf7  8.Bg3±  White trades off Black's most active piece and can continue with e3 followed by the standard Be2 and O-O. White is simply up a free pawn in these lines. }
5. exf6 Nxf6 6. Nc3 { Developing the knight to its most active square. } 6...
Be7 7. e3 { Preparing to finish development with Be2 followed by O-O. } 7...
O-O 8. Be2
{ We are going to castle short on the next move and White is simply up a pawn. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2) Englund Gambit"]
[Black "Englund: 2...Nc6 3.Nf3 Qe7 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 e5
{ The Englund Gambit ➼ this is the guilty pleasure of all amateurs. We can almost hear Eric Rosen saying 'Oh no, my knight!' when this move appears on the board. Objectively speaking ➼ this opening is just losing, but we already know that 'Black has some tricks'. }
2. dxe5 Nc6 { Attacking the e5-pawn ➼ this is the old school variation. } 3.
Nf3 { Developing the knight while protecting the e5-pawn. } 3... Qe7
{ Hitting the e5-pawn one more time ➼ this is Black's main idea. } 4. Bf4
{ Protecting the e5-pawn. With this move we are going for the refutation because I believe this gives White the biggest advantage.   In case you are struggling to memorize these forcing lines you could keep it simple by playing  4.Nc3  Nxe5  5.e4  with no complications at all, and White is clearly better because Black's queen is misplaced on e7. }
4... Qb4+
{ This is how Black begins setting up the traps. After this move Black is going for an adventurous journey with the queen hoping that White will be unable to defend against some cheap tricks. }
5. Bd2
{ This is forced ➼ keeping the bishop safe and attacking Black's queen. } 5...
Qxb2 { Attacking the a1-rook. } 6. Nc3
{ This is very important to remember! According to the statistics one out of four players goes  6.Bc3??  which is losing on the spot after  6...Bb4!  and now a famous variation goes  7.Qd2  Bxc3  8.Qxc3  Qc1#  .   After the important  6.Nc3!  Black has a choice between:  6...Bb4  6... Nb4. }
6... Nb4 { Threatening ...Nxc2! } 7. Nd4
{ Protecting the c2-pawn ➼ we are ready to play Rb1 next which gets rid of the annoying queen. This move is important because  7.Rc1  Nxa2!  is very unclear. }
7... c5
{ One last trick! Black hopes to scare us into moving away the d4-knight which would allow ...Nxc2+ winning the queen!   A more solid approach by Black would be  7...c6  , but then  8.Rb1  gets rid of the annoying queen and after  8...Qa3  9.Ne4!  +-  White has a simple threat of playing Nf5 followed by Nd6+! and there is not much that Black can do about it. }
8. Rb1
{ After this intermezzo White is completely winning being so ahead in development while all the tricks are gone. }
8... Qa3 9. Ndb5 { Attacking Black's queen and threatening Nc7+! } 9... Qa5
{ The only move to keep the c7-square under control. } 10. a3
{ Forcing the b4-knight to go back. } 10... Nc6 11. Nd5
{ Attacking the a5-queen and we are ready to play Nc7+ on the next move. Black's position is resignable at this point. }
*

