[Black "Copycat: 2...Bf5 without early ...Nf6"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3
{ This is the most precise move ➼ avoiding the annoying  2.Bf4  c5!  which gives us some headaches as explained in this informational. }
2... Bf5
{ This will most likely transpose to the normal 'Copycat lines', but Black has some additional options to delay ...Nf6! }
3. Bf4 e6 4. e3 Bd6
{ This is the only sensible option to deviate from the standard 4... Nf6 lines. }
5. Bg3
{ I find this to be the easiest way to deal with Black's tricky move order. Obviously  5...Bxg3  6.hxg3  is very pleasant for White, so Black needs to avoid that. }
5... Nf6 6. Bd3
{ Inviting  6...Bxd3  7.cxd3  which leads to our beloved typical pawn structure. }
6... Ne4
{ 6...Bg6  7.Ne5!  The standard way to deal with ...Bg6! The point is to win the enemy bishop with Nxg6.  7...Nbd7  8.Nxg6  Eliminating the bishop.  8...hxg6  9.Bxd6!  This is important because Black was threatening ...Bxg3 and we would have been forced to recapture with the f-pawn because of the pin along the h-file.  9...cxd6  10.Nd2⩲  With a slightly better position for White with bishop against knight. }
7. Bxe4 { Using the same idea as in the normal lines. } 7... Bxe4
{ 7...dxe4  8.Nfd2⩲  We can continue with c4 followed by Nc3 when White has a slightly better position because of the vulnerable black e4-pawn. }
8. Nbd2 { Attacking the e4-bishop and preparing the c4-push. } 8... Bg6 9. c4
{ Threatening to play Qb3! } 9... dxc4 10. Nxc4 Bb4+
{ This check might seem a bit annoying at first. } 11. Ncd2
{ We can simply block. There is no need for the fancy  11.Ke2!? } 11... O-O 12.
Rc1 { We can continue with O-O next. White has pressure on the queenside. } *

