1. d4 d5 2. Nf3
{ This is the most precise move ➼ avoiding the annoying  2.Bf4  c5!  which gives us some headaches as explained in this informational. }
2... Bg4
{ This is a typical mistake made in lower rated games. Black is trying to unbalance White's structure with ...Bxf3 in order to avoid the standard London System gameplay. In terms of popularity ➼ this is as common as 2...c5  @@StartBracket@@ known as The Tarrasch Defense@@EndBracket@@, so we need to be aware of it because I've noticed my students face this move quite regularly. }
3. Ne5
{ This is the key move that a lot of London System beginners are missing! White gets a very dangerous initiative because the enemy light-squared bishop becomes a target. }
3... Bh5 { This move allows White to go for quick kingside play. } 4. g4 Bg6 5.
h4
{ Threatening to push h5 ➼ trapping the g6-bishop! Black does not have a good way to deal with this move. }
5... f6
{ 5...h6  leads to similar structures compared to what we've seen in the 5...f6 lines, except Black gets an additional option to defend the g6-pawn with ...Qd6!  6.Nxg6  fxg6  7.Qd3  Attacking Black's biggest weakness ➼ the g6-pawn!  7...Qd6  8.Nc3  a6  9.Bg2  Attacking the d5-pawn.  9...c6  10.e4±  After opening up the position, White is much better being ahead in development. }
6. Nxg6 hxg6 7. Qd3 { Attacking Black's biggest weakness ➼ the g6-pawn! } 7...
Kf7 8. h5 gxh5 9. gxh5
{ With Qg6 ideas. White is much better because Black already lost the right to castle. }
