1. d4 d5 2. Nf3
{ This is the most precise move ➼ avoiding the annoying  2.Bf4  c5!  which gives us some headaches as explained in this informational. }
2... Bg4
{ This is a typical mistake made in lower rated games. Black is trying to unbalance White's structure with ...Bxf3 in order to avoid the standard London System gameplay. In terms of popularity ➼ this is as common as 2...c5 @@StartBracket@@ known as The Tarrasch Defense@@EndBracket@@, so we need to be aware of it because I've noticed my students face this move quite regularly. }
3. Ne5
{ This is the key move that a lot of London System beginners are missing! White gets a very dangerous initiative because the enemy light-squared bishop becomes a target. }
3... Bf5 4. c4
{ This is objectively best ➼ introducing Qb3 ideas. While going for the hyper aggressive  4.g4  is also possible, Black has an additional option to retreat the bishop on the c8-h3 diagonal and it's no longer that simple to make progress. }
4... f6
{ 4...e6  5.cxd5  exd5  6.Qb3!  Attacking the b7-pawn.  6...b6  7.Nc3  Attacking the d5-pawn.  7...c6  8.e4±  White is much better after this move because Black has problems with the f7-square @@StartBracket@@that's why Black can't capture on e4@@EndBracket@@. }
5. Nf3 e6
{ 5...dxc4  6.Nc3⩲  With e4 next followed by regaining the pawn with Bxc4 ➼ White is clearly better. }
6. Nc3 Bb4 7. Qb3
{ Attacking the b4-bishop and putting pressure on the d5-square. } 7... Bxc3+
8. bxc3 { Attacking the b7-pawn. } 8... b6 9. e3 Ne7 10. cxd5
{ This is a typical idea to put pressure in the center ➼ making use of the doubled pawns. }
10... exd5 11. c4
{ White is clearly better with the bishop pair and pressure in the center. } *

