{ This is somewhat similar to @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.Nf3  Bg4  We are going to react in the same fashion, by going for the aggressive knight move! }
4. Ne5
{ This is the key move to punish the early ... Bg4! White is creating a big positional threat of Nxg4. }
4... Bf5 5. e3 { Preparing to push g4. } 5... e6
{ This is by far the most natural move, preparing to develop the dark squared bishop and castle. }
6. g4 { This move gives White a powerful initiative. } 6... Bg6
{ The natural reply. Keep in mind that  6...Be4  won't change anything after  7.f3  and we get back into the normal lines.   6...Nxg4!!  The engine comes up with this stunning move, but I don't really expect any of your opponents to find it.  7.Nxg4  h5  8.Ne5  g5!  The point! Black is able to regain the piece.  9.Bg3  h4  10.Nxf7!  Giving back the piece in a good version for us because the enemy king is exposed.  10...Kxf7  11.Be5⩲  With an edge for White because we can continue with Nc3-Bd3-Qf3 and O-O-O while Black is having a hard time coordinating. }
7. h4 { Threatening to push h5 ➼ trapping the g6-bishop. } 7... h6
{ This is the most popular reaction.  7...h5  leads to similar positions. } 8.
Nxg6 { Creating a big weakness on g6. } 8... fxg6 9. Bd3
{ Targeting the weak g6-pawn. } 9... Kf7 10. Qf3
{ We can continue with Nc3-Qf3 followed by O-O-O and White has a huge threat of pushing g5. }
