[White "3) Copycat"]
[Black "Copycat 5...Bg6: Why I don't recommend 5.c4"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3
{ This is the most precise move ➼ avoiding the annoying  2.Bf4  c5!  which gives us some headaches as explained in this informational. }
2... Nf6 3. Bf4 Bf5 4. e3 e6
{ 4...c6  would transpose to the Slav Defense Chapter. } 5. c4 Bxb1
{ The most discouraging move. Not to mention  5...Bd6  and  5...Bb4+  are equally annoying and should give Black a comfortable game. }
6. Rxb1
{ Carlsen's most recent try!   6.Qxb1  is another line, but a bit inferior to Carlsen's latest try. He used this line as well on many occassions a few years back, but seems that Black is fine with best play.  6...Bb4+  7.Kd1  This is another alternative for White to meet 5...Bxb1, and we have seen over 100 Grand Masters-games with a 50/50 score. There is definitely a lot of play left, but I find it pretty uncomfortable to play as White, and it doesn't really allow us to get typical London play. }
6... Bb4+ 7. Ke2
{ This is a highly debated position in top level chess, but I find it incredibly tricky to play, and even if you manage to understand all the subtleties, Black should be able to equalise comfortably with best play. }
*

