[Black "Copycat: 5...Bg6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3
{ This is the most precise move ➼ avoiding the annoying  2.Bf4  c5!  which gives us some headaches as explained in this informational. }
2... Nf6 3. Bf4 Bf5 4. e3 e6
{ 4...c6  would transpose to the Slav Defense Chapter. } 5. Bd3
{ The simplest and most effective way of dealing with the ...Bf5 lines in general. Black can now choose between:   5...Bxd3 @@StartBracket@@the most popular move@@EndBracket@@  5...Bg6 @@StartBracket@@the flexible move@@EndBracket@@  5...Ne4 @@StartBracket@@using our favorite plan against us!@@EndBracket@@  5...Bd6 @@StartBracket@@the 'copy-cat'@@EndBracket@@. }
5... Bg6
{ With this move Black is staying very flexible, allowing White to take on g6 and open up the h-file for the rook. Another idea is to trade on d3 once White pushes the c-pawn, so that retaking on d3 with the pawn will no longer be an option for White. }
6. Ne5 Be7
{ This is less frequently seen compared to 6...Bd6, but still a pretty natural move. }
7. O-O
{ As in the 6...Bd6 lines, we are still giving Black the chance to take on d3 and improve our control over the center. }
7... O-O 8. Nxg6
{ Grabbing the bishop and going for solid positional play next. } 8... hxg6 9.
c3
{ Keeping it very 'London'-like. There is no need to venture into pushing c4. }
9... c5 10. Nd2 Nc6 11. Qe2
{ With a slightly better position for White thanks to the bishop pair. A simple and effective plan is to bring the rook with Rad1 and then we have a nice combo of dxc5 followed by e4! ➼ opening up the position for the bishop pair.   Keep in mind that  11...Nh5  can be met with  12.dxc5!  like in the game between Berkes-Tratar, 2017. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3) Copycat"]
[Black "Copycat: 5...Bg6 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3
{ This is the most precise move ➼ avoiding the annoying  2.Bf4  c5!  which gives us some headaches as explained in this informational. }
2... Nf6 3. Bf4 Bf5 4. e3 e6
{ 4...c6  would transpose to the Slav Defense Chapter. } 5. Bd3
{ The simplest and most effective way of dealing with the ...Bf5 lines in general. Black can now choose between:   5...Bxd3 @@StartBracket@@the most popular move@@EndBracket@@  5...Bg6 @@StartBracket@@the flexible move@@EndBracket@@  5...Ne4 @@StartBracket@@using our favorite plan against us!@@EndBracket@@  5...Bd6 @@StartBracket@@the 'copy-cat'@@EndBracket@@. }
5... Bg6
{ With this move Black is staying very flexible, allowing White to take on g6 and open up the h-file for the rook. Another idea is to trade on d3 once White pushes the c-pawn, so that retaking on d3 with the pawn will no longer be an option for White. }
6. Ne5 Bd6
{ This is clearly the most popular place for the bishop, fighting for the e5-square. }
7. O-O
{ There is no need to rush with Nxg6 since the e5-knight is an annoying piece for Black. We don't really mind if Black changes his mind and takes on d3, as we will get a nice initiative as shown in the game between Korobov-Mamedyarov, 2020. }
7... Nbd7
{ Threatening ...Bxe5 followed by ...Nh5 with good counterpay for Black. } 8.
Nxg6
{ The logical follow up, cashing in the light-squared bishop. Please keep in mind that opening up the h-file for Black's rook is not dangerous at all in this case @@StartBracket@@I know many users might have second thoughts about this@@EndBracket@@, and we will safely be able to put pressure on the queenside. }
8... hxg6 9. Bxd6
{ Another move that might be a little bit surprising because we are improving Black's control over the center. The point is that Black simply has no way to benefit from this, as pushing the e-pawn will not really achieve much as you will see in the following moves, and we can put pressure on the queenside with c3-Qb3. }
9... cxd6 10. Nd2 e5
{ This move comes very naturally for Black. In case of a waiting game with  10...O-O  White can simply play  11.c3  followed by Qb3 with play on the queenside. A typical plan could look something like a4-a5 followed by Qa3 and then push the b-pawn. }
11. c3 { Overprotecting the center and preparing Qb3. } 11... e4 12. Be2
{ Notice how nicely the bishop covers the g4-square which could have been potentially used by Black's knight in some lines. }
12... Qe7 13. Qb3 Rb8 14. Qa3
{ Threatening the direct Qxa7, while also keeping an eye on the d6-pawn. }
14... a6 15. c4
{ It's not clear what Black will do with the open h-file, while we have easy play on the other side of the board. We can continue with the natural Rac1 and then cxd5 followed by Nc4 is something that Black should be really worried about, as the d6-pawn is in danger. }
