[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3
{ This is the most precise move ➼ avoiding the annoying  2.Bf4  c5!  which gives us some headaches as explained in this informational. }
2... Nf6 3. Bf4 Bf5 4. e3 e6
{ 4...c6  would transpose to the Slav Defense Chapter. } 5. Bd3
{ The simplest and most effective way of dealing with the ...Bf5 lines in general. Black can now choose between:   5...Bxd3 @@StartBracket@@the most popular move@@EndBracket@@  5...Bg6 @@StartBracket@@the flexible move@@EndBracket@@  5...Ne4 @@StartBracket@@using our favorite plan against us!@@EndBracket@@  5...Bd6 @@StartBracket@@the 'copy-cat'@@EndBracket@@. }
5... Bg6
{ With this move Black is staying very flexible, allowing White to take on g6 and open up the h-file for the rook. Another idea is to trade on d3 once White pushes the c-pawn, so that retaking on d3 with the pawn will no longer be an option for White. }
6. Ne5 Bd6
{ This is clearly the most popular place for the bishop, fighting for the e5-square. }
7. O-O
{ There is no need to rush with Nxg6 since the e5-knight is an annoying piece for Black. We don't really mind if Black changes his mind and takes on d3, as we will get a nice initiative as shown in the game between Korobov-Mamedyarov, 2020. }
7... Nh5
{ This move initiaties a couple of trades, and Black is dreaming of an attack down the h-file. }
8. Nxg6
{ Sticking to the main plan of grabbing the bishop because Black's 'initiative' along the h-file should not provide him with any realistic chances of an attack, as shown in the model game between Brunello-De Ruiter, 2016. }
8... hxg6 9. Bxd6
{ Forced. Now Black has choice between:   9...Qxd6 @@StartBracket@@eyeing the h2-square@@EndBracket@@  9...cxd6 @@StartBracket@@trying to play in the center@@EndBracket@@. }
9... Qxd6
{ Keeping an eye on the h2-square. Notice that  9...cxd6  can be met in similar fashion as 7...Nbd7 with Nd2-c3-Qb3 and pressure on the queenside. }
10. c4
{ Playing for a quick storm on the queenside, following Grandmaster Brunello. The standard  10.c3  is also playable, it's just that the more aggressive move works very well in this case with Black's queen on d6, as c5 will come with tempo. }
10... Nf6 11. h3
{ This small move is a big problem for Black's attacking chances. } 11... c6
12. Nd2
{ This move might seem rather odd when the super natural Nc3 is available, but it will all become clear after the next couple of moves. }
12... Nbd7 13. c5 Qc7 { Threatening to push ...e5! } 14. f4
{ Stopping Black's counterplay and now the game is very one-sided. It becomes clear why the knight was developed to d2, because after the last key move, the knight can reach the e5-square via Nf3-Ne5! Make sure to check out the super instructive game between Brunello,S @@StartBracket@@2562@@EndBracket@@-De Ruiter,D @@StartBracket@@2312@@EndBracket@@ Amsterdam 2016, for a better understanding of this structure. }
