1. d4 d5 2. Nf3
{ This is the most precise move ➼ avoiding the annoying  2.Bf4  c5!  which gives us some headaches as explained in this informational. }
2... Nf6 3. Bf4 Bf5 4. e3 e6
{ 4...c6  would transpose to the Slav Defense Chapter. } 5. Bd3
{ The simplest and most effective way of dealing with the ...Bf5 lines in general. Black can now choose between:   5...Bxd3 @@StartBracket@@the most popular move@@EndBracket@@  5...Bg6 @@StartBracket@@the flexible move@@EndBracket@@  5...Ne4 @@StartBracket@@using our favorite plan against us!@@EndBracket@@  5...Bd6 @@StartBracket@@the 'copy-cat'@@EndBracket@@. }
5... Bg6
{ With this move Black is staying very flexible, allowing White to take on g6 and open up the h-file for the rook. Another idea is to trade on d3 once White pushes the c-pawn, so that retaking on d3 with the pawn will no longer be an option for White. }
6. Ne5 Bd6
{ This is clearly the most popular place for the bishop, fighting for the e5-square. }
7. O-O
{ There is no need to rush with Nxg6 since the e5-knight is an annoying piece for Black. We don't really mind if Black changes his mind and takes on d3, as we will get a nice initiative as shown in the game between Korobov-Mamedyarov, 2020. }
7... Bxd3
{ This might seem a bit surprising after playing ...Bg6, but some players might simply want to avoid giving up their precious bishop for the knight. This was seen in the game between Korobov-Mamedyarov, 2020. }
8. cxd3
{ The key recapture in our Repertoire, with a slightly improved version thanks to the knight on e5. These positions can become incredibly tricky to play for Black, and White has a relatively simple set-up that is just deadly. From now on, we will be following in Korobov's footsteps. }
8... c6 9. Nd2
{ There was nothing wrong with the natural  9.Nc3  ,  but Korobov is preparing to reinforce the e5-knight with Ndf3, which is a very interesting idea that took Mamedyarov by surprise. }
9... O-O 10. Qf3
{ The queen is heading towards h3, from where it will support White's kingside play. This is a common maneuver in the London System, and we see it more often with the light squared bishops on the board. Nevertheless, here is at least as strong. }
10... Nbd7
{ This move is usually a blunder, but here Black has a computer-ish counter trick! }
11. Nxc6
{ Thanks to this tactical trick, White can get a lot of free wins when Black's bishop remains unprotected on d6. }
11... bxc6
{ The computer realizes that after  11...Qc7!  White doesn't really have a good way to keep the extra pawn, and the position remains close to equal, but I still favor White in the upcoming forced lines. Play could continue  12.Ne5  Nxe5  13.dxe5  Bxe5  14.Rfc1!  , taking control over the c-file. This is an important intermezzo!  14...Qd6  15.Bxe5  Qxe5  16.Rc2  Preparing to double on the c-file.  16...Rac8  17.Rac1  Rxc2  18.Rxc2⩲  With the simple plan of playing Qd1-Qc1 ➼ gaining control over the c-file and then threatening Rc7. White has a pleasant position even though Black should be able to hold with best play. }
12. Bxd6 { With an extra pawn for White and a decisive advantage. } *

