[White "3) Copycat"]
[Black "Copycat: 5...Ne4 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3
{ This is the most precise move ➼ avoiding the annoying  2.Bf4  c5!  which gives us some headaches as explained in this informational. }
2... Nf6 3. Bf4 Bf5 4. e3 e6
{ 4...c6  would transpose to the Slav Defense Chapter. } 5. Bd3
{ The simplest and most effective way of dealing with the ...Bf5 lines in general. Black can now choose between:   5...Bxd3 @@StartBracket@@the most popular move@@EndBracket@@  5...Bg6 @@StartBracket@@the flexible move@@EndBracket@@  5...Ne4 @@StartBracket@@using our favorite plan against us!@@EndBracket@@  5...Bd6 @@StartBracket@@the 'copy-cat'@@EndBracket@@. }
5... Ne4
{ This move can be annoying to deal with, since it's trying to 'beat us with our own weapons'. I'm saying that because usually we are the one planting the knight in the center, but it can also happen the other way around! Luckily I think I came up with a pretty unorthodox, but efficient solution. }
6. Bxe4
{ This is not an ideal trade, to give up the bishop for the knight, but it's one that I think had to be done in order to deal with the annoying e4-knight once and for all. In return for this trade we are getting: -speedy development -queenside play -we are most likely winning back the bishop. }
6... Bxe4
{ The recapture  6...dxe4  can work, but it's quite risky strategically speaking. After  7.Nfd2  there's a big threat of Nc3 when Black has issues defending the e4-pawn.  7...Bd6  8.Bxd6  cxd6  9.c4!  prepares Qb3 and Nc3 when Black has some serious questions to answer. The line continues  9...Bg6  10.Nc3  f5  11.Qb3  Qd7  12.O-O  ⩲  when White will break with f3 on the next move. Black's position is really fragile. }
7. Nbd2 { Threatening Nxe4 ➼ damaging Black's pawn structure. } 7... Bxf3
{ This is playable, but generally I think Black will try to keep the bishop pair. }
8. Qxf3 Bd6
{ Looking forward to the exchange of bishops. The positions seems pretty flat, but White has a nice way to spice things up. }
9. h4
{ Thanks to this idea, Black will have some serious questions to answer on the kingside in this seemingly 'dull' position. }
9... Bxf4 10. exf4
{ I prefer this capture, keeping it very similar to what we get from the quick 4...Bd6 lines. The position should be objectively equal, but White keeps the easier game in the typical 'Berkes Structure'. }
10... Nc6 11. c3 Qf6 12. h5
{ With a lot of ways to improve White's position, while I couldn't come up with an obvious plan for Black. Our plan is pretty simple because we are going to castle long, bring the queen to e3 and then the knight can activate via Nf3-Ne5. }
