5... Bxd3
{ This is Black's most popular answer in both OTB and online chess. Taking on d3 is obviously very natural since Black is willing to continue with quick development without allowing White to double up his pawns after Bxf5. }
6. cxd3
{ This is where it gets interesting! Taking back with the pawn is four times less common than taking with the queen in both OTB and online chess, but I think it's a very underrated move! For an in-depth overview of the main plans and ideas, check out the double d-pawns structure in the Typical Structures chapter. }
6... Bd6
{ The most principled reply, challenging White's strong f4-bishop.   6...Be7  is less active compared to 6...Bd6 but it's still a natural move.  7.Nc3  O-O  8.Rc1  creates a big threat of Nb5, and after  8...c6  9.e4⩲  White has a pleasant position. We are going to castle short and then we can expand in the center with e5 followed by kingside play based on advancing the h-pawn. For more details check out the 'double d-pawns structure' in the Typical Pawn Structures chapter. }
7. Qb3
{ Hitting the b7-pawn and setting up a small trap. Now Black has to make an awkward move on the queenside. }
7... Qc8 8. Bg3
{ Not the only move, but I think it is the trickiest. You have a large choice depending on what works best against your opponents. A few honorable alternatives are  8.Bg5  and  8.Be5!?   Meanwhile,  8.Bxd6  is still playable, but it doesn't work as well as against 7...b6 because of the recapture  8...cxd6  .  The main issue with this structure is that Black's pawn is still on b7, meaning that we will no longer be able to exploit the weakness of the c6-square. For a better understanding of this theme make sure to check out the 'double d-pawns structure' in the Typical Pawn Structures chapter. }
8... O-O 9. Nc3 Nc6 { The knight is a little awkward on c6 in this structure. }
10. Rc1 Rb8 11. O-O Qd8
{ 11...Bxg3  is an alternative that has become more appealing, now that White has castled. But White can go for a positional squeeze after  12.hxg3  Qd8  13.Na4!  Ne7  14.Nc5  c6  15.Ne5⩲  , with a lasting initiative on the queenside based on the minority attack after Qa4 followed by pushing the b-pawn all the way to b5! }
12. Bh4
{ Creating an ugly pin and preparing to expand in the center with the standard Rfe1 followed by e4. White enjoys a pleasant position. }
