{ 4...c6  would transpose to the Slav Defense Chapter. } 5. Bd3
{ The simplest and most effective way of dealing with the ...Bf5 lines in general. Black can now choose between:   5...Bxd3 @@StartBracket@@the most popular move@@EndBracket@@  5...Bg6 @@StartBracket@@the flexible move@@EndBracket@@  5...Ne4 @@StartBracket@@using our favorite plan against us!@@EndBracket@@  5...Bd6 @@StartBracket@@the 'copy-cat'@@EndBracket@@. }
5... Bxd3
{ This is Black's most popular answer in both OTB and online chess. Taking on d3 is obviously very natural since Black is willing to continue with quick development without allowing White to double up his pawns after Bxf5. }
6. cxd3
{ This is where it gets interesting! Taking back with the pawn is four times less common than taking with the queen in both OTB and online chess, but I think it's a very underrated move! For an in-depth overview of the main plans and ideas, check out the 'double d-pawns structure' in the Typical Structures chapter. }
6... Bd6
{ The most principled reply, challenging White's strong f4-bishop.   6...Be7  is less active compared to 6...Bd6 but it's still a natural move.  7.Nc3  O-O  8.Rc1  creates a big threat of Nb5, and after  8...c6  9.e4⩲  White has a pleasant position. We are going to castle short and then we can expand in the center with e5 followed by kingside play based on advancing the h-pawn. For more details check out the double d-pawns structure in the Typical Structures chapter. }
7. Qb3
{ Hitting the b7-pawn and setting up a small trap. Now Black has to make an awkward move on the queenside. }
7... Bxf4 { You'd be surprised to see how common this move is! } 8. Qxb7
{ The good news is that White is simply up a pawn in the upcoming lines thanks to this cute intermezzo. }
8... Nbd7 { Forced, otherwise Black loses the exchange. } 9. exf4 O-O
{ After  9...Rb8  10.Qxa7  it's important to keep in mind that  10...Ra8  does not force a repetition because White would continue  11.Qb7  Rb8  12.Qc6!  with a big advantage.  Instead, @@StartFEN@@1r1qk2r/Q1pn1ppp/4pn2/3p4/3P1P2/3P1N2/PP3PPP/RN2K2R b KQk - 0 10@@EndFEN@@  10...Rxb2  is more natural but after  11.Qa3  Qb8  12.Nbd2±  White keeps an extra pawn, and Black's position is really uncomfortable. Their king is stuck in the center while ideas such as Nb3 are looming @@StartBracket@@the b2-rook gets in trouble@@EndBracket@@. }
10. O-O Rb8 11. Qxa7
{ This move is important so we can remain up a pawn. There is no danger because White's queen can easily come back into the game in various ways if Black tries attacking it. }
11... Rxb2 12. Rc1
{ After this move Black has big problems with the c7-pawn. I've reached this position quite often in my own games and I want to point out that the agressive  12...Ng4  can be met by the cold-blooded  13.h3!  when Black is losing material after  13...Nxf2  14.Qa3!  Qb8  15.Nbd2  and the knight gets trapped on f2. }
