1. d4 d5 2. Nf3
{ This is the most precise move ➼ avoiding the annoying  2.Bf4  c5!  which gives us some headaches as explained in this informational. }
2... Nf6 3. Bf4 Bf5 4. e3 e6
{ 4...c6  would transpose to the Slav Defense Chapter. } 5. Bd3
{ The simplest and most effective way of dealing with the ...Bf5 lines in general. Black can now choose between:   5...Bxd3 @@StartBracket@@the most popular move@@EndBracket@@  5...Bg6 @@StartBracket@@the flexible move@@EndBracket@@  5...Ne4 @@StartBracket@@using our favorite plan against us!@@EndBracket@@  5...Bd6 @@StartBracket@@the 'copy-cat'@@EndBracket@@. }
5... Bxd3
{ This is Black's most popular answer in both OTB and online chess. Taking on d3 is obviously very natural since Black is willing to continue with quick development without allowing White to double up his pawns after Bxf5. }
6. cxd3
{ This is where it gets interesting! Taking back with the pawn is four times less common than taking with the queen in both OTB and online chess, but I think it's a very underrated move! For an in-depth overview of the main plans and ideas, check out the double d-pawns structure in the Typical Structures chapter. }
6... Bd6
{ The most principled reply, challenging White's strong f4-bishop.   6...Be7  is less active compared to 6...Bd6 but it's still a natural move.  7.Nc3  O-O  8.Rc1  creates a big threat of Nb5, and after  8...c6  9.e4⩲  White has a pleasant position. We are going to castle short and then we can expand in the center with e5 followed by kingside play based on advancing the h-pawn. For more details check out the 'double d-pawns structure' in the Typical Pawn Structures chapter. }
7. Qb3
{ Hitting the b7-pawn and setting up a small trap. Now Black has to make an awkward move on the queenside. }
7... b6 8. Bxd6
{ My favorite move, but not the only way to play this position. What I love about these positions, it's the fact that we have so much room for fresh ideas. Just imagine: White has a lot of alternatives such as  8.Bg3  ,  8.Bg5  ,  8.Be5  ,  8.Ne5  , and even  8.O-O  seems interesting but leads to a complex pawn structure. You can try all of them and see what works best in your rating range.For example, in lower-rated games it might be a clever idea to play 8.Bg3 because people take on g3 all the time and you manage to open up the rook on h1. I picked 8.Bxd6 as the main move for the course because I feel like it's the best objectively and I scored quite well with it in my games. }
8... cxd6
{ Taking with the pawn is not completely out of the ordinary. The computer is not impressed with White's chances for an objective advantage, but in a practical game I feel like this position is quite dangerous because of the weak c6-square. I take a more in-depth look into this in the 'double d-pawn structure' in the Typical Pawn Structures chapter. }
9. Nc3 Nc6 10. Rc1
{ Placing the rook on the ideal square while also threatening Nxd5 ➼ winning a pawn. }
10... Qd7 { Keeping the c6-knight well defended.   10...O-O ??  11.Nxd5± } 11.
Qa4 { Making room for the b-pawn while reinforcing the Nxd5 trick. } 11... Rc8
{ Keeping the c6-knight safe.   11...O-O ?  Would give White a winning position quickly. After  12.Nxd5  White collects the c6-knight next with a big advantage. }
12. O-O O-O 13. b4
{ With the simple plan to double up on the c-file and then push b5. White has long-term pressure on the queenside. A typical maneuver that you want to keep in mind is that after you grab more space with a4, the c3-knight can be rerouted via Na2-Nb4 ➼ heading towards the weak c6-square. But for more details, make sure to check out the double d-pawns structure in the Typical Structures chapter. }
