[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4) Slav Defense"]
[Black "Introduction"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Bf4 c6 4. e3
{ In this chapter we will be dealing with the thematic Slav Defense lines while also covering the more unusual options, so the theory will be split between:  •  4...Bf5   •  4...Bg4   •  4...Nh5   •  4...Qb6   *in this chapter we also cover the Anti-London starting with @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  Nf6  2.Bf4  c6  3.Nf3  Qb6    To get familiar with the main plans for both sides you can check out The Slav Endgame.  Model endgames arising from this structure:  ➡ Nikolic Predrag-Piket Jeroen, Wijk aan Zee 1989  ➡ Grachev Boris-Rychagov Andrey, Moscow 2010 }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4) Slav Defense"]
[Black "Anti-London 3...Qb6: 4...Nh5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4
{ This is the most flexible move order ➼ making sure that we keep everything in London System teritory. For more details about the move order make sure to check out the informational. }
2... c6
{ Preparing to play ...Qb6 next ➼ this can be a very annoying sideline if you are not aware of it. }
3. Nf3 Qb6
{ Attacking the b2-pawn and trying to exploit the fact that we have developed the bishop so early in the game. }
4. Nbd2
{ This is the most dangerous way to counter Black's plan! Initially I wanted to make  4.Qc1  work like in the Slav lines, but the problem is that Black can go for  4...g6  and we get a strange version of the King's Indian. }
4... Nh5
{ This is very rare, but I managed to find an interesting try for White. } 5.
Nc4 { This variation is connected with a piece sacrifice. } 5... Qb4+
{ Going after the piece ➼ this is the most principled approach.   I feel like most of the players that play in this aggressive fashion, won't retreat with  5...Qd8  , but it's good to have an idea of how to deal with it. We answer  6.Bc1!  , which is the safest square for the bishop. We have a very strange position on the board. We can guess that Black will improve his knight with  6...Nf6  , when after  7.c3  we are playing in London System fashion anyways, we are just delaying Bf4 for a bit.  Going for some kind of King's Indian with  7...g6  seems logical for Black.  8.h3!  is a precise reply so we can play Bf4 without being bothered by ...Nh5!  Finally after  8...Bg7  9.Bf4  we get our beloved London System, and after  9...O-O  10.e3  d6  11.Be2⩲  we can castle short next and continue with the typical plan of going a4-a5 with a slightly better position for White. }
6. Bd2
{ This may be not enough for an objective advantage, but for sure it's going to shock your opponent. On a good day we might even trap their queen! }
6... Qxc4 7. e4
{ The point! White gets a strong center while Black has problems finding a safe square for the queen. }
7... Qa4 { This loses the queen. } 8. b3 { Forcing ...Qa3! } 8... Qa3 9. Ne5
{ Creating a double threat of Nc4 and Qxh5! } 9... Nf6 10. Nc4
{ Attacking Black's queen. } 10... Qa6 { The only square left. } 11. Nd6+
{ After this last trick White is cashing in the queen. } 11... exd6 12. Bxa6
Nxa6 13. O-O
{ With an interesting material balance, but a much better position for White because Black's pieces are far from being active we can continue with Re1 followed by c4-d5 ➼ suffocating Black's pieces! }
*

