[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4) Slav Defense"]
[Black "Anti-London 3...Qb6: 4...d5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4
{ This is the most flexible move order ➼ making sure that we keep everything in London System teritory. For more details about the move order make sure to check out the informational. }
2... c6
{ Preparing to play ...Qb6 next ➼ this can be a very annoying sideline if you are not aware of it. }
3. Nf3 Qb6
{ Attacking the b2-pawn and trying to exploit the fact that we have developed the bishop so early in the game. }
4. Nbd2
{ This is the most dangerous way to counter Black's plan! Initially I wanted to make  4.Qc1  work like in the Slav lines, but the problem is that Black can go for  4...g6  and we get a strange version of the King's Indian. }
4... d5
{ This could be a clever move order trick for Black ➼ transposing back into the Slav where we can no longer get the usual c4-c5 followed by Nc3 since the knight has already commited with Nbd2. The good news is that the d2-knight is also quite decently placed, and we can use the same plan with similar ideas. }
5. c4
{ Inviting Black to grab the poisoned pawn and threatening to push c5 ➼ going for a positional squeeze on the queenside.  5.Qc1  Nh5!  is a bit annoying! }
5... Qxb2
{ This move is very tempting, but White has a surprisingly powerful initiative.   5...Bf5  is a safer line for Black, going for a normal Slav. After  6.Qc1!  we get very similar plans compared to what we have seen in the Slav ➼ the only difference being that we have Nbd2 instead of Nc3 which is not a big deal. We can go for a thematic squeeze with  6...e6  7.c5  Qd8  8.b4  Nbd7  9.h3!  This is the safest move to start with ➼ getting ready to meet ...Nh5 with Bh2!  The line continues  9...Be7  10.e3  O-O  11.Be2  Ne4  12.O-O  Bf6  13.Nb3!  @@StartBracket@@ introducing ideas to play Na5!? @@EndBracket@@  13...Re8  @@StartBracket@@threatening to push ...e5 @@EndBracket@@  14.Qb2!  ⩲,  which is a nice idea to remember. The queen nicely prevents Black's typical ...e5-break from the b2-square, which is fairly typical for these Qc1 lines. Next up we can expand on the queenside in the usual way with a4-b5! }
6. cxd5
{ At first this looks like a blunder because Black's knight is coming over to c3 after ...Nxd5 ➼ but it's sealed with a deadly trap. }
6... cxd5 7. Rb1 Qa3
{ An important move because  7...Qxa2  8.Qc1!  gives White a large advantage, threatening both Qxc8 and Ra1. }
8. e4
{ After this stunning move White has a big advantage. The point is that  8...dxe4  9.Nc4!  traps Black's queen! }
8... Nxe4
{ This is Black's best try, but White is much better after the following forced sequence! }
9. Bxb8
{ This is important so Black loses the right to castle and we can play Bb5+ next. }
9... Rxb8 10. Bb5+ { Getting quick development and misplacing Black's king. }
10... Bd7 11. Bxd7+ Kxd7 12. Nxe4 dxe4 13. Ne5+ Ke8 14. O-O
{ Despite being down two pawns, White is completely winning, being so far ahead in development and Black having lost the right to castle. }
