{ This is the most flexible move order ➼ making sure that we keep everything in London System teritory. For more details about the move order make sure to check out the informational. }
2... c6
{ Preparing to play ...Qb6 next ➼ this can be a very annoying sideline if you are not aware of it. }
3. Nf3 Qb6
{ Attacking the b2-pawn and trying to exploit the fact that we have developed the bishop so early in the game. }
4. Nbd2
{ This is the most dangerous way to counter Black's plan! Initially I wanted to make  4.Qc1  work like in the Slav lines, but the problem is that Black can go for  4...g6  and we get a strange version of the King's Indian. }
4... Qxb2
{ This is the most logical move ➼ otherwise 3...Qb6 doesn't make much sense. }
5. e4
{ Setting up a strong center. We can already stop and say that White has good compensation, but I think it's worth mentioning some of the common traps in this variation. }
5... d6
{ Stopping White from pushing e5 ➼ this is the most common move for online chess, but it's actually a huge blunder!   5...d5  is an attempt to be more aggressive and play ...Ne4, but this approach will most likely backfire after  6.e5  grabbing more space and attacking the f6-knight.  6...Ne4  7.Nxe4!  gets rid of the active knight and creating a weak pawn on e4, and  after  7...dxe4  White has the important intermezzo  8.Rb1!  @@StartBracket@@ the immediate  8.Nd2  would allow  8...Qxd4  @@EndBracket@@. @@StartFEN@@rnb1kb1r/pp2pppp/2p5/4P3/3PpB2/5N2/PqP2PPP/1R1QKB1R b Kkq - 1 8@@EndFEN@@  8...Qxa2  9.Nd2  wins a tempo on the e4-pawn, when after  9...Qd5  10.Be3±  White can continue with Bc4 followed by O-O with a much better position. }
6. Nc4 Qb4+ 7. c3
{ This is the key move because after  7.Bd2  Qa4  Black would escape. } 7...
Qxc3+ 8. Bd2 { Winning Black's queen. } *

[Event "?"]
