[White "4) Slav Defense"]
[Black "Triangle Slav"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 e6 3. Bf4 c6
{ This is not a critical line at all, but it might be played by Triangle Slav players, so I would say that it's relatively common at the club level.   The move order @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp1pppp/8/3p4/3P4/8/PPP1PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.Nf3  c6  3.Bf4  Qb6  4.Qc1  is not problematic either because we can simply play e3 followed by c4-c5 transpose into our mainlines. }
4. e3 Bd6
{ This is by far the most common square for the bishop.  4...f5  This is always an alternative for the Triangle players, but it doesn't change anything compared to the standard move order from the Dutch.  5.c4  Nf6  6.Nc3  Transposing to the Dutch Defense.   4...Nf6  The only difference here compared to the main variation could be if Black plays with ...Be7!  5.Nbd2  Be7  6.Bd3  O-O  7.Ne5!  The standard London plan works really well against the Triangle Slav.  7...Nbd7  8.Qf3⩲  Preparing to play Qh3 on the next move with good attacking prospects on the kingside. White is simply much better in these lines because Black does not have any pressure in the center and they are stuck with the passive light-squared bishop. }
5. Nbd2
{ While  5.Bg3  was also perfectly playable in this case, I would much rather allow the Berkes structure ➼ highlighting Black's problems with the light squared bishop. }
5... Bxf4
{ The critical move, otherwise, we can continue in the typical fashion with Bd3-c3-Ne5-Qf3-Qh3 with good attacking prospects on the kingside. }
6. exf4 Nf6 7. Bd3
{ Developing using the standard square for the light squared bishop while keeping an eye on the enemy kingside. }
7... O-O 8. O-O Nbd7 { Preparing to break with ...c5! } 9. Re1 c5 10. c3
{ Protecting the d4-pawn and making a square on c2 for the bishop @@StartBracket@@in case Black tries ...c4@@EndBracket@@. }
10... cxd4 11. Nxd4
{ I think this is the simplest even though  11.cxd4  was also perfectly fine ➼ restricting Black's d7-knight. }
11... Nc5 12. Bc2
{ Important not to allow ...Nxd3 because the light squared bishop is exerting a lot of pressure against the enemy king. We can continue with Ndf3-Ne5 followed by Qe2-Rad1 with a better position thanks to the more active bishop. }
