[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4) Slav Defense"]
[Black "Slav: 4...Nh5"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5
{ 1...d5  2.Nf3  c6  3.Bf4  Qb6  4.Qc1  This move order is not really that problematic because we can simply play e3 followed by c4-c5 and we transpose. }
2. Nf3
{ This is the most precise move ➼ avoiding the annoying  2.Bf4  c5!  which gives us some headaches as explained in this informational. }
2... Nf6 3. Bf4 c6
{ This will most likely be the choice of Slav Defense players. Known as an ultra solid opening, rich in both strategical and tactical nuances, there is no question why a lot of players picked up the Slav. However, I consider it to be an inferior choice against our London System in particular. }
4. e3 Nh5
{ Going for the early bishop hunt is a rare choice for Black in this position, but it can be quite effective if White does not react properly. }
5. Be5
{ This is the typical way of punishing Black's premature ...Nh5 move. The idea is to strike in the center with c4 next, and any ...Nd7-Nxe5 will be met by dxe5! ➼ trapping Black's h5-knight on the rim. }
5... Nd7 { 5...Qb6  6.Qc1  transposes to 4...Qb6. } 6. c4
{ Generally we like playing with c3 in the London, but against the Slav Defense, our main weapon will be to play with c4. This strategy is really effective here because it catches the h5-knight a bit offside. }
6... e6 7. Nc3 Nxe5
{ This is the principled continuation after starting this super aggressive operation with 4...Nh5, but Black is getting an uncomfortable position against White's best play. Black has a few alternatives we should consider:   7...Be7  gets back into a position that is mostly seen from the Queen's Gambit Declined. I suggest  8.Bd3!  when White has a juicy 75% winrate after this move. It's clear that Black's h5-knight is not ideally placed, while White can set up a strong attack on the kingside as shown in the game Erdos-Kovacevic, which continued  8...O-O  9.Qc2  g6  10.h4  when White had a crushing attack with O-O-O and g4 in Erdos,V-Kovacevic,B Prague 2016.   After  7...Nhf6  I prefer going for quick development with  8.Bd3!  rather than trying to save the bishop with 8. Bf4, mainly because the latter would enter an important theoretical position in the QGD. Black's standard reply is  8...dxc4  ,  trying to 'steal' half a tempo.  9.Bxc4  Nxe5  10.Nxe5  Bd6  11.f4!  After we manage to get in the typical way of supporting the knight with f4, I think such positions should be easier to play as White. After  11...O-O  12.Qf3  we can continue with O-O followed by Rad1 with an easy game. Black should be close to equal with best play, but I find it incredibly tricky to play with the passive light-squared bishop. }
8. dxe5
{ The key move to punish the h5-knight. White has a huge threat of g4 and Black is in trouble. }
8... g6 9. h4 { Preparing g4 followed by h5! } 9... Be7 10. g4 Ng7
{ The knight fianchetto rarely works well! } 11. h5
{ With a lot of pressure on the kingside. We have a simple way to continue with Qc2 followed by O-O-O and Black is struggling to make sensible moves. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4) Slav Defense"]
[Black "Slav: 4...Qb6 5.Qc1 Nh5"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5
{ 1...d5  2.Nf3  c6  3.Bf4  Qb6  4.Qc1  This move order is not really that problematic because we can simply play e3 followed by c4-c5 and we transpose. }
2. Nf3
{ This is the most precise move ➼ avoiding the annoying  2.Bf4  c5!  which gives us some headaches as explained in this informational. }
2... Nf6 3. Bf4 c6
{ This will most likely be the choice of Slav Defense players. Known as an ultra solid opening, rich in both strategical and tactical nuances, there is no question why a lot of players picked up the Slav. However, I consider it to be an inferior choice against our London System in particular. }
4. e3 Qb6
{ This is always a tricky move to deal with if you are not familiar with it. }
5. Qc1
{ To make it easier to remember I came up with a set of rules which you can use to determine what the right response to ...Qb6 is. First of all, we will NEVER PLAY b3 against ...Qb6! Ideally we want to meet ...Qb6 with the simple Rb1 if that's a legal move. If not, we will heavily rely on Nc3 when ...Qxb2 can be answered by Nb5! ➼ with a strong initiative. However, in this position Nb5 is not an option due to Black's c6-pawn. Therefore the only remaining move is the best one, which is 5.Qc1! in our case. }
5... Nh5 6. Be5
{ This is the typical way to react against ... Nh5 in general in the Slav lines. The main point is to always capture back on e5 with the pawn after Black goes ... Nd7-Nxe5, after which the h5-knight is stuck on the rim. }
6... f6
{ This is a rather extreme way for Black to hunt the bishop, but we have a simple way to deal with it.   In case of  6...Nd7  we again play  7.c4  , the key move against the Slav.  7...Nxe5  8.dxe5!  traps Black's knight on the rim. This is the whole point of having played 6. Be5 in the first place. Black can create an escape square with  8...g6  , but we can develop with tempo with  9.cxd5  cxd5  10.Nc3  e6  11.Bb5+  and force Black to lose the right to castle.  11...Bd7  12.Bxd7+  Kxd7  13.O-O  We are ready to open up the position with e4 when Black's king is in a lot of trouble. }
7. Bxb8
{ Simple and strong. We are ready to attack in the center with c4 next, when Black's coordination is awkward. }
7... Rxb8 8. c4 { The key move against the Slav. } 8... g6 9. Nc3 e6 10. Bd3
Be7 11. Qc2 { Preparing O-O-O. } 11... O-O 12. h4
{ With a big initiative on the kingside based on O-O-O followed by g4. } *

