[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5
{ 1...d5  2.Nf3  c6  3.Bf4  Qb6  4.Qc1  This move order is not really that problematic because we can simply play e3 followed by c4-c5 and we transpose. }
2. Nf3
{ This is the most precise move ➼ avoiding the annoying  2.Bf4  c5!  which gives us some headaches as explained in this informational. }
2... Nf6 3. Bf4 c6
{ This will most likely be the choice of Slav Defense players. Known as an ultra solid opening, rich in both strategical and tactical nuances, there is no question why a lot of players picked up the Slav. However, I consider it to be an inferior choice against our London System in particular. }
4. e3 Qb6
{ This is always a tricky move to deal with if you are not familiar with it. }
5. Qc1
{ To make it easier to remember I came up with a set of rules which you can use to determine what the right response to ...Qb6 is. First of all, we will NEVER PLAY b3 against ...Qb6! Ideally we want to meet ...Qb6 with the simple Rb1 if that's a legal move. If not, we will heavily rely on Nc3 when ...Qxb2 can be answered by Nb5! ➼ with a strong initiative. However, in this position Nb5 is not an option due to Black's c6-pawn. Therefore the only remaining move is the best one, which is 5.Qc1! in our case. }
5... Bf5
{ This is the best square for the bishop and Black's most common move. } 6. c4
{ The key pawn push against the Slav. The plan is to fully expand on the queenside with c5-b4-a4-b5. Of course, we'll need to finish development in the meantime. }
6... e6
{ The most common continuation, and what I expect you to encounter the most going into these 4... Qb6 lines. }
7. c5 { The star move to expand on the queenside. } 7... Qd8
{ Black's most logical move. Going 7...Qa5+ doesn't make much sense since the queen will get harassed by a3-b4 in the future. }
8. Nc3
{ The standard square for the knight. Playing Nbd2 is not really a mistake since we might just very well transpose after Black plays ...Ne4 and we trade knights, but generally c3 is the standard developing square after you've moved the c-pawn forward. }
8... Nbd7
{ Black could also try  8...a5  ,  trying to slow down White's play on the queenside. I've run into this plan occasionally in my games. We continue with  9.h3  ,  making a square for the bishop on h2.   This was not mandatory, as for example, you can start with  9.Be2  ,  but it will always be a useful move in this structure. Sooner or later it has to be played, otherwise Black might go ...Nh5!  Now the line could continue  9...Be7  10.Be2  O-O  11.O-O  Nbd7  12.a3  intending to expand with b4. Now  12...a4  is the only sensible continuation. Otherwise White can push his pawns on the queenside easily. However,  13.Bd1!  hits the a4-pawn, forcing Black to play  13...b5  , when  14.Na2!  heads for the juicy square on b4. After  14...h6  15.Nb4  Qc8  16.b3⩲  White has a lasting initiative on the queenside. }
9. h3 { Making a square on h2 for the bishop ➼ making ...Nh5 less effective. }
9... Be7 10. Be2 Ne4
{ This is a tricky move, delaying ...O-O with the idea to meet  11.O-O  with  11...g5!? }
11. b4
{ The most precise! We are staying flexible and waiting for Black to castle first, avoiding the complications arising after  11.O-O  g5!?  ,  which could be a bit annoying as in Kamsky,G-Kramnik,V Turin 2006. }
11... O-O 12. O-O
{ Now we can safely castle, as ...g5 is no longer tempting for Black. } 12...
Bf6 13. Nxe4
{ The most precise way! Getting rid of the active knight.   13.b5?!  would generally be a big mistake because it allows a typical trick for this line,  13...Ndxc5=  This is what you have to watch out for. As long as you stay away from this, White has very nice pressure. }
13... Bxe4 14. Nd2 Bg6 { With the big threat of ...e5! } 15. Bd6
{ The start of a nice prophylactical sequence. } 15... Re8 16. f4
{ The key move to keep everything under control. We have managed to stop Black's key breakthrough with ...e5 and now we can focus on the queenside with a4-b5 with a lasting initiative, while Black has to wait and try to defend this passive position. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4) Slav Defense"]
[Black "Slav: 4...Bg4 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5
{ 1...d5  2.Nf3  c6  3.Bf4  Qb6  4.Qc1  This move order is not really that problematic because we can simply play e3 followed by c4-c5 and we transpose. }
2. Nf3
{ This is the most precise move ➼ avoiding the annoying  2.Bf4  c5!  which gives us some headaches as explained in this informational. }
2... Nf6 3. Bf4 c6
{ This will most likely be the choice of Slav Defense players. Known as an ultra solid opening, rich in both strategical and tactical nuances, there is no question why a lot of players picked up the Slav. However, I consider it to be an inferior choice against our London System in particular. }
4. e3 Bg4
{ This is another very common move for Black, used by strong players like Fedoseev and Jobava, though mainly in blitz. }
5. Nbd2
{ The most precise move order! Starting with  5.h3  is also reasonable, but Black would get an aditional option of  5...Bxf3  6.Qxf3  Qb6!?  and it's not so simple to defend the b2-pawn. }
5... e6
{ The most natural and most played move in the database.   5...Nbd7  is an interesting move order for Black, with the idea to prevent White from getting in the annoying Ne5-move. I suggest  6.h3  ,  nevertheless going for a similar structure, using the h4-square, this time for the knight. After  6...Bh5  7.g4  Bg6  8.Nh4!  we see a main theme of these 4...Bg4 lines, which is winning the bishop pair.  8...e6  9.Nxg6  hxg6  10.c3⩲  I don't think we need to dive deeper here since there are pretty much no games, and White has a simple, but effective plan. We are going to play Qf3 with the idea to castle long, finish development with Bd3 and then we can push on the kingside with h4. }
6. h3 Bxf3
{ This is the choice made by stronger players. As said earlier, they are mostly playing this line in blitz, so it makes a lot of sense to just give up the bishop pair and try to set up a solid structure that is easier to play in short time controls. Objectively speaking this is a bit better than the alternative 6... Bh5. }
7. Qxf3
{ This is the best way to recapture because the d2-knight is controlling the important e4-square. }
7... Bd6 8. g4
{ Starting with  8.O-O-O  is also fine, with the same plan. The important concept is to understand that because we have nice central control + the bishop pair, we can afford a bold move such as g4 without Black having a direct way to punish it. }
8... Bxf4 9. Qxf4 { Now Black has a choice between long and short castle. }
9... O-O
{ 9...Nbd7  has the idea to play ...Qe7 and ...O-O-O. We can continue  10.O-O-O  Qe7  11.h4  O-O-O  12.h5!  h6  13.Bd3⩲  With a lasting initiative for White in a positional battle on the kingside. }
10. O-O-O Nbd7 11. h4 { With good chances for White on the kingside. } *

