[White "4) Slav Defense"]
[Black "Slav 4...Bf5: why not 6.Nc3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5
{ 1...d5  2.Nf3  c6  3.Bf4  Qb6  4.Qc1  This move order is not really that problematic because we can simply play e3 followed by c4-c5 and we transpose. }
2. Nf3
{ This is the most precise move ➼ avoiding the annoying  2.Bf4  c5!  which gives us some headaches as explained in this informational. }
2... Nf6 3. Bf4 c6
{ This will most likely be the choice of Slav Defense players. Known as an ultra solid opening, rich in both strategical and tactical nuances, there is no question why a lot of players picked up the Slav. However, I consider it to be an inferior choice against our London System in particular. }
4. e3 Bf5
{ This is the most common way for Black to continue. The idea is to simply get the bishop outside the pawn chain before playing ...e6 followed by ...Bd6 @@StartBracket@@if allowed@@EndBracket@@ and ...O-O, with no bad pieces for Black and an equal game. }
5. c4
{ Here  5.c4!  followed by Qb3 gives White, unlike against 4... e6, the advantage, objectively speaking. The big difference is that Black's options are quite restricted in the Slav, making it easier for White to dictate the course of the game on the queenside. The idea is to apply immediate pressure on the b7-pawn with  @@StartFEN@@rn1qkb1r/pp2pppp/2p2n2/3p1b2/2PP1B2/4PN2/PP3PPP/RN1QKB1R w - - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  6.Qb3  and if Black tries to annihilate our pressure with  6...Qb6  , we can force a favorable endgame by going  7.c5! }
5... e6
{ The main line. Black doesn't really have much of a choice at this point. } 6.
Nc3
{ This super natural move is quite inaccurate because it allows Black to swap the dark-squared bishops by playing ...Bd6! }
6... Bd6 { After this important move, Black gets a comfortable game. } 7. Bxd6
{ Usually White simply accepts the trade. } 7... Qxd6 8. Qb3
{ This was tried by Kamsky in a blitz game, but even the biggest expert of the London failed to get any pressure from the opening.   8.c5  would be another natural move, but Black has a comfortable game once again because they can simply play ...Qe7-Nbd7 and break with ...e5!  8...Qe7  9.b4  White is taking a lot of space on the queenside, but what good for if we can't make any use of it?  9...Nbd7  10.Be2  O-O  11.O-O  e5∞  With no weaknesses and good control in the center, Black has no problems. }
8... Qe7
{ This is a nice way for Black to keep a solid position. It's pretty clear that after the bishop trade, it has become much easier for Black to organize his pieces. I will just attach the upcoming 10 moves of the Kamsky-Nastore game to illustrate how Black should get a comfortable position in this structure. }
9. Be2 O-O 10. O-O dxc4
{ Not the only move, but a nice one. Black's plan is connected with grabbing space over the queenside with ...b5! }
11. Bxc4 b5 12. Be2 Nbd7 13. Rfc1 Rfc8
{ Another fine positional move. This is the right rook because the other one will come to b8. }
14. Nh4
{ White manages to win the bishop, but Black's activity on the queenside is fully compensating. }
14... Bg6 15. Nxg6 hxg6 16. Bf3
{ Putting pressure on the long diagonal. If White could somehow fix Black's pawns on the queenside, that would result in a large positional advantage. It's not really the case here. }
16... Rab8
{ Stepping away from the dangerous diagonal and preparing to push ...c5! } 17.
a4 b4 18. Ne2 c5
{ With a very solid position for Black. This was just textbook play in the Slav. The game later ended in a draw. Kamsky,G-Nastore,P Chess.com INT 2022 }
