{ This is the most precise way to play for White. The idea is to apply immediate pressure on Black's queenside, so that they are not in time with ...Bd6 like in the 6. Nc3-line.Now Black has an important decision to make. The most common moves are:  6...Qb6 @@StartBracket@@the most common move@@EndBracket@@  6...Qc8 @@StartBracket@@Jobava's favorite@@EndBracket@@  6...b6 @@StartBracket@@common for lower-rated players@@EndBracket@@. }
6... Qc8
{ This is the best move, objectively speaking, if Black plays it properly. The good news is that White has a lot of deadly traps based on Nc3-Rc1 followed by cxd5-Nb5! and Black can get a losing position right away. This has happened in a lot of titled games. }
7. Nc3 Nbd7
{ This is the most common move order for Black in both OTB and online chess. }
8. Rc1
{ This line has an insane potential to give you a quick win according to my experience and what people do on average in the database. Even strong players have failed to avoid the upcoming deadly traps.   In case you are a fan of slower play, there is a good alternative in going  8.h3  followed by Be2 and O-O with a pleasant position. }
8... a6
{ Not the most common move, but quite a logical one because Black wants to stop White's Nb5 ideas. }
9. Nh4
{ This is not the only move, but by far the best! Suddenly Black has a lot of concrete problems. }
9... Be4
{ This is Black's best try, objectively speaking.   9...Bg6?!  is another natural move that doesn't save Black.  10.Nxg6  hxg6  11.cxd5  exd5?   After  11...Nxd5  12.Nxd5  exd5  13.e4±  Black is in a world of trouble yet again, because  13...dxe4?  runs into  14.Bc4+-  with a winning position for White.  12.e4+-  White is objectively winning already because of exd5/e5+Nxd5 ideas. Keep in mind that  12...dxe4  will be met by  13.Bc4!  and White has a crushing position. }
10. f3 dxc4 11. Bxc4
{ Now Black has a choice between 11...Bd5 and 11...Bg6, but both moves have their drawbacks. }
11... Bd5
{ The problem with this plan is that White will open up the position with e4 after Bxd5 first!   11...Bg6  12.O-O  Be7  13.Be2  is not the most natural retreat, but White is just opening up the c-file for the rook. After  13...O-O  14.Nxg6  hxg6  15.e4⩲  , with the two bishops and extra space, White is ready to expand with Be3 and f4 with a dominating position. }
12. Bxd5 cxd5
{ In case of  12...Nxd5  13.Nxd5  exd5  14.e4⩲  Black is in a very delicate spot. The computer likes ...g6, but that can usually be answered by g3-Ng2 while the pawn on d5 is still under a lot of pressure. Keep in mind that any careless ... Be7 move will run into Nf5! with a crushing advantage for White. }
13. e4 { Black's center is about to collapse. } *

