7... Bd6 { The main move, and the most critical variation after 6...b6. } 8.
Bxd6
{ I find this to be the simplest answer, giving us a choice on the next move between active and positional chess. }
8... Qxd6 9. Nh4
{ This is my main recommendation because objectively speaking, White can get a large advantage. If you are not comfortable going for the bishop hunt, you can by all means go for the slower 9.Be2  followed by O-O with a pleasant position for White.  Typically whenever we play Nh4, Black has a choice between three main moves:   9...Bg4  9...Bg6  9...Be4 @@StartBracket@@the most challenging@@EndBracket@@. }
9... Bg4
{ This is a standard way to meet Nh4 generally. Black's idea is to force White into 'overextending' before grabbing the bishop. }
10. h3 Bh5 11. g4
{ Going for the typical bishop hunt. You don't have to worry about the potential weakening on the kingside, because you will see that we can use it as an asset later on in the game. }
11... Bg6 12. Nxg6 hxg6 { Threatening ...Nxg4. } 13. Bg2
{ Keeping everything defended on the kingside and preparing the e4-break. }
13... g5 14. O-O-O Nbd7 15. Kb1
{ We are going to open up the position with e4 and it is pretty clear we have a dominating position thanks to the extra space and the powerful bishop. Remember that I said we are going to use what Black hopes to be a ''weak kingside'' as an asset? Notice that Black is struggling to castle short because we can open up the h-file with h4! and his king will be in danger. }
