{ This is the most precise move ➼ avoiding the annoying  2.Bf4  c5!  which gives us some headaches as explained in this informational. }
2... Nf6 3. Bf4 c6
{ This will most likely be the choice of Slav Defense players. Known as an ultra solid opening, rich in both strategical and tactical nuances, there is no question why a lot of players picked up the Slav. However, I consider it to be an inferior choice against our London System in particular. }
4. e3 Bf5
{ This is the most common way for Black to continue. The idea is to simply get the bishop outside the pawn chain before playing ...e6 followed by ...Bd6 @@StartBracket@@if allowed@@EndBracket@@ and ...O-O, with no bad pieces for Black and an equal game. }
5. c4
{ Here  5.c4!  followed by Qb3 gives White, unlike against 4... e6, the advantage, objectively speaking. The big difference is that Black's options are quite restricted in the Slav, making it easier for White to dictate the course of the game on the queenside. The idea is to apply immediate pressure on the b7-pawn with  @@StartFEN@@rn1qkb1r/pp2pppp/2p2n2/3p1b2/2PP1B2/4PN2/PP3PPP/RN1QKB1R w - - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  6.Qb3  and if Black tries to annihilate our pressure with  6...Qb6  , we can force a favorable endgame by going  7.c5! }
5... e6
{ The main line. Black doesn't really have much of a choice at this point. } 6.
Qb3
{ This is the most precise way to play for White. The idea is to apply immediate pressure on Black's queenside, so that they are not in time with ...Bd6 like in the 6. Nc3-line.Now Black has an important decision to make. The most common moves are:  6...Qb6 @@StartBracket@@the most common move@@EndBracket@@  6...Qc8 @@StartBracket@@Jobava's favorite@@EndBracket@@  6...b6 @@StartBracket@@common for lower-rated players@@EndBracket@@. }
6... b6
{ This move is equally as popular as 6...Qc8. My general feeling is that it's favored by the lower rated players, but we should stay careful because if played well, this line could pose some problems. }
7. Nc3
{ After this move Black has a choice between:  7...Bd6 @@StartBracket@@the main move@@EndBracket@@  7...Nbd7 @@StartBracket@@huge blunder!@@EndBracket@@  7...Be7 @@StartBracket@@equally popular to 7...Nbd7@@EndBracket@@. }
7... Bd6 { The main move, and the most critical variation after 6...b6. } 8.
Bxd6
{ I find this to be the simplest answer, giving us a choice on the next move between active and positional chess. }
8... Qxd6 9. Nh4
{ This is my main recommendation because objectively speaking, White can get a large advantage. If you are not comfortable going for the bishop hunt, you can by all means go for the slower 9.Be2  followed by O-O with a pleasant position for White.  Typically whenever we play Nh4, Black has a choice between three main moves:   9...Bg4  9...Bg6  9...Be4 @@StartBracket@@the most challenging@@EndBracket@@. }
9... Be4
{ The most stubborn move.   The move  9...Bg6  gives us the light-squared bishop without putting up a fight. I like starting with the move  10.cxd5!  because Black's next move is forced, as taking back with  10...cxd5  is not an alternative because of the thematic  11.Rc1  with annoying pressure on the c-file followed by Nb5! So there follows  10...exd5  11.Nxg6  hxg6  and now  12.g3!?  It is not very common that we go for the fianchetto in the London System, but in this case it works quite well, minimizing Black's pressure on the kingside.  12...Nbd7  13.Bg2  O-O  14.O-O  ⩲  With a simple and effective plan for White. The rooks will be placed on c1 and d1, Qa4 and then we push the b-pawn with b4-b5 ➼ undermining Black's queenside. }
10. cxd5
{ Forcing Black to find  10...Bxd5!  The other moves lead to a large advantage for White. }
10... Bxd5
{ The lesser evil.   10...cxd5?  is typically not good because of Nb5-ideas. After  11.f3  Bg6  the move  12.Nb5!  is very unpleasant to meet. White is close to winning after  12...Qd7  13.Qa3±  with the huge threat of Nd6+.   10...exd5  looks to be the most natural move for Black, but it has it own drawbacks.  11.f3  forces the bishop to step back and prepares e4-ideas in the future.  11...Bg6  12.Nxg6  hxg6  13.O-O-O !  It is not very common in the London System that we castle long, but in this particular case it works very well combined with e4 ideas.  Now the greedy  13...Rxh2  is bad after  14.Rxh2  Qxh2  15.Kb1  .  With e4 to come, Black is having a hard time finding a safe place for his king. Instead, after  13...O-O  we avoid annoying Qf4+ ideas with  14.Kb1±  and we can push e4 on the next move with a large advantage. }
11. Nxd5 exd5
{ The most natural recapture.  11...cxd5  still leads to suffering in view of  12.Bb5+! }
12. Nf5 { Misplacing Black's queen. } 12... Qd7 13. Ng3
{ Of course, taking the pawn  13.Nxg7+?  is bad in view of  13...Kf8!  and the knight gets trapped. }
13... O-O 14. Be2 g6
{ This has to be played in order to keep the g3-knight under control. } 15. O-O
Qd6 { Making room for ...Nbd7. } 16. Rac1
{ With a small edge for White, but close to equal according to the engine. I feel like White's position is much easier to play. We can double up on the c-file with Rc2-Rfc1 and then organise the minority attack after Qa4 followed by b4-b5. The g3-knight might seem a bit restricted by the g6-pawn, but we can always maneuver it after Bf3 and Ne2-Nf4. }
