9. Rxb1 Nbd7 10. b4 a6 11. Ra1 Rc8 12. h4
{ This is the most dangerous setup for Black's position. It might look very fancy at first glance, but the plan is pretty simple! First of all, If Black spends a tempo on taking space with  12...h5  we get the perfect timing to play the standard Nd2-Nb3-Na5. Second of all, if they allow us to grab more space with h5, then we can just focus on the kingside with a simple set-up. We are going to play Bd3-Ke2 followed by Rag1-g4 with pressure on the kingside. }
12... h5
{ This is played with the idea to stop White from expanding on the kingside. }
13. Nd2
{ Now the standard plan works well because we have managed to force Black in ''wasting'' a tempo on the kingside instead of rushing with the typical ... Be7-Bd8 followed by ...O-O and ...Re8 and then breaking with ...e5! }
13... Be7 14. Nb3 Bd8 15. Na5 Bxa5 16. bxa5
{ The star recapture, preparing Ra4-Rb4 in the future. } 16... O-O 17. Bd6
{ It's always nice to throw in this move, making sure that Black's ...e5-push will not directly hit the f4-bishop. }
17... Rfe8 18. Bd3 { The most precise move! } 18... e5 19. O-O exd4
{ Instead  19...Ne4?!  20.Bxe4!  dxe4  21.Ra4±  leads to a winning position for White strategically speaking, based on Rb4 ideas. Keep in mind that  21...exd4  is met by  22.Rxd4!  and then we return to b4. }
20. exd4 Ne4 21. Bf4
{ With a lasting initiative for White on the queenside. These endgames are very problematic for Black. }
