12... Be7 13. h5
{ After this move we will be focusing on the kingside. White's plan is simple and straightforward. If allowed, we will simply play Bd3-Ke2-Rag1 followed by pushing the g-pawn down the board! }
13... O-O 14. Bd3
{ This is an important nuance because even though 14.h6 is playable, I think it's better to keep the pawn on h5. The reason for that is, first of all, after  14.h6  g6  it is not so clear how to proceed, and secondly the main plan for White after 14. Bd3 is to play Ke2-Rag1 followed by g4-g5 and then we break with g6! }
14... Bd8
{ The more human move in my opinion.   14...Ng4  is what the computer likes, with the idea to push ...f5 and slow down White's expansion on the kingside.  15.Ke2  f5  16.Rag1!  We mind our own business!  16...Rce8  17.Bc2!?  is a prophylactic move that the computer really likes. The idea is to prepare the typical Nh4-f3 while making Black's ...e5 break less effective. The line continues  17...Bf6  18.Nh4  Bxh4  19.Rxh4  e5!  An important resource that keeps Black in the game with decent chances.  20.dxe5  Ngxe5  21.Kd2⩲  This is probably the best play for Black in the whole line. After finding a lot of resources, Black is still suffering in this position and I like White's potential with the bishop pair. We have ideas of brinking the king towards d4 and then prepare the e4-break with Re1-f3-Bg3 and then e4. Once the position opens up, the bishops are deadly. }
15. Ke2 Bc7 16. Rag1
{ We don't mind  16...Bxf4  as that will improve our control over the center after  17.exf4  . }
16... Rfe8 17. g4 { Creating a big threat of g5 followed by g6! } 17... e5
{ The critical resource to stay in the game. } 18. dxe5 Bxe5
{ 18...Nxe5??  would be a surprising blunder due to  19.Bf5!  Ra8  20.g5  Nxf3  21.Kxf3  Bxf4  22.gxf6!  +-  After this intermezzo, Black is lost. }
19. Nxe5 Nxe5 20. Bc2
{ We are ready to push g5 on the next move with annoying pressure on the kingside. Keep in mind that Black is unable to take on g4 in view of Bf5! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4) Slav Defense"]
[Black "Slav endgame 8...Bxb1 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5
{ 1...d5  2.Nf3  c6  3.Bf4  Qb6  4.Qc1  This move order is not really that problematic because we can simply play e3 followed by c4-c5 and we transpose. }
2. Nf3
{ This is the most precise move ➼ avoiding the annoying  2.Bf4  c5!  which gives us some headaches as explained in this informational. }
2... Nf6 3. Bf4 c6
{ This will most likely be the choice of Slav Defense players. Known as an ultra solid opening, rich in both strategical and tactical nuances, there is no question why a lot of players picked up the Slav. However, I consider it to be an inferior choice against our London System in particular. }
4. e3 Bf5
{ This is the most common way for Black to continue. The idea is to simply get the bishop outside the pawn chain before playing ...e6 followed by ...Bd6 @@StartBracket@@if allowed@@EndBracket@@ and ...O-O, with no bad pieces for Black and an equal game. }
5. c4
{ Here  5.c4!  followed by Qb3 gives White, unlike against 4... e6, the advantage, objectively speaking. The big difference is that Black's options are quite restricted in the Slav, making it easier for White to dictate the course of the game on the queenside. The idea is to apply immediate pressure on the b7-pawn with  @@StartFEN@@rn1qkb1r/pp2pppp/2p2n2/3p1b2/2PP1B2/4PN2/PP3PPP/RN1QKB1R w - - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  6.Qb3  and if Black tries to annihilate our pressure with  6...Qb6  , we can force a favorable endgame by going  7.c5! }
5... e6
{ The main line. Black doesn't really have much of a choice at this point. } 6.
Qb3
{ This is the most precise way to play for White. The idea is to apply immediate pressure on Black's queenside, so that they are not in time with ...Bd6 like in the 6. Nc3-line.Now Black has an important decision to make. The most common moves are:  6...Qb6 @@StartBracket@@the most common move@@EndBracket@@  6...Qc8 @@StartBracket@@Jobava's favorite@@EndBracket@@  6...b6 @@StartBracket@@common for lower-rated players@@EndBracket@@. }
6... Qb6
{ Offering the queen trade. This is the main line in OTB games, and also what I have encountered the most in online chess.   6...Bxb1?  , intending to meet  7.Rxb1  with  7...Qa5+  , doesn't work due to the strong intermezzo  7.Qxb7!  when White just wins, as after  7...Qa5+  8.Kd1+-  White will collect the rook on a8 on the next move. }
7. c5
{ The key move to grab the initiative, forcing Black to take on b3, giving us the upper hand on the queenside. Now you can fully understand why it was so important to play 5. c4 instead of the 'automatic' 5.c3-move that we see most of the time in the London.   Keep in mind that you want to force your opponent to take on b3 and open up the a-file for the rook, otherwise there is no point in going for the early queen trade.  7.Qxb6?!  axb6∞  would already give Black a very comfortable position, so it should be avoided! }
7... Qxb3 { Forced, as otherwise Black has issues with the b7-square. } 8. axb3
{ We have arrived at the first crossroads of the 'Slav endgame'. We can divide the material in two big categories:  endgames with 8...Bxb1  endgames with 8...Nbd7. }
8... Bxb1
{ This is less popular than 8...Nbd7, but much more challenging. I find this to be a smart trade for Black despite conceding the bishop pair unprovoked this early in the game! Once you take a look at the main lines with 8...Nbd7 you will notice that generally the light-squared bishop is either a target for White's g4-move, or sometimes it simply finds itselft 'hitting in the desert' on the b1-h7 diagonal. That's the positional idea behind Bxb1, but there are also some concrete benefits that can be spotted in the notes to 12. h3.To sum things up here, it will take more time for White to regroup before getting the ideal set-up with Nd2-Nb3-Na5 and Black manages to organize play in the center with ...e5! }
9. Rxb1 Nbd7 10. b4 a6 11. Ra1 Rc8 12. h4
{ This is the most dangerous setup for Black's position. It might look very fancy at first glance, but the plan is pretty simple! First of all, If Black spends a tempo on taking space with  12...h5  we get the perfect timing to play the standard Nd2-Nb3-Na5. Second of all, if they allow us to grab more space with h5, then we can just focus on the kingside with a simple set-up. We are going to play Bd3-Ke2 followed by Rag1-g4 with pressure on the kingside. }
12... Be7 13. h5
{ After this move we will be focusing on the kingside. White's plan is simple and straightforward. If allowed, we will simply play Bd3-Ke2-Rag1 followed by pushing the g-pawn down the board! }
13... h6
{ I feel like a lot of players would just make this move, feeling uncomfortable allowing White to advance the pawn even further. }
14. Bd3 { Perparing the standard plan with Ke2-Rag1. } 14... O-O 15. Ke2 Bd8
16. Rag1
{ With a nice initiative on the kingside after pushing the g-pawn all the way to g5! }
*

