{ This is by far the most common move for Black, according to the database and also from my experience. }
9. Nc3
{ This is the standard square for the knight. Now we are threatening to launch the b-pawn all the way to b5, if Black is not careful enough. Black needs to take some prophylactic measures in order to avoid immediate disaster. }
9... Be7
{ This is a very natural move, at the end of the day Black simply wants to castle and meet  10.b4  with  10...a6  ➼ slowing down White's play on the queenside. What could go wrong? }
10. b4 { Preparing to expand even further with b5. } 10... Nh5
{ This also doesn't work well. } 11. Be5
{ Inviting Black to take the bishop so we can activate our knight while the enemy horse has remained a bit offside on h5. }
11... Nxe5 12. Nxe5
{ Threatening not only to play g4 and win a piece thanks to the fork, but also to expand on the queenside with b5! }
12... f6
{ Now White is much better after any move, but I wanted to show you the following instructive sacrifice. }
13. Nxc6
{ Temporarily sacrificing the piece because we can take advantage of Black's misplaced knight on the next turn. }
13... bxc6 14. Be2
{ White is regaining the piece with a much better position. } 14... Nf4
{ Trying to damage White's structure since  14...Bg6  would have been met by  15.g4!  winning back the piece. }
15. exf4
{ With a lot of pressure on the queenside. We can double up on the a-file by playing Ra6-Kd2-Rha1 while b5 is also looming. }
