10... f6
{ If  10...Nxe5  11.Nxe5  Nf6  12.b4  Nd7  trying to get rid of White's active knight, there is the move  13.Nb5!!  - not the only move to keep the advantage, but the most precise one @@StartBracket@@and also the most aesthetic@@EndBracket@@. After  13...cxb5  14.Bxb5  Rd8  15.Rxa7  Black's queenside is just getting demolished.  15...f6  16.Nxd7  Rxd7  17.Rxb7+-  With three pawns and a rook for two minors, White is simply crushing here. It's not really the number of pawns, but the quality of them since the connected passers are really close to getting promoted. }
11. Bc7
{ With the idea to lure Black's rook to c8! Otherwise, pushing h3 is a huge threat! }
11... g5
{ This is Black's defense according to the computer ➼ creating a square on g7 for the knight. }
12. b4 Rc8 13. b5
{ Even though  13.Bd6  is perfectly playable, I very much like this idea of sacrificing the piece for a long-term initiative. }
13... Rxc7 14. Rxa7 { Creating a huge threat of b6! } 14... cxb5 15. Nxb5 Rc8
16. Rxb7
{ The engine thinks White is only slightly better here, but in a practical game, to me it looks like the pawns are simply unstoppable. White can continue with the following moves: Be2, Kd2, Ra1-Ra7 followed by the march of the b-pawn. }
