11. h3
{ This is a very important move, securing a square for the dark-squared bishop on h2 in case of any ... Nh5.   11.h4!?  is also playable, but not needed with Black's light-squared bishop on the board. }
11... h6
{ This is another common move for Black in this position. Some people are afraid of the bishop hunt based on Nh4 or g4 followed by Nh4. Nevertheless, practice has shown that this is not really a problem for Black, and that it's better to simply develop with 11...Be7. }
12. Nd2
{ Starting the key maneuver in this structure! White is preparing Nb3-Na5 ➼ attacking the b7-pawn. }
12... Be7 13. Nb3 Bd8 14. Bd6
{ Generally we like to throw in Bd6 when Black goes ...Bd8. It works even better in this case because we are keeping Black's king in the center! }
14... Ne4
{ This is a sad necessity due to the lack of other moves. The desired  14...Bc7  runs into a typical trick after  15.Bxc7  Rxc7  16.b5!  ➼ and Black has problems because  16...axb5  allows  17.Ra8+! }
15. Nxe4 Bxe4 16. Na5 { Attacking the b7-pawn. } 16... Bxa5 17. bxa5
{ This is the key recapture in the Slav endgame. The point is that now White has ideas to put pressure on the b7-pawn with Ra4-Rb4! }
17... Ra8 { Preparing to defend the b7-pawn with ...Ra7. } 18. Ra4 Kd8
{ Black is lacking other moves because of the powerful d6-bishop. } 19. Rb4 Kc8
20. f3 Bg6 21. g4
{ Black is completely tied down. White has a free hand on both sides of the board. Typically we'd like to grab more space on the kingside with h4-h5 and eventually we can break in the center with e4. Another annoying idea for Black is to bring the h1-rook to the queenside with Ra1-Ra3-Rab3 with a lot of pressure on the b7-pawn. The king generally goes to d2 and the light-squared bishop can stay on e2. Imagine we get all the aforementioned moves, and we already have a threat of winning on the spot if Black plays the only move to defend the pawn ...Ra7 with Rxb7! with the idea that ...Rxb7 is running into Bxa6! ➼ winning back the rook and keeping two extra pawns. }
