{ This mysterious rook move might look a bit odd since opening up the c-file doesn't seem to be happening in the near future. The truth is that this move is purely prophylactic, and the goal of it is to avoid White's direct b5-push. To get a better understanding of White's threat you can review the line starting with 9... Be7.   10...O-O-O ??  It is quite naive for Black to think that the king is safe without the queens on the board.  11.Rxa6!  is a good illustration that we always need to watch our for tactics @@StartBracket@@even in the endgame@@EndBracket@@! After  11...bxa6  12.Bxa6#  we have a typical checkmate. }
11. h3
{ This is a very important move, securing a square for the dark-squared bishop on h2 in case of any ... Nh5.   11.h4!?  is also playable, but not needed with Black's light-squared bishop on the board. }
11... Be7 { The most common move for Black ➼ preparing ...O-O. } 12. Nd2
{ This is the key maneuver in the Slav Endgame. White is preparing Nb3-Na5 hitting the weakest spot in Black's camp  @@StartBracket@@the b7-pawn@@EndBracket@@! }
12... O-O 13. Nb3 { Creating a huge threat of Na5 ➼ winning the b7-pawn. }
13... Bd8
{ 13...Ra8  is the passive way of defending b7. Black is preparing to meet Na5 with ...Ra7.  14.Na5  Ra7  For the time being, Black is holding the queenside, but at a pretty high cost of making the a7-rook very passive. Here I suggest  15.g4!  We need to open up the other flank in order to make progress, so expanding on the kingside is the way to go. Here we see the principle of the two weaknesses in action. It is a pretty incipient phase since we have not even finished development yet, but you can picture White expanding further on the kingside after h4-h5 ➼ looking forward to creating the second weakness. Now according to the 'principle of the two weaknesses' the attacking side will be able to switch between the two weaknesses much easier than the defending one. This will result in Black dropping one of the pawns sooner or later in our case.    15...Bg6  16.f3±  White can finish development by playing Kd2 and Be2 followed by the kingside push with h4-h5. Let's say Black will push ...h6 to slow down our pawn storm, but that will already give us ideas to break with g5 and use the g-file for the rook. On the other hand, we have another interesting plan on the queenside of playing Bc7 with the idea of Bb6 and Black will have problems with the b7-pawn. Combining these ideas will make you unstoppable in this structure! }
14. Bd6
{ Generally we like to throw in Bd6 when Black plays ...Bd8 because:   it creates a mess in Black's camp  the ...e5 break will be easier to meet since it no longer hits the f4-bishop. }
14... Re8 15. g4
{ Expanding on the queenside is the most precise plan. Another common move in this structure is to go  15.Na5  ,  but that allows some unnecessary counterplay. For more details check out the informational line. }
15... Be4
{ The problem with this move is that Black will be dealing with a huge threat of g5, and White is in time to block the center ➼ resulting in free initiative for White on the queenside with the typical Na5. }
16. Rg1
{ Creating a huge threat of g5 and the knight has no good squares. More so, after the knight leaves f6, we can take the e4-bishop ➼ messing up Black's pawn structure. }
16... h6 { Threatening to push ...e5! } 17. f4
{ Stopping Black's ...e5 break @@StartBracket@@the only source of counterplay@@EndBracket@@. From now on, White can focus on the queenside with the typical play after Na5 ➼ targeting the b7-pawn. }
17... Bh7 18. Na5 Bxa5 19. bxa5
{ The key recapture in this structure! White is making room for the rook to activate down the b-file. The plan is to play Ra4 followed by Rb4 with huge pressure on the b7-pawn. Black can defend with ...Ra8-Ra7 but then we can bring in the other rook with Kd2-Be2 followed by Ra1-Ra3-Rab3 and Black will be unable to save the b7-pawn. White has a strategically winning position. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4) Slav Defense"]
[Black "Slav endgame 8...Nbd7 9.Nc3 a6 #5"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5
{ 1...d5  2.Nf3  c6  3.Bf4  Qb6  4.Qc1  This move order is not really that problematic because we can simply play e3 followed by c4-c5 and we transpose. }
2. Nf3
{ This is the most precise move ➼ avoiding the annoying  2.Bf4  c5!  which gives us some headaches as explained in this informational. }
2... Nf6 3. Bf4 c6
{ This will most likely be the choice of Slav Defense players. Known as an ultra solid opening, rich in both strategical and tactical nuances, there is no question why a lot of players picked up the Slav. However, I consider it to be an inferior choice against our London System in particular. }
4. e3 Bf5
{ This is the most common way for Black to continue. The idea is to simply get the bishop outside the pawn chain before playing ...e6 followed by ...Bd6 @@StartBracket@@if allowed@@EndBracket@@ and ...O-O, with no bad pieces for Black and an equal game. }
5. c4
{ Here  5.c4!  followed by Qb3 gives White, unlike against 4... e6, the advantage, objectively speaking. The big difference is that Black's options are quite restricted in the Slav, making it easier for White to dictate the course of the game on the queenside. The idea is to apply immediate pressure on the b7-pawn with  @@StartFEN@@rn1qkb1r/pp2pppp/2p2n2/3p1b2/2PP1B2/4PN2/PP3PPP/RN1QKB1R w - - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  6.Qb3  and if Black tries to annihilate our pressure with  6...Qb6  , we can force a favorable endgame by going  7.c5! }
5... e6
{ The main line. Black doesn't really have much of a choice at this point. } 6.
Qb3
{ This is the most precise way to play for White. The idea is to apply immediate pressure on Black's queenside, so that they are not in time with ...Bd6 like in the 6. Nc3-line.Now Black has an important decision to make. The most common moves are:  6...Qb6 @@StartBracket@@the most common move@@EndBracket@@  6...Qc8 @@StartBracket@@Jobava's favorite@@EndBracket@@  6...b6 @@StartBracket@@common for lower-rated players@@EndBracket@@. }
6... Qb6
{ Offering the queen trade. This is the main line in OTB games, and also what I have encountered the most in online chess.   6...Bxb1?  , intending to meet  7.Rxb1  with  7...Qa5+  , doesn't work due to the strong intermezzo  7.Qxb7!  when White just wins, as after  7...Qa5+  8.Kd1+-  White will collect the rook on a8 on the next move. }
7. c5
{ The key move to grab the initiative, forcing Black to take on b3, giving us the upper hand on the queenside. Now you can fully understand why it was so important to play 5. c4 instead of the 'automatic' 5.c3-move that we see most of the time in the London.   Keep in mind that you want to force your opponent to take on b3 and open up the a-file for the rook, otherwise there is no point in going for the early queen trade.  7.Qxb6?!  axb6∞  would already give Black a very comfortable position, so it should be avoided! }
7... Qxb3 { Forced, as otherwise Black has issues with the b7-square. } 8. axb3
{ We have arrived at the first crossroads of the 'Slav endgame'. We can divide the material in two big categories:  endgames with 8...Bxb1  endgames with 8...Nbd7. }
8... Nbd7
{ This is by far the most common move for Black, according to the database and also from my experience. }
9. Nc3
{ This is the standard square for the knight. Now we are threatening to launch the b-pawn all the way to b5, if Black is not careful enough. Black needs to take some prophylactic measures in order to avoid immediate disaster. }
9... a6
{ This is Black's best reaction, and the main move from a theoretical perspective. Black is preparing to step away with the rook when White will push b4 so there won't be an immediate breakthrough on the queenside with b5! }
10. b4
{ Creating a huge threat of b5 because Black is pinned along the a-file. }
10... Rc8
{ This mysterious rook move might look a bit odd since opening up the c-file doesn't seem to be happening in the near future. The truth is that this move is purely prophylactic, and the goal of it is to avoid White's direct b5-push. To get a better understanding of White's threat you can review the line starting with 9... Be7.   10...O-O-O ??  It is quite naive for Black to think that the king is safe without the queens on the board.  11.Rxa6!  is a good illustration that we always need to watch our for tactics @@StartBracket@@even in the endgame@@EndBracket@@! After  11...bxa6  12.Bxa6#  we have a typical checkmate. }
11. h3
{ This is a very important move, securing a square for the dark-squared bishop on h2 in case of any ... Nh5.   11.h4!?  is also playable, but not needed with Black's light-squared bishop on the board. }
11... Be7 { The most common move for Black ➼ preparing ...O-O. } 12. Nd2
{ This is the key maneuver in the Slav Endgame. White is preparing Nb3-Na5 hitting the weakest spot in Black's camp  @@StartBracket@@the b7-pawn@@EndBracket@@! }
12... O-O 13. Nb3 { Creating a huge threat of Na5 ➼ winning the b7-pawn. }
13... Bd8
{ 13...Ra8  is the passive way of defending b7. Black is preparing to meet Na5 with ...Ra7.  14.Na5  Ra7  For the time being, Black is holding the queenside, but at a pretty high cost of making the a7-rook very passive. Here I suggest  15.g4!  We need to open up the other flank in order to make progress, so expanding on the kingside is the way to go. Here we see the principle of the two weaknesses in action. It is a pretty incipient phase since we have not even finished development yet, but you can picture White expanding further on the kingside after h4-h5 ➼ looking forward to creating the second weakness. Now according to the 'principle of the two weaknesses' the attacking side will be able to switch between the two weaknesses much easier than the defending one. This will result in Black dropping one of the pawns sooner or later in our case.    15...Bg6  16.f3±  White can finish development by playing Kd2 and Be2 followed by the kingside push with h4-h5. Let's say Black will push ...h6 to slow down our pawn storm, but that will already give us ideas to break with g5 and use the g-file for the rook. On the other hand, we have another interesting plan on the queenside of playing Bc7 with the idea of Bb6 and Black will have problems with the b7-pawn. Combining these ideas will make you unstoppable in this structure! }
14. Bd6
{ Generally we like to throw in Bd6 when Black plays ...Bd8 because:   it creates a mess in Black's camp  the ...e5 break will be easier to meet since it no longer hits the f4-bishop. }
14... Re8 15. g4
{ Expanding on the queenside is the most precise plan. Another common move in this structure is to go  15.Na5  ,  but that allows some unnecessary counterplay. For more details check out the informational line. }
15... Bg6 { Threatening to break with ...e5. } 16. f3
{ This multipurpose move secures a large advantage for White. We are not only preparing to expand on the kingside with h4-h5, but also Black's ...e5 break can be met by Kd2! and Black is unable to make use of the e4-square thanks to our last move. Please keep in mind that the thematic Na5-plan is still something that we are looking forward to! We just had to start with the prophylactic play first.   16.f4⩲  This was the key move against 15...Be4, but in this particular case Black will be able to get good counterplay after  16...Ne4  ➼  threatening ...Bh4+. }
16... Bc7
{ This can be a tricky move to deal with if you are not familiar with the position. }
17. Na5
{ The only move to keep the initiative, but it gives White a large advantage. }
17... Bxd6
{ This leads to a relatively strange pawn structure, but as a general rule after ...Bxd6 White plays cxd6 followed by Na4-Nc5 and Black has problems on the queenside.   17...Bxa5?  would allow the ideal scenario for White on the queenside after the typical  18.bxa5?  The key recapture, making room for the rook to put pressure on the b7-pawn after Ra4-Rb4!  18...e5  threatens ...exd4, but it is simply sidestepped by  19.Kd2!  ,  placing the king on a very good square. As is typical for this line, but also a good general strategy when there are no queens on the board, the king becomes an attacking piece in the endgame.   Now the plan  19...Re6  used to be a problem in the 15. Na5 line - see the alternative, but here White has an improved version, and a winning position.  20.Ra4  prepares Rb4, and after  20...Ne8  the move  21.Bxe5!  is simply winning now because Black is unable to take twice on e5.  21...Nxe5  22.dxe5+-  with an extra pawn for White. Notice that  22...Rxe5  runs into  23.f4!  followed by f5 ➼ trapping the g6-bishop. }
18. cxd6 { Threatening Nxb7. } 18... Rb8
{ Trying to keep a solid pawn structure.   18...b6  only creates additional weaknesses.  19.Nb3+-  is the simplest answer. White is ready to take on a6 with the bishop on the next move, with a crushing advantage. }
19. Na4
{ The key move to get a big advantage. The idea is to play Nc5 and then the b7-pawn will be under huge pressure. Black will most likely have to take on c5 and repair our pawn structure. }
19... e5 { Threatening ... exd4. } 20. Kf2
{ Simply avoiding the pin.  20.Kd2  is also fine. } 20... exd4 21. exd4 Kf8 22.
Nc5 { Threatening to take on b7. } 22... Nxc5 23. bxc5
{ With a winning position for White from a strategical perspective with the simple plan of playing Ra4 followed by Rb4 and the b7-pawn will drop. }
