17... exd4 18. exd4
{ This is the most intructive way to recapture I think. The computer slightly prefers  18.Nxd4  , but I decided to make  18.exd4  our main line because:  it gives White a huge advantage  it is more common  it will help you understand the dynamic of the Slav Endgame.   Let's look at a typical continuation:  18...Nf8  19.h4!  This is a really nice move, threatening h5 ➼ trapping the g6-bishop, and also introducing Bh3 ideas which combined with g5 can be very powerful.  19...h6  20.Na5  Attacking the weakest spot in Black's camp @@StartBracket@@the b7-pawn@@EndBracket@@!  20...Ne6  Creating a counter threat of ...Nxd4.   20...Bxa5  gives White a dream position after  21.bxa5!  The last finesse of the position. Taking with the pawn is the star idea in the Slav Endgame, preparing to put pressure on the b7-pawn with Ra4-Rb4!  21...Ne6  22.Ra4  With a dream position for White that can continue with Rb4 followed by Bh3 and then Ra1-Ra3-Rab3 creating decisive pressure against the b7-pawn. Just make sure that the d4-pawn is defended before taking on b7, and you can usually do that by playing Ne2.  21.Ne2  Making sure that the d4-pawn is well defended, which will allows us to focus on our own initiative on both sides of the board.  21...Bxa5  22.bxa5!  The cherry on the cake. You will notice that this is the universal way to recapture in the Slav endgame. The idea is to make room for the rook ➼ attacking the b7-pawn after Ra4-Rb4 and Black is having a hard time defending it.  22...Red8  23.Bh3±  With a dominating position for White. So far this has been the best play for both sides, illustrating the main issue of the Slav Endgame against the London System. Black is generally very passive if you keep the ...e5-break under control. In the final position White can continue with Ra3-Rb3  (I find it a bit better than the standard Ra4 because we might switch it over the e-file with Re3)  and then we can combine queenside pressure with kingside play, using the 'principle of the two weaknesses' by playing Rg1 and breaking with g5. Objectively speaking White has a huge advantage in this line, but it still requires a bit of precise play. }
