{ Creating a huge threat of b5 because Black is pinned along the a-file. }
10... Rc8
{ This mysterious rook move might look a bit odd since opening up the c-file doesn't seem to be happening in the near future. The truth is that this move is purely prophylactic, and the goal of it is to avoid White's direct b5-push. To get a better understanding of White's threat you can review the line starting with 9... Be7.   10...O-O-O ??  It is quite naive for Black to think that the king is safe without the queens on the board.  11.Rxa6!  is a good illustration that we always need to watch our for tactics @@StartBracket@@even in the endgame@@EndBracket@@! After  11...bxa6  12.Bxa6#  we have a typical checkmate. }
11. h3
{ This is a very important move, securing a square for the dark-squared bishop on h2 in case of any ... Nh5.   11.h4!?  is also playable, but not needed with Black's light-squared bishop on the board. }
11... Be7 { The most common move for Black ➼ preparing ...O-O. } 12. Nd2
{ This is the key maneuver in the Slav Endgame. White is preparing Nb3-Na5 hitting the weakest spot in Black's camp  @@StartBracket@@the b7-pawn@@EndBracket@@! }
12... O-O 13. Nb3 { Creating a huge threat of Na5 ➼ winning the b7-pawn. }
13... Bd8
{ 13...Ra8  is the passive way of defending b7. Black is preparing to meet Na5 with ...Ra7.  14.Na5  Ra7  For the time being, Black is holding the queenside, but at a pretty high cost of making the a7-rook very passive. Here I suggest  15.g4!  We need to open up the other flank in order to make progress, so expanding on the kingside is the way to go. Here we see the principle of the two weaknesses in action. It is a pretty incipient phase since we have not even finished development yet, but you can picture White expanding further on the kingside after h4-h5 ➼ looking forward to creating the second weakness. Now according to the 'principle of the two weaknesses' the attacking side will be able to switch between the two weaknesses much easier than the defending one. This will result in Black dropping one of the pawns sooner or later in our case.    15...Bg6  16.f3±  White can finish development by playing Kd2 and Be2 followed by the kingside push with h4-h5. Let's say Black will push ...h6 to slow down our pawn storm, but that will already give us ideas to break with g5 and use the g-file for the rook. On the other hand, we have another interesting plan on the queenside of playing Bc7 with the idea of Bb6 and Black will have problems with the b7-pawn. Combining these ideas will make you unstoppable in this structure! }
14. Bd6
{ Generally we like to throw in Bd6 when Black plays ...Bd8 because:   it creates a mess in Black's camp  the ...e5 break will be easier to meet since it no longer hits the f4-bishop. }
14... Re8 15. Na5
{ This is the most natural move, and it seems to be the the perfect follow up of the early Nd2-Nb3. I want to start by saying that this is perfectly playable, and a lot of your opponents will probably not be aware of Black's best chance of getting counterplay. So just in case you don't remember to play the most precise 15. g4! it won't be a disaster. To be honest, in most of my games I have played 15.Na5 with very good results. }
15... Bxa5 16. bxa5 e5 17. Kd2 Re6
{ This is the key defensive resource for Black, threatening ... Ne8 ➼ putting pressure on the d6-bishop.   17...exd4?!  is the most common reaction that I got in my games.  18.exd4  Ne4+?!  Another typical 'tempo' move that is just leading to a strategical disaster for Black.  19.Nxe4  Bxe4  20.Ra4!  Threatening to win the b7-pawn after Rb4. Now  20...Ra8  is a sad necessity in order to be able to meet Rb4 with ...Ra7.  21.Rb4  Ra7  22.f3  Getting rid of the annoying bishop so we can play Be2 without dropping the g2-pawn.  22...Bg6  23.Be2+-  With the ultra simple plan of going Ra1-Ra3-Rab3 winning the b7-pawn. I've had countless games like this. What I really like about the London System is that you can get this kind of thematic plans that generate instant wins. Once you get familiar with the plans, everything is so simple, almost no calculation is required. }
18. Ra4
{ The most natural move for us will give Black a pretty solid position. The computer still finds the only move to keep the initiative  18.g4!  ➼ giving White a serious advantage, but this made me wonder why not start with it and allow the bishop trade? }
18... Ne8 19. Bxe5 Nxe5 20. dxe5 Rxe5
{ After  20...Rxe5  White might still keep a small edge, but it's far from simple, and Black can just meet  21.Rb4  with  21...Re7  . }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5) Queen's Gambit Declined with a quick ...e6 & ...Bd6"]
[Black "Introduction"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3
{ This is the most precise move ➼ avoiding the annoying  2.Bf4  c5!  which gives us some headaches as explained in this informational. }
2... Nf6 3. Bf4 e6 4. e3 Bd6 5. Nbd2
{ This is my main recommandation because  5.Bg3  gives Black a number of interesting alternatives, such as  5...O-O  6.Nbd2  c5  7.c3  Qc7  8.Bd3  Nbd7  followed by ...e5! or  5...O-O  6.Nbd2  b6  7.Bd3  Bb7  8.c3  Ne4  with a very solid position for Black.   In this chapter you will also find an interesting alternative for White which starts with  5.Ne5  leading to a more double-edged fight. After  5.Nbd2  the material will be split between:  •  5...Bxf4   •  5...O-O  . }
5... Bxf4 6. exf4
{ From this position we are going to cover:  •  6...O-O   •  6...Qd6  .    Typical pawn structures arising from this chapter:  The Berkes structure - the classical approach  The Berkes structure - the modern approach  The reversed Stonewall.   Model games arising from this chapter:  Moroni Luca Jr-Batsiashvili Nino, Titled Tuesday 2022  Nihal Sarin-Petrosyan Manuel, Jermuk 2022   Typical endgames arising from this chapter:  Nihal Sarin-Batsiashvili Nino, Menorca 2022  Carlsen Magnus-Sunilduth Lyna Narayanan, Chess24 2020  Grachev Boris-Matlakov Maxim, EU Cup Online 2021  Giri Anish-Antonenko Vladimir Georgievic, chesscom 2021  Grachev Boris-Solovchuk Alexey, chesscom 2021. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5) Queen's Gambit Declined with a quick ...e6 & ...Bd6"]
[Black "The super quick 3...Bd6"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3
{ This is the most precise move ➼ avoiding the annoying  2.Bf4  c5!  which gives us some headaches as explained in this informational. }
2... e6 3. Bf4 Bd6
{ This could be annoying if you are not familiar with Black's main ideas. } 4.
e3 { Going for the 'Berkes structure'. This is the most ambitious set-up! }
4... Bxf4
{ The only critical move.  4...Nf6  would transpose to the normal lines. } 5.
exf4 Qd6
{ Attacking the f4-pawn and threatening ...Qb4+ followed by ...Qxb2. This is the only independent line because  5...Nf6  would again transpose to the standard lines.   5...Ne7  is a typical idea for the 3...Bd6 move order.  6.h4!?  This move works very well against the ...Ng6 plan because we can annoy Black with h5 ideas.  6...O-O  7.h5  Threatening to push h6!  7...h6  8.Nc3  Preparing to play Qd2 followed by O-O-O.  8...Qd6  9.Qd2  Protecting the f4-pawn.  9...c5  10.g4⩲  We can continue with O-O-O followed by Rg1-g5 ideas and White has dangerous play on the kingside. }
6. Qd2
{ This is the key move to remember ➼ protecting both the f4-pawn and the b4-square. }
6... Nf6 7. Nc3
{ This is not a typical square for the knight in the 'Berkes structure', but it's a small adjustment that we have to make against this unusual 5...Qd6 line. }
7... O-O 8. Rg1
{ This is a novelty ➼ preparing to push on the kingside with g4-g5! } 8... c5
{ 8...b6  9.O-O-O  This is the 'normal' way to castle against this independent 5...Qd6 line.  9...Bb7  10.Ne5  Centralizing the knight and preparing to push g4.  10...c5  11.g4→  With g5 next ➼ White has good attacking prospects on the kingside. }
9. dxc5 Qxc5 10. g4
{ We can continue with O-O-O followed by Bd3-g5 ➼ with good attacking prospects on the kingside. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5) Queen's Gambit Declined with a quick ...e6 & ...Bd6"]
[Black "The quick 3...e6/4...Bd6: 5...Bxf4 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3
{ This is the most precise move ➼ avoiding the annoying  2.Bf4  c5!  which gives us some headaches as explained in this informational. }
2... Nf6 3. Bf4 e6 4. e3 Bd6
{ Playing ...Bd6 without ...c5 is a solid approach for Black. The main difference is that  5.Bg3  is no longer such a good move and White has a choice between:  5.Nbd2 @@StartBracket@@going for the Berkes structure@@EndBracket@@  5.Ne5!? @@StartBracket@@going for a double-edged fight@@EndBracket@@. }
5. Nbd2
{ This is the best try for White.  5.Bg3  gives Black a number of interesting tries such as  5...O-O  6.Nbd2  c5  7.c3  Qc7  8.Bd3  Nbd7  followed by ...e5! or  5...O-O  6.Nbd2  b6  7.Bd3  Bb7  8.c3  Ne4  with a very solid position for Black.   5.Ne5  could be an interesting alternative if you want to avoid the Berkes Structure ➼ leading to a double-edged game. }
5... Bxf4
{ This is a solid variation for Black. If played well, this can be pretty annoying, but overall I think this structure is easier to play for White. }
6. exf4 { Entering the Berkes structure! } 6... Qd6
{ This is a reasonable line for Black, but I feel like keeping the d6-square available for the knight is a better idea. Black generally plays this line with ...b6 followed by ...Ba6 Bxa6 ...Nxa6 and then ...Nc7-Ne8-Nd6! }
7. g3 { This is the standard way to protect the f4-pawn. } 7... b6 8. c3 O-O 9.
Ne5
{ This is a clever move. We are waiting for Black to play ...Ba6 so we can capture it without wasting a tempo on playing Bd3! }
9... Ba6 { This is the main idea for Black to trade off the bad bishop. } 10.
Bxa6 { Misplacing Black's knight on a6. } 10... Nxa6 11. h4
{ Going for the modern plan. However, there is nothing wrong either with  11.O-O  with a balanced game. }
11... c5 12. Qe2 { Attacking the a6-knight. } 12... Nb8 13. Ndf3
{ Preparing to take back on d4 with the knight. } 13... Nc6 14. h5
{ Threatening to push h6. Keep in mind that  14...cxd4  is met by  15.Nxc6!  Qxc6  16.Nxd4  with a better position for White. }
14... h6 15. O-O-O
{ We have a simple plan to push on the kingside with g4-g5! } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5) Queen's Gambit Declined with a quick ...e6 & ...Bd6"]
[Black "The quick 3...e6/4...Bd6: 5...Bxf4 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3
{ This is the most precise move ➼ avoiding the annoying  2.Bf4  c5!  which gives us some headaches as explained in this informational. }
2... Nf6 3. Bf4 e6 4. e3 Bd6
{ Playing ...Bd6 without ...c5 is a solid approach for Black. The main difference is that  5.Bg3  is no longer such a good move and White has a choice between:  5.Nbd2 @@StartBracket@@going for the Berkes structure@@EndBracket@@  5.Ne5!? @@StartBracket@@going for a double-edged fight@@EndBracket@@. }
5. Nbd2
{ This is the best try for White.  5.Bg3  gives Black a number of interesting tries such as  5...O-O  6.Nbd2  c5  7.c3  Qc7  8.Bd3  Nbd7  followed by ...e5! or  5...O-O  6.Nbd2  b6  7.Bd3  Bb7  8.c3  Ne4  with a very solid position for Black.   5.Ne5  could be an interesting alternative if you want to avoid the Berkes Structure ➼ leading to a double-edged game. }
5... Bxf4
{ This is a solid variation for Black. If played well, this can be pretty annoying, but overall I think this structure is easier to play for White. }
6. exf4 { Entering the Berkes structure! } 6... O-O 7. c3
{ Staying very flexible. This move is played with the idea to meet  7...b6  with  8.h4! }
7... b6 8. h4
{ This is the modern way of handling the Berkes structure. In the past, players used to play  8.Bd3  automatically with an equal game. The point of  8.h4  @@StartBracket@@besides being a 'waiting' move ➼ preparing to meet ...Ba6 with Bxa6 without having wasted a tempo on Bd3@@EndBracket@@ is to advance the pawn all the way to h6 @@StartBracket@@if allowed@@EndBracket@@ when Black's king will be weak in the long run. If Black plays ...h6 himself @@StartBracket@@trying to stop our pawn@@EndBracket@@ ➼ this will create a hook for g4-g5! }
8... Ba6 { This is the main idea for Black to trade off the bad bishop. } 9.
Bxa6 { Misplacing Black's knight on a6. } 9... Nxa6 10. Qe2
{ Attacking the a6-knight. } 10... Nb8 11. h5
{ Threatening to push h6 when Black's king will be vulnerable. } 11... h6 12.
Rh4
{ After this move White has good attacking prospects on the kingside. The simple threat is to push g4-g5. We can castle long and centralize with Ne5, while if Black goes ...c5 we can usually meet that with dxc5! with a promising position for White. }
