[White "5) Queen's Gambit Declined with a quick ...e6 & ...Bd6"]
[Black "The quick 3...e6/4...Bd6: 5...Bxf4 #6"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3
{ This is the most precise move ➼ avoiding the annoying  2.Bf4  c5!  which gives us some headaches as explained in this informational. }
2... Nf6 3. Bf4 e6 4. e3 Bd6
{ Playing ...Bd6 without ...c5 is a solid approach for Black. The main difference is that  5.Bg3  is no longer such a good move and White has a choice between:  5.Nbd2 @@StartBracket@@going for the Berkes structure@@EndBracket@@  5.Ne5!? @@StartBracket@@going for a double-edged fight@@EndBracket@@. }
5. Nbd2
{ This is the best try for White.  5.Bg3  gives Black a number of interesting tries such as  5...O-O  6.Nbd2  c5  7.c3  Qc7  8.Bd3  Nbd7  followed by ...e5! or  5...O-O  6.Nbd2  b6  7.Bd3  Bb7  8.c3  Ne4  with a very solid position for Black.   5.Ne5  could be an interesting alternative if you want to avoid the Berkes Structure ➼ leading to a double-edged game. }
5... Bxf4
{ This is a solid variation for Black. If played well, this can be pretty annoying, but overall I think this structure is easier to play for White. }
6. exf4 { Entering the Berkes structure! } 6... O-O 7. c3
{ Staying very flexible. This move is played with the idea to meet  7...b6  with  8.h4! }
7... c5
{ This line could equalize if Black plays very precise ➼ otherwise White gets a pleasant position. }
8. dxc5 Qc7
{ This is the trick to regain the pawn. Black is attacking both c5 and f4. } 9.
g3 { This is the standard way to protect the f4-pawn. } 9... Qxc5
{ This is by far the most common move in online chess.   Black's best move is  9...Nbd7!  The point of this line is to meet  10.Bd3  with  10...e5!  Objectively speaking this line should give Black an easy game, but I find it super rare. My suggestion is  10.Bg2!  Nxc5  11.Nb3!?  ,  an interesting try to avoid ...Bd7-Ba4 ideas. After  11...Bd7  12.Nxc5  Qxc5  13.O-O  ⩲  we can continue by playing Re1 and Nd4 with a slightly more pleasant position for White thanks to the more active bishop. }
10. Bd3
{ This is the ideal square for the light-squared bishop in the Berkes structure. }
10... Nc6
{ The alternative  10...b6  threatens to play ...Ba6! ➼ trading off the bad bishop, but we can delay this with  11.Qe2!  Black will reinforce the idea with  11...a5  when we can centralize our knight with  12.Nb3  Qc7  13.Nbd4!  and prepare to meet  13...Ba6  with  14.Nb5!  , inviting Black to give up his bishop for our knight. After  14...Qe7  15.a4⩲  White has a small edge thanks to the strong knight on b5. }
11. O-O Bd7
{ Black can also play active with  11...b5  ➼ this is a common plan for Black. We can attack the b5-pawn with  12.Qe2  when after  12...b4  13.Rfc1⩲  White threatens cxb4 and Black has problems on the c-file. It turns out that White will benefit from opening up the queenside! }
12. Re1 { Activating the rook. } 12... Rfd8 13. Qe2
{ This is the ideal square for the queen in the Berkes structure. } 13... Rac8
14. Rad1
{ With a typical advantage for White in the Berkes structure. We can play Bb1 followed by Nb3-Nbd4, Nf3-Ne5 and ideas to push on the kingside with h4-h5 and g4-g5. White won a smooth game between Moroni,L-Morefield,J,  Chess.com INT 2019. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5) Queen's Gambit Declined with a quick ...e6 & ...Bd6"]
[Black "The quick 3...e6/4...Bd6: 5...c5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3
{ This is the most precise move ➼ avoiding the annoying  2.Bf4  c5!  which gives us some headaches as explained in this informational. }
2... Nf6 3. Bf4 e6 4. e3 Bd6
{ Playing ...Bd6 without ...c5 is a solid approach for Black. The main difference is that  5.Bg3  is no longer such a good move and White has a choice between:  5.Nbd2 @@StartBracket@@going for the Berkes structure@@EndBracket@@  5.Ne5!? @@StartBracket@@going for a double-edged fight@@EndBracket@@. }
5. Nbd2
{ This is the best try for White.  5.Bg3  gives Black a number of interesting tries such as  5...O-O  6.Nbd2  c5  7.c3  Qc7  8.Bd3  Nbd7  followed by ...e5! or  5...O-O  6.Nbd2  b6  7.Bd3  Bb7  8.c3  Ne4  with a very solid position for Black.   5.Ne5  could be an interesting alternative if you want to avoid the Berkes Structure ➼ leading to a double-edged game. }
5... c5 6. c3
{ This is the true London System move with the idea to meet  6...Qc7  with  7.Bxd6  Qxd6  8.Ne5!  followed by f4.  @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/pp3ppp/3bpn2/2pp4/3P1B2/4PN2/PPPN1PPP/R2QKB1R w KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Bg3  would allow  6...Qc7  7.c3  Nbd7  followed by ...e5! with good counterplay for Black.   6.dxc5  is a serious alternative which I had in mind to recommend, but I felt that it's not very typical for the London System strategy. Also,  6.Bb5+  could be an interesting sideline to take your opponent out of his confort zone. }
6... Qc7
{ This is a very common move for Black ➼ trying to go for the ...Nbd7-e5 plan, but without really understanding when it works! In this version White gets a very pleasant position without having to do much. This setup is very popular not only for advanced players, but also for beginners because it's featured in a popular video made by Jonathan Schrantz. }
7. Bxd6 { Trading the bishops so we can play Ne5 followed by f4! } 7... Qxd6 8.
Ne5 { Centralizing the knight and preparing to support it with f4! } 8... Nbd7
{ Trying to challenge the e5-knight. } 9. f4
{ The key move that gives White a very pleasant position ➼ getting the Reversed Stonewall structure. }
9... O-O 10. Bd3 b6 11. g4
{ While  11.O-O  gives White a solid advantage, this aggressive move works best! }
11... Bb7
{ Creating a big positional threat of playing ...Ne4! ➼ Whenever Black manages to play ...Ne4 he is generally fine, so we need to stop that. }
12. Qf3
{ This is the key move that I REALLY want you to remember ➼ stopping Black from playing ...Ne4! Once you understand this concept, it will really boost your results in the London System. We can continue with g5 followed by O-O-O when White has good attacking prospects on the kingside.   A typical mistake would have been  12.g5  Ne4!  and Black is very comfortable. }
