6... Qc7
{ This is a very common move for Black ➼ trying to go for the ...Nbd7-e5 plan, but without really understanding when it works! In this version White gets a very pleasant position without having to do much. This setup is very popular not only for advanced players, but also for beginners because it's featured in a popular video made by Jonathan Schrantz. }
7. Bxd6 { Trading the bishops so we can play Ne5 followed by f4! } 7... Qxd6 8.
Ne5 { Centralizing the knight and preparing to support it with f4! } 8... O-O
9. Bd3 b6 { Preparing ...Ba6 ideas. } 10. f4
{ Setting-up the Reversed Stonewall structure. } 10... Ba6 11. Bc2
{ Keeping the bishop for the attack because the king can stay in the center for a while. This idea was used by Magnus Carlsen. }
11... Nc6 12. g4 { Going for the attack with g5. } 12... Rac8
{ This is a very logical move for Black.  12...Nd7  can be met by  13.Qf3!  followed by Qh3, Ndf3 with ideas to castle long. }
13. Rg1
{ Not rushing, and giving the opponent more chances to go wrong. I really like Carlsen's approach. }
13... Nd7 14. Ndf3 f6
{ This is a bit inaccurate. Best is  14...cxd4!  15.exd4  f6  16.Nxd7  Qxd7  17.Qd2  intending O-O-O with a complex position. }
15. Nxc6
{ Going for simple chess. I guess Magnus exchanged the c6-knight because it was a bit more active than the one on d7. }
15... Rxc6 16. g5
{ Threatening to open up the g-file with gxf6! Black already felt the need to close the position with  16...f5  and White won an instructive game in Carlsen,M @@StartBracket@@2863@@EndBracket@@-Sunilduth Lyna,N @@StartBracket@@2618@@EndBracket@@ chess24.com INT 2020. }
