{ This is the true London System move with the idea to meet  6...Qc7  with  7.Bxd6  Qxd6  8.Ne5!  followed by f4.  @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/pp3ppp/3bpn2/2pp4/3P1B2/4PN2/PPPN1PPP/R2QKB1R w KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Bg3  would allow  6...Qc7  7.c3  Nbd7  followed by ...e5! with good counterplay for Black.   6.dxc5  is a serious alternative which I had in mind to recommend, but I felt that it's not very typical for the London System strategy. Also,  6.Bb5+  could be an interesting sideline to take your opponent out of his confort zone. }
6... cxd4
{ This is a super rare move, but interesting for Black ➼ played once by Ding against Carlsen. The point is that White lacks the standard reply  7.exd4  because the f4-bishop would hang. }
7. Bxd6
{ Now  7...Qxd6  is covered in the ...e6-Bd6 main lines with an easy game for White ➼ so in order to justify the previous play, Black has a choice between:  7...dxe3  7... dxc3. }
7... dxe3
{ 7...dxc3  is similar but a bit better for Black compared to 7... dxe3. The critical move is again  8.Ba3!  ➼ keeping Black's king in the center. After  8...cxd2+  9.Nxd2  Nc6  Black intends ...Ne7 and short castle, so we need to prevent this with  10.Bb5!  Bd7  11.Bxc6!  Bxc6  12.O-O  =∞  when Black is up a pawn but they are struggling to find a safe square for the king. The position is balanced, but easier to play as White with the safer king. }
8. Ba3 { This is the critical move ➼ keeping Black's king in the center. } 8...
exd2+ 9. Qxd2
{ White obviously has good compensation with Black's king being stuck in the center. The difference compared to the 7...dxc3 line, is that White has additional Qg5 ideas with very interesting play on the kingside as in the game between Carlsen,M-Ding,L, chess24.com INT 2020. }
