5... c5 6. c3
{ This is the true London System move with the idea to meet  6...Qc7  with  7.Bxd6  Qxd6  8.Ne5!  followed by f4.  @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/pp3ppp/3bpn2/2pp4/3P1B2/4PN2/PPPN1PPP/R2QKB1R w KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Bg3  would allow  6...Qc7  7.c3  Nbd7  followed by ...e5! with good counterplay for Black.   6.dxc5  is a serious alternative which I had in mind to recommend, but I felt that it's not very typical for the London System strategy. Also,  6.Bb5+  could be an interesting sideline to take your opponent out of his confort zone. }
6... O-O 7. Bd3 Bxf4
{ This is a clever way for Black to enter the Berkes structure because they avoid the modern plans with h4!  7...Nc6  8.Bg3  would tranpose back to the ...c5 & ...Bd6 main lines.   7...b6  is played occasionally as a sideline for Black, but White has a surprisingly easy fix:  8.Bxd6  Qxd6  9.e4⩲  Black simply lacks a good way to deal with this advance. We are threatening to push e5 and in case of  9...dxe4  10.Nxe4  White has a very pleasant position. }
8. exf4 Nc6 9. dxc5 Qc7 10. g3 e5
{ This super concrete move is the key way to generate counterplay for Black. It works pretty well with our bishop placed on d3. }
11. fxe5 Nxe5 12. Nxe5 Qxe5+ 13. Qe2
{ When it would be a dream scenario for us to trade queens. Of course, Black should keep the queens on. }
13... Qc7
{ Compensating with dynamic play. Black has a huge threat to play ...Re8! after castling. }
14. O-O Re8 15. Qd1 Bh3 16. Re1
{ We will maneuver the knight with Nb3-Nd4 with chances to outplay our opponent later in this dynamically balanced position with the isolated pawn. }
