{ This is a very solid line for Black ➼ played by Caruana and Keymer. Black is preparing ...Ba6 ideas. Black has some alternatives:   8...Nc6  9.dxc5  Qc7  10.g3  e5!  This super concrete move is the key way to generate counterplay for Black. It works pretty well with our bishop placed on d3.  11.fxe5  Nxe5  12.Nxe5  Qxe5+  13.Qe2  when it would be a dream scenario for us to trade queens. Of course, Black should keep the queens on with  13...Qc7!  to compensate with dynamic play. Black has a huge threat to play ...Re8! After  14.O-O  Re8  15.Qd1  Bh3  16.Re1⩲  we will maneuver the knight with Nb3-Nd4 with chances to outplay our opponent later in this dynamically balanced position with the isolated pawn.   8...cxd4  9.Nxd4  Qc7  Black attacks the f4-pawn and intends to meet  10.g3  with  10...e5!  However, @@StartFEN@@rnb2rk1/ppq2ppp/4pn2/3p4/3N1P2/2PB4/PP1N1PPP/R2QK2R w KQ - 1 10@@EndFEN@@  10.Ne2!  is a clever way to defend the f4-pawn ➼ making the ...e5-break less effective. Now Black's best plan is  10...b6!  11.O-O  Ba6!  ➼ solving the problem of the light-squared bishop. After  12.Nf3  Bxd3  13.Qxd3  Nc6  14.Rfe1⩲  We can continue with g3 followed by Ned4 with a balanced position. This is the ideal version of the Berkes structure for Black, but it's still pretty easy to play as White and we could outplay our opponent later. }
9. O-O Ba6
{ This is the main idea for Black, trading off the bad bishop.   9...Bb7  is also playable, but a bit passive compared to 9... Ba6. We can continue  10.Ne5  Nc6  11.Ndf3  , preparing to meet  11...cxd4  with  12.Nxc6!  Bxc6  13.Nxd4!  , while after @@StartFEN@@r2q1rk1/pb3ppp/1pn1pn2/2ppN3/3P1P2/2PB1N2/PP3PPP/R2Q1RK1 b - - 5 11@@EndFEN@@  11...Qd6  12  Re1⩲  we can continue with Qe2 followed by Rad1 with a good version of the Berkes structure. We can follow it up with Bb1 followed by pushing the kingside pawns. }
10. Bxa6 { Misplacing Black's knight on a6. } 10... Nxa6 11. Qe2
{ Attacking the a6-knight. Now Black has two plans:  11...Nc7  11...Nb8. }
11... Nc7
{ Preparing the knight maneuver with ... Ne8-Nd6!   If  11...Nb8  we reply  12.Ne5  , activating the knight. We are not afraid of  12...cxd4  13.cxd4  because White has pressure on the c-file after Rac1 next. Instead, after  @@StartFEN@@rn1q1rk1/p4ppp/1p2pn2/2ppN3/3P1P2/2P5/PP1NQPPP/R4RK1 b - - 3 12@@EndFEN@@  12...Qc7  we simply make all the useful moves with  13.Ndf3  Nc6  14.Rad1  intending Rfe1.  Now Black exchanged  14...cxd4  when  15.Nxd4  is perfectly playable, but Grachev replied  15.Nxc6  Qxc6  16.Nxd4  Qc7  17.g3⩲  with an equal position objectively speaking, but the experienced London System master managed to outplay his opponent in the game between Grachev,B -Matlakov,M,Tornelo INT 2021. }
12. g3 { This is a useful move for us, keeping the f4-pawn protected. } 12...
Nce8 13. c4
{ This is an interesting try to open up the position and exploit Black's time consuming plan. }
13... Nd6 14. Rac1 { Bringing the rooks towards the center. } 14... Rc8 15.
Rfd1 Nf5 16. Nb3
{ With an equal position objectively speaking, but a bit easier to play as White. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5) Queen's Gambit Declined with a quick ...e6 & ...Bd6"]
[Black "The quick 3...e6/4...Bd6: 5...O-O #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3
{ This is the most precise move ➼ avoiding the annoying  2.Bf4  c5!  which gives us some headaches as explained in this informational. }
2... Nf6 3. Bf4 e6 4. e3 Bd6
{ Playing ...Bd6 without ...c5 is a solid approach for Black. The main difference is that  5.Bg3  is no longer such a good move and White has a choice between:  5.Nbd2 @@StartBracket@@going for the Berkes structure@@EndBracket@@  5.Ne5!? @@StartBracket@@going for a double-edged fight@@EndBracket@@. }
5. Nbd2
{ This is the best try for White.  5.Bg3  gives Black a number of interesting tries such as  5...O-O  6.Nbd2  c5  7.c3  Qc7  8.Bd3  Nbd7  followed by ...e5! or  5...O-O  6.Nbd2  b6  7.Bd3  Bb7  8.c3  Ne4  with a very solid position for Black.   5.Ne5  could be an interesting alternative if you want to avoid the Berkes Structure ➼ leading to a double-edged game. }
5... O-O
{ In this branch we simply assume that Black never takes on f4 since that will generally transpose to 5... Bxf4. }
6. c3
{ This is the most flexible move. We are ready to transpose after  6...c5  7.Bd3  @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/ppp2ppp/3bpn2/3p4/3P1B2/2P1PN2/PP1N1PPP/R2QKB1R b KQ - 0 6@@EndFEN@@ while  6...Bxf4  7.exf4  is covered via 5...Bxf4. }
6... b6 7. h4
{ This is the modern way of handling this position. In the past, people used to play  7.Bd3  automatically with an equal game. The point of  7.h4  @@StartBracket@@besides being a 'waiting' move ➼ preparing to meet ...Ba6 with Bxa6 without having to waste a tempo on playing Bd3@@EndBracket@@ is to advance the pawn all the way to h6 @@StartBracket@@if allowed@@EndBracket@@ when Black's king will be weak in the long run. If Black plays ...h6 himself  @@StartBracket@@trying to stop our pawn@@EndBracket@@ ➼ this will create a hook for g4-g5!Black now has a choice between:   7...Ba6  7...Bb7  7...c5. }
7... Ba6 { This is the main idea for Black to trade off the bad bishop. } 8.
Bxa6 { Misplacing Black's knight on a6. } 8... Nxa6 9. h5
{ Threatening to push h6! } 9... h6 10. Ne5
{ Centralizing the knight and making room for g4-g5! } 10... Nb8 11. g4
{ Threatening g5! } 11... Nh7 12. Qe2
{ Improving over the game between Duda-Giri, 2021 that continued  12.Ndf3  with a small advantage for White. The point of Qe2 is to stay a bit more flexible and prepare O-O-O. }
12... Nd7 13. O-O-O
{ With the simple plan of going Bg3 followed by f4 with good attacking prospects on the kingside. }
*

