{ In this branch we simply assume that Black never takes on f4 since that will generally transpose to 5... Bxf4. }
6. c3
{ This is the most flexible move. We are ready to transpose after  6...c5  7.Bd3  @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/ppp2ppp/3bpn2/3p4/3P1B2/2P1PN2/PP1N1PPP/R2QKB1R b KQ - 0 6@@EndFEN@@ while  6...Bxf4  7.exf4  is covered via 5...Bxf4. }
6... b6 7. h4
{ This is the modern way of handling this position. In the past, people used to play  7.Bd3  automatically with an equal game. The point of  7.h4  @@StartBracket@@besides being a 'waiting' move ➼ preparing to meet ...Ba6 with Bxa6 without having to waste a tempo on playing Bd3@@EndBracket@@ is to advance the pawn all the way to h6 @@StartBracket@@if allowed@@EndBracket@@ when Black's king will be weak in the long run. If Black plays ...h6 himself  @@StartBracket@@trying to stop our pawn@@EndBracket@@ ➼ this will create a hook for g4-g5!Black now has a choice between:   7...Ba6  7...Bb7  7...c5. }
7... c5 8. h5 { Threatening to push h6! } 8... h6
{ There are a few alternatives for Black:   8...Qc7  invites the bishop trade, which we don't mind as we get a good version after  9.Bxd6!  Qxd6  10.h6!  weakening the dark squares, and after  10...g6  we can install and support our knight with  11.Ne5  Nfd7  11.f4⩲  .  We will continue with Bd3, Ndf3 and then Qe2 followed by O-O-O. Keep in mind that in some positions ...f6 can be met by Ng4!   8...cxd4  The point of this move is that White lacks the standard recapture exd4 because the f4-bishop would be hanging. So instead we continue  9.Bxd6  Qxd6  10.exd4  ,  keeping the threat of h6. Now  10...h6  11.Ne5!  followed by f4 would give White a pleasant position, while after  @@StartFEN@@rnb2rk1/p4ppp/1p1qpn2/3p3P/3P4/2P2N2/PP1N1PP1/R2QKB1R b KQ - 0 10@@EndFEN@@  10...Nbd7  11.h6  g6  we need to prevent ...e5 with  12.Qe2⩲  when our plan is to castle long followed by Ne5, f4 ➼ with a promising position for White. }
9. Bxd6 { I find this the simplest. } 9... Qxd6 10. Ne5
{ With an easy position for White. We can continue with f4, Bd3 followed by Qf3 and O-O-O. }
