[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5) Queen's Gambit Declined with a quick ...e6 & ...Bd6"]
[Black "The quick 3...e6/4...Bd6 - 5.Ne5!? alternative #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3
{ This is the most precise move ➼ avoiding the annoying  2.Bf4  c5!  which gives us some headaches as explained in this informational. }
2... Nf6 3. Bf4 e6 4. e3 Bd6 5. Ne5
{ This could be a viable alternative to the main move  5.Nbd2  if you are trying to avoid the doubled pawns/want to mix it up a bit. }
5... O-O 6. Nd2 c5 7. c3
{ Preparing to play Bd3 so we can meet ...c4 with Bc2! } 7... Nc6 8. Bd3 Qc7
{ Putting pressure on the e5-square. } 9. Ndf3
{ Reinforcing the e5-knight! At this point Black has a choice between:  9...b6  9...Nd7  9...Ne4  9... cxd4. }
9... Nd7
{ Playing against the e5-knight, but this super common move gives White a powerful initiative. }
10. Ng5 { Threatening Bxh7+! } 10... g6 { This allows a powerful combination. }
11. Nxh7 Kxh7 12. Qh5+ { Taking advantage of the pin. } 12... Kg7 13. Qh6+
{ Forcing ...Kg8 because  13...Kf6  allows  14.Bg5#  . } 13... Kg8 14. Nxg6
{ Threatening Qh8#. } 14... f5
{ Creating an espace square for the king.   14...fxg6  allows a forced mate with  15.Qxg6+  Kh8  16.Qh7#  . }
15. Qh8+ Kf7 16. Qh7+ Ke8 17. Nxf8 { Collecting the exchange. } 17... Kxf8 18.
Bh6+ Ke8 19. Be2
{ Threatening to play Bh5+ with a deadly initiative. There will be no immediate checkmate, but Black will never be able to have a safe king. In the long run White can push the h-pawn which will be quite tricky to stop. }
*

