1. d4 d5 2. Nf3
{ This is the most precise move ➼ avoiding the annoying  2.Bf4  c5!  which gives us some headaches as explained in this informational. }
2... Nf6 3. Bf4 c5 4. e3 Nc6 5. Nbd2 e6 6. c3
{ In this chapter we will focus on the ...c5 main lines where Black plays with the light-squared bishop inside the pawn chain. In this position Black has a wide choice between:  •  6...Bd6   •  6...Be7   •  6...cxd4   •  6...c4   •  6...Qb6   •  6...Nh5  .   Typical pawn structures arising from this chapter:  The reversed Stonewall  The Carlsbad with Bd3.  Model games arising from this chapter:  Carlsen Magnus-Ghaem Maghami Ehsan, Baku 2016  Aronian Levon-Hemant Sharma, Gibraltar 2018  Sedlak Nikola-Szabo Gergely Andras, Budapest 2018  Kovacevic Vlatko-Ree Hans, Maribor 1980  Kovacevic Vlatko-Fressinet Laurent, Solin 2000  Kovacevic Aleksandar-Pap Misa, Valjevo 2018  Kamsky Gata-Goganov Aleksey, Moscow 2016.  Typical endgames arising from this chapter:  Artemiev Vladislav-Savchenko Boris, Chess24 2021  Grachev Boris-Dourerassou Jonathan, chesscom 2020  Kamsky Gata-Belozerov Andrei, chesscom 2020. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "6) Queen's Gambit Declined with 5…e6"]
[Black "QGD with ...e6: Black avoids ...c5"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3
{ This is the most precise move ➼ avoiding the annoying  2.Bf4  c5!  which gives us some headaches as explained in this informational. }
2... Nf6 3. Bf4 e6 4. e3 Be7
{ This will most likely transpose back to the ...c5 & ...Be7 lines!   If  4...c5  I prefer the move order  5.Nbd2!  , even though 5. c3 is playable as well. Now Black has an interesting sideline in  5...Qb6  , which we should respond to with  6.Rb1  Bd6  . Here the best try is  7.dxc5!?  , because the 'natural'  7.Bg3  O-O  8.c3  Nbd7  9.Bd3  Qc7  followed by ...e5! gives Black good counterplay. After 7.dxc5 the line continues  @@StartFEN@@rnb1k2r/pp3ppp/1q1bpn2/2Pp4/5B2/4PN2/PPPN1PPP/1R1QKB1R b Kkq - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7...Qxc5  8.b4!  ,  taking advantage of our rook on b1. After  8...Qc7  9.Bxd6  Qxd6  10.c4!  the position seems a bit easier to play as White. It could continue with  10...O-O  11.Be2  b6  12.O-O  Bb7  13.Qb3  Nbd7  14.Rfd1⩲  . The position should be objectively equal, but it feels a bit easier to play as White because Black's queen is a little misplaced. White managed to win a long game in Sadhwani,R @@StartBracket@@2616@@EndBracket@@-Dreev,A @@StartBracket@@2623@@EndBracket@@ Chess.com INT 2022. }
5. Nbd2 O-O 6. Bd3 b6
{ Preparing the queenside fianchetto. This is the only way Black can deviate from the ... c5-lines. }
7. c3 { Preparing to meet  7...Ba6  with  8.Bc2! } 7... Bb7 8. Ne5
{ This is the most important plan for the London System. The e5-knight gives White pressure in the center and on the kingside. }
8... Nbd7 9. Qf3
{ While  9.h4!?  is always an interesting move in this structure, I prefer  9.Qf3  in this case preparing to play Qh3. This is a typical plan for White after playing Ne5 in a lot of positions. }
9... Nxe5 10. dxe5 { Attacking the f6-knight. } 10... Nd7 11. Qh3
{ Threatening Qxh7# Notice how nicely the d3-bishop and the h3-queen are working together! }
11... g6 12. Nf3 { Protecting the e5-pawn and preparing Qh6 followed by Ng5! }
12... Nc5 { Attacking the d3-bishop. } 13. Bc2
{ White has a simple plan of going Qh6 followed by Ng5 and there is not much Black can do to stop that! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "6) Queen's Gambit Declined with 5…e6"]
[Black "QGD with ...e6: 6...Be7 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3
{ This is the most precise move ➼ avoiding the annoying  2.Bf4  c5!  which gives us some headaches as explained in this informational. }
2... Nf6 3. Bf4 c5 4. e3 Nc6 5. Nbd2
{ This is the key move to start with. A common mistake that most London System players make is  5.c3  allowing  5...Qb6  with a good version for Black.  After 5.Nbd2 Black has a choice between:  5...Qb6 @@StartBracket@@leading to the complex 6.dxc5! lines@@EndBracket@@  5...e6 @@StartBracket@@locking the light squared bishop@@EndBracket@@  5...cxd4 @@StartBracket@@usually combined with ...Bg4/Bf5@@EndBracket@@  5...Bf5 @@StartBracket@@allowing 6.dxc5!@@EndBracket@@  5...Bg4 @@StartBracket@@developing according to the center@@EndBracket@@  5...Nh5 @@StartBracket@@hunting the London bishop@@EndBracket@@ }
5... e6
{ Locking the light squared bishop inside the pawn chain. This generally means that Black will have to queenside fianchetto with ...b6-Bb7. }
6. c3
{ Creating a square on c2 so we can play Bd3 and in case of ...c4 there will be Bc2 followed by the e4-break. In this position Black has a choice between:  6...Qb6  6...Bd6  6...Be7  6...cxd4 followed by ...Nh5  6...Nh5 @@StartBracket@@hunting the London bishop@@EndBracket@@  6...c4 @@StartBracket@@stopping Bd3@@EndBracket@@. }
6... Be7
{ This is the second most common way for Black to develop in this structure. We are dealing with a subtle threat of ...Nh5 and for this reason 7.h3 used to be a very popular choice for White @@StartBracket@@simply creating a square on h2 for the bishop@@EndBracket@@.   However, the issue with  7.h3  is that Black has the annoying  7...Bd6!  ➼ and we can no longer use the typical Bg3 idea. This is one of the reasons why I recommend we stick with the most aggressive 7.Ne5! }
7. Ne5 O-O
{ This is the most popular move for Black in OTB and even more so in online chess. }
8. Bd3 Bd7
{ This is not a critical line, but it's something I expect to see a lot in the lower rated games.   8...Nxe5  9.dxe5  Nd7  10.h4!  transposes to 7...Nxe5 and 9... O-O.   8...Nd7  transposes to 7... Nd7.   Releasing the tension with  8...cxd4  is generally not a good idea for Black. However it can lead to an intresting decision on move 10.  9.exd4  Nxe5!?  This variation is slightly dubious, but I find it quite interesting. Personally I used to retake on e5 with the bishop in general and just play a slightly more pleasant position, but it seems to be even better to play aggressively and take back with the pawn!  10.dxe5!  This works best. While taking with the bishop gives White a rather small and risk free advantage, I prefer taking with the pawn. If Black stays passive we can simply play Nf3-Nd4 with an amazing version of the French Defense.  10...Nd7  11.O-O  Nc5  12.Bc2  Sidestepping Black's threat and keeping the bishop on the most active diagonal ➼ eyeing the enemy king. Now Black has to try  12...d4!?  ,  otherwise White would have played Nf3-Nd4 with a much better position and no counterplay for Black.  13.Qf3!  prepares to meet  13...dxc3  with  14.Qxc3  , while after  13...d3  the pawn will be impossible to keep:  14.Bb1  a5  15.Nb3⩲  , swapping Black's knight and on the next move d3 will hang. We should stay away from  15.b4  axb4  16.cxb4  Qd4!  with counterplay for Black. }
9. Qf3
{ While  9.h4  is a very serious alternative, I wanted to introduce you to this powerful maneuver! White is preparing to play Qh3 ➼ with good attacking prospects on the kingside. }
9... Rc8 { There is not much else to do for Black. } 10. Qh3
{ I want you to take a mental screenshot of this position because White has a powerful attacking mechanism with the d3-bishop and the h3-queen. The next step is to eliminate the f6-knight so we can deliver checkmate on h7! White usually has two ways to do that:   Bg5-Bxf6  g4-g5. }
10... h6
{ This is played with the idea to avoid checkmate on h7, but allows a deadly typical sacrifice.   10...g6  is the other way, shutting down White's d3-bishop, but weakening the dark-squares.  11.Bh6  attacks the rook and makes room for the f4-push. After  11...Re8  12.f4⩲  White has a simple and straightforward plan. First we push f4, and then Ndf3-Ng5 will be deadly ➼ targeting the f7-pawn. }
11. Bxh6 { This bishop sacrifice is very common for the Qf3-Qh3 plan! } 11...
gxh6 12. Qxh6
{ White is completely winning after the key idea of pushing h4! followed by Rh3-Rg3! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "6) Queen's Gambit Declined with 5…e6"]
[Black "QGD with ...e6: 6...Be7 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3
{ This is the most precise move ➼ avoiding the annoying  2.Bf4  c5!  which gives us some headaches as explained in this informational. }
2... Nf6 3. Bf4 c5 4. e3 Nc6 5. Nbd2
{ This is the key move to start with. A common mistake that most London System players make is  5.c3  allowing  5...Qb6  with a good version for Black.  After 5.Nbd2 Black has a choice between:  5...Qb6 @@StartBracket@@leading to the complex 6.dxc5! lines@@EndBracket@@  5...e6 @@StartBracket@@locking the light squared bishop@@EndBracket@@  5...cxd4 @@StartBracket@@usually combined with ...Bg4/Bf5@@EndBracket@@  5...Bf5 @@StartBracket@@allowing 6.dxc5!@@EndBracket@@  5...Bg4 @@StartBracket@@developing according to the center@@EndBracket@@  5...Nh5 @@StartBracket@@hunting the London bishop@@EndBracket@@ }
5... e6
{ Locking the light squared bishop inside the pawn chain. This generally means that Black will have to queenside fianchetto with ...b6-Bb7. }
6. c3
{ Creating a square on c2 so we can play Bd3 and in case of ...c4 there will be Bc2 followed by the e4-break. In this position Black has a choice between:  6...Qb6  6...Bd6  6...Be7  6...cxd4 followed by ...Nh5  6...Nh5 @@StartBracket@@hunting the London bishop@@EndBracket@@  6...c4 @@StartBracket@@stopping Bd3@@EndBracket@@. }
6... Be7
{ This is the second most common way for Black to develop in this structure. We are dealing with a subtle threat of ...Nh5 and for this reason 7.h3 used to be a very popular choice for White @@StartBracket@@simply creating a square on h2 for the bishop@@EndBracket@@.   However, the issue with  7.h3  is that Black has the annoying  7...Bd6!  ➼ and we can no longer use the typical Bg3 idea. This is one of the reasons why I recommend we stick with the most aggressive 7.Ne5! }
7. Ne5 Nxe5
{ Eliminating White's powerful knight must be done sooner or later. This will be our main focus for the 6...Be7 line, with the mention that  7...O-O  followed by 8... Nxe5 is another very popular way of getting into these positions.   7...Qb6  is played occasionally by Black, but I don't really see much point behind this move when White can easily defend the b2-pawn with  8.Rb1  .  Generally when this is a legal reply to ...Qb6 you can play Rb1 quite automatically.  8...O-O  9.Bd3  Nd7  10.Ndf3!  Improving over the game between Le Quang and Wesley So which went 10. O-O.  10...Ndxe5  11.dxe5!  Playing for the attack.  11...Bd7  12.h4→  With good attacking prospects on the kingside based on the typical Greek Gift.   7...Nd7  is, despite being a pretty rare choice for Black, a bit underrated. We follow both Grachev and Sedlak with  8.Ndf3!  White keeps pressure even after the trades.  8...Ndxe5  9.Nxe5  Nxe5  10.Bxe5  O-O  11.Bd3  Bd6  Black is trying to exchange the powerful bishop on e5. Now we force Black to create a hook with  12.Qh5!  f5  13.O-O-O  →  With a pretty unclear position where I think White has the easier play based on the typical g4-break. }
8. dxe5 Nd7 9. h4
{ This aggressive move is fairly typical against the 6... Be7 lines, with the e5-pawn and the h1-rook. However, this is still a very fresh approach in this move order, and I expect this move to become the main line for White. This is because it's Leela's favorite move and it was already validated by top class London System connoisseurs such as Kamsky and Demchenko.   9.h4!?  is a multi-purpose move because in the short term it prepares Qg4 ideas @@StartBracket@@think about the fact that  9.Qg4  doesn't work because of  9...g5!  followed by ...h5-h4 ➼ and Black wins the bishop@@EndBracket@@, and in the long run we are preparing the typical Greek Gift @@StartBracket@@see the 10...c4 line@@EndBracket@@.   The simple  9.Bd3  is also fine @@StartBracket@@but not as useful as 9. h4@@EndBracket@@, and Black then has some annoying alternatives such as  9...Qb6  or  9...Qc7  . }
9... Qc7
{ This is the only sensible queen move because  9...Qb6  can easily be met by  10.Rb1  ➼  when the b6-queen seems to be rather misplaced than super useful. We will just apply the usual plans with a small edge for White. }
10. Qg4 { Hitting the g7-pawn. } 10... g6
{ The lesser evil. The natural  10...O-O  is close to losing after  11.Nf3!  ➼ with a direct threat of Bh6 and the typical greek gift is looming after Bd3 ➼ Bxh7 is a huge threat  @@StartBracket@@see the 10...c4 line@@EndBracket@@. }
11. Qg3
{ With a small but steady edge for White thanks to the weakened dark-squares around the enemy kingside. We can break in the center with e4, and attack on the kingside with Be2-h5! }
*

