{ This position can also be reached from the 7...O-O & 8...Nxe5 move order.   9...c4!?  prevents White from playing the natural Bd3. We can continue  10.Qg4  when Black has to play  10...g6  because  10...O-O  11.Bh6!  wins an exchange. After @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/pp1nbp1p/4p1p1/3pP3/2p2BQP/2P1P3/PP1N1PP1/R3KB1R w KQkq - 0 11@@EndFEN@@  11.e4⩲  White has a small edge because Black is struggling to find a safe square for their king. White has a direct threat on the kingside with h5! while we can usually finish development with Be2-Rd1, generally castling short @@StartBracket@@when the h4-pawn is not hanging@@EndBracket@@, and in some positions we can even play on the queenside with b3.Please keep in mind that the concrete  11...Qb6  can easily be met by  12.Rb1  and Black hasn't made any progress.   9...b6  10.Qg4⩲  just gives White a better position since  10...g6  can be met by  11.e4!  with pressure both in the center and on the kingside.   Finally, taking the poisoned pawn with  9...Bxh4??  is very risky.  10.Qg4+-  gives White a winning position because Black has to either give up the g7-pawn or allow  10...g5  11.Rxh4!  ➼ with a disaster on the kingside. }
10. Bd3
{ We have arrived at the most critical position for the 6...Be7 line. With the last move ➼ White is threatening the accelerated Greek Gift @@StartBracket@@see the 10...c4 line@@EndBracket@@. Black's choice is weighted more towards  10...f5  &  10...f6  , but we will also cover moves such as  10...Re8  and  10...c4  . }
10... c4
{ This mistake is way more common than you may think because people don't expect the Greek gift in this form ➼ thinking that the d2-knight is way too far from the action. Little do they know what's coming! }
11. Bxh7+
{ This motif came as a shocker when I first came across it. It is incredibly effective because generally people expect the greek gift when the knight is closer to the battle ground @@StartBracket@@typically on f3@@EndBracket@@. The fact of the matter is that White can simply take on h7 right away, because Nf3-Ng5 will be virtually unstoppable for Black ➼ highlighting the power of having played 9.h4! }
11... Kxh7 12. Qh5+
{ It is important to start with this because  12.Nf3  would allow  12...Rh8!  and Black wins. }
12... Kg8 13. Nf3
{ Threatening Ng5 with a mating attack since ...Bxg5 is always met by hxg5! }
13... f6
{ The only try because  13...g6  14.Qh6!  followed by Ng5 is hopeless for Black. }
14. Ng5 fxg5 15. hxg5
{ Creating a big threat of g6 @@StartBracket@@setting-up the mating net@@EndBracket@@ followed by Qh8#. }
15... Rxf4
{ People generally try to bail out this way, but White has a very cute and forcing idea.   15...Rf5  stops the typical g6-idea, but loses the g7-pawn. After  16.Qh7+  Kf8  the reply  17.Qg6  is deadly, so  16...Kf7  is forced, but then there follows  17.g6+  Ke8  18.Qxg7+-  and the g-pawn is simply too close to queening! White can continue with O-O-O followed by Rh8 with a winning position thanks to the threat of pushing the g-pawn down the board. }
16. Qh8+ Kf7 17. g6+ { Luring Black's king on the worst square possible! }
17... Kxg6 18. Qh5# { You'd be surprise how often I got this position! } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "6) Queen's Gambit Declined with 5…e6"]
[Black "QGD with ...e6: 6...Nh5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3
{ This is the most precise move ➼ avoiding the annoying  2.Bf4  c5!  which gives us some headaches as explained in this informational. }
2... Nf6 3. Bf4 c5 4. e3 Nc6 5. Nbd2
{ This is the key move to start with. A common mistake that most London System players make is  5.c3  allowing  5...Qb6  with a good version for Black.  After 5.Nbd2 Black has a choice between:  5...Qb6 @@StartBracket@@leading to the complex 6.dxc5! lines@@EndBracket@@  5...e6 @@StartBracket@@locking the light squared bishop@@EndBracket@@  5...cxd4 @@StartBracket@@usually combined with ...Bg4/Bf5@@EndBracket@@  5...Bf5 @@StartBracket@@allowing 6.dxc5!@@EndBracket@@  5...Bg4 @@StartBracket@@developing according to the center@@EndBracket@@  5...Nh5 @@StartBracket@@hunting the London bishop@@EndBracket@@ }
5... e6
{ Locking the light squared bishop inside the pawn chain. This generally means that Black will have to queenside fianchetto with ...b6-Bb7. }
6. c3
{ Creating a square on c2 so we can play Bd3 and in case of ...c4 there will be Bc2 followed by the e4-break. In this position Black has a choice between:  6...Qb6  6...Bd6  6...Be7  6...cxd4 followed by ...Nh5  6...Nh5 @@StartBracket@@hunting the London bishop@@EndBracket@@  6...c4 @@StartBracket@@stopping Bd3@@EndBracket@@. }
6... Nh5 7. Bg5
{ Forcing Black to put up a fight if they want to win the London bishop. Beginners usually make the mistake to play the 'safer'  7.Bg3  ➼ giving Black an easy game after  7...Nxg3  with the bishop pair and good central control. }
7... Qb6
{ The point of this line is to distract White by attacking the b2-pawn and buy some time to hunt the London Bishop with ...h6-g5! }
8. dxc5
{ This move is important because the natural  8.Rb1  allows  8...h6  9.Bh4  g5  which is a bit annoying. }
8... Bxc5
{ 8...Qxb2  leads to a big advantage for White after some precise moves.  9.Nd4!  creates a threat of Rb1 followed by picking up the h5-knight.  9...Nxd4  10.cxd4  would give White a winning position already as in the game between Paehtz,E @@StartBracket@@2474@@EndBracket@@-Banusz,T @@StartBracket@@2616@@EndBracket@@ Minsk 2017. After  9.Nd4  Black plays  9...Nf6  , but  10.Nb5!  creates a very annoying threat of Nc7+ and after  10...Rb8  White wins on the spot with the spectacular tactic  11.Nc4!!  +- because  11...Qxb5  12.Nd6+  wins the queen, and  11...dxc4  allows  12.Nc7+  Ke7  13.Qd6#  .  The position after 11. Nc4!! was seen in the game between Jojua,D @@StartBracket@@2588@@EndBracket@@ -Dordzhieva,D @@StartBracket@@2340@@EndBracket@@ Chess.com INT 2019. }
9. b4
{ This pawn push can take a lot of your opponents by surprise. A common trick that you want to keep in mind is that  9...Bd6  allows  10.Nc4!  winning the bishop pair. }
9... Be7 10. b5
{ Disturbing Black's coordination!  10...Bxg5??  allows  11.Nxg5!  ➼ and White wins a piece. }
10... Na5 11. Bxe7
{ This is why the whole 8.dxc5! line is so powerful ➼ Black loses the right to castle. }
11... Kxe7 12. Qa4
{ With Qb4+ and c4-ideas, White is much better because Black lacks any coordination as in the game between Dhulipalla,B @@StartBracket@@2353@@EndBracket@@ -Vaibhav,S @@StartBracket@@2552@@EndBracket@@ Chess.com INT 2017. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "6) Queen's Gambit Declined with 5…e6"]
[Black "QGD with ...e6: 6...Nh5 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3
{ This is the most precise move ➼ avoiding the annoying  2.Bf4  c5!  which gives us some headaches as explained in this informational. }
2... Nf6 3. Bf4 c5 4. e3 Nc6 5. Nbd2
{ This is the key move to start with. A common mistake that most London System players make is  5.c3  allowing  5...Qb6  with a good version for Black.  After 5.Nbd2 Black has a choice between:  5...Qb6 @@StartBracket@@leading to the complex 6.dxc5! lines@@EndBracket@@  5...e6 @@StartBracket@@locking the light squared bishop@@EndBracket@@  5...cxd4 @@StartBracket@@usually combined with ...Bg4/Bf5@@EndBracket@@  5...Bf5 @@StartBracket@@allowing 6.dxc5!@@EndBracket@@  5...Bg4 @@StartBracket@@developing according to the center@@EndBracket@@  5...Nh5 @@StartBracket@@hunting the London bishop@@EndBracket@@ }
5... e6
{ Locking the light squared bishop inside the pawn chain. This generally means that Black will have to queenside fianchetto with ...b6-Bb7. }
6. c3
{ Creating a square on c2 so we can play Bd3 and in case of ...c4 there will be Bc2 followed by the e4-break. In this position Black has a choice between:  6...Qb6  6...Bd6  6...Be7  6...cxd4 followed by ...Nh5  6...Nh5 @@StartBracket@@hunting the London bishop@@EndBracket@@  6...c4 @@StartBracket@@stopping Bd3@@EndBracket@@. }
6... Nh5 7. Bg5
{ Forcing Black to put up a fight if they want to win the London bishop. Beginners usually make the mistake to play the 'safer'  7.Bg3  ➼ giving Black an easy game after  7...Nxg3  with the bishop pair and good central control. }
7... f6
{ This is by far the most common continuation for Black in online chess. What's even more interesting to see, is that they usually combine it with 8...g5 ➼ which is a huge blunder.   7...Be7  doesn't make much sense to me because the whole idea behind ...Nh5 is to harrass the London Bishop ➼ so offering the trade will result in misplacing the h5-knight for no particular reason. After  8.Bxe7  Qxe7  we centralize the knight with  9.Ne5  while gaining a tempo! Now 9...Nxe5 10. dxe5  leads to a solid advantage for White because the h5-knight is struggling to get back in the game, while after  9...Nf6  10.f4⩲  we managed to get in the typical 'Reversed Stonewall' pawn structure. On the next move we are going to play Bd3 followed by O-O with a risk-free advantage for White thanks to the active knight on e5. }
8. Bh4 g5
{ I was able to find around 1000 games with this move in the Lichess database @@StartBracket@@which is pretty huge out of 1500 total games@@EndBracket@@!   8...g6  is a better try for Black, but I still prefer White. The only trick to remember while dealing with these lines is to meet ...cxd4 with cxd4! ➼ avoiding any ...Nf4 ideas.  9.Bd3  cxd4  10.cxd4!   This is the key move because the natural  10.exd4  allows  10...Nf4!  and Black takes over the initiative.  10...Be7  11.O-O  O-O  12.Rc1⩲  White has an easy push on the queenside with a3-b4 while Black lacks any active play. For more details check out the game between Bluebaum,M @@StartBracket@@2641@@EndBracket@@-Van Foreest,L @@StartBracket@@2531@@EndBracket@@ Germany 2020. }
9. Nxg5 { This wins on the spot ➼ exploiting the undefended h5-knight. } 9...
fxg5 10. Qxh5+
{ With two extra pawns and a safer king, this should be a walk in the park. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "6) Queen's Gambit Declined with 5…e6"]
[Black "QGD with ...e6: 6...c4"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3
{ This is the most precise move ➼ avoiding the annoying  2.Bf4  c5!  which gives us some headaches as explained in this informational. }
2... Nf6 3. Bf4 c5 4. e3 Nc6 5. Nbd2
{ This is the key move to start with. A common mistake that most London System players make is  5.c3  allowing  5...Qb6  with a good version for Black.  After 5.Nbd2 Black has a choice between:  5...Qb6 @@StartBracket@@leading to the complex 6.dxc5! lines@@EndBracket@@  5...e6 @@StartBracket@@locking the light squared bishop@@EndBracket@@  5...cxd4 @@StartBracket@@usually combined with ...Bg4/Bf5@@EndBracket@@  5...Bf5 @@StartBracket@@allowing 6.dxc5!@@EndBracket@@  5...Bg4 @@StartBracket@@developing according to the center@@EndBracket@@  5...Nh5 @@StartBracket@@hunting the London bishop@@EndBracket@@ }
5... e6
{ Locking the light squared bishop inside the pawn chain. This generally means that Black will have to queenside fianchetto with ...b6-Bb7. }
6. c3
{ Creating a square on c2 so we can play Bd3 and in case of ...c4 there will be Bc2 followed by the e4-break. In this position Black has a choice between:  6...Qb6  6...Bd6  6...Be7  6...cxd4 followed by ...Nh5  6...Nh5 @@StartBracket@@hunting the London bishop@@EndBracket@@  6...c4 @@StartBracket@@stopping Bd3@@EndBracket@@. }
6... c4
{ This is played with the idea to stop White from developing naturally with Bd3. }
7. Qc2
{ Generally the key idea to counter Black's queenside play connected with ...c4 ➼ is to break in the center with e4!   Going for the thematic  7.b3  does not work very well because Black gets good counterplay after  7...b5  8.a4  b4!  with a double-edged position. }
7... Bd6
{ After  7...Be7  the most precise is  8.b3!  ➼ using the c4-pawn as a 'hook'.   The problem with the natural  8.e4  is that Black has a strange resource based on  8...Nh5  9.Be3  f5!  with very annoying threats such as pushing ...f4! ➼ trapping the e3-bishop.  After  8.b3  , the idea  8...b5  no longer works that well because of  9.a4  b4  10.bxc4  bxc3  11.Qxc3  and Black does not have enough play for the pawn. So Black plays  8...cxb3  9.axb3  O-O  10.Bd3  Bd7  11.O-O  Rc8  with the positional threat of going ... Nb4 ➼ winning the bishop pair.  After the important prophylactic move  12.Qb1!  ⩲  White has a safe advantage. You can choose between playing in the center with e4 or playing on the queenside with b4-Nb3-Nc5! }
8. Bxd6
{ Taking on d6 works well because we can combine it with e4 and win time. }
8... Qxd6 9. e4
{ With a slightly better position for White thanks to the extra space in the center. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "6) Queen's Gambit Declined with 5…e6"]
[Black "QGD with ...e6: 6...Qb6"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3
{ This is the most precise move ➼ avoiding the annoying  2.Bf4  c5!  which gives us some headaches as explained in this informational. }
2... Nf6 3. Bf4 c5 4. e3 Nc6 5. Nbd2
{ This is the key move to start with. A common mistake that most London System players make is  5.c3  allowing  5...Qb6  with a good version for Black.  After 5.Nbd2 Black has a choice between:  5...Qb6 @@StartBracket@@leading to the complex 6.dxc5! lines@@EndBracket@@  5...e6 @@StartBracket@@locking the light squared bishop@@EndBracket@@  5...cxd4 @@StartBracket@@usually combined with ...Bg4/Bf5@@EndBracket@@  5...Bf5 @@StartBracket@@allowing 6.dxc5!@@EndBracket@@  5...Bg4 @@StartBracket@@developing according to the center@@EndBracket@@  5...Nh5 @@StartBracket@@hunting the London bishop@@EndBracket@@ }
5... e6
{ Locking the light squared bishop inside the pawn chain. This generally means that Black will have to queenside fianchetto with ...b6-Bb7. }
6. c3
{ Creating a square on c2 so we can play Bd3 and in case of ...c4 there will be Bc2 followed by the e4-break. In this position Black has a choice between:  6...Qb6  6...Bd6  6...Be7  6...cxd4 followed by ...Nh5  6...Nh5 @@StartBracket@@hunting the London bishop@@EndBracket@@  6...c4 @@StartBracket@@stopping Bd3@@EndBracket@@. }
6... Qb6 7. Rb1
{ This is the standard way to defend against ...Qb6! While  7.Qb3  could be an alternative, I don't think it should be as good as our main line. }
7... Nh5
{ 7...Be7  threatens ...Nh5, so we create an escape square with  8.h3!  The line could continue  8...O-O  9.Bd3  Rd8  10.O-O  Bd7  11.Qe2!  Placing the queen on the optimal square so we can break with e4 in the near future.  11...Be8  12.dxc5!  Taking on c5 first because the direct 12. e4 would allow Black to take twice on d4.  12...Bxc5  13.e4⩲  With an improved version of the French for White. The plan is to push e5 and then maneuver with Nb3-Nbd4. White won a nice game in Van den Doel,E @@StartBracket@@2568@@EndBracket@@-Stark,L @@StartBracket@@2379@@EndBracket@@ Haarlem 2016. }
8. dxc5
{ This is the key move to fight for an advantage because  8.Bg5  transposes into a good version for Black of the 6...Nh5 line. }
8... Bxc5 9. b4
{ Attacking the c5-bishop. Keep in mind that  9...Nxf4  loses to  10.bxc5! }
9... Be7 10. b5 { Hitting the c6-knight. } 10... Nb8 11. Be5
{ White is able to keep the London-Bishop with Bd4 next, followed by the c4-break with pressure on the queenside. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "6) Queen's Gambit Declined with 5…e6"]
[Black "QGD with ...e6: 6...cxd4 and 7...Bd6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3
{ This is the most precise move ➼ avoiding the annoying  2.Bf4  c5!  which gives us some headaches as explained in this informational. }
2... Nf6 3. Bf4 c5 4. e3 Nc6 5. Nbd2
{ This is the key move to start with. A common mistake that most London System players make is  5.c3  allowing  5...Qb6  with a good version for Black.  After 5.Nbd2 Black has a choice between:  5...Qb6 @@StartBracket@@leading to the complex 6.dxc5! lines@@EndBracket@@  5...e6 @@StartBracket@@locking the light squared bishop@@EndBracket@@  5...cxd4 @@StartBracket@@usually combined with ...Bg4/Bf5@@EndBracket@@  5...Bf5 @@StartBracket@@allowing 6.dxc5!@@EndBracket@@  5...Bg4 @@StartBracket@@developing according to the center@@EndBracket@@  5...Nh5 @@StartBracket@@hunting the London bishop@@EndBracket@@ }
5... e6
{ Locking the light squared bishop inside the pawn chain. This generally means that Black will have to queenside fianchetto with ...b6-Bb7. }
6. c3
{ Creating a square on c2 so we can play Bd3 and in case of ...c4 there will be Bc2 followed by the e4-break. In this position Black has a choice between:  6...Qb6  6...Bd6  6...Be7  6...cxd4 followed by ...Nh5  6...Nh5 @@StartBracket@@hunting the London bishop@@EndBracket@@  6...c4 @@StartBracket@@stopping Bd3@@EndBracket@@. }
6... cxd4
{ This move combined with 7...Nh5 became popular in 2017 when Hikaru played it on a number of occasions. The line seems to have hit its peak, but it's still seen from time to time in elite games. If we are talking about online chess, the casual players seem to combine this mostly with 7...Bd6 ➼ which gives White an easy game. }
7. exd4
{ This is the most common recapture in the London System. Taking back with the c-pawn is very situational as in the rare line with 6...Nh5 & 8...g6. As a general rule I would say taking back with the e-pawn is the best move in 90% of the cases. }
7... Bd6
{ By far the most common choice in online chess, but this is simply slightly worse for Black because of the silly blocked-in light-squared bishop. }
8. Bg3
{ Giving Black the chance to take on g3 ➼ opening up the h-file for our rook. There is obviously nothing wrong with  8.Bxd6  , but I prefer the text move because after  8.Bg3  a lot of lower rated players will play  8...Bxg3  giving us good attacking prospects after  9.hxg3! }
8... Bxg3 { Played in half of the games. } 9. hxg3
{ We pretty much always take back with the h-pawn. Taking back with the f-pawn is very situational and rare I would say, it could make sense only if White already castled short and we could somehow use the open f-file for the rook, but I would say over 90% of the cases ➼ taking with the h-pawn is the way to go. }
9... Bd7
{ This usually prepares ...O-O-O because going short is very risky with the open h-file. }
10. Bd3 Qc7 11. O-O
{ Following a balanced strategy is optimal here. Even though having the open h-file for the rook was nice, we have to be realistic and understand the fact that Black is simply going to castle long if we wait any longer. There is not much point to dreaming about an attack on the h-file in that case. If Black decides to castle long, the game will become a race, but we are also fine with him castling short since we are getting a slightly better risk-free position. }
11... O-O-O
{ This move leads to a double-edged affair which should favor White because of the better central control.   In case of  11...O-O  we can activate our rook and prepare Ne5 with  12.Re1  Rfe8  13.Ne5⩲  , with a better position for White thanks to the active e5-knight and the huge difference between the bishops. The d7-bishop is very passive while the d3-bishop is playing a big role in our initiative against the enemy king. Next up, the plan is to push the g-pawn with g4-g5 when Black's king becomes vulnerable. }
12. Re1
{ Keeping good control over the e5-square. The natural  12.b4  would have been a bit careless in view of  12...e5!  with a messy position. }
12... h5 13. b4
{ White should be faster in this race after Rc1 followed by b5 and c4! } *

