2... Nf6 3. Bf4 c5 4. e3 Nc6 5. Nbd2
{ This is the key move to start with. A common mistake that most London System players make is  5.c3  allowing  5...Qb6  with a good version for Black.  After 5.Nbd2 Black has a choice between:  5...Qb6 @@StartBracket@@leading to the complex 6.dxc5! lines@@EndBracket@@  5...e6 @@StartBracket@@locking the light squared bishop@@EndBracket@@  5...cxd4 @@StartBracket@@usually combined with ...Bg4/Bf5@@EndBracket@@  5...Bf5 @@StartBracket@@allowing 6.dxc5!@@EndBracket@@  5...Bg4 @@StartBracket@@developing according to the center@@EndBracket@@  5...Nh5 @@StartBracket@@hunting the London bishop@@EndBracket@@ }
5... e6
{ Locking the light squared bishop inside the pawn chain. This generally means that Black will have to queenside fianchetto with ...b6-Bb7. }
6. c3
{ Creating a square on c2 so we can play Bd3 and in case of ...c4 there will be Bc2 followed by the e4-break. In this position Black has a choice between:  6...Qb6  6...Bd6  6...Be7  6...cxd4 followed by ...Nh5  6...Nh5 @@StartBracket@@hunting the London bishop@@EndBracket@@  6...c4 @@StartBracket@@stopping Bd3@@EndBracket@@. }
6... cxd4
{ This move combined with 7...Nh5 became popular in 2017 when Hikaru played it on a number of occasions. The line seems to have hit its peak, but it's still seen from time to time in elite games. If we are talking about online chess, the casual players seem to combine this mostly with 7...Bd6 ➼ which gives White an easy game. }
7. exd4
{ This is the most common recapture in the London System. Taking back with the c-pawn is very situational as in the rare line with 6...Nh5 & 8...g6. As a general rule I would say taking back with the e-pawn is the best move in 90% of the cases. }
7... Bd6
{ By far the most common choice in online chess, but this is simply slightly worse for Black because of the silly blocked-in light-squared bishop. }
8. Bg3
{ Giving Black the chance to take on g3 ➼ opening up the h-file for our rook. There is obviously nothing wrong with  8.Bxd6  , but I prefer the text move because after  8.Bg3  a lot of lower rated players will play  8...Bxg3  giving us good attacking prospects after  9.hxg3! }
8... O-O { This is played generally by the players which never take on g3. } 9.
Bd3 Re8
{ This is by far the most common move for Black in online chess ➼ threatening to push ...e5! Black has a few alternatives:   9...b6  is another way for Black to develop the light-squared bishop to b7. White has a number of ways to get an advantage, but we will be following the footsteps of Gata Kamsky!  10.Qe2  Placing the queen on the optimal square and preparing Ne5 ideas. Going 10. Qc2 is a pretty common mistake that I've seen a lot of beginners make.  10...Bb7  11.O-O  Bxg3  12.hxg3  Rc8  13.Rae1!?  This is an interesting take by Kamsky because 13. Rfe1 was also completely fine. The point of 13.Rae1 is to play Ne5 followed by f4 ➼ when the f1-rook is quite well-placed.  13...Re8  14.Ne5⩲  White has a simple and powerful plan to push f4 followed by g4-g5 with good attacking prospects on the kingside. White won a nice game in: Kamsky,G @@StartBracket@@2674@@EndBracket@@-Veiga,E @@StartBracket@@2106@@EndBracket@@ Chess.com INT 2020.   9...Qc7  threatens to push in the center with ...e5!, but  10.Qe2!  controls the e5-square, and in case of  10...Re8  we are in time with  11.Ne5!  Play could continue @@StartFEN@@r1b2rk1/ppq2ppp/2nbpn2/3p4/3P4/2PB1NB1/PP1NQPPP/R3K2R b KQ - 6 10@@EndFEN@@  10...a6  11.Bxd6  Qxd6  12.Ne5  Nd7  13.f4⩲  With a risk-free advantage for White. For more details check out the  game between Esipenko,A @@StartBracket@@2593@@EndBracket@@ -Stoyanov,T @@StartBracket@@2310@@EndBracket@@ Skopje 2018. }
10. Ne5 { The key move to stop Black's counterplay! } 10... Qc7
{ 10...Bxe5  11.dxe5  gives White an improved version of the French. After  11...Nd7  12.Nf3  feels more natural than 12.f4 because it seemed to restrict our g3-bishop quite a bit @@StartBracket@@despite the fact the White keeps the advantage there as well@@EndBracket@@.  12...Nc5  13.Bc2!  We make sure to keep our main attacking piece alive.  13...b6  14.O-O  ⩲  With Re1 and Nd4, White has a slightly better position in the long run thanks to the extra space and the two bishops. White won a nice game in: Grachev,B @@StartBracket@@2649@@EndBracket@@-Demidov,M @@StartBracket@@2497@@EndBracket@@ Moscow 2015. }
11. f4
{ The e5-knight secures a pleasant/risk-free position for White. What I find very interesting is that a lot of players have gone  11...Nd7??  allowing the typical  12.Bxh7+  Kxh7  13.Qh5+  Kg8  14.Qxf7+  Kh7  15.Qxe8  with an instant win for White. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "6) Queen's Gambit Declined with 5…e6"]
[Black "QGD with ...e6: 6...cxd4 and 7...Nh5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3
{ This is the most precise move ➼ avoiding the annoying  2.Bf4  c5!  which gives us some headaches as explained in this informational. }
2... Nf6 3. Bf4 c5 4. e3 Nc6 5. Nbd2
{ This is the key move to start with. A common mistake that most London System players make is  5.c3  allowing  5...Qb6  with a good version for Black.  After 5.Nbd2 Black has a choice between:  5...Qb6 @@StartBracket@@leading to the complex 6.dxc5! lines@@EndBracket@@  5...e6 @@StartBracket@@locking the light squared bishop@@EndBracket@@  5...cxd4 @@StartBracket@@usually combined with ...Bg4/Bf5@@EndBracket@@  5...Bf5 @@StartBracket@@allowing 6.dxc5!@@EndBracket@@  5...Bg4 @@StartBracket@@developing according to the center@@EndBracket@@  5...Nh5 @@StartBracket@@hunting the London bishop@@EndBracket@@ }
5... e6
{ Locking the light squared bishop inside the pawn chain. This generally means that Black will have to queenside fianchetto with ...b6-Bb7. }
6. c3
{ Creating a square on c2 so we can play Bd3 and in case of ...c4 there will be Bc2 followed by the e4-break. In this position Black has a choice between:  6...Qb6  6...Bd6  6...Be7  6...cxd4 followed by ...Nh5  6...Nh5 @@StartBracket@@hunting the London bishop@@EndBracket@@  6...c4 @@StartBracket@@stopping Bd3@@EndBracket@@. }
6... cxd4
{ This move combined with 7...Nh5 became popular in 2017 when Hikaru played it on a number of occasions. The line seems to have hit its peak, but it's still seen from time to time in elite games. If we are talking about online chess, the casual players seem to combine this mostly with 7...Bd6 ➼ which gives White an easy game. }
7. exd4
{ This is the most common recapture in the London System. Taking back with the c-pawn is very situational as in the rare line with 6...Nh5 & 8...g6. As a general rule I would say taking back with the e-pawn is the best move in 90% of the cases. }
7... Nh5 { This is a good line theoretically speaking, but hard to play. } 8.
Be3 Bd6
{ This is the key idea behind Black's set-up. The whole point is to meet  9.Bd3  with  9...Nf4!  ➼ and White has to give up the bishop pair. }
9. Ne5 { Attacking the h5-knight and avoiding Black's ...Nf4-idea. } 9... g6
{ The main move for Black because  9...Nf6  10.f4  gives White a risk-free advantage. }
10. Nd3
{ The knight is generally really well placed on d3 in the Carlsbad Structure. This was played by London System experts such as Demchenko, Berkes and Kamsky. The natural  10.f4  leads to an unclear game after  10...f6  11.Nd3  O-O  12.Be2  Ng7  because we lack the typical ideas to trade off the dark squared bishops with Bf4. }
10... O-O 11. g3
{ Going for the fianchetto is optimal here with the knight placed on d3. }
11... b6
{ This is Black's best try ➼ preparing to play Ba6 @@StartBracket@@trading off the bad bishop@@EndBracket@@ .   The alternative  11...f5?!  creates a direct threat of pushing ...f4 ➼ but weakens the e5-square in the long run. With  12.Bh6!  we avoid Black's threat with gain of tempo, and after  12...Re8  13.Be2  gain another tempo with the threat of Bxh5.  13...Nf6  14.Nf3  The knight is heading to e5.  14...b6  15.Bf4!  Trading the dark-squared bishops ➼ will make it easier for White to play around the e5-square.  15...Ba6  16.Bxd6  Qxd6  17.Nde5⩲  with a pleasant position for White thanks to the juicy outpost on e5. }
12. Bg2 { Preparing O-O. } 12... Ba6 { Attacking the d3-knight. } 13. Nf3
{ Defending the d3-knight and controlling the e5-square. } 13... f6
{ This is the most flexible approach ➼ controlling the critical e5-square. The computer is usually happy playing this type of position, but in a practical game I find White's position much easier to play. It's very easy for Black to make an inaccuracy which can easily start snowballing the game in White's favor. }
14. O-O
{ Getting our king to safety and setting up a small trap. In case Black goes for the overly ambitious  14...e5  we can punish it with  15.Nfxe5!  ➼ with a winning position for White thanks to the huge threat of Bxd5+. }
14... Qd7 { Preparing to bring the rook over with ...Rae8! } 15. Re1
{ Unpinning and activating the rook. } 15... Rae8 16. Bh6
{ Attacking the f8-rook while clearing the e-file so we can double up and put pressure on the backward e6-pawn. }
16... Rf7 17. Bh3
{ With a balanced position according to the engine, but it's much harder to play as Black from a human perspective. White has got a big advantage soon in @@StartBracket@@38@@EndBracket@@ Aryan,C @@StartBracket@@2585@@EndBracket@@-Erigaisi,A  @@StartBracket@@2559@@EndBracket@@ Lichess.org INT 2020. }
