10... Ng7
{ This is a common maneuver for Black, preparing ...Nf5!   10...f6  11.g3  Ng7  transposes to 10...Ng7 and 11...f6.   10...f5  threatens to trap our bishop with ...f4, but we can sidestep it with  11.Bh6!  Qc7  12.Be2  Nf6  13.g3  b6  14.Bf4⩲  with a lasting initiative for White thanks to the backward pawn on e6 and pressure on the e-file. Torre,E @@StartBracket@@2458@@EndBracket@@-Begmuratov,A @@StartBracket@@2403@@EndBracket@@ Ashkhabad 2017 }
11. g3
{ Going for the fianchetto is optimal here with the knight placed on d3. }
11... Nf5 { Introducing ...Nxe3 ideas. } 12. Bf4
{ Trading off the dark-squared bishops works very well here because Black remains with the passive light-squared bishop. }
12... O-O 13. Bg2 { Preparing O-O. } 13... b6 14. Bxd6 Qxd6 15. O-O Ba6
{ Attacking the d3-knight. } 16. Nf3 f6 17. Re1
{ With an easier position for White. We can continue with Qd2 followed by Nf4-h4 with pressure on the kingside and on the backward e6-pawn. White won the correspondence game Tedesco,M @@StartBracket@@2283@@EndBracket@@ -Weiss,L @@StartBracket@@2176@@EndBracket@@ ICCF email 2018. }
