{ The star move for the London System. Besides inviting Black to go ...Bxg3 ➼ opening up the h-file for our rook, we have a deeper idea in mind. White's strategy @@StartBracket@@after Black goes ...d5@@EndBracket@@ will most of the times be focused on using the e5-square for the knight.To sum things up, if White manages to place the knight on e5 and keep it there ➼ this will always guarantee a bit of pressure on Black's position. Likewise, if Black manages to take control over the e5-square and push ...e6-e5 ➼ this will result in a completely even game. }
7... O-O { This is the most common move for Black. } 8. Bd3 Qe7
{ Similarly to  8...Re8  ➼ Black is preparing to push ... e5! The main difference between  8...Qe7  and  8...Re8  is that with  8...Qe7  Black has an additional idea to meet  9.Ne5  with  9...Nd7!?  which is not really a thing after @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/pp3ppp/2nbpn2/2pp4/3P4/2PBPNB1/PP1N1PPP/R2QK2R b KQ - 4 8@@EndFEN@@  8...Re8  9.Ne5  because in that case  9...Nd7??  simply loses a piece after  10.Nxc6  bxc6  11.Bxd6! }
9. Ne5
{ This is the key move to begin with. The careless  9.O-O  allows  9...e5!  and after  10.dxe5  Nxe5  11.Nxe5  Bxe5  12.Bxe5  Qxe5  ➼ Black manages to fully equalise and we are left with a dry position on the board. }
9... Bxe5
{ This capture is pretty common since most people don't have the patience to play around the e5-knight. In fact Black doesn't really have a pleasant choice to make because after 9. Ne5! White should be a bit better regardless. }
10. dxe5
{ Taking back with the pawn on e5 is generally the way to go against ...d5 lines. Taking with the bishop is very situational and it's usually done in case Black can somehow attack the e5-pawn and potentially win it. }
10... Nd7 { Attacking the e5-pawn! } 11. f4
{ This move works best. The alternative  11.Nf3  is a bit inferior, but definitely playable as well. }
11... f6
{ This is by far Black's most common move in online chess ➼ immediately fighting for the e5-square.   11...f5  would set up the 'Stonewall'. This is a typical structure that we can get after we go for the Ne5-plan. Generally the key idea to break it ➼ is to go for the g4-push.  12.h4Ν !  Suggested by Leela, this is a completely new approach in a relatively well known position. The main point of this move is to push h5 ➼ which allows us to activate the bishop with Bh4! Once that is achieved, we can focus on the main plan to break the 'Stonewall' and organize the g4-break with Rg1.   The standard alternative  12.Nf3  with a similar idea to play Bh4 followed by the g4-break is playable as well, it's just that pushing the h-pawn seems to be a bit faster.  After 12. h4  ! the line could continue  12...c4  13.Bc2  Keeping the bishop on the key diagonal ➼ eyeing the enemy kingside.  13...Nc5  14.h5  Preparing to activate the bishop with Bh4.  14...b5  15.Bh4  Activating the bishop while making room for the g-pawn.  15...Qc7  16.g4  We are going to open up the g-file with gxf5 followed by Rg1. We have ideas to bring the knight over with Nf3-Nd4 or Nf3-Ng5. We should constantly watch out for the right opportunity to throw in h6 followed by Bf6! @@StartBracket@@in case Black answers with ...g6@@EndBracket@@. The queen can generally activate via Qe2-Qg2 and the king is safer in the center than on the queenside because Black could be getting some annoying counterplay with ...b4! }
12. Qh5
{ Targetting the h7-square ➼ this is the most precise reaction. Most players went  12.exf6  in this position, but after  12...Nxf6  13.O-O  e5!  ➼ objectively speaking Black has equalized and scored very well in the online database. As you will see in the upcoming lines, the queen turns out to be very useful on the kingside, stopping the ...e5-break or making it less effective. }
12... g6
{ The most common move for Black, not being afraid of  13.Bxg6  hxg6  14.Qxg6+  because there is always  14...Qg7!  ➼ keeping the Black king safe.   The passive alternative  12...f5  gives White nice play in the upcoming endgames after  13.Bh4  Qf7  14.Qxf7+  Rxf7  15.Rg1  with g4 next, White is pressing with the extra space and the bishop pair. }
13. exf6
{ This is a nice intermezzo because  13...gxh5  14.fxe7  favors White because Black's doubled pawns are pretty weak. }
13... Nxf6
{ The most common move.   13...Qxf6  is less common than taking back with the knight, but it's definitely something we need to be ready for. We reply  14.Qh6!  The queen is really well placed on this square, and if Black is willing to get rid of it, they have to enter the endgame which are definitely better for White with the bishop pair.  14...e5  The only ambitious try for Black.   14...Qg7  gives White easy play after  15.Qxg7+  Kxg7  16.O-O  followed by the e4-break with a pleasant endgame.  15.O-O !  Creating a huge threat of fxe5, so Black is forced to keep the f-file closed.  15...e4  Taking a bit of space, but mainly avoiding fxe5. The issue with this plan, though, is that White will have ideas to undermine Black's structure with c4 and the e4-pawn becomes vulnerable.  16.Bh4!  Another powerful intermezzo because something like  16...Qe6  runs into  17.f5!  and Black has concrete problems. Safer is  16...Qg7  , but Black is still suffering after  17.Qxg7+  Kxg7  18.Be2⩲  The plan is to undermine Black's structure with c4 so that the overextended e4-pawn will become vulnerable. }
14. Qg5 { The key square for the queen, stopping Black from pushing ...e5! }
14... Qg7 15. O-O
{ We are going to break with e4 next followed by Rae1 with a slightly better position thanks to the extra space and the bishop pair. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "6) Queen's Gambit Declined with 5…e6"]
[Black "QGD with ...e6: 6...Bd6 and 7...O-O #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3
{ This is the most precise move ➼ avoiding the annoying  2.Bf4  c5!  which gives us some headaches as explained in this informational. }
2... Nf6 3. Bf4 c5 4. e3 Nc6 5. Nbd2
{ This is the key move to start with. A common mistake that most London System players make is  5.c3  allowing  5...Qb6  with a good version for Black.  After 5.Nbd2 Black has a choice between:  5...Qb6 @@StartBracket@@leading to the complex 6.dxc5! lines@@EndBracket@@  5...e6 @@StartBracket@@locking the light squared bishop@@EndBracket@@  5...cxd4 @@StartBracket@@usually combined with ...Bg4/Bf5@@EndBracket@@  5...Bf5 @@StartBracket@@allowing 6.dxc5!@@EndBracket@@  5...Bg4 @@StartBracket@@developing according to the center@@EndBracket@@  5...Nh5 @@StartBracket@@hunting the London bishop@@EndBracket@@ }
5... e6
{ Locking the light squared bishop inside the pawn chain. This generally means that Black will have to queenside fianchetto with ...b6-Bb7. }
6. c3
{ Creating a square on c2 so we can play Bd3 and in case of ...c4 there will be Bc2 followed by the e4-break. In this position Black has a choice between:  6...Qb6  6...Bd6  6...Be7  6...cxd4 followed by ...Nh5  6...Nh5 @@StartBracket@@hunting the London bishop@@EndBracket@@  6...c4 @@StartBracket@@stopping Bd3@@EndBracket@@. }
6... Bd6
{ This is the most popular move in both OTB and online chess. Black is developing the dark-squared bishop to its most active spot ➼ fighting for the e5-square. }
7. Bg3
{ The star move for the London System. Besides inviting Black to go ...Bxg3 ➼ opening up the h-file for our rook, we have a deeper idea in mind. White's strategy @@StartBracket@@after Black goes ...d5@@EndBracket@@ will most of the times be focused on using the e5-square for the knight.To sum things up, if White manages to place the knight on e5 and keep it there ➼ this will always guarantee a bit of pressure on Black's position. Likewise, if Black manages to take control over the e5-square and push ...e6-e5 ➼ this will result in a completely even game. }
7... O-O { This is the most common move for Black. } 8. Bd3 Qe7
{ Similarly to  8...Re8  ➼ Black is preparing to push ... e5! The main difference between  8...Qe7  and  8...Re8  is that with  8...Qe7  Black has an additional idea to meet  9.Ne5  with  9...Nd7!?  which is not really a thing after @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/pp3ppp/2nbpn2/2pp4/3P4/2PBPNB1/PP1N1PPP/R2QK2R b KQ - 4 8@@EndFEN@@  8...Re8  9.Ne5  because in that case  9...Nd7??  simply loses a piece after  10.Nxc6  bxc6  11.Bxd6! }
9. Ne5
{ This is the key move to begin with. The careless  9.O-O  allows  9...e5!  and after  10.dxe5  Nxe5  11.Nxe5  Bxe5  12.Bxe5  Qxe5  ➼ Black manages to fully equalise and we are left with a dry position on the board. }
9... Nd7 10. Nxd7
{ The best try for White ➼ setting up a deadly trap. The natural  10.f4  does not work so well because of  10...f6!  and Black manages to equalize. }
10... Bxd7
{ This is the most natural way to recapture, and the most played move in online chess. It's pretty funny that after this 'innocent' move ➼ Black is lost! Even experienced grandmasters have fallen for this in the past, and the best example that comes to mind is the game between Kamsky-Shankland, 2014. }
11. Bxd6 Qxd6 12. dxc5 { Luring Black's queen to a vulnerable square! } 12...
Qxc5 { The only critical move ➼ otherwise Black is just down a pawn. } 13.
Bxh7+ { This stunning Greek Gift just wins. } 13... Kxh7 14. Qh5+ Kg8 15. Ne4
{ The point behind everything White did so far. Now it's easier to understand why 12. dxc5! was required. The enemy queen is under attack while Ng5 is coming on the next move. }
15... Qc4
{ The problem with  15...g6  is that White can simply go  16.Nxc5  gxh5  17.Nxd7  with a winning endgame. }
16. Ng5 { Threatening Qh7#. } 16... Rfd8
{ This is the best defense.   16...Qd3  is a common try in online chess, preparing to bring the queen over to g6, but after the key move  17.e4!  ➼ blocking Black's queen, White wins:  17...Rfd8  18.Qxf7+  Kh8  19.Rd1!  Activating the rook with tempo.  19...Qc4  Stopping White from castling.  20.f4+-  After this strong move White is completely winning. The plan is to simply go Rf1-Rf3-Rh3 and checkmate Black on the h-file. }
17. Qxf7+ Kh8 { Threatening ...Qh4! } 18. Qh5+
{ This is very precise! Stopping Black's defensive idea with ...Qh4. } 18...
Kg8 19. Rd1
{ With a winning position for White, objectively speaking. For more details check out the game between Kamsky,G @@StartBracket@@2709@@EndBracket@@ -Shankland,S @@StartBracket@@2611@@EndBracket@@ Sturbridge 2014. }
*

