7... O-O { This is the most common move for Black. } 8. Bd3 Qe7
{ Similarly to  8...Re8  ➼ Black is preparing to push ... e5! The main difference between  8...Qe7  and  8...Re8  is that with  8...Qe7  Black has an additional idea to meet  9.Ne5  with  9...Nd7!?  which is not really a thing after @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/pp3ppp/2nbpn2/2pp4/3P4/2PBPNB1/PP1N1PPP/R2QK2R b KQ - 4 8@@EndFEN@@  8...Re8  9.Ne5  because in that case  9...Nd7??  simply loses a piece after  10.Nxc6  bxc6  11.Bxd6! }
9. Ne5
{ This is the key move to begin with. The careless  9.O-O  allows  9...e5!  and after  10.dxe5  Nxe5  11.Nxe5  Bxe5  12.Bxe5  Qxe5  ➼ Black manages to fully equalise and we are left with a dry position on the board. }
9... Nd7 10. Nxd7
{ The best try for White ➼ setting up a deadly trap. The natural  10.f4  does not work so well because of  10...f6!  and Black manages to equalize. }
10... Qxd7
{ This is Black's best way to recapture, avoiding immediate disaster. } 11. O-O
{ Keeping the tension because the concrete approach will lead to a forced draw after  11.Bxd6  Qxd6  12.dxc5  Qxc5  13.Bxh7+  Kxh7  14.Qh5+  Kg8  15.Ne4  and now Black has the key move  15...g6!  ➼ and compared to the 10...Bxd7 line, we can no longer grab the enemy queen because we will remain down a piece. Therefore the best way to continue would be to force the perpetual with  16.Qg5  Qe7  17.Nf6+  Kg7  18.Nh5+  followed by a repetition. }
11... Bxg3
{ The most common move. Keep in mind that the 'ambitious'  11...e5  runs into  12.dxe5  Bxe5  13.Bxe5  Nxe5  14.Bxh7+!  Kxh7  15.Qh5+  Kg8  16.Qxe5  and White wins a pawn. }
12. hxg3 Qe7
{ Preparing the ...e5 break because  12...e5  would allow the same motif after  13.dxe5  Nxe5  14.Bxh7+  Kxh7  15.Qh5+  Kg8  16.Qxe5  with an extra pawn for White. }
13. f4
{ With an easier position for White with the extra space in the center and Black's passive bishop. We can push g4-g5 and grab space on the kingside followed by Qf3-Rae1. }
