2... Nf6 3. Bf4 c5 4. e3 Nc6 5. Nbd2
{ This is the key move to start with. A common mistake that most London System players make is  5.c3  allowing  5...Qb6  with a good version for Black.  After 5.Nbd2 Black has a choice between:  5...Qb6 @@StartBracket@@leading to the complex 6.dxc5! lines@@EndBracket@@  5...e6 @@StartBracket@@locking the light squared bishop@@EndBracket@@  5...cxd4 @@StartBracket@@usually combined with ...Bg4/Bf5@@EndBracket@@  5...Bf5 @@StartBracket@@allowing 6.dxc5!@@EndBracket@@  5...Bg4 @@StartBracket@@developing according to the center@@EndBracket@@  5...Nh5 @@StartBracket@@hunting the London bishop@@EndBracket@@ }
5... e6
{ Locking the light squared bishop inside the pawn chain. This generally means that Black will have to queenside fianchetto with ...b6-Bb7. }
6. c3
{ Creating a square on c2 so we can play Bd3 and in case of ...c4 there will be Bc2 followed by the e4-break. In this position Black has a choice between:  6...Qb6  6...Bd6  6...Be7  6...cxd4 followed by ...Nh5  6...Nh5 @@StartBracket@@hunting the London bishop@@EndBracket@@  6...c4 @@StartBracket@@stopping Bd3@@EndBracket@@. }
6... Bd6
{ This is the most popular move in both OTB and online chess. Black is developing the dark-squared bishop to its most active spot ➼ fighting for the e5-square. }
7. Bg3
{ The star move for the London System. Besides inviting Black to go ...Bxg3 ➼ opening up the h-file for our rook, we have a deeper idea in mind. White's strategy @@StartBracket@@after Black goes ...d5@@EndBracket@@ will most of the times be focused on using the e5-square for the knight.To sum things up, if White manages to place the knight on e5 and keep it there ➼ this will always guarantee a bit of pressure on Black's position. Likewise, if Black manages to take control over the e5-square and push ...e6-e5 ➼ this will result in a completely even game. }
7... O-O { This is the most common move for Black. } 8. Bd3 Re8
{ Threatening to push ...e5 ➼ this is Black's second most common move. } 9. Ne5
{ The key idea to stop Black's e5-break, but also a typical plan in the London System! The careless  9.O-O  allows Black to completely equalize after  9...e5!  10.dxe5  Nxe5  with an equal and pretty dry game. }
9... Qc7
{ Increasing the pressure on the e5-knight, but this is not a very effective strategy for Black considering the fact that White can easily support the knight with f4. }
