10. f4
{ This can be played almost automatically after we centralize the knight. To get an explanation of the basic plans for this position, read The reversed Stonewall with dark-squared bishops in the Typical Pawn Structures Chapter. }
10... Ne7 { This is a common maneuver for Black ➼ preparing to play ...Nf5! }
11. Bh4
{ Creating a direct threat of  11...--  12.Bxf6  gxf6  followed by  13.Bxh7+! }
11... Nf5 12. Bxf6 gxf6 13. Qh5
{ This critical move can be easily missed by the weaker engines. White has a direct threat of g4! }
13... fxe5 14. fxe5
{ White has the initiative because  14...Bf8  can be met by  15.g4!   In fact, it might be best for Black to give back the piece with  14...Bxe5  15.dxe5  Qxe5  but after  16.e4!  White is still much better. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "6) Queen's Gambit Declined with 5…e6"]
[Black "QGD with ...e6: 6...Bd6 and 7...O-O #7"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3
{ This is the most precise move ➼ avoiding the annoying  2.Bf4  c5!  which gives us some headaches as explained in this informational. }
2... Nf6 3. Bf4 c5 4. e3 Nc6 5. Nbd2
{ This is the key move to start with. A common mistake that most London System players make is  5.c3  allowing  5...Qb6  with a good version for Black.  After 5.Nbd2 Black has a choice between:  5...Qb6 @@StartBracket@@leading to the complex 6.dxc5! lines@@EndBracket@@  5...e6 @@StartBracket@@locking the light squared bishop@@EndBracket@@  5...cxd4 @@StartBracket@@usually combined with ...Bg4/Bf5@@EndBracket@@  5...Bf5 @@StartBracket@@allowing 6.dxc5!@@EndBracket@@  5...Bg4 @@StartBracket@@developing according to the center@@EndBracket@@  5...Nh5 @@StartBracket@@hunting the London bishop@@EndBracket@@ }
5... e6
{ Locking the light squared bishop inside the pawn chain. This generally means that Black will have to queenside fianchetto with ...b6-Bb7. }
6. c3
{ Creating a square on c2 so we can play Bd3 and in case of ...c4 there will be Bc2 followed by the e4-break. In this position Black has a choice between:  6...Qb6  6...Bd6  6...Be7  6...cxd4 followed by ...Nh5  6...Nh5 @@StartBracket@@hunting the London bishop@@EndBracket@@  6...c4 @@StartBracket@@stopping Bd3@@EndBracket@@. }
6... Bd6
{ This is the most popular move in both OTB and online chess. Black is developing the dark-squared bishop to its most active spot ➼ fighting for the e5-square. }
7. Bg3
{ The star move for the London System. Besides inviting Black to go ...Bxg3 ➼ opening up the h-file for our rook, we have a deeper idea in mind. White's strategy @@StartBracket@@after Black goes ...d5@@EndBracket@@ will most of the times be focused on using the e5-square for the knight.To sum things up, if White manages to place the knight on e5 and keep it there ➼ this will always guarantee a bit of pressure on Black's position. Likewise, if Black manages to take control over the e5-square and push ...e6-e5 ➼ this will result in a completely even game. }
7... O-O { This is the most common move for Black. } 8. Bd3 Re8
{ Threatening to push ...e5 ➼ this is Black's second most common move. } 9. Ne5
{ The key idea to stop Black's e5-break, but also a typical plan in the London System! The careless  9.O-O  allows Black to completely equalize after  9...e5!  10.dxe5  Nxe5  with an equal and pretty dry game. }
9... Bxe5
{ This is always very likely to happen after we play Ne5.   9...cxd4  is not super relevant from a theoretical perspective, but I noticed it's played from time to time in online chess.  10.exd4  Bxe5  The only move worth looking at ➼ otherwise White can push f4 and secure an easy advantage.  11.dxe5  Nd7  Attacking the e5-pawn. Now  12.Nf3  works a bit better than 12. f4 since it keeps the g3-bishop a bit more active. Black can try  12...f6  with aggressive play in the center. Otherwise Black is simply worse in a static game with the improved version of the French Defense for White. After  13.exf6  Nxf6  we need to counter Black's threat of advancing ...e5 with  14.Ne5!  ±  The key move to secure a big advantage. White is much better in the current position because we are dominating the center.   The careless  14.O-O  gives Black the initiative after  14...e5!  After 14. Ne5 a key variation to prove that White is clearly better is the following:  14...Nxe5  15.Bxe5  Nd7  16.Qh5!  g6  17.Bxg6!  and Black is getting checkmated in his try to fight for the center. }
10. dxe5 Nd7 { Attacking the e5-pawn. } 11. Nf3
{ This move works best in the current position because  11.f4  allows a bit of counterplay after  11...c4  12.Bc2  Qb6  ➼ hitting both b2 and e3. }
11... Qc7
{ This is the most common move for Black. The e5-pawn seems rather vulnerable, but it's not!   In case of  11...f6  12.exf6  Nxf6  Black is threatening to push ...e5!, so we should stop that with  13.Ne5⩲  After this key move, White is clearly better with the bishop pair and good control over the center. }
12. O-O Ndxe5
{ This is a very common mistake after which Black is simply lost. Black has a few alternatives we can consider:   If  12...b6  we can continue  13.e4!  , threatening to take on d5 and push e6!  13...dxe4  14.Bxe4  Bb7  15.Re1!  Overprotecting the e5-pawn.  15...Rad8  16.Qc2  Nf8  17.h4⩲  We can push the h-pawn all the way to h6 followed by Nh2-Ng4 with good attacking prospects on the kingside.   12...g6  threatens to take on e5 without allowing Qh5 like in the 12...Ndxe5 line.  13.Bb5!  This move keeps our e5-pawn safe.  13...a6  14.Bxc6  Qxc6  15.Qd2±  With pressure on the kingside because Black's dark squares have been weakened. We have ideas to sacrifice the pawn with e4-Qh6 in some lines, while a typical maneuver could be h3 followed by Nh2-Ng4! }
13. Nxe5 Nxe5 14. Qh5
{ The point! Black is unable to defend both the e5-knight and the h7-pawn, so White wins. }
