6. c3
{ Creating a square on c2 so we can play Bd3 and in case of ...c4 there will be Bc2 followed by the e4-break. In this position Black has a choice between:  6...Qb6  6...Bd6  6...Be7  6...cxd4 followed by ...Nh5  6...Nh5 @@StartBracket@@hunting the London bishop@@EndBracket@@  6...c4 @@StartBracket@@stopping Bd3@@EndBracket@@. }
6... Bd6
{ This is the most popular move in both OTB and online chess. Black is developing the dark-squared bishop to its most active spot ➼ fighting for the e5-square. }
7. Bg3
{ The star move for the London System. Besides inviting Black to go ...Bxg3 ➼ opening up the h-file for our rook, we have a deeper idea in mind. White's strategy @@StartBracket@@after Black goes ...d5@@EndBracket@@ will most of the times be focused on using the e5-square for the knight.To sum things up, if White manages to place the knight on e5 and keep it there ➼ this will always guarantee a bit of pressure on Black's position. Likewise, if Black manages to take control over the e5-square and push ...e6-e5 ➼ this will result in a completely even game. }
7... O-O { This is the most common move for Black. } 8. Bd3 Bxg3
{ This can be a much trickier idea than you would have imagined at first! } 9.
hxg3 Qd6
{ Threatening to push ...e5 on the next move. Generally, if Black is able to achieve that, they manage to fully equalize. }
10. Ne5
{ This is Leela's stunning solution to stop Black from pushing ...e5! The point is to open up queen's path towards the enemy king. }
10... Nxe5 11. Bxh7+
{ The key idea. This tactic will take a lot of your opponents by surprise. }
11... Nxh7 12. Qh5
{ Afer this move White is clearly better, despite being down two pieces! }
12... Nd3+ 13. Ke2 f6
{ This had to be played in order to avoid the immediate checkmate. } 14. Qxh7+
Kf7 15. Qxd3 { With the extra pawn and safer king, White is clearly better. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "6) Queen's Gambit Declined with 5…e6"]
[Black "QGD with ...e6: 6...Bd6 and 7...O-O #10"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3
{ This is the most precise move ➼ avoiding the annoying  2.Bf4  c5!  which gives us some headaches as explained in this informational. }
2... Nf6 3. Bf4 c5 4. e3 Nc6 5. Nbd2
{ This is the key move to start with. A common mistake that most London System players make is  5.c3  allowing  5...Qb6  with a good version for Black.  After 5.Nbd2 Black has a choice between:  5...Qb6 @@StartBracket@@leading to the complex 6.dxc5! lines@@EndBracket@@  5...e6 @@StartBracket@@locking the light squared bishop@@EndBracket@@  5...cxd4 @@StartBracket@@usually combined with ...Bg4/Bf5@@EndBracket@@  5...Bf5 @@StartBracket@@allowing 6.dxc5!@@EndBracket@@  5...Bg4 @@StartBracket@@developing according to the center@@EndBracket@@  5...Nh5 @@StartBracket@@hunting the London bishop@@EndBracket@@ }
5... e6
{ Locking the light squared bishop inside the pawn chain. This generally means that Black will have to queenside fianchetto with ...b6-Bb7. }
6. c3
{ Creating a square on c2 so we can play Bd3 and in case of ...c4 there will be Bc2 followed by the e4-break. In this position Black has a choice between:  6...Qb6  6...Bd6  6...Be7  6...cxd4 followed by ...Nh5  6...Nh5 @@StartBracket@@hunting the London bishop@@EndBracket@@  6...c4 @@StartBracket@@stopping Bd3@@EndBracket@@. }
6... Bd6
{ This is the most popular move in both OTB and online chess. Black is developing the dark-squared bishop to its most active spot ➼ fighting for the e5-square. }
7. Bg3
{ The star move for the London System. Besides inviting Black to go ...Bxg3 ➼ opening up the h-file for our rook, we have a deeper idea in mind. White's strategy @@StartBracket@@after Black goes ...d5@@EndBracket@@ will most of the times be focused on using the e5-square for the knight.To sum things up, if White manages to place the knight on e5 and keep it there ➼ this will always guarantee a bit of pressure on Black's position. Likewise, if Black manages to take control over the e5-square and push ...e6-e5 ➼ this will result in a completely even game. }
7... O-O { This is the most common move for Black. } 8. Bd3 b6
{ This is the most common move for Black in all rating ranges. Black solves the problem with the light-squared bishop by placing it on b7.   8...c4  is always playable, but usually not great. We keep the bishop on the key diagonal with  9.Bc2  and prepare the e4-push:  9...b5  10.e4⩲  This is the key idea to counter Black's ...c4 plans. Here White's position seems a bit easier to play. It's nothing dramatic just yet, but I prefer White with more space in the center. }
9. Qe2
{ This is the modern main line, championed by Gata Kamsky. White stays very flexible, intending Rd1 followed by the e4-break.   The most popular move for a while has been  9.Ne5  @@StartBracket@@very natural and logical@@EndBracket@@. However, there is a concrete line that Black has which makes me want to stay away from it: Black can play  9...Bb7  10.f4  Ne7!  11.Qf3  Nf5  12.Bf2  Be7  13.g4  Nd6  with good control over the e4-square. I tried to make this position work for quite some time, but I was simply unable to find enough interesting ideas to even recommend it as an alternative.   The other interesting option that White has is the concrete  9.e4  which is generally connected with a pawn sacrifice after  9...Be7  10.e5  Nh5  11.Ng5  Bxg5  12.Qxh5  g6  13.Qe2  cxd4  14.h4  with interesting play on the kingside in exchange for the sacrificed pawn.   To sum things up, I think  9.Qe2  is a perfect balance between these two lines! }
9... Bb7 10. Rd1
{ The d1-rook is incredibly well-placed when going for the e4-break. Black has to watch out for a lot of tactics not to lose on the spot to a surprising discovery attack. }
10... Ne7
{ This is a pretty decent alternative for Black, popular in both OTB and online chess. Black is threatening to play ...Nf5! }
11. e4 { Following the main plan! } 11... dxe4 12. Nxe4 Bxe4
{ This is the best move order!  12...Nxe4?!  is very common, but White can get a quick win after  13.Bxe4  Bxe4  14.dxc5!!  @@StartBracket@@this move is missed by 90% of the players@@EndBracket@@ and White just wins a free pawn. }
13. Bxe4 Nxe4 14. Qxe4
{ Threatening dxc5 and Black will have issues on the d-file. } 14... c4
{ Keeping the d-file closed is a must in order to avoid immediate disaster. }
15. Bh4 Qc7 16. Bxe7 Bxe7 17. h4
{ The position should be close to equal, but I think White has good attacking prospects on the kingside with Rh3-Rg3 ideas. }
