{ This random looking move is a very tricky line because our standard move  11.e4  now gives Black a good version after  11...Bxg3!  12.hxg3  cxd4  13.cxd4  dxe4  14.Nxe4  Nb4  with a small edge for Black.   Let's pick one of the other lines and try to spot the difference together.  10...Rc8  can be a good example: we go for the standard  11.e4  and if Black tries to do the same trick with  11...Bxg3  12.hxg3  cxd4  White has the important  13.e5!  ➼ attacking the knight and winning the h7-pawn. With this comparison you can clearly understand why 10...h6 is a pretty clever move. }
11. Ne5 { Following Kamsky's footsteps. } 11... Qc7 12. f4 Ne7
{ Threatening ...Ne4! } 13. Qf3 { Controlling the critical e4-square. } 13...
Nf5 14. Bf2 { Making room for the g-pawn. } 14... Be7 15. g4 Nd6 16. g5
{ With a pretty messy position with chances for both sides which eventually turned out to be an easy win for White in the game between Kamsky,G @@StartBracket@@2665@@EndBracket@@ -Diaz Camallonga,C @@StartBracket@@2463@@EndBracket@@ Chess.com INT 2021. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "6) Queen's Gambit Declined with 5…e6"]
[Black "QGD with ...e6: 6...Bd6 and 7...O-O #13"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3
{ This is the most precise move ➼ avoiding the annoying  2.Bf4  c5!  which gives us some headaches as explained in this informational. }
2... Nf6 3. Bf4 c5 4. e3 Nc6 5. Nbd2
{ This is the key move to start with. A common mistake that most London System players make is  5.c3  allowing  5...Qb6  with a good version for Black.  After 5.Nbd2 Black has a choice between:  5...Qb6 @@StartBracket@@leading to the complex 6.dxc5! lines@@EndBracket@@  5...e6 @@StartBracket@@locking the light squared bishop@@EndBracket@@  5...cxd4 @@StartBracket@@usually combined with ...Bg4/Bf5@@EndBracket@@  5...Bf5 @@StartBracket@@allowing 6.dxc5!@@EndBracket@@  5...Bg4 @@StartBracket@@developing according to the center@@EndBracket@@  5...Nh5 @@StartBracket@@hunting the London bishop@@EndBracket@@ }
5... e6
{ Locking the light squared bishop inside the pawn chain. This generally means that Black will have to queenside fianchetto with ...b6-Bb7. }
6. c3
{ Creating a square on c2 so we can play Bd3 and in case of ...c4 there will be Bc2 followed by the e4-break. In this position Black has a choice between:  6...Qb6  6...Bd6  6...Be7  6...cxd4 followed by ...Nh5  6...Nh5 @@StartBracket@@hunting the London bishop@@EndBracket@@  6...c4 @@StartBracket@@stopping Bd3@@EndBracket@@. }
6... Bd6
{ This is the most popular move in both OTB and online chess. Black is developing the dark-squared bishop to its most active spot ➼ fighting for the e5-square. }
7. Bg3
{ The star move for the London System. Besides inviting Black to go ...Bxg3 ➼ opening up the h-file for our rook, we have a deeper idea in mind. White's strategy @@StartBracket@@after Black goes ...d5@@EndBracket@@ will most of the times be focused on using the e5-square for the knight.To sum things up, if White manages to place the knight on e5 and keep it there ➼ this will always guarantee a bit of pressure on Black's position. Likewise, if Black manages to take control over the e5-square and push ...e6-e5 ➼ this will result in a completely even game. }
7... O-O { This is the most common move for Black. } 8. Bd3 b6
{ This is the most common move for Black in all rating ranges. Black solves the problem with the light-squared bishop by placing it on b7.   8...c4  is always playable, but usually not great. We keep the bishop on the key diagonal with  9.Bc2  and prepare the e4-push:  9...b5  10.e4⩲  This is the key idea to counter Black's ...c4 plans. Here White's position seems a bit easier to play. It's nothing dramatic just yet, but I prefer White with more space in the center. }
9. Qe2
{ This is the modern main line, championed by Gata Kamsky. White stays very flexible, intending Rd1 followed by the e4-break.   The most popular move for a while has been  9.Ne5  @@StartBracket@@very natural and logical@@EndBracket@@. However, there is a concrete line that Black has which makes me want to stay away from it: Black can play  9...Bb7  10.f4  Ne7!  11.Qf3  Nf5  12.Bf2  Be7  13.g4  Nd6  with good control over the e4-square. I tried to make this position work for quite some time, but I was simply unable to find enough interesting ideas to even recommend it as an alternative.   The other interesting option that White has is the concrete  9.e4  which is generally connected with a pawn sacrifice after  9...Be7  10.e5  Nh5  11.Ng5  Bxg5  12.Qxh5  g6  13.Qe2  cxd4  14.h4  with interesting play on the kingside in exchange for the sacrificed pawn.   To sum things up, I think  9.Qe2  is a perfect balance between these two lines! }
9... Bb7 10. Rd1
{ The d1-rook is incredibly well-placed when going for the e4-break. Black has to watch out for a lot of tactics not to lose on the spot to a surprising discovery attack. }
10... Re8
{ This is the main move in OTB. Black is threatening to play ...Bxg3 followed by ...e5!   If  10...Rc8  we should again stick to the main plan with  11.e4!  Be7  This is Black's best try, but only really well prepared opponents will go for such subtle ideas.   Most players would go  11...dxe4  12.Nxe4  Nxe4  13.Qxe4  with a very pleasant position for White.  12.e5  Nh5  13.a3!?  This is a very useful move for our structure, controlling the b4-square because sometimes Black wants ...cxd4 followed by ... Nb4!  13...g6  14.O-O  c4  Not great, but Black needs to do something.  15.Bb1  b5  16.h4!  Threatening Bh2 followed by g4! This is the key move you need to remember because we are not afraid to take back on g3 with the f-pawn.  16...Nxg3  17.fxg3↑  With good attacking prospects on the kingside. A simple and effective maneuver is Nh2-Ng4-Nf6 and Black's king is most likely going to be checkmated. }
11. e4
{ Following the main plan! We don't need to be afraid of  11...e5  because White has a pleasant position after  12.dxc5!  Bxc5  13.O-O  with pressure in the center. }
11... Be7
{ The critical move because  11...dxe4  12.Nxe4  Nxe4  13.Bxe4  is very pleasant for White. }
12. e5 Nh5
{ Hunting the London Bishop. This is Black's main argument for allowing White to expand in the center.  12...Nd7  is just a bit pointless and it gives White a good version of the French Defense after  13.O-O  a5  14.Rfe1  Qc8  15.Bb1!  @@StartBracket@@avoiding the bishop trade@@EndBracket@@  15...Ba6  16.Qe3  with a solid advantage. }
13. h4
{ This is a standard idea for our pawn structure. Generally speaking, it's less common that taking back on g3 with the f-pawn is good, but in our case it works very well! White has a concrete threat of playing Bh2 followed by g4! }
13... Nxg3
{ This has to be played in order to justify knight's journey to h5.   13...g6  doesn't justify Black's previous play, and after  14.Bh2  the threat to play g4 becomes concrete. After  14...cxd4  15.Nxd4!  is the key way to recapture.   The natural  15.cxd4  would give Black very good counterplay after  15...Nb4  16.Bb1  Ba6!  with annoying pressure on the queenside.  15...Nxd4  16.cxd4  Ng7  17.g4  with a crushing attack on the kingside in the game between Sedlak,N @@StartBracket@@2586@@EndBracket@@-Noe,C @@StartBracket@@2534@@EndBracket@@ Warsaw 2019. }
14. fxg3 f5
{ This seems to be the most common move for Black in online chess @@StartBracket@@from a small sample of games@@EndBracket@@. }
15. exf6 Bxf6 16. Ng5
{ This move is very strong, and it's connected with a lot of tactical tricks! }
16... Bxg5 17. Bxh7+ { Zwischenzug! } 17... Kxh7 18. hxg5+
{ Opening up the rook's path with tempo, that was the point of the previous move! }
18... Kg8 19. Qh5
{ Black might hold with best defensive play, but it's definitely a very difficult practical task. }
