[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "6) Queen's Gambit Declined with 5…e6"]
[Black "QGD with ...e6: Gledura's pet line 5...Qb6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3
{ This is the most precise move ➼ avoiding the annoying  2.Bf4  c5!  which gives us some headaches as explained in this informational. }
2... Nf6 3. Bf4 c5 4. e3 e6 5. Nbd2 Qb6
{ This is an interesting sideline which has been recommended by Benjamin Gledura in his Lifetime Repertoire on the Queen's Gambit Accepted. Before we dive deeper in to the lines, I want to mention that in my opinion his course is a must buy for anyone who's willing to have a solid reply against 1. d4! }
6. Rb1 { Protecting the b2-pawn. } 6... Bd7
{ Preparing to trade off the bad bishop with ...cxd4 followed by ...Bb5! } 7.
c3
{ Solidifying the center. We can't really stop Black from playing ...Bb5! The only argument we can make is that it's a bit time-consuming. }
7... cxd4 8. exd4 Bb5
{ Trading the bad bishop, and if White continues in normal fashion, Black has an easy game. }
9. h4
{ This is a pretty common theme for our repertoire and also White's best try against Benjamin's line. He does an amazing job in covering and explaining a brand new position while also covering interesting novelties for White. There is not really that much I can add since he did a fantastic job, but we can go a bit deeper with the analysis where he stops. }
9... Nbd7 10. h5 { Threatening to push h6 ➼ softening Black's dark squares. }
10... h6 { Centralizing the knight and making room for Qg4 ideas. } 11. Ne5
Nxe5 12. dxe5 { Attacking the f6-knight. } 12... Nd7 13. Rh3
{ With Nf3-Nd4 followed by Rg3 ➼ White has good attacking prospects on the kingside. }
*

