[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3
{ This is the most precise move ➼ avoiding the annoying  2.Bf4  c5!  which gives us some headaches as explained in this informational. }
2... Nf6 3. Bf4 c5 4. e3 e6 5. Nbd2 Qb6
{ This is an interesting sideline which has been recommended by Benjamin Gledura in his Lifetime Repertoire on the Queen's Gambit Accepted. Before we dive deeper in to the lines, I want to mention that in my opinion his course is a must buy for anyone who's willing to have a solid reply against 1. d4! }
6. Rb1 { Protecting the b2-pawn. } 6... Bd7
{ Preparing to trade off the bad bishop with ...cxd4 followed by ...Bb5! } 7.
c3
{ Solidifying the center. We can't really stop Black from playing ...Bb5! The only argument we can make is that it's a bit time-consuming. }
7... cxd4 8. exd4 Bb5
{ Trading the bad bishop, and if White continues in normal fashion, Black has an easy game. }
9. h4
{ This is a pretty common theme for our repertoire and also White's best try against Benjamin's line. He does an amazing job in covering and explaining a brand new position while also covering interesting novelties for White. There is not really that much I can add since he did a fantastic job, but we can go a bit deeper with the analysis where he stops. }
9... Nbd7 10. h5 { Threatening to push h6 ➼ softening Black's dark squares. }
10... h6 { Centralizing the knight and making room for Qg4 ideas. } 11. Ne5 Be7
12. Nxd7 Nxd7 13. Qg4 { Attacking the g7-pawn. } 13... Bxf1 14. Nxf1 Bf8
{ Protecting the g7-pawn and keeping the f6-square available for the knight. }
15. Nd2 Nf6 16. Qg3 { Keeping the g7-square under control. } 16... Qa6
{ Attacking the a2-pawn. } 17. a3 Rc8
{ Here Benjamin stops, claiming that the position is balanced. With best play Black should be fine, but I think we can hope at least for an easier game for White. }
18. Be5 { Introducing ideas to double Black's pawns with Bxf6. } 18... Nd7
{ Setting up a small trap because 19.Bxg7 Rg8! wins for Black. } 19. Rh4
{ Activating the rook and renewing the threat of Bxg7 because now we have Rg4 against ...Rg8! }
19... Nxe5 20. dxe5 { Creating a square on d4 for the knight. } 20... Be7 21.
Rg4 Bg5 22. Nf3
{ Threatening Nxg5. Black has a choice between:     A@@EndBracket@@  22...Rc4  23.Rd1  Rxg4  24.Qxg4  Qb5  25.Qb4  Qxb4  26.axb4  with a slightly better endgame for White after Ke2-Ra1 followed by Nd4-g3-f4 ideas with pressure on both flanks.   B@@EndBracket@@  22...Qd3  23.Rd1  Qc2  24.Rb4  Be7  25.Rxb7  Qe4+  26.Kf1  with an extra pawn for White and Black has to find the only move  26...Qa4  to stay in the game!The position should be equal with precise play, but I think this is easier said than done. }
