[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "6) Queen's Gambit Declined with 5…e6"]
[Black "QGD with ...e6: 5...Qb6 and 6...cxd4"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3
{ This is the most precise move ➼ avoiding the annoying  2.Bf4  c5!  which gives us some headaches as explained in this informational. }
2... e6 3. Bf4 c5 4. e3 Nc6 5. Nbd2 Qb6
{ Attacking both the b2 and the d4 pawns. } 6. Rb1
{ Sacrificing the d4-pawn works perfectly fine in this case because Black will lose the right to castle. }
6... cxd4
{ The only sensible move, otherwise Black's move order is not really justified.  6...Nf6  7.c3  Nh5  Transposes to this line. }
7. exd4 Nxd4 8. Nxd4
{ Important to deflect Black's queen from protecting the b5-square. } 8... Qxd4
9. Bb5+
{ This is the key point behind playing 6. Rb1! Black's king becomes vulnerable after this move. }
9... Bd7 10. Be3 { Sidestepping Black's ...Qxf4 threat while gaining a tempo. }
10... Qb4 11. Bxd7+ { Forcing Black's king on a vulnerable square. } 11... Kxd7
12. O-O
{ We are going to open up the position with c4 next and White has good attacking prospects for the sacrificed pawn. }
