[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "7) Queen's Gambit Declined without 5…e6"]
[Black "QGD 5.Nbd2 Bf5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3
{ This is the most precise move ➼ avoiding the annoying  2.Bf4  c5!  which gives us some headaches as explained in this informational. }
2... Nf6 3. Bf4 c5 4. e3 Nc6 5. Nbd2
{ This is the key move to start with. A common mistake that most of the London System players make is  5.c3  allowing  5...Qb6  with a good version for Black. }
5... Bf5
{ This line is a bit inferior compared to  5...cxd4  6.exd4  Bf5  ➼ because it gives White the additional option to grab the c5-pawn. However, it shouldn't be underestimated. }
6. dxc5
{ Not the most typical move for the London, but works really well combined with Nd4 on the next move. }
6... e6 7. Nd4
{ This comes as a surprise to a lot of players. Black has to make a pretty tricky decision whether to grab the c5-pawn and allow Nxf5 or to step back with 7... Bg6. }
7... Bg6 { Natural, but simply bad. } 8. Bb5
{ Another surprising move! Black has issues with the c6-knight. } 8... Rc8 9.
b4
{ With an extra pawn and more active pieces for White. A common mistake that black players now often make is  9...Be7  allowing  10.Nxc6  bxc6  11.Ba6!  ➼ winning the exchange. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "7) Queen's Gambit Declined without 5…e6"]
[Black "QGD 5.Nbd2 Bf5 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3
{ This is the most precise move ➼ avoiding the annoying  2.Bf4  c5!  which gives us some headaches as explained in this informational. }
2... Nf6 3. Bf4 c5 4. e3 Nc6 5. Nbd2
{ This is the key move to start with. A common mistake that most of the London System players make is  5.c3  allowing  5...Qb6  with a good version for Black. }
5... Bf5
{ This line is a bit inferior compared to  5...cxd4  6.exd4  Bf5  ➼ because it gives White the additional option to grab the c5-pawn. However, it shouldn't be underestimated. }
6. dxc5
{ Not the most typical move for the London, but works really well combined with Nd4 on the next move. }
6... e6 7. Nd4
{ This comes as a surprise to a lot of players. Black has to make a pretty tricky decision whether to grab the c5-pawn and allow Nxf5 or to step back with 7... Bg6. }
7... Bxc5 { The lesser evil. } 8. Nxf5
{ Cashing in the bishop pair and ruining Black's pawn structure. From a static point of view, White is doing amazing already, but Black compensates by being slightly ahead in development for now. }
8... exf5 9. c3 { Fixing the isolated pawn on d5. } 9... O-O 10. Be2
{ This move is very important because the natural  10.Bd3  d4!  would already give Black the initiative.With very few games available from this position, we will cover Black's most important moves such as:  10...Qe7  10...Ne4  10...Re8. }
10... Re8 11. Qc2 { Attacking the f5-pawn. } 11... Qd7 12. Rd1 h6
{ Creating a big threat of pushing ...g5 followed by ...f4! } 13. h4
{ Keeping the London Bishop safe by stopping Black's ...g5 threat. } 13... Qe6
14. Nb3 Bb6 15. g3 { Making a square for the king on g2. } 15... Ne4
{ Renewing the ...g5-threat! } 16. h5
{ After this move Black will no longer have ...g5 ideas, and White can slowly build up the pressure after Kf1-Kg2 followed by the c4-break. Once the position opens up, the two bishops will start to shine. }
