[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "7) Queen's Gambit Declined without 5…e6"]
[Black "QGD 5.Nbd2 Bg4 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3
{ This is the most precise move ➼ avoiding the annoying  2.Bf4  c5!  which gives us some headaches as explained in this informational. }
2... Nf6 3. Bf4 c5 4. e3 Nc6 5. Nbd2
{ This is the key move to start with. A common mistake that most of the London System players make is  5.c3  allowing  5...Qb6  with a good version for Black. }
5... Bg4 { This is one of Black's most solid replies. } 6. c3 cxd4
{ This is played in order to transpose back into the Caro Kann. } 7. exd4 e6 8.
Qb3
{ Attacking the b7-pawn and breaking the pin ➼ This is a common theme when Black develops the light-squared bishop in the ...c5 lines. }
8... Qd7
{ This is not a good move because the queen is really vulnerable to Bb5 ideas on this square, however it's played quite often in casual games. }
9. Ne5 Nxe5
{ This allows a typical trick.   Meanwhile, after  9...Qc8?  10.f3!  Black has a huge problem with the light-squared bishop:  10...Bf5  11.g4  Bg6  12.h4  Now Black has to make an unpleasant choice due to the threat of h5.  12...h5  13.Nxg6!  Not only winning the bishop pair, but creating a huge weakness on g6.  13...fxg6  14.Qc2+-  Black is simply lost because they are unable to defend the g6-pawn. }
10. dxe5 { Attacking the f6-knight. } 10... Ne4 11. Bb5
{ This is why the queen is 'no bueno' on d7 in this structure! } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "7) Queen's Gambit Declined without 5…e6"]
[Black "QGD 5.Nbd2 Bg4 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3
{ This is the most precise move ➼ avoiding the annoying  2.Bf4  c5!  which gives us some headaches as explained in this informational. }
2... Nf6 3. Bf4 c5 4. e3 Nc6 5. Nbd2
{ This is the key move to start with. A common mistake that most of the London System players make is  5.c3  allowing  5...Qb6  with a good version for Black. }
5... Bg4 { This is one of Black's most solid replies. } 6. c3 cxd4
{ This is played in order to transpose back into the Caro Kann. } 7. exd4 e6 8.
Qb3
{ Attacking the b7-pawn and breaking the pin ➼ This is a common theme when Black develops the light-squared bishop in the ...c5 lines. }
8... Qc8
{ This is the main move for Black in OTB.   The endgames after  8...Qb6  with the double isolated b-pawn are amazing for White:  9.Qxb6  axb6  10.Bb5⩲  With a small but steady edge for White. We can play Ne5 and push on the queenside with a4. White won a nice game in Kramnik,V @@StartBracket@@2777@@EndBracket@@ -Wojtaszek,R @@StartBracket@@2734@@EndBracket@@ Berlin 2015.   8...Bd6  is somewhat interesting, although I believe White should have an objective advantage with super precise play after  9.Qxb7  . However, I am not a fan of long & complex lines, so we will stick with a more practical approach with  9.Bxd6  Qxd6  10.Bd3  O-O  11.O-O  leading to a typical position. Black can attempt to start the minority attack with  11...Rab8  , which we should stop with  12.a4!  when  12...a6  13.a5!  would fix the structure in a favorable way for White. Otherwise after @@StartFEN@@1r3rk1/pp3ppp/2nqpn2/3p4/P2P2b1/1QPB1N2/1P1N1PPP/R4RK1 b - - 0 12@@EndFEN@@  12...Rfc8  13.Rfe1⩲  White will play Ne5 next, followed by Re3-Rae1 with potential for a rook lift. White has good attacking prospects. }
9. Bd3 Be7
{ Sooner or later, Black can throw in  9...Bxf3  if they want. It's not a terrible move because the bishop can sometimes become a target to White's pawns, but we get a pretty nice asset in the long term with bishop against knight:  10.Nxf3  Be7  11.O-O  O-O  12.Rfe1  Preparing the knight jump to e5.  12...a6  Preparing the minority attack!  13.a4!  Na5  14.Qc2  Nc4  15.Ne5⩲  With the strong knight on e5, and the bishop pair ➼ White is clearly better. A typical plan that we can use is connected with Qe2 followed by pushing h4-h5. }
10. O-O
{ Here Black has two main plans:  10...O-O  10...Bh5 @@StartBracket@@delaying ...O-O and intending to play ...Bg6@@EndBracket@@. }
10... Bh5
{ The point of this move is to go for a quick ...Bg6 trading off the light-squared bishops ➼ making it harder for White to get an attack on the kingside. }
11. Rfe1 { The positional approach works best. } 11... Bg6 12. Bxg6
{ The principled move! You don't have to worry about the open h-file because it's very unlikely that Black will manage to bring enough pieces to create an attack, and if they are going to castle short, we can potentially use the h-file to attack their king @@StartBracket@@imagine a combo with Qh4 and Ng5@@EndBracket@@. }
12... hxg6 13. h3 { Creating a square for the bishop on h2. } 13... O-O 14. Qb5
{ This is a very sweet maneuver. The queen is optimal on d3 after the light-squared bishop have been traded off. }
14... a6 15. Qd3
{ This is a dream position for White. We can play Ne5 followed by h4-g3-Kg2-Rh1 with good attacking prospects on the kingside. }
