[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "7) Queen's Gambit Declined without 5…e6"]
[Black "QGD 5.Nbd2 Bg4 #4"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3
{ This is the most precise move ➼ avoiding the annoying  2.Bf4  c5!  which gives us some headaches as explained in this informational. }
2... Nf6 3. Bf4 c5 4. e3 Nc6 5. Nbd2
{ This is the key move to start with. A common mistake that most of the London System players make is  5.c3  allowing  5...Qb6  with a good version for Black. }
5... Bg4 { This is one of Black's most solid replies. } 6. c3 e6
{ 6...Qb6  is a very rare sideline that was played by a couple of strong Grandmasters. We should reply  7.dxc5!  when  7...Qxc5  is the most precise answer.   7...Qxb2  8.Rb1  Qxc3  9.Rxb7  gives White a considerable advantage.  8.Qb3  attacks b7, and we are happy to enter the endgame after  8...Qb6  9.Qxb6!  due to our superior pawn structure.  9...axb6  10.Bb5⩲  With a long-term initiative in the endgame thanks to the weak pawn on b6. White won a nice game in Kramnik,V @@StartBracket@@2777@@EndBracket@@-Meier,G @@StartBracket@@2654@@EndBracket@@ Berlin 2015. }
7. Qb3
{ Attacking the b7-pawn ➼ This is a common theme when Black develops the light-squared bishop in the ...c5 lines. }
7... Qc8
{ This is the main move in OTB. This is the safest square for the queen because  7...Qd7  8.Bb5!  is a bit problematic, and also the endgames arising from the @@StartFEN@@r2qkb1r/pp3ppp/2n1pn2/2pp4/3P1Bb1/1QP1PN2/PP1N1PPP/R3KB1R b KQkq - 1 7@@EndFEN@@  7...Qb6  lines are not very fun to play for Black. }
8. Nh4
{ This was recently implemented by Aronian and Demchenko. This is the most serious attempt to put the ...Bg4-lines under a question mark. White's plan is to advance on the kingside with h3-g4 and win the bishop pair.   An alternative could be  8.h3  followed by g4 which could lead to similar positions, but I prefer 8.Nh4 because it avoids ...Bf5. }
8... cxd4 9. exd4 { Going for the standard recapture. } 9... Be7 10. h3
{ Following the main strategy ➼ hunting the light-squared bishop. } 10... Bh5
11. g4 Bg6 12. Nxg6 hxg6 { Threatening ...Nxg4! } 13. Be2
{ This is the most flexible move. White keeps both plans of going Kf1-Kg2 or O-O-O available. The problem with O-O-O is that we have to watch out for the ...Nxd4 tactic, so we need to wait a bit. }
13... a6 14. h4 { Preparing to push h5! } 14... Nd7 15. h5
{ Improving over the game between Petrosyan-Basso, 2021 that went  15.Nf3  . }
15... gxh5 16. Rxh5 Rxh5 17. gxh5
{ We are going to play Be3 first ➼ defending the d4-pawn so that we can castle long @@StartBracket@@avoiding ...Nxd4-tricks@@EndBracket@@. After that White can put pressure on the g-file with Rg1 and bring the queen back with Qd1. White is pressing with the bishop pair. }
