{ This is the key move to start with. A common mistake that most of the London System players make is  5.c3  allowing  5...Qb6  with a good version for Black. }
5... Bg4 { This is one of Black's most solid replies. } 6. c3 e6
{ 6...Qb6  is a very rare sideline that was played by a couple of strong Grandmasters. We should reply  7.dxc5!  when  7...Qxc5  is the most precise answer.   7...Qxb2  8.Rb1  Qxc3  9.Rxb7  gives White a considerable advantage.  8.Qb3  attacks b7, and we are happy to enter the endgame after  8...Qb6  9.Qxb6!  due to our superior pawn structure.  9...axb6  10.Bb5⩲  With a long-term initiative in the endgame thanks to the weak pawn on b6. White won a nice game in Kramnik,V @@StartBracket@@2777@@EndBracket@@-Meier,G @@StartBracket@@2654@@EndBracket@@ Berlin 2015. }
7. Qb3
{ Attacking the b7-pawn ➼ This is a common theme when Black develops the light-squared bishop in the ...c5 lines. }
7... Qd7 8. Bb5
{ Threatening Ne5. This is the precise way to punish the misplaced queen.   The tempting  8.Ne5  allows Black to escape after  8...Nxe5  9.dxe5  c4!  ➼ and we are not in time to pin the queen with Bb5. }
8... Bd6
{ If  8...Bxf3  9.Nxf3  Bd6  we play in a similar way:  10.dxc5!  Deflecting Black's bishop.  10...Bxc5  11.Ne5!  Qc8  12.Qa4⩲  Winning at least a pawn because Black is unable to defend the c6-knight. }
9. dxc5 { Deflecting Black's bishop. } 9... Bxc5 10. Ne5 Qc8 11. Qa4
{ With a free pawn for White because Black is unable to protect the c6-knight. }
