[White "7) Queen's Gambit Declined without 5…e6"]
[Black "QGD 5.Nbd2 Bg4 #8"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3
{ This is the most precise move ➼ avoiding the annoying  2.Bf4  c5!  which gives us some headaches as explained in this informational. }
2... Nf6 3. Bf4 c5 4. e3 Nc6 5. Nbd2
{ This is the key move to start with. A common mistake that most of the London System players make is  5.c3  allowing  5...Qb6  with a good version for Black. }
5... Bg4 { This is one of Black's most solid replies. } 6. c3 e6
{ 6...Qb6  is a very rare sideline that was played by a couple of strong Grandmasters. We should reply  7.dxc5!  when  7...Qxc5  is the most precise answer.   7...Qxb2  8.Rb1  Qxc3  9.Rxb7  gives White a considerable advantage.  8.Qb3  attacks b7, and we are happy to enter the endgame after  8...Qb6  9.Qxb6!  due to our superior pawn structure.  9...axb6  10.Bb5⩲  With a long-term initiative in the endgame thanks to the weak pawn on b6. White won a nice game in Kramnik,V @@StartBracket@@2777@@EndBracket@@-Meier,G @@StartBracket@@2654@@EndBracket@@ Berlin 2015. }
7. Qb3
{ Attacking the b7-pawn ➼ This is a common theme when Black develops the light-squared bishop in the ...c5 lines. }
7... Qb6
{ This move is very popular in online chess. My guess is that people underestimate White's initiative in the upcoming endgames. }
8. Ne5
{ After deeply analysing all the alternatives, this strikes me as by far the best chance for White. I experienced quite a lot of games with  8.Qxb6  axb6  9.Bb5  which is slightly more pleasant for White and can be 'an easy fix' if you are lazy, but my winrate was around 50%.   Since I started playing the precise  8.Ne5!  I win most of my games in this line, and I've noticed that most of the Black players are unable to react properly. Even those who find the best defence will suffer in the long run in these lines. }
8... c4 { This is something that I faced pretty often with very good results. }
9. Qxb6
{ Generally we don't really like to take on b6 and open up the enemy rook, but it's a completely different story when we can capture the light-squared bishop on the next move! }
9... axb6 10. Nxg4 { Cashing in the bishop pair. } 10... Nxg4 11. e4
{ This move is very logical because the bishop pair will be dominating the board once the position opens up. }
11... b5 12. exd5 exd5 13. g3
{ We are going to continue with Bg2 followed by O-O and Rfe1. A nice maneuver that you want to keep in mind while playing this structure is Nf1-Ne3, but in some positions Nf3-Ne5 might work even better. }
