[White "7) Queen's Gambit Declined without 5…e6"]
[Black "QGD 5.Nbd2 Bg4 - 7.Qa4!? alternative #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3
{ This is the most precise move ➼ avoiding the annoying  2.Bf4  c5!  which gives us some headaches as explained in this informational. }
2... Nf6 3. Bf4 c5 4. e3 Nc6 5. Nbd2
{ This is the key move to start with. A common mistake that most of the London System players make is  5.c3  allowing  5...Qb6  with a good version for Black. }
5... Bg4 { This is one of the most solid replies for Black. } 6. c3 e6 7. Qa4
{ This could be a fun alternative to the main move  7.Qb3!  If Black is precise and knows what he is doing, we are likely to get an equal game, but according to the statistics Black falls into a trap on a regular basis in this line.Keep in mind that Qa4 is not a common idea for the London System, and it's very situational against the ...c5 & ...Bg4 mainline. This is probably why the Black players have such a poor score against it - most people don't expect it! I felt the need to mention this since I've noticed a lot of my students trying to do this against various lines after seeing it as a famous trap on YouTube. Definitely, this can have good surprise value, but you have to get this exact position in order for it to work. }
7... Nd7
{ Blocking the a4-e8 diagonal and controlling the e5-square. This is Black's best line. }
8. Bb5 { Threatening Bxc6. } 8... Qb6 9. Ne5
{ Attacking both the c6-knight and the g4-bishop. } 9... Ndxe5
{ This move is important.   After  9...Ncxe5??  10.Bxe5+-  White wins on the spot in this line because the d7-knight is under attack and White also has a threat of dxc5 ➼ winning the g4-bishop. }
10. dxc5
{ This surprising intermezzo gives White the initiative. It's all about opening up the queen's path towards the g4-bishop. }
10... Nd3+ 11. Bxd3 Bxc5 12. b4 { Expanding on the queenside. } 12... Be7 13.
b5 { Attacking the c6-knight. } 13... Nd8
{ 13...Qa5!  is the only move to get a reasonable position.  14.Qc2  reinforces the attack against Black's knight, when  14...Nb8  15.e4⩲  gives White an edge because Black is underdeveloped. }
14. Be5
{ Attacking both the g4-bishop and the g7-pawn with a winning position for White. }
*

