1. d4 d5 2. Nf3
{ This is the most precise move ➼ avoiding the annoying  2.Bf4  c5!  which gives us some headaches as explained in this informational. }
2... Nf6 3. Bf4 c5 4. e3 Nc6 5. Nbd2
{ This is the key move to start with. A common mistake that most of the London System players make is  5.c3  allowing  5...Qb6  with a good version for Black. }
5... Bg4 { This is one of the most solid replies for Black. } 6. c3 e6 7. Qa4
{ This could be a fun alternative to the main move  7.Qb3!  If Black is precise and knows what he is doing, we are likely to get an equal game, but according to the statistics Black falls into a trap on a regular basis in this line.Keep in mind that Qa4 is not a common idea for the London System, and it's very situational against the ...c5 & ...Bg4 mainline. This is probably why the Black players have such a poor score against it - most people don't expect it! I felt the need to mention this since I've noticed a lot of my students trying to do this against various lines after seeing it as a famous trap on YouTube. Definitely, this can have good surprise value, but you have to get this exact position in order for it to work. }
7... Bd6
{ This is a super common mistake for Black. After all they are developing according to the center, fighting for the e5-square and preparing ...O-O, right? Wrong! }
8. Ba6
{ This stunning move wins on the spot for White. I am pretty sure you have seen this famous trap on various YouTube channels! }
8... Bxf4
{ The alternatives don't work for Black:   8...Qd7  9.Bxb7!  Deflecting Black's queen from protecting the d6-bishop.  9...Qxb7  10.Bxd6+-  With an extra pawn for White and Black's king is caught in the center.   8...Qb6  leaves the d6-bishop undefended:  9.Bxd6  Qxa6  10.Qxa6  bxa6  11.Bxc5+-  With an extra pawn for White.   8...O-O  9.Bxb7  Bxf4  10.Bxc6+-  Winning at least the exchange with a winning position. }
9. Bxb7 { After this intermezzo White gets a winning position. } 9... O-O 10.
Bxc6 { Winning at least the exchange with a winning position. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "7) Queen's Gambit Declined without 5…e6"]
[Black "QGD 5.Nbd2 Nh5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3
{ This is the most precise move ➼ avoiding the annoying  2.Bf4  c5!  which gives us some headaches as explained in this informational. }
2... Nf6 3. Bf4 c5 4. e3 Nc6 5. Nbd2
{ This is the key move to start with. A common mistake that most of the London System players make is  5.c3  allowing  5...Qb6  with a good version for Black. }
5... Nh5
{ This line is very special because there are almost no Grandmaster games played before 2020 when Dubov used it to get an easy draw against Firouzja in the Tata Steel tournament. From that game, a lot of players have picked up this idea, and the theory is developing as we speak. In my opinion this variation can already be considered a main line because it has a very solid foundation. Black is sacrificing a pawn to win the London Bishop and to get good control over the center. }
6. dxc5
{ The most ambitious move because, at the end of the day, a pawn is a pawn until proven otherwise! The natural  6.Bg5  gives Black what they want after  6...h6  7.Bh4  g5  8.Bg3  Nxg3  .   An alternative could be  6.Be5  , even though after  6...e6  Black should be okay objectively speaking, but those lines are filled with interesting traps. }
6... Nxf4 7. exf4
{ At this point Black has to make the first important decision between:  7...g6 @@StartBracket@@the gambit line@@EndBracket@@  7...Qa5 @@StartBracket@@the solid line@@EndBracket@@. }
7... g6
{ The Gambit line! With this move Black is not looking to win back the pawn immediately and is focussing on quick development with a super compact pawn structure and good control over the center. This line could be very effective in the right hands, but luckily for us, this style is very hard to play for Black! }
8. c3 Bg7
{ This is what Dubov played against Firouzja in Tata Steel 2020.   8...Bh6  has also been tried, but the h6-bishop looks a bit misplaced. We continue  9.g3  O-O  10.Nb3!  The most precise, even though 10. Bg2 has also been seen.  10...a5  11.a4!  The standard reply to ...a5 ➼ stopping Black's threat of pushing ...a4!  11...Bg4  12.h3Ν  Improving over the previous games where White played 12. Be2/12. Bg2. Now after  12...Bxf3  13.Qxf3⩲  , first of all, if Black goes for the aggressive  13...e5  we can answer  14.O-O-O!  with a large advantage, and if they are going for the slower play ➼ we can push on the kingside with h4-h5. }
9. Bb5
{ Developing the bishop to b5 is very common against the Gambit line with 7... g6!? }
9... O-O
{ This is the most common choice for Black.   9...Qc7  was tried by Karjakin in a very recent game against Pragg in Wijk aan Zee, 2022. After  10.Nb3  the d5-pawn is attacked, and after  10...a6  my improvement over the Pragg-Karjakin game that went 11.Bxc6+ with an unclear game is  11.Be2!  Qxf4  12.Qxd5  O-O  13.Qd2  with an extra pawn, so we'd love to trade queens. After  13...Qc7  14.Qe3⩲  we are going to castle short followed by Nbd4 and the b4-push. }
10. Nb3
{ Played by Demchenko, this is the only serious test since Black turns out to be very comfortable after  10.O-O  d4!  as in Firouzja-Dubov, Tata Steel 2020. The point of starting with 10. Nb3 is to stop Black from pushing ...d4 and open up lines for the bishop pair. }
10... a6 11. Bxc6
{ Trading bishop for knight is good here because our knights are controlling the key squares d4 and e5. }
11... bxc6 12. O-O Qc7 13. Re1
{ We can continue with Nbd4 on the next move, and if Black tries to grab the f4-pawn we have Rxe7 as a good reply. }
*

