1. d4 d5 2. Nf3
{ This is the most precise move ➼ avoiding the annoying  2.Bf4  c5!  which gives us some headaches as explained in this informational. }
2... Nf6 3. Bf4 c5 4. e3 Nc6 5. Nbd2
{ This is the key move to start with. A common mistake that most of the London System players make is  5.c3  allowing  5...Qb6  with a good version for Black. }
5... cxd4 6. exd4 Qb6
{ Forcing White to play Nb3 in order to protect both the b2 and d4 pawns. This line is played occasionally by strong players, but overall it's not very common. }
7. Nb3 { The only move to defend both b2 and d4 ➼ but it's good enough! } 7...
Bg4
{ Threatening ...Bxf3!   In case of  7...Bf5  we can play  8.a4  , threatening to grab more space on the queenside with a5.  Now  8...a6  is the most flexible reply.   8...a5  9.Bb5  is very pleasasant for White.  9.a5  Qd8  10.Ne5!   This concrete move works well. The main reason is that  10...Nxe5  can get Black in trouble after  11.dxe5!  10...e6  11.Nxc6  bxc6  12.Bd3  Bxd3  13.Qxd3⩲  With O-O and Nc5-ideas, White enjoys a slightly better position. Black will have to constantly watch out for the a6-pawn. }
8. c3
{ Stepping away from the most common path which is  8.Be2  because we can develop the bishop to a more active square a bit later. }
8... e6 9. h3 Bh5
{ 9...Bxf3  gives us easy play with the bishop pair:  10.Qxf3  a5  11.Rb1  Defending the b2-pawn so we can move the knight away safely in case of ... a4!  11...a4  12.Nd2  Be7  13.Bd3⩲  With the bishop pair White enjoys a lasting initiative. }
10. Bd3 { Developing the bishop to the most active square. } 10... Be7 11. Qe2
{ Stopping ...Ne4-ideas! } 11... a5 12. Rb1
{ Defending the b2-pawn so we can meet  12...a4  with  13.Nbd2  .  White won a model game in Berkes,F @@StartBracket@@2636@@EndBracket@@-Mihok,O @@StartBracket@@2498@@EndBracket@@ Zalakaros 2016. }
