[White "7) Queen's Gambit Declined without 5…e6"]
[Black "QGD 5.Nbd2 cxd4 6.exd4 a6"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3
{ This is the most precise move ➼ avoiding the annoying  2.Bf4  c5!  which gives us some headaches as explained in this informational. }
2... Nf6 3. Bf4 c5 4. e3 Nc6 5. Nbd2
{ This is the key move to start with. A common mistake that most of the London System players make is  5.c3  allowing  5...Qb6  with a good version for Black. }
5... cxd4 6. exd4 a6
{ This interesting side-line has been introduced very recently in 2021 by Levon Aronian against Wesley So. The point is that if we go  7.Bd3  directly ➼ Black has the annoying  7...Nb4  .   Meanwhile, if we try to stop  ...Nb4  by going  7.c3  ➼ then Black can go  7...Bf5  with a good version of 6 ...Bf5. Can we say that White is in a pretty funny zugzwang? Almost! }
7. Bd3
{ I suggest we stick with the fun stuff. Black can get a losing position pretty quickly if they try 7...Nb4. }
7... Nb4
{ If  7...Bg4  we can defend the d4-pawn and get a comfortable setup with  8.c3  . Play might continue  8...e6  9.O-O  Bd6  10.Bxd6  Qxd6  11.Re1  O-O  12.a4⩲  Threatening to fix Black's structure with a5! The position should be close to equal, objectively speaking, but it feels a bit easier to play as White. }
8. O-O { Ignoring Black's threat! } 8... Nxd3 9. cxd3
{ I find it pointless to go deeper than this with no games ever played. My conclusion is that White has surprisingly dangerous play on the c-file connected with Rc1 and Bc7/Qc2-ideas. }
*

