[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3
{ This is the most precise move ➼ avoiding the annoying  2.Bf4  c5!  which gives us some headaches as explained in this informational. }
2... Nf6 3. Bf4 c5 4. e3 Nc6 5. Nbd2
{ This is the key move to start with. A common mistake that most of the London System players make is  5.c3  allowing  5...Qb6  with a good version for Black. }
5... cxd4 6. exd4 Bf5 7. c3
{ I prefer to stick with the standard approach, but if you are willing to mix it up, you can try  7.Bb5  which is connected with Ne5-ideas like in the game between Firouzja-Anton Guijarro, Wijk and Zee 2021. The main reason why I like to stick with  7.c3  ➼ is because it fits better with our repertoire overall. }
7... h6
{ This tricky sideline completely counters the Nh4-plan, but similar to 7... a6, we can play in the center!   7...a6  is a very rare but interesting side-line for Black and it is mainly directed against our Nh4-plan. Now the move  8.Ne5!  works well when Black is wasting time. We are threatening to push g4 if Black goes not take the e5-knight.  8...Nxe5  9.dxe5  Nd7  10.g4!  This was already played in a couple of high profile games.  10...Bg6  11.h4  Threatening to trap the bishop with h5!  11...h5  12.e6↑  After this typical pawn sacrifice Black will have a hard time finishing development. For more details check out the game between Naiditsch,A @@StartBracket@@2702@@EndBracket@@-Idani,P @@StartBracket@@25762@@EndBracket@@ Sharjah 2017. }
8. Ne5 { Going for concrete play connected with Bb5-ideas. } 8... Nxe5 9. dxe5
{ Attacking the f6-knight. } 9... Nd7 10. g4
{ Black has some concrete problems after this move. } 10... Bh7 11. e6
{ White gets interesting play in return for the pawn after  11...fxe6  12.Bb5!  followed by Nf3-Ne5 ideas. }
*

