[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3
{ This is the most precise move ➼ avoiding the annoying  2.Bf4  c5!  which gives us some headaches as explained in this informational. }
2... Nf6 3. Bf4 c5 4. e3 Nc6 5. Nbd2
{ This is the key move to start with. A common mistake that most of the London System players make is  5.c3  allowing  5...Qb6  with a good version for Black. }
5... cxd4 6. exd4 Bf5 7. c3
{ I prefer to stick with the standard approach, but if you are willing to mix it up, you can try  7.Bb5  which is connected with Ne5-ideas like in the game between Firouzja-Anton Guijarro, Wijk and Zee 2021. The main reason why I like to stick with  7.c3  ➼ is because it fits better with our repertoire overall. }
7... e6
{ The most common move ➼ preparing to develop the dark-squared bishop and castle short. }
8. Qb3
{ Attacking the b7-pawn ➼ This is a common theme when Black develops the light-squared bishop in the ...c5 lines. }
8... Qb6
{ This is not as bad as it often is in this chapter, but it's still inferior after some precise moves. While very few people do this in OTB, this is incredibly common in online chess! }
9. Nh4
{ Best objectively speaking, while also sticking with the core idea of the repertoire. }
9... Be4
{ This seems to be just an inferior version of the main line.   9...Bg6  just allows us to collect the bishop pair with  10.Nxg6  hxg6  11.g3⩲  when we can grab space on the kingside with h4 on the next move while Black will run out of useful moves soon. Of course, we would be very happy to see something like  11...Qxb3  12.axb3!   9...Bg4  is also met in the same fashion after h3-g4:  10.h3  Bh5  11.g4  Bg6  12.Nxg6  hxg6  13.Be2⩲  We can continue with Kf1-Kg2 with a small edge thanks to the bishop pair. }
10. Nxe4 dxe4 11. g3 { Using the typical move to reroute the knight. } 11... h6
{ Threatening ...g5! } 12. Ng2 Nd5 13. Bd2
{ We can play in the same fashion as against the main line by going Be2, O-O and then break with f3. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "7) Queen's Gambit Declined without 5…e6"]
[Black "QGD 5.Nbd2 cxd4 6.exd4 Bf5 #5"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3
{ This is the most precise move ➼ avoiding the annoying  2.Bf4  c5!  which gives us some headaches as explained in this informational. }
2... Nf6 3. Bf4 c5 4. e3 Nc6 5. Nbd2
{ This is the key move to start with. A common mistake that most of the London System players make is  5.c3  allowing  5...Qb6  with a good version for Black. }
5... cxd4 6. exd4 Bf5 7. c3
{ I prefer to stick with the standard approach, but if you are willing to mix it up, you can try  7.Bb5  which is connected with Ne5-ideas like in the game between Firouzja-Anton Guijarro, Wijk and Zee 2021. The main reason why I like to stick with  7.c3  ➼ is because it fits better with our repertoire overall. }
7... e6
{ The most common move ➼ preparing to develop the dark-squared bishop and castle short. }
8. Qb3
{ Attacking the b7-pawn ➼ This is a common theme when Black develops the light-squared bishop in the ...c5 lines. }
8... Qc8 { The main move in OTB. } 9. Nh4 { Hunting the bishop pair. } 9... Be4
{ This is the most ambitious move for Black ➼ not conceding the bishop pair for free and trying to make an argument that White's knight is misplaced on the rim.   9...Bg6  10.Nxg6  just collects the bishop pair.  10...hxg6  11.Bd3  Be7  12.O-O  O-O  13.Rae1  With an easy attacking plan for White. We can continue with Qd1 followed by Nf3-Ne5 combined with the h-pawn push. Make sure to check out the model game between Iturrizaga Bonelli,E @@StartBracket@@2673@@EndBracket@@-Gomez,J @@StartBracket@@2481@@EndBracket@@ Ho Chi Minh City 2017.   Meanwhile,  9...Bg4  is just an improved version of the 5...Bg4 lines for us because Black lost a tempo playing ...Bf5-Bg4. After  10.h3  Bh5  11.g4  Bg6  12.Nxg6  hxg6  13.Be2⩲  White is up a tempo compared to the normal 5...Bg4 lines. }
10. Nxe4 Nxe4
{ Played by Wojtaszek in the famous game against Magnus Carlsen. } 11. Nf3
{ Bringing back the knight because it was no longer useful on h4. } 11... Bd6
12. Bxd6 Nxd6 13. Bd3 Qc7 14. Qc2
{ The queen has done it's job on b3 ➼ now it's returning to e2. Black has a choice between two big plans:  14...h6 @@StartBracket@@going for ...O-O@@EndBracket@@  14...O-O-O. }
14... h6 { Preparing to castle short. } 15. O-O O-O 16. Qe2 Rab8 17. g4
{ Trying to make use of the h6-hook by pushing g5 next. If you want something more positional, there is obviously nothing wrong with  17.a4  ,  but I really like this aggressive idea! }
*

