1. d4 d5 2. Nf3
{ This is the most precise move ➼ avoiding the annoying  2.Bf4  c5!  which gives us some headaches as explained in this informational. }
2... Nf6 3. Bf4 c5 4. e3 Nc6 5. Nbd2
{ This is the key move to start with. A common mistake that most of the London System players make is  5.c3  allowing  5...Qb6  with a good version for Black. }
5... cxd4 6. exd4 Bf5 7. c3
{ I prefer to stick with the standard approach, but if you are willing to mix it up, you can try  7.Bb5  which is connected with Ne5-ideas like in the game between Firouzja-Anton Guijarro, Wijk and Zee 2021. The main reason why I like to stick with  7.c3  ➼ is because it fits better with our repertoire overall. }
7... e6
{ The most common move ➼ preparing to develop the dark-squared bishop and castle short. }
8. Qb3
{ Attacking the b7-pawn ➼ This is a common theme when Black develops the light-squared bishop in the ...c5 lines. }
8... Qc8 { The main move in OTB. } 9. Nh4 { Hunting the bishop pair. } 9... Be4
{ This is the most ambitious move for Black ➼ not conceding the bishop pair for free and trying to make an argument that White's knight is misplaced on the rim.   9...Bg6  10.Nxg6  just collects the bishop pair.  10...hxg6  11.Bd3  Be7  12.O-O  O-O  13.Rae1  With an easy attacking plan for White. We can continue with Qd1 followed by Nf3-Ne5 combined with the h-pawn push. Make sure to check out the model game between Iturrizaga Bonelli,E @@StartBracket@@2673@@EndBracket@@-Gomez,J @@StartBracket@@2481@@EndBracket@@ Ho Chi Minh City 2017.   Meanwhile,  9...Bg4  is just an improved version of the 5...Bg4 lines for us because Black lost a tempo playing ...Bf5-Bg4. After  10.h3  Bh5  11.g4  Bg6  12.Nxg6  hxg6  13.Be2⩲  White is up a tempo compared to the normal 5...Bg4 lines. }
10. Nxe4 dxe4
{ Playing against the h4-knight. This is the main line in OTB, but very rare online. }
11. g3
{ After this important move, the knight will be very well placed on g2. } 11...
Be7 12. Ng2 O-O
{ 12...Nd5  is likely to transpose after  13.Rd1!?  Preparing Bc1. There is not much Black can do to stop it since  13...Nxf4  14.Nxf4  O-O  15.Bg2  is quite problematic for Black because it's not easy to defend the e4-pawn. So instead play probably continues  13...O-O  when  14.Bc1  transposes back to 12... O-O. }
13. Rd1
{ This is super precise. The point is to meet  13...Nd5  with  14.Bc1  ➼ getting the best version.   Most players went for the softer  13.Be2  which is fine, but not that strong. }
13... Nd5 { Threatening ...Nxf4! } 14. Bc1 Qd7 15. Be2 { Preparing O-O. } 15...
Rac8 16. O-O
