[White "8) Queen's Gambit Declined with 5...Qb6"]
[Black "Introduction"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Bf4 c5 4. e3 Nc6 5. Nbd2 Qb6 6. dxc5
{ In this chapter we are dealing with the ...c5 main lines combined with the critical @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp2pppp/2n2n2/2pp4/3P1B2/4PN2/PPPN1PPP/R2QKB1R b KQkq - 2 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Qb6  , but also covering the quicker @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pp2pppp/5n2/2pp4/3P1B2/4PN2/PPP2PPP/RN1QKB1R b KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Qb6  . As a general idea, the game usually becomes more dynamic compared to what we are normally used to seeing in the London System. We will split the material between:   •  6...Qxc5   •  6...Qxb2   Model Games arising from this structure:  ➡ Berkes Ferenc-Forcen Esteban Daniel, Spain 2020  ➡ Nihal Sarin-Navrotescu Andreea Cristiana, Cannes 2022  ➡ Naiditsch Arkadij-Wells Peter, Antalya 2017  ➡ Gholami Aryan-Sahoo Utkal Ranjan, Mumbai 2020  ➡ Sedlak Nikola-Blagojevic Dragisa, Cetinje 2016 }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "8) Queen's Gambit Declined with 5...Qb6"]
[Black "QGD 4...Qb6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3
{ This is the most precise move ➼ avoiding the annoying  2.Bf4  c5!  which gives us some headaches as explained in this informational. }
2... Nf6 3. Bf4 c5 4. e3 Qb6
{ Attacking the b2-pawn ➼ this is a common theme in the ...c5-lines. } 5. Nc3
{ The standard reply to ...Qb6 when the knight is still on b1! The point is to meet  5...Qxb2  with  6.Nb5! }
5... Bd7 { Threatening ...Qxb2 without allowing Nb5! } 6. dxc5
{ Transposing into an improved version of the Jobava London where Black's bishop has been developed to d7. }
6... Qxb2
{ This move looks tempting for Black because White is left with the weak pawns. }
7. Nb5 { This stunning line will take by surprise most of your opponents. }
7... Bxb5 8. Qd4
{ The point! Black is forced to move away the queen and we can collect the b5-bishop with check! }
8... Qxd4
{ This is the natural move, but Black is just lost!   8...Qa3!  is the best defense, but this is never played. Play continues  9.Bxb5+  Nc6  10.Rb1  e6  11.Qa4!  We would love to trade queens because the b7-pawn will become vulnerable.  11...Qc3+  12.Kf1  The king is safe and we keep the f3-knight for the attack with Ne5!  12...Qxc5  13.Ne5  Rc8  14.Bxc6+  Making room for the queen to infiltrate.  14...bxc6  15.Qa6  Rd8  16.g4⩲  With Kg2/Rb7 ideas, White has the initiative. This was best play for both sides. }
9. Bxb5+ { The key idea to win back the piece. } 9... Nfd7 10. exd4 f6
{ Controlling the e5-square. } 11. Rb1 { Threatening Bxd7 followed by Rxb7! }
11... Nc6 12. c4
{ We can meet  12...e6  with  13.cxd5  exd5  14.Bxc6  bxc6  15.Rb7  and Black is paralyzed. }
