{ Attacking the b2-pawn ➼ this is a common theme in the ...c5-lines. } 5. Nc3
{ The standard reply to ...Qb6 when the knight is still on b1! The point is to meet  5...Qxb2  with  6.Nb5! }
5... Bd7 { Threatening ...Qxb2 without allowing Nb5! } 6. dxc5
{ Transposing into an improved version of the Jobava London where Black's bishop has been developed to d7. }
6... Qxc5 { Entering the Jobava London structure. } 7. h3
{ Stopping ...Bg4 ideas is quite important to avoid Black's counterplay! } 7...
Nc6 8. Bd3 { Preparing O-O and the e4-break. } 8... e6 9. O-O Be7 10. e4
{ We have the ideal setup for the Jobava London while Black's pieces are oddly placed.  10...dxe4  11.Nxe4  is usually very pleasant for White ➼ otherwise we can push e5 and get an improved version of the French Defense. }
