1. d4 d5 2. Nf3
{ This is the most precise move ➼ avoiding the annoying  2.Bf4  c5!  which gives us some headaches as explained in this informational. }
2... Nf6 3. Bf4 c5 4. e3 Qb6
{ Attacking the b2-pawn ➼ this is a common theme in the ...c5-lines. } 5. Nc3
{ The standard reply to ...Qb6 when the knight is still on b1! The point is to meet  5...Qxb2  with  6.Nb5! }
5... a6
{ Threatening ...Qxb2 without allowing Nb5! This is similar to  5...Bd7  except there will be no ...Qxb2 lines after we grab the c5-pawn. This is by far the main move in online chess. }
6. dxc5 Qxc5
{ The most solid move because  6...Qxb2  7.Na4!  gives White a big advantage with Nb6 coming on the next move. }
7. h3
{ Avoiding any ...Bg4 ideas. This is the safest way to avoid Black's counterplay. }
7... Nc6 8. Bd3 e6 9. O-O Be7 10. e4
{ We have the ideal set-up for the Jobava London while Black's pieces are oddly placed.  10...dxe4  11.Nxe4  is usually very pleasant for White ➼ otherwise we can push e5 and get an improved version of the French Defense. }
