1. d4 d5 2. Nf3
{ This is the most precise move ➼ avoiding the annoying  2.Bf4  c5!  which gives us some headaches as explained in this informational. }
2... Nf6 3. Bf4 c5 4. e3 Qb6
{ Attacking the b2-pawn ➼ this is a common theme in the ...c5-lines. } 5. Nc3
{ The standard reply to ...Qb6 when the knight is still on b1! The point is to meet  5...Qxb2  with  6.Nb5! }
5... c4
{ Threatening ...Qxb2 without allowing Nb5 because the f1-a6 diagonal has been blocked.   5...cxd4?!  is an inferior try because of White's response  6.Nb5!  , threatening Nc7+ ➼ forcing Black's knight to the passive a6-square.  6...Na6  7.exd4  Bg4  8.c3  Bxf3  9.Qxf3  e6  10.Bd3⩲  With the bishop pair and a monster knight on b5, White is much better. We can go super aggressive with g4-g5 with pressure on the kingside. }
