[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3
{ This is the most precise move ➼ avoiding the annoying  2.Bf4  c5!  which gives us some headaches as explained in this informational. }
2... Nf6 3. Bf4 c5 4. e3 Nc6 5. Nbd2
{ This is the key move to start with. A common mistake that most of the London System players make is  5.c3  allowing  5...Qb6  with a good version for Black. }
5... Qb6 { This is Black's most direct attempt ➼ attacking both d4 and b2. } 6.
dxc5
{ The point of having started with 5. Nbd2! Black has a choice between:  6...Qxc5  6...Qxb2. }
6... Qxc5
{ This is the safer alternative to the capture on b2, but a bit inferior. } 7.
a3 { Preparing the typical queenside storm with c4-b4! } 7... Bg4
{ This is very common in online chess. Black has a concrete threat of pushing ...e5! }
8. Be2
{ The simplest. First we are breaking the pin, and then we can focus on the typical queenside play. }
8... e6 9. c4
{ It is important to start with this move because  9.b4  Qc3  is very annoying. }
9... Be7
{ Another line is  9...dxc4  10.Nxc4  ,  threatening Rc1.  10...Rd8  11.Qc2  Be7  12.b4  Qh5  13.O-O  ⩲  We are going to win the bishop pair after we push h3, with a safe advantage. }
10. b4 { Taking a lot of space on the queenside. } 10... Qb6 11. O-O
{ There's no need to rush with c5! } 11... O-O 12. h3 Bh5 13. c5
{ Forcing Black's queen back home. } 13... Qd8 14. Rc1
{ White can look to force the issue on the queenside with b5 followed by Qa4 and c6 ideas. The queenside pawns are very strong. }
