8. Bb5 { This is simply a must in order to generate good play as White. } 8...
e6
{ This is the most common move for online chess, and White can already get a winning position in less than 10 moves!   8...Bd7  breaks the pin ➼ this is also pretty common for online chess. Now after  9.O-O  we will focus on  9...e6  because it's the most common move even though Black has a bunch of alternatives. The good news is that most of them can be met in the standard fashion with c4.  10.Ne5!  Threatening Nxd7 and playing for the queen trap.  10...Nxe5  11.Bxe5  Threatening Ra1 and Bxd7-Rxb7 ideas. Now  11...Bxb5  12.Ra1±  collects Black's queen, while after  11...Qa5  Black saves the queen, but White keeps very good pressure on the queenside with  12.c4! }
9. Nb3
{ Taking away the a5-square from Black's queen, and threatening Ra1 followed by Be5 ➼ winning the house. Black can't do much to avoid this. }
9... Ne4
{ This was tried by a number of players with the idea to go ...Nc3, but it simply doesn't work.   9...Qa3  tries to escape with ...Qb4+, but after  10.Qd4+-  Black is defenseless against Ra1 ➼ trapping the queen.   9...Nd7  stops White's direct threat of going Be5. We reply  10.O-O !  , threatening the cold-blooded Qc1 followed by Ra1. After  10...a6  11.Bxc6  bxc6  12.Qd4+-  White is threatening Rfc1 followed by Ra1, and in case of  12...Qxc2  White wins with  13.Qa4! }
10. Ra1 { Attacking Black's queen. } 10... Qb2 { Forced. } 11. Be5
{ Taking advantage of the fact that the c6-knight is pinned. } 11... Nc3 12.
Qd3
{ Instead of only winning the queen, we are also collecting the knight. How generous by Black! }
