{ Attacking Black's queen and pinning the f6-knight. } 10... Qa5
{ This is forced because  10...Qxc5  is much better for White after  11.Bxf6  exf6  12.Nxe4  Qe7  13.O-O! }
11. O-O exf3 12. Nc4
{ This is a very fresh practical try. Personally I tried  12.Qxf3  quite a lot on the internet, but my opponents seemed pretty comfortable after  12...Qxb5!  with a forced draw a few moves later.   12.Bxc6+  is another interesting try to avoid the forced draw, but still it didn't really convince me, especially after  12...bxc6  13.Qxf3  Nd5!?  which can even backfire if you are not careful. }
12... Qd8 { The only move. } 13. Bxc6+
{ It's really important to throw this move in, even though  13.Qxf3  is playable as well. The trick is to convince them into playing 14...Qd5 and fall for our trap! Going 13.Qxf3 won't achieve that effect. }
13... bxc6 14. Qxf3
{ Attacking both the c6-pawn and the f6-knight. I find this to be incredibly tricky to play for Black because it looks like they have a 'natural' winning move. }
14... Bg4 { This is the computer move ➼ keeping the game equal. } 15. Qxc6+ Bd7
16. Qf3
{ Creating a double threat of c6 and Nd6+ @@StartBracket@@that's why ...Bg7 is forced@@EndBracket@@. }
16... Bg7 17. c6 { Attacking the bishop. } 17... Bg4 18. c7
{ Winning back the sacrificed piece. } 18... Bxf3 19. cxd8=Q+ Rxd8 20. gxf3 O-O
21. Rb7 { With an equal endgame. } *

