5... Qb6 { This is Black's most direct attempt ➼ attacking both d4 and b2. } 6.
dxc5
{ The point of having started with 5. Nbd2! Black has a choice between:  6...Qxc5  6...Qxb2. }
6... Qxb2
{ The most common move in both OTB and online chess. Before we dive into the action I want to make clear that this line is very unique because we will be getting into a different pawn structure compared to what we have seen so far. While learning this variation try to think about it very specifically and not from a general perspective because we are about to enter some sharp lines. You can think of it as a completely new opening, because the typical static plans are gone and we should guide ourselves with concrete factors in order to succeed. }
7. Rb1
{ The only serious move for White. Now Black has a choice between: 7...Qc3  @@StartBracket@@The Main Line@@EndBracket@@  7...Qa3  7...Qa2. }
7... Qc3 { This is by far the main line. } 8. Bb5
{ This is simply a must in order to generate good play as White. In this position Black's main moves are  8...e6  and  8...g6  , but we will also cover the sidelines starting with  8...Qxc5  and  8...Bd7  . }
8... e6 9. O-O Be7
{ Preparing to castle short ➼ this is the main move in both OTB and online chess.   9...Qxc5  is covered via 8...Qxc5.   9...Bd7?!  is not a great move because the b7-pawn becomes vulnerable. After  10.Bd3⩲  White is already much better because there is not an easy way for Black to defend the b7-pawn. A few strong players lost in a funny way after  10...Bxc5??  11.Rb3!  Qa5  12.Rb5!  Qa3  13.Nb1  ➼ collecting the c5-bishop on the next move. }
10. e4
{ The AlphaZero pawn sacrifice. This is extremly dangerous for Black. The main point is that the 'natural'  10...dxe4  runs into  11.Nc4!!  exf3  12.Rb3  ➼ trapping Black's queen. }
10... O-O
{ The main move.   10...Qxc5  is a very rare alternative. It is somewhat playable, but leads to a bit of suffering for Black:  11.Be3  Qa3  12.Ne5!  Attacking the c6-knight. The line is quite forcing.  12...O-O !  13.Nxc6  bxc6  14.Bxc6  Ba6!  Attacking the f1-rook, this is the only way to stay in the game.  15.e5!  The most precise.  15...Ne4  16.Nxe4  dxe4  17.Bxa8  Both sides capture the rook, and we'll get an interesting endgame.  17...Bxf1  18.Qxf1  Rxa8  19.Qc4⩲  White is a bit better because the e4-pawn is weak. I don't really see a lot of people following this line in the future. Black managed to hold in Abasov,N @@StartBracket@@2656@@EndBracket@@-Maurizzi,M @@StartBracket@@2488@@EndBracket@@ Reykjavik 2021. }
11. e5 { We are entering a structure that reminds me of the French Defense. }
11... Nd7 { The only good square for the knight. } 12. Nb3
{ Threatening Bd2 ➼ trapping Black's queen! } 12... Qb4
{ The only move not to get the queen trapped while at the same time attacking the f4-bishop. }
13. Nfd4 { Creating a subtle threat of going c3 ➼ trapping Black's queen! }
13... Nxd4
{ 13...Ndxe5  would show White's point beautifully:  14.c3!  a small magnet sacrifice. Now after  14...Qxc3  15.Bd2±  Black has to give up the queen for two knights, but  14...Qa3  15.Bc1  is even worse. }
14. Nxd4 Qxc5 15. Re1
{ We could already stop here and say that White has good attack for the pawn with ideas to rook lift with Rb3-Rh3, but I decided to give some extra lines since I think the theory will develop pretty quickly in the upcoming years. }
15... a6 { This is the best line for Black according to Leela. } 16. Bd3
{ Using the trick that  16...Qxd4  runs into  17.Bxh7+! } 16... g6
{ Threatening ...Qxd4! } 17. Nb3 Qc7 18. Qg4
{ I find White's position much easier to play. We can push the h4-h5 followed by Re3-Rh3. The knight could be activated with Nd4 and White has very good attacking prospects on the kingside. }
