[White "9) Tarrasch Defense"]
[Black "Introduction"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 c5 3. dxc5
{ In this chapter we are going to deal with the Tarrasch Defense. Unfortunately, we can no longer get the typical London structure, but it's the small price we have to pay for the most precise move order.   I recommend we avoid the main lines arising after  3.c4  and instead go for the tricky  3.dxc5!?  which leads to fresh positions with good surprise value. We will split the material between:  •  3...Qa5+   •  3...Nc6   •  3...Nf6   •  3...e6 }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "9) Tarrasch Defense"]
[Black "Tarrasch: 3...Qa5+"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3
{ This is the most precise move ➼ avoiding the annoying  2.Bf4  c5!  which gives us some headaches as explained in this informational. }
2... c5
{ This is played by Tarrasch players. It's a bit annoying for us since we can no longer get the typical London System lines, but the good news is that this move order is very rare. I suggest we go for  3.dxc5  in order to avoid the Tarrasch main lines which arise after  3.c4! }
3. dxc5
{ This sideline is full of very dangerous ideas such as  3...Nc6  4.e4!  or @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp2pppp/8/2Pp4/8/5N2/PPP1PPPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3...e6  4.e4!?  I really like this variation because it's a mix of ideas that we will see in the Grunfeld chapter with additional options to play aggressive in the center with e4! Black has a big choice between:  3...Qa5+  3...Nf6  3... Nc6  3...e6. }
3... Qa5+
{ Trying to win back the c5-pawn immediately ➼ this is a common mistake for Black because generally they tend to overlook White's next move. }
4. Nc3
{ This is the most efficient way to block the check ➼ attacking the d5-pawn one more time. }
4... Nf6
{ This is Black's only serious try because after the most common reply ➼  4...Qxc5  White is completely winning with the simple  5.Qxd5! }
5. Nd4 { This is a new move ➼ threatening to play Nb3 and keep the c5-pawn. }
5... Qxc5 6. Nb3
{ Attacking Black's queen and forcing them to make an unpleasant move because the queen needs to protect the d5-pawn. }
6... Qd6 7. e4 { After this typical idea White gets a promising endgame. } 7...
Nxe4
{ This is the most stubborn defense. White gets an easy push after  7...dxe4  8.Qxd6  exd6  9.Bg5!  followed by O-O-O with a large advantage. }
8. Nb5 { Attacking Black's queen and preparing a cute trick with Qxd5! } 8...
Qd8 9. Qxd5
{ Using a small tactical trick because we will regain the queen after Nc7+ while also misplacing Black's king. }
9... Qxd5 10. Nc7+
{ Winning back the queen. This is the point of the previous move. } 10... Kd8
11. Nxd5
{ 11...e6  can be met by  12.Ne3  ➼ keeping a smooth pawn structure with a promising endgame for White because Black is struggling to coordinate. }
*

