{ This is played by Tarrasch players. It's a bit annoying for us since we can no longer get the typical London System lines, but the good news is that this move order is very rare. I suggest we go for  3.dxc5  in order to avoid the Tarrasch main lines which arise after  3.c4! }
3. dxc5
{ This sideline is full of very dangerous ideas such as  3...Nc6  4.e4!  or @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp2pppp/8/2Pp4/8/5N2/PPP1PPPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3...e6  4.e4!?  I really like this variation because it's a mix of ideas that we will see in the Grunfeld chapter with additional options to play aggressive in the center with e4! Black has a big choice between:  3...Qa5+  3...Nf6  3... Nc6  3...e6. }
3... e6
{ Preparing to recapture the pawn with ...Bxc5 ➼ this is the second most popular move for Black. }
4. e4
{ Challenging Black's center immediately! This is a temporary pawn sacrifice with the idea to play exd5 ➼ creating an isolated pawn for Black. }
4... Bxc5
{ This is the main move for Black, and what you are most likely going to encounter.   Accepting the pawn sacrifice is not really a good idea for Black:  4...dxe4??  5.Qxd8+  Kxd8  6.Ng5±  Attacking both f7 and e4 ➼ this move gives White a winning advantage already. }
5. Nc3
{ Attacking the d5-pawn and giving Black the chance to make an inaccurate move. Now  5...Nf6  is the only move to fight for an equal game. }
5... d4
{ This is the most popular move for Black. It looks very tempting, but it won't be so easy to keep the d4-pawn defended. }
6. Na4
{ This is what most players tend to underestimate. The knight on the rim is supposed to be bad, but we have a concrete theat to eliminate the c5-bishop which is the main defender of the d4-pawn. }
6... Qa5+
{ The check is very tempting ➼ This is Black's most common reply.   Giving a check with  6...Bb4+  is equally tempting, but White is close to winning after  7.c3!  which forces a promising endgame:  7...dxc3  8.Qxd8+  Kxd8  9.bxc3!  This move is important ➼ gaining a tempo by attacking the b4-bishop and speeding up development.  9...Ba5  10.Ne5±  White has a big initiative because it's going to be very hard for Black to coordinate his pieces. The f7-pawn is not easy to protect because  10...Nh6  runs into  11.Bxh6!  and Black's king is vulnerable after @@StartFEN@@rnbk2nr/pp3ppp/4p3/b3N3/N3P3/2P5/P4PPP/R1B1KB1R b KQ - 2 10@@EndFEN@@  10...Ke8  11.Bb5+!  Another important idea to keep in mind is that @@StartFEN@@rnbk2nr/pp3ppp/4p3/b3N3/N3P3/2P5/P4PPP/R1B1KB1R b KQ - 2 10@@EndFEN@@  10...Ke7  11.Ba3+!  is very unpleasant for Black. }
7. c3
{ This is the key move ➼ blocking the check and protecting the a4-knight. }
7... dxc3 8. Nxc3 Nf6 9. Bd3
{ Preparing to castle short with a slightly better position for White thanks to the extra space. A common trap in this line can appear on the board after  9...O-O  10.e5  Nfd7  11.Bxh7+!  with a winning position after the typical Greek Gift. }
