[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "9) Tarrasch Defense"]
[Black "Tarrasch: 3...e6 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3
{ This is the most precise move ➼ avoiding the annoying  2.Bf4  c5!  which gives us some headaches as explained in this informational. }
2... c5
{ This is played by Tarrasch players. It's a bit annoying for us since we can no longer get the typical London System lines, but the good news is that this move order is very rare. I suggest we go for  3.dxc5  in order to avoid the Tarrasch main lines which arise after  3.c4! }
3. dxc5
{ This sideline is full of very dangerous ideas such as  3...Nc6  4.e4!  or @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp2pppp/8/2Pp4/8/5N2/PPP1PPPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3...e6  4.e4!?  I really like this variation because it's a mix of ideas that we will see in the Grunfeld chapter with additional options to play aggressive in the center with e4! Black has a big choice between:  3...Qa5+  3...Nf6  3... Nc6  3...e6. }
3... e6
{ Preparing to recapture the pawn with ...Bxc5 ➼ this is the second most popular move for Black. }
4. e4
{ Challenging Black's center immediately! This is a temporary pawn sacrifice with the idea to play exd5 ➼ creating an isolated pawn for Black. }
4... Bxc5
{ This is the main move for Black, and what you are most likely going to encounter.   Accepting the pawn sacrifice is not really a good idea for Black:  4...dxe4??  5.Qxd8+  Kxd8  6.Ng5±  Attacking both f7 and e4 ➼ this move gives White a winning advantage already. }
5. Nc3
{ Attacking the d5-pawn and giving Black the chance to make an inaccurate move. Now  5...Nf6  is the only move to fight for an equal game. }
5... Nf6
{ This is the second most common move for Black in online chess, and the most solid variation.   5...Qb6  attacks  f2  , but we can defend with the move  6.Qd2!  ,blocking the dark-squared bishop for the time being, but we are creating a threat of going Na4 ➼ winning an important bishop. After  6...dxe4  7.Nxe4  Be7  8.Bd3⩲  we can continue with O-O followed by Qe2 @@StartBracket@@unblocking the c1-bishop@@EndBracket@@ when White has a good version of the Rubinstein French being slightly ahead in development.   5...dxe4  gives White a very promising endgame after  6.Qxd8+  Kxd8  7.Nxe4±  when Black has to do something about the c5-bishop. Meanwhile we can continue with quick development by playing Bf4 and O-O-O with a close to winning position because Black is struggling to find a safe place for his king and coordinate. }
6. exd5 { Creating the isolated pawn on d5. } 6... exd5 7. Bg5
{ Pinning the f6-knight and immediately applying pressure to the isolated pawn. }
7... O-O
{ This is Black's most common move ➼ sacrificing the d5-pawn. With very precise play, Black should get enough compensation for the pawn, but this is easier said than done!   7...Be6  tries to cover the d5-pawn, but  8.Bxf6!  is problematic for Black. After  8...Qxf6  9.Bb5+!  Nc6  10.Nxd5⩲  White has an extra pawn without much counterplay for Black.   7...Qb6  may appear tempting for Black ➼ attacking both b2 and f2, but  8.Qe2+!  is important because we are protecting the f2-pawn while buying some time to castle long. After  8...Be6  9.Bxf6!  gxf6  10.O-O-O  +-  White is simply crushing with a big threat of playing Nxd5! }
8. Bxf6 { Eliminating the knight so we can collect the d5-pawn. } 8... Qxf6 9.
Qxd5
{ Attacking the c5-bishop. Black has a choice between:  9...Re8+  9...Bb4. }
9... Bb4
{ Threatening ...Bxc3+!   In case of  9...Re8+  the only good move for White and the standard way to block the check is  10.Be2+  . After  10...Bb6  11.O-O  ⩲  Black definitely has some long term compensation with the bishop pair, but generally I think it's much easier to be up a pawn rather than constantly trying to justify compensation. }
10. Qd4
{ This move is very unpleasant for Black ➼ Offering the queen trade because endgames with the extra pawn are very promising for White and also attacking the b4-bishop. }
10... Re8+ 11. Be2 Bxc3+
{ This is Black's best try because  11...Qe7  can easily be met by  12.O-O  with the main point being that  12...Bxc3  13.Qxc3  Qxe2  14.Rfe1  wins for White because of the back rank mate. }
12. Qxc3 Qxc3+ 13. bxc3
{ 13...Nc6  will be met by  14.Kd2  and White is up a pawn in the endgame. Despite it being doubled, it's still a good asset. }
