[White "9) Tarrasch Defense"]
[Black "Tarrasch: 3...Nf6 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3
{ This is the most precise move ➼ avoiding the annoying  2.Bf4  c5!  which gives us some headaches as explained in this informational. }
2... c5
{ This is played by Tarrasch players. It's a bit annoying for us since we can no longer get the typical London System lines, but the good news is that this move order is very rare. I suggest we go for  3.dxc5  in order to avoid the Tarrasch main lines which arise after  3.c4! }
3. dxc5
{ This sideline is full of very dangerous ideas such as  3...Nc6  4.e4!  or @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp2pppp/8/2Pp4/8/5N2/PPP1PPPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3...e6  4.e4!?  I really like this variation because it's a mix of ideas that we will see in the Grunfeld chapter with additional options to play aggressive in the center with e4! Black has a big choice between:  3...Qa5+  3...Nf6  3... Nc6  3...e6. }
3... Nf6 { This is a pretty rare choice for Black. } 4. c3
{ Preparing to support the c5-pawn with b4! } 4... Nc6 5. b4
{ This move is very annoying for Black. It's not easy at all to regain the pawn. }
5... e5
{ Setting up a strong pawn center, but it's really the question whether Black can keep this center. The main drawback of this move is that if they have to push ...e4 ➼ White gets a very juicy square on d4. }
6. e3 { Preparing to develop with Be2/Bb5 ideas. } 6... Bg4
{ Pinning the f3-knight and threatening to push ...e4!   The immediate  6...e4  is exactly the type of move that we want to see because we are getting the juicy d4-square. Now  7.Nd4  Ne5  would have been interesting for Black, if they were not down a pawn! I now suggest  8.Nd2  - starting with 8.Be2 is also perfectly fine, but we are keeping open the option to play Bb5+. For example,  8...Bg4  can be met by  9.Bb5+!  with a large advantage for White. Instead play might continue  8...Be7  9.Be2  Bg4  10.O-O  ±  when White has a clearly better position with the extra pawn. We can continue by playing a4 followed by N2b3 with a5-a6 ideas to expand on the queenside.   6...a5  tries to undermine the c5-pawn, but we have a simple reply in  7.b5  Nb8  8.Nxe5  This is simplest. The computer likes 8.Ba3, but there is no need to overcomplicate things. After  8...Bxc5  9.Be2⩲  we can continue with O-O, and to me it looks like White is simply up a pawn. }
7. h3
{ This is always nice to include. We would be happy to see  7...Bxf3  8.Qxf3  with an easy game for White. }
7... Bh5 8. Be2 { Preparing O-O. } 8... a5 { Trying to undermine the c5-pawn. }
9. b5 { Attacking the c6-knight which is protecting the e5-pawn. } 9... Bxf3
{ This has to be played not to lose the e5-pawn. } 10. Bxf3 Na7 11. O-O Bxc5
12. Bb2
{ We will break with c4 on the next move with a very promising position for White thanks to the bishop pair. }
