{ This will most likely take your opponent by surprise because it was seen in less than 5% out of 50  000  games. The point is that after  4...dxe4  White gets a very promising endgame, and in case of  4...e6  it won't be that simple for Black to regain the c5-pawn. }
4... dxe4
{ This is the most common reply for Black.   4...Nf6  is best, but very rare. After  5.exd5  Nxd5  6.Bc4  we develop with tempo ➼ attacking the d5-knight, and then create an isolated pawn with  6...e6  7.Bxd5  Qxd5  8.Qxd5  exd5  9.Be3⩲  with an extra pawn for White.  7...exd5  8.Be3⩲  is similar. }
5. Qxd8+ Nxd8
{ Taking with the knight is the most common move because  5...Kxd8  6.Ng5!  gives White an easy game ➼ regaining the pawn with a much better position. }
6. Ne5 { Creating a deadly threat of Bb5+! } 6... Nc6
{ This is important. A lot of people have had to resign after  6...f6  7.Bb5+! }
7. Bb5 { Developing with tempo. We are threatening Nxc6! } 7... Bd7 8. Nxd7
{ Eliminating the bishop pair and misplacing Black's king. } 8... Kxd7 9. Nc3
{ Attacking the e4-pawn. } 9... Nf6 10. Bf4
{ Taking away the c7-square from the enemy king ➼ this is generally the key move to grab a large advantage in these endgames. We can continue with O-O-O with a close to winning position. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "10) Queen's Indian Defense"]
[Black "Introduction"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4 e6 3. e3 b6 4. Nf3
{ In this chapter we are dealing with the Queen's Indian lines. This is a pretty rare choice below 1800 blitz on chess.com, but it's definitely one of the important main lines to understand in order to be a successful London player.   Black has a variety of ways to develop which makes it pretty tough to make a move-by-move summary of the chapter. Typical pawn structures arising from this chapter:   • The hedgehog structure   Model games arising from this structure:   ➡ Carlsen Magnus-Tomashevsky Evgeny, Wijk aan Zee 2016   ➡ Bronstein David Ionovich-Shmit, Anatoly, Moscow 1970   Typical endgames arising from this structure:   ➡ Aronian Levon-Carlsen Magnus, NIC Classic 2021   ➡ Grachev Boris-Akopian Vladimir, Khanty-Mansiysk 2013 }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "10) Queen's Indian Defense"]
[Black "Queen's Indian: 4...O-O with 6...Nh5"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4
{ This is the most flexible move order ➼ making sure that we keep everything in London System territory. For more details about the move order make sure to check out the informational. }
2... e6
{ This move is usually preferred by the Queen's Indian players since Black is most likely going to follow it up by playing either 3... b6 or 3...c5. Going for 3...d5 is of course playable ➼ transposing to the QGD main lines, but less logical because Black could have played the more flexible 2...d5 ➼ putting a pawn in the center while not yet restricting the light-squared bishop. }
3. e3
{ Starting  3.Nf3  is also perfectly playable, but going  3.e3  is the most flexible move for a number of reasons. First and foremost White can now meet the agressive  3...c5  with  4.c3  ➼ preparing to meet  4...Qb6  with  5.Qb3  @@StartBracket@@this move order was played almost exclusively by Grachev and Kamsky@@EndBracket@@.   Another reason is that against  3...b6  White has an aditional option to spice things up by going for the creative  4.Qf3!?  line. Those are some important points to keep in mind, however we won't be using any of those lines in particular in this repertoire!That being said, both moves are playable, but going 3.e3 gives you a bit more room for creativity and that's why I made it our main line. }
3... Be7 4. Nd2
{ I find this to be the best move order because  4.Nf3  Nh5  seems annoying and @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/ppppbppp/4pn2/8/3P1B2/4P3/PPP2PPP/RN1QKBNR w - - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  4.h3  d5  allows Black to get back into the ...c5 and ...Be7 Main Line where we prefer to play the Ne5 line over h3. }
4... O-O 5. c3
{ Setting up the London triangle, but  5.Bd3  is also playable. } 5... c5 6.
Ngf3
{ This is the most flexible move and the best I think. Black will most likely transpose back into the following lines:   Queen's Indian after 6...b6 7.h3  QGD ...Be7 Main Lines after 6...d5 7.Bd3 Nc6 8. Ne5. }
6... Nh5
{ This is the only way for Black to deviate from the standard theory. } 7. dxc5
{ This is the best way of dealing with ...Nh5. White has a pleasant position in the typical 'Berkes Structure'. }
7... Nxf4 8. exf4 Bxc5 9. Bd3 { Preparing the standard O-O. } 9... Nc6 10. O-O
d5 11. Nb3 { Hitting the c5-bishop and heading towards the d4-square. } 11...
Bb6 12. Re1 Bd7 13. Qd2
{ We can continuously improve our position with moves such as Qd2,Rad1 followed by pushing pawns on the kingside with g3-h4 and then Nbd4 ideas. For more details about these positions, make sure to check out the Berkes structure. }
