[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "10) Queen's Indian Defense"]
[Black "Queen's Indian: 4...Be7 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4
{ This is the most flexible move order ➼ making sure that we keep everything in London System territory. For more details about the move order make sure to check out the informational. }
2... e6
{ This move is usually preferred by the Queen's Indian players since Black is most likely going to follow it up by playing either 3... b6 or 3...c5. Going for 3...d5 is of course playable ➼ transposing to the QGD main lines, but less logical because Black could have played the more flexible 2...d5 ➼ putting a pawn in the center while not yet restricting the light-squared bishop. }
3. e3
{ Starting  3.Nf3  is also perfectly playable, but going  3.e3  is the most flexible move for a number of reasons. First and foremost White can now meet the agressive  3...c5  with  4.c3  ➼ preparing to meet  4...Qb6  with  5.Qb3  @@StartBracket@@this move order was played almost exclusively by Grachev and Kamsky@@EndBracket@@.   Another reason is that against  3...b6  White has an aditional option to spice things up by going for the creative  4.Qf3!?  line. Those are some important points to keep in mind, however we won't be using any of those lines in particular in this repertoire!That being said, both moves are playable, but going 3.e3 gives you a bit more room for creativity and that's why I made it our main line. }
3... b6
{ With this move being played, we are now entering Queen's Indian teritory. While ...Bb7 is played almost exclusively, I would like to draw your attention to the fact that Black could also use ...Ba6 as an idea to trade off our powerful light-squared bishop. }
4. Nf3
{ Going for the standard approach. the g1-knight is always placed on f3 in the Classical London System. Even though 4. Qf3 is an interesting line, I am not a huge fan of it because its quite speculative and if Black plays the move order with 3...c5 and later on decides to fianchetto with ...b6, we would have to learn a lot of additional theory.   While  4.Qf3  could surprise some of your opponents, I don't see it as a healthy approach when Black can use a simple move order trick and avoid our whole idea. }
4... Be7
{ The only way this can be different compared to the main move  4...Bb7  is if Black will follow it up with ...Ba6 ➼ otherwise we will simply transpose. }
5. h3
{ It is important not to allow ...Nh5 ➼ getting rid of the London Bishop. }
5... O-O 6. Nbd2
{ This is generally the most precise way to develop. We know for sure the b1-knight belongs to d2 and we are waiting to see what Black is willing to play. An important difference can be noticed when Black goes ...Ba6 ➼ because we can take directly on a6 without having to spend a tempo on Bd3.   That being said,  6.c3  and  6.Bd3  are also playable, but a bit inaccurate. }
6... c5 7. c3
{ The most flexible move order. Now Black has two ways to deviate from the direct transposition into the ...Bb7 lines:  7...Ba6  directly or  7...cxd4  and 8...Ba6 getting back into the normal lines. }
7... cxd4
{ The point of this move order is to avoid White's plans of taking back cxd4 followed by expanding in the center with e4 like in the game played between Kamsky-Del Rio de Angelis, Sitges 2016. }
8. exd4
{ Going for the standard recapture. Taking with the c-pawn is also interesting in this position, but for the sake of simplicity we will keep 8.exd4 as the main move. }
8... Ba6
{ Going for a quick ...Ba6 leads to a good version for White because we can take on a6 in one go without having spent a tempo on playing Bd3. This is why it's important to be mindful of your options, and not rush with 'natural' looking moves. }
9. Bxa6 Nxa6 10. O-O Qc8
{ Played with the idea to bring the queen over to b7. That is a common maneuver in this structure.   10...d6  11.Qe2  develops and hits the a6-knight, and after  11...Nc7  I really like the move  12.c4!  ➼ taking control over the d5-square.  12...Qd7  13.Nb1!  This seems to be a shocking move at first sight, but we are taking advantage of the fact that Black is unable to go for any active operations by improving our knight with Nb1-Nc3 ➼ reaching a much better square.  13...a6  14.Nc3⩲  We can slowly improve our position with moves such as Rac1, Rfd1, b3 and then Ne5 becomes a direct threat! }
11. Qe2 Qb7 12. Nc4
{ Creating ideas of Nd6 ➼ taking advantage of the weak d6-square. } 12... Nd5
13. Bh2
{ With Nd6 ideas in the air White has pleasant position and went on to win a model game in: Van Foreest,J  @@StartBracket@@2609@@EndBracket@@-Adhiban,B @@StartBracket@@2671@@EndBracket@@ Hoogeveen 2017. }
