{ The point of this move order is to avoid White's plans of taking back cxd4 followed by expanding in the center with e4 like in the game played between Kamsky-Del Rio de Angelis, Sitges 2016. }
8. exd4
{ Going for the standard recapture. Taking with the c-pawn is also interesting in this position, but for the sake of simplicity we will keep 8.exd4 as the main move. }
8... d6
{ This is a tricky attempt by Black, with the idea to wait a bit and give White the chance to play the natural 9.Bd3, the point being that ➼ 9...Ba6 wins a tempo compared to the direct 8...Ba6. }
9. a4 { This is a very clever move ➼ directed againt the ...Ba6 plans. } 9...
Ba6
{ Keep in mind that  9...Bb7  10.Bd3  will tranpose back into the normal lines. }
10. Bb5
{ The point! Black has nothing better than to go back with ...Bb7 because  10...Bxb5  11.axb5  ➼ gives White a nice initiative on the queenside. }
10... Bb7 11. O-O a6 12. Bd3 Nbd7 13. Re1 Re8 14. Bh2
{ Getting back into the normal lines - see the variation. } *

