{ This is the most flexible move order ➼ making sure that we keep everything in London System territory. For more details about the move order make sure to check out the informational. }
2... e6
{ This move is usually preferred by the Queen's Indian players since Black is most likely going to follow it up by playing either 3... b6 or 3...c5. Going for 3...d5 is of course playable ➼ transposing to the QGD main lines, but less logical because Black could have played the more flexible 2...d5 ➼ putting a pawn in the center while not yet restricting the light-squared bishop. }
3. e3
{ Starting  3.Nf3  is also perfectly playable, but going  3.e3  is the most flexible move for a number of reasons. First and foremost White can now meet the agressive  3...c5  with  4.c3  ➼ preparing to meet  4...Qb6  with  5.Qb3  @@StartBracket@@this move order was played almost exclusively by Grachev and Kamsky@@EndBracket@@.   Another reason is that against  3...b6  White has an aditional option to spice things up by going for the creative  4.Qf3!?  line. Those are some important points to keep in mind, however we won't be using any of those lines in particular in this repertoire!That being said, both moves are playable, but going 3.e3 gives you a bit more room for creativity and that's why I made it our main line. }
3... b6
{ With this move being played, we are now entering Queen's Indian teritory. While ...Bb7 is played almost exclusively, I would like to draw your attention to the fact that Black could also use ...Ba6 as an idea to trade off our powerful light-squared bishop. }
4. Nf3
{ Going for the standard approach. the g1-knight is always placed on f3 in the Classical London System. Even though 4. Qf3 is an interesting line, I am not a huge fan of it because its quite speculative and if Black plays the move order with 3...c5 and later on decides to fianchetto with ...b6, we would have to learn a lot of additional theory.   While  4.Qf3  could surprise some of your opponents, I don't see it as a healthy approach when Black can use a simple move order trick and avoid our whole idea. }
4... Bb7
{ The most standard move and what I expect you to encounter the most. } 5. Nbd2
{ This move is important for a number of reasons. First and foremost, if Black deviates from the standard path @@StartBracket@@5...Be7@@EndBracket@@ by playing  5...d5  , we can simply play  6.c3  Bd6  7.h4!  ➼ transposing back to the quick ...Bd6 lines.   Following Magnus Carlsen's footsteps blindly by playing  5.h3  would give Black the chance to switch and get an improved version after  5...d5!  Of course, that is not the end of the world, but we can no longer get the best version of our setup.   Another reason why I prefer  5.Nbd2  is that  5...Bd6!?  can be met by the standard  6.Bg3! }
5... Nh5
{ This is another rare sideline for Black with the idea to get into an improved version of the Classical Dutch. }
6. Bg5 { The typical reaction when facing ...Nh5. } 6... Be7 7. h4
{ This is the key move to get an advantage against this sideline. The 'natural'  7.Bxe7  Qxe7  8.Bd3  f5  ➼ gives Black a good version of the Classical Dutch with an equal game. }
7... h6
{ The only sensible way to continue because  7...f6  allows  8.g4!  and White is better. }
8. Bxe7 Qxe7 9. Bd3 { Preparing Qe2 and O-O-O followed by the e4 push. } 9...
d6
{ 9...f5??  10.Ne5+-  is a very nice illustration of why it is beneficial for White to include h4 and h6 on the board. Compared to the previous version, White now has a huge threat of Ng6! Black is simply losing material. }
10. Qe2 Nf6 11. O-O-O Nbd7 12. e4
{ With a pleasant position for White with more space. If Black does nothing, we can improve our position with moves such as Kb1,c3 and then grab space on the kingside with h5 followed by Nh4 and f4. If Black goes for ...O-O-O ➼ we are ready to play Ba6 and in case they decide to break with ...e5 ➼ Nf1-Ng3 becomes a powerful maneuver. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "10) Queen's Indian Defense"]
[Black "Queen's Indian: 5...g6"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4
{ This is the most flexible move order ➼ making sure that we keep everything in London System territory. For more details about the move order make sure to check out the informational. }
2... e6
{ This move is usually preferred by the Queen's Indian players since Black is most likely going to follow it up by playing either 3... b6 or 3...c5. Going for 3...d5 is of course playable ➼ transposing to the QGD main lines, but less logical because Black could have played the more flexible 2...d5 ➼ putting a pawn in the center while not yet restricting the light-squared bishop. }
3. e3
{ Starting  3.Nf3  is also perfectly playable, but going  3.e3  is the most flexible move for a number of reasons. First and foremost White can now meet the agressive  3...c5  with  4.c3  ➼ preparing to meet  4...Qb6  with  5.Qb3  @@StartBracket@@this move order was played almost exclusively by Grachev and Kamsky@@EndBracket@@.   Another reason is that against  3...b6  White has an aditional option to spice things up by going for the creative  4.Qf3!?  line. Those are some important points to keep in mind, however we won't be using any of those lines in particular in this repertoire!That being said, both moves are playable, but going 3.e3 gives you a bit more room for creativity and that's why I made it our main line. }
3... b6
{ With this move being played, we are now entering Queen's Indian teritory. While ...Bb7 is played almost exclusively, I would like to draw your attention to the fact that Black could also use ...Ba6 as an idea to trade off our powerful light-squared bishop. }
4. Nf3
{ Going for the standard approach. the g1-knight is always placed on f3 in the Classical London System. Even though 4. Qf3 is an interesting line, I am not a huge fan of it because its quite speculative and if Black plays the move order with 3...c5 and later on decides to fianchetto with ...b6, we would have to learn a lot of additional theory.   While  4.Qf3  could surprise some of your opponents, I don't see it as a healthy approach when Black can use a simple move order trick and avoid our whole idea. }
4... Bb7
{ The most standard move and what I expect you to encounter the most. } 5. Nbd2
{ This move is important for a number of reasons. First and foremost, if Black deviates from the standard path @@StartBracket@@5...Be7@@EndBracket@@ by playing  5...d5  , we can simply play  6.c3  Bd6  7.h4!  ➼ transposing back to the quick ...Bd6 lines.   Following Magnus Carlsen's footsteps blindly by playing  5.h3  would give Black the chance to switch and get an improved version after  5...d5!  Of course, that is not the end of the world, but we can no longer get the best version of our setup.   Another reason why I prefer  5.Nbd2  is that  5...Bd6!?  can be met by the standard  6.Bg3! }
5... g6
{ Going for the double fianchetto. This is a rare choice for Black, but we will be getting positions that are similar to the King's Indian Defense. In this particular case we have a bit of an improved version because we can develop the bishop directly to d3 and push in the center with e4. }
6. Bd3
{ The light-squared bishop is generally placed on e2 when Black goes for the kingside fianchetto, but in this particular case ➼ Bd3 works well combined with the quick e4. }
6... Bg7 7. e4
{ Setting up a strong center of pawns which should provide White with at least a small advantage. }
7... d6 8. O-O O-O 9. Re1
{ Keeping the e4-pawn well defended and preparing Nf1-Ng3 in some positions, if Black does not strike in the center. }
9... Nbd7 10. c3
{ This is an important move ➼ keeping the pawn center very solid and also restricting Black's dark-squared bishop. }
10... h6 { Played with the idea to avoid  10...e5  11.Bg5! } 11. h3 e5
{ Black has to do something, otherwise White can simply play Bh2-Qe2-Rad1 and push e5 with a big advantage. }
12. Bh2
{ This is the standard reaction. Taking the poisoned pawn on e5 is generally very dangerous and Black gets at least an equal game. A good example is the line  12.dxe5  dxe5  13.Bxe5  Nxe5  14.Nxe5  Re8  ➼ with a lot of pressure on the e4-pawn and ideas to play on the kingside with ...Nh5-Nf4. We should definitely stay away from this kind of scenario! }
12... Re8 13. a4
{ Threatening to expand on the queenside with a5. Once the pawn reaches that square, it will be very uncomfortable for Black with a6 looming. Generally Black has a choice between two standard reactions:  13...a5  13...a6. }
13... a6
{ After  13...a5  ,  14.Bb5!  ⩲  should be the automatic reaction as Black weakens the b5-square by playing ...a5! Generally the knight is better placed on b5, but the bishop is doing fine there as well. Now White will continue with Qc2-Rad1 followed by the b4-break ➼ taking over the initiative on the queenside. }
14. Qc2
{ With a small but safe advantage for White. The plan is to centralize the rook with Rad1 and then we can push on the queenside with b4-a5. In case Black goes ...bxa5 ➼ we can take back with the pawn and use the b-file to our advantage, and in case of ...b5 ➼ we can break with c4 when Black's queenside becomes vulnerable. }
