[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "10) Queen's Indian Defense"]
[Black "Queen's Indian: 8...d6"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4
{ This is the most flexible move order ➼ making sure that we keep everything in London System territory. For more details about the move order make sure to check out the informational. }
2... e6
{ This move is usually preferred by the Queen's Indian players since Black is most likely going to follow it up by playing either 3... b6 or 3...c5. Going for 3...d5 is of course playable ➼ transposing to the QGD main lines, but less logical because Black could have played the more flexible 2...d5 ➼ putting a pawn in the center while not yet restricting the light-squared bishop. }
3. e3
{ Starting  3.Nf3  is also perfectly playable, but going  3.e3  is the most flexible move for a number of reasons. First and foremost White can now meet the agressive  3...c5  with  4.c3  ➼ preparing to meet  4...Qb6  with  5.Qb3  @@StartBracket@@this move order was played almost exclusively by Grachev and Kamsky@@EndBracket@@.   Another reason is that against  3...b6  White has an aditional option to spice things up by going for the creative  4.Qf3!?  line. Those are some important points to keep in mind, however we won't be using any of those lines in particular in this repertoire!That being said, both moves are playable, but going 3.e3 gives you a bit more room for creativity and that's why I made it our main line. }
3... b6
{ With this move being played, we are now entering Queen's Indian teritory. While ...Bb7 is played almost exclusively, I would like to draw your attention to the fact that Black could also use ...Ba6 as an idea to trade off our powerful light-squared bishop. }
4. Nf3
{ Going for the standard approach. the g1-knight is always placed on f3 in the Classical London System. Even though 4. Qf3 is an interesting line, I am not a huge fan of it because its quite speculative and if Black plays the move order with 3...c5 and later on decides to fianchetto with ...b6, we would have to learn a lot of additional theory.   While  4.Qf3  could surprise some of your opponents, I don't see it as a healthy approach when Black can use a simple move order trick and avoid our whole idea. }
4... Bb7
{ The most standard move and what I expect you to encounter the most. } 5. Nbd2
{ This move is important for a number of reasons. First and foremost, if Black deviates from the standard path @@StartBracket@@5...Be7@@EndBracket@@ by playing  5...d5  , we can simply play  6.c3  Bd6  7.h4!  ➼ transposing back to the quick ...Bd6 lines.   Following Magnus Carlsen's footsteps blindly by playing  5.h3  would give Black the chance to switch and get an improved version after  5...d5!  Of course, that is not the end of the world, but we can no longer get the best version of our setup.   Another reason why I prefer  5.Nbd2  is that  5...Bd6!?  can be met by the standard  6.Bg3! }
5... Be7
{ The standard move. Black is preparing ...O-O and then the most common plan is to go ...c5 followed by ...cxd4 ➼ entering the typical 'Hedgehog Structure'. Besides that, we should not forget about the 'innocent' positional threat of going ...Nh5! }
6. h3
{ This is important because we need to have a square to hide our dark-squared bishop in case of ... Nh5. }
6... O-O
{ Black has an alternative in  6...d6  . The idea behind this move is to play a waiting game with ...Nbd7 and ...h6 ➼ hoping that White will castle short and then ...g5!? becomes annoying to deal with. This line does not have any theoretical value, but I thought it might be useful to include since I ran into the ...g5 plan a couple of times and I had a hard time dealing with it OTB. The key idea to counter this setup as White is to simply wait a bit before castling!  7.Bd3  Nbd7  . Now  8.c3!  is a very clever waiting move. We are inviting Black to castle short, so we can safely do the same and avoid the ...g5 nonsense.   8.O-O  I made this move automatically in a few blitz games, and quickly found myself in trouble after the following moves:  8...h6  9.e4!  g5  10.Bg3  g4  11.hxg4  Nxg4  12.Qe2  h5∞  With a complicated position, where Black is getting way more counterplay than they were supposed to!  8...h6  Black is still hoping to see O-O from White.  9.e4!  ⩲  Avoiding all the ...g5 nonsense! Black is running out of useful moves, and we can simply castle next with a slightly better position thanks to the extra space in the center. }
7. Bd3
{ This is the most active place for our light-squared bishop. It normally belongs on this square except when we are dealing with the kingside fianchetto. }
7... c5
{ The only big move in the position since both  7...d5  and  7...d6  are very likely to transpose. }
8. O-O
{ This is the standard way to castle against the Queen's Indian, and also in general. In some positions White can try to play for long castle, but it's very situational. Now Black has a choice between:  8...d6  8...d5  8...cxd4 @@StartBracket@@the main line@@EndBracket@@. }
8... d6
{ This can very much transpose to the  8...cxd4  lines, but we will have a look at the alternatives involving ...Nc6. }
9. c3 Nc6
{ This is the only sensible alternative since  9...Nbd7  will most likely transpose to the main line. }
10. Qe2
{ This is the safest square for the queen, supporting e4 in the future. You should avoid  10.Qc2  because the queen is vulnerable to  10...Rc8  with all sorts of unpleasant threats along the c-file @@StartBracket@@I've had a lot of students making this mistake!@@EndBracket@@. }
10... Re8
{ Preparing to play ...Bf8 and ...e5. This is Black's only active plan. } 11.
Bh2
{ The standard prophylactical retreat works very well against Black's ...e5-break ➼ saving us time to counter it when it gets played. }
11... Rc8
{ If  11...Bf8  we can play  12.a3  preparing to push e4 without allowing counterplay based on ...cxd4 & ...Nb4! After  12...e5  13.dxe5  dxe5  14.Ne4⩲  White has a better position thanks to the slightly weakened light squares and the vulnerable e5-pawn. White will activate by playing Rad1 and Qc2 ➼ followed by Nxf6+ combined with Be4 with very annoying pressure on Black's center. }
12. a3
{ This is the key way of getting an easy push against these lines! We are getting rid of Black's only source of counterplay which was ...cxd4 combined with ...Nb4! }
12... Bf8 13. e4
{ With a steady edge for White thanks to the extra space in the center. A simple plan is to push further in the center with e5 and play Ne4 with a dominating position. White won a nice game in Kamsky,G @@StartBracket@@2674@@EndBracket@@ -Spyropoulos,N @@StartBracket@@2425@@EndBracket@@ Chess.com INT 2020. }
