8... d5
{ This position can be reached from a number of different move orders, but I decided to cover it here. }
9. c3
{ Preparing to meet  9...c4  with  10.Bc2!  in case Black is going aggressive on the queenside. Now Black has a choice between two very popular moves, and a bunch of sidelines:   9...Nc6 @@StartBracket@@big line@@EndBracket@@  9...Nbd7 @@StartBracket@@big line and might be the best@@EndBracket@@  9...Ba6 @@StartBracket@@trading the bad bishop@@EndBracket@@  9...Ne4 @@StartBracket@@playing in the center@@EndBracket@@. }
9... Nc6
{ Even though, optically speaking ...Nc6 seems a bit more active than ...Nbd7, the issue with this line is that the c6-knight is blocking the b7-bishop which allows White to play in the center with e4. }
10. Qe2
{ This is the safest square for the queen, supporting e4 in the future. You should avoid  10.Qc2  because the queen is vulnerable to  10...Rc8  with all sorts of unpleasant threats along the c-file @@StartBracket@@I've had a lot of students making this mistake!@@EndBracket@@. }
10... Rc8
{ This was tried by the Russian top GM Evgeny Tomashevsky ➼ trying to improve over his game against Magnus Carlsen that went 10...Bd6.   There is also the move  10...Re8  ,  which is occasionally played by Black. The idea is to go for ... Bd6 and break with ...e5! We should reply  11.Ne5!  Not the only move, but it seems to work best. If Black stays passive we can play Nxc6 and the bring the other knight with Nf3-Ne5!  11...Nxe5  12.dxe5  Nd7  13.Qg4⩲  This is a strong move because it's preparing to set-up one of the key attacking positions for the London System. The plan is to simply follow up with Nf3 and Rad1 with a big advantage. Whenever you can get Qg4, Nf3, Bf4, Bd3 @@StartBracket@@with pawn on e5@@EndBracket@@ White gets an amazing position! }
11. Rad1 { This move is always a good follow up after playing Qe2! } 11... Re8
12. Rfe1
{ This move is very strong because it creates the threat of dxc5 followed by e4! }
12... Bd6 { The logical follow up. } 13. Bxd6 Qxd6 14. e4
{ With a huge threat of pushing e5 ➼ White is taking over the initiative and won a nice game in Xu,X @@StartBracket@@2580@@EndBracket@@-Tomashevsky,E @@StartBracket@@2705@@EndBracket@@ Chess.com INT 2020. }
