{ Black has an alternative in  6...d6  . The idea behind this move is to play a waiting game with ...Nbd7 and ...h6 ➼ hoping that White will castle short and then ...g5!? becomes annoying to deal with. This line does not have any theoretical value, but I thought it might be useful to include since I ran into the ...g5 plan a couple of times and I had a hard time dealing with it OTB. The key idea to counter this setup as White is to simply wait a bit before castling!  7.Bd3  Nbd7  . Now  8.c3!  is a very clever waiting move. We are inviting Black to castle short, so we can safely do the same and avoid the ...g5 nonsense.   8.O-O  I made this move automatically in a few blitz games, and quickly found myself in trouble after the following moves:  8...h6  9.e4!  g5  10.Bg3  g4  11.hxg4  Nxg4  12.Qe2  h5∞  With a complicated position, where Black is getting way more counterplay than they were supposed to!  8...h6  Black is still hoping to see O-O from White.  9.e4!  ⩲  Avoiding all the ...g5 nonsense! Black is running out of useful moves, and we can simply castle next with a slightly better position thanks to the extra space in the center. }
7. Bd3
{ This is the most active place for our light-squared bishop. It normally belongs on this square except when we are dealing with the kingside fianchetto. }
7... c5
{ The only big move in the position since both  7...d5  and  7...d6  are very likely to transpose. }
8. O-O
{ This is the standard way to castle against the Queen's Indian, and also in general. In some positions White can try to play for long castle, but it's very situational. Now Black has a choice between:  8...d6  8...d5  8...cxd4 @@StartBracket@@the main line@@EndBracket@@. }
8... d5
{ This position can be reached from a number of different move orders, but I decided to cover it here. }
9. c3
{ Preparing to meet  9...c4  with  10.Bc2!  in case Black is going aggressive on the queenside. Now Black has a choice between two very popular moves, and a bunch of sidelines:   9...Nc6 @@StartBracket@@big line@@EndBracket@@  9...Nbd7 @@StartBracket@@big line and might be the best@@EndBracket@@  9...Ba6 @@StartBracket@@trading the bad bishop@@EndBracket@@  9...Ne4 @@StartBracket@@playing in the center@@EndBracket@@. }
9... Nc6
{ Even though, optically speaking ...Nc6 seems a bit more active than ...Nbd7, the issue with this line is that the c6-knight is blocking the b7-bishop which allows White to play in the center with e4. }
10. Qe2
{ This is the safest square for the queen, supporting e4 in the future. You should avoid  10.Qc2  because the queen is vulnerable to  10...Rc8  with all sorts of unpleasant threats along the c-file @@StartBracket@@I've had a lot of students making this mistake!@@EndBracket@@. }
10... Bd6
{ This is the most popular move for Black, featured in the stem game between Magnus Carlsen and Evgeny Tomashevsky.   10...Nh5  This plan is combined with pushing ...f5 next ➼ stopping White from advancing in the center with e4.  11.Bh2  f5  12.g4!  This is the key move to refute the 10... Nh5 plan. Black is now forced to take on g4 ➼ otherwise they lose a pawn.  12...fxg4  13.hxg4  Nf6  14.Ng5  Threatening Nxe6 while also defending the g4-pawn. After  14...Qd7  15.f4±  White is threatening to push f5! and then we can bring our forces to the kingside with moves such as Qg2 followed by Kh1-Rg1 with a big attack. }
11. Rfe1 Bxf4
{ This is possible, but it gives White a pleasant version of the typical 'Berkes pawn structure'.   11...Ne7  was featured in the stem game between Carlsen-Tomashevsky. Black is maneuvering the knight to g6.  12.Rad1!  This is always a good follow up after Qe2.  12...Ng6  13.Bxg6!  This counter-intuitive move is the key idea to get a lasting initiative. It's not very often that we voluntarily trade our light-squared bishop for the knight, but the point is to attack Black on the h-file!  13...hxg6  14.Bxd6!  This is a nice exchange in order to establish our knight on e5 and support it with f4!  14...Qxd6  15.Ne5⩲  White has a very clear cut plan:   Step 1: play f4  Step 2: Ndf3-Ng5  step 3: Qf2-Qh4.   After all these moves White gets a decisive attack along the h-file which is a very standard theme for the London System in general. White won a nice game in: Carlsen,M @@StartBracket@@2844@@EndBracket@@-Tomashevsky,E @@StartBracket@@2728@@EndBracket@@ Wijk aan Zee 2016, which is analyzed in the model game section. }
12. exf4 cxd4 13. Nxd4
{ This move is important ➼ otherwise Black will get annoying ...Nb4 ideas after  13.cxd4  . }
13... Nxd4 14. cxd4 Qd6 15. g3
{ With only a slight edge for White, but with so many ways to improve our position. White can literally premove the following moves: Nf3-Ne5, h4-h5, Kg2, Rad1, a3@@StartBracket@@stopping ...Qb4@@EndBracket@@ and then we can set-up the battery with Bb1-Qd3.What is Black going to do in the meantime? That's not an easy question to answer! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "10) Queen's Indian Defense"]
[Black "Queen's Indian: 8...d5 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4
{ This is the most flexible move order ➼ making sure that we keep everything in London System territory. For more details about the move order make sure to check out the informational. }
2... e6
{ This move is usually preferred by the Queen's Indian players since Black is most likely going to follow it up by playing either 3... b6 or 3...c5. Going for 3...d5 is of course playable ➼ transposing to the QGD main lines, but less logical because Black could have played the more flexible 2...d5 ➼ putting a pawn in the center while not yet restricting the light-squared bishop. }
3. e3
{ Starting  3.Nf3  is also perfectly playable, but going  3.e3  is the most flexible move for a number of reasons. First and foremost White can now meet the agressive  3...c5  with  4.c3  ➼ preparing to meet  4...Qb6  with  5.Qb3  @@StartBracket@@this move order was played almost exclusively by Grachev and Kamsky@@EndBracket@@.   Another reason is that against  3...b6  White has an aditional option to spice things up by going for the creative  4.Qf3!?  line. Those are some important points to keep in mind, however we won't be using any of those lines in particular in this repertoire!That being said, both moves are playable, but going 3.e3 gives you a bit more room for creativity and that's why I made it our main line. }
3... b6
{ With this move being played, we are now entering Queen's Indian teritory. While ...Bb7 is played almost exclusively, I would like to draw your attention to the fact that Black could also use ...Ba6 as an idea to trade off our powerful light-squared bishop. }
4. Nf3
{ Going for the standard approach. the g1-knight is always placed on f3 in the Classical London System. Even though 4. Qf3 is an interesting line, I am not a huge fan of it because its quite speculative and if Black plays the move order with 3...c5 and later on decides to fianchetto with ...b6, we would have to learn a lot of additional theory.   While  4.Qf3  could surprise some of your opponents, I don't see it as a healthy approach when Black can use a simple move order trick and avoid our whole idea. }
4... Bb7
{ The most standard move and what I expect you to encounter the most. } 5. Nbd2
{ This move is important for a number of reasons. First and foremost, if Black deviates from the standard path @@StartBracket@@5...Be7@@EndBracket@@ by playing  5...d5  , we can simply play  6.c3  Bd6  7.h4!  ➼ transposing back to the quick ...Bd6 lines.   Following Magnus Carlsen's footsteps blindly by playing  5.h3  would give Black the chance to switch and get an improved version after  5...d5!  Of course, that is not the end of the world, but we can no longer get the best version of our setup.   Another reason why I prefer  5.Nbd2  is that  5...Bd6!?  can be met by the standard  6.Bg3! }
5... Be7
{ The standard move. Black is preparing ...O-O and then the most common plan is to go ...c5 followed by ...cxd4 ➼ entering the typical 'Hedgehog Structure'. Besides that, we should not forget about the 'innocent' positional threat of going ...Nh5! }
6. h3
{ This is important because we need to have a square to hide our dark-squared bishop in case of ... Nh5. }
6... O-O
{ Black has an alternative in  6...d6  . The idea behind this move is to play a waiting game with ...Nbd7 and ...h6 ➼ hoping that White will castle short and then ...g5!? becomes annoying to deal with. This line does not have any theoretical value, but I thought it might be useful to include since I ran into the ...g5 plan a couple of times and I had a hard time dealing with it OTB. The key idea to counter this setup as White is to simply wait a bit before castling!  7.Bd3  Nbd7  . Now  8.c3!  is a very clever waiting move. We are inviting Black to castle short, so we can safely do the same and avoid the ...g5 nonsense.   8.O-O  I made this move automatically in a few blitz games, and quickly found myself in trouble after the following moves:  8...h6  9.e4!  g5  10.Bg3  g4  11.hxg4  Nxg4  12.Qe2  h5∞  With a complicated position, where Black is getting way more counterplay than they were supposed to!  8...h6  Black is still hoping to see O-O from White.  9.e4!  ⩲  Avoiding all the ...g5 nonsense! Black is running out of useful moves, and we can simply castle next with a slightly better position thanks to the extra space in the center. }
7. Bd3
{ This is the most active place for our light-squared bishop. It normally belongs on this square except when we are dealing with the kingside fianchetto. }
7... c5
{ The only big move in the position since both  7...d5  and  7...d6  are very likely to transpose. }
8. O-O
{ This is the standard way to castle against the Queen's Indian, and also in general. In some positions White can try to play for long castle, but it's very situational. Now Black has a choice between:  8...d6  8...d5  8...cxd4 @@StartBracket@@the main line@@EndBracket@@. }
8... d5
{ This position can be reached from a number of different move orders, but I decided to cover it here. }
9. c3
{ Preparing to meet  9...c4  with  10.Bc2!  in case Black is going aggressive on the queenside. Now Black has a choice between two very popular moves, and a bunch of sidelines:   9...Nc6 @@StartBracket@@big line@@EndBracket@@  9...Nbd7 @@StartBracket@@big line and might be the best@@EndBracket@@  9...Ba6 @@StartBracket@@trading the bad bishop@@EndBracket@@  9...Ne4 @@StartBracket@@playing in the center@@EndBracket@@. }
9... Nbd7
{ This is probably the best line for Black in this structure, because compared to the 9...Nc6 lines ➼ Black has better control over the e4-square since the b7-bishop is not blocked by the c6-knight anymore.   The move  9...Ne4  is usually connected with ...f5 ➼ reinforcing the e4-knight, but it has the drawback that it weakens the e5-square! We should reply  10.Qc2  f5  11.Ne5!  when all of a sudden, it's White who has the stronger outpost!  11...Nd7  12.Nxd7!  This is a good trade because it will be followed up by moving the other knight over to e5!  12...Qxd7  13.Nf3⩲  With a clear advantage for White. We are going to establish our own knight on e5 and then kick the enemy knight with f3 ➼ securing a steady positional edge.   If  9...Ba6  I really like the move  10.Bxa6!  because it misplaces Black's knight. After  10...Nxa6  11.Ne5⩲  White has a slightly better position because it will take some time for Black to bring the a6-knight back in the game. A potential plan could be to play Qe2 and open up the position with e4 ➼ taking advantage of the fact that Black is a little underdeveloped. }
10. Qb1
{ After digging quite a lot in these position I found out that this plan poses the most practical issues for Black. The problem with the standard  10.Qe2  is that Black can play  10...Ne4  ➼ and we can no longer play for the desired e4-push. After 10.Qb1 the trick is to focus on the queenside with a4 and b4 ➼ taking advantage of the slightly passive d7-knight @@StartBracket@@notice that Qb1 was not effective vs 9...Nc6 because the knight was controlling the b4-square@@EndBracket@@. }
10... h6
{ This is the most natural move for Black because in some lines White jumps to e5 with the knight and the h7-pawn could become a bit vulnerable.   10...c4  was played in a high profile game between Dubov-Artemiev.  11.Bc2  b5  12.b3  Ba6  This is quite forced.   The standard  12...a6  is not working well in view of  13.bxc4  dxc4  14.e4!  with a strong pawn center for White.  13.b4  Bb7  14.a4⩲  with a slightly better position for White without much risks. The natural  14...a6  can be met by  15.Ne5  and White will be breaking with e4 sooner or later. Dubov,D @@StartBracket@@2648@@EndBracket@@ -Artemiev,V @@StartBracket@@2663@@EndBracket@@ Sochi 2016 }
11. a4
{ Threatening a very annoying pawn push to a5. The dream scenario would be to push the pawn all the way to a6 when Black's light-squared bishop will have a hard time finding a safe square. This is a very common idea in the London System! }
11... a5
{ If  11...a6  12.b4⩲  black has a variety of ways to deal with the concrete threat of bxc5, but my general feeling is that White's position is more pleasant after the standard Ne5. }
12. Bb5
{ With a risky position for Black, strategically speaking ➼ because of the weak square on b5. The computer is not too impressed, but in a practical game I feel like White has very good potential. We can continue with the standard Ne5 plan followed by Qd1-Qe2 @@StartBracket@@the queen is no longer amazing on b1 when the b4-push is not available@@EndBracket@@ ➼ focusing on pawn breaks such as e4 or c4. }
*

