{ This is the standard way to castle against the Queen's Indian, and also in general. In some positions White can try to play for long castle, but it's very situational. Now Black has a choice between:  8...d6  8...d5  8...cxd4 @@StartBracket@@the main line@@EndBracket@@. }
8... cxd4 9. exd4 Nc6
{ This is somewhat playable for Black, but my general feeling is that the knight is slightly misplaced on c6 ➼ making it harder to achieve the typical queenside play. }
10. c3 d6
{ This is the standard move.   The move  10...Nd5?!  is usually connected with ...f5 and although I've faced it a couple of times in my blitz games, the line should be very dubious!  11.Bh2  f5  Black is trying to organize an attack on the kingside with moves such as ...Qe8 and ...Rf6 but this plan is doomed to fail. White can refute it by playing in the center with c4-d5!  12.Re1  Activating the rook and preparing to push c4. This way we can meet ...Ndb4 ideas with the simple and strong Bf1! After  12...Qe8  13.c4  Nf6  14.d5!  ±  Black is simply lost. }
11. Re1 Re8 12. Bh2
{ This is always a useful move ➼ making the ...e5-break less effective. } 12...
Bf8 13. a4 g6 { Preparing to fianchetto. } 14. Qb3
{ With an easier position for White. We can continue with Rad1, Bf1 followed by the knight maneuver with Ng5-Nge4 with pressure on the d6-pawn. }
