12... Bf8 { This is Black's most common plan. } 13. a4
{ Threatening to push a5. } 13... a6
{ An automatic reaction, in order to be able to meet  14.a5  with  14...b5! }
14. Nc4
{ I prefer this move because it's a bit more forcing than the alternatives.  14.Qe2  and  14.Ng5  have also been tried occasionally by White. }
14... Qc7 { This move is forced in order to secure the d6-pawn. } 15. Ne3
{ This is an amazing square for the knight ➼ protecting the g2-square and also supporting an eventual pawn storm on the queenside with b4-c4. }
15... g6
{ This seems to be a relatively popular choice for Black in online chess. Simply preparing the kingside fianchetto. The good news is that we have a great way to punish this plan! }
16. Nd2 Bg7
{ The most natural way to follow up the previous move.   16...e5  was seen in a pretty high profile game of Levon Aronian with the white pieces, but the problem is that it weakens the f7-square.  17.Bf1  Bg7  18.Qb3⩲  With a slight edge for White who can target the f7-square by playing Rad1 followed by Nf3-Ng5 with Bc4. }
17. a5 b5 18. c4
{ With a big initiative on the queenside and pressure on the d6-pawn. } *

