{ I prefer this move because it's a bit more forcing than the alternatives.  14.Qe2  and  14.Ng5  have also been tried occasionally by White. }
14... Qc7 { This move is forced in order to secure the d6-pawn. } 15. Ne3
{ This is an amazing square for the knight ➼ protecting the g2-square and also supporting an eventual pawn storm on the queenside with b4-c4. }
15... e5
{ This move scores really well for Black @@StartBracket@@from the few games that I managed to find@@EndBracket@@. The main reason for that is because most of the players tend to play passive. The key idea to @@StartBracket@@almost@@EndBracket@@ refute 15...e5 is by finding the weak spot in Black's camp ➼ the f7-square! }
16. Bc4
{ Targeting the weakest spot in Black's camp. There already are tactical ideas of Bxf7+ combined with Qb3+! }
16... exd4
{ Natural, but losing on the spot!   16...Re7  is the only move that's not losing immediately to Bxf7+! We can continue  17.Qb3  Creating a double threat of Nf5 and Ng5!  17...Bxf3  might look a bit scary ➼ allowing the doubled pawns, but you have to undestand that this way ➼ we get rid of Black's strongest piece.  18.gxf3  Threatening Nf5 so the next move is forced.  18...g6  19.f4!  Threatening fxe5 followed by Ng4!  19...exd4  20.cxd4±  With f5 coming on the next move, Black has problems on the kingside. }
17. Bxf7+
{ This is the key pattern that you need to keep in mind whenever Black decides to push ...e5 because the f7-square becomes vulnerable! }
17... Kxf7 18. Qb3+ Kg6 19. Nh4+ Kh5 20. Nef5
{ With multiple threats such as Qf7+ or Qd1 ➼ Black will get checkmated soon. }
