[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "10) Queen's Indian Defense"]
[Black "Queen's Indian: Kamsky's Plan 12.a4"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4
{ This is the most flexible move order ➼ making sure that we keep everything in London System territory. For more details about the move order make sure to check out the informational. }
2... e6 3. e3 b6 4. Nf3 Bb7 5. Nbd2 Be7 6. h3 O-O
{ Black has an alternative in  6...d6  . The idea behind this move is to play a waiting game with ...Nbd7 and ...h6 ➼ hoping that White will castle short and then ...g5!? becomes annoying to deal with. This line does not have any theoretical value, but I thought it might be useful to include since I ran into the ...g5 plan a couple of times and I had a hard time dealing with it OTB. The key idea to counter this setup as White is to simply wait a bit before castling!  7.Bd3  Nbd7  . Now  8.c3!  is a very clever waiting move. We are inviting Black to castle short, so we can safely do the same and avoid the ...g5 nonsense.   8.O-O  I made this move automatically in a few blitz games, and quickly found myself in trouble after the following moves:  8...h6  9.e4!  g5  10.Bg3  g4  11.hxg4  Nxg4  12.Qe2  h5∞  With a complicated position, where Black is getting way more counterplay than they were supposed to!  8...h6  Black is still hoping to see O-O from White.  9.e4!  ⩲  Avoiding all the ...g5 nonsense! Black is running out of useful moves, and we can simply castle next with a slightly better position thanks to the extra space in the center. }
7. Bd3 c5 8. O-O cxd4 9. exd4 d6 10. Re1 Nbd7 11. Bh2 Re8 12. a4
{ This is the Gata Kamsky move order, delaying c3 and focusing on quick play on the queenside based on a4-a5 followed by c2-c4! }
12... a6 { This is forced so that Black can meet  13.a5  with  13...b5! } 13.
a5 b5
{ This is the only serious try for Black.  13...bxa5  14.Nc4  is very promising for White with Nxa5 coming on the next move. }
14. c4
{ This is Kamsky's pet line. Please keep in mind that if you planning to pick up these lines you have to be very careful with the move order and delay the typical c2-c3 move so you can get this c2-c4 in one go! }
14... bxc4
{ This is the main move for Black.   14...Bc6?!  allows a typical trap for the variation:  15.d5!  Preparing to play Nd4 on the next move, this will take a lot of your opponents by surprise.  15...exd5  16.Nd4  Attacking the c6-bishop and applying pressure on the b5-pawn.  16...Bb7  17.cxb5+-  White is simply crushing on the queenside and went on to win in Kamsky,G @@StartBracket@@2665@@EndBracket@@-Alavi Moghaddam,S @@StartBracket@@2445@@EndBracket@@ Europe Echecs INT 2021. }
15. Nxc4 { Attacking the d6-pawn. } 15... Qb8
{ This is Black's main move ➼ preparing to play ...Rc8!   15...Nf8  16.Nb6!  is the main issue with Black's previous move.  16...Rb8  17.Nd2⩲  Preparing to play Ndc4 on the next move with a dominating position for White thanks to the b6-knight.   15...d5?!  is a strategical mistake because it allows Nd6 and it's locking the b7-bishop.  16.Nd6!  Attacking both the e8-rook and the b7-bishop.  16...Bxd6  17.Bxd6±  White is much better with the bishop pair and a simple plan could be to push b4-b5 ➼ creating a dangerous outside passer on the a-file. }
16. Nfd2 { Preparing to play Qa4 without allowing ...Bxf3! } 16... Bd5
{ 16...Rc8  17.Qa4  Preparing to play Qa3 ➼ targeting the d6-pawn.  17...Bc6  18.Qa3  Attacking the d6-pawn.  18...Ne8  19.Rac1⩲  With a big positional threat of playing Ne4 ➼ White has pressure on the d6-pawn.   16...Bf8  With idea to push ...e5!  17.Qa4  e5  18.Bf1⩲  We can continue with b4-b5 with pressure on the queenside. }
17. Bf1 { Following Nihal's footsteps. } 17... Rc8 18. Qa4 Bc6
{ Attacking White's queen. } 19. Qa3 { Targeting the d6-pawn. } 19... Ne8 20.
Ne4
{ This is a small improvement over the very recent game between Nihal-Macon, Cappelle la Grande 2022 that went  20.Rac1  and White was pressing, but failed to win. }
20... Bxe4 21. Rxe4
{ With the bishop pair and a simple plan to play Ree1-Rec1 followed by Ne3. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "10) Queen's Indian Defense"]
[Black "3...c5 & 4...b6 Move Order: 5. Nc3 Alternative #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4
{ This is the most flexible move order ➼ making sure that we keep everything in London System territory. For more details about the move order make sure to check out the informational. }
2... e6 3. e3 c5 4. Nf3 b6
{ This move order is a bit inaccurate because it gives White the chance to get an improved version of the Jobava London after  5.Nc3!   Disclaimer: the upcoming lines are very sharp and move by move dependent so you need to be really careful if you are willing to pick this up. Personally I like to keep it simple by going  5.Nbd2  Bb7  6.h3  and just transpose back into the regular lines. }
5. Nc3
{ Creating a threat of playing Nb5 because the d6-square has been weakened. }
5... Bb7 { This is the most common move for Black. } 6. Nb5
{ Creating a big threat of Nc7+! } 6... d6
{ This is Black's most natural move because it stops the fork while also covering the d6-square.   6...Na6  7.Nd2!  threatens to play Nc4 followed by Nd6+!   This move is important because the 'tempting'  7.Nd6+  Bxd6  8.Bxd6  Ne4!  gives Black good counterplay.  7...d5  8.g4↑  With the strong b5-knight and ideas to play on the kingside with g5-h4-h5-Rg1-g6 White has the initiative, however the position remains pretty messy.   6...Nd5  covers the c7-square and creates a positional threat of ...Nxf4! We can answer  7.Nd6+!  This move works well now because Black won't have an easy way to get rid of the d6-bishop. After  7...Bxd6  8.Bxd6±  White has a clearly better position because the d6-bishop is a thorn in Black's position. }
7. dxc5 { This is the problem! Black has issues with the d6-pawn. } 7... e5
{ This had to be played - otherwise Black could resign immediately. } 8. cxd6
{ This is the killer move ➼ creating a big threat of Nc7+! } 8... exf4 9. Nc7+
{ Not only winning the a8-rook, but exposing Black's king! } 9... Kd7 10. Ne5+
{ I think we can call this a 'knightmare'. } 10... Kc8 11. Nxf7
{ Picking up both rooks soon with a crushing advantage for White. } *

