1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4 g6 3. Nf3 Bg7 4. c3 O-O 5. Nbd2 d6 6. e4
{ In this chapter we are dealing with the King's Indian Defense. I recommend we use the underrated/unfamous line with 4. c3 followed by 5. Nbd2 & 6. e4! It is important to understand that we like to stay away from the standard e3 lines and instead we go for the direct e2-e4 push.   This chapter contains a pretty large number of trainables, but that is only because I literally covered all of Black's legal moves! The material will be split between:  •  6...Nc6   •  6...Nbd7   •  6...Nfd7   •  6...Bg4   •  6...c5   •  6...e5    Typical pawn structures arising from this chapter:   • The King's Indian Defense with the ...e5-break   • The King's Indian Defense with the ...c5-break    Model games arising from this chapter:   ➡ Berkes Ferenc-Ftacnik Lubomir, Batumi 2019   ➡ Kamsky Gata-Fedorowicz John, Los Angeles 1991 }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "11) King's Indian Defense"]
[Black "1...g6: Why I don't recommend 4.e3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 g6
{ This move is generally a hard counter for the Classical London if you are trying to play it the traditional way with e3. The good news is that if you are following the more aggressive plan with e4 ➼ we will get positions that are very similar to the main lines. }
2. Bf4 Bg7 3. Nf3 d6 4. e3
{ This is an example of the super annoying set-up that Black has against the most common lines with e3. }
4... Nd7 5. h3 e5 6. Bh2 Qe7 7. Be2 Nh6
{ With ...O-O and ...f5 Black gets good counterplay on the kingside. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "11) King's Indian Defense"]
[Black "1...g6 with 3...d6"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 g6
{ This move is generally a hard counter for the Classical London if you are trying to play it the traditional way with e3. The good news is that if you are following the more aggressive plan with e4 ➼ we will get positions that are very similar to the main lines. }
2. Bf4 Bg7 3. Nf3 d6 4. c3 { The best move order, preparing to push e4. } 4...
Nd7 5. e4
{ Setting up a strong pawn center. This is White's best way of playing against 1...g6. }
5... e5 6. dxe5 dxe5
{ 6...Nxe5  7.Nbd2⩲  with Be2-Qc2-short castle-Rfd1 ➼ we will most likely get back into the main lines. }
7. Be3 { The best square for the bishop after Black manages to push ...e5! }
7... Ngf6 { Hitting the e4-pawn. } 8. Qc2
{ Defending the e4-pawn. This is the most common square for the queen in this pawn structure. }
8... O-O
{ The most common move. Against  8...Ng4  White has an interesting idea to play  9.Bg5  f6  10.Bc1!?  ➼ and Black's g4-knight is lacking a good square after we push h3. }
9. h3 { This is a nice prophylactic move ➼ stopping ...Ng4! } 9... b6
{ Seems to be a slightly improved version for Black without having to play ...Re8. }
10. Nbd2 Bb7 11. Be2 { Preparing O-O. } 11... Qe7 12. O-O Nc5
{ This may seem very annoying at first, but I want you to remember the following forced sequence. }
13. Ng5
{ This is the key way to defend the e4-pawn because against  13...h6  we have the strong intermezzo with  14.b4! }
13... h6 14. b4 { The key idea behind 13.Ng5! } 14... Ncd7 15. Ngf3
{ We can advance on the queenside with a4-a5 while ...Nh5-Nf4 can always be answered with Rfe1-Bf1. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "11) King's Indian Defense"]
[Black "Old Indian Move Order"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4
{ This is the most flexible move order ➼ making sure that we keep everything in London System teritory. For more details about the move order make sure to check out the informational. }
2... d6 3. Nf3 Nbd7
{ The Old Indian move order. This will most likely transpose to the standard main lines if Black continues with ...g6-Bg7. There is one annoying sideline that we need to be familiar with, and that is 4...c5!? }
4. c3 c5
{ This is the only annoying line that Black can get from the super tricky move order with 2...d6 and 3...Nbd7. The point is to avoid the typical structure arising in the main line after 6...c5 7.dxc5! ➼ because if we are trying to transpose with  5.dxc5  Black has the aditional option of going  5...Nxc5!  I don't really expect you to encounter this move order because The Old Indian is usually connected with the ...e5-break, but even if you do, I think we have an easy fix. }
5. h3
{ Creating a square for the bishop on h2 because 5.Nbd2 would have allowed 5...Nh5 which would have been a little bit annoying. }
5... g6 6. Nbd2 { Preparing the standard e4-push. } 6... Bg7 7. e4
{ Going for similar positions to what we will see in the main lines. } 7...
cxd4 8. cxd4 O-O 9. Be2 { Preparing to castle short. } 9... b6 10. O-O Bb7 11.
Qb1
{ Because we have spent a tempo on 5.h3 we are not in time to defend the e4-pawn with Re1-Bf1 like in the main line with 6... Nbd7 & 7... c5, but this also works just fine! The queen on b1 will support the queenside play connected with a4-b4. }
11... Rc8 12. a4
{ With a slightly better position for White thanks to the solid center and ideas to push on the queenside with a5-b4. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "11) King's Indian Defense"]
[Black "KID: 3...c5"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4
{ This is the most flexible move order ➼ making sure that we keep everything in London System teritory. For more details about the move order make sure to check out the informational. }
2... g6
{ Going for the kingside fianchetto will generally lead to a more dynamic game. Black has a choice between two main openings: The King's Indian Defense The Grunfeld Defense. }
3. Nf3 c5
{ This is a better try for Black to get into the quick ...c5 lines @@StartBracket@@at least compared to 5...c5@@EndBracket@@. }
4. dxc5
{ The good news is that White can react in the typical way ➼ and keep a slight advantage. }
4... Qa5+
{ This is Black's best play ➼ winning back the pawn immediately.   If  4...Na6  , the move  5.Qd4!  makes it harder for Black to regain the pawn. For instance  5...Qa5+  6.Nc3  when  6...Nxc5  loses on the spot to  7.b4!  , so Black has to play  6...Qxc5  . Then with  7.e4!  we invite Black to trade on d4 because we are getting a better endgame thank to the enemy misplaced knight on a6.  7...Qxd4  8.Nxd4  Bg7  9.Ndb5!  Getting the Jobava-London knights! The b5-knight is much more active than the enemy a6-knight.  9...O-O  10.f3  This is a nice move to make, defending the e4-pawn and avoiding ...Ng4-ideas.  10...d6  11.O-O-O  Bd7  12.Be3⩲  We are most likely going to win the a7-pawn. The key trick that you want to watch out for is that  12...b6  runs into  13.Nxd6  and the enemy a6-knight drops at the end of the line. }
5. Nc3 Qxc5 6. e4
{ The key move to get the advantage. We are entering a better version of the Sicilian Defense because the enemy queen has lost a lot of time. }
6... d6 7. Qd2 { Preparing O-O-O! } 7... Bg7 8. Be3
{ Hitting the black queen. } 8... Qa5
{ This is an important move for Black because  8...Qc7  would allow  9.e5  dxe5  10.Nb5!  with a winning position for White. }
9. Nb5
{ This strong move forces a better endgame for White. Keep in mind that  9...Qd8  is not good in view of  10.e5! }
9... Qxd2+ 10. Nxd2
{ Securing the e4-pawn while keeping the double attack with Nxa7-Nc7+. } 10...
Na6 11. Nxa7
{ With an extra pawn for White. Black has to show some serious defense in order to get any counterplay. }
