[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4
{ This is the most flexible move order ➼ making sure that we keep everything in London System teritory. For more details about the move order make sure to check out the informational. }
2... g6
{ Going for the kingside fianchetto will generally lead to a more dynamic game. Black has a choice between two main openings: The King's Indian Defense The Grunfeld Defense. }
3. Nf3 b6
{ This is not a popular line for Black, but it could be a little bit annoying because if we are playing the standard 4.Nbd2 Black is in time with 4...Bb7 ➼ stopping our main ideas connnected with e4. }
4. Nc3
{ This is not a common move for the classical London System, but it works very well in this situational case. }
4... Bb7
{ 4...d5  is played with the idea to stop White's e4-sacrifice, but we can answer  5.Nb5  just playing an improved version of the Jobava London.  5...Na6  6.e3  Bg7  7.Ne5  Activating the knight and threatening to win a pawn with Nc6 and Nxa7!  7...Bb7  8.h4!  Threatening to push h5.  8...h5  9.Qf3  Preparing O-O-O.  9...c6  10.Nc3  Nc7  11.Bd3⩲  White can castle long and break with g4 ➼ with a big advantage. }
5. e4 { Because of this stunning idea ➼ White gets a big advantage. } 5... Nxe4
6. Nxe4 Bxe4 7. d5
{ The key move! Now Qd4 is a huge threat ➼ hitting the e4-bishop and the h8-rook. }
7... Bxf3 8. Qxf3 Bg7 9. O-O-O
{ White has a concrete threat of pushing d6, while h4-h5 remains a very viable plan to attack on the kingside. }
