[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "11) King's Indian Defense"]
[Black "KID: 5...Nh5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4
{ This is the most flexible move order ➼ making sure that we keep everything in London System teritory. For more details about the move order make sure to check out the informational. }
2... g6
{ Going for the kingside fianchetto will generally lead to a more dynamic game. Black has a choice between two main openings: The King's Indian Defense The Grunfeld Defense. }
3. Nf3 Bg7
{ 3...Nh5  is a super rare move for Black. We should reply  4.Be5!  ,  which I prefer over 4.Bg5 because we are forcing the ugly ...f6.  4...f6  5.Bg3  Now we are ready to push in the center with e4.  5...Nxg3  6.hxg3  Bg7  7.e4!  Setting up a strong pawn center.  7...d6  8.Nc3  Bg4  9.Qd2⩲  We can castle long with a dream position thanks to Black's weakened kingside. }
4. c3
{ This is a very underrated move! White is preparing to play Nbd2 followed by e4 if allowed @@StartBracket@@this is why we are not rushing to push e3 like in the most common lines@@EndBracket@@. }
4... d6
{ This will most likely transpose to the main lines, but Black has two additional options that are worth keeping in mind. }
5. Nbd2
{ Preparing the standard e4. If Black goes 5...O-O we will transpose back into the main lines, but they also have a choice between two interesting sidelines:  5...Nh5  5...Bf5. }
5... Nh5
{ I don't expect you to face this move very often, but Black can try to be annoying and harass our bishop. What you should avoid is to play the simple  6.Bg3  and allow Black to capture the precious London-bishop without any effort. This is the most common mistake I've seen my students make. }
6. Bg5
{ Threatening to push e4 in case Black doesn't follow up with the typical ...h6-g5! }
6... h6 7. Bh4
{ This is the point of having gone for the whole 6.Bg5 plan! If Black really wants to grab our bishop ➼ they have to overextend with ...g5 and create additional weaknesses. }
7... g5 8. Bg3 f5
{ 8...g4  is hyper aggressive ➼ but compromises the kingside in the long run. After  9.Nh4!  the knight looks awkward on the rim, but it will reach the f5-square after we push e4.  9...Bf6  10.e4⩲  With a better position for White. If Black plays  10...e5  11.Nf5!  is strong and  10...e6  can be met by  11.Qxg4!  with a winning position. }
9. e4
{ This is a very interesting piece sacrifice, but if you want to play something simpler, then  9.e3  might be the choice for you. }
9... f4 10. Bc4
{ This is a positional piece sacrifice that work very well because Black's king is caught in the center. }
10... fxg3
{ Let's check a few alternatives:   10...Nf6  11.e5  with big initiative already because the natural  11...Nfd7  runs into  12.Nh4!  with a winning attack thanks to the Qh5+ idea.   10...e6  11.Nh4!!  hits the h5-knight.  11...Nxg3  12.hxg3  gxh4  13.Qh5+  Ke7  14.gxf4  with easy play for White based on O-O-O followed by f5 ➼ opening up the center to attack Black's king. }
11. hxg3 Nf6 12. e5
{ This move is very annoying for Black because  12...dxe5  allows  13.Nxe5  with Nf7/Ng6 ideas. }
12... Ng4 13. Qc2 { Creating a huge threat of Qg6+. } 13... Kf8
{ The best move for Black, but not a fun one to play. } 14. Qe4
{ Stopping Black from pushing ...d5 and introducing Nxg5-ideas. } 14... Nc6 15.
Nb3
{ With Rd1 and Nxg5 ideas, White has very good compensation because the enemy king is vulnerable. }
*

