7... g5 8. Bg3 Nxg3
{ This is the most common move according to the online database. } 9. hxg3
{ I want you to pause for a bit and compare this position to the one arising after @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/ppp1ppbp/3p2p1/7n/3P1B2/2P2N2/PP1NPPPP/R2QKB1R w KQkq - 2 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Bg3  Nxg3  7.hxg3  .  It will become clear that it is much better for us to provoke ...h6-g5 before allowing the bishop to be exchanged, because now it will be much trickier for Black to castle short since the ...f5-h5 squares have been weakened. }
9... Nc6 { Preparing to push ...e5! } 10. e4
{ Following the standard strategy that we use in the main lines. } 10... e5 11.
d5
{ Even though  11.dxe5  is also interesting, I prefer  11.d5  because we are winning an important tempo. }
11... Ne7 12. Nc4
{ White has a simple plan. The c4-knight is heading towards e3 ➼ from where it controls the f5-square. The f3-knight will go to d2 and then Be2-Bg4 is a nice positional idea to trade off the light-squared bishops ➼ so we can exploit the enemy vulnerable light squares f5-h5. }
