{ I really like this move despite not being the engine's favorite. The computer is not a huge fan of it because Black has the cold blooded  6...O-O!  which should lead to an equal game with best play. However, I think most of your opponent will try to defend the b7-pawn with either ...Qc8 or ...b6. }
6... b6
{ 6...Qc8  7.Ng5!  hits the f7-pawn and preparing to advance in the center with e4!  7...O-O  8.e4!  Another advantage of 6.Qb3!? ➼ White can still get in the e4-push!  8...Bd7  9.h3!?  Not the only move, but a nice detail to stop ...Bg4/Ng4-ideas.  9...h6  10.Ngf3  Nc6  11.Be2  e5  12.dxe5  This move is very important ➼ otherwise Black will play ... exd4 and the e4-pawn will have to suffer.  12...dxe5  13.Be3⩲  We can castle short on the next move and then push on the queenside with a4 ➼ with a typical structure for the King's Indian. I think we just have an improved version because the enemy queen is awkwardly placed on c8.   6...O-O !  is best according to the computer, but I don't really expect a lot of people to find this move.  7.h3  Creating a square for the bishop on h2.  7...Nbd7  8.e3  c5  9.Be2  Qc7  10.O-O  ⩲  We can take space on the queenside with a4-a5 when White's position is a bit easier to play. Another typical plan is to go Rfe1-Bf1 with e4-ideas and the enemy f5-bishop is in trouble. }
7. e4
{ The key trick behind 6.Qb3! I guess this will take a lot of your opponents by surprise. }
7... Nxe4
{ Black's best try because  7...Bxe4  allows  8.Nxe4  Nxe4  9.Qd5  ➼ winning on the spot. }
8. Nxe4 Bxe4 9. Ng5
{ The point! The b3-queen is cooperating very well with the g5-knight ➼ hitting both the e4-bishop and the f7-pawn. }
9... d5 { The only move not to lose on the spot. } 10. Nxe4 dxe4 11. Bc4
{ Hitting the f7-pawn and threatening Bd5! } 11... e6 12. Qc2
{ Winning back the e4-pawn with a better position thanks to the bishop pair. }
*

[Event "?"]
