[White "11) King's Indian Defense"]
[Black "KID: 5...c5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4
{ This is the most flexible move order ➼ making sure that we keep everything in London System teritory. For more details about the move order make sure to check out the informational. }
2... g6
{ Going for the kingside fianchetto will generally lead to a more dynamic game. Black has a choice between two main openings: The King's Indian Defense The Grunfeld Defense. }
3. Nf3 Bg7
{ 3...Nh5  is a super rare move for Black. We should reply  4.Be5!  ,  which I prefer over 4.Bg5 because we are forcing the ugly ...f6.  4...f6  5.Bg3  Now we are ready to push in the center with e4.  5...Nxg3  6.hxg3  Bg7  7.e4!  Setting up a strong pawn center.  7...d6  8.Nc3  Bg4  9.Qd2⩲  We can castle long with a dream position thanks to Black's weakened kingside. }
4. c3
{ This is a very underrated move! White is preparing to play Nbd2 followed by e4 if allowed @@StartBracket@@this is why we are not rushing to push e3 like in the most common lines@@EndBracket@@. }
4... O-O 5. Nbd2
{ Threatening to grab space with e4. Black has a choice between:  5...d5 @@StartBracket@@The Grunfeld move@@EndBracket@@  5...d6 @@StartBracket@@The King's Indian move@@EndBracket@@. }
5... c5
{ The computer makes this line playable somehow, but it's very tricky to play ➼ from a human perspective. That is why I couldn't find any Grandmaster games with this move. }
6. dxc5
{ This is the issue with Black's play! It's important to remember  6.dxc5  because otherwise Black would love to play ...cxd4 and get an improved version of the Benoni.   Going  6.e4  is perhaps playable ➼ with chances to tranpose back into the Old Indian but you need to be aware of the fact that Black has additional ways to deviate such as  6...d5!?  After 6.dxc5 it's pretty tough to predict how the game could go since there are almost no games, but I will do my best to make an educated guess. }
6... Nc6
{ 6...b6!?  is a typical pawn sacrifice for the Grunfeld, but here I don't think it gives full compensation for the pawn.  7.cxb6  axb6  8.Qb3⩲  White can continue with simple moves such as e3-Be2-short castle while Black has to prove something for the sacrificed pawn. }
7. e4 { After this move, it's already hard for Black to do anything! } 7... b6
{ This has to be played, otherwise I don't see how Black is planning to develop. }
8. cxb6 Qxb6 { Hitting the b2-pawn. } 9. Nc4
{ Attacking the enemy queen while keeping the b2-pawn safe. } 9... Qc5 10. Nfd2
{ White can continue with the simple Be2 followed by O-O and then harass the enemy queen with Be3. }
*

