{ This is the most logical move ➼ trying to win back the pawn immediately with ...Nxc5.   6...a5  has the idea to stop White from pushing b4, but the next move should give White a large advantage:  7.e4!  This can come as a surprise to a lot of black players since they don't really expect to see e2-e4 very often in the London!  7...Na6  8.Bxa6!  This move works well to keep the extra pawn + White is getting quick development.  8...Rxa6  9.O-O  ±  White is simply up a pawn. }
7. Nb3
{ Making it a challenge for Black to regain the pawn. It's not going to be a simple task! }
7... b6 { This is probably the best try objectively. } 8. cxb6 Qxb6
{ Or  8...axb6  9.e3  Simply preparing Be2 and O-O.  9...Bb7  10.Be2  d6  11.O-O  ⩲  The computer says Black has decent compensation, but to me this should be a solid advantage for White in a practical game. }
9. Be3
{ This is the most precise because after the natural 9.e3 Black could get decent compensation based on 9.. .d6 followed by ...Nc5. }
9... Qc7 10. g3
{ It's not very often that we fianchetto in the London System, but it works very well here! }
10... Bb7 11. Bg2 { With an extra pawn for White and a solid position. } *

