6. e4 Nc6
{ This is the second most common square for the knight ➼ after ...Nbd7! Black is preparing to push ...e5 whithout blocking his own light-squared bishop. }
7. Be2
{ Developing the bishop on the standard square ➼ making the ...e5 pawn sacrifice less appealing for Black. Please keep in mind that the naive  7.d5  would give Black good counterplay after  7...e5! }
7... Nh5
{ By using this move order Black is trying to save a tempo from playing ...Re8 before delievering the ... e5-break. The rook will be better placed on f8 for the kingside play with ...f5 ➼ however, Black's counterplay remains very slow if countered correctly! }
8. Be3
{ The natural retreat. There is no reason to play Bg5 when we have the e3-square available. Bg5 is usually a good reaction against ...Ng4. }
8... e5 9. O-O
{ We have arrived at the main crossroads for the ...Nh5 plan. Black has a choice between:  9...h6 @@StartBracket@@preparing ...Qf6 & ...Nf4@@EndBracket@@  9...Nf4  9...f5. }
9... Nf4 10. Bxf4
{ This generally gives White a pleasant position when we have the solid center with c3 and d4. In the 6... Nbd7 main lines you will notice that the main theme to deal with the f4-knight is by playing around it with Re1 and Bf1  (see Kamsky-Shukh, 2020)  . The difference in those lines is that White has commited with dxe5 ➼ so Bxf4 would open up a lot of lines for Black's pieces. This is no longer the case when we have the solid center with c3-d4. }
10... exf4 11. Re1 g5
{ Greating a big threat of pushing ...g4 ➼ which can be easily stopped. } 12.
h3
{ As a general rule you don't want to push pawns on the side where your opponent is attacking ➼ but in our case it works really well. This move completely stops any attacking dreams that Black might have had because  12...h5  is always met by  13.Nh2!  and all of a sudden Black's pawns are very weak. }
12... h6 13. Bd3
{ White can take space on the queenside with a4, activate the knight with Nc4 and then we can even do something like Nh2 followed by Qh5 ➼ taking advantage of the overextended kingside. }
*

