{ This subtle move is played with the idea to have ...Qf6 without White being able to trap the queen with Bg5! The point is to then play ...Nf4 and in case of Bxf4 Black has ...Qxf4 with an unclear game. }
10. Re1
{ I find this to be the simplest set-up for White! The idea is fairly simple, we are preparing Bf1 and then we can start to play both in the center and on the queenside with ideas such as a4 & Nc4! }
10... Qf6 11. Bf1
{ The bishop is really well placed on f1 ➼ making the king feel very safe. }
11... Nf4 12. a4
{ This is the most common London System plan. When there is not an obvious continuation, we can push a4 ➼ creating a positional threat of pushing a5, grabbing a lot of space on the queenside. }
12... a5 13. Nc4
{ White has a very harmonious set-up! Next up, we can take over the initiative on the queenside by pushing d5 and then b4! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "11) King's Indian Defense"]
[Black "KID Mainline: 6...Nc6 #5"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4
{ This is the most flexible move order ➼ making sure that we keep everything in London System teritory. For more details about the move order make sure to check out the informational. }
2... g6
{ Going for the kingside fianchetto will generally lead to a more dynamic game. Black has a choice between two main openings: The King's Indian Defense The Grunfeld Defense. }
3. Nf3 Bg7
{ 3...Nh5  is a super rare move for Black. We should reply  4.Be5!  ,  which I prefer over 4.Bg5 because we are forcing the ugly ...f6.  4...f6  5.Bg3  Now we are ready to push in the center with e4.  5...Nxg3  6.hxg3  Bg7  7.e4!  Setting up a strong pawn center.  7...d6  8.Nc3  Bg4  9.Qd2⩲  We can castle long with a dream position thanks to Black's weakened kingside. }
4. c3
{ This is a very underrated move! White is preparing to play Nbd2 followed by e4 if allowed @@StartBracket@@this is why we are not rushing to push e3 like in the most common lines@@EndBracket@@. }
4... O-O 5. Nbd2
{ Threatening to grab space with e4. Black has a choice between:  5...d5 @@StartBracket@@The Grunfeld move@@EndBracket@@  5...d6 @@StartBracket@@The King's Indian move@@EndBracket@@. }
5... d6
{ This is the King's Indian move ➼ allowing White to expand in the center and then trying to create counterplay with the ...e5-break. This is way more popular than 5...d5, but we should be equally well prepared against both!   5...d5  stops White from pushing e4 ➼ this will be the choice of Grunfeld Defense players. }
6. e4 Nc6
{ This is the second most common square for the knight ➼ after ...Nbd7! Black is preparing to push ...e5 whithout blocking his own light-squared bishop. }
7. Be2
{ Developing the bishop on the standard square ➼ making the ...e5 pawn sacrifice less appealing for Black. Please keep in mind that the naive  7.d5  would give Black good counterplay after  7...e5! }
7... Bg4
{ This is a common sense developing move, but Black will have to give up the bishop for the knight which we are happy to see.   7...Nd7  This move prepares to push ...e5 followed by the typical ...f5 counterplay. The advantage compared to 7...Nh5 is that the d7-knight won't be vulnerable to the usual Nxe5-tactics. The problem is that White can take more space in the center with  8.d5!  (Now)   8...Nce5  is the only serious move because 8...Nb8 would have been way too slow.  9.Nxe5  Nxe5  10.Be3!  Preparing to kick the e5-knight with f4!  10...c6  11.O-O  ⩲  White can continue with f4 followed by Bf3 with a slightly better position thanks to the extra space. }
8. O-O Re8 { Preparing the standard ...e5-break! } 9. h3
{ Forcing Black to give up the bishop pair. } 9... Bxf3 10. Bxf3 e5 11. dxe5
{ This move is very important ➼ otherwise Black will play ...exd4 and the e4-pawn will have to suffer. }
11... dxe5
{ 11...Nxe5  12.Be2⩲  gives White a small edge thanks to the bishop pair. We will finish development with Qc2-Rad1 and then a potential plan is Bh2 followed by f4. }
12. Be3
{ With a steady edge for White thanks to the bishop pair followed by the typical London play on the queenside connected with a4. }
*

