[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4
{ This is the most flexible move order ➼ making sure that we keep everything in London System teritory. For more details about the move order make sure to check out the informational. }
2... g6
{ Going for the kingside fianchetto will generally lead to a more dynamic game. Black has a choice between two main openings: The King's Indian Defense The Grunfeld Defense. }
3. Nf3 Bg7
{ 3...Nh5  is a super rare move for Black. We should reply  4.Be5!  ,  which I prefer over 4.Bg5 because we are forcing the ugly ...f6.  4...f6  5.Bg3  Now we are ready to push in the center with e4.  5...Nxg3  6.hxg3  Bg7  7.e4!  Setting up a strong pawn center.  7...d6  8.Nc3  Bg4  9.Qd2⩲  We can castle long with a dream position thanks to Black's weakened kingside. }
4. c3
{ This is a very underrated move! White is preparing to play Nbd2 followed by e4 if allowed @@StartBracket@@this is why we are not rushing to push e3 like in the most common lines@@EndBracket@@. }
4... O-O 5. Nbd2
{ Threatening to grab space with e4. Black has a choice between:  5...d5 @@StartBracket@@The Grunfeld move@@EndBracket@@  5...d6 @@StartBracket@@The King's Indian move@@EndBracket@@. }
5... d6
{ This is the King's Indian move ➼ allowing White to expand in the center and then trying to create counterplay with the ...e5-break. This is way more popular than 5...d5, but we should be equally well prepared against both!   5...d5  stops White from pushing e4 ➼ this will be the choice of Grunfeld Defense players. }
6. e4 Nfd7
{ This plan is connected with an accelerated storm on the kingside after the typical ...e5 followed by ...f5!   The move  6...Bg4  generally gives us an easy game with the bishop pair. Now  7.Qc2!  is the most precise move because we are protecting the e4-pawn so that ...Bxf3 can be answered with Nxf3!  7...Nbd7  8.h3  Bxf3  9.Nxf3  e5!?  This is a clever pawn sacrifice because Black gets a lot of play in return. The good news is that we can simply avoid it.  10.dxe5!  This move is very important ➼ otherwise Black will play ...exd4 and the e4-pawn will have to suffer.  10...dxe5  11.Be3  The key retreating square. The bishop is really active on e3 while Black is unable to bother us with any ...Ng4 jumps thanks to the precise 8.h3!  11...c6  12.a4!  This is the most common London System plan. When there is not an obvious continuation, we can push a4 ➼ creating a positional threat of pushing a5, grabbing a lot of space on the queenside.  12...a5  13.Bc4⩲  With a long term initiative for White thanks to the bishop pair combined with the queenside play connected with the b4-push. }
7. h4
{ This is far from the only move for White, but I quite like it. The point is to exploit the fact that Black's knight is no longer on f6. This will most likely take your opponent by surprise since there are no games from this position, but I will try to provide you with a good overview of what Black is likely to play. I think there is a choice between:  7...e5  7... Nf6  7...h5  7...h6. }
7... e5 8. Bg5
{ Normally you'll see that the standard reaction to meet ...e5 is by going dxe5 followed by Be3, but the situation is a bit different after having commited to this aggressive h4-move. 8.Bg5! works better here because we are attacking Black's queen. }
8... Bf6
{ 8...f6  will only create additional weaknesses. Now  9.Bc4+!  forces Black's king in a mating net because the king on h8 will be vulnerable to h5-ideas. After  9...Kh8  10.Be3±  we are threatening to push h5 on the next move. White has a big advantage. }
9. Qc2 { Placing the queen on the standard square and preparing O-O-O. } 9...
Nc6 10. O-O-O
{ Black's pieces are stuck and we can slowly maneuver our knight via Nc4-Ne3-Nd5. }
*

