8. Nc4
{ Activating the knight and preparing to play Qd2 ➼ putting pressure on the h6-pawn. }
8... e5 9. dxe5 dxe5 10. Be3
{ Switching to positional play! We can safely castle short after Be2 and then the plan is to grab space on the queenside with the typical b4-a4 @@StartBracket@@If you are feeling aggressive in this position long castle is also doable@@EndBracket@@. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "11) King's Indian Defense"]
[Black "KID Mainline: 6...c5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4
{ This is the most flexible move order ➼ making sure that we keep everything in London System teritory. For more details about the move order make sure to check out the informational. }
2... g6
{ Going for the kingside fianchetto will generally lead to a more dynamic game. Black has a choice between two main openings: The King's Indian Defense The Grunfeld Defense. }
3. Nf3 Bg7
{ 3...Nh5  is a super rare move for Black. We should reply  4.Be5!  ,  which I prefer over 4.Bg5 because we are forcing the ugly ...f6.  4...f6  5.Bg3  Now we are ready to push in the center with e4.  5...Nxg3  6.hxg3  Bg7  7.e4!  Setting up a strong pawn center.  7...d6  8.Nc3  Bg4  9.Qd2⩲  We can castle long with a dream position thanks to Black's weakened kingside. }
4. c3
{ This is a very underrated move! White is preparing to play Nbd2 followed by e4 if allowed @@StartBracket@@this is why we are not rushing to push e3 like in the most common lines@@EndBracket@@. }
4... O-O 5. Nbd2
{ Threatening to grab space with e4. Black has a choice between:  5...d5 @@StartBracket@@The Grunfeld move@@EndBracket@@  5...d6 @@StartBracket@@The King's Indian move@@EndBracket@@. }
5... d6
{ This is the King's Indian move ➼ allowing White to expand in the center and then trying to create counterplay with the ...e5-break. This is way more popular than 5...d5, but we should be equally well prepared against both!   5...d5  stops White from pushing e4 ➼ this will be the choice of Grunfeld Defense players. }
6. e4 c5 7. dxc5
{ This move might seem a bit odd at first because why wouldn't we keep the pawn center?! In fact 7.Be2 is an alternative and we'll most likely transpose to my recommendation against the Old Indian. Now let's address of the elephant in the room! Why are the top grandmasters playing 7. dxc5! exclusively?There are a couple of reasons, but the funny one is that there is simply nothing better! Going 7.d5 would lead to a comfortable Benoni for Black and the simple 7.Be2 is interesting, but equal with correct play.Now that we have seen what the alternatives are, let's discuss about the pawn structure after 7.dxc5 dxc5 for a bit. Black's main issue is that it's not easy to find a good square for the queen. White can easily develop with Qc2-Be2-short castle-Rfd1 followed by a4-Nc4 with positional play on the queenside. At the same time it's much trickier for Black to organize their pieces. Throw in h3 at the right moment and it's even worse for them!Of course, this is only a very brief introduction, but for more details check out the 'King's Indian Pawn Structure'. }
7... dxc5 8. h3
{ This is by far the most annoying move to face for Black ➼ making it a nightmare for Black to develop the light-squared bishop because we are stopping ...Bg4-ideas. }
8... Nc6
{ 8...b6  would have been another way to play, but that will most likely transpose to  8...Nc6 & 9...b6! }
9. Qc2
{ While  9.Bb5  is a very interesting alternative, I decided to pick this move for the sake of simplicity. }
9... Re8
{ Preparing to push ...e5!   9...Be6?!  is an awkward square for the bishop, but it seems pretty common in online chess. We continue in standard fashion with  10.Be2  ,  preparing to castle.  10...h6  11.O-O  Qc8  12.Bh2!  This is always a nice move to throw in. The bishop is just better placed on h2 most of the time.  12...b6  13.Nh4⩲  Although you can play anything and have a slightly better position, this is the best way to punish the ...Be6 set-up. White is ready to push f4-f5 which will create a massive headache for Black on the kingside. }
10. Be2 { Getting ready to castle short. } 10... e5 11. Be3
{ Although Bh2 is playable, I like this better because we are gaining a tempo by attacking the c5-pawn. }
11... b6 12. Nc4
{ Threatening to play Rd1 follwed by Nd6 ➼ at the very least winning the bishop pair. }
12... Qc7 13. Rd1 { Threatening to win the bishop pair with Nd6-Nxc8! } 13...
Rd8 14. O-O Bb7 15. Bg5
{ Another key idea that you can use to exploit the d5 square is to trade the dark-squared bishop @@StartBracket@@a piece that can't directly fight for the d5-square because d5 is a light square@@EndBracket@@ for black's f6-knight @@StartBracket@@a key defender of the d5-square@@EndBracket@@. After this trade, Ne3-Nd5 becomes a huge threat. }
15... h6 16. Bh4
{ While  16.Bxf6  is perfectly fine, this move is even better ➼ keeping the pressure on the f6-knight while Ne3-Nd5 is coming on the next moves. }
*

