6. e4 c5 7. dxc5
{ This move might seem a bit odd at first because why wouldn't we keep the pawn center?! In fact 7.Be2 is an alternative and we'll most likely transpose to my recommendation against the Old Indian. Now let's address of the elephant in the room! Why are the top grandmasters playing 7. dxc5! exclusively?There are a couple of reasons, but the funny one is that there is simply nothing better! Going 7.d5 would lead to a comfortable Benoni for Black and the simple 7.Be2 is interesting, but equal with correct play.Now that we have seen what the alternatives are, let's discuss about the pawn structure after 7.dxc5 dxc5 for a bit. Black's main issue is that it's not easy to find a good square for the queen. White can easily develop with Qc2-Be2-short castle-Rfd1 followed by a4-Nc4 with positional play on the queenside. At the same time it's much trickier for Black to organize their pieces. Throw in h3 at the right moment and it's even worse for them!Of course, this is only a very brief introduction, but for more details check out the 'King's Indian Pawn Structure'. }
