{ 8...b6  would have been another way to play, but that will most likely transpose to  8...Nc6 & 9...b6! }
9. Qc2
{ While  9.Bb5  is a very interesting alternative, I decided to pick this move for the sake of simplicity. }
9... b6
{ This is Black's most common move ➼ trying to solve the issue of the light-squared bishop by placing it on b7.   9...a6  threatens to take space with ...b5, but after the strong move  10.a4⩲  we will get back to one of the other lines with a4-a6 included on the board which should favor White because the enemy queenside has been slightly weakened. }
10. Be2 Bb7 11. O-O
{ We have arrived at one of the main crossroads for the whole 6...c5 line. Black has a big choice, but none of the following moves seem particularly fun to play:  11...Nh5  11...Rc8  11...Re8  11...Qd7  11...Qc8. }
11... Qd7 12. Rad1
{ After this move Black can hide the queen on c8 after  12...Rad8  or perhaps on e8 after  12...Rfd8  . }
12... Rad8
{ This plan works better than  12...Rfd8  because Black is preparing ...Qc8 with additional ideas of ...Ba6.   12...Rfd8  13.Bh2  Qe8  14.Rfe1⩲  with a threat of e4-e5-e6. }
13. Rfe1 Nh5
{ This was seen in a pretty high profile game between Bu-Xu, 2017. } 14. Bh2
Bh6 { Preparing ...Nf4/Bf4 ideas. } 15. Ng5
{ Improving over the Bu Xianghzi game that went  15.Nc4  with a small edge. This cute tactical trick wins the important fianchetto bishop because Bxh5 is a huge threat. }
15... Bxg5 16. Nf3
{ We are going to collect the bishop on the next move with a significant strategical advantage thanks to the dark squared bishop ➼ the enemy king will be vulnerable. }
