{ Preparing to push ...e5!   11...Rc8?!  I added this silly move just to higlight Black's issue with the queen!  12.Rad1  Qe8  13.Rfe1⩲  This is a very uncomfortable position for Black where we can simply play Bf1-Bh2 and then use the typical pawn push with e5-e6 ➼ creating a huge mess in Black's camp. }
12. Bh2
{ This is a nice prophylactic move with or without ... e5 on the board. } 12...
e5 13. Rad1 Qc7 14. Nc4
{ With a solid positional advantage thanks to the weak square on d5. White has a simple plan because we can improve our position with Rfe1-Bf1 followed by Ne3-Nd5 ideas ➼ taking advantage of the juicy outpost. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "11) King's Indian Defense"]
[Black "KID Mainline: 6...c5 #7"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4
{ This is the most flexible move order ➼ making sure that we keep everything in London System teritory. For more details about the move order make sure to check out the informational. }
2... g6
{ Going for the kingside fianchetto will generally lead to a more dynamic game. Black has a choice between two main openings: The King's Indian Defense The Grunfeld Defense. }
3. Nf3 Bg7
{ 3...Nh5  is a super rare move for Black. We should reply  4.Be5!  ,  which I prefer over 4.Bg5 because we are forcing the ugly ...f6.  4...f6  5.Bg3  Now we are ready to push in the center with e4.  5...Nxg3  6.hxg3  Bg7  7.e4!  Setting up a strong pawn center.  7...d6  8.Nc3  Bg4  9.Qd2⩲  We can castle long with a dream position thanks to Black's weakened kingside. }
4. c3
{ This is a very underrated move! White is preparing to play Nbd2 followed by e4 if allowed @@StartBracket@@this is why we are not rushing to push e3 like in the most common lines@@EndBracket@@. }
4... O-O 5. Nbd2
{ Threatening to grab space with e4. Black has a choice between:  5...d5 @@StartBracket@@The Grunfeld move@@EndBracket@@  5...d6 @@StartBracket@@The King's Indian move@@EndBracket@@. }
5... d6
{ This is the King's Indian move ➼ allowing White to expand in the center and then trying to create counterplay with the ...e5-break. This is way more popular than 5...d5, but we should be equally well prepared against both!   5...d5  stops White from pushing e4 ➼ this will be the choice of Grunfeld Defense players. }
6. e4 c5 7. dxc5
{ This move might seem a bit odd at first because why wouldn't we keep the pawn center?! In fact 7.Be2 is an alternative and we'll most likely transpose to my recommendation against the Old Indian. Now let's address of the elephant in the room! Why are the top grandmasters playing 7. dxc5! exclusively?There are a couple of reasons, but the funny one is that there is simply nothing better! Going 7.d5 would lead to a comfortable Benoni for Black and the simple 7.Be2 is interesting, but equal with correct play.Now that we have seen what the alternatives are, let's discuss about the pawn structure after 7.dxc5 dxc5 for a bit. Black's main issue is that it's not easy to find a good square for the queen. White can easily develop with Qc2-Be2-short castle-Rfd1 followed by a4-Nc4 with positional play on the queenside. At the same time it's much trickier for Black to organize their pieces. Throw in h3 at the right moment and it's even worse for them!Of course, this is only a very brief introduction, but for more details check out the 'King's Indian Pawn Structure'. }
7... dxc5 8. h3
{ This is by far the most annoying move to face for Black ➼ making it a nightmare for Black to develop the light-squared bishop because we are stopping ...Bg4-ideas. }
8... Nc6
{ 8...b6  would have been another way to play, but that will most likely transpose to  8...Nc6 & 9...b6! }
9. Qc2
{ While  9.Bb5  is a very interesting alternative, I decided to pick this move for the sake of simplicity. }
9... b6
{ This is Black's most common move ➼ trying to solve the issue of the light-squared bishop by placing it on b7.   9...a6  threatens to take space with ...b5, but after the strong move  10.a4⩲  we will get back to one of the other lines with a4-a6 included on the board which should favor White because the enemy queenside has been slightly weakened. }
10. Be2 Bb7 11. O-O
{ We have arrived at one of the main crossroads for the whole 6...c5 line. Black has a big choice, but none of the following moves seem particularly fun to play:  11...Nh5  11...Rc8  11...Re8  11...Qd7  11...Qc8. }
11... Qc8
{ The point of this move is to trade off the light squared bishops with ...Ba6 and then the queen will have a reasonable square on b7.   11...Nh5  is another common move for Black ➼ preparing ...e5 followed by ...Nf4!  12.Bh2  e5  13.Rfe1!   We prefer this over 13.Rad1 so we can meet  13...Nf4  with  14.Bf1!  13...Qe7  14.Nc4!  The knight is usually going to maneuver via Ne3-Nd5. Once we get there in good conditions ➼ White has a winning position from a strategical point of view.  14...Nf4  Creating a big positional threat of ...Nxe2!  15.Bf1!  The key reaction to ...Nf4 as seen in the ...e5 main lines.  15...Rad8  16.Rad1  h6  17.Qc1!  Threatening to take on f4 twice and win a pawn ➼ forcing Black to make an ugly move.  17...g5  18.Ne3⩲  With Nd5/Nf5 ideas ➼ White has a solid positional advantage. }
12. Rad1 Rd8 13. Bh2
{ Always a nice prophylactic move, waiting to see what Black is up to while introducing e5-e6 ideas in the position. }
13... Ba6 14. Nc4
{ If Black wants to get rid of the light-squared bishop, he'd better give us the bishop pair! We can push e5 on the next move with an easy game. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "11) King's Indian Defense"]
[Black "KID Mainline: 6...Nbd7 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4
{ This is the most flexible move order ➼ making sure that we keep everything in London System teritory. For more details about the move order make sure to check out the informational. }
2... g6
{ Going for the kingside fianchetto will generally lead to a more dynamic game. Black has a choice between two main openings: The King's Indian Defense The Grunfeld Defense. }
3. Nf3 Bg7
{ 3...Nh5  is a super rare move for Black. We should reply  4.Be5!  ,  which I prefer over 4.Bg5 because we are forcing the ugly ...f6.  4...f6  5.Bg3  Now we are ready to push in the center with e4.  5...Nxg3  6.hxg3  Bg7  7.e4!  Setting up a strong pawn center.  7...d6  8.Nc3  Bg4  9.Qd2⩲  We can castle long with a dream position thanks to Black's weakened kingside. }
4. c3
{ This is a very underrated move! White is preparing to play Nbd2 followed by e4 if allowed @@StartBracket@@this is why we are not rushing to push e3 like in the most common lines@@EndBracket@@. }
4... O-O 5. Nbd2
{ Threatening to grab space with e4. Black has a choice between:  5...d5 @@StartBracket@@The Grunfeld move@@EndBracket@@  5...d6 @@StartBracket@@The King's Indian move@@EndBracket@@. }
5... d6
{ This is the King's Indian move ➼ allowing White to expand in the center and then trying to create counterplay with the ...e5-break. This is way more popular than 5...d5, but we should be equally well prepared against both!   5...d5  stops White from pushing e4 ➼ this will be the choice of Grunfeld Defense players. }
6. e4 Nbd7
{ This is the most common move for Black ➼ preparing the typical ... e5-break! Black's light-squared bishop is blocked by the knight, but this is not the biggest issue since it was lacking a good square on the c8-h3 diagonal. Black will most likely develop the light-squared bishop with ...b6-Bb7 or simply delay it's development and focus on the kingside play with ...e5 followed by ...Nh5-Nf4.   The immediate  6...e5  is never played, but the ...e5 advance is always a question. To me, Black doesn't get full compensation for the pawn.  7.dxe5  dxe5  8.Bxe5  Re8  Black's whole counterplay is based on the e4-pawn.  9.Bc4!  The most precise way to develop. This way Black is unable to win back the pawn.  9...Nbd7  10.Bxf6!  Keeping the tempo up so we can finish development fast and ➼ protect the e4-pawn.  10...Nxf6  11.O-O  ⩲  White is simply up a pawn, but I want you to remember the following tactical trick in case Black takes on e4:  11...Nxe4??  allowing a classical motif.  12.Nxe4  Qxd1  13.Raxd1  Rxe4  14.Bxf7+!  +-  The punchline! Black is unable to play  14...Kxf7  in view of  15.Ng5+! }
7. Be2 b6
{ Although recommended by Gawain Jones in his gorgeous Lifetime Repertoire on the King's Indian, the double fianchetto seems to be a relatively rare choice among the average Black players. This move leads to complex positions that are full of life with chances for both sides. My general feeling is that the player with more experience in this structure should generally triumph @@StartBracket@@despite engine showing 0.00 everywhere@@EndBracket@@. }
8. O-O Bb7 9. Qc2 { Defending the e4-pawn. } 9... e5
{ This is a common pawn sacrifice for Black and I think we should decline the 'kind' offer. }
10. Bg5
{ Keeping the tension is way better than greeding out with double captures on e5, because that would have allowed a lot of simplifications ➼ leading to a draw. }
10... h6 11. Bh4
{ Keeping the tension! We never take on f6 ➼ unless there is some concrete reward in return. }
11... Qe8
{ Sidestepping the pin and preparing ...Nh5!   11...exd4!?  12.cxd4  Re8  13.Bd3  Protecting the e4-pawn.  13...Rc8  14.b3!  This is an important move because Black was threatening to push ...c5 followed by the pawn sacrifice with ...c4! ➼ using the pin along the c-file.  14...c5  15.d5!  Keeping a strong center and limiting Black's b7-bishop.  15...g5  16.Bg3  Nh5  17.Rad1  The rook is quite well placed on this square because we keep the e1-square for the f1-rook.  17...Nxg3  18.hxg3⩲  We can continue Rfe1 followed by Nc4-Ne3-Nf5 and White is slightly better. }
12. Rfe1
{ This is always a nice move ➼ lining up against the enemy queen. By placing the rook on e1, the e4-pawn feels much safer. }
12... Nh5 13. Rad1
{ You can't really go wrong playing only natural moves! The rooks are nicely placed in the center ➼ getting ready to meet Black's kingside assault. }
13... Kh8
{ This is another typical move for the King's Indian ➼ Black's king feels a bit safer in the corner when preparing to push ...f5! }
14. dxe5
{ This is not the only way of playing, but I am a big fan of entering this pawn structure. To me it feels like Black's counterplay is slowing down dramatically & they have to be very careful with the hanging pawns after pushing ...f5! }
14... dxe5 15. Nc4
{ The knight is well placed on this square + we can go Ne3-Nd5! } 15... Nc5 16.
Nfd2 { Defending the e4-pawn + attacking the enemy h5-knight. } 16... Nf4
{ This is an improvement over the Papaioannou-Giri game, played in Batumi 2019.   16...Bf6  was Anish's choice, but White seems to have a comfortable position after  17.Bxf6+  Nxf6  18.f3!  This is a very nice solid move, defending the e4-pawn while also killing the b7-bishop.  18...Kg7  19.b4⩲  Black's attack has not even started yet, while White is pushing on the queenside with a4-a5 and Ne3-Bc4-Nd5 ideas. }
17. Bf1
{ Of course, we keep the bishop which plays a nice defensive role on the kingside + it can also be a very useful piece after we start our queenside play. Generally I am not a huge fan of super deep lines, but in order to get more familiar with this structure, we are going to have a look on Black's main attacking plans:  17...g5  17...f5 @@StartBracket@@recommended by Gawain@@EndBracket@@. }
17... f5
{ Here is where Gawain stops in his course claiming that Black has a good attack. I think that could be very much the case if White has a bad reaction, but first, let's make some forced moves and discuss the position on move 20.   17...g5  18.Bg3  h5  with the idea to push ...h4.  19.Nf3!  This move works best ➼ hitting the g5-pawn.  19...f6  20.Bxf4!  This is a strong move because we are getting rid of Black's most annoying piece + we get a good square for our knight no matter what Black recaptures with.  20...gxf4  21.Nh4⩲  With a clear edge for White because the knight reaches the f5-square. Additionally we can kick the enemy c5-knight with b4, maneuver Nd2-Nf3 and activate the light squared bishop with Bc4!   Or  20...exf4  21.Nd4⩲  when the e4-pawn is untouchable because of the pin along the e-file, and we are ready to kick the enemy knight with b4 followed by jumping on the weak f5-square with the knight. }
18. exf5
{ This move simply has to be played. It opens up the e1-rook and the e5-pawn feels vulnerable. }
18... gxf5
{ This is always the standard reaction. Taking with a piece would generally give White the e4-square and Black is just worse strategically speaking. }
19. Bg3 { Forcing the knight to step back because Bxf4 is a huge threat. }
19... Ng6 20. f3
{ This is a super useful move ➼ restricting the b7-bishop and keeping the hanging pawns  @@StartBracket@@e5 & f5@@EndBracket@@ under control. This is a good time to pause and discuss the position. We have a very common situation for the King's Indian because Black has delievered the typical ...f5-break and now what's next?The hanging pawns  @@StartBracket@@e5 & f5@@EndBracket@@ are looking quite nice ➼ controlling a lot of central squares. The big downside of them is that pushing any of the pawns creates juicy squares for White's pieces. They are not only very tricky to advance, but White can use simple moves such as b4 ➼ getting rid of the c5-knight, followed by Bd3 ➼ with pressure on f5.Objectively speaking, the position is dynamically balanced, but to me it looks much easier to attack the hanging pawns as White, rather than delivering checkmate as Black. We only need one mistake from Black, and the position could easily be compromised, while White seems to have more options generally when dealing with Black's threats. }
