[Black "KID Mainline: 6...Nbd7 #4"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4
{ This is the most flexible move order ➼ making sure that we keep everything in London System teritory. For more details about the move order make sure to check out the informational. }
2... g6
{ Going for the kingside fianchetto will generally lead to a more dynamic game. Black has a choice between two main openings: The King's Indian Defense The Grunfeld Defense. }
3. Nf3 Bg7
{ 3...Nh5  is a super rare move for Black. We should reply  4.Be5!  ,  which I prefer over 4.Bg5 because we are forcing the ugly ...f6.  4...f6  5.Bg3  Now we are ready to push in the center with e4.  5...Nxg3  6.hxg3  Bg7  7.e4!  Setting up a strong pawn center.  7...d6  8.Nc3  Bg4  9.Qd2⩲  We can castle long with a dream position thanks to Black's weakened kingside. }
4. c3
{ This is a very underrated move! White is preparing to play Nbd2 followed by e4 if allowed @@StartBracket@@this is why we are not rushing to push e3 like in the most common lines@@EndBracket@@. }
4... O-O 5. Nbd2
{ Threatening to grab space with e4. Black has a choice between:  5...d5 @@StartBracket@@The Grunfeld move@@EndBracket@@  5...d6 @@StartBracket@@The King's Indian move@@EndBracket@@. }
5... d6
{ This is the King's Indian move ➼ allowing White to expand in the center and then trying to create counterplay with the ...e5-break. This is way more popular than 5...d5, but we should be equally well prepared against both!   5...d5  stops White from pushing e4 ➼ this will be the choice of Grunfeld Defense players. }
6. e4 Nbd7
{ This is the most common move for Black ➼ preparing the typical ... e5-break! Black's light-squared bishop is blocked by the knight, but this is not the biggest issue since it was lacking a good square on the c8-h3 diagonal. Black will most likely develop the light-squared bishop with ...b6-Bb7 or simply delay it's development and focus on the kingside play with ...e5 followed by ...Nh5-Nf4.   The immediate  6...e5  is never played, but the ...e5 advance is always a question. To me, Black doesn't get full compensation for the pawn.  7.dxe5  dxe5  8.Bxe5  Re8  Black's whole counterplay is based on the e4-pawn.  9.Bc4!  The most precise way to develop. This way Black is unable to win back the pawn.  9...Nbd7  10.Bxf6!  Keeping the tempo up so we can finish development fast and ➼ protect the e4-pawn.  10...Nxf6  11.O-O  ⩲  White is simply up a pawn, but I want you to remember the following tactical trick in case Black takes on e4:  11...Nxe4??  allowing a classical motif.  12.Nxe4  Qxd1  13.Raxd1  Rxe4  14.Bxf7+!  +-  The punchline! Black is unable to play  14...Kxf7  in view of  15.Ng5+! }
7. Be2 Nh5
{ The difference compared to the 6...Nh5 line is that White has already committed to Be2 and we can no longer get Bc4 in one go, but it shouldn't be a huge problem as seen in Demchenko's games. }
8. Be3
{ The natural retreat. There is no reason to play Bg5 when we have the e3-square available. Bg5 is usually a good reaction against ...Ng4 instead. }
8... e5
{ This has to be played, otherwise there is not much point behind having played ... Nh5. }
9. O-O Nf4
{ This is the main idea of ...Nh5. If Black plays a waiting move such as 9...h6, White has an easy set-up with Qc2, Rfe1-Rad1, Bf1 followed by dxe5 and Nc4 as we have seen in the Papaioannou-Giri model game. }
10. Bxf4
{ This simple capture works well because Black is struggling to push the kingside pawns while White has a solid center. The main issue for Black is that ...g5 generally can be met by h3 and ...h5 will often run into Nh2! ➼ and Black's pawns are weak. }
10... exf4 11. Re1 Re8
{ 11...g5  does not achieve much, as after  12.h3⩲  Black is unable to push the desired ...h5 because of Nh2! and White can push on the queenside with a4-a5 and Bc4 ideas. }
12. a4
{ The typical London move, grabbing space and forcing Black to act accordingly. }
12... a5 13. h3 Nf6 14. Bc4
