7. Be2 c6
{ This move is occasionally seen in online chess, but it doesn't seem to change much, and the general ideas will apply the same. }
8. O-O Re8 { Preparing to push ...e5! } 9. h3
{ This is a nice prophylactic move in our structure. White is preparing to meet  9...e5  with  10.dxe5  dxe5  11.Be3!  ➼ and thanks to our h3-pawn, Black does not have any annoying ...Ng4 ideas. }
9... e5 10. dxe5 Nxe5
{ My general feeling is that trading a pair of minor pieces should help Black in this structure ➼ due to the lack of space, but this doesn't mean that all of Black's issues are gone. }
11. Nxe5 dxe5 12. Be3
{ We have a symmetrical pawn structure, but White has the initiative because of the small lead in development, and we are simply quicker with the queenside play. Black does not have any attack like they would normally love to, plus the difference between the dark-squared bishops will be felt more and more, after White makes some progress on the queenside. }
12... Be6 13. a4
{ White is already winning important space on the queenside because the standard  13...a5  would run into  14.Qc2  followed by Nc4 and Black has issues with the b6-square. }
13... Qc7 14. a5 { Always grabbing more space when allowed. } 14... Bf8
{ Trying to resuscitate the dark-squared bishop, but it's still a bit passive. }
15. Qc2 Nd7 16. b4
{ With a risk-free advantage for White. A cool idea that you want to keep in mind is that we want to play Bc4 ➼ trading Black's most active piece, followed by Nc4 and then we can simply double up on the d-file. Once this is achieved Nd6 will become a very unpleasant threat to deal with. Caruana,F @@StartBracket@@2811@@EndBracket@@-Gabuzyan,H @@StartBracket@@2571@@EndBracket@@ Chess.com INT 2018 }
