11. O-O Nf4 { With the positional threat of ...Nxe2! } 12. Bc4
{ This move is important, keeping the light-squared bishop alive while preparing to kick the annoying enemy knight from f4. Going for the pragmatic  12.Bxf4  is not a good idea because after  12...exf4  Black has pressure on the e4-pawn. Bxf4 is usually only a good way to deal with ...Nf4 when there are still pawns on d4 and d6. }
12... Qf6 13. g3
{ This is a cool idea that I want you to remember. We can usually sacrifice the h3-pawn ➼ because ...Nxh3 will result in positions where Black is struggling to rescue the knight. }
13... Ne6
{ This is usually how the journey to f4 ends. Black has too many pieces and too little space.   13...Nxh3+?!  would be too risky. After  14.Kg2⩲  White can claim a better position after some crazy complications. I won't go deeper with the line because I want to keep it simpler, and easier to understand. We can just say that the h3-knight is very loose and we can use Rh1-ideas to target it. }
14. a4 { Time to use the typical idea ➼ threatening to expand with a5. } 14...
a5 15. Kg2
{ White can continue with Qc2 followed by Rfd1 with an easier position to play. }
