6. e4 Nbd7
{ This is the most common move for Black ➼ preparing the typical ... e5-break! Black's light-squared bishop is blocked by the knight, but this is not the biggest issue since it was lacking a good square on the c8-h3 diagonal. Black will most likely develop the light-squared bishop with ...b6-Bb7 or simply delay it's development and focus on the kingside play with ...e5 followed by ...Nh5-Nf4.   The immediate  6...e5  is never played, but the ...e5 advance is always a question. To me, Black doesn't get full compensation for the pawn.  7.dxe5  dxe5  8.Bxe5  Re8  Black's whole counterplay is based on the e4-pawn.  9.Bc4!  The most precise way to develop. This way Black is unable to win back the pawn.  9...Nbd7  10.Bxf6!  Keeping the tempo up so we can finish development fast and ➼ protect the e4-pawn.  10...Nxf6  11.O-O  ⩲  White is simply up a pawn, but I want you to remember the following tactical trick in case Black takes on e4:  11...Nxe4??  allowing a classical motif.  12.Nxe4  Qxd1  13.Raxd1  Rxe4  14.Bxf7+!  +-  The punchline! Black is unable to play  14...Kxf7  in view of  15.Ng5+! }
7. Be2 Re8
{ This is the most common move for Black ➼ preparing the ...e5-break. } 8. h3
{ This is the key reaction that I want you to remember against Black's main idea. Here is the trick to easily memorize it! When ...e5 is played, you want to answer it by playing dxe5 followed by Be3 @@StartBracket@@asuming they take back on e5 with the pawn@@EndBracket@@. That will lead to the main pawn structure for our variation which is explained in the 'Typical Pawn Structures' chapter. }
8... e5
{ The logical follow up after having played ...Re8! Other moves simply don't make much sense. }
9. dxe5
{ This move is very important ➼ otherwise Black will play ...exd4 and the e4-pawn will have to suffer. }
9... dxe5
{ Both  9...dxe5  and  9...Nxe5  are equally good. According to the online database, taking back with the pawn seems to be more frequent, and I am guessing you will get it in 3/4 of your games. }
10. Be3
{ The key retreating square. The bishop is really active on e3 while Black is unable to bother us with any ...Ng4 jumps thanks to the precise 8.h3! }
10... Qe7
{ This is the most flexible square for Black's queen. From e7, the queen is preparing ...Nc5 in some positions, or simply to go ...b6-Bb7 and finish development.   10...c6  might transpose into the 10... Qe7 line, but I want to show how the game could go if Black plays ... Qc7 as in the Demchenko-Murzin games.  11.O-O  Qc7  The queen doesn't seem to have dramatically improved it's position, so I recommend we continue in the same fashion as against ...Qe7:  12.a4!  Threatening to grab more space with a5.  12...Bf8!?  This little idea could be the major diference between ...Qc7 and ...Qe7 that you want to keep in mind. Black is trying to trade off the bad bishop with ... Bc5 on the next move. The good news is that we can avoid this trade, and White should keep a significant advantage.  13.a5!  Grabbing space as we can meet ...Bc5 with Bg5!   Playing  13.b4  is also an option, but Black could respond with the annoying  13...a5!?  13...Bc5  14.Bg5!  Simply avoiding the trade, while b4 becomes a huge threat ➼ gaining more space on the queenside with tempo.  14...Nh5  15.b4  Be7  16.Be3⩲  After this simple move White keeps a large advantage. Strangely enough Demchenko played  16.Re1  which made Black's position a bit easier to play. My guess is that he was perhaps worried about  16.Be3  Nf4  but we can simply play  17.Bc4!  followed by Qb3 and Rfd1 ➼ playing around the f4-knight. }
11. O-O
{ The simplest ➼ going for a positional game. If you want to experiment a bit, you can follow Demchenko's flexible approach of going  11.Qc2  c6  12.a4  Nh5  13.g3!?  with a lot of room for creativity. The computer recommends long castle in a lot of variations after using Demchenko's plan, but personally I think that is a bit too complex, and not really in the spirit of our repertoire. }
11... c6
{ This is a typical move for the King's Indian player ➼ controlling the d5-square and potentially pushing ...b5 in some variations if White allows it.   11...b6  is another sensible choice for Black ➼ going for harmonious development.  12.Qc2  The queen always stays on c2 in this structure.  12...Bb7  13.a4  Threatening a5.  13...a5  14.b4⩲  I suggest you try out this interesting pawn sacrifice. I think White definitely has a lot of interesting play after  14...axb4  15.cxb4  Qxb4  16.Qxc7!  However, if you prefer something simpler ➼ you can start with  14.Rfb1  and the trick is to meet  14...Nc5  with  15.Ng5  h6  16.b4!  Ncd7  17.Ngf3  with a small edge for White. }
12. a4
{ This is the most common London System plan. When there is not an obvious continuation, we can push a4 ➼ creating a positional threat of pushing a5, grabbing a lot of space on the queenside. }
12... a5
{ Stopping White from advancing, but slightly weakening the b6-square. } 13.
Qc2
{ The queen is always placed on this square in our structure. From c2, the queen is protecting the e4-pawn ➼ making Nc4 a possible threat that Black needs to watch out for. }
13... Nh5
{ Preparing to play ...Nf4 ➼ this is Black's only shot to active counterplay since the typical ...f5-break seems very tough to achieve. }
14. Rfe1
{ This is an amazing prophylactic move ➼ preparing to meet ...Nf4 with Bf1! }
14... Nf4 15. Bf1
{ This is the key move to a significant advantage. We can simply play around the f4-knight as Black does not have enough pieces on the kingisde to create any realistic problems for us. The f1-bishop is playing a very nice role in defending the kingside while also keeping an eye on the queenside.   Last but not least, I need to mention that  15.Bxf4  exf4  would have given Black very good counterplay and I want you to remember that ...Nh5-Nf4 can be met by Bxf4 only if we have the pawn center with d4-d6 included. Remember that after committing with dxe5 ➼ the key idea is to play around the f4-knight. }
15... Nc5
{ This was tried by an international master, but Black soon ran into problems. }
16. Nc4
{ With a large advantage for White. Nb6 is a very annoying idea that Black has to watch out for, but even more effective might be the tactical trick connected with Nxa5!  @@StartBracket@@idea to play b4 after ...Rxa5@@EndBracket@@. White had a comfortable victory in: Kamsky,G @@StartBracket@@2674@@EndBracket@@-Shukh,N @@StartBracket@@2467@@EndBracket@@ Chess.com INT 2020 }
*

