[White "12) Grünfeld Defense"]
[Black "Introduction"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 g6 3. Bf4 Bg7 4. c3 O-O 5. Nbd2 d5 6. e3
{ In this chapter we are dealing with the Grunfeld Defense. The difference compared to the King's Indian Defense is that Black is no longer allowing us to grab the center with e4. The material will be split between:  •  6...Nh5   •  6...Nc6   •  6...Nbd7   •  6...Bf5   •  6...b6   •  6...c5 }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "12) Grünfeld Defense"]
[Black "Grunfeld: 6...Nh5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4
{ This is the most flexible move order ➼ making sure that we keep everything in London System teritory. For more details about the move order make sure to check out the informational. }
2... g6 3. Nf3 Bg7 4. c3 O-O 5. Nbd2 d5 6. e3
{ While many players have preferred  6.h3  ➼ countering ...Nh5,  I recommend that we stick with  6.e3  for the following reasons:  6...Nh5 ➼ is not such a bad counter in this version  6...c5 ➼ is the most common move ➼ allowing 7. dxc5!  against 6...Nbd7 & 6...b6 we can use h4-ideas to speed up the kingside play.Now it's Black's turn to make an important decision between:  6...Nh5 @@StartBracket@@rare, but critical@@EndBracket@@  6...Nbd7 @@StartBracket@@very popular@@EndBracket@@  6...Bf5 @@StartBracket@@a bit rare@@EndBracket@@  6...b6 @@StartBracket@@similar to 6...Nbd7@@EndBracket@@  6...c5 @@StartBracket@@most popular in online by far@@EndBracket@@  6...Nc6 @@StartBracket@@rare@@EndBracket@@. }
6... Nh5
{ This is the biggest question that we need to answer before playing 6. e3! }
7. Bg5
{ This move works best because the alternative gives Black an easy game after  7.Be5  f6  8.Bg3  e5!  with good counterplay. }
7... h6
{ 7...f6  is played with the same idea to harass the bishop, but it's much worse compared to 7... h6 because of  8.Bh4  g5  9.Bd3!  Thanks to this precise move, White has a big advantage. Now White has a HUGE threat of playing Nxg5 followed by Qxh5.  9...gxh4  10.Nxh4  Targeting the h5-knight.  10...Qe8  11.Be2±  It's pretty funny that the h5-knight gets trapped and White has a completely winning position. }
8. Bh4 Nd7 { Played with the idea to control the e5-square. } 9. Bd3
{ I think this might be the best practical chance. At first I was investigating  9.g4  Nhf6  10.h3  with the simple plan of going Qc2-long castle followed by Ne5-f4, but there is no need for that! With 9.Bd3 we are setting up a deadly trap, and in case Black avoids it ➼ we get a slightly improved version of the 'normal' lines because the h5-knight is misplaced. }
9... g5
{ This is a huge mistake. It is better for Black to play something like  9...c5  and after  10.O-O  White only has a slightly easier position to play with typical ideas such a4-a5 and Re1-e4. }
10. Nxg5
{ I was able to find a relatively large number of games allowing this trick @@StartBracket@@from a pretty small sample of games@@EndBracket@@! }
10... hxg5 11. Qxh5
{ White is winning the g5-pawn thanks to the mating threat on h7. } *

