[Black "Grunfeld: 6...Bf5"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4
{ This is the most flexible move order ➼ making sure that we keep everything in London System teritory. For more details about the move order make sure to check out the informational. }
2... g6 3. Nf3 Bg7 4. c3 O-O 5. Nbd2 d5 6. e3
{ While many players have preferred  6.h3  ➼ countering ...Nh5,  I recommend that we stick with  6.e3  for the following reasons:  6...Nh5 ➼ is not such a bad counter in this version  6...c5 ➼ is the most common move ➼ allowing 7. dxc5!  against 6...Nbd7 & 6...b6 we can use h4-ideas to speed up the kingside play.Now it's Black's turn to make an important decision between:  6...Nh5 @@StartBracket@@rare, but critical@@EndBracket@@  6...Nbd7 @@StartBracket@@very popular@@EndBracket@@  6...Bf5 @@StartBracket@@a bit rare@@EndBracket@@  6...b6 @@StartBracket@@similar to 6...Nbd7@@EndBracket@@  6...c5 @@StartBracket@@most popular in online by far@@EndBracket@@  6...Nc6 @@StartBracket@@rare@@EndBracket@@. }
6... Bf5
{ This is not very common for Black because the bishop does not belong on f5. I wasn't able to find a single game played by a GM with this move and the reason is pretty simple as you will see in the following lines ➼ the f5-bishop is a bit vulnerable. }
7. Be2 Nbd7
{ Creating a threat of ...Nh5! Keep in mind that  7...Nh5  could have been met by the following typical reaction:  8.Bg5  h6  9.Bh4  g5  10.g4!  Bxg4  11.Nxg5!  Bxe2  12.Qxe2  hxg5  13.Qxh5  gxh4  14.Rg1  with a deadly attack for White. }
8. h3
{ Creating a square for the bishop and introducing ideas such as g4 followed by Ng5 @@StartBracket@@in case of ...Be6@@EndBracket@@. }
8... c5 9. O-O Rc8 10. Qb3
{ Sticking with the human approach. The computer likes  10.g4  Be6  11.Ng5  with a big advantage, but that looks a bit extreme to me. }
10... Qb6 11. a4
{ Even though the computer always prefers  11.g4!  followed by Ng5 ➼ I decided to stick with Kamsky's choice since I think it's more instructive to see a practical example of how White is going to make progress on the queenside. Kamsky,G @@StartBracket@@2674@@EndBracket@@-Do Nascimento,C @@StartBracket@@2034@@EndBracket@@ Chess.com INT 2020 }
