1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4
{ This is the most flexible move order ➼ making sure that we keep everything in London System teritory. For more details about the move order make sure to check out the informational. }
2... g6 3. Nf3 Bg7 4. c3 O-O 5. Nbd2 d5 6. e3
{ While many players have preferred  6.h3  ➼ countering ...Nh5,  I recommend that we stick with  6.e3  for the following reasons:  6...Nh5 ➼ is not such a bad counter in this version  6...c5 ➼ is the most common move ➼ allowing 7. dxc5!  against 6...Nbd7 & 6...b6 we can use h4-ideas to speed up the kingside play.Now it's Black's turn to make an important decision between:  6...Nh5 @@StartBracket@@rare, but critical@@EndBracket@@  6...Nbd7 @@StartBracket@@very popular@@EndBracket@@  6...Bf5 @@StartBracket@@a bit rare@@EndBracket@@  6...b6 @@StartBracket@@similar to 6...Nbd7@@EndBracket@@  6...c5 @@StartBracket@@most popular in online by far@@EndBracket@@  6...Nc6 @@StartBracket@@rare@@EndBracket@@. }
6... Nbd7
{ This move together with  6...b6  is the main choice for Black in over the board games. The plans are similar and these two moves usually end up transposing to each other. Black is preparing the usual ...b6-Bb7 followed by ...c5 ➼ without allowing a good version for White to 'steal' the c5-pawn. }
7. Be2
{ This is the most precise way to continue. While  7.h4  is definitely playable, it's not as precise as against 6...b6 ➼ because in this case after 6...Nbd7 7.h4 it turns out that ...Nbd7 is a more useful move for Black than ...b6 and they can use that to push in the center:  7...Re8  8.Be2  Ng4  with ...e5! coming on the next move, Black is fine. }
7... c5 8. h4
{ This is a completely new idea introduced by Leela. People used to play it slow with h3 and castle short almost automatically vs the Grunfeld set-up and Black's position was known to be pretty safe & solid. However, after this recent discovery Black needs to be very careful not to fall under a big attack quickly.I am generally not a huge fan of computer-ish solutions, but I will give credit to this move because White's position is incredibly easy to play! The plan is to go Ne5 followed by h5 with a big attack. This idea was already seen at the top level in a classical affair between Duda-Caruana, Tata Steel Masters 2022.Now generally Black will either play:  8...h5 ➼ stopping White's pawn for good  8...h6 ➼ with the idea to meet h5 with ...g5. }
8... h5
{ This is the most natural reaction, stopping the h-pawn, but ➼ weakening the g5-square.   8...Re8  9.Ne5  With an easy game for White. We are ready to push the h-pawn and in case Black goes  9...h5  we can take advantage of the g5-square by playing  10.Ndf3  followed by Ng5! }
9. Ng5 { This can be automatically played after Black commits to ... h5! } 9...
b6
{ This seems very natural to me ➼ trying to finish development in normal fashion with ...Bb7.   9...Re8  10.Ndf3  Introducing Nxf7-ideas followed by Ng5!  10...Ng4  11.O-O  This time creating a big threat of Nxf7 so Black needs to do something.  11...e5  This is probably the best move, not to mention the most natural one.  12.dxe5  Ndxe5  13.Qd2⩲  With Rad1 next, White keeps a small edge thanks to the weaker pawn on d5 and the strong g5-knight.   9...cxd4  doesn't seem super natural to me, but it has been seen in a couple of online games.  10.exd4  Nb6   10...Re8  can be met by  11.Ndf3  Qb6  12.Qb3  with ideas to castle short and play Ne5 with a pleasant position.  11.a4!  This is always the best way to counter the awkwardly placed b6-knight.  11...a5  12.Qb3⩲  White has a simple plan to castle short, activate the rook with Rfe1 and then a powerful maneuver could be Nf1-Ne3. }
10. Qc2
{ The queen is very dangerous on c2 against the Grunfeld ➼ because it supports g4-ideas. The point is to open lines on the kingside so that the c2-queen will cooperate with the g5-knight threatening to checkmate on h7. }
10... Bb7 11. g4
{ With a very dangerous attack already. A typical trap that could appear on the board is  11...hxg4  12.h5  Nxh5  13.Rxh5!  gxh5  14.Qh7# }
