[Black "Grunfeld: 6...b6 #4"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4
{ This is the most flexible move order ➼ making sure that we keep everything in London System teritory. For more details about the move order make sure to check out the informational. }
2... g6 3. Nf3 Bg7 4. c3 O-O 5. Nbd2 d5 6. e3
{ While many players have preferred  6.h3  ➼ countering ...Nh5,  I recommend that we stick with  6.e3  for the following reasons:  6...Nh5 ➼ is not such a bad counter in this version  6...c5 ➼ is the most common move ➼ allowing 7. dxc5!  against 6...Nbd7 & 6...b6 we can use h4-ideas to speed up the kingside play.Now it's Black's turn to make an important decision between:  6...Nh5 @@StartBracket@@rare, but critical@@EndBracket@@  6...Nbd7 @@StartBracket@@very popular@@EndBracket@@  6...Bf5 @@StartBracket@@a bit rare@@EndBracket@@  6...b6 @@StartBracket@@similar to 6...Nbd7@@EndBracket@@  6...c5 @@StartBracket@@most popular in online by far@@EndBracket@@  6...Nc6 @@StartBracket@@rare@@EndBracket@@. }
6... b6
{ This move is meant to avoid the 6...c5 7.dxc5 line. Black's plan is pretty simple. The difference compared to the 6...Nbd7 variation is that Black has an additional option of playing with ...Bb7-c5 followed by ...Nc6-Nd7 ➼ delivering the ...e5-break with an equal position. }
7. h4
{ This is a completely new idea introduced by Leela. People used to play it slow with h3 and castle short almost automatically against the Grunfeld set-up, when Black's position was known to be pretty safe & solid. However, after this recent discovery Black needs to be very cafeul not to fall under a big attack quickly.   I am generally not a huge fan of computer-ish solutions, but I will give credit to this move because White's position is incredibly easy to play! The plan is to go Ne5 followed by Be2-h5 with a big attack. This idea was already seen at the top level in a classical affair between Duda-Caruana, Tata Steel Masters 2022. Now Black generally has a choice between  7...h6  or  7...h5  , but we will also cover moves such as  7...Bb7  ,  7...Bg4  and  7...c5  . }
7... h6
{ This together with 7...h5 is the most common reaction to me. Generally the point of ...h6 is to meet  8.h5  with  8...g5!  The good news for us is that White then has a very interesting idea to sacrifice the bishop with Bxg5 and get a strong initiative on the kingside. }
8. Ne5
{ This is a bit more precise than starting with  8.h5  immediately because we want to have our queen ready to join the attack in case Black goes for the greedy approach with ...Nxh5. }
8... c5 9. h5
{ This move just works very well. Against g5 we can sacrifice the bishop, and against ...Nxh5 we can sacrifice the exchange with very good play on the kingside. }
9... g5
{ Probably the best try because  9...Nxh5  10.Rxh5!  gxh5  11.Qxh5  gives White an easy attack. }
10. Bxg5
{ Thanks to this thematic bishop sacrifice ➼ White gets a big initiative. }
10... hxg5 11. h6
{ And Black is in trouble. A sample line is  11...Bh8  12.h7+  Kg7  13.Qf3  threatening Qg3 and Black's king feels very weak. }
