1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4
{ This is the most flexible move order ➼ making sure that we keep everything in London System teritory. For more details about the move order make sure to check out the informational. }
2... g6 3. Nf3 Bg7 4. c3 O-O 5. Nbd2 d5 6. e3
{ While many players have preferred  6.h3  ➼ countering ...Nh5,  I recommend that we stick with  6.e3  for the following reasons:  6...Nh5 ➼ is not such a bad counter in this version  6...c5 ➼ is the most common move ➼ allowing 7. dxc5!  against 6...Nbd7 & 6...b6 we can use h4-ideas to speed up the kingside play.Now it's Black's turn to make an important decision between:  6...Nh5 @@StartBracket@@rare, but critical@@EndBracket@@  6...Nbd7 @@StartBracket@@very popular@@EndBracket@@  6...Bf5 @@StartBracket@@a bit rare@@EndBracket@@  6...b6 @@StartBracket@@similar to 6...Nbd7@@EndBracket@@  6...c5 @@StartBracket@@most popular in online by far@@EndBracket@@  6...Nc6 @@StartBracket@@rare@@EndBracket@@. }
6... Nc6
{ This is a pretty interesting sideline! Black is threatening ...Nh5 among other things, but the main idea is to go for the quick ...Nd7 followed by ...e5 ➼ with an easy game if Black manages to get that. }
7. h3 { Creating a square on h2 for the London bishop. } 7... Nd7
{ Threatening to equalise on the spot with ...e5! } 8. Bb5
{ This is the key move to get an advantage, but not an easy one if you are not familiar with the idea! }
8... e5
{ This has to be played ➼ otherwise Black gets a passive position.   8...a6  gives White an easy game after some precise moves:  9.Bxc6!  bxc6  10.Qa4!  Targeting the weak c6-pawn.  10...Bb7  11.Qa5  Threatening the c7-pawn.  11...Rc8  12.Nb3⩲  Black's pieces are very passive. White can castle short followed by Rac1 with the c4-break. }
9. Bxc6 { The complications will favor us. } 9... exf4
{ The most testing continuation.   9...bxc6  leads to a pretty straightforward advantage for White.  10.Nxe5  We are simply collecting the free pawn.  10...Nxe5  11.Bxe5  Bxe5  12.dxe5  Rb8  Threatening ...Rxb2.  13.b3  Qe7  Hitting the e5-pawn.  14.Nf3⩲  Black has some compensation after  14...Ba6  ,  but White managed to convert it into a full point. @@StartBracket@@38@@EndBracket@@ Nozicka,V @@StartBracket@@1980@@EndBracket@@ -Flecher,J @@StartBracket@@1970@@EndBracket@@ ICCF email 2016 }
10. Bxd5 { The only move to keep the advantage! } 10... Nf6 11. Bb3
{ Sidestepping Black's threat and preparing to castle short. } 11... fxe3 12.
fxe3 Re8 { Targeting the e3-pawn. } 13. O-O
{ After this strong move White is much better! The point is to meet  13...Rxe3  with  14.Ne5!  with a winning advantage for White. Shimanov,A @@StartBracket@@2593@@EndBracket@@-Savchenko,B @@StartBracket@@2564@@EndBracket@@ Chess.com INT 2020 }
