{ The standard way to defend the c5-pawn. This move makes it very awkward for Black to continue. }
8... Ne4
{ This was played in a top level game between the two young American talents Xiong-Robson, Saint Louis 2016. The computer finds some obscure compensation for Black, but from a human perspective it definitely feels easier to play as White. It's no wonder why nobody picked up this line in OTB since their game! }
9. Qxd5 Ndxc5 { Using a small tactical trick. } 10. Qxd8
{ The endgames are always a safe choice for White with the extra pawn. } 10...
Rxd8 11. Nxc5 Nxc5
{ Creating a big threat of going .. .Na4! If Black could get that on the board, that would give him the initiative because White is lacking a good way to protect the b2-pawn since Rb1 runs into ...Bf5! }
12. Bc7
{ The key move to get an advantage. Black has to either block his light-squared bishop with  12...Rd7  or play a passive move such as  12...Rf8  . }
12... Rd7 13. Be5
{ White is up a pawn and Black has to show some resilient defense. I want you to pay close attention to the fact that  13...Na4  is no longer a threat in this position since that can be met by  14.Bb5!  In the game Xiong,J @@StartBracket@@2618@@EndBracket@@-Robson,R @@StartBracket@@2663@@EndBracket@@ Saint Louis 2016 Black played a better move, and it was eventually drawn. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "12) Grünfeld Defense"]
[Black "Grunfeld: 6...c5 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4
{ This is the most flexible move order ➼ making sure that we keep everything in London System teritory. For more details about the move order make sure to check out the informational. }
2... g6 3. Nf3 Bg7 4. c3 O-O 5. Nbd2 d5 6. e3
{ While many players have preferred  6.h3  ➼ countering ...Nh5,  I recommend that we stick with  6.e3  for the following reasons:  6...Nh5 ➼ is not such a bad counter in this version  6...c5 ➼ is the most common move ➼ allowing 7. dxc5!  against 6...Nbd7 & 6...b6 we can use h4-ideas to speed up the kingside play.Now it's Black's turn to make an important decision between:  6...Nh5 @@StartBracket@@rare, but critical@@EndBracket@@  6...Nbd7 @@StartBracket@@very popular@@EndBracket@@  6...Bf5 @@StartBracket@@a bit rare@@EndBracket@@  6...b6 @@StartBracket@@similar to 6...Nbd7@@EndBracket@@  6...c5 @@StartBracket@@most popular in online by far@@EndBracket@@  6...Nc6 @@StartBracket@@rare@@EndBracket@@. }
6... c5
{ This is by far the most common move in online chess even though players in over the board games are mixing it with  6...Nbd7  and  6...b6  . }
7. dxc5
{ Taking on c5 is not the most common theme for our repertoire, but here it works very well. Generally this comes as a big surprise for the Black players. It's pretty tricky to make an accurate guess of how the play could go, but I did my best to add all the natural continuations + what I encountered myself playing this variation. }
7... Bg4
{ This is the engine's favorite. The idea is pretty simple despite not being the most natural move in the position. Black wants to play ...Nbd7 followed by ...Rc8 winning back the ...c5-pawn. }
8. Be2 { Preparing O-O. } 8... Nbd7 { Threatening ...Nxc5! } 9. Nb3
{ Sticking with the standard approach. It would be too risky to play  9.b4  in view of  9...Nh5! }
9... Rc8 10. h3
{ We can't keep the extra pawn, but we do win the bishop pair. } 10... Bxf3 11.
Bxf3 Nxc5 12. Nxc5 Rxc5 13. O-O
{ With an equal position according to the engine. I would definitely pick White with the bishop pair because we are basically playing for two results, while Black still needs to be careful for the rest of the game. Defending is of course very simple for the computer, but human players tend to collapse quickly in such positions where they have no active plan and need to 'stay solid'. The average player is always looking to do something active which will most likely backfire here. }
*

