[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "12) Grünfeld Defense"]
[Black "Grunfeld: 6...c5 #4"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4
{ This is the most flexible move order ➼ making sure that we keep everything in London System teritory. For more details about the move order make sure to check out the informational. }
2... g6 3. Nf3 Bg7 4. c3 O-O 5. Nbd2 d5 6. e3
{ While many players have preferred  6.h3  ➼ countering ...Nh5,  I recommend that we stick with  6.e3  for the following reasons:  6...Nh5 ➼ is not such a bad counter in this version  6...c5 ➼ is the most common move ➼ allowing 7. dxc5!  against 6...Nbd7 & 6...b6 we can use h4-ideas to speed up the kingside play.Now it's Black's turn to make an important decision between:  6...Nh5 @@StartBracket@@rare, but critical@@EndBracket@@  6...Nbd7 @@StartBracket@@very popular@@EndBracket@@  6...Bf5 @@StartBracket@@a bit rare@@EndBracket@@  6...b6 @@StartBracket@@similar to 6...Nbd7@@EndBracket@@  6...c5 @@StartBracket@@most popular in online by far@@EndBracket@@  6...Nc6 @@StartBracket@@rare@@EndBracket@@. }
6... c5
{ This is by far the most common move in online chess even though players in over the board games are mixing it with  6...Nbd7  and  6...b6  . }
7. dxc5
{ Taking on c5 is not the most common theme for our repertoire, but here it works very well. Generally this comes as a big surprise for the Black players. It's pretty tricky to make an accurate guess of how the play could go, but I did my best to add all the natural continuations + what I encountered myself playing this variation. }
7... Nc6 { Creating a big positional threat of ...Nh5! } 8. h3
{ This move is really important ➼ in order to meet ...Nh5 with Bh2! The careless  8.Be2  would give Black very decent compensation after something like  8...Nh5  9.Bg5  h6  10.Bh4  g5  11.Bg3  Nxg3  12.hxg3  e5  13.O-O  f5  with a position where White is still 'slightly better' according to the engine, but from a human perspective it feels easier to play as Black ➼ despite being down a pawn. }
8... Nd7
{ This move has the same plan as ...Re8 @@StartBracket@@to push ...e5@@EndBracket@@, but it just seems inferior to me because Black is struggling to develop. }
9. Nb3 { This is the key move to defend the c5-pawn. } 9... e5
{ If  9...a5  10.a4!  Black has a hard time regaining the pawn. Keep in mind that  10...e5  allows  11.Bg5!  and  11...f6?  12.Qxd5+!  wins another pawn for White. }
10. Bg5
{ Not the only move to keep an edge, but the most annoying one! The biggest issue that Black has is that  10...f6  allows  11.Qxd5+!  with a completely winning position for White. }
10... Nf6
{ This is pretty much the only move because  10...Bf6  runs into  11.Bh6!  followed by Qxd5. }
11. Bb5
{ This is the key move to get a serious advantage! Developing the bishop to b5 is not the most standard thing to do in the London System, but it works very well here because we are putting pressure on the e5-square.   The problem with the most natural  11.Be2  is that Black becomes very active after  11...h6  12.Bh4  g5  13.Bg3  Ne4  14.Bh2  f5!  with full compensation for the pawn. If you place White's bishop on b5 in that variation, you can notice that Bxc6! ➼ wins the e5-pawn. }
11... h6 12. Bh4
{ This is generally the best, even though White has an interesting alternative in  12.Bxf6  Bxf6  13.e4!? }
12... g5
{ This has to be played sooner or later, otherwise Black will never unpin himself. }
13. Bg3 { Threatening Nxe5! } 13... Ne4
{ This is Black's best try ➼ creating a huge threat of ...Nxg3! Something like  13...e4  14.Nfd4  would be exactly what we want to see because White is getting acces to the critical square on d4 ➼ with a close to winning position. }
14. Bh2 { Threatening Bxc6 followed by Nxe5! } 14... Re8 15. Nfd2
{ This is the key move to secure an advantage for White because ➼ we are getting rid of the e4-knight. Also keep in mind that ...a6 will generally be met by Ba4 ➼ because keeping the c6-knight pinned is very annoying for Black. }
