{ Taking on c5 is not the most common theme for our repertoire, but here it works very well. Generally this comes as a big surprise for the Black players. It's pretty tricky to make an accurate guess of how the play could go, but I did my best to add all the natural continuations + what I encountered myself playing this variation. }
7... Nc6 { Creating a big positional threat of ...Nh5! } 8. h3
{ This move is really important ➼ in order to meet ...Nh5 with Bh2! The careless  8.Be2  would give Black very decent compensation after something like  8...Nh5  9.Bg5  h6  10.Bh4  g5  11.Bg3  Nxg3  12.hxg3  e5  13.O-O  f5  with a position where White is still 'slightly better' according to the engine, but from a human perspective it feels easier to play as Black ➼ despite being down a pawn. }
8... Re8
{ Preparing to push ...e5 ➼ this is the most common move in online chess. Black also has some alternatives:   8...a5  is a pretty common move for Black, but we can just answer  9.a4⩲  and will most likely transpose into some other lines where the inclusion of a4-a5 should favor White because the b5-square has been weakened.   8...Nh5  9.Bh2  f5   Black's only try because  9...e5  allows  10.g4!  with a big advantage for White.  10.Bb5!  This is not the most standard square for the bishop, but it works really well because we are fighting for the e5-square.  10...f4  Black has to play very aggressively. Otherwise they are simply worse, being down a pawn.  11.O-O !  This is the best move, improving over Sedlak's game that went 11. exf4?!  11...e5  12.e4±  After this strong move White is threatening to take on d5 because ...Qxd5 could potentially run into Bc4! A key line for White is after  12...Be6  13.exd5  Bxd5  14.Nc4  e4  White has the strong  15.Nd6!  ➼ hitting the d5-bishop with a winning position.   8...Ne8  is a rare move, but it was played by Morozevich once!  9.Bg3  Nc7  10.Be2  e5  11.O-O  Ne6  Threatening ...Nxc5!  12.b4  With a solid advantage for White despite the fact that Black got some decent coordination. The key idea is to meet ...f5 with b5! and the e5-pawn will be under a lot of pressure. A sample line could be something like  12...f5  13.b5!  f4  14.exf4  exf4  15.Bh4  g5  16.bxc6  bxc6  17.Rc1  gxh4  18.c4  with a large advantage for White because Black's position is full of weaknesses. }
9. Bb5
{ This is the key move against 8...Re8. The main point is to stop Black's ...e5-push since  9...e5  allows  10.Bxc6  bxc6  11.Bxe5!  with a winning position for White.   The naive  9.Be2  would allow some unnecessary counterplay after  9...e5  10.Bh2  Bf8  11.Nb3  Ne4!  ➼ winning back the c5-pawn. }
9... a6 10. Bxc6
{ Taking the knight is always a double-edged decision ➼ but it works very well when we can control the e5-square. }
10... bxc6 11. Be5
{ It is not too late to spoil the advantage with  11.O-O?!  Nd7!  with ...e5 next and good counterplay for Black.   After the key move  11.Be5!  White enjoys a big advantage. Bxc6 followed by Be5 is a great combo to keep in mind in these lines after 'stealing' the c5-pawn. The e5-bishop does a great job shutting down the enemy fianchetto ➼ allowing White to advance the queenside pawns with a4-b4 much easier. Shimanov,A @@StartBracket@@2639@@EndBracket@@-Bellahcene,B @@StartBracket@@2467@@EndBracket@@ Chess.com INT 2016 }
*

