[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "13) Benoni Defense"]
[Black "1...c5 2.d5 e5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 c5 2. d5 e5
{ This is the Czech Benoni. Black's plan is to get a King's Indian type of structure while avoiding most of the opening theory. They would love to push ...f5 and generate play on the kingside while another typical plan is to trade off the bad bishop with ...Be7-Bg5! This strategy is pretty easy to implement and it could be very effective against unprepared opponents ➼ however if White is well prepared, the lines are very dangerous for Black. }
3. e4 d6 4. Nc3
{ This is the best setup for White ➼ keeping the c4-square available for the knight after the typical maneuver with Nf3-Nd2-Nc4!   I believe White can fight for an advantage after  4.c4  as well, but those positions are much harder to break. }
4... a6
{ Threatening to push ...b5 ➼ Black can at any point throw in this move. } 5.
a4 { The typical answer to ...a6 ➼ stopping Black from pushing ...b5! } 5...
Be7 { Threatening to trade off the bad bishop with ...Bg5! } 6. Nf3
{ Stopping ... Bg5 and preparing to get in the typical maneuver with Nf3-Nd2-Nc4! Black has a choice between:  6...Nf6  6...Bg4. }
6... Nf6 7. Nd2 { Preparing to play Nc4. } 7... O-O 8. Nc4
{ The knight is ideally placed on this square. White has a positional threat of pushing a5 ➼ fixing the weak square on b6. }
8... b6
{ This is played with the idea to meet  9.a5  with  9...b5!   8...Ne8  is another typical move for Black ➼ preparing to push ...f5!  9.a5!  Fixing the weak square on b6 and threatening Nb6 ideas!  9...Nd7  Trying to keep the b6-square under control.  10.Na4±  We will continue with Nab6 followed by Bd3 and O-O with a dominating position for White. }
9. h4
{ This is the new way of handling the position ➼ suggested by Leela. Black lacks useful moves and we will expand with g4 soon. }
9... Ne8 { This is a typical move for Black ➼ preparing to push ...f5! } 10. g4
{ This is both prophylactic and attacking in the same time! We are stopping Black from pushing ...f5 while preparing attacking ideas with Qf3-Qg3,Ne3,Be2 followed by pushing the kingside pawns with g5-h5 and g6! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "13) Benoni Defense"]
[Black "1...c5 2.d5 e5 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 c5 2. d5 e5
{ This is the Czech Benoni. Black's plan is to get a King's Indian type of structure while avoiding most of the opening theory. They would love to push ...f5 and generate play on the kingside while another typical plan is to trade off the bad bishop with ...Be7-Bg5! This strategy is pretty easy to implement and it could be very effective against unprepared opponents ➼ however if White is well prepared, the lines are very dangerous for Black. }
3. e4 d6 4. Nc3
{ This is the best setup for White ➼ keeping the c4-square available for the knight after the typical maneuver with Nf3-Nd2-Nc4!   I believe White can fight for an advantage after  4.c4  as well, but those positions are much harder to break. }
4... a6
{ Threatening to push ...b5 ➼ Black can at any point throw in this move. } 5.
a4 { The typical answer to ...a6 ➼ stopping Black from pushing ...b5! } 5...
Be7 { Threatening to trade off the bad bishop with ...Bg5! } 6. Nf3
{ Stopping ... Bg5 and preparing to get in the typical maneuver with Nf3-Nd2-Nc4! Black has a choice between:  6...Nf6  6...Bg4. }
6... Bg4
{ This is played with the idea to eliminate the f3-knight so they can trade off the bad bishop with ...Bg5! }
7. h3
{ 'When you see your opponent going for a bad plan, it is usually a good idea to not disturb him'. This is what I learned from Petrosian's games, and it's a bit of a joke in our case because Black's plan is strategically sound, it's just that Black's position is simply bad. }
7... Bxf3 8. Qxf3 Bg5
{ Getting the dream position ➼ trading off the bad bishop. } 9. Bxg5 Qxg5
{ Unfortunately Black's dream position is simply bad! } 10. Qg4
{ Forcing Black to trade queens and open up the h-file for our rook because Qc8 is a big threat. This is not the only move to keep an advantage according to the computer, but it's the simplest ➼ giving White an easy and risk free game. }
10... Qxg4 11. hxg4
{ We can continue with Be2,Kd2 followed by Rh3-Rah1 with pressure on the h-file. After that we can maneuver the knight with Nd1-Ne3 and then we decide between Nc4/ Nf5 with a very promising position for White. }
