3. e4 d6 4. Nc3
{ This is the best setup for White ➼ keeping the c4-square available for the knight after the typical maneuver with Nf3-Nd2-Nc4!   I believe White can fight for an advantage after  4.c4  as well, but those positions are much harder to break. }
4... f5
{ This is Black's most common move ➼ giving White a winning position immediately! }
5. Bb5+
{ After this exploitative check ➼ White is most likely going to pick up the f5-pawn. }
5... Bd7
{ This is Black's most common move. After  5...Nd7  6.exf5  White is simply up a pawn. Also it seems to be very risky to play @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp4pp/3p4/1BpPpp2/4P3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQK1NR b KQkq - 1 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Kf7  6.f4!  a6  7.Bd3  followed by Nf3 and O-O with a promising attack for White. }
6. exf5 { Collecting the f5-pawn because the d7-bishop is pinned. } 6... Bxb5
7. Nxb5
{ We can continue with Nf3 followed by O-O with a winning position for White thanks to the extra pawn. }
