{ This is the best setup for White ➼ keeping the c4-square available for the knight after the typical maneuver with Nf3-Nd2-Nc4!   I believe White can fight for an advantage after  4.c4  as well, but those positions are much harder to break. }
4... Nf6
{ 4...g6  is another line, when  5.Be2!?  is an interesting move order ➼ avoiding 5.Nf3 Bg4 which is less clear.  5...Bg7  6.Nf3!  The point of this move order is to meet  6...Bg4  with  7.Nd2!  with a large advantage for White thanks to the extra space and the knight reaching the ideal c4-square soon. Meanwhile, after  @@StartFEN@@rnbqk1nr/pp3pbp/3p2p1/2pPp3/4P3/2N2N2/PPP1BPPP/R1BQK2R b KQkq - 3 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Ne7  there is  7.h4!  Threatening to push h5! Now  7...h6  is the most flexible move because 7...h5 weakens the g5-square.  8.Nd2  Heading to the c4-square.  8...O-O  9.h5  Threatening hxg6 ➼ opening up the h-file for our rook.  9...g5  10.g4±  This is the key move to stop Black from pushing ...f5! From now on, White has a free hand on the queenside with moves such as Nc4-Ne3,Bd2,Kf1-Kg2 followed by a4-a5 and ideas to break with Rb1-b4! }
