1. d4 c5 2. d5 e6 3. Nc3
{ Preparing to push e4. In case of  3...d6  we will play  4.dxe6!  of course ➼ transposing to 4...e6 lines. }
3... exd5 4. Nxd5 Nf6
{ This line can be very annoying if you are not aware how to counter it. } 5.
e4
{ This move is important in order to secure an opening advantage. The tactical justification is  5...Nxe4  6.Qe2  f5  7.f3  ➼ winning the e4-knight. }
5... Nxd5
{ If  5...d6  , the move  6.Nxf6+!  works well ➼ preparing Ne2-Nc3-Nd5!  6...Qxf6  7.Ne2!  Heading towards the d5-square.  7...Nc6  8.Nc3⩲  With a clearly better position for White thanks to the d5-outpost. We can continue with Be2 followed by O-O and Nd5 is always something that Black needs to watch out for. }
6. Qxd5
{ This is best ➼ keeping the d5-square available for a piece. Instead,  6.exd5  only gives White a small advantage. }
6... d6 7. Bc4 { Threatening checkmate in one on f7! } 7... Be6
{ Defending against the checkmate, but dropping the exchange.   7...Qc7  8.Ne2!  The knight is heading towards the d5-square with Nc3/Nf4!  8...Be6  9.Qd3⩲  We can continue with O-O followed by Nf4 with a large advantage. }
8. Qxb7 Bxc4 9. Qxa8
{ With a much better position for White thanks to the extra exchange. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "13) Benoni Defense"]
[Black "1...c5 2.d5 d6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 c5 2. d5 d6 3. Nc3
{ This works best ➼ keeping the c4-square available for the knight. } 3... Nf6
4. e4 e6 5. dxe6
{ This move works best no matter what Black will recapture with. The point is to avoid  5.Nf3  exd5  6.exd5  with a symmetrical structure which is known to be slightly better for White, but pretty tricky to execute. }
5... Bxe6
{ This is the most common way for Black to recapture.   5...fxe6  improves Black's control over the center, but they will be vulnerable to e5-ideas ➼ messing up Black's pawn structure.  6.Nf3  already threatens to push e5!  6...Nc6  7.Bf4!  Reinforcing the e5-threat. Black can't really do much about it because 7...e5 would create a huge weakness on d5!  7...Be7  8.e5!  After this key idea White has long term pressure with the better pawn structure.  8...dxe5  9.Qxd8+  Bxd8  10.Nxe5⩲  With a long-term advantage for White because of the isolated e6-pawn. Keep in mind that  10...Bc7  is met by  11.Nd3  with a risk-free game for White. }
6. Nge2
{ Nobody really played this move out of 5000 online games, which is interesting to see because 6.Nge2! is the key move to grab the advantage. White is preparing Nf4 which not only attacks the e6-bishop, but also keeps an eye on the d5-outpost. }
6... Nc6 7. Nf4
{ The knight is really well-placed here ➼ controlling the d5-outpost. } 7...
Be7 8. Be2 { Preparing O-O. } 8... O-O 9. O-O Re8
{ Preparing ...Bf8 followed by ...g6-Bg7! This is a typical regroupment for Black. }
10. Re1 { Preparing to play Bf1 ➼ slowly improving our position. } 10... Bf8
11. Bf1 a6 { Threatening to push ...b5! } 12. a4
{ This is the typical answer to ...a6 ➼ stopping Black from pushing ...b5! }
12... g6 13. f3
{ Preparing to play Be3 without allowing any annoying ...Ng4 ideas. Then we can continue with Qd2 followed by Rad1 with pressure on the backward d6-pawn. }
