[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "13) Benoni Defense"]
[Black "1...c5 2.d5 d6 #4"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 c5 2. d5 d6 3. Nc3
{ This works best ➼ keeping the c4-square available for the knight. } 3... Nf6
4. e4 g6
{ This is the most common plan for Black ➼ setting-up the kingside fianchetto and then trying to play on the queenside with ...a6-b5! }
5. Nf3 Bg7 6. Bc4
{ There are many ways of playing this position, but I find this one to be the most effective ➼ following a recent game by Grischuk. The main advantage of playing 6.Bc4 is that Black can no longer break with ...e6 which is a typical plan in this Benoni structure.   Initially I was considering to recommend  6.Bb5+  which is known to be a 'clever' move to include, but the main issue is that after  6...Bd7  7.a4  Bxb5  8.axb5  it's not so easy to make progress for White. @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/pp2ppbp/3p1np1/2pP4/4P3/2N2N2/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 2 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Be2  is a very viable alternative, but then Black has an additional option to break with ...e6!? }
6... O-O 7. O-O
{ After this move Black has a choice between three main plans:  7...Bg4  7...Na6  7...a6. }
7... a6 { Threatening to push ...b5! } 8. a4
{ This is the typical answer to ...a6 ➼ stopping Black from pushing ...b5! }
8... Nbd7
{ In this line we will be focusing on lines with the light-squared bishop on c8.  8...Bg4  transposes to 7...Bg4. }
9. Re1
{ Activating the rook and preparing to play Bf1. It would have been a bit too early to play the standard  9.a5  because of  9...b5!  and Black gets decent counterplay on the queenside. }
9... Rb8 10. h3
{ This is a useful move to have ➼ creating a luft and preparing Bf4 ideas. }
10... Ne8 { Preparing to play ...Nc7 ➼ supporting the ...b5-break! } 11. Bf1
{ This is a nice way to improve White's position. The bishop is much safer on f1! }
11... Nc7 { Threatening to push ...b5! } 12. a5
{ Making Black's ...b5-break less effective. } 12... b5
{ This has to be played because  12...Ne5  13.Nd2!  gives White a large advantage, similar to the previous trainable. }
13. axb6 { After this move Black has a choice between:  13...Rxb6  13...Nxb6. }
13... Rxb6 14. Ra2
{ This is a typical prophylactical move ➼ defending the b2-pawn so we can develop the dark-squared bishop next. }
14... Nb5 { This is Black's main source of getting counterplay. } 15. Nb1
{ After this stunning retreating move, White has a large advantage. It's the backward knight moves that are the hardest to spot in a chess game, so knowing this in advance will make it much easier to find during the game. The point is to play c3 on the next move ➼ shutting down both the b5-knight and the g7-bishop. After that we can maneuver the knight with Nd2-Nc4 with a large advantage for White. Keep in mind that Black has to watch out for the isolated a6-pawn. }
