[Black "1...c5 2.d5 d6 #5"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 c5 2. d5 d6 3. Nc3
{ This works best ➼ keeping the c4-square available for the knight. } 3... Nf6
4. e4 g6
{ This is the most common plan for Black ➼ setting-up the kingside fianchetto and then trying to play on the queenside with ...a6-b5! }
5. Nf3 Bg7 6. Bc4
{ There are many ways of playing this position, but I find this one to be the most effective ➼ following a recent game by Grischuk. The main advantage of playing 6.Bc4 is that Black can no longer break with ...e6 which is a typical plan in this Benoni structure.   Initially I was considering to recommend  6.Bb5+  which is known to be a 'clever' move to include, but the main issue is that after  6...Bd7  7.a4  Bxb5  8.axb5  it's not so easy to make progress for White. @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/pp2ppbp/3p1np1/2pP4/4P3/2N2N2/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 2 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Be2  is a very viable alternative, but then Black has an additional option to break with ...e6!? }
6... O-O 7. O-O
{ After this move Black has a choice between three main plans:  7...Bg4  7...Na6  7...a6. }
7... Bg4
{ This is a typical plan for the Benoni structure ➼ trading a pair of minor pieces because Black is lacking space.   The move  7...Na6  This is connected with ...Nc7 and ...Rb8 ideas ➼ to push on the queenside with ...b5! We can reply  8.Re1  Nc7  9.e5!  ⩲  This move is quite problematic for Black. Whenever White manages to get this in, it generally leads to a large advantage. }
8. h3 { Forcing Black to give up the bishop pair. } 8... Bxf3 9. Qxf3 Nbd7
{ Creating a big positional threat of going ...Ne5 ➼ attacking both the c4-bishop and the f3-queen. }
10. Qd1
{ Returning to the safe square and preparing to meet  10...Ne5  with  11.Be2! }
10... a6 { Threatening to push ...b5! } 11. a4
{ This is the typical answer to ...a6 ➼ stopping Black from pushing ...b5! }
11... Ne8
{ 11...b6  is a slower plan ➼ mainly stopping White from pushing a5!  12.Bg5  Ne8  This is the main plan ➼ preparing to play ...Nc7.   12...h6  13.Bd2!  looks very promising for White with f4 next.  13.f4  Nc7  Threatening to play ...Rb8 followed by ...b5!  14.Qe2±  Preparing to play Rae1 followed by the e5-break. This move is very useful because it's also stopping Black from playing  14...Rb8  because of  15.Bxa6! }
12. Re1 { Activating the rook and preparing to play Bf1. } 12... Nc7
{ Threatening to push ...b5! } 13. a5
{ Making Black's ...b5-break less effective. } 13... b5 14. axb6 Nxb6
{ Attacking the c4-bishop. } 15. Bf1
{ With a slightly better position for White thanks to the bishop pair and the isolated a6-pawn. We can continue with Bg5 followed by Qd2-Bh6 ideas. }
