{ Defending the b2-pawn while also attacking the h6-pawn. Notice that White is winning a tempo because we have provoked this ...h6-move by playing 13.Bg5! }
17... Kh7 { Defending the h6-pawn. } 18. Bf1
{ This is a nice way to improve White's position. The bishop is much safer on f1! }
18... Nb5 19. Nd1
{ After this stunning retreating move, White has a large advantage. It's the backward knight moves that are the hardest to spot in a chess game, so knowing this in advance will make it much easier to find during the game. The point is to play c3 on the next move ➼ shutting down both the b5-knight and the g7-bishop. After that we have ideas to play Ne3-Nc4. Last but not least, Black has to be careful with the isolated a6-pawn which is a very juicy target. }
