[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "13) Benoni Defense"]
[Black "Benoni: 3...g6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4
{ This is the most flexible move order ➼ making sure that we keep everything in London System teritory. For more details about the move order make sure to check out the informational. }
2... c5
{ This can be played by the Benoni One-Trick-Ponies, or by players who have this as a tricky line against the London System. }
3. e3
{ Preparing to meet ...cxd4 with exd4 and ➼ inviting Black to play  3...d5  which transposes back into the normal lines after  4.Nf3  .   The reason why I am not a huge fan of  3.d5  is because Black has an option of going  3...b5  and the resulting positions are very different compared to what we normally see in the London System. }
3... g6
{ This is a somewhat strange move order for the King's Indian players, but it is still played ocassionally. }
4. Nd2
{ This is important to start with because  4.c3  Qb6  forces us to play  5.Qb3  and get into some theoretical lines that we are trying to avoid. }
4... Bg7 5. c3 { Creating a threat of dxc5! } 5... cxd4
{ Avoiding dxc5!   After  5...O-O  we could use the typical idea  6.dxc5⩲  that we have in the Grunfeld as well. Black is unable to win back the pawn easily. }
6. exd4 O-O 7. Ngf3 d6 8. Be2
{ The light-squared bishop really belongs on e2 in this structure. A lot of my students make the mistake to play 8.Bd3 against the kingside fianchetto. The bishop is not more active on d3 because it's restricted by the g6-pawn, but it's more vulnerable to Black's typical idea of pushing ...e5! }
8... Nc6 9. O-O
{ This is a common position for the King's Indian. We are not getting this variation in the main lines because we generally go dxc5, but against this specific move order, that was not really an option. Black now has a choice between:  9...Bg4  9... Re8  9...Nd5. }
9... Bg4
{ This is pretty common for Black, but we are happy to win the bishop pair. }
10. h3 { Forcing Black to give up the bishop. } 10... Bxf3 11. Bxf3
{ I prefer this move because the bishop is very active on the long diagonal. }
11... e5 12. dxe5 dxe5 13. Bh2
{ With a clear advantage for White with the two bishops in an open position. Black has to watch out for the direct threat of Bxc6 followed by Bxe5! }
