[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4
{ This is the most flexible move order ➼ making sure that we keep everything in London System teritory. For more details about the move order make sure to check out the informational. }
2... c5
{ This can be played by the Benoni One-Trick-Ponies, or by players who have this as a tricky line against the London System. }
3. e3
{ Preparing to meet ...cxd4 with exd4 and ➼ inviting Black to play  3...d5  which transposes back into the normal lines after  4.Nf3  .   The reason why I am not a huge fan of  3.d5  is because Black has an option of going  3...b5  and the resulting positions are very different compared to what we normally see in the London System. }
3... g6
{ This is a somewhat strange move order for the King's Indian players, but it is still played ocassionally. }
4. Nd2
{ This is important to start with because  4.c3  Qb6  forces us to play  5.Qb3  and get into some theoretical lines that we are trying to avoid. }
4... Bg7 5. c3 { Creating a threat of dxc5! } 5... d6 6. dxc5
{ Getting into very similar positions compared to what we have seen in the King's Indian main lines. The difference is that the pawn is on e3 instead of e4, but the plans remain the same. }
6... dxc5 7. h3 { Stopping ...Bg4-ideas. } 7... O-O 8. Ngf3 Nc6 9. Qc2
{ I like to start this way ➼ with the idea to meet  9...Bf5  with  10.e4! }
9... b6 10. Be2 { Preparing O-O. } 10... Bb7 11. O-O Qd7 12. Nc4
{ With the simple plan of pushing a4-a5. A trick that you want to keep in mind is that if we manage to push a5 and Black tries ...b5 ➼ we can push a6! as an intermezzo followed by Na5/Ne5 ideas. }
