[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "13) Benoni Defense"]
[Black "Benoni: 3...Nd5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4
{ This is the most flexible move order ➼ making sure that we keep everything in London System teritory. For more details about the move order make sure to check out the informational. }
2... c5
{ This can be played by the Benoni One-Trick-Ponies, or by players who have this as a tricky line against the London System. }
3. e3
{ Preparing to meet ...cxd4 with exd4 and ➼ inviting Black to play  3...d5  which transposes back into the normal lines after  4.Nf3  .   The reason why I am not a huge fan of  3.d5  is because Black has an option of going  3...b5  and the resulting positions are very different compared to what we normally see in the London System. }
3... Nd5
{ Attacking the f4-bishop directly ➼ this can be a very annoying sideline if you are not familiar with it @@StartBracket@@sometimes even if you are!@@EndBracket@@. }
4. Bg3 Qb6
{ Attacking the b2-pawn and keeping an eye on the d4-square. This is probably one of the most annoying anti-Londons. The good news is that I came up with a completely new approach that most black players won't expect. }
5. c4
{ This new exchange sacrifice is the most ambitious way to deal with Black's play and it also gave me a crushing win rate, while I was scoring around 50% with the softer  5.b3  . }
5... Qxb2
{ Going after the exchange ➼ This is what most of my opponents played, and probably what you are going to encounter as well. }
6. cxd5 Qxa1 7. Qc2
{ Trapping Black's queen in the corner while stopping  7...cxd4  because of  8.Qxc8#  . }
7... b6
{ This is best according to the engine, but generally people tend to go for something faster when the queen is in such a dangerous position, that's why  7...Na6  is more likely in my opinion. }
8. Nf3 Na6 { Threatening ...Nb4! } 9. a3
{ Stopping Black's threat of ...Nb4 is very important. } 9... g5
{ Trying to distract us from our main task of finishing development and trapping Black's queen. }
10. Bb5 { Developing the bishop to the most active square and preparing O-O. }
10... g4 { Attacking the f3-knight. } 11. Ne5 Bg7 12. d6
{ This is a strong move because  12...exd6  13.Nxf7!  gives White a winning attack with Qf5 coming next. }
12... cxd4 13. Qf5 { Attacking both d7 and f7. } 13... Bxe5 14. Bxe5
{ Attacking the h8-rook and the d4-pawn. } 14... e6
{ Attacking White's queen. } 15. Qd3
{ White is much better in this crazy position. I will just give the best computer line because we don't need more than that:  15...f6  16.Bxd4!   This is precise because  16.Bxf6  Nc5  would have allowed some counterplay.  16...Qa2  17.O-O  ±  We are down an exchange but with Black's king being vulnerable and the queen that is almost trapped   @@StartBracket@@not to mention the hanging a6-knight@@EndBracket@@ White is close to winning. }
*

