[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "13) Benoni Defense"]
[Black "Benoni: 3...Nd5 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4
{ This is the most flexible move order ➼ making sure that we keep everything in London System teritory. For more details about the move order make sure to check out the informational. }
2... c5
{ This can be played by the Benoni One-Trick-Ponies, or by players who have this as a tricky line against the London System. }
3. e3
{ Preparing to meet ...cxd4 with exd4 and ➼ inviting Black to play  3...d5  which transposes back into the normal lines after  4.Nf3  .   The reason why I am not a huge fan of  3.d5  is because Black has an option of going  3...b5  and the resulting positions are very different compared to what we normally see in the London System. }
3... Nd5
{ Attacking the f4-bishop directly ➼ this can be a very annoying sideline if you are not familiar with it @@StartBracket@@sometimes even if you are!@@EndBracket@@. }
4. Bg3 Qb6
{ Attacking the b2-pawn and keeping an eye on the d4-square. This is probably one of the most annoying anti-Londons. The good news is that I came up with a completely new approach that most black players won't expect. }
5. c4
{ This new exchange sacrifice is the most ambitious way to deal with Black's play and it also gave me a crushing win rate, while I was scoring around 50% with the softer  5.b3  . }
5... Nf6 { The best line for Black objectively speaking. } 6. Bd3
{ This is my improvement over the few games that have been played from this position. The idea is to speed up development with Ne2-O-O-Nbc3 @@StartBracket@@trapping Black's queen@@EndBracket@@. The bishop also plays an important role on d3, defending the b1-knight so we can safely meet ...Qxb2-Qxa1 with Qd2  @@StartBracket@@catching Black's queen in a box@@EndBracket@@. }
6... Qxb2 { Going after the exchange will get Black's queen in trouble. } 7.
Ne2
{ This is important and very typical for the line. We typically develop like this with Nge2 and Nbc3. }
7... Qxa1 { Threatening ...Qxa2! } 8. Qd2
{ Defending the a2-pawn and trapping Black's queen. This move is important because  8.Qc2  would allow  8...Nc6!  followed by ...Nb4 and Black wins. }
8... g6
{ Black can choose any method of development at this point because the queen gets trapped regardless. }
9. O-O Bg7 10. Nbc3 { Trapping Black's queen. } 10... Qxf1+ 11. Kxf1
{ We have an interesting middlegame where White has a queen and Black's got the two rooks. I think White should be better because there are no open files for the rooks and we can attack Black's king by pushing the h-pawn @@StartBracket@@eventually after trading the knights with Nd5@@EndBracket@@. }
