[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "13) Benoni Defense"]
[Black "Benoni: 3...Qb6 and 4...Qxb2 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4
{ This is the most flexible move order ➼ making sure that we keep everything in London System teritory. For more details about the move order make sure to check out the informational. }
2... c5
{ This can be played by the Benoni One-Trick-Ponies, or by players who have this as a tricky line against the London System. }
3. e3
{ Preparing to meet ...cxd4 with exd4 and ➼ inviting Black to play  3...d5  which transposes back into the normal lines after  4.Nf3  .   The reason why I am not a huge fan of  3.d5  is because Black has an option of going  3...b5  and the resulting positions are very different compared to what we normally see in the London System. }
3... Qb6 4. Nc3
{ This is the universal reply to ...Qb6 that you are going to see in this course. Generally White has many alternatives, but in order to keep it simple, my advice is to always play Nc3 with the idea to meet 4...Qxb2 with 5. Nb5! }
4... Qxb2
{ This is a very committal decision. With best play, this leads to complicated positions where Black sacrifices the queen for an active position. Black should hold with best play, but this is easier said than done.   The first thing I noticed is that after  5.Nb5  half of the online games feature  5...Na6  ➼ which is an instant win for White if you know what you are doing! There are definitely a lot of points to be scored in this line, and the fact that Black can hold with best play doesn't bother me. }
5. Nb5 { Threatening Nc7+ so Black has a choice between:  5...Na6  5... Nd5. }
5... Na6
{ Covering the c7-square and threatening ...Nb4! This line is very common in online chess, but Black is just lost after precise play! }
6. a3
{ This move not only stops ...Nb4/Qb4 ideas, but it makes trapping the enemy queen much easier.  6.Rb1  merely leads to a draw. }
6... Nd5 { Threatening ...Nc3! } 7. Rb1 Qa2 8. Bg3
{ Although the typical  8.Rb3  is completely fine, this is just stronger. Black is dead lost because of the simple Qc1 followed by Rb2 ➼ trapping Black's queen. }
