[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "13) Benoni Defense"]
[Black "Benoni: 3...Qb6 and 4...Qxb2 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4
{ This is the most flexible move order ➼ making sure that we keep everything in London System teritory. For more details about the move order make sure to check out the informational. }
2... c5
{ This can be played by the Benoni One-Trick-Ponies, or by players who have this as a tricky line against the London System. }
3. e3
{ Preparing to meet ...cxd4 with exd4 and ➼ inviting Black to play  3...d5  which transposes back into the normal lines after  4.Nf3  .   The reason why I am not a huge fan of  3.d5  is because Black has an option of going  3...b5  and the resulting positions are very different compared to what we normally see in the London System. }
3... Qb6 4. Nc3
{ This is the universal reply to ...Qb6 that you are going to see in this course. Generally White has many alternatives, but in order to keep it simple, my advice is to always play Nc3 with the idea to meet 4...Qxb2 with 5. Nb5! }
4... Qxb2
{ This is a very committal decision. With best play, this leads to complicated positions where Black sacrifices the queen for an active position. Black should hold with best play, but this is easier said than done.   The first thing I noticed is that after  5.Nb5  half of the online games feature  5...Na6  ➼ which is an instant win for White if you know what you are doing! There are definitely a lot of points to be scored in this line, and the fact that Black can hold with best play doesn't bother me. }
5. Nb5 { Threatening Nc7+ so Black has a choice between:  5...Na6  5... Nd5. }
5... Nd5
{ This is generally played by the advanced players, so if you are a beginner that's just trying to pick up the London System ➼ There is no way you'll to get this variation in your games, however it's still useful to see how the game could go. }
6. a3
{ Using the same idea as against 5...Na6. This is the only try for White because 6.Rb1 is just a forced draw. }
6... a6
{ The most common move for Black, attacking the b5-knight ➼ but allowing White to trap the queen.   6...Nc3  is a rare move leads to a complex endgame. The following moves are forced.  7.Nc7+  Kd8  8.Qc1  Avoiding the ...Nxd1 threat.  8...Qxc1+  9.Rxc1  e5!  This is the key trick that keeps Black alive.  10.Bxe5  d6  Attacking both the e5-bishop and the c7-knight.  11.Nxa8  dxe5  12.dxe5∞  We are going to get rid of the annoying c3-knight by playing Ne2 next. Black will slowly be able to collect the a8-knight, but the position remains equal with best play for both sides. You can definitely analyze these endgames a little bit deeper, but this should be good enough to get you started. }
7. Rb1 Qa2 8. Qc1
{ There was no way to save the knight, but capturing Black's queen should give us a bit of compensation. The point is to play Ra1 on the next move. }
8... axb5
{ Black doesn't have an alternative other than sacrificing the queen. } 9. Ra1
{ Trapping Black's queen. } 9... Qxa1 10. Qxa1
{ We have arrived at the main crossroads for this variation. Black has a choice between:  10...e5!  10... Nc6  10... Nxf4. }
10... Nxf4
{ This looks like a normal move for Black.   If  10...Nc6  we collect the free pawn with  11.Bxb5  cxd4  12.Bxc6!  This is important so we can combine it with Qxd4 next.  12...bxc6  13.Qxd4⩲  White has some advantage according to Leela, but the position remains incredibly complex. Black was able to hold in Prie,E @@StartBracket@@2490@@EndBracket@@ -Argandona Riveiro,I @@StartBracket@@2388@@EndBracket@@ San Sebastian 2011. }
11. exf4 { Threatening Bxb5! } 11... c4 12. Qb2 { Threatening Qxb5! } 12... Ra5
13. d5
{ Taking away ...Nc6 ideas and we can continue development with Nf3,Be2 and O-O. The knight could centralize with Nd4 and the position seems easier for White with Black's awkward rook on a5. }
