[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "13) Benoni Defense"]
[Black "Benoni: 3...Qb6 and 4...cxd4 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4
{ This is the most flexible move order ➼ making sure that we keep everything in London System teritory. For more details about the move order make sure to check out the informational. }
2... c5
{ This can be played by the Benoni One-Trick-Ponies, or by players who have this as a tricky line against the London System. }
3. e3
{ Preparing to meet ...cxd4 with exd4 and ➼ inviting Black to play  3...d5  which transposes back into the normal lines after  4.Nf3  .   The reason why I am not a huge fan of  3.d5  is because Black has an option of going  3...b5  and the resulting positions are very different compared to what we normally see in the London System. }
3... Qb6 4. Nc3
{ This is the universal reply to ...Qb6 that you are going to see in this course. Generally White has many alternatives, but in order to keep it simple, my advice is to always play Nc3 with the idea to meet 4...Qxb2 with 5. Nb5! }
4... cxd4
{ This is not a super theoretical line, but we get positions that are pretty chaotic ➼ so it's good to see how the game could go. }
5. exd4 Nc6
{ This is a bit better than 5...e6  because it keeps an eye on the d4-pawn, forcing us to play the less active Be2 move @@StartBracket@@instead of the ideal Bd3@@EndBracket@@ .   Whenever you see the move  5...d6  ,  it is generally a pretty good indicator that Black will go for a King's Indian setup.  6.Qd2!?  Anticipating their kingside fianchetto with an aggressive plan to castle long.  6...g6   The best try because  6...Qxb2  is losing after  7.Rb1  Qa3  8.Bb5+  Nbd7  9.Ba4!  with Rb3 next, and Black's queen is in trouble.  7.O-O-O  Bg7  8.Bh6  Going for the typical kingside play.  8...O-O  9.h4→  With h5 next, White has good attacking prospects on the kingside. }
6. Nf3 e6
{ The greedy  6...Qxb2  loses after the forced  7.Nb5  Nd5  8.Rb1  Qxa2  9.Bd2  a6  10.Ra1  Qb2  11.Bc4!  e6  12.Bb3  and Black's queen is in trouble after Rb1. }
7. a3
{ Stopping  7...Qxb2??  because of the typical  8.Na4!  ➼ trapping Black's queen. }
7... Be7 8. Be2 { Preparing O-O. } 8... O-O 9. O-O d5 10. Na4
{ This is a surprisingly strong maneuver. The knight is heading towards c5. }
10... Qd8 11. Re1 { Activating the rook. } 11... Bd7 12. Nc5
{ We can either support the knight with b4 next, or win the bishop pair with Nxd7 followed by c3-Bd3 with Ne5 being the main plan. }
