{ This is the most flexible move order ➼ making sure that we keep everything in London System teritory. For more details about the move order make sure to check out the informational. }
2... c5
{ This can be played by the Benoni One-Trick-Ponies, or by players who have this as a tricky line against the London System. }
3. e3
{ Preparing to meet ...cxd4 with exd4 and ➼ inviting Black to play  3...d5  which transposes back into the normal lines after  4.Nf3  .   The reason why I am not a huge fan of  3.d5  is because Black has an option of going  3...b5  and the resulting positions are very different compared to what we normally see in the London System. }
3... Qb6 4. Nc3
{ This is the universal reply to ...Qb6 that you are going to see in this course. Generally White has many alternatives, but in order to keep it simple, my advice is to always play Nc3 with the idea to meet 4...Qxb2 with 5. Nb5! }
4... cxd4
{ This is not a super theoretical line, but we get positions that are pretty chaotic ➼ so it's good to see how the game could go. }
5. exd4 a6
{ Threatening ...Qxb2 because there is no more Nb5 for White.   5...e6  also threatens ...Qxb2. We can keep it simple by playing  6.a3!  when 6...Qxb2 never works because of the classical trick with 7.Na4 ➼ trapping Black's queen.  6...Be7  7.Nf3  O-O  8.Bd3!  Developing the bishop on the most active square.  8...Nc6  9.O-O   We can safely castle because  9...Nxd4  10.Nxd4  Qxd4  11.Bxh7+!  wins the queen.  9...d5  10.Re1  Bd7  11.Na4!  Using the Na4-Nc5 plan.  11...Qd8  12.c3⩲  We can play Nc5 on the next move followed by b4-a4 with good play on the queenside. }
6. a3
{ The simplest way to deal with the  6...Qxb2  threat because we have the classical reply  7.Na4!  ➼ trapping Black's queen. }
6... d5 7. Nf3 { Now Black has a choice between:  7...Bg4  7... Nc6. } 7... Nc6
{ If  7...Bg4  we can gambit the d4-pawn with  8.h3!  Bxf3  9.Qxf3  e6   This is the safest because  9...Qxd4  10.Be3!  followed by O-O-O gives White a big initiative.  10.O-O-O  ⩲  We are ready to push on the kingside next with g4 with good attacking prospects. }
8. Na4
{ Forcing Black's queen to a passive square and preparing the typical Nc5 plan. }
8... Qa5+ 9. c3 { Blocking the check and defending the a4-knight. } 9... Bg4
{ Threatening to double our pawns with ...Bxf3! } 10. Be2
{ Preparing to meet  10...Bxf3  with  11.Bxf3  . } 10... e6 11. h3 Bh5 12. O-O
Be7 13. b4 { Taking space on the queenside and preparing Nc5! } 13... Qd8 14.
Nc5
{ With a better position for White thanks to the strong c5-knight.  14...Bxc5  is met by  15.bxc5!  with pressure on the b7-pawn. }
