[Round "?"]
[White "13) Benoni Defense"]
[Black "Benoni: 3...Qb6 and 4...d6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4
{ This is the most flexible move order ➼ making sure that we keep everything in London System teritory. For more details about the move order make sure to check out the informational. }
2... c5
{ This can be played by the Benoni One-Trick-Ponies, or by players who have this as a tricky line against the London System. }
3. e3
{ Preparing to meet ...cxd4 with exd4 and ➼ inviting Black to play  3...d5  which transposes back into the normal lines after  4.Nf3  .   The reason why I am not a huge fan of  3.d5  is because Black has an option of going  3...b5  and the resulting positions are very different compared to what we normally see in the London System. }
3... Qb6 4. Nc3
{ This is the universal reply to ...Qb6 that you are going to see in this course. Generally White has many alternatives, but in order to keep it simple, my advice is to always play Nc3 with the idea to meet 4...Qxb2 with 5. Nb5! }
4... d6
{ This is an interesting line for Black. After digging for quite a bit, I think I came up with a pretty simple and effective solution. }
5. Bb5+
{ This check already restrains Black's options quite dramatically because most of the people will play  5...Bd7  . However, we will also have a look at both  5...Nc6  and  5...Nbd7! }
5... Nbd7
{ This is played sometimes, but not as often as 5...Bd7!   5...Nc6  is not really a human move because allowing 6.d5! looks very scary!  6.d5!  a6  7.Ba4  Sidestepping Black's threat and keeping the pin.  7...Qc7  8.Nge2!  ⩲   This is important because  8.dxc6  b5!  would have allowed unnecessary counterplay.  Keep in mind that if Black goes  8...b5  the trick is to play  9.Nxb5  axb5  10.Bxb5  and only then collect the c6-knight! }
6. a4
{ This is the key idea to remember. We are taking space with a5 and only then do we step back with the bishop. }
6... a6 { Attacking the b5-bishop. } 7. a5
{ The point! Attacking Black's queen so we can keep the bishop without losing the b2-pawn. }
7... Qc7 8. Be2
{ This move is important because giving away the bishop pair with  8.Bxd7  would have been a serious mistake. }
8... g6 9. d5 { Getting into a good version of the Benoni. } 9... Bg7 10. e4
O-O 11. Nf3 { Preparing O-O. } 11... b5
{ This is the typical way to generate counterplay for Black in this structure, but it may also generate some weaknesses. }
12. axb6 Qxb6 { Attacking the b2-pawn. } 13. Ra2
{ We can finish development with 0-0 and White has a slightly better position because of the a6-pawn which is pretty weak. }
*

