{ The Stonewall Variation. Black weakens the e5-square, while getting a relatively simple game plan in return. Black usually plays something like ...c6-Be7-short castle-Ne4 with ...g5 ideas. This could be pretty effective against newer players, but if you know the right plans, Black's kingside play can be easily countered ➼ and they remain with a passive position, generally with a nice initiative for White on the queenside. }
5. c4
{ This is an important move in the Dutch, and it's something very important to clarify. People generally have trouble understanding when to play c3 or c4 in the London System. To sum things up, we always play with c4 against the Dutch Defense. The reason is that Black has more space on the kingside and they usually control the e5-square @@StartBracket@@except when they play the Stonewall@@EndBracket@@ ➼ making it impossible for us to use the standard plans with Ne5 that you see in the London mainlines. Therefore, the only side where we can create something ➼ is the queenside, which makes c4 mandatory. }
5... c6
{ The most common move for both OTB and online chess.   5...Bd6  is a rare move order, with the point to meet 6.Bxd6 with 6...cxd6.  6.Bxd6!  We don't really mind 6...cxd6 here, and 6...Qxd6 will transpose to the 6...Bd6-lines.  6...cxd6  7.Nc3  Threatening cxd5!  7...dxc4  8.Bxc4  d5  This is very common for the Stonewall players.  9.Bd3  O-O  10.O-O  Nc6  11.Rc1  Bd7  12.Bb5⩲  The whole gameplay is based around the e5-square. We can maneuver the knight with Ne2-Nf4-Nd3 followed by Bxc6 and White has full control over the e5-square. }
6. Nc3 { Now Black has a choice between two main plans:  6...Be7  6...Bd6. }
6... Be7
{ Keeping the dark-squared bishops on the board generally leads to a more complicated game ➼ which should still favor White. }
7. Bd3
{ The light-squared bishop is generally placed on e2 against the Dutch because Black has ...e5 ideas. However, specifically against the Stonewall ➼ the light-squared bishop is even better on d3 because it gives us ideas to maneuver the knight with Ne2 later on in the game. }
7... O-O 8. h3 { Avoiding ...Nh5 ideas because we can play Bh2! } 8... Ne4 9.
O-O Nd7 10. Rc1
{ This is a very useful move to have because our plan is to push with c5 followed by b4-b5 and we need to keep the c3-knight protected. Now Black has two main plans:  10...Ndf6  10...g5. }
10... g5
{ This is the most ambitious move for Black, and very typical for the Stonewall. Black's attack might look pretty scary at first side, but after you get more familiar with the positions, dealing with Black's attack will become a walk in the park! }
11. Bh2 Qe8
{ Preparing ...Qg6.   11...h5?!  is not a great move, but it's pretty common for online chess.  12.Ne5  Centralizing and attacking the h5-pawn.  12...g4  13.hxg4  hxg4  14.Bxe4!  Eliminating Black's knight and preparing a powerful combination because Black's 'attack' only created weaknesses that we can take advantage of.  14...dxe4  15.Nxe4!  +-  After this typical tactic White has a completely winning position because  15...fxe4  16.Qxg4+  gives White a powerful attack! }
12. Ne2
{ This is a very strong move ➼ anticipating Black's ...g4-break because we will have Nf4 ideas after that. }
12... Qg6 13. c5 { Preparing the typical queenside play with b4-b5! } 13... h5
14. b4 { Preparing to break with b5! } 14... g4 15. Ne5
{ This detail is important! Opening up the h-file with  15.hxg4  would only have helped Black ➼ opening up more lines for his pieces. The tactical justification of  15.Ne5  is  15...Nxe5  16.Bxe5  gxh3  17.Nf4!  winning back the h3-pawn with a much better position for White. }
15... Qg7 16. Kh1
{ Threatening to push f3 ➼ White dominates the game by controlling the e5-square. }
*

