[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "14) Dutch Defense"]
[Black "Dutch: 3...e6 with 4...d5 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 f5 2. Bf4 Nf6 3. e3 e6
{ After this move Black will take play into either the Stonewall or the Classical Dutch. }
4. Nf3 d5
{ The Stonewall Variation. Black weakens the e5-square, while getting a relatively simple game plan in return. Black usually plays something like ...c6-Be7-short castle-Ne4 with ...g5 ideas. This could be pretty effective against newer players, but if you know the right plans, Black's kingside play can be easily countered ➼ and they remain with a passive position, generally with a nice initiative for White on the queenside. }
5. c4
{ This is an important move in the Dutch, and it's something very important to clarify. People generally have trouble understanding when to play c3 or c4 in the London System. To sum things up, we always play with c4 against the Dutch Defense. The reason is that Black has more space on the kingside and they usually control the e5-square @@StartBracket@@except when they play the Stonewall@@EndBracket@@ ➼ making it impossible for us to use the standard plans with Ne5 that you see in the London mainlines. Therefore, the only side where we can create something ➼ is the queenside, which makes c4 mandatory. }
5... c6
{ The most common move for both OTB and online chess.   5...Bd6  is a rare move order, with the point to meet 6.Bxd6 with 6...cxd6.  6.Bxd6!  We don't really mind 6...cxd6 here, and 6...Qxd6 will transpose to the 6...Bd6-lines.  6...cxd6  7.Nc3  Threatening cxd5!  7...dxc4  8.Bxc4  d5  This is very common for the Stonewall players.  9.Bd3  O-O  10.O-O  Nc6  11.Rc1  Bd7  12.Bb5⩲  The whole gameplay is based around the e5-square. We can maneuver the knight with Ne2-Nf4-Nd3 followed by Bxc6 and White has full control over the e5-square. }
6. Nc3 { Now Black has a choice between two main plans:  6...Be7  6...Bd6. }
6... Bd6 { This is by far the most common move for online chess. } 7. Bxd6
{ Generally speaking the bishop trade should give us better control over the e5-square and it will decrease Black's chances of an attack on the kingside. }
7... Qxd6 8. Bd3
{ The light-squared bishop is generally developed to e2 against the Dutch because Black has ...e5 ideas. However, specifically against the Stonewall ➼ the light-squared bishop is even better on d3 because it gives us ideas to maneuver the knight with Ne2 later on in the game. }
8... O-O 9. O-O Ne4 10. Qb3
{ Creating a tactical threat of cxd5 and taking twice on e4. } 10... Nd7
{ This is natural, but it ignores White's last move. } 11. cxd5 exd5
{ The desired move strategically speaking, but it fails tactically!   11...cxd5  has to be played not to lose the pawn.  12.Rfc1  Threatening to infiltrate with Nb5-Nc7!  12...a6  13.Ne2⩲  We can trade queens next with Qa3 and White has a risk-free push in the endgame. }
12. Bxe4 fxe4 13. Nxe4
{ Taking advantage of the fact that the d5-pawn is pinned! White is simply up a pawn with a winning position. }
