[White "14) Dutch Defense"]
[Black "Dutch: 3...e6 with 4...b6"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 f5 2. Bf4 Nf6 3. e3 e6
{ After this move Black will take play into either the Stonewall or the Classical Dutch. }
4. Nf3 b6
{ This move will most likely transpose back into the Classical Dutch with  4...Be7  and 6...b6 ➼ but Black can also deviate and play with ...Bd6!? which can be annoying to deal with if you see it for the first time. }
5. Be2 { Preparing O-O. } 5... Bb7 6. O-O Bd6
{ This is an interesting sideline for Black. Personally I find it tricky to make progress after  7.Bxd6  cxd6  , so I prefer to allow the doubling with  7.c4  Bxf4  8.exf4  . At this point it's a matter of style because both lines are perfectly playable. }
7. c4
{ This is an important move in the Dutch, and it's something very important to clarify. People generally have trouble understanding when to play c3 or c4 in the London System. To sum things up, we always play with c4 against the Dutch Defense. The reason for that is because Black has more space on the kingside and they usually control the e5-square @@StartBracket@@except when they play the Stonewall@@EndBracket@@ ➼ making it impossible for us to use the standard plans with Ne5 that you see in the main lines. Therefore, the only side of the board where we can create something ➼ is the queenside, which makes c4 mandatory. }
7... Bxf4 { This has to be played sooner or later. } 8. exf4 O-O 9. Nc3 Ne4
{ This is important for Black because  9...d6  10.d5!  gives White a big advantage. }
10. Rc1
{ White should look out to break with d5 and we can improve our position with Re1,Bf1,g3,Bg2.   Keep in mind that  10...d6  runs into  11.Nxe4  Bxe4  12.Ng5! }
