[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "14) Dutch Defense"]
[Black "Dutch: 3...e6 with 4...Be7 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 f5 2. Bf4 Nf6 3. e3 e6
{ After this move Black will take play into either the Stonewall or the Classical Dutch. }
4. Nf3 Be7
{ The Classical Dutch. In this variation Black has two big plans. The most common plan is to play with ...b6-Bb7 and the other one is to focus on the ...e5-break. This variation is the most balanced compared to the Leningrad Dutch and the Stonewall. }
5. h3
{ This is a useful move to have because we can meet ...Nh5 ideas with Bh2! }
5... O-O 6. Be2
{ This is where the light-squared bishop normally belongs in the Dutch Defense @@StartBracket@@except when they play the Stonewall@@EndBracket@@. The e2-square is the safest because the bishop on d3 is vulnerable to ...e5-e4 ideas by Black  @@StartBracket@@which is never a thing in the Stonewall@@EndBracket@@. }
6... d6
{ This is an aggressive way of playing ➼ preparing the ...e5-break with ideas such as ...Qe8-Bd8 followed by ...e5! }
7. O-O Nc6
{ 7...Qe8  8.c4!  This is an important move in the Dutch, and it's something very important to clarify. As I've mentioned a few times by now, we always play with c4 against the Dutch, because the queenside is where we should create our play.  8...Bd8  9.Nc3  Nbd7  Preparing to push ... e5!  10.b4  Preparing the standard queenside play with c5!  10...e5  11.Bh2⩲  We can break with c5 on the next move with pressure on the queenside. }
8. Bh2
{ This is the most precise because  8.c4  Ne4  followed by ...Bf6 and ...e5 gives Black good counterplay. }
8... Qe8
{ This is a typical idea, not only preparing ...Qh5, but also making room for ...Bd8!   8...Ne4  9.Nbd2  Threatening Nxe4 followed by Nd2 with a typical advantage for White.  9...Nxd2  10.Qxd2  Bf6  11.b4⩲  We can continue with c4 and then we decide between breaking with c5 or advancing the a-pawn with a4-a5. In both cases White has pressure on the queenside. }
9. c4
{ You know the drill by now - against the Dutch, we always play c2-c4 instead of c2-c3! }
9... Bd8 { Preparing the ...e5-break! } 10. Nc3 e5 11. dxe5
{ 11.c5  was also interesting, but this works even better. } 11... dxe5 12. c5
{ Threatening to push b4 on the next move with a nice initiative on the queenside for White. Keep in mind that something like  12...a5  can be met by  13.Bb5!  with a big advantage for White. }
*

