[Black "Dutch: 3...g6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 f5 2. Bf4 Nf6 3. e3 g6 { The Leningrad Dutch. } 4. Nf3 Bg7 5. Be2
{ This is where the light-squared bishop normally belongs in the Dutch Defense  @@StartBracket@@except when they play the Stonewall@@EndBracket@@. The e2-square is the safest because the bishop on d3 is vulnerable to ...e5-e4 ideas by Black @@StartBracket@@which is never a thing in the Stonewall@@EndBracket@@ . }
5... d6 6. h3
{ This is a useful move to have because we can meet ...Nh5 ideas with Bh2! }
6... O-O 7. O-O Qe8
{ This is a typical square for the queen, preparing the ...e5-break! } 8. c4
{ This is an important move in the Dutch, and it's something very important to clarify. People generally have trouble understanding when to play c3 or c4 in the London System. To sum things up, we always play c4 against the Dutch Defense. The reason is that Black has more space on the kingside and they are usually controlling the e5-square @@StartBracket@@except when they play the Stonewall@@EndBracket@@ ➼ making it impossible for us to use the standard plans with Ne5 that you see in the main lines. Therefore, the only side where we can create something ➼ is on the queenside, which makes c4 mandatory. }
8... Nbd7
{ Preparing to break with ...e5!  8...Nc6  will transpose to 7.O-O Nc6. } 9.
Nc3 e5 10. Bh2
{ This move is important because the computer will generally suggest both dxe5 and Bh2 as perfectly playable options. Personally, I think keeping the tension works much better because White has ideas to break with c5 that are very powerful and surprising for your opponent. White is already threatening to play Nb5 or c5! }
10... e4
{ Taking space and attacking the f3-knight ➼ this is the most common move for Black in online chess. Although this looks pretty tempting for Black, we are very happy to see it because it activates the h2-bishop! It's hard to suggest anything else because Nb5 was a huge threat. }
11. Nd2 { Threatening a juicy combo with c5 followed by ...dxc5 Nb5! } 11... g5
{ Trying to create an attack, but our position on the kingside is very safe, and we can grab the initiative on the queenside!   11...Qe7  is a better defense for Black, making the immediate c5 less effective.  12.b4  Preparing the c5-break!  12...c6  This is very common for online chess.  13.c5  d5  14.b5±  This is even stronger than collecting the exchange with  14.Bd6!  White's next move is Qa4 and Black's queenside is about to collapse. }
12. c5 { Threatening cxd6! } 12... dxc5 13. Nb5
{ This is the trick! We don't play the soft  13.Bxc7  because it's going to be much better for us to capture on c7 with the knight! White is completely winning with the knight coming over to c7 on the next move. }
