8... Ne4 { This is played with the idea of trading a pair of knights. } 9. Nbd2
{ Threatening  9...--  10.Nxe4  followed by  10...fxe4  11.Nd2!  with a typical advantage for White in the Dutch. }
9... e5 10. dxe5 dxe5
{ This would be a disaster for Black.   10...Nxe5?!  is also a pretty big inaccuracy because White is much better after the upcoming forced moves:  11.Nxe4!   The point is to meet  11...fxe4  with  12.Nxe5  ➼ ruining Black's pawns.  11...Nxf3+  12.Bxf3  fxe4  13.Bxe4  Bxb2  14.Rb1±  Black has to move away the b2-bishop and we can collect the b7-pawn on the next move with a winning position. }
11. Nxe4 fxe4 12. Bc4+ { Going for a winning endgame. } 12... Kh8 13. Qxd8 Rxd8
14. Ng5 { And White is winning the e4-pawn at the very least. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "14) Dutch Defense"]
[Black "Dutch: 3...g6 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 f5 2. Bf4 Nf6 3. e3 g6 { The Leningrad Dutch. } 4. Nf3 Bg7 5. Be2
{ This is where the light-squared bishop normally belongs in the Dutch Defense  @@StartBracket@@except when they play the Stonewall@@EndBracket@@. The e2-square is the safest because the bishop on d3 is vulnerable to ...e5-e4 ideas by Black @@StartBracket@@which is never a thing in the Stonewall@@EndBracket@@ . }
5... d6 6. h3
{ This is a useful move to have because we can meet ...Nh5 ideas with Bh2! }
6... O-O 7. O-O Nc6
{ I couldn't find too many OTB games with this move, but it's actually very popular in online chess. }
8. Bh2
{ This works best because  8.d5?!  allows a typical trick:  8...e5!  with good play in the center for Black.   The other candidate move  8.c4  would also allow some counterplay after  8...Ne4! }
8... Ne4 { This is played with the idea of trading a pair of knights. } 9. Nbd2
{ Threatening  9...--  10.Nxe4  followed by  10...fxe4  11.Nd2!  with a typical advantage for White in the Dutch. }
9... e5 10. dxe5 Nxd2
{ This intermezzo keeps the situation under control for Black. } 11. Qxd2 Nxe5
{ This has to be played because  11...dxe5  12.Bc4+  Kh8  13.Qxd8  Rxd8  14.Ng5!  wins for White. }
12. Bxe5
{ This is an interesting try for White because  12...Bxe5  13.Qd5+!  wins on the spot. }
12... dxe5 { Forced. } 13. Bc4+
{ Forcing Black's king in the corner so we can use the Ng5 motif. } 13... Kh8
14. Qxd8 Rxd8 15. Ng5
{ With a dangerous position for Black with Nf7-Nxe5 looming. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "14) Dutch Defense"]
[Black "Dutch: 3...g6 #4"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 f5 2. Bf4 Nf6 3. e3 g6 { The Leningrad Dutch. } 4. Nf3 Bg7 5. Be2
{ This is where the light-squared bishop normally belongs in the Dutch Defense  @@StartBracket@@except when they play the Stonewall@@EndBracket@@. The e2-square is the safest because the bishop on d3 is vulnerable to ...e5-e4 ideas by Black @@StartBracket@@which is never a thing in the Stonewall@@EndBracket@@ . }
5... d6 6. h3
{ This is a useful move to have because we can meet ...Nh5 ideas with Bh2! }
6... O-O 7. O-O Nc6
{ I couldn't find too many OTB games with this move, but it's actually very popular in online chess. }
8. Bh2
{ This works best because  8.d5?!  allows a typical trick:  8...e5!  with good play in the center for Black.   The other candidate move  8.c4  would also allow some counterplay after  8...Ne4! }
8... Qe8 9. c4 e5 10. Nc3
{ Keeping the tension and creating a threat of going c5! } 10... e4
{ Taking space and attacking the f3-knight ➼ this is the most common move for Black in online chess. Although this looks pretty tempting for Black, we are very happy to see it because it activates the h2-bishop! }
11. Nd2 g5
{ Trying to create some attack, but our king is pretty safe and we can take over the initiative on the other side of the board. }
12. c5
{ Taking over the initiative on the queenside. This is the key idea to keep in mind while playing against the Leningrad Dutch. }
12... dxc5
{ 12...f4  tries to make a mess.  13.Nb5  Attacking both c7 and d6 while defending the d4-pawn.  13...Qe7  14.cxd6  cxd6  15.exf4±  Collecting a free pawn. It's not obvious where Black's attack is. }
13. Nb5
{ This is the trick! We don't play the soft  13.Bxc7  because it's going to be much better for us to capture on c7 with the knight! White is much better with the knight coming over to c7 on the next move. }
*

