[White "14) Dutch Defense"]
[Black "Dutch: 3...g6 #6"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 f5 2. Bf4 Nf6 3. e3 g6 { The Leningrad Dutch. } 4. Nf3 Bg7 5. Be2
{ This is where the light-squared bishop normally belongs in the Dutch Defense  @@StartBracket@@except when they play the Stonewall@@EndBracket@@. The e2-square is the safest because the bishop on d3 is vulnerable to ...e5-e4 ideas by Black @@StartBracket@@which is never a thing in the Stonewall@@EndBracket@@ . }
5... d6 6. h3
{ This is a useful move to have because we can meet ...Nh5 ideas with Bh2! }
6... O-O 7. O-O Nc6
{ I couldn't find too many OTB games with this move, but it's actually very popular in online chess. }
8. Bh2
{ This works best because  8.d5?!  allows a typical trick:  8...e5!  with good play in the center for Black.   The other candidate move  8.c4  would also allow some counterplay after  8...Ne4! }
8... Qe8 9. c4 e5 10. Nc3
{ Keeping the tension and creating a threat of going c5! } 10... e4
{ Taking space and attacking the f3-knight ➼ this is the most common move for Black in online chess. Although this looks pretty tempting for Black, we are very happy to see it because it activates the h2-bishop! }
11. Nd2 Ne7
{ Preparing ...g5 followed by ...Ng6 ➼ this is a common plan for Black in the Dutch, but it's just too slow here! }
12. c5
{ Taking the initiative over the queenside. This is the key idea to keep in mind while playing against the Leningrad Dutch. }
12... dxc5 13. dxc5
{ Keep in mind that we are threatening Bxc7 which a lot of players tend to forget about. }
13... c6 14. Qb3+
{ Not the only move, but throwing in this check is very useful because it stops Black from playing ... Be6! }
14... Ned5 15. Nc4
{ We are going to plant the knight on d6 next with a huge advantage. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Typical Tactics"]
[Black "Introduction"]
[Result "*"]

{ Tactics in the London?! What kind of joke is this, you may be wondering! This chapter will have a really big impact on your London System overall because most people tend to call our beloved opening 'boring', which makes them vulnerable to our toolkit of deadly tactics!   The London System is a solid opening, sometimes very positional, but more often than not ➼ we have to use small tactics to control the board.   I recommend you go over these puzzles at least five times at first @@StartBracket@@getting that pattern recognition rolling@@EndBracket@@ and then it could be a good idea to go over the puzzles again once a month to stay in shape. }
1. -- *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Typical Tactics"]
[Black "Chigorin #1"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r2q1rk1/ppp1nppp/2nb4/3pp3/3P1B2/2PBPQ1P/PP1N1PP1/R3K2R w KQ - 0 2"]
[SetUp "1"]

2. dxe5 Nxe5 3. Bxe5 { Luring Black's bishop onto a mined square! } 3... Bxe5
4. Bxh7+
{ The point! Thanks to this move White manages to keep control of the critical e5-square in a lot of variations. }
4... Kxh7 5. Qh5+ { Forking black's king and bishop. } 5... Kg8 6. Qxe5
{ White is up a clean pawn with a winning position. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Typical Tactics"]
[Black "Chigorin #2"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r2qk2r/ppp1bppp/2n2n2/3p1bB1/3P4/2N1PN2/PP3PPP/R2QKB1R w KQkq - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

1. Bxf6 { Eliminating the main defender of the d5-pawn. } 1... Bxf6 2. Qb3
{ Winning a pawn. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Typical Tactics"]
[Black "Chigorin #3"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r2qk2r/ppp2pp1/2nbpn1p/5bB1/2BP4/2N1PN2/PP3PPP/R2QK2R w KQkq - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

1. Bxf6
{ Generally we try to avoid giving up the bishop for knight if possible, but not when there is a concrete motif! }
1... Qxf6 2. e4 { Attacking the f5-bishop and preparing to push e5! } 2... Bg4
3. e5
{ Winning a piece. Black gets some compensation in this particular case, but that's not really the goal of our puzzle ➼ just make sure to remember this pattern! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Typical Tactics"]
[Black "Chigorin #4"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1bqr1k1/pppn1ppp/2nbp3/3pN3/3P1B2/2PBP3/PP1N1PPP/R2QK2R w KQ - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ Black has just played ...Nd7 ➼ trying to get rid of the e5-knight, but it's given us a golden opportunity! }
1. Bxh7+ Kxh7 2. Qh5+
{ This works well because the f7-square is vulnerable  @@StartBracket@@this is a common pattern with when black played ...Re8@@EndBracket@@. }
2... Kg8 3. Qxf7+ Kh8 4. Bg5
{ According to the computer  4.Ng6+  is even stronger, but I wanted to show this cool idea. We are deflecting Black's queen from defending the e8-rook. }
4... Qxg5
{ 4...Re7  This would be best defense.  5.Bxe7  Nxe7  6.Ndf3+-  With a long-term initiative for white. }
5. Qxe8+ Kh7 6. Nxd7
{ We are up an exchange and two pawns with a completely winning position. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Typical Tactics"]
[Black "Chigorin #5"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r2qkb1r/ppp2ppp/2n1pn2/1B1p3b/3P1B2/4PN1P/PPP2PP1/RN1QK2R w KQkq - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

1. g4
{ This is a theoretical position, but I think it makes sense to be included in this section because it's very concrete and might help you learn the idea faster. We are breaking the pin while gaining a tempo! Ne5 is coming on the next move. }
1... Bg6 2. Ne5
{ Increasing the pressure on the c6-knight. Black has not an easy task to defend the c6-knight. }
2... Bd6
{ This is the most common move in online chess ➼ giving White a free win. For more details make sure to check this out in the theory chapter. }
3. Nxc6 bxc6 4. Bxc6+ { Winning the exchange. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Typical Tactics"]
[Black "Copycat #1"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r2q1rk1/pp1n1ppp/2pbpn2/3pN3/3P1B2/3PPQ2/PP1N1PPP/R4RK1 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

1. Nxc6
{ This is a typical trick to watch out for. The main theme is that the d6-bishop is undefended.   Usually White has a choice between the text move and  1.Nxf7  , but in this particular case Black would have  1...Rxf7  2.Bxd6  Ne4!  taking over the initiative. }
1... bxc6
{ 1...Qc7!  This would have been a better defensive try! @@StartBracket@@keep in mind that usually Black does not have this resource@@EndBracket@@  2.Ne5  Nxe5  3.dxe5  Bxe5  4.Rfc1⩲  With only a small edge for White thanks to the c-file. }
2. Bxd6 { With an extra pawn for White. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Typical Tactics"]
[Black "Copycat #2"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1q2rk1/p1pn1ppp/1p1bpn2/3p4/3P4/1QNPPNB1/PP3PPP/2R1K2R w K - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

1. Nxd5
{ Exploiting the pin. Here you can see a classical example of why it is very dangerous to have the queen placed on the same file with the enemy rook. Don't be surprised if tactics like this happen! }
1... Nxd5
{ 1...Bxg3??  Trying to save the bishop, but blundering the fork.  2.Ne7++-  Winning the queen. }
2. Bxd6 { With an extra pawn and a winning position for White. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Typical Tactics"]
[Black "Copycat #3"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r2q1rk1/p4ppp/1pnppn2/3p4/3P4/1QNPPN2/PP3PPP/2R1K2R w K - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

1. Nxd5 { Exploiting the undefended c6-knight! } 1... Nxd5
{ 1...Na5  Counter attacking, but not saving the day because of the intermezzo.  2.Nxf6+±  Thanks to this move White keeps a healthy extra pawn. }
2. Rxc6 { With an extra pawn for White. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Typical Tactics"]
[Black "Slav #1"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1q1k2r/pp1nbppp/2p2n2/3p1b2/3P1B2/1QN1PN2/PP3PPP/2R1KB1R w Kkq - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

1. Nb5
{ This is a theoretical trap coming from the Slav Defense. It has been covered in the Theory Chapter, but still I think it's useful to have it here to refresh your memory. White has a big threat of playing Nc7! }
1... O-O 2. Bd6
{ This is the key move to remember because  2...Bxd6  loses after  3.Nxd6  attacking both the c8-queen and the f5-bishop. }
2... Qd8 3. Qa3 { Another important move ➼ putting pressure on the e7-bishop! }
3... Re8 { 3...Bxd6  4.Nxd6+-  White wins the b7-pawn next. } 4. Bxe7 Rxe7
{ 4...Qxe7  5.Nc7+-  Winning the exchange. } 5. Nd6
{ Winning the b7-pawn with a technically won position for White. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Typical Tactics"]
[Black "Slav #2"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r2qkb1r/p2n1ppp/1pp1pn2/3p1b2/2PP1B2/1QN1PN2/PP3PPP/R3KB1R w KQkq - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

1. cxd5
{ Opening up bishop's path! This is another very common trap seen in the Slav Defense. }
1... exd5 2. Ba6
{ This stunning move takes a lot of people by surprise. There is simply no way to defend against Bb7 which picks up the exchange. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Typical Tactics"]
[Black "Slav #3"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "2r1k2r/1pbn1ppp/p1p1pn2/2Pp1b2/1P1P1B2/1NN1P2P/1P3PP1/R3KB1R w KQk - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

1. Bxc7
{ This one is an endgame trick despite being a pretty famous opening trap! }
1... Rxc7 2. b5 cxb5 3. Nxb5
{ The key move! ➼ taking advantage of the fact that Black has not castled yet. In case of  3...Rc6  white simply wins with  4.Nd6+  . }
3... axb5 4. Ra8+ Ke7 5. Rxh8
{ With a winning endgame thanks to the extra exchange. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Typical Tactics"]
[Black "QGD #1"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1bq1rk1/pp1nbppp/2p1p3/3pP3/5B1P/3BP3/PPPN1PP1/R2QK2R w KQ - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

1. Bxh7+
{ This is a typical motif when white has delayed O-O against the ...Be7 lines. This motif is also covered in the model game between Kovacevic-Ree, Maribor 1980. }
1... Kxh7 2. Qh5+
{ This is important to start with because  2.Nf3  Rh8!  wins for Black. } 2...
Kg8 3. Nf3
{ Threatening to play Ng5 and recapture with the h-pawn ➼ creating a deadly mating net. }
3... f6 { Trying to discourage White from playing Ng5. } 4. Ng5
{ This is the whole point of having played h4 earlier! White is able to get an overwhelming initiative after opening up the h-file for the rook. }
4... fxg5 5. hxg5
{ Threatening to push g6 ➼ trapping Black's king in a mating net. } 5... Rxf4
{ This is what people usually played against me ➼ desperately trying to make room for the king.   5...Bxg5  This would be a better try for Black.  6.Bxg5  Attacking the d8-queen.  6...Qa5+  7.c3  Blocking the check.  7...Nxe5  This might look like Black's getting very good counterplay, but White has it all under control:  8.Qh7+  Kf7  9.f4!  Attacking the e5-knight ➼ this is the most precise, even though 9.Rh4 @@StartBracket@@with idea to play Rf4+@@EndBracket@@ is generally a very strong idea.  9...Nc4  10.Rh6+-  Creating a deadly threat of playing Rf6+ next ➼ White has a crushing attack! }
6. Qh8+ Kf7 7. g6+ { This leads to a forced mate. } 7... Kxg6 8. Qh5#
{ I had this exact checkmate countless times! } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Typical Tactics"]
[Black "QGD #2"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "2rq1rk1/pp1bbpp1/2n1pn1p/2ppN3/3P1B2/2PBP2Q/PP1N1PPP/R3K2R w KQ - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ This is a typical position for the Ne5 plan with the dark squared bishop on f4. White has just played the critical Qf3-Qh3 maneuver and now it's time to collect the goods. }
1. Bxh6 gxh6 2. Qxh6
{ Black's king is completely naked and White has a simple threat of playing h4 followed by Rh3-Rg3 with a brutal checkmate. }
2... Re8
{ Threatening to play ...Bf8!   2...Ne4  3.h4!  Preparing the typical Rh3-Rg3!  3...f5  4.Nxe4  fxe4  5.Rh3+-  With Rg3 on the next move and Black is getting mated. }
3. Ng4
{ This is the key move to get a winning position, otherwise Black would have been in time with ...Bf8! }
3... e5
{ This allows a standard pattern.   3...Ne4  4.Bxe4!  This is important so we can get the d2-knight to f6!  4...dxe4  5.Nxe4+-  With Nf6+ coming on the next move ➼ white has a crushing attack..   3...Nxg4  4.Qh7+  Kf8  5.Qh8 }
4. Nxf6+ Bxf6 5. Bh7+ { Luring Black's king in the corner. } 5... Kh8 6. Bg6+
{ This is the key detail to remember ➼ controlling the f7-square! } 6... Kg8 7.
Qh7+ Kf8 8. Qxf7# { With a standard checkmate. } *

