[Round "?"]
[White "Typical Tactics"]
[Black "QGD #4"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1b1r1k1/ppqn1ppp/2nbp3/3pN3/3P1P2/2PB2B1/PP1N2PP/R2QK2R w KQ - 0 2"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ Black has just played ...Nd7 hoping to get rid of our strong knight by pushing ...f6 next! }
2. Bxh7+
{ This move works very well because the f7-square is vulnerable @@StartBracket@@not to mention the ...Re8@@EndBracket@@! }
2... Kxh7 3. Qh5+ Kg8 4. Qxf7+ { Forking the king and rook. } 4... Kh7 5. Qxe8
{ With a completely winning position thanks to the extra exchange. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Typical Tactics"]
[Black "QGD #5"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r4rk1/pp1bqppp/2nbp3/2pp4/3P4/2PBP1B1/PP1N1PPP/R2QK2R w KQ - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

1. Bxd6 { The start of a nice combination. } 1... Qxd6 2. dxc5
{ Luring Black's queen to a vulnerable square. } 2... Qxc5 3. Bxh7+
{ The point of the previous play. } 3... Kxh7 4. Qh5+ Kg8 5. Ne4
{ This is why it was important to play 2.dxc5 ➼ attracting Black's queen to a vulnerable square. }
5... Qc4 6. Ng5 { Threatening Qh7#. } 6... Qd3
{ Covering the h7-square and threatening to play ...Qg6!   6...Rfd8  This was featured in the famous game between Kamsky-Shankland.  7.Qxf7+  Kh8  Threatening to bring the queen over with ...Qh4!  8.Qh5+!  This is very important to include in order to stop Black from playing ...Qh4!  8...Kg8  9.Rd1  Stopping ...Qd3 so we can play f4 followed by Rf1-Rf3-Rh3 with a direct checkmate.  9...e5  Stopping White from pushing f4!  10.Qf7+  Kh8  11.e4+-  Threatening Qg6 followed by Rxd5! with a completely winning position since Black can hardly make any moves. White went on to win in Kamsky,G @@StartBracket@@2709@@EndBracket@@-Shankland,S @@StartBracket@@2611@@EndBracket@@ Sturbridge 2014. }
7. e4
{ This is the key move to block the enemy queen from coming over to the kingside. }
7... Rfd8 8. Qxf7+ Kh8 9. Rd1 Qc4 { Stopping White from castling. } 10. f4
{ After this move White is completely winning because Black can barely make any moves without huge material losses. The simple plan is to play Rf1 followed by Rf3-Rh3! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Typical Tactics"]
