[SetUp "1"]

{ This is a classical example of White squeezing Black's position in the 'Berkes structure'. While White methodically improved all the pieces, Black only weakened himself trying to cover the critical squares. }
1. Nxe6+
{ The point of this is to deflect Black's queen from defending the g6-square. }
1... Bxe6 2. Rxe6 Rxe6 3. Rxe6 Qxe6 4. Qxg6+
{ Black's next move is forced because  4...Kh8  leads to a direct mate after  5.Qh7#  . }
4... Kf8 5. Ng5
{ The hidden point. The knight is untouchable because the e6-queen drops, and it becomes impossible for Black to defend because they have to keep the f7-square under control. }
5... Qd7
{ 5...Qe7  loses directly:  6.Nh7+  Qxh7  7.Qxh7+-  With an extra queen for white.   5...Qe8  allows a forced mate after  6.Qxf6+  6...Kg8  7.Bh7+-   5...Qg8!?  is perhaps the toughest defense.  6.Qxf6+  Ke8  7.Bh7!!  This is the key move, but I think somewhat findable. Of course, it's hard to see it from the very beginning, but if you manage to see 5.Ng5 it definitely looks very promising and you don't have to see all the moves in advance to play it.  7...Qf8  8.Qe6+   Everything is forced because  8...Ne7  9.Bg6+  is deadly for Black.  8...Qe7  9.Bg6+  Kf8  10.Qf5+  Kg7  Everything was forced until this moment.  11.Bxh5!  Creating a deadly threat of Qh7+.  11...Rh8  12.Qg6+  Kf8  13.Ne6++-  Winning Black's queen. A long line, but good for practising forced variations! }
6. Qxf6+ Kg8 7. Bh7+
{ Winning the queen is the easiest even though  7.Bf5  is a bit more precise according to the computer. }
*

