[Result "*"]
[FEN "2rr2k1/1p3p2/2n1pbp1/2qp4/p4P2/P1PQ1NP1/1P3PB1/2R1R1K1 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

1. Rxe6
{ This is a typical motif for the 'Berkes structure' after White has pushed h4-h5 and weakened Black's king with hxg6! Please notice that with the black pieces we have Alexander Grischuk. }
1... fxe6 2. Qxg6+ Bg7 { Forced. } 3. Bh3
{ The key move! Bringing the bishop with deadly effect.  3.Ng5  was also winning, but is a bit worse compared to  3.Bh3! }
3... Re8
{ 3...Qe7  This would have been probably the toughest defense.  4.Bxe6+  4...Kf8   Forced because Black is getting mated after  4...Kh8  5.Ng5!  5.Ng5  5...Qe8  6.Qf5+  6...Ke7  7.Bxc8  Time to collect the goods.  7...Rxc8  8.Re1++-  Winning the queen.   3...Rc7  4.Ng5  Threatening Qh7+ followed by Nxe6 picking up the queen.  4...Re7  5.Bxe6+  Rxe6  Forced as otherwise Black was getting mated immediately.  6.Qxe6+  Kh8  7.Kg2+-  After this stylish move White is going to play Rh1 with a mating attack. }
4. Bxe6+ { Black has to allow mate or suffer huge material losses. } 4... Rxe6
{ 4...Kh8  5.Qh5+  5...Bh6  6.Qxh6  With a standard checkmate. } 5. Qxe6+
{ Picking up the c8-rook next with a completely winning position for White. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Typical Tactics"]
[Black "Nihal, Sarin vs. Grigorian, Spartak, Menorca 2022"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1b1r1k1/pp3pp1/1qnpp2p/8/3PB3/2P2NP1/PP3PP1/R1Q1K2R w KQ - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

1. Rxh6
{ This is clearly the move! The variation is harder to calculate until the very end, but it's a safe sacrifice since White has at least a perpetual. }
1... gxh6
{ 1...f5  This was played in Nihal's game.  2.Qg5!!  With multiple threats such as Qg6-Ng5 or the direct Rh8+.  2...Qxb2  Attacking the a1-rook.  3.Rh8+!!  Nihal is deadly in such positions. All of White's moves are coming with tempo.  3...Kxh8  4.Qh5+  4...Kg8  5.Qxe8+  Kh7  Everything was forced until here. There is only one last hope for Black ➼ the a1-rook.  6.Rb1!  The final touch. After this move Black has no threats and we get a free hand on the kingside.  6...Qxa2  7.g4+-  White had a number of winning moves, but this is the most precise. The threat is to play  --  8.Ng5+  followed by  8...Kh6  9.Qh5#  and for this reason Black had to resign. }
2. Qxh6 { Threatening a forced pattern checkmate with Bh7+. } 2... f5
{ Avoiding Bh7+! When you see Black has this move, you don't really need to see everything till the very end. For example you can consider Qg6+ and Ng5 ideas and try to evaluate the position. I would adise you to go for it anyways if you are having troubles deciding whether it's winning or not. At the very least you can force a draw with a perpetual check, and most of the times it will be easier to find new ideas once you get the position on the board.Quick note:This is a good strategy when 1.Rxh6 was the only promising continuation. If you have other alternatives that are less risky, I would advise to pick the safer option if it's promising enough.   2...Qxb2  This would have allowed forced mate.  3.Bh7+!  3...Kh8  4.Bg6+!!  This is the important part! Placing the bishop on g6 so we can continue with Qh7 followed by Qf7#!  4...Kg8  5.Qh7+  5...Kf8  6.Qxf7  Notice how important it was to place the bishop on g6! }
3. Qg6+ Kf8 { 3...Kh8  4.O-O-O  +-  Allows a direct checkmate with Rh1+ next. }
4. Qf6+ Kg8 5. Ng5 { Threatening Qf7 with mate on h7. } 5... Qc7
{ 5...Re7  6.Qg6+!   Forcing ...Kf8 because  6...Rg7  leads to a mate after  7.Qe8#  .  6...Kf8  7.O-O-O !!  Black is up a rook but he's simply defenseless against Rh1-Rh8!  7...Nd8  8.Rh1  Nf7  Stopping Rh8!  9.Rh7+-  With a crushing attack for White. }
6. Qg6+ { Forcing ...Kf8. } 6... Kf8 7. Bxc6
{ This is the simplest because  7...Qxc6  now allows  8.Qf7#  . } 7... bxc6 8.
Nh7+ Ke7 { Forced. } 9. Qg5+
{ The key move! Black has no good square for the king. } 9... Kf7
{ 9...Kd7  10.Nf6+  Kd8  11.Nd5++-  Winning the queen. } 10. Qf6+ Kg8 11. Qg6+
Kh8 { 11...Qg7  12.Nf6++-  With Qxe8 on the next move. } 12. Nf6
{ Cleanest! Black is unable to stop checkmate on the h-file. } *

