[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Typical Endgames"]
[Black "Introduction"]
[Result "*"]

{ I already see that a lot of players will neglect this chapter, but let me make things clear before you skip it too. Personally, I don't recommend spending most of your time on endgames @@StartBracket@@especially as a beginner@@EndBracket@@, because you can get away by knowing how to convert positions with extra material and standard drawing mechanisms like Philidor's position and so on.   Studying a lot of 'random endgames' might not really pay off in the near future because let's be honest, if you are a beginner ➼ the game is usually decided in the middlegame.   However, there is a pretty big catch with Thematic London System endgames because in this opening, oftentimes @@StartBracket@@in the ...c5 main lines@@EndBracket@@ we are playing Qb3, and the opponent replies with ...Qb6 and we get an endgame by move ten. Understanding how to play these typical endgames will make you step away from the main crowd of players and will also improve you as a player in general.   What are you waiting for? ➼ here is a beautiful game that will change your mind about the London System endgames: Grachev-Rychagov, 2010. }
1. -- *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Typical Endgames"]
[Black "Artemiev, Vladislav vs. Savchenko, Boris, Chess24 2021"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. Bf4 c5 4. e3 d5 5. Nbd2 Nc6 6. c3 Bd6 7. Bg3 O-O 8. Bd3
b6 9. Qe2 Bb7 10. Rd1 Qe7 11. e4 dxe4 12. Nxe4 Nxe4 13. Bxe4 cxd4 14. Bxd6 Qxd6
15. Nxd4 Qc5 16. Qb5 { Forcing a very unpleasant endgame for Black! } 16...
Qxb5 17. Nxb5 { Threatening to play Nd6! } 17... Na5
{ Exchanging White's powerful bishop and defending against the direct Nd6 threat. }
18. Bxb7 Nxb7 19. Ke2
{ The king becomes an attacking piece in the endgame.  19.O-O  Rfd8  would give Black very good defensive chances. }
19... Rfc8
{ 19...Rfd8  20.Rxd8+  Rxd8  21.Rd1!   Better than going for  21.Nxa7  Ra8  with chances for counterplay.  21...Rxd1  22.Kxd1  Threatening Nxa7!  22...a6  Attacking the b5-knight.  23.Nc7  Threatening Nxa6 and forcing black to weaken the b5-square.  23...a5  24.Kc2±  With the simple plan of going Kb3-Ka4-Kb5 with an easy win for White if that is allowed. Black can probably hold this position with perfect play, but it's a very difficult task in a practical game because the black king is far away from the queenside. }
20. Rd7
{ Enterting the seventh rank and attacking the b7-knight. White wants to force ...Nc5 so we can get the d6-square for our knight. }
20... Nc5 21. Rd4
{ Threatening Nd6 ideas and preparing to double up with Rhd1. } 21... a6 22.
Nd6 Rd8 23. Rhd1
{ White has made all the strong natural moves and Black is facing a difficult defensive task. This is a common scenario for the London System: 'White has a pleasant position, makes the natural moves and if Black mananges to solve a difficult task, the game enters the drawing zone. When they don't, White gets an effortless win'. }
23... Kf8
{ Natural, but losing. Black was trying to bring the king closer to the center with ...Ke7 which is a standard procedure in the endgame.   23...Rab8!!  This would have been a stunning find. It's the only move to keep drawing chances.  24.Nxf7  Rxd4  25.cxd4!  Attacking the c5-knight.  25...Kxf7  26.dxc5  bxc5=  This is why 23...Rab8 was such an important move. Black gets enough counterplay to hold thanks to the ...Rxb2+ threat and White is not in time to infiltrate. }
24. Nxf7 { After this small tactical trick White gets a winning position. }
24... Rxd4 { 24...Kxf7  25.Rxd8  Rxd8  26.Rxd8+- } 25. cxd4
{ The point! We are counter-attacking the c5-knight. } 25... Na4
{ 25...Kxf7  This would have been a better try according to the computer.  26.dxc5  bxc5  27.Rd7+!  Activating the rook.  27...Kf6  28.Rc7  28...Rb8  This is a bit too late now.  29.b3±  Maybe the computer can hold this as Black, but it's very tricky to spot in a practical game. Black has weak pawns and White's pieces are very active. }
26. Ng5 { Attacking both e6 and h7. } 26... Rc8
{ Trying to stay active.   26...Nxb2  27.Rc1+-  This is simply crushing for White with Rc7 next and Black is losing a bunch of pawns while the b2-knight is caught offside. }
27. Rd2 { Stopping ...Rc2+ ideas and protecting the b2-pawn. } 27... Ke7 28.
Kd3 { Threatening to play b3 ➼ trapping Black's knight. } 28... h6
{ 28...b5  This would have saved the knight, but Black is still lost.  29.Rc2!  With this precise move White forces a winning knight endgame.  29...Rxc2  30.Kxc2  30...h6  31.Ne4+-  With a winning position thanks to the extra pawn. You can think of knight endgames as similar to king and pawn endgames. When one side is up a pawn, it is generally enough to win. }
29. Ne4 Rc1 { 29...b5  would have been better, but still loses after  30.Rc2! }
30. b3 { Trapping the knight, so Black had to resign. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Typical Endgames"]
[Black "Nihal, Sarin vs. Batsiashvili, Nino, Menorca 2022"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 d5 3. c3 e6 4. Bf4 Bd6 5. e3 Bxf4 6. exf4 b6 7. Nbd2 O-O 8. h4
c5 9. h5 Qd6 10. h6 g6 11. g3 cxd4 12. Nxd4 e5 13. fxe5 Qxe5+ 14. Be2 Ba6 15.
Kf1 Bxe2+ 16. Qxe2 Qxe2+ 17. Nxe2 Nc6 18. Nf3
{ Heading towards the d4-square. This is a typical endgame coming from the quick 4...Bd6 lines. Nihal is a beast in such positions and one of the main players to follow for instructive London System games. }
18... Rfe8 19. Rd1
{ Activating the rook and keeping an eye on the isolated d5-pawn. } 19... Ne5
{ This is perhaps a bit inaccurate because generally Black should try to trade heavy pieces @@StartBracket@@rooks/queens@@EndBracket@@ and keep minor pieces ➼ when defending the isolated pawn. }
20. Nxe5 Rxe5 21. f3 { This move is great because it restricts the f6-knight. }
21... Rae8
{ 21...Nh5!  This would have been more stubborn ➼ threatening ...Rxe2!  22.Rg1  Defending the g3-pawn.  22...Rae8  23.Nd4  f5∞  With more chances to hold even though White is still pressing after  24.Kf2  . }
22. Nd4
{ Centralizing the knight and threatening to squeeze Black on the kingside with g4 followed by Kf2. }
22... Nh5 23. Kf2 Kf8
{ Again it would have been better to play  23...f5  , but White is still slightly better after  24.Rd2!  ➼ threatening to push f4! followed by Nxf5 or to play the simple Nc6! }
24. Rd2
{ Securing the second rank and thereatening to play Nc6 ➼ forking the a7-pawn and the e5-rook! }
24... a5 25. Rhd1
{ Preparing to play Re2! Keep in mind that the immediate  25.Re2  would lose after  25...Rxe2+  26.Nxe2  Rxe2+  27.Kxe2  Nxg3+  and Black remains up a piece. }
25... f5 26. Re2
{ Trading a pair of rooks is the key idea in these positions ➼ cancelling Black's pressure on the e-file. }
26... Nf6 27. Rxe5 Rxe5 28. a4
{ Another strong positional move ➼ fixing Black's pawns. } 28... Re8 29. Ne2
{ Rerouting the knight to f4 ➼ from where it's attacking the isolated d5-pawn. }
29... Rb8 { Preparing to create counterplay with ...b5! } 30. Nf4
{ Threatening Nxd5! } 30... b5
{ This is a good try for Black because the natural  31.Nxd5  allows  31...Rd8!  32.Ne3  Rxd1  33.Nxd1  bxa4  and it's not obvious at all if White is better. For example  34.Ke3  Ng8!  gives Black good chances to save the game. }
31. Ne6+ { The best practical chance. } 31... Ke7
{ Black cracks under pressure.   31...Kf7!  This was required, when there still is a long game ahead.  32.Ng5+  32...Ke7  33.axb5  Rxb5  34.Rd2⩲  We can activate the king with Ke3-Kf4 and White has pressure against the isolated d5-pawn. Another important factor is that the h6-pawn can be very dangerous and White has sacrificial ideas on g6 in the long run ➼ opening up the path for the h-pawn to queen. }
32. Nd4 { Attacking both the b5-pawn and threatening a fork with Nc6+! } 32...
Kd6 33. axb5
{ After this move White is completely winning and the result is no longer in doubt. I will leave the rest of the game without annotations. }
33... Ng8 34. Re1 Nxh6 35. Rh1 Nf7 36. Rxh7 Ne5 37. Ke2 Nc4 38. Ra7 Re8+ 39.
Kf1 Nxb2 40. Rxa5 Nd1 41. Ra6+ Kd7 42. Rxg6 Nxc3 43. b6 Ra8 44. Nxf5 Nb5 45. g4
Rb8 46. Ke2 Ra8 47. Kf2 Rb8 48. Ke3 Re8+ 49. Kd3 Rb8 50. Nd4 Na3 51. Nc6 Rb7
52. Ne5+ *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Typical Endgames"]
[Black "Carlsen, Magnus vs. Sunilduth Lyna, Narayanan, Chess24 2020"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 d5 3. Bf4 e6 4. e3 Bd6 5. Nbd2 O-O 6. c3 c5 7. Bd3 Qc7 8. Bxd6
Qxd6 9. Ne5 b6 10. f4 Ba6 11. Bc2 Nc6 12. g4 Rac8 13. Rg1 Nd7 14. Ndf3 f6 15.
Nxc6 Rxc6 16. g5 f5 17. Kf2 cxd4 18. cxd4 Rfc8 19. Ba4 R6c7 20. Qd2 Bb5 21. Bb3
a5 22. Rgc1 Bc4 23. Bd1 Ba6 24. Rxc7 Qxc7 25. a3 Bb5 26. a4 Ba6 27. b4 axb4 28.
Qxb4 Nf8 29. a5 bxa5 30. Qxa5 Bd3 31. Qxc7 Rxc7 32. Ne5
{ Centralizing the knight and attacking the d3-bishop. We have a symmetrical structure which may give a lot of players the false impression that the game is heading towards a draw. Generally the symmetrical structure can lead to dry positions, but in this case White is simply much more active which proves to be a decisive factor. }
32... Be4 33. Ra8 { Activating the rook and pinning Black's knight. } 33... g6
34. Ba4 { Preparing to activate the bishop. } 34... Kg7
{ Playing waiting moves. } 35. Bc6
{ Activating the bishop and restricting Black's rook. } 35... Re7 36. h4
{ Another useful move to have! We will need to break with h5 at some point. }
36... Rc7 37. Ke1
{ Preparing to bring the king with decisive effect after Kd2-Kc3-Kb4-Kc5-Kd6 ➼ trapping Black's rook. There is simply no other human better than Magnus at positional chess and specifically at 'how to optimize your pieces'. With every move he is methodically improving his position while putting pressure on his opponent. }
37... Re7 38. Kd2 Rc7 39. Kc3 Nd7
{ The only try for Black, but it is still lost after correct play.   39...Bg2  Passive defense simply fails to help.  40.Kb4  Be4  41.Kc5  Bg2  42.Kd6+-  The c7-rook is literally trapped. This is a very good example showing that in the endgame ➼ the king becomes an attacking piece. }
40. Nxd7 Rxc6+ 41. Nc5
{ This is a blunder under time pressure because this game was played in a blitz format. However this doesn't make it any less instructive!   41.Kb4!  would have been the correct move.  41...Rc4+  42.Kb5!  Not afraid of Black's counterplay. The activity is more important.  42...Rc3  Winning the e3-pawn.  43.Nc5!  Making room for the king to enter Black's camp!  43...Rxe3  44.Kc6  Threatening Kd6 with an easy win because White is creating a mating net.  44...Rh3  Losing for sure, but at least capturing pawns. Sometimes your opponent might miss the direct win and you could come back into the game.  45.Nxe6+  45...Kf7  46.Kd6+-  There is simply no way to stop Rf8# on the next move. }
41... Rb6
{ Black misses his chance!  41...Rxc5+  42.dxc5  d4+!  would have won on the spot. }
42. Ra7+ { Taking control over the seventh rank. } 42... Kg8 43. Nd7
{ Attacking the b6-rook and preparing Nf6+! } 43... Rb1 44. Nf6+
{ Winning the h7-pawn. } 44... Kf8 45. Nxh7+ Ke8 46. Nf6+ Kd8 47. h5
{ Remember when White played 36.h4! This is why it was super useful. Strong players have this skill of doing stuff that 'randomly' turns out to be useful 10-20 moves later. }
47... gxh5 48. g6
{ The pawn is simply unstoppable. Notice that the 'strong' e4-bishop turns out to be completely useless in this structure, being unable to help Black defend. }
48... Rg1 49. g7 h4 50. g8=Q+ Rxg8 51. Nxg8 h3 { Threatening ...h2! } 52. Rh7
{ Stopping Black's pawn and forcing resignation. This was a pure masterpiece by the World Champion showing the importance of having active pieces and using your king as an attacking piece in the endgame. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Typical Endgames"]
[Black "Grachev, Boris vs. Matlakov, Maxim, EU Cup Online 2021"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 e6 3. e3 Bd6 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Nbd2 b6 6. Bb5+ c6 7. Bd3 Bxf4 8.
exf4 O-O 9. O-O c5 10. c3 Ba6 11. Bxa6 Nxa6 12. Qe2 Nb8 13. Ne5 Qc7 14. Ndf3
Nc6 15. Rad1 cxd4 16. Nxc6 Qxc6 17. Nxd4 Qc7 18. g3 a6 19. Rfe1 Rfe8 20. Rd3
Qc4 21. a3 Ne4 22. f3 Nd6 23. Re3
{ This is a very interesting choice by White. Going for the endgame was not mandatory, but it shows deep understanding by Boris Grachev who thought White is pressing in the endgame. }
23... Qxe2 24. R3xe2 { Threatening to push f5! } 24... g6 25. g4
{ White's only constructive plan is to break with f5! This is a typical endgame arising from the 'Berkes structure' and with the White pieces we have Boris Grachev ➼ one of the biggest London System experts @@StartBracket@@not to mention that with the black pieces is another world class player Maxim Matlakov@@EndBracket@@. }
25... Kf8 26. Kf2 b5 27. Kg3
{ The king becomes an attacking piece in the endgame! White is ready to push f5 on the next move! }
27... a5
{ Black is also doing the right thing ➼ organizing the minority attack. } 28.
f5
{ Winning or not, that's not really the question you should be asking yourself! We are trying to pose as many problems as we can and if opponent is able to defend that's okay. You will be scoring really well in the long run in these pretty one-sided affairs. }
28... exf5 29. gxf5 Rxe2 30. Rxe2 Nxf5+ 31. Nxf5 gxf5 32. Kf4
{ This is why it was important to bring the king towards g3 before pushing f5! Now the king becomes an attacking piece. }
32... b4
{ Black goes for active play! This is best defence so far. Most of your opponents will generally play more passive ➼ giving White a risk-free initiative. }
33. axb4 axb4 34. cxb4 Rb8 35. Kxf5 Rxb4 36. Ke5
{ Threatening Kxd5! Black's position is very dangerous because we have the 'outside passer' on b2. }
36... d4
{ This natural move already makes Black's task more difficult. It would have been better to play  36...Rb5  37.Kd6  d4!  with enough counterplay. Keep in mind that it's very easy to spot these ideas with the computer, or in the post-game analysis, but while you are at the board and your life depends on a 'coin flip' decision between two natural moves that look very similar, it's not a fun spot to be in. From our point of view as London players, we have nothing to lose and we can generally make a draw from the superior side if the opponent defends accurately. }
37. Kd5 Rb3
{ Attacking the f3-pawn, but this already makes Black's position very difficult.   37...d3!  This would have been the best defense.  38.Rd2  38...Ke7  39.Kc5  Attacking black's rook and threatening to push b4!  39...Rh4  40.b4  Rh3!  Attacking the f3-pawn.  41.Rxd3  Rxh2  42.b5↑  This is holdable according to the engine, but White's b-pawn looks very dangerous. }
38. Kxd4 Rxf3
{ The losing mistake!   38...Rb8⩲  This would have been a study like draw. Somehow Black is able to give a lot of checks and it's very hard to make progress as White. This doesn't stop you from playing this position forever, though, because most of your opponents will eventually blunder and you can win without risking anything. }
39. b4 { The outside passer is simply decisive. } 39... Rb3 40. Kc4 Rb1 41. b5
Kg7 42. Re3
{ Preparing to play Rb3! ➼ placing the rook behind the passed pawn @@StartBracket@@this is the best way to support your pawn in the rook endgames@@EndBracket@@. }
42... f5 43. Rb3 Rc1+ 44. Kd5
{ The king is activated and White is queening the pawn. } 44... Kf6 45. b6 Rd1+
46. Kc6 Rc1+ 47. Kd7 Rd1+ 48. Kc8 { With the idea to hide on b8. } 48... Rc1+
49. Kb8 { This is a safe square. } 49... f4 50. b7 Kf5 51. Ka7 Rc7
{ Trying to sacrifice the rook for the pawn, but it's simply too late. } 52.
Kb6 Rxb7+ 53. Kxb7 Ke4 54. Rh3
{ Black had to resign because White would have collected the h7-pawn with an easy win because we can sacrifice the rook for the f-pawn and queen the h-pawn. This was a masterpiece by Boris Grachev who made all the right moves, posing practical problems for his opponent.Now if you look at the game again from Black's perspective, you will notice that Black made no obvious mistakes. Everything seemed very logical, Black was in the 'drawing zone' for most of the game, but he still lost. After losing such games, you start to realize that chess is a hard game sometimes because you can lose without making any 'obvious' mistakes. From our perspective as London System players, this was the perfect scenario. We had a slightly more pleasant position, kept pressing without any risks until our opponent cracked under the pressure. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Typical Endgames"]
[Black "Grachev, Boris vs. Dourerassou, Jonathan, chesscom 2020"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3 d5 2. d4 Nf6 3. Bf4 e6 4. e3 Be7 5. Nbd2 O-O 6. Bd3 c5 7. c3 Nc6 8. Qe2
b6 9. Rd1 Bb7 10. h3 Re8 11. O-O Bd6 12. Bxd6 Qxd6 13. e4 Qe7 14. e5 Nd7 15. a3
cxd4 16. cxd4 a6 17. h4 f5 18. exf6 Nxf6 19. Rfe1 g6 20. Qe3 Qg7 21. Ne5 Nxe5
22. Qxe5 Rac8 23. Nf3 Nd7 24. Qe2 b5 25. Qe3 Qf6 26. Re2 Re7 27. Rde1 Rf8
{ This is a dream position arising from the 'QGD with 5...e6' lines. } 28. Qg5
{ The endgames are very promising for White because the e6-pawn will be harder to protect. White also has a very interesting idea to play Qg3 followed by Qd6 ➼ entering Black's camp. }
28... Bc8
{ Preparing to defend the e6-pawn.   28...Qxg5  29.Nxg5+-  Would have dropped the e6-pawn. }
29. Rc1
{ Taking advantage of the open file and threatening to play Rc7! At this point White is much better with any legal move, but playing  29.Qg3  would have been the most precise way! }
29... Qxg5 30. hxg5
{ Keeping good control over the e5-square because  30.Nxg5  e5  could give Black some hopes for active play. }
30... Nb6 { Threatening to play ...Nc4! } 31. b3 { Taking away the c4-square! }
31... Bd7 32. Ne5 { Threatening to play Rc7 followed by Rb7! } 32... Rf4
{ Attacking the d4-pawn. Black is trying everything in order to get some counterplay. }
33. g3
{ While the simple  33.Rc7  does the job, Boris Grachev goes for a very original solution ➼ which is even more impressive that he was able to find this stunning idea in a blitz game! @@StartBracket@@idea which is missed at first by the weaker computers@@EndBracket@@. }
33... Rxd4
{ 33...Rf8  Passive defense was not helping.  34.Rc7  Threatening to play Rb7 ➼ winning a piece.  34...Rb8  35.Nc6+-  Black can't keep everything defended! White wins material. }
34. f4
{ The subtle point! Black's d4-rook is trapped and White will simply collect it with the king after Kf2-Ke3! Notice that the king becomes an attacking piece in the endgame. }
34... Be8 35. Kf2
{ Preparing to play Ke3 and collect Black's rook. There is simpy no way to save the exchange. }
35... Nd7 36. Ke3 { Attacking the d4-rook. } 36... Nxe5 37. Kxd4 Nc6+ 38. Kc5
{ Always remember that the king becomes an attacking piece in the endgame. Boris Grachev is one of the very best at doing that! }
38... Na5 { Attacking the b3-pawn. } 39. Rb1 Nb7+ 40. Kd4
{ 40.Kb6  was even better, but Boris wants to bring it over to e5! } 40... Nd6
41. Rc1
{ Occupying the open file and preparing Rec2-Rc7 ➼ infiltrating in Black's camp! }
41... Kf7 42. Rec2 { Threatening to play Rc7! } 42... Bd7 43. Rc7
{ With the idea to play Ra7 ➼ winning the a6-pawn. } 43... a5
{ Played in order to meet Ra7 with ...a4! } 44. Ke5
{ After the rooks have been activated it's time for the king to shine! } 44...
Nf5 45. Bxf5 { Getting rid of the annoying knight. } 45... exf5+ 46. Kd6
{ This is the most annoying king of all time. Just imagine what it's like being in Black's shoes! We have a perfect example showing why the king is such a strong attacking piece in the endgame. }
46... Ke8 47. Ra7 { Threatening to play Ra8+ followed by Rh8! } 47... Re6+ 48.
Kxd5 Re3 49. Rcc7 { Attacking the d7-bishop. } 49... Be6+ 50. Kd6
{ The king does it again! White is literally threatening to checkmate. } 50...
Kd8 51. Ra8+ Bc8 52. Raxc8#
{ What a nice final picture! The king was really the MVP, even better than in the Grachev-Matlakov game. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Typical Endgames"]
[Black "Aronian, Levon vs. Carlsen, Magnus, NIC Classic 2021"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. Bf4 b6 4. e3 Bb7 5. Bd3 Be7 6. h3 c5 7. c3 cxd4 8. exd4
O-O 9. O-O d6 10. Re1 Nbd7 11. a4 a6 12. Bg3 Re8 13. Na3 Bf8 14. Nc4 Qc7 15.
Nfd2 b5 16. Na3 bxa4 17. Qxa4 Bc6 18. Qc2 Qb7 19. Nac4 Qc7 20. Na5 Ra7 21. Nxc6
Qxc6 22. b4 Rc8 23. c4 e5 24. dxe5 Nxe5 25. Bf1 Rb7 26. Qb3 Rcb8 27. b5 axb5
28. cxb5 Qb6 29. Nc4 Nxc4 30. Bxc4 Rc8 31. Ra6 Qc5 32. Bd3 d5 33. Bf4 Ne4 34.
Be3 d4 35. Bf4 Nc3 36. Re5 Qb4 37. Qxb4 Bxb4
{ You can't really tell this far into the game that we had a London System, but I find this game incredibly instructive ➼ because it illustrates how strong the bishop pair is an open position. }
38. g4
{ This move is usually incredibly powerful in the endgame. White is expanding on the kingside and the threat is to grab even more space with h4-h5! }
38... g6 39. Kg2 { Improving the position slowly. } 39... Rcb8 40. Re1
{ Attacking the b8-rook. } 40... Rd8
{ 40...Nxb5?  This move might seem tempting ➼ attacking the e1-rook, but it doesn't quite work.  41.Rb1!  Black's pieces are too loose.  41...Bd6  42.Bxd6  Nxd6  43.Rxb7!  Forcing Black to recapture with the knight.  43...Nxb7  44.Rb6+-  Creating a deadly pin. We can play Be4/Ba6 next ➼ winning the knight. }
41. Bg5 Rdb8 42. Bf4 { Repeating to gain time on the clock. } 42... Rd8 43. Re5
{ Defending the b5-pawn! } 43... Rdb8 44. Rc6 Nxb5 45. Rd5
{ Hitting the b8-rook. White keeps a very dangerous initiative even when down a pawn! }
45... Na7 { Carlsen defends very well even in time trouble. } 46. Rc1
{ Keeping rooks and preapring to pin Black's bishop on the b-file. } 46... Re8
47. Rb1 { Using 'the pin'! } 47... Rb6 { Threatening to unpin with ...Rf6! }
48. Bc7
{ 48.g5±  This would have been best, with a large advantage for White with h4-h5 next ➼ slowly squeezing Black. }
48... Rc6 49. Rd7 Re7
{ 49...Bf8  This was also playable.  50.Rb7⩲  White is pressing because Black's knight is poorly placed. }
50. Rd8+ Kg7 51. Bf4
{ White keeps making annoying threats and Black has to be careful not to lose immediately against the bishop pair. }
51... Ba5 52. Ra8
{ The best practical chance!   52.Rxd4  Rb6=  With ...Nc6 next ➼ Black's position would have been easier to defend. }
52... Rc8 53. Rbb8 Rxb8 54. Bxb8 { Putting pressure on Black's minor pieces. }
54... Bb6
{ Finally Magnus makes a mistake in time trouble... on move 54! That shows how resilient the World Champion is!   54...Nc6!  Would have been the best defense.  55.Bd6  55...Rd7  56.Bf8+  Kg8!!  White has no useful discovery.  57.Bb4+  Rd8=  With an equal game. }
55. Bd6 Rd7 56. Bf8+ Kf6 { 56...Kg8??  57.Bc5++-  Wins material. } 57. Rb8
{ Missing the direct win.   57.Re8+-  Controlling the e-file and setting up the mating net. The black king is almost checkmated after h4-g5! }
57... Ba5 { 57...Bd8⩲  Would have kept a defendable position. } 58. Re8
{ White doesn't miss the second chance. Black's king is trapped in a mating net. }
58... Bc7
{ 58...Bd2  This was perhaps better, but still lost.  59.h4  Threatening to push g5!  59...h6  60.Re2  60...Bc1  61.Ra2+-  With Kf3 next and Black is in a pretty funny Zugzwang! }
59. h4 { Threatening to mate with g5! } 59... g5
{ The only move not to get mated. } 60. Bf5
{ After this move Black is losing material. } 60... Rd5 61. Be7+ Ke5
{ Avoiding the mate, but losing material.   61...Kg7  62.hxg5+-  With Bf6+/Bf8+ White is mating soon. }
62. Bc5+ Kf6 63. hxg5+ Kxg5 64. Bxa7
{ Cashing in the free piece. The rest is simple. } 64... d3 65. Be3+ Kf6 66.
Bd2 h5 67. Be4 Rb5 68. g5+
{ This was a marathon game showing how powerful the bishop pair is when controlling a lot of squares @@StartBracket@@thanks to the open character of the position@@EndBracket@@. Even the G.O.A.T. was unable to defend against such tremendous pressure @@StartBracket@@even though he got pretty close@@EndBracket@@. }
