[Black "Giri, Anish vs. Antonenko, Vladimir Georgievic, chesscom 2021"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. e3 Bd6 5. Nbd2 Bxf4 6. exf4 c5 7. dxc5 Qa5 8.
Bd3 Nbd7 9. O-O Nxc5 10. Nb3 Qc7 11. Nxc5 Qxc5 12. Re1 O-O 13. c3 Bd7 14. Nd4
a5 15. a4 Rfe8 16. Qd2 Rad8 17. Re2 Qc7 18. Qe3 Nh5 19. g3 Nf6 20. Qe5
{ White is trying to force a pleasant endgame. } 20... Rc8
{ 20...Qxe5  This would have been clearly worse.  21.fxe5  21...Ng4  22.h3  Forcing the knight to a passive position.  22...Nh6  23.f4±  White can expand with g4 followed by f5 with a much better position thanks to the superb d4-knight. Check out Grachev-Solovchuk in order to see how White intends to make progress. }
21. Qxc7 Rxc7 22. f3
{ Controlling the e4-square and preparing to expand on the kingside with g4! }
22... Kf8 23. g4 { Taking space and threatening to push f5 in some positions. }
23... g6 24. Bc2 { Protecting the a4-pawn so we can play Rae1 next. } 24... Rb8
{ Black goes for active counterplay ➼ using the a4-hook. This is a good idea, but it requires careful execution. }
25. Kf2
{ Anish makes a useful waiting move. Inviting black to make a mistake! } 25...
b5
{ Black takes the bait!   25...Rcc8=  With ...b5 next would have given Black enough counterplay to hold the balance. }
26. axb5 Bxb5 27. Rxe6 { The hidden point. } 27... Ne8
{ 27...fxe6  28.Nxe6++-  Would have been even worse with two extra pawns for White. }
28. Re5 { White has a technical win, and Anish's technique was very clean. }
28... Bd7 29. Ra2 Rc5 30. Kg3 Nc7 31. f5
{ Threatening fxg6 ➼ getting rid of the doubled pawn. } 31... f6 32. Re2 g5 33.
h4 { Sooner or later White will manage to trade the pawns with f4! } 33... h6
34. hxg5 hxg5 35. f4
{ Finally getting rid of the doubled pawns, and the extra pawn starts to tell. }
35... gxf4+ 36. Kxf4 Kf7 37. Rh2 Kg7 38. g5 fxg5+ 39. Kxg5 { Threatening f6+! }
39... Rb6 40. f6+ Rxf6 41. Rh7+
{ Collecting the f6-rook on the next move so Black had to resign. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Typical Endgames"]
[Black "Kamsky, Gata vs. Belozerov, Andrei, chesscom 2020"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Bf4 c5 4. e3 Nc6 5. Nbd2 e6 6. c3 Bd6 7. Bg3 O-O 8. Bd3
b6 9. Qe2 Bb7 10. Rd1 Rc8 11. a3 Ne7 12. e4 c4 13. Bb1 Nxe4 14. Nxe4 dxe4 15.
Bxe4 Bxe4 16. Qxe4 Nd5 17. Bxd6 Qxd6 18. O-O b5 19. Ng5 Nf6 20. Qh4 a5 21. Rfe1
b4 22. axb4 axb4 23. Re3 h6 24. Ne4 Nxe4 25. Qxe4 Rfd8
{ This is a typical endgame arising from the Carlsbad structure. Objectively speaking ➼ generally Black should be able to hold, but it's incredibly tricky in a practical game because it's much easier to play as White and we have no risks pressing in this type of position. }
26. h4
{ This is a very strong practical move, because ➼ the h-pawn will play an important role in a lot of lines and it gives White better chances to succeed on the kingside. Last but not least, we are also creating a luft for the king which is quite important ➼ solving all the potential back rank issues. }
26... Qd5 27. Qg4
{ Keeping queens on is the key idea to generate winning chances! Going for the rook endgame will generally give Black an easy game. }
27... bxc3 28. bxc3 Rb8 29. Rg3 { Threatening checkmate on g7. } 29... g6 30.
Qf4 { Attacking the h6-pawn. } 30... Qh5
{ Covering the h6-pawn and attacking the d1-rook.   30...Kg7  31.Rf3  Attacking the f7-pawn.  31...Rb7  32.Qf6+  Kh7!   This is important because  32...Kg8  33.h5!  gives white a large advantage. Notice how useful the h-pawn turns out to be in this structure.  33.Re1⩲  With Re5 on the next move ➼ White keeps annoying pressure. }
31. Ra1 { Introducing Ra7 ideas. } 31... Rb3 32. Qf6
{ Attacking the d8-rook and keeping an eye on the g6-pawn. } 32... Rf8 33. Re1
{ White noticed a deadly tactical trick. } 33... Qf5
{ Trying to defend against Rxe6.   33...Rb5  34.Rf3!  Threatening Rxe6!   The immediate  34.Rxe6??  Rf5-+  wins for Black.  34...Rf5  35.Rxf5  Qxf5  36.Qxf5  gxf5  37.Ra1⩲  White has a promising endgame with pressure on the c4-pawn.   33...Rb6?  Defending against ...Rxe6!  34.Re5!  34...Qd1+  35.Kh2  Rb1  Trying to play for checkmate, but allowing White to get a forced mate.  36.Rxg6+!  fxg6  37.Qxg6+  Kh8  38.Qxh6+  Kg8  39.Rg5+  39...Kf7  40.Rg7+  40...Ke8  41.Qxe6+  Kd8  42.Qd7  Everything was forced. }
34. Rxe6 { This move still works! } 34... Qxf6
{ The safest, but still much worse for Black.   34...Qxe6  35.Rxg6+!!  The point!  35...fxg6  36.Qxe6+  Kg7  37.Qxc4+-  With a winning endgame for White thanks to the two connected passers.   34...fxe6  This allows White to collect all the pawns.  35.Rxg6+  Qxg6  36.Qxg6+  36...Kh8  37.Qxh6+  37...Kg8  38.Qxe6+  38...Kg7  39.Qxc4+-  With a winning endgame for White. }
35. Rxf6 Re8 36. Rc6 { 36.Rgf3+-  This was even more precise! } 36... Re1+ 37.
Kh2 Re2 38. Rf3
{ We have an amazing rook on f3 because it defends both the c3 and the f2-pawn while putting pressure on the enemy f7-pawn. }
38... Rc2 39. Rc8+ Kg7 40. Rc7
{ Threatening mate! White is objectively winning. } 40... Rcxc3
{ Allowing mate, but the position was hopeless. } 41. Rcxf7+ Kg8 42. Rf8+ Kg7
43. R3f7# { With a direct checkmate. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Typical Endgames"]
[Black "Grachev, Boris vs. Rychagov, Andrey, Moscow 2010"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 c6 3. e3 Bf5 4. c4 e6 5. Nc3 Nd7 6. Qb3 Qb6 7. c5 Qxb3 8. axb3
a6 9. b4 Rc8 10. Nf3 Ngf6 11. h3 Be7 12. Nd2 Bd8 13. Nb3 Bc7 14. Bxc7 Rxc7 15.
b5 O-O 16. b6 Rcc8 17. Na5 Rb8
{ This is a typical position coming from the Slav Defense. } 18. Bxa6
{ This is the key idea to break through. White's b6-c5 pawns are stronger than a piece. The only thing we have to watch out for ➼ is to not give Black the chance to sacrifice the knight for two pawns, because that will give Black a safe position most of the times. }
18... bxa6 19. Nxc6 { Attacking the b8-rook. } 19... Ra8
{ This was played with the idea to sacrifice the exchange ➼ trying to slow down White's pawns.   19...Rb7  20.Ne7+  20...Kh8  21.Nxf5  exf5  22.Rxa6!  This is the most important detail that you want to remember after the piece sacrifice. The two connected passers are insanely strong and we just need to avoid Black's threat to eliminate them with ...Nxb6!   22.c6??  This might seem tempting because we are winning back the piece, but Black is able to get a safe position after the piece sacrifice.  22...Rxb6!  23.cxd7  Rxb2  24.O-O  Rb7  25.Rxa6  Rxd7⩲  White still has a slightly better position, but most of the advantage has evaporated.  22...Rfb8  Threatening to play ...Nxb6!  23.Na4+-  The most precise ➼ avoiding ...Nxb6! and winning slowly with Ke2, Rc1 followed by b4-b5 and finally c6! Just remember: we don't need to rush because the connected passers are winning the game easily if you don't allow Black to sacrifice the piece and eliminate them in a good way.   19...Rbe8  Avoiding Ne7+ ➼ but allowing Rxa6!  20.Rxa6  At this point we have three pawns for the sacrificed piece, but it's more about the quality of the pawns than the number!  20...e5  This is a try for Black to create counterplay, but it's not particularly threatening.  21.Kd2  Re6  Attacking the c6-knight.  22.b7  Protecting the knight and preparing to push b4-b5!  22...Rfe8  23.b4  exd4  24.exd4  Ne4+  25.Nxe4  Rxe4  26.Ra8+-  26...Re2+  can be met by  27.Kc3  and White is winning easily with the advanced pawns. }
20. b7 Rab8
{ This is an interesting sacrifice, but not quite enough to hold.   20...Rae8  Keeping the extra material wouldn't help.  21.Rxa6+-  We can continue with Kd2 followed by advancing the b-pawn. After that another simple but effective plan is to go Rha1 followed by Ra8! }
21. Nxb8 Nxb8
{ 21...Rxb8  22.c6+-  This is a nice picture ➼ illustrating the power of the advanced connected passers. Here you can clearly see why two connected passers on the 6th rank are usually stronger than a rook in the endgame. }
22. b4
{ Threatening to push b5!   22.Kd2+-  This would have been even more precise ➼ avoiding ...Bd3! }
22... Bd3 23. Kd2 { Activating the king with tempo. } 23... Bc4 24. Rhb1
{ Supporting the b5-push. } 24... Ne4+
{ Deflecting White's knight from supporting b5! This is a good try, but White's position has simply too much 'hidden' potential. }
25. Nxe4 dxe4 26. b5
{ Boris Grachev has no mercy in such situations. This is a textbook play of how to make progress after the positional bishop sacrifice. Pure class! }
26... axb5
{ 26...Bxb5  I guess this was the initial idea behind 24...Ne4+ ➼ but Black later realized it won't save him.  27.Rxb5!!  It's all about opening up lines and getting into a scenario with two far advanced pawns against the useless rook.  27...axb5  28.Ra8!  The key idea is that White is threatening Rxb8 followed by c6!  28...Nc6   28...f6  Allows White's main idea:  29.Rxb8!  Rxb8  30.c6+-  The rook is simply defenseless against the pawns.  29.Rc8+-  The final touch. Black is forced to move the knight and White is able to get a new queen. }
27. Ra8 { Threatening Rxb8! followed by c6. } 27... Bd5
{ Attacking the b7-pawn. } 28. Rxb5 { Protecting the b7-pawn. } 28... f5 29.
Rb6 { White's plan is to bring the king all the way to b5 and then push c6! }
29... Kf7 30. Kc3 Ke7
{ Threatening to play ...Kd7 followed by ...Kc7 and Black wins the b7-pawn. }
31. Rd6
{ This move is extremely important. We are cutting Black's king off and introducing ideas to sacrifice the exchange with Rxd5! }
31... g5
{ 31...Bxb7??  The pawn is poisoned.  32.Ra7  White collects the bishop thanks to the pin. }
32. Kb4
{ White's plan is to bring the king to b6 and then sacrifice both rooks with Rxd5 and Rxb8 followed by c6-c7 ➼ promoting the pawns. }
32... Kf6 { Threatening to pick up the pawn with ...Bxb7! } 33. Rxd5
{ The start of a stunning idea. } 33... exd5 34. Rxb8 Rxb8 35. c6
{ The final point! The position has cleared up and it becomes obvious that Black's rook is defenseless against the pawns. }
35... Ke7 36. Kc5
{ Followed by Kb6 and c7 ➼ promoting the pawns, so Black had to resign. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Typical Endgames"]
[Black "Grachev, Boris vs. Solovchuk, Alexey, chesscom 2021"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 e6 3. e3 Bd6 4. Nf3 Bxf4 5. exf4 c5 6. dxc5 Qa5+ 7. Nbd2 Qxc5
8. Bd3 Nc6 9. c3 Nf6 10. O-O O-O 11. Re1 Re8 12. Qe2 Qb6 13. Nb3 a5 14. Nbd4
Bd7 15. Rad1 Nxd4 16. Nxd4 a4 17. a3 g6 18. Rd2
{ This is a very useful move ➼ protecting the b2-pawn so we can play Qf3 followed by Rde2. After that the plan is to expand on the kingside with g4-h4-h5! }
18... Qc7 19. Qe5
{ Similar to Giri-Antonenko ➼ White is forcing a pleasant endgame because we have more space and a much better bishop. }
19... Qxe5
{ Black didn't have much of a choice because the f6-knight was under attack. }
20. fxe5 { Improving our pawn structure and attacking Black's knight. } 20...
Ng4 21. h3 Nh6 22. g4
{ This is the most precise because after  22.f4  Nf5  Black manages to bring back the knight into the game. }
22... Kg7 23. f4 Re7 24. Rg2
{ Notice how useful the 18.Rd2 move turns out to be! White is protecting the g4-pawn so we can push h4-h5 next. }
24... Kh8
{ Black can't really do much in the meantime, but it's very instructive to see how White is slowly building up the pressure. }
25. Kf2
{ Bringing the king closer to the center and making room for the rook to activate via h1. }
25... Rae8 26. h4 { Threatening Rh1 followed by h5! } 26... Ng8 27. h5 Kg7
{ 27...gxh5  28.g5+-  This is not the only move to get a large advantage, but the most precise one. Black's pieces are completely stuck and White is ready to play Rh1 followed by Rxh5 with pressure on the h7-pawn. }
28. Rh1
{ Preparing to double up on the h-file with Rgh2 ➼ threatening hxg6 with mating ideas! }
28... f6 29. hxg6 hxg6 30. Rgh2 { Threatening Rh7+ followed by Bxg6! } 30... f5
{ This is an attempt to close the position, but Black's piece are simply to passive in order to create any resistance. }
31. gxf5 gxf5
{ 31...exf5  This is also not helping. White wins with any legal move according to the computer.  32.c4!  I find this to be the simplest solution. Threatening cxd5 and Black can't play ...dxc4 because our bishop will activate.  32...Bc6  33.Rg1  Threatening Nxf5+!  33...Kf7  34.c5!  Not the only move, but the nicest one. Black will be in zugzwang soon.  34...Bd7  35.Be2!   This is the cleanest because  35.Rhg2  Nh6!  could be a bit annoying because we have to sacrifice the exchange. That is still completely winning, but there is no need to give up material in this kind of positions where black has no active ideas.  35...Bc6  36.Bf3+-  Black is simply defencsless against Rhg2 ➼ winning the g6-pawn. }
32. Be2 { Introducing Bh5 ideas! } 32... Kf8 33. Ke3 Rg7 34. Nf3
{ The knight is heading towards g5. } 34... Rc8 35. Rh8 Ke7 36. Ng5 Bc6
{ Threatening a small trick with ...d4+! ➼ winning the h1-rook. } 37. R1h7
{ Black had to resign because after  37...Rxh7  38.Rxh7+  the e6-pawn is dropping. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Typical Endgames"]
[Black "Nikolic, Predrag vs. Piket, Jeroen, Wijk aan Zee 1989"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3 Nf6 2. d4 d5 3. Bf4 Bf5 4. c4 c6 5. e3 e6 6. Nc3 Nbd7 7. Qb3 Qb6 8. c5
Qxb3 9. axb3 a6 10. b4 Rc8 11. h3 h6 12. Nd2 Be7 13. Nb3 Bd8 14. Bd6 Ne4 15.
Nxe4 Bxe4 16. f3 Bg6
{ This is a typical structure arising from the 'Slav Defense'. Understanding the main ideas and typical plans is much more valuable than knowing concrete lines @@StartBracket@@even though I still encourage you to drill the MoveTrainer in this course as well!@@EndBracket@@. }
17. Na5
{ The b7-pawn is Black's main weakness in these lines. With Na5 White is targeting exactly that pawn! }
17... Bxa5 18. bxa5
{ This stunning move was an eye opener for myself when I first started looking into the typical positions. This is a very specific idea ➼ planning to go Ra4-Rb4 attacking the b7-pawn.   You'd be surprised that even GM/IM players have gone  18.Rxa5  when I asked them about this line, but that's only because they were mainly 1.e4 players. }
18... Kd8
{ This is played with the idea to bring the king over to c8 ➼ protecting the b7-pawn.   18...Nf6  This could have been a better try.  19.Ra4  Preparing Rb4!  19...Rd8  20.Rb4  Attacking the b7-pawn.  20...Rd7  21.Kd2  This is the simplest approach.   21.Rb6  The computer finds a stunning idea here.  21...Ng8  Threatening to play ...Ne7-Nc8!  22.Bxa6+-  This is objectively best for White, with a winning position if you can find all the precise moves. I did quite some analysis here, but decided to not recommend this as the main idea because even though the position is winning, White has to come up with a lot of counter-intuitive moves, otherwise Black might even get the upper hand. I invite you to do your own analysis to get familiar with the typical ideas that we also see in Grachev-Rychagov.  21...Ng8  22.Be2  Ne7  23.Ra1±  With Ra3-Rb3 next White has huge pressure on the b7-pawn. This plan has brought me a lot of effortless wins. }
19. Ra4 Ra8 20. Rb4 Kc8 21. h4 h5 22. Rh3
{ 22.g4!  This is more direct. White is threatening to push g5 and then Black's position is very passive.  22...hxg4  This has to be played, but it opens up lines on the kingside.  23.fxg4  Nf6  24.h5!   Setting up a small trap because  24...Nxg4  allows  25.hxg6!  Rxh1  26.gxf7  and White promotes the pawn.  24...Be4  25.Rg1  Bf3  26.Bh3±  Threatening to play g5 followed by g6 with a large advantage for White. }
22... Bf5 23. Rg3 g6 24. Kd2 Re8 25. Rg5 f6
{ This is unnecessarily weakening the g6-pawn. After this move Black should be objectively lost because the position is too passive and White has free pressure against the g6-pawn.   25...Ra7  26.Bd3  Threatening to push e4!  26...Bxd3  27.Kxd3  27...Nf6  28.e4±  Threatening to grab more space with e5 and then the plan is to play Rg3-Rh3 followed by the g4-break. }
26. Rg3
{ Threatening to simply play Bd3 and then Black has huge issues with the g6-pawn. }
26... g5 27. Bd3
{ Threatening to push e4!   27.hxg5  h4∞  This was Black's trick ➼ the g3-rook is trapped. }
27... g4
{ 27...Bxd3  28.Kxd3  Rg8  29.e4+-  White is winning because Black's pieces are stuck. A simple plan is to play Ke2-Rb3 followed by exd5-Re3 ➼ and Black is basically playing down a rook. }
28. e4 { This is the key pawn push ➼ opening up the position. } 28... dxe4
{ 28...Bh7  This simply loses a pawn.  29.exd5  Bxd3  30.Kxd3  exd5  31.fxg4+-  White keeps the extra pawn with an easily winning position. }
29. fxe4 Bg6 30. Bc2
{ Preparing to bring the g3-rook over the queenside with Rgb3! } 30... f5
{ 30...Bh7  Passive defense doesn't help either.  31.Rgb3  Threatening Rxb7!  31...Ra7  32.Bd3  Bg6  33.Rxb7!  The key idea to breakthrough.  33...Rxb7  34.Bxa6+-  Collecting the b7-rook next with a crushing position. }
31. e5 { Preparing Rgb3 and the we can activate the king with Ke3-Kf4! } 31...
Rg8 32. Rgb3 { Threatening Rxb7! } 32... Ra7 33. Bd3
{ Threatening Rxb7 followed by Bxa6! } 33... Nb8 34. Ke3
{ All of our pieces were on optimal squares except... the king! Nikolic does a great job of optimizing all of his pieces before going for any concrete operations. }
34... Rg7 35. Kf4
{ The king has reached the optimal square, and we might even be threatening Kg5 in some positions. }
35... Bf7 36. Rb6
{ Threatening Bxb8 followed by Rxc6 ➼ taking advantage of the pin. } 36... Be8
{ Covering the c6-pawn. Now it's the part of the game where a lot of players might get stuck because there is no obvious way to make progress. You have to understand that passive defense rarely works in chess and look for more 'unorthodox' ways to make progress because generally there is always a way! }
37. d5 { After this stunning move Black's position falls apart. } 37... cxd5
{ 37...exd5  Allows an easy win for White:  38.Bxf5+  38...Bd7  39.e6+-  Winning at least a piece. }
38. Bxb8
{ The point! The rook is able to collect the e6-pawn next followed by collecting the kingside pawns one by one. }
38... Kxb8 39. Rxe6 { The rest is pretty simple. } 39... Ba4 40. Rb4 g3
{ The last trick!   40...Bd7  41.Rf6+-  With e6 on the next move, White is easily winning. }
41. Bxf5
{ Avoiding ...Rg4+ so Black had to resign because White was about to collect the remaining pawns and push the e-pawn.   41.Rxa4  Rg4++-  This is still winning for White because black's a7-rook is out of the game, but it is unnecessary to give away any material. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Typical Endgames"]
[Black "Miles, Anthony John vs. Nogueiras Santiago, Jesus, Varadero 2000"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Bf4 c5 4. e3 Nc6 5. c3 Bg4 6. Nbd2 e6 7. Qb3 Qb6 8. Ne5
Nxe5 9. Bxe5 Qxb3 10. axb3 Nd7 11. Bg3 Be7
{ This is a common endgame for the London System arising after Black decides to trade queens on b3. }
12. dxc5
{ This is the key idea to get the game going! Releasing the tension is usually a sign of weakness, but in this particular case ➼ it allows White to grab the initiative on the queenside with b4 followed by Nb3-Na5 ideas. }
12... Bxc5 { 12...Nxc5  13.Bb5+  Nd7  14.e4± } 13. b4 Be7
{ 13...Bb6  This is an alternative. White has a choice between two promising plans, 14. e4 and 14. c4.   14.e4⩲  You could simplify your strategy by going for the e4-break against both 13...Be7 and 13...Bb6 because White is slightly better anyways.   14.Nb3  With the enemy bishop on b6 this plan is less effective.  14...e5  15.Bb5  f6∞  The problem is that we can no longer break with f4 like in the 13...Be7 14.Nb3 line because the e3-pawn will drop.   14.c4!  This is the most precise. The trick is to recapture on c4 with the knight and White has a very annoying Nd6 idea + we also have c5 ideas ➼ attacking the b6-bishop.  14...dxc4  15.Nxc4  Threatening Nd6+!  15...O-O  16.Bd3!  Creating a huge threat of playing Be4 followed by Bxb7!  16...Bf5  17.Bxf5  exf5  18.Ke2±  With Rhd1 and Nd6 ideas, White has a solid advantage. }
14. e4
{ 14.Nb3!  This might have been even simpler ➼ threatening to play Na5!  14...e5   14...b6?  Stopping Na5, but weakening the c6-square.  15.Bb5+-  With Bc6 next and Black is dropping the a7-pawn.  15.Bb5!  Threatening Bxe5!  15...f6  16.f4!  Forcing Black to create a weakness because fxe5 is a big threat.  16...exf4  17.exf4±  Threatening to play Nd4 and h3 ➼ Black has problems with the d7-knight. White has a long-term initiative against the isolated d5-pawn. }
14... O-O 15. f3
{ This move works well because White is able to gain a tempo later on with Bb5! @@StartBracket@@otherwise the g4-bishop would have protected the d7-knight@@EndBracket@@.   15.exd5  Playing without f3 is less precise because Black is in time to create counterplay.  15...exd5  16.Bd3  d4⇆  With a safe position for Black because they managed to get rid of the isolated pawn. The main point is  17.cxd4  Bxb4!  and Black has it all under control.   15.Bb5  This is no longer working that well here.  15...Nf6  Attacking the e4-pawn and preparing to meet 16.exd5 with ...Nxd5 ➼ avoiding the isolated pawn.  16.e5  16...Nh5∞  Winning the bishop pair ➼ with a safe position for Black. }
15... Bh5 16. exd5 { Creating the isolated pawn. } 16... exd5 17. Bb5
{ Developing with tempo! This is why 15.f3! was important. } 17... Nb6
{ Threatening to push ...d4! ➼ getting rid of the isolated pawn. } 18. Bf2
{ Controlling the critical d4-square. } 18... a6 19. Be2
{ Keeping the bishop pair.   19.Bxb6  This is also very promising.  19...axb5  20.Kf2±  With Nb3-Na5 White is much better because Black's position is full of weaknesses. }
19... Nd7 20. O-O Rfe8
{ Threatening to play ...Bg5 ➼ attacking both the d2-knight and the e2-bishop. }
21. Rfe1 { Protecting the e2-bishop so we can easily meet ...Bg5 with Nb3! }
21... f6 22. Nb3 { Preparing to play Na5 ➼ attacking the b7-pawn. } 22... Ne5
23. Na5 { This move is very annoying for Black! They have to commit now. }
23... b5
{ After this move Black has a backward pawn on a6 which is a very juicy target for White's pieces.   23...Rab8  This would have been ideal, but it loses a pawn.  24.Ba7!  24...Ra8  25.Bb6!  Reinforcing the Nxb7 threat.  25...Rab8  26.Bc7!  26...Rbc8  27.Bxe5  fxe5  28.Nxb7+-  The a6-pawn will be collected on the next move with a winning endgame for White. }
24. Rad1 { Not the only move, but very principled play by White! } 24... Bf7
{ This seems to be the losing mistake, but the position was already very bad.   24...Bd8  The computer prefers this move.  25.Rxd5  Bc7  26.Rdd1+-  White's position looks simply winning after Kf1-Bg3 with an extra pawn. }
25. f4 Nc4
{ The best try, but Black should be lost because the queenside pawns are vulnerable.   25...Ng6  26.g3±  We can continue with Bf3 followed by Rd2-Red1 and the isolated pawn will drop. }
26. Nxc4
{ White was very confident about this decision. In a way we are improving Black's structure, but we switch the pressure on the backward a6-pawn. }
26... dxc4 27. Bf3 Rad8 28. Ra1
{ There is no way to defend the a6-pawn because  28...Rd6  29.Bc5!  wins for White. }
28... Bf8
{ 28...Rd2  , trying to play more actively, is not enough to save the game.  29.Rxa6  Rxb2  30.Bc6+-  Winning material. }
29. Rxe8 Bxe8 30. Rxa6 Rd2 31. Ra8
{ The bishops are vulnerable and White spots that immediately. } 31... Kf7 32.
Be3 { Setting up a trap because the b2-pawn is poisoned. } 32... Rd3
{ 32...Rxb2  This leads to a forced win for White.  33.Bd5+  Ke7  34.Bc5+  Kd7  35.Bxf8+-  With an extra piece for White. }
33. Kf2 { White is up a pawn and technically winning. } 33... f5 34. Bc5
{ Very precise! } 34... Be7
{ 34...Bxc5+  This was not really an option for Black.  35.bxc5  Rd2+  36.Ke3  Rxb2  37.c6+-  Black has to give up the bishop for the c-pawn. }
35. Ra7 { Forcing a winning bishop endgame. } 35... Rd7
{ 35...Bd7  This was losing material.  36.Bd4  Be8  37.Be2!  Rd2  38.Ke3  Rxb2  39.Bc5+-  Winning the e7-bishop. }
36. Rxd7 Bxd7 37. Bd5+ { Activating the bishop with tempo! } 37... Kf6
{ 37...Be6  38.Bc6+-  Collecting the b5-pawn. } 38. Bxe7+ Kxe7 39. Ke3
{ Centralizing the king. } 39... Kd6 40. Kd4
{ Black resigned because White is ready to push b3 on the next move ➼ creating a passed pawn on the queenside which gives White an easily winning endgame. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Typical Endgames"]
[Black "Speelman, Jonathan vs. Ree, Hans, Wijk aan Zee 1983"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 g6 3. Bf4 Bg7 4. e3 d6 5. h3 O-O 6. Be2 Nbd7 7. O-O e6 8. Bh2
Qe7 9. c4 Ne4 10. Nbd2 Nxd2 11. Qxd2 b6 12. Ne1 Bb7 13. Bf3 Bxf3 14. Nxf3 f5
15. Rac1 Nf6 16. Rfd1 Ne4 17. Qc2 Rfd8 18. Nd2 Nxd2 19. Rxd2 e5 20. dxe5 Bxe5
21. Bxe5 Qxe5
{ This is a typical endgame which can arise from both the Queen's Indian and the Dutch Defense. White has pressure on both sides of the board because the ...f5 move has weakened Black's king. }
22. b4
{ Preparing the c5-break. White's idea is to play Rd5 first ➼ followed by c5! }
22... a5
{ Seeking active counterplay.   22...f4  23.Rd5  23...Qf6  24.e4!  Threatening to push f3.  24...f3  25.g3⩲  We can play Kh2 next ➼ securing the kingside, followed by putting pressure on the queenside with c5! Notice that the f3-pawn can also be quite vulnerable in these lines.   22...Qf6  23.Rcd1  Preparing to push c5.  23...Rf8  24.c5  dxc5  25.bxc5  Threatening to infiltrate on the seventh rank with Rd7!  25...Rad8  26.Qc4+  26...Kg7  27.c6→  With Rd7 next, White has a dangerous initiative. }
23. Rd5 Qe6
{ 23...Qe4  24.Qb3!   This is the best try because  24.Qxe4  fxe4  is quite safe for black. We need the queens on the board to keep the initiative going.  24...axb4  25.c5!  Threatening a deadly discovery.  25...Kg7  26.cxd6  Threatening Rc7+!  26...c5!  The best defense, avoiding Rc7+!  27.Qb2+  27...Kh6  28.Qd2±  With a much better position for White with the dangerous passed pawn and threats against the enemy king. }
24. bxa5 c6
{ Avoiding the isolated pawn on the a-file, but weakening the d6-pawn.   24...Rxa5  25.Rxa5!  Creating a weak pawn on a5.  25...bxa5  26.Qd2  Attacking the a5-pawn.  26...a4   26...Ra8  27.c5!  keeps the initiative for White.  27.Qa5  Attacking the a4-pawn.  27...Qd7  28.c5  dxc5  29.Qxc5±  With a pretty one-sided game. White will most likely win the c-pawn while also keeping threats against the enemy king. }
25. Rd2 Rxa5 26. Qb3
{ Attacking the b6-pawn and keeping an eye on the a2-g8 diagonal. } 26... Ra6
{ 26...b5  This is an alternative.  27.Qc3!  Attacking the a5-rook.  27...Raa8  28.cxb5  cxb5  29.Qb2  Attacking the b5-pawn and threatening to play Rc7!  29...Rac8  30.Rdc2  Fighting for the c-file.  30...Rxc2  31.Rxc2±  With Rc7 ideas, White keeps the initiative against Black's king. }
27. Rcd1 { Preparing to play Qb4 ➼ putting pressure on the d6-pawn. } 27... b5
{ The losing mistake.   27...Kf7  This would have been a better try, but still suffering.  28.Qb4  Attacking the d6-pawn.  28...Qe5   28...c5  29.Qb5+-  Winning the b6-pawn.   28...d5  29.cxd5  Rxd5  30.Rxd5  cxd5  31.Rc1±  Threatening Rc7+ next ➼ Black's king is in trouble.  29.c5!  Threatening Qc4+!  29...Qxc5  30.Qh4↑  Attacking both the d8-rook and the h7-pawn. Objectively speaking, Black should still be able to hold, but this is a very tricky task in a practical game. }
28. Rxd6
{ Using a cute tactical trick. My guess is that Black saw it in advance, but failed to evaluate the upcoming position properly. }
28... Rxd6 29. Rxd6 Qxc4
{ 29...Qxd6  30.cxb5++-  Wins back the rook with a winning endgame. } 30. Rd8+
Kf7 31. Qd1
{ The material is equal, but White is much better when we compare king's safety. This position is already objectively lost, besides being very hard to play as Black in a practical game. }
31... Ra7 32. Qa1
{ This is also good, but less precise. White is preparing Qh8 ideas!   32.Qd6+-  is even better because  32...Re7  33.Rh8  is quite problematic. }
32... Ke6 33. Qh8
{ We are simply evacuating Black's king! Black can rarely escape in this type of position. }
33... Re7 34. f4 { Controlling the e5-square. } 34... Qc1+ 35. Kh2 Qc4
{ 35...Qxe3  This loses the queen.  36.Qg8+  Rf7  37.Re8++-  Picking up Black's queen next. }
36. a3 { Not the only move, but now Black is in a pretty hilarious zugzwang. }
36... c5 37. Rc8 { Threatening Qg8+! } 37... Kd6 38. Qd8+ Ke6
{ 38...Rd7  This also doesn't help.  39.Qf6+  Qe6  40.Rc6++-  Winning the queen. }
39. Rc6+ Kf7 40. Qh8
{ Creating a deadly double attack ➼ threatening both Rf6# and Qxh7+! } 40...
Qe4 41. Rf6#
{ With a checkmate on the board. Notice that the key idea in this structure was to keep the queens on the board and constantly create threats against the enemy king. White was able to do that thanks to the weakening ...f5 move which was played earlier by Black. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Typical Endgames"]
[Black "Kovacevic, Vlatko vs. Sprecic, Mustafa, Tuzla 1981"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 g6 2. Nf3 Bg7 3. Bf4 c5 4. e3 Nf6 5. c3 Qb6 6. Qb3 Qxb3 7. axb3 cxd4 8.
exd4 Nc6 9. Na3 O-O 10. Nc4 Nd5 11. Bg3 d6 12. b4 Bd7 13. Be2 Bh6 14. O-O a6
15. Rfe1 b5 16. Na5 Nxa5 17. Rxa5 Bc6 18. Bd1 Rfe8 19. Bb3 Nb6 20. Bh4 e6 21.
Ng5 d5 22. Nf3 Bg7 23. g4 Bb7 24. Bg3 Rac8 25. g5 h6 26. h4 Nd7 27. Raa1 h5 28.
Re2 Bf8 29. Ne1 Red8 30. Nd3 Nb6 31. Bd1 Nd7 32. Bc2 Rc6 33. Rae1 Bd6 34. Bxd6
Rxd6 35. Nc5 Nxc5 36. bxc5 Rc6 37. Bd3 Kg7 38. Kg2 Rd7 39. Kg3 Rd8 40. Kf4 Re8
41. Re3 Rd8
{ This is an important scenario we need to master in order to get the most out of the London System. White is in full control. However, there is no easy breakthrough available, and a lot of players lack the patience to maneuver around and they rush with b3-c4 ➼ allowing Black to get very decent counterplay. }
42. Ke5
{ This is a nice move to make on the board. The king is very active and Black can't do anything other than wait. However, we will see that White decided to reroute the king a bit later. This is an important quality in order to be a strong player ➼ admitting your mistake and choosing a different path. In this specific position we can't really say 42. Ke5 was a mistake since Black has no active plan what so ever, it's just that it took some time for White to find the winning plan. }
42... Bc8 43. Ra1 { Activating the rook. } 43... Rc7 44. Rf3
{ This is an interesting plan with the idea to play Rf6. } 44... Bb7 45. Rf6
{ Placing the rook on the most active square. } 45... Bc8 46. Kf4
{ The king is heading towards a5. } 46... Re8 47. Ke3 Bb7
{ 47...e5  Active play was not working.  48.Rd6+-  Winning the d5-pawn. } 48.
Kd2 { Heading towards the b4-square. } 48... Bc8 49. Kc2 Ree7
{ Black is just making waiting moves in the meantime. } 50. Kb3 Rc6 51. Kb4 Rb7
{ Black was mostly concerned about Ka5-Kb6 ideas and missed White's 'hidden' plan.   51...Rcc7  This is a better defense, preparing to play ...Re8-Rh8 ➼ avoiding the direct f4-f5 break. To the unexperienced eye, it might seem like Black is setting up a fortress, but White has some fascinating resources to break down Black's defenses.  52.f4  Re8  53.Be2  Keeping an eye on the h5-pawn and preparing f5 ideas.  53...Rh8  Defending the h5-pawn in order to meet f5 with ...gxf5 without dropping the h5-pawn like in the game.  54.b3  This is very useful to have, preparing the c4-break at the 'right time'.  54...Bb7  55.Ka5  Introducing Kb6 ideas.  55...Rc6  56.Bd3!  Rc7  This is meant to play ...Bc8 @@StartBracket@@without allowing f5@@EndBracket@@ ➼ the point being to defend against the positional piece sacrifice with Bxg6 followed by Rxe6!   56...Rh7  Making a waiting move.  57.Re1!  The rook is important on this file ➼ preparing Bxg6 followed by Rexe6 ideas.  57...Rh8  58.b4!  Improving the position, but also putting Black in zugzwang. There is simply no way to stop both f5 and Bxg6 ideas.  58...Rh7   58...Bc8  Protecting the e6-pawn which is meant to discourage Bxg6.  59.f5!!  This move works even better than before because the c6-rook is undefended.  59...gxf5  60.Bxf5  Black is unable to capture the bishop because the c6-rook will drop. White has managed to open up the f-file which is already huge progress.  60...Bd7  61.Bc2  Simply preparing to double the rooks with Ref1!  61...Be8  62.Ref1  Black is in zugzwang again.  62...Rf8  63.Rh6  Attacking the h5-pawn.  63...f5  This is a better try, but it doesn't save Black.   63...Rh8  This gives White an easy win.  64.Rxh8  Kxh8  65.Rf6+-  Followed by the simple Bd1-Bxh5 and White wins material.  64.Bd1  Threatening Bxh5!  64...Rh8  65.Rxh8  Kxh8  66.c4!!  After another stunning pawn break, White is cruising to victory.  66...dxc4   66...bxc4  This allows a winning rook endgame.  67.Ba4!  67...Rc8  68.Bxe8  Rxe8  69.Kxa6+-  The two connected passers are usually a deadly combo. White will push the b-pawn all the way to b7 followed by his comrade ➼ the c-pawn.  67.Re1  Threatening to push d5 because the e8-bishop will remain undefended in case of ...exd5!  67...Bf7  68.Bf3  Attacking the c6-rook.  68...Rc8  69.Kxa6+-  White will promote after Kb7 followed by advancing the c-pawn.  59.Bxg6  fxg6  60.Rexe6  Rxe6  61.Rxe6  Kf7  62.Rf6+  Kg7  63.Rd6+-  57.Re1  Threatening to break Black's 'fortress' with Bxg6 followed by Rexe6!   57.Kb6  This looks tempting, but we have to watch out for Black's tricks as well!  57...Rc6+!  This is not a big deal because we can simply go back with Ka5 and continue.  58.Kxb7  Rhc8=  Black will play ...R8c7+ followed by ...Rc7+ with a funny perpetual.  57...Bc8  Defending against Bxg6.  58.f5!!  This stunning idea works very well.  58...gxf5   58...exf5  59.Rd6  Threatening Rxd5!  59...Bb7  60.Bf1+-  We are going to play Bg2 followed by Bxd5 with a winning endgame thanks to the connected passers.  59.Rh6!!  Sacrificing another pawn in order to deflect Black's king and rook from covering the queenside where White will win thanks to the c-pawn.  59...Rxh6  60.gxh6+  Kxh6  61.Kb6!  The king becomes a very important attacking piece in the endgame!  61...Rb7+  62.Kxa6!  We can safely collect this pawn because Black is lacking a useful discovery.  62...Rb8+  63.Ka7  Attacking the b8-rook.  63...Rb7+  64.Ka8+-  With an easily winning endgame for White. We can play Rg1-Rg8 and in case Black stops that with ...Kh7 ➼ then Rg5 wins the h5-pawn. }
52. Be2
{ Targeting the h5-pawn. There was no need to play Ka5 when concrete play works on the kingside. }
52... Rb8 53. f4
{ I guess only now Black realized what's about to happen, but it was too late. }
53... Bd7 { With the idea to play ...Rh8 and protect the h5-pawn. } 54. f5
{ After this stunning break White has an easy win. } 54... gxf5
{ 54...exf5  This drops the a6-pawn, and with that ➼ the whole queenside.  55.Rxc6  Bxc6  56.Rxa6+-  With a winning position because Black's queenside is falling apart. }
55. Bxh5 { Threatening Rxf7+! } 55... Rf8
{ 55...Be8  56.Bf3+-  This would have been similar to the game. } 56. Bf3
{ Making room for the h-pawn to advance. } 56... Rh8 57. h5 Be8 58. b3
{ Preparing the c4-break! } 58... Bd7 59. h6+
{ Keeping Black's rook passive on h8. } 59... Kf8 60. c4
{ All of Black's pieces are on bad squares! The rest is simple. } 60... bxc4
61. bxc4 Ke7 62. cxd5 exd5 63. Rxa6
{ One of many possible solutions. White is using the 'X-rays'. } 63... Rb8+ 64.
Kc3 Re6 65. Bxd5 Re3+ 66. Kd2
{ White's king is very safe. There is no realistic attack for Black! } 66...
Rh3 67. Rxf7+ Ke8 68. Rb6
{ Making Black's b8-rook passive and all the 'checkmating dreams' are fading away so Black had to resign. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Typical Endgames"]
[Black "Kovacevic, Vlatko vs. Milovanovic, Ninoslav, Tuzla 1981"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 d5 3. Bf4 g6 4. e3 Bg7 5. Nbd2 O-O 6. c3 b6 7. a4 c5 8. Bd3
Ba6 9. Bxa6 Nxa6 10. O-O Nh5 11. Qe2 Nxf4 12. Qxa6 Ne6 13. Rfd1 Qc8 14. Qe2 a5
15. Nb1 Qc6 16. Nfd2 Nc7 17. Nf3 Rad8 18. Qc2 f6 19. Nbd2 e5 20. dxe5 fxe5 21.
e4 Ne6 22. exd5 Qxd5 23. Qb3 Qxb3 24. Nxb3 Nf4 25. Rxd8 Rxd8 26. Nfd2 Nd3 27.
Nc4 e4 28. Rd1 Re8 29. Nc1 Ne5 30. Nxe5 Bxe5 31. Kf1 e3 32. g3 exf2 33. Kxf2
Rb8 34. Rd5 Bf6 35. Nd3 Kf7 36. Ke3 Re8+ 37. Kd2 h6 38. Rd7+ Re7 39. Rxe7+ Kxe7
{ This is a basic knight vs bad bishop endgame. I decided to put it into our 'Thematic Endgames' section because first of all it's coming from a London System game, and secondly I think the queenside pawn structure is very common after White pushes a4 and Black reacts with ...a5. }
40. Ke3
{ Centralizing the king is one of the most important ideas in the endgame. }
40... Kd6
{ 40...Ke6  This also does not help.  41.Ke4!  Threatening to play Nf4-Nd5!  41...g5  42.Nf2  Threatening to play Ng4-Ne3 with Nd5/Nf5!  42...h5  43.Nd1!  Preparing to play Ne3!  43...g4  44.Ne3  Heading towards d5.  44...Bd8  45.Nd5+-  With Nf4 on the next move ➼ winning the h5-pawn. }
41. c4
{ Fixing the enemy pawns on the dark squares is sound strategical idea, but it allows Black to set up a surprising fortress.   41.Ke4!  This is the most accurate move ➼ threatening to play Nf4!  41...g5   41...Bg5  42.Ne5+-  Winning the g6-pawn.   41...c4  42.Nf4  Attacking the g6-pawn.  42...g5  43.Nd5  43...Bd8  44.Kd4+-  Winning the c4-pawn.  42.Nf2!  Threatening Ng4!  42...h5   42...Bg7  43.Ng4  h5  44.Ne3  Threatening Kf5/Nd5!  44...Kc6  45.Kf5  Attacking the g5-pawn.  45...g4  46.Kg6+-  Winning the h5-pawn.  43.Kf5+-  With Ne4 on the next move ➼ winning the g5-pawn. }
41... Bg5+
{ Returning the favor.   41...g5!!  This anti-positional move would have saved the game for black!  42.Ke4  Ke6  43.g4  Bh8  This is super counter-intuitive, but Black holds. Usually with the pawns on the same color as your bishop the position should be lost, but White is unable to activate the knight because Black can keep control over the key squares.  44.b3  Bg7  45.Nf2  If we could play Ne3 that would give us some pressure ➼ threatening both Nd5 and Nf5.  45...Bh8  46.Nd1  Bd4!  The simplest! Black is ready to get rid of the knight once it arrives on e3, with a drawn position as a result.   46...Bg7  For analytical purposes I had a look at this move and it seems that Black also holds here, but it's a study-like case. Generally Black should be losing with passive defense.  47.Ne3  Be5  48.h3  Bg7  49.Nd5  Bf8  50.Nxb6  Be7  51.Nd5  Bd8=  Somehow Black is also able to hold down a pawn because we have no entry squares for the king.  47.Ne3  Bxe3  48.Kxe3  Ke5  49.h3=  We are lucky to save the game with this move! }
42. Ke4 { Now White is back on the winning track. } 42... Bf6 43. b3
{ Threatening to play Nf4 without dropping the b2-pawn. } 43... Bd4 44. Nf4
{ Attacking the g6-pawn. } 44... Bg1
{ 44...g5  45.Ne2!  The only winning move!   45.Nd5  Ke6=  And Black holds in similar fashion to what we've seen in the 41...g5!! line.  45...Bb2  46.Kf5  Ba1  47.Ng1!  Avoiding all the counterplay! First we bring the knight to f3 ➼ avoiding ...Ke5 and then we can safely collect the kingside pawns with Kg6.  47...Bb2  48.Nf3  Bc3  49.g4!  A nice final touch!  49...Bg7  50.Kg6  Bf8  51.Kf7  51...Be7  52.Kg7+-  Collecting the h6-pawn next ➼ with a winning position. }
45. h3 g5
{ 45...Bh2  46.Kf3+-  Threatening to collect the g6-pawn and to trap the enemy bishop with Kg2! Keep in mind that  46...g5  runs into  47.Ne2!  and the bishop gets trapped. }
46. Ne2 Bf2 47. Kf5
{ Threatening to play Nc3-Ne4 followed by g4 with a winning endgame. } 47... h5
{ This was an interesting try, but not good enough. Black is sacrificing the pawns in order to get some activity on the queenside. }
48. Kxg5 Ke5 49. Kxh5 Ke4 50. g4 Ke3 51. Nc3 { Heading towards d5. } 51... Kd3
52. Nd5
{ Black had to resign because Nxb6 is coming ➼ defending both the a4 and c4 pawns. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Typical Endgames"]
[Black "Capablanca, Jose Raul vs. Kreymborg, Alfred, New York 1910"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Bf4 e6 4. e3 c5 5. c3 Nc6 6. Bd3 Bd6 7. Bxd6 Qxd6 8.
Nbd2 e5 9. dxe5 Nxe5 10. Nxe5 Qxe5 11. Bb5+ Bd7 12. Qa4 Qc7 13. O-O-O O-O 14.
Bxd7 Nxd7 15. Nf3 Qc6 16. Qxc6 bxc6 17. Nd2 Ne5 18. Kc2 c4 19. Rhf1 f5 20. Nf3
Nxf3 21. gxf3 Rae8
{ This is a classical endgame and I mainly decided to include it because we have the great Jose Raul Capablanca with the white pieces. He didn't manage to get a whole lot from the opening @@StartBracket@@despite playing the London System@@EndBracket@@, but he was always outclassing his opponents in the endgame phase. }
22. Rd4 { This is played with the idea to meet ...f4 with e4! } 22... Rf6
{ 22...f4!  This results in decent counterplay.  23.e4  Rf6=  Black has ...Rh6 ideas ➼ holding equality according to the computer. }
23. b3 { Opening up lines on the queenside. } 23... cxb3+ 24. axb3 Kf7
{ 24...f4=  This is still the right call for black. } 25. Kd3 Re7 26. Ra1
{ Activating the rook. } 26... Ke6 27. Ra6 Rc7 28. Rda4 g5
{ Trying to avoid the squeeze.   28...Rff7  29.f4!  This move is very strong because it prevents Black's ...f4 ideas to get counterplay. The following line is pretty instructive.  29...Kd6  30.b4  Rfe7  31.h4!  Taking space on the kingside.  31...g6  32.Ra1  Preparing Rh1 ideas.  32...Rcd7  33.h5!  This works well because 33...gxh5 34.Rh1 wins back the pawn with a better position.  33...Rb7  34.h6!  Rec7  35.R1a5  Re7  36.b5  Threatening Rxc6+!  36...Rec7  37.Kd4+-  Black is in zugzwang. }
29. h4
{ 29.Rxa7?!  This gives White no advantage.  29...Rxa7  30.Rxa7  Rh6=  Winning the h2-pawn with an equal game. }
29... g4 { Setting up a small trick. } 30. Ke2
{ Protecting the f2-pawn and threatening fxg4 since Black will no longer be able to play ...Rxf2 at the end of the line.   30.fxg4?!  fxg4  31.Rxg4  Rxf2=  This is Black's point. }
30... gxf3+ 31. Kxf3 Rff7 32. Ke2
{ Missing the chance to activate the king, but White is still pressing.   32.Kf4+-  Activating the king is more precise with c4 ideas next. }
32... Kd6 33. b4 Rb7
{ 33...f4=  Would have given Black better chances to hold! } 34. h5 h6 35. f4
{ After this move there is no more ...f4 counterplay! } 35... Rg7 36. Kd3 Rge7
37. Ra1
{ 37.R4a5!  Would have put Black in zugzwang!  37...Rg7   37...Rbc7  38.b5+-  With bxc6 next followed by Rxa7 with a winning endgame.  38.Kd4+-  Threatening Rxd5+! winning on the spot. }
37... Rg7 38. Kd4 Rg2 39. R6a2 Rbg7 40. Kd3
{ Threatening Rxa7! and forcing Black to trade rooks. From this point on White is objectively winning. }
40... Rxa2 41. Rxa2
{ Black has to give up on the g-file not to lose the a7-pawn which turns out to be decisive. }
41... Re7
{ 41...Ke6  This allows Ra6 with b5!  42.Ra6!  Kd6  43.b5  Rc7  44.Kd4+-  With an easily winning endgame. }
42. Rg2 { Threatening to play Rg6! } 42... Re6 43. Rg7
{ Attacking the a7-pawn. } 43... Re7 44. Rg8 { Threatening Rf8! } 44... c5 45.
Rg6+ Re6 46. bxc5+ Kd7 47. Rg7+ { Winning the a7-pawn. } 47... Kc6 48. Rxa7
Kxc5 49. Rf7 { Picking up the f5-pawn next, so Black had to resign. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Typical Endgames"]
[Black "Grachev, Boris vs. Akopian, Vladimir Eduardovic, Khanty-Mansiysk 2013"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. Bf4 b6 4. e3 Bb7 5. h3 Be7 6. Bd3 O-O 7. O-O c5 8. c3 h6
9. Qe2 cxd4 10. exd4 d6 11. Nbd2 Nbd7 12. Bg3 Qc7 13. Rfe1 Rfe8 14. Ba6 Bxa6
15. Qxa6 Qc8 16. Qd3 d5 17. Ne5 Nxe5 18. Bxe5 Nd7 19. Bf4 Nf8 20. Nf3 Qd8 21.
Ne5 Bd6 22. Qg3 Bxe5 23. Bxe5 Qg5 24. Qd3 Ng6 25. Re3 Nxe5 26. Rxe5 Qf6
{ This is a typical endgame arising from the Carlsbad structure. Objectively speaking, Black should be able to hold, but as seen in the games between Kamsky-Belozerov and Nihal-Checa ➼ White has the easier game with annoying pressure on the kingside. }
27. Rae1
{ White has a very good version of this typical endgame because Black has made no progress on the queenside yet. }
27... g6
{ Simply too passive.   27...Rab8!  Black needs to create counterplay quickly with the minority attack ➼ otherwise the game becomes very one-sided.  28.R1e3!?  Bringing the rook over seems pretty dangerous.  28...b5  29.Qe2  Threatening Rxd5!  29...Rec8  30.Rf3  Attacking Black's queen.  30...Qd8  31.Qd2!?  Slowing down Black's ...b4 push.  31...a5  32.g4↑  With g5 on the next move ➼ exploiting the h6-hook, White has a dangerous initiative. }
28. R5e3
{ White has many ways of playing this position. For example,  28.R1e3  is also very interesting. }
28... Qf5 29. Qe2
{ Remember that the key idea is to keep queens on the board in order to get any attacking chances! }
29... h5
{ Controlling the g4-square, but creating another hook on h5. The position is difficult to play for Black regardless. }
30. Rf3 Qg5 31. Rg3
{ White keeps making annoying threats. Black's queen is already in danger. }
31... Qh6
{ 31...Qf5  This seems logical, but the queen can easily get trapped.  32.Qd2  Threatening to infiltrate with Qh6!  32...Kg7??  Stopping Qh6, but allowing something worse.   32...Qf6  This is a better defense, but still much worse for Black.  33.Rf3  33...Qg7  34.Qg5±  With Rf6 next followed by g4 ➼ White is in full control.  33.Rf3+-  The queen gets trapped. }
32. Qe5
{ White has a simple and effective plan: R1e3-Ref3-Rf6 with good attacking prospects. }
32... Qg7 33. Qf4
{ Following the golden rule 'We need queens to create an attack in these positions'. White is threatening to play Re5 followed by Rxh5! }
33... f6 { Controlling the e5-square, but weakening the e6-pawn. } 34. Rge3
{ Attacking the e6-pawn. Black can only defend it with the queen which will allow us to infiltrate with Qh6! }
34... Qf7 35. Qh6
{ Threatening Rg3 next ➼ switching back to the g6-pawn. White is using the principle of the two weaknesses. Generally if you attack only a single weak square your opponent will be able to defend it, so that is why it's important to have two weaknesses to play against ➼ because it's much harder for your opponent to keep both under control. }
35... Re7 36. Rg3 { Threatening Rxg6! } 36... g5 37. f4
{ After this move White wins material. Black is unable to keep everything defended. }
37... Qg7 38. Qxg7+
{ This move is winning for white, but a bit inaccurate. I will leave the rest of the game without annotations because White could have won on the spot here and the rest is not super relevant to our topic.   38.Qxh5!  This was the easiest and for sure Grachev would have made this move with more time on the clock @@StartBracket@@this was a blitz game@@EndBracket@@.  38...Qh7  This has to be played to avoid immediate collapse.  39.Qxh7+  Kxh7  40.fxg5+-  White is up two pawns with an easily winning endgame.  40...Rg8  does not help because of  41.gxf6! }
38... Kxg7 39. fxg5 f5 40. h4 Rc8 41. Rge3 Rc6 42. Kf2 b5 43. a3 a5 44. Kf3 Kf7
45. Ra1 Rc4 46. Kf4 Rb7 47. Ke5 Rb6 48. Kf4 b4 { 48...Rcc6± } 49. axb4 axb4 50.
Ra7+ Kg6 51. Re7 Rcc6 52. Ke5 bxc3 53. Rxc3 Rxc3 54. bxc3 Rb2 55. Rxe6+ Kg7 56.
Kxf5 Rf2+ 57. Ke5 Rxg2 58. Rh6 Rg3 59. Kxd5 Rxc3 60. Rxh5 *

