[White "Typical Endgames"]
[Black "Tang, Andrew vs. Ali Marandi, Cemil Can, chesscom 2019"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 c5 3. e3 cxd4 4. exd4 Nc6 5. c3 Bf5 6. Nf3 Qb6 7. Qb3 e6 8.
Nbd2 Nf6
{ This is a very common endgame which can be very pleasant if you know the key plans and typical maneuvers, otherwise it's not that simple to make progress. I highly advise you to focus your endgame study around these positions because they appear very often on the board when Black defends against Qb3 by playing ...Qb6. }
9. Qxb6
{ Entering a slightly better endgame because Black has the 'doubled isolated' pawns. }
9... axb6 10. Bb5 { Creating an unpleasant threat of going Ne5! } 10... Nd7
{ Controlling the e5-square. } 11. a4
{ This is typically a very strong move after playing Bb5 in these endgames. White support the b5-bishop and in some positions Black has to watch out for a5 ➼ potentially opening up the a-file for the rook.   11.a3!?  The computer comes up with this idea mainly because in some lines ...Na7 could be a bit annoying. The a3-pawn is a bit safer compared to what was played in the game, but the difference is very slim.  11...Be7   11...f6  Threatening to expand on the kingside with ...g5! If Black is able to achieve that move, the position is close to equal. White's initiative is based on kingside play as in the game.  12.h4!  Stopping the ...g5 push!  12...h5  13.Nf1  Maneuvering the knight to e3!  13...Na7  Attacking the b5-bishop.  14.Be2!  b5!?  This is an interesting plan for Black ➼ threatening to play ...Nb6-Nc4!  15.Ne3  Threatening Nxf5!  15...Bg6  16.Bc7!  Stopping Black from playing ...Nb6!  16...Rc8  Attacking the c7-bishop.  17.Ba5!  Keeping the b6-square under control.  17...Nc6  Attacking the a5-bishop.  18.Bb4!  Keeping the bishop safe and attacking the b5-pawn.  18...Na7  19.Nd2!  Making room for the f4-push.  19...Nb6  20.f4!  Nc4  21.Ndxc4  bxc4  22.O-O  ⩲  We are going to push f5 on the next move and Black has problems with the d5-pawn.  12.h4!  Initiating the kingside play! ➼ this is the way to start crushing in these endgames. Going for the natural 12. O-O only leads to an equal game @@StartBracket@@this is what most players would play in general@@EndBracket@@.  12...O-O   12...h5  This move weakens the g5-square.  13.O-O  O-O  14.Rfe1!  Activating the rook and preparing the typical maneuver with Nf1-Ne3!  14...Rfc8  15.Nf1  Preparing to play Ne3!  15...Bd8  Played with the idea to go ...Bc7.  16.Ne3  Threatening Nxf5!  16...Bg6   16...Be4  17.Ng5!  Threatening Nxe4!  17...Bg6  18.g3  Bc7  19.Bxc7  Rxc7  20.Nh3⩲  With Nf4 on the next move ➼ White has pressure on the kingside.  17.g3!  This is a very useful move, protecting the h4-pawn among other things.  17...Bc7  18.Bxc7  Rxc7  19.Ng5!  With the idea to play Nh3 followed by Nf4!  19...Nf6  20.Nh3⩲  With the idea to play Nf4 followed by f3-g4 ➼ with pressure on the kingside.  13.Nf1  Preparing the standard Ne3!  13...h6  14.Ne3  Threatening Nxf5!  14...Be4  15.h5!  Fixing the hook on h6.  15...Rfd8  16.Ke2⩲  We can continue with Rhg1 followed by g4-g5 ➼ taking advantage of the ...h6-hook and attacking Black on the kingside. }
11... Be7 12. Ke2 { The king is useful in the center. } 12... O-O
{ Black goes for the natural move, but after this White plays a perfect game.   12...f6!  Preparing to expand on the kingside with ...g5 ➼ This would have given Black very good chances to get a balanced endgame.  13.Nf1!?  Preparing to play Ne3.   13.h4  This is typically the right move ➼ stopping the ...g5 push, but Black can force the bishop trade with ...Na7!  13...Na7!  Threatening ...Nxb5!  14.Bd3  Bxd3+  15.Kxd3  Kf7=  With a balanced endgame.  13...g5  14.Bg3  h5  Threatening to trap the g3-bishop with ...h4!  15.h4!  g4  16.N3d2  e5!  Gaining space in the center. This move gives Black a reasonable position.  17.dxe5  fxe5  18.Ne3  Attacking both the f5-bishop and the d5-pawn.  18...Be6  19.Rhe1  Activating the rook and preparing to hide the king with Kf1-Kg1.  19...O-O  20.Kf1  Threatening to push c4!  20...Nc5!?   With the idea to meet  21.c4  by playing  21...d4!  22.Nd5  Bd8  and Black is solid.  21.Kg1=  The position should be objectively equal, but White can try Nc2 with b4 ideas and the e5-pawn is a bit vulnerable. }
13. Nf1 { Going for the typical maneuver ➼ preparing to play Ne3! } 13... h6
{ Making a square for the bishop on h7, but at the same time creating a hook! }
14. Ne3 { Threatening Nxf5! } 14... Bh7 15. h4
{ My guess is that this plan took Black by surprise. It now becomes obvious that ...h6 has made White's kingside play much quicker. }
15... Bf6
{ 15...Rfc8  This could have been a small improvement over the game, but Black's position is already quite unpleasant.  16.g4  Nf8  17.h5⩲  With g5 on the next move ➼ White has annoying pressure on the kingside. }
16. g4
{ Threatening to play g5! White's kingside storm is very effective. This is the key plan that I want you to remember. }
16... Be4 17. g5 Bxf3+
{ This is the losing mistake, but Black's position was already very difficult.   17...hxg5  This would have been a better try.  18.hxg5  Be7  19.Rhg1±  White has a very dangerous initiative with Nh4 followed by Ng4 coming next. }
18. Kxf3 hxg5
{ 18...Be7  This can be a clever trick to avoid the attack, but it doesn't work here.  19.gxh6  g6!?  Trying to keep the kingside closed.  20.Rag1+-  The problem with this plan is that White is able to break with Bd3 followed by h5! }
19. hxg5 Be7 20. Rh3
{ Preparing to double up on the h-file. Black is simply getting checkmated. }
20... f5 21. g6
{ The key move to create a mating net ➼ taking away the escape f7-square. }
21... Rf6 { The only move to avoid mate, but dropping the rook. } 22. Rah1 Rxg6
23. Rh8+ Kf7 24. Rxa8 { With an extra rook for white! The rest is simple. }
24... e5 25. Bxe5 Ncxe5+ 26. dxe5 Nxe5+ 27. Ke2 Rd6 28. Nxf5
{ This was simply a perfect London System display by 'The Penguin'! } *

