1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Bf4 c5 4. e3 Nc6 5. Nbd2 cxd4 6. exd4 Bg4 7. c3 e6 8.
Qb3 Qc8 9. Bd3 Be7 10. O-O O-O 11. Rfe1 Bh5 12. h3 Bg6 13. Be2 Ne4 14. Nxe4
Bxe4 15. Ne5 Nxe5 16. Bxe5 Bg6 17. Rad1 a6 18. a4 Qc6 19. a5 Rfc8 20. Bd3 Bxd3
21. Rxd3 Bd6 22. Rg3 Bxe5 23. Rxe5 g6
{ This is a typical endgame arising from the Carlsbad structure. Objectively speaking ➼ generally Black should be able to hold, but it's incredibly tricky in a practical game because it's much easier to play as White and we generally have no risks pressing in this type of position. }
24. h4
{ This is an improved version compared to the Kamsky-Bleizerov game because Black has made no progress on the queenside while White is ready to attack the enemy king. }
24... Qb5
{ Trading queens would be ideal for Black ➼ avoiding the kingside danger.   24...b6!  This was required in order to get counterplay on the queenside.  25.axb6  Rab8!  26.Qc2  Threatening h5!  26...Qxb6  Attacking the b2-pawn.  27.Re2⩲  White keeps a better position with good attacking prospects on the kingside, but it's fair to say that Black is more active compared to what happened in the game. }
25. Qa3
{ Keeping queens on the board is crucial in this structure ➼ in order to attack Black on the kingside. }
25... Qe8 26. h5
{ Now Black continually has to reckon with White either taking on g6 or pushing the pawn to h6! }
26... Kg7 27. Ree3 { Threatening to bring the queen with Qd6-Qe5+! } 27... Rc4
{ With the idea to play ...Ra4-Ra1+ ➼ but allowing White to bring the queen over the kingside faster.   27...Rc6!  This was a better defense ➼ stopping Qd6.  28.Qa1±  White would have still been much better with Qe1 next followed by Ref3 and Qe5+! }
28. Qd6
{ After this move White has a deadly initiative with four attackers against the lonely king. }
28... Qf8 29. Qe5+
{ Once again, we are not interested in trading queens in this structure ➼ unless we can win material. }
29... Kg8 30. Ref3 { Threatening to take twice on g6! } 30... Qg7 31. Rf6
{ For the third time ➼ we are not interested in exchanging queens! } 31... Rc6
{ 31...Rcc8  This allows a direct win.  32.hxg6  hxg6  33.Rfxg6!!  After this move White wins the queen.  33...fxg6  34.Qxe6+   This wins because  34...Qf7  runs into  35.Rxg6+!  34...Kh8  35.Rh3++-  Picking up the queen next with a winning endgame because Black's king is too weak.   31...Re8  32.Rgf3  Threatening Rxf7!  32...Rf8  33.Qe3+-  With the simple threat of pushing h6 ➼ White is winning the f7-pawn. }
32. Rgf3 { Threatening Rxf7! } 32... Rf8 33. Qg5
{ Threatening h6 followed by Rxf7! } 33... Re8
{ With the idea to meet h6 with ...Qf8 ➼ but allowing White to get a winning endgame.   33...Rcc8  34.h6  34...Qh8  35.Qf4+-  Collecting the f7-pawn next with a winning position.   33...b6  This shows White's idea quite well.  34.h6  34...Qh8  35.Rxf7!  Rxf7  36.Qd8++-  With checkmate on the next move. }
34. Rxf7 Qxf7 35. Rxf7 Kxf7 36. Qh6
{ White has an easy win because the enemy king is too weak! The rest is simple. }
36... gxh5 37. Qxh7+ Kf6 38. Qxb7 Rec8 39. g3 R8c7 40. Qb8 Ke7 41. Kg2 Rc8 42.
Qe5 Kd7 43. Qxh5 Rb8 44. Qe2
{ 44.Qf7+!  This would have been more precise.  44...Kc8  45.g4+-  White is simply queening the g-pawn. }
44... Rb5 45. g4 Rxa5 46. Kg3 Ra2 47. Qc2 Rb6 48. Qh7+ Kd6 49. Qg8 Rbxb2 50.
Qd8+ Kc6 51. f3 a5 52. Qc8+ Kd6 53. Qd8+ Kc6 54. Qe7 Re2 55. g5 a4 56. Kf4
{ Preparing to push the g-pawn without allowing ...Rg2+. } 56... Re1 57. c4
dxc4 58. Qc5+ Kd7 59. Qb5+ Kd6 60. Qb4+ Kd7 61. Qxe1 *

