1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 Nf6 3. e3 c5 4. c3 Nc6 5. Nd2 cxd4 6. exd4 Bf5 7. Ngf3 e6 8.
Be2 Bd6 9. Bg3 O-O 10. O-O h6 11. a4 a6 12. Re1 Ne4 13. Nxe4 Bxe4 14. Nd2 Bg6
15. Bxd6 Qxd6 16. Qb3 Rab8 17. Bf1 Qc7 18. Qa3 Rfc8 19. Nb3 e5 20. dxe5 Nxe5
21. Nd4 Re8 22. Qb3 Ng4 23. g3 Rxe1 24. Rxe1 Rd8 25. Bg2 Nf6 26. f3 h5 27. Qb4
Re8 28. Rxe8+ Nxe8 29. Bf1 Nf6
{ This is a very common endgame which can arise after Black plays ...cxd4 and then breaks with ...e5! }
30. Nb3 { Preparing to play Qc5! } 30... Bf5
{ This allows White to grab a firm grip over the position.   30...Qe5!  31.Qd4  Qe1∞  This was a better chance to create counterplay, but not easy to find. }
31. Qc5 { After this move Black's position becomes very hard to play. } 31...
Qd8
{ Keeping the queens is the best practical decision I think ➼ keeping chances for a perpetual check.   31...Qxc5+  This clearly leads to a very unpleasant endgame for Black which would be a nightmare to defend. At first it looks like Black should be able to hold with computerish defense, but after I did some digging, it's not clear at all if Black can actually save this position. The general idea is that these endgames are very dangerous and fairly one-sided.  32.Nxc5  Attacking the b7-pawn.  32...Bc8  33.a5!  Fixing Black's pawns on the light squares! This is important because our bishop will be able to attack them later on.  33...Kf8  34.Kf2  Bringing the king closer to the center.  34...Ke7  35.Nb3  Preparing to play Nd4.  35...Kd6  36.Nd4  g6  37.Ke3  Preparing to play Kf4.  37...Nd7  38.Kf4  Threatening to infiltrate with Kg5!  38...f6  39.h4!  Fixing Black's pawns.  39...Ne5  40.Ke3  Bd7  41.Be2  Preparing to maneuver the bishop with Bd1-Bc2 ➼ attacking the g6-pawn.  41...Bc8  42.b3!  This is important so we can play Bd1 without allowing ...Nc4+!  42...Bd7  43.Bd1  Preparing to play Bc2!  43...Bc8  44.Bc2  Keeping an eye on the g6-pawn.  44...Bd7  45.Ke2  Threatening to push f4 ➼ deflecting Black's knight so we can collect the g6-pawn.  45...Be8  Protecting the g6-pawn.  46.Kd2!  This is the most precise!   46.f4?!  Gives Black counterplay after a crazy line.  46...Ng4  47.f5  g5!  48.hxg5  fxg5  49.Nf3  Attacking the g5-pawn.  49...Bb5+!  The hidden resource!  50.Kd2  h4!  Deflecting White's knight in order to get ...Ke5!  51.gxh4  gxh4  52.Nxh4  Ke5=∞  Black manages to activate with very good chances to hold despite being down a pawn.  46...Nd7   46...Bf7  Passive defense won't save Black.  47.f4  47...Nd7   47...Ng4  This loses a pawn.  48.f5!  g5  49.hxg5  fxg5  50.Nf3+-  With Nxg5 next and most likely a winning endgame.  48.b4!  Controlling the c5-square.  48...Be8  49.Ke3  Activating the king.  49...Bf7  50.Nf3!  Preparing to push f5 without allowing ...g5!  50...Be8   50...f5  Stopping the f5-push, but weakening too many dark squares.  51.Kd4  Be8  52.Bb3  Attacking the d5-pawn.  52...Nf6  53.Ne5+-  Black is in zugzwang because  53...Ke6  allows  54.Kc5!  51.f5!  gxf5  52.Nd4!  Bf7  53.Kf4+-  We are going to play Nxf5+ next ➼ with a winning endgame.  47.Bd3  Ne5  48.Be2  Preparing to push f4-f5 and then the h5-pawn will be vulnerable.  48...Bd7  49.f4  Attacking the e5-knight.  49...Ng4  50.f5!!  After this stunning idea White is winning.  50...gxf5   50...Bxf5  51.Nxf5+  gxf5  52.b4!  White now has a simple plan to go Bf3 followed by the c4-break ➼ collecting the enemy queenside pawns.  52...Ke6  53.Bf3  Ke5  54.Ke2!  Kd6  55.c4!  dxc4  56.Bxb7  Here you can see why it was important to fix Black's pawns on the light squares with 33.a5!  56...Ne5  57.Kd2  f4  58.gxf4  Ng6  59.Bxa6  Nxh4  60.Bxc4+-  With a winning endgame for White thanks to the two connected passers.  51.Bf3  Nh2  52.Bxh5  Nf1+  53.Ke1  Nxg3  54.Bf7+-  White should be winning with the outside passer and the queenside pawns fixed on the light squares. }
32. Nd4 { Centralizing and attacking the f5-bishop. } 32... Bc8 33. a5
{ Fixing Black's pawns on the light squares! This is a very important strategical concept because the pawns will be targets for our bishop in the future. }
33... Qe8 { Threatening ...Qe3+! } 34. Kf2 { Controlling the e3-square. } 34...
g6 35. Qd6 Kg7 36. b3
{ Stopping ...Qa4 ideas.   36.h4!  This would have been the most precise ➼ fixing Black's pawns and avoiding any ...h4 moves that Black can throw in.  36...Qd7  37.Qxd7  Bxd7  38.Ke3±  With Kf4 next followed by Nb3-Nc5 White should be winning. }
36... Bd7 { 36...h4±  Good or bad, this had to be tried. } 37. Qc7
{ Attacking the b7-pawn. } 37... Bc8 38. Bd3 { Activating the bishop. } 38...
h4
{ This is a good try, but a bit too late.   38...Qd7  Trading queens is very dangerous for Black.  39.Qxd7  Nxd7  40.Ke3  Ne5  Threatening ...Nxd3!  41.Bc2  Kf6  42.h4!  Fixing Black's pawns.  42...Ke7  43.Kf4  Attacking the e5-knight.  43...f6  44.g4!  hxg4  45.fxg4  Kf7  45...Bxg4 46.Bxg6! was the point.  46.g5  Nd7  47.Bd1+-  With Bf3 comming on the next move ➼ White has a winning endgame. }
39. gxh4 Qh8 40. Qf4
{ Protecting the h4-pawn.   40.Ke2!   This is even more precise because  40...Qxh4  allows  41.Qxc8!  40...Qe8+  41.Kd2+-  With Kc2-b4 White has a winning endgame thanks to the extra pawn. }
40... Qd8 41. b4 Qd7 42. Qe5
{ 42.Nf5+!  This cute trick was available.  42...gxf5  43.Qg5+!  Winning back the knight.  43...Kf8  44.Qxf6+-  White wins thanks to the h-pawn. }
42... Qh3 43. h5 { 43.Qg3+-  This would have been simpler. } 43... Qh4+
{ 43...Qxh5  This was also not saving Black's position.  44.Qxh5  Nxh5  45.b5!  axb5   45...Kf6  46.bxa6  bxa6  47.Ke3+-  Avoiding ...Nf4 and we can play Nc6-Nb4 next ➼ winning a pawn.  46.Nxb5+-  WIth Nd6 next ➼ winning the b7-pawn. }
44. Ke2 gxh5 45. Qg3+
{ The human move!   45.Bf5!  The computer always finds something a bit more precise.  45...Qg5  46.Qg3+-  The same idea, but a bit more precise. }
45... Qxg3 46. hxg3 Ne8 47. Ke3 Nd6
{ Giving White an easy win.   47...Kf6  This would have been a better try, but it still loses.  48.Kf4  Nd6  49.b5!  Going for the bishop endgame.  49...axb5  50.Nxb5  Nxb5  51.Bxb5  This is objectively winning because all of Black's pawns are on light squares @@StartBracket@@which means they are easy targets@@EndBracket@@.  51...Be6  52.Bf1  Bd7  53.Ke3  Preparing to play Kd4!  53...Ke5  54.f4+!  Getting rid of Black's king so we can play Kd4!  54...Kd6  55.Kd4  f6  56.Bg2!  Attacking the d5-pawn.  56...Be6  57.Bf3  Attacking the h5-pawn.  57...Bf7  58.c4!  dxc4  59.Bxb7+-  White wins thanks to the outside passer on the a-file. }
48. Ne2 { The point is to play Nf4 next ➼ attacking both d5 and h5. } 48... Kf6
49. Nf4 Ke5 50. Nxh5 Bf5 51. f4+
{ Black resigned because  51...Ke6  is going to be met by  52.Ng7+! } *

