1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4 d5 3. Nf3 c5 4. e3 Nc6 5. Nbd2 Bg4 6. c3 e6 7. Qb3 Qb6 8. Ne5
c4 9. Qxb6 axb6 10. Nxg4 Nxg4
{ This is a typical endgame from the 'QGD Without 5...e6' lines. There are very few games in the database with this position, but I managed to get this position plenty of times already in my 'London System Rating Climb' on YouTube. }
11. e4 { Opening up the position for our bishop pair. } 11... b5 12. exd5 exd5
13. g3
{ Preparing to play Bg2. So far, this has been covered in the Theory Chapter. }
13... Nf6
{ 13...b4  This is another game that I had in my Rating Climb series on YouTube.  14.Bg2  Attacking the d5-pawn.  14...Nf6  This is the most natural move.   14...Ra5!  The computer prefers to defend the d5-pawn this way.  15.a3!!  Threatening to play O-O and open up the position on the queenside. This is not a very natural move, but the computer absolutely loves it!  15...bxc3  16.bxc3  Kd7!   16...Bxa3??  17.Bc7!  The point!  17...Ra6  18.Bxd5+-  Collecting the queenside pawns one by one with a winning position.  17.Rb1  Attacking the b7-pawn.  17...Nd8  18.Rb6!  Stopping ...Bd6!  18...Bxa3  19.O-O  ⩲  With Bh3 next and Black's king is vulnerable.  15.O-O  bxc3??  This is natural, but bad because it opens up the b-file for us.   15...Be7  16.a3!!  This stunning idea that we have seen against 14...Ra5 works here as well.  16...b3  Keeping the position closed, but it's only a matter of time before White will open things up.  17.Rfe1  Already threatening Nxc4 followed by d5!  17...O-O  18.Nxc4  dxc4  19.d5+-  White is winning back the piece and will win the queenside pawns as well, because the light-squared bishops is ready to enter the game with decisive effect. Notice how strong the bishop pair is in an open position.  16.bxc3  Be7  17.Rab1  Attacking the b7-pawn.  17...Ra7  18.Rb5!  Threatening Bxd5!  18...O-O  19.Bxd5  Nxd5  20.Rxd5  20...Ra3  Attacking the c3-pawn.  21.Rc1!  Simply protecting the c3-pawn.  21...Na5  Defending against Nxc4.  22.Rd7  Attacking the e7-bishop.  22...Bf6  My opponent resigned because he realized Bd6 was coming ➼ with a deadly fork. CountLondon @@StartBracket@@2401@@EndBracket@@-adwilhans @@StartBracket@@2453@@EndBracket@@ Chess.com 2022. }
14. Bg2 Be7 15. O-O O-O 16. a3 Rfd8 17. Rfe1 h6 18. Re2
{ Played too fast. I immediately realized that the a1-rook is undefended and Black can equalize on the spot.   18.Nf1!?  Preparing to play Ne3 ➼ this was a serious alternative. }
18... Bd6
{ 18...b4=  Getting rid of the doubled pawn ➼ this would have been really unpleasant. }
19. Bxd6 Rxd6 20. Rae1 Kf8 21. Nf3
{ Playing for Ne5 ➼ this felt more active during the game.   21.Nf1!?  This was another candidate move that I had ➼ preparing the typical Ne3. }
21... Re8 22. Ne5 Rdd8 23. f4 Ne7 24. g4 Nc6 25. Bf3
{ I rushed with this move and immediately realized I had something even better.   25.g5!!  This move is connected with a beautiful tactic.  25...hxg5  26.fxg5  26...Nh7   26...Nxe5  This also doesn't help.  27.gxf6+-  White plays fxg7+ after Black moves the knight ➼ winning the e8-rook.  27.Nd7++-  The point! White is winning the e8-rook. }
25... g5 { Black finds the best defensive resource ➼ avoiding my g5 ideas. }
26. h4
{ I tried to go for the same idea, but it was too late and my opponent can now defend against it. }
26... gxf4 27. g5 hxg5 28. hxg5 Nxe5
{ 28...Nh7??  I was hoping for this move.  29.Nd7++-  Because this was still working ➼ winning the e8-rook. }
29. Rxe5 Nh7
{ This is too passive.   29...Ne4!  30.Bxe4  Rxe5!  This intermezzo holds the balance.  31.dxe5  dxe4  32.Rxe4=  With an equal rook endgame. }
30. Bxd5
{ After this important pawn falls, the whole queenside becomes vulnerable. }
30... Rxe5 31. Rxe5 Rd7 32. Rf5 { Threatening to push g6! } 32... Kg7 33. Kf2
{ This is a typical mistake during a time scramble. } 33... f6
{ Black misses the chance to come back into the game.   33...Kg6!  Winning the g5-pawn.  34.Be4  Nxg5∞  Black is close to drawing. }
34. gxf6+ Nxf6 35. Bf3
{ After this move White is completely winning. There is no way to stop Rxb5 followed by Rxb7 with an easy win. The rest is not important. }
35... Re7 36. Rxb5 Re3 37. Rxb7+ Kg6 38. Rb5 Rd3 39. Ke2 Re3+ 40. Kf2 Rd3 41.
Be2 Rd2 42. Kf3 Nh7 43. Bxc4 Ng5+ 44. Kxf4 Rf2+ 45. Ke3 Rf3+ 46. Ke2 Rh3 47.
Bd3+ Kh6 48. Bf5 Rh2+ 49. Kd3 Nf3 50. d5 Ne5+ 51. Ke4 Nc4 52. Kd4 Nd6 53. Rb6
Rd2+ 54. Bd3 Kg5 55. Rxd6 Rxb2 56. Re6 Rb8 57. Re5+ Kf6 58. Re6+ Kf7 59. Re3
Kg7 60. c4 Rd8 61. c5 Rd7 62. d6 Rxd6+ 63. cxd6 Kh6 64. Re7 Kg5 65. Ke5 Kg4 66.
d7 Kf3 67. d8=Q Kf2 68. Qf8+ Ke1 69. Rg7 Kd2 70. Qh8 Kc3 71. Rg3 Kb2 72. Bf5
