[Result "*"]

{ In this chapter, I selected the most instructive London System games of all time. You will find a mix between classical games and very recent ones @@StartBracket@@the most recent game was played less than a month before publishing@@EndBracket@@.   This section should be studied religiously and your win rate with the London System will skyrocket!   I had to choose between over 500 quality games and finally stuck with a selection of 31 games ➼ illustrating White's main strategy in the purest form. I think the games that are selected are covering all the important ideas that you need to know, but I am planning to update the course over time so we can get a number of 50 model games in total by the end of the year. }
1. -- *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Carlsen, Magnus vs. Ghaem Maghami, Ehsan, Baku 2016"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Bf4 e6 4. e3 Bd6 5. Bg3 c5 6. c3 Nc6 7. Nbd2 Bxg3 8.
hxg3 Qd6 { Threatening to push ...e5! } 9. Bb5
{ The bishop usually develops to d3 in this structure, but we have to stop Black from getting the e5-break which generally gives him an equal game. }
9... Bd7 10. Bxc6 { Eliminating the main defender of the e5-square. } 10...
Bxc6 11. Ne5
{ This was the point of the previous move. White is able to install the powerful knight on e5! }
11... Qc7
{ Protecting the f7-pawn so they can ...O-O-O!   11...Nd7  12.Ndf3!  It's not easy at all for Black to get rid of the e5-knight.  12...f6  13.Ng6!  Taking advantage of the pin.  13...Rg8  14.Rxh7  With an extra pawn for White, even though the position remains a bit messy. }
12. Qf3
{ I really like Carlsen's approach. The point is to push g4-g5 and the f3-queen is putting tremendous pressure on the f7-square.   12.f4  Going for the reversed Stonewall is less effective here because Black has good control over the e4-square.  12...cxd4  13.exd4  O-O-O  14.g4  Ne4=  Black is very comfortable. }
12... h6 { This is played against White's g4-g5 idea. } 13. Qf4
{ Overprotecting the e5-knight and threatening to play dxc5! } 13... Qe7
{ Protecting the c5-pawn. } 14. g4
{ Threatening to push g5 ➼ exploiting the pin over the h-file. } 14... Nh7
{ Stopping White from pushing g5.   14...O-O-O  Doesn't quite work.  15.dxc5!  Black is unable to recapture  15...Qxc5  because of  16.Nxf7! }
15. Qg3
{ White is creating a very annoying threat of going dxc5 followed by g5!? }
15... Rg8
{ Avoiding the g5-push. The problem is that Black's king remains in the center.   15...a6  illustrates White's threat quite nicely.  16.dxc5!  Qxc5  17.g5!!  Nxg5   17...hxg5  18.Ndf3+-  There is no way to stop Nxg5, and White has a deadly initiative. The main point is that  18...f6  allows  19.Ng6!  ➼ winning material.  18.Qxg5!  White wins too many pieces for the queen.  18...hxg5  19.Rxh8+  Ke7  20.Nxc6+!  Qxc6  21.Rxa8+-  With two rooks and a knight for the queen ➼ White is completely winning.   15...O-O  16.f4  Threatening to push g5 on the next move ➼ White has a very dangerous initiative.   15...cxd4  is still bad for Black but probably the best defense.  16.exd4  O-O-O  Black gets castled at least.  17.Rc1  White keeps the initiative with c4 on the next move. }
16. O-O
{ There was no action on the h-file anymore, so it was quite pointless to keep the rook there. }
16... Nf6 17. Rac1
{ Black's king is caught in the center and in order to take advantage of that ➼ we need to open up the position, so that's why Magnus is preparing the c4-break! }
17... Rc8 18. c4 { Threatening cxd5! } 18... dxc4 19. dxc5 Qxc5 20. Ndxc4
{ Threatening Nxf7+ followed by Nd6+! ➼ winning the queen. } 20... Ke7 21. b4
{ The simplest.   21.Nxf7+-  This is also winning, but Magnus opts for the simpler alternative.   21.Nd3  doesn't win directly.  21...Qd5  and there is no immediate way to make progress. }
21... Qxb4 22. Nd3
{ Black can no longer play ...Qd5 like in the 21.Nd3-line. White is completely winning! }
22... Ne4
{ This was a good try, but Magnus has it all under control.   22...Qa4  23.Qd6+  Ke8  24.Nc5  Attacking the a4-queen and threatening Nxe6!  24...Qb4  25.Nxe6+-  White is winning at least the exchange. }
23. Nxb4 Nxg3 24. fxg3 Bb5
{ This was Black's trick, but White has a surprising move. } 25. Rxf7+
{ The only move to keep the advantage, but a large one! } 25... Kxf7 26. Nd6+
{ This way White managed to get rid of the pin and win back the rook. } 26...
Ke7 27. Nxc8+ Kd7 28. Nxa7 Ba4 29. Nd3
{ Black had to resign because both Nc5+ and Rc4 were on the agenda ➼ saving the a7-knight. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Bachmann, Axel vs. Hong, Andrew, Philadelphia 2017"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 c5 3. e3 Nc6 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Nbd2 cxd4 6. exd4 Bf5 7. c3 e6 8.
Qb3 Bd6 9. Bxd6 Qxd6 10. Be2 O-O 11. O-O Rab8 12. a4
{ Stopping Black from pushing ...b5! } 12... Rfc8 13. h3
{ Making a luft and introducing Nh4 ideas. } 13... h6
{ Creating a square for the bishop.   13...g5!?  This is a funny idea found by the computer. Nobody really plays like that, but it's interesting and good to be aware of.  14.Qd1!   14.Nxg5  Capturing the pawn can be pretty dangerous  14...Qf4  15.Ngf3  Kh8  With ...Rg8 next, Black has very good compensation.  14...g4  15.hxg4  Nxg4  16.g3  We can continue with Kg2-Rh1, and Black's kingside has been slightly weakened after this aggressive operation with ...g5!? }
14. Rfe1 Qd8
{ 14...a6  Threatening to push ...b5!  15.a5!  Making Black's ...b5 push less effective.  15...Qc7  Threatening ...Nxa5!  16.Qa3  Protecting the a5-pawn and preparing to push b4!  16...Ne4   16...b5?!  This allows us to create a weak pawn on a6.  17.axb6!  Rxb6  18.b4!  Fixing the weak pawn on a6. We can continue with Nb3-Nc5 with pressure on the queenside.  17.Nxe4  Bxe4  18.Nd2  Threatening Nxe4!  18...Bf5  19.Bf1  Improving the bishop. At this point, it's already difficult for Black to find a plan because both ...e5 and ...b5 create additional weaknesses.  19...Re8  20.b4  We can continue with Nb3-Nc5 with an easier position for us. }
15. Qa3
{ Preparing to push on the queenside with b4-a5. Meanwhile it's not simple at all to come up with a plan for Black because ...a6 is instantly met by a5! }
15... Nd7 16. b4 { Taking space. } 16... Qf8 { Threatening to push ...a5! } 17.
Qb2
{ 17.a5  This was also playable.  17...b6  18.axb6  axb6  19.Qb2  With Ra6 next ➼ White has pressure on the queenside. }
17... Rc7
{ 17...a5  Trying to slow down White's initiative on the queenside.  18.b5  Ne7  19.c4!  Threatening to push c5.  19...dxc4  20.Nxc4  With Nxa5 and Nd6 ideas ➼ White is slightly better. }
18. a5 a6
{ After this move White is getting an easy game.   18...b6  This is a bit similar to 18...a6 ➼ helping White make progress on the queenside.  19.axb6  axb6  20.Bf1  Improving the bishop.  20...Rbc8  21.Ra3  Protecting the c3-pawn and preparing to double up on the a-file.  21...Qd6  22.Rea1  Ne7  23.Ra8!  Exchanging a pair of rooks ➼ diminishing Black's pressure on the c3-pawn.  23...Qc6  24.Rxc8+  Rxc8  Threatening ...Qxc3!  25.Ra7  Black is unable to grab the c3-pawn because the d7-knight will drop. Additionally, White threatens to push c4 on the next move ➼ with pressure on the queenside.   18...Ne7  This is what the computer likes.  19.Bf1  Rbc8  Threatening ...Rxc3!  20.Rec1  Protecting the c3-pawn.  20...Qd8  21.b5=  With a balanced position, but White has some pressure on the queenside ➼ with c4 coming on the next move. }
19. Nb3 { Preparing to play Nc5. } 19... Qd6 20. Nc5 Nxc5
{ This is another move that helps us to make progress, but at this point ➼ Black's position was already difficult.   20...Re8  This is suggested by the computer ➼ with the idea to play around the c5-knight.  21.Bf1  Improving the bishop.  21...Qe7  22.Qd2  Preparing to play f4 ➼ activating the queen.  22...Qd8  23.Qf4  With a clearly better position for White thanks to the super annoying c5-knight. }
21. bxc5
{ The natural move ➼ opening up the b-file.   21.dxc5!?  This was also very interesting ➼ preparing to play Nd4!  21...Qe7  22.Nd4  Threatening Nxf5!  22...Be4   22...Nxd4?!  23.cxd4  We can play a3-b3 followed by the b5-break with pressure on the b7-pawn.  23.Nxc6  Rxc6  24.c4!  Threatening to play f3 followed by cxd5! White is much better as  24...dxc4  allows  25.Qe5!  winning material because Black is unable to protect both the b8-rook and the e4-bishop. }
21... Qd8 22. Bd1
{ Preparing to play Bc2 ➼ getting rid of Black's bishop so we can play Rb1 and use the b-file to put pressure on the b7-pawn. }
22... Re7 { Attacking the a5-pawn. } 23. Qb6
{ The best way to protect the a5-pawn ➼ inviting Black to enter a problematic endgame. }
23... Bd3
{ 23...Qxb6  24.axb6  We can continue with Ba4 @@StartBracket@@threatening Bxc6@@EndBracket@@, and after Black moves the knight away ➼ Ne5 becomes very unpleasant. }
24. Re3 Bb5 { Trying to set-up a blockade on the queenside. } 25. Be2
{ Getting rid of Black's bishop so we can apply pressure on the queenside. }
25... Bxe2 26. Rxe2 Rc8 27. Ne5 Nxe5 28. Rxe5 Qd7
{ Keeping an eye on the b7-pawn.   28...Qxb6  29.axb6  White is dominating this endgame. The key idea is to break with f5, and we can do that after playing Rae1 followed by f4-f5 ➼ with pressure on the e6-pawn. }
29. Rb1 Rc7 30. Rbe1 { Switching to the f4-f5 plan. } 30... Qa4 31. f4
{ Threatening to push f5. } 31... g6 32. Kh2 { Improving the king. } 32... Kg7
{ 32...Qc2  33.R5e3  Protecting the c3-pawn. White has an interesting idea to bring the queen over with Qd6-Qe5 ➼ with good attacking prospects on the kingside. }
33. R1e2
{ Controlling the second rank and potentially preparing to push g4 followed by f5. }
33... Qa3 34. R2e3 Qa4
{ This is the losing mistake.   34...Qc1!?  This would've been a better try, but White would've kept the initiative.  35.f5!  gxf5  36.Rg3+  Kf8  37.Qd6  With a HUGE threat of playing Qd8+ @@StartBracket@@winning the c7-rook@@EndBracket@@ ➼ Black has problems with the king. }
35. f5 gxf5 36. Rg3+ Kh7 37. Rxd5
{ Good idea, but wrong execution.   37.Rxf5!  +-  This was simply crushing and avoiding Black's counterplay. My guess is that White was in big time trouble because we are close to the time control on move 40. The point is that  37...exf5  38.Qf6  is mating. }
37... f4
{ This keeps Black in the game!   37...exd5  This allows a forced checkmate.  38.Qf6+-  There is no way to stop Qg7#. }
38. Rg4 { Threatening to play Qb1+ and Rh5 with a mating attack. } 38... f3
{ Missing the chance.   38...Qc2!!  39.Rd8  Threatening Qd6!  39...f5!  This move keeps Black's position together.  40.Rgg8  Qe2=  Black can meet  41.Rh8+  with  41...Kg6  @@StartBracket@@preparing ...Kh5@@EndBracket@@ with a safe position. }
39. Qb1+ Kh8
{ 39...f5  This was also not saving.  40.Rxf5!  With a forced mate after  40...exf5  41.Qxf5+  Kh8  42.Qf8+  Kh7  43.Qg8# }
40. Qc1 Kh7 41. Rh5
{ There is no way to stop the checkmate on h6, so Black had to resign. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Iturrizaga Bonelli, Eduardo vs. Gomez, John Paul, Ho Chi Minh City 2017"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4 c5 3. e3 cxd4 4. exd4 d5 5. c3 Nc6 6. Nd2 Bf5 7. Qb3 Qc8 8.
Ngf3 e6 9. Nh4 Bg6 10. Nxg6 hxg6 11. Bd3 Be7 12. O-O O-O 13. Rae1
{ White went for the most aggressive plan ➼ focusing mainly on the kingside play.   13.Rfe1  This is another viable plan.  13...a6  Threatening to push ...b5 ➼ going for the minority attack.  14.a4!  Stopping Black from pushing ...b5!  14...Bd8  Preparing to play ...Bc7.   14...Na5  15.Qc2  Nc4  16.a5  Threatening Bxc4 followed by Ra4! ➼ winning the c4-pawn.  15.Nf3  Bc7  16.Bg5  With pressure on the kingside after g3-h4-Kg2-Rh1! }
13... a6 { Preparing the minority attack with ...b5! } 14. Qd1
{ 14.a4  This move no longer works that well.  14...Na5!  15.Qd1  Nc4  With decent counterplay on the queenside because ...b5 is coming on the next move. }
14... b5 { Threatening to push ...b4! } 15. a3
{ Slowing down Black's play on the queenside because  15...a5  runs into  16.Bxb5!  ➼ with an extra pawn for White. }
15... Na5 16. Nf3 { Preparing to activate the knight with Ne5. } 16... Nc4 17.
Qe2 { Protecting the b2-pawn. } 17... Ra7
{ 17...a5  18.Ne5  White will push on the kingside with h4-g4 ➼ with similar play to what happened in the game. }
18. Ne5 Nd6
{ 18...a5  19.h4  Threatening to push g4.  19...b4  20.cxb4  axb4  21.a4!?  Not the only move but an instructive idea to remember. White is getting a dangerous outside passer, and we can play on the queenside with Rc1 followed by b3! }
19. g4
{ Going for the typical kingside play. White is threatening to push h4-h5!   Starting with  19.h4  was playable as well ➼ with the same idea. }
19... Nfe4
{ 19...Nc4  This could have been a better defensive try.  20.h4  Threatening to push h5!  20...Nxe5  21.dxe5  Attacking the f6-knight.  21...Nd7  22.h5!  gxh5  23.gxh5  Nc5  Creating a positional threat of ...Nxd3!  24.Bb1  White can continue with Qg4 followed by Kh1-Rg1 ➼ with very good attacking prospects on the kingside. }
20. f3
{ It is not super clear whether Black missed this move or wanted to provoke it ➼ closing the d1-h5 diagonal. }
20... Nf6 21. h4 { Threatening to push h5! } 21... a5 22. h5
{ White is wasting no time! Simply textbook play by Iturrizaga Bonelli.   22.Bxb5  This is still slightly better for us, but you should stay away from this 'greedy' approach when you can ignore it and focus on the kingside play. The reason for that is simply because it will be more rewarding and, most of the time, lead to a quick win ➼ while with the extra pawn and open files on the queenside, Black might get some unnecessary counterplay.  22...Nxb5  23.Qxb5  Rb7  24.Qe2  Nd7  White is still slightly better, objectively speaking, but I find it very unnecessary. Keep in mind that this is a happy outcome because most of the time, I would say that Black gets enough compensation after this kind of 'greedy' play. }
22... gxh5 23. Qh2
{ Threatening g5 followed by Qxh5! This is the most effective plan because we are also creating a tactical motif against the d6-knight.   23.g5  Nfe8  24.g6  This was a promising alternative.   23.Rf2!?  Preparing Rh2 ➼ this was another interesting idea for White, but a bit too slow for my taste. }
23... g6
{ Protecting the h5-pawn because White was threatening g5 followed by Qxh5.   23...hxg4  24.Kf2!  +-  We will play Rh1 next ➼ with a deadly attack on the h-file.   23...b4  The minority attack is simply too slow here.  24.g5!  This is a cool trick to remember. First, we are getting rid of the f6-knight so we can recapture the h5-pawn with the queen.  24...Nd7  25.Qxh5  Threatening Qh7#  25...Nf5  26.Bxf5  exf5  27.Kg2+-  With Rh1 on the next move ➼ and there is no way for Black to stop checkmate on the h-file. }
24. Nxg6 { The simplest because the d6-knight is hanging. } 24... fxg6 25. Bxd6
{ The material is even for now, but Black's position is full of weaknesses. }
25... hxg4
{ 25...Bxd6  26.Qxd6  hxg4  27.Rxe6+-  With problems on the sixth rank. } 26.
Be5
{ Threatening Bxg6!   26.Bxg6??  It was not too late to spoil the game!  26...Bxd6  27.Qxd6  Rg7!  -+  Black wins all of a sudden because ...gxf3+ is coming after we step back with the bishop. }
26... g3
{ Trying to create some confusion.  26...Kg7 This allows a simple win. 27.fxg4+-  With g5 coming on the next move ➼ winning the f6-knight. }
27. Qh6
{ Attacking the g6-pawn! This is the most precise, even though  27.Qxg3  was completely fine too. }
27... Bd8 28. Bd6
{ Another very practical move. At this point White wins with a lot of moves, so we can just stick to what happened in the game. }
28... Rff7 29. Bxg6 Rg7 30. Kg2 { Threatening to play Rh1 followed by Qh8! }
30... Rxg6 31. Qf8+
{ Black had to resign because  31...Kh7  runs into  32.Rh1+  with a forced mate. }
