[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Limbert, Neil vs. Mueller, Gerhard, Correspondence 2016"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 Nf6 3. e3 c5 4. c3 Nc6 5. Nd2 cxd4 6. exd4 Bf5 7. Ngf3 e6 8.
Qb3 Qc8 9. Nh4 Be4 10. Nxe4 dxe4 11. g3 Be7 12. Ng2 O-O 13. Rd1 Nd5 14. Bc1 Qd7
15. Be2 Rac8 16. O-O Rfd8
{ This is a typical position after Black meets 10.Nxe4 with 10...dxe4. } 17.
Nf4 { Threatening Nxd5 followed by the f3-break! ➼ making use of the e4-hook. }
17... Nf6
{ Avoiding Nxd5.   17...a6  This illustrates White's threat quite nicely.  18.Nxd5  exd5  19.f3!  Opening up the position for the bishop pair.  19...f5  20.fxe4  fxe4  21.Rde1!  We will play Qd1 followed by Bg4 with pressure on the light squares.   17...Na5  18.Qc2  Attacking the e4-pawn.  18...Nf6  19.f3!  Opening up the position ➼ increasing the strength of the bishop pair.  19...exf3  20.Bxf3  b5  Going for the minority attack with ...b4!  21.Qg2!  This is a typical maneuver for our structure.  21...b4  22.g4!  This is the key move to grab the initiative! White is threatening to push g5 next.  22...bxc3  23.g5!  Attacking the f6-knight.  23...Ne8   23...Nd5  24.Nxd5  exd5  25.Bg4+-  Winning the exchange.  24.d5!  White has a very dangerous initiative with the bishop pair in an open position. }
18. a3
{ This is a subtle prophylactic move. White is preparing in advance for the ...b5-b4 break.  18.f3  was also fine @@StartBracket@@and perhaps a bit more natural@@EndBracket@@. }
18... Na5 19. Qc2
{ Sidestepping Black's threat and keeping an eye on the e4-square. } 19... b5
{ Preparing the minority attack. } 20. f3
{ Taking advantage of the e4-hook and opening up the position for the bishop pair. }
20... exf3 21. Bxf3 Nc4
{ Activating the knight and preparing to push on the queenside with ...a5-b4! }
22. Qg2
{ This is a standard play for the variation. The queen is very well placed on g2 preparing to push g4!   This idea reminds me of the following variation from the French Defense: @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  e6  2.d4  d5  3.Nd2  Nf6  4.e5  Nfd7  5.Bd3  c5  6.c3  Nc6  7.Ne2  cxd4  8.cxd4  f6  9.exf6  Nxf6  10.Nf3  Bd6  11.Nc3  O-O  12.O-O  a6  13.Bg5  Qc7  14.Bh4  Nh5  15.Rc1  g6  16.Bb1  Qg7!  and Black has very interesting play on the kingside. }
22... a5 { Preparing to push ...b4! } 23. g4
{ Preparing to push g5! ➼ this is the key move to get the initiative. } 23...
Bd6
{ Threatening ...Bxf4 followed by ...Nd5!   23...h6  This could have been a better defensive try, even though it's breaking one of the general principles that 'We should not be pushing pawns on the side where our opponent is attacking.' Sometimes ➼ based on concrete factors, this rule can be broken, and here it looks like it was the case.  24.h4  Threatening g5.  24...Nh7!  This was the point. In order to keep the initiative going, White has to sacrifice a pawn.  25.g5!  Sacrificing a pawn in order to open up lines for the attack.  25...hxg5  26.hxg5  Bxg5!  This is Black's best defense, keeping the game close to equal.   26...Nxg5  27.Nh5!  Threatening Bxg5 and putting pressure on the g7-square.  27...Nxf3+  28.Rxf3!  Threatening Qxg7#  28...g6  29.Rxf7!!  After this final trick, White gets an easy win.  29...Kxf7  30.Rf1+  Bf6  31.Nxf6+-  Black is getting mated.  27.Rde1  Threatening Nxe6!  27...b4!   27...Bxf4  28.Bxf4  White has very good compensation with the simple plan of going Qh3 followed by Re2-Rh2 ➼ with good attacking prospects on the kingside.  28.Nxe6!  Using a small trick to regain the pawn.  28...fxe6  29.Bxg5  Rf8  30.Bh4  The position should be close to equal, objectively speaking, but I tend to pick White with the bishop pair in an open position. }
24. g5
{ Attacking the f6-knight.  24...Bxf4  is no longer that appealing because White has  25.exf6!  ➼ winning a piece. }
24... Ne8 { Black has ideas to go ...Bxf4 folloewd by ...Ned6-Nf5. } 25. Nd3
{ Keeping more pieces on the board because we have the extra space @@StartBracket@@notice the awkwardly placed e8-knight@@EndBracket@@. }
25... Bf8
{ 25...b4  26.b3!  This is a powerful pawn sacrifice!  26...Nxa3  27.c4  White is clearly better with a solid structure in the center and has the bishop pair while the enemy a3-knight is caught offside. }
26. Kh1
{ Threatening to push d5 and avoiding ...Qa7+ which was saving Black in case White went for 26.d5 directly.   26.d5!?  This was also interesting, but Black can get away with the check on a7.  26...exd5  27.Bg4  Going for the fork.  27...Qa7+  Thanks to this move, Black is able to save the exchange. }
26... Ned6
{ Preparing to play ...Nf5.   26...g6  27.b3  Attacking the c4-knight.  27...Ncd6  28.Ne5  Centralizing and attacking Black's queen.  28...Qc7  29.Nc6  Attacking the d8-rook.  29...Rd7  30.Bf4  We are going to push c4 next, with a large advantage thanks to the bishop pair. }
27. Ne5 { Attacking Black's queen and preparing Ng4. } 27... Qc7
{ 27...Nxe5??  This was not really a choice because Black would drop a piece.  28.dxe5+-  Collecting the pinned knight on the next move. }
28. Ng4
{ The knight is very annoying for Black on this square ➼ preparing Nf6+/Nh6+ ideas! }
28... Nf5
{ 28...b4  29.axb4  axb4  30.b3!  Attacking the c4-knight.  30...Na5  31.Bf4!  Pinning the d6-knight.  31...bxc3   31...Qa7  32.Nh6+!  The knight is untouchable because Black is getting mated.  32...Kh8  33.Bh5  Threatening Bxd6 followed by Nxf7+!  33...Qb7  Trying to bail out by exchanging queens.  34.d5!  +-  With a big threat of playing Bxd6 and Nxf7+ ➼ White has a winning attack.  32.Be4!  +-  With a huge threat of playing Nh6+ followed by Bxd6 and Nxf7+ ➼ White has a crushing initiative. }
29. Be4 { Threatening Bxf5! } 29... Ncd6
{ Protecting the f5-knight and threatening ...Nxe4!   29...b4  The minority attack would've allowed a powerful sacrifice.  30.Rxf5!  exf5  31.Bxf5  White is at least winning back the exchange.  31...Rb8??  This allows a mating attack.  32.Nf6+  Kh8  33.Bxh7  gxf6  34.gxf6+-  With Rg1/Qh3 ideas ➼ there is no way for Black to avoid the checkmate. }
30. Bf4 { Pinning the d6-knight and threatening Rd3-Rh3! } 30... Be7
{ 30...b4  This was still dangerous because White could get a powerful attack.  31.Nf6+  Kh8  32.Qh3  Threatening Qxh7#  32...gxf6  33.Bxd6!  Rxd6  34.Rxf5!  After this move, Black is dead lost.  34...exf5  35.Qxf5+-  There is no way to stop Qh7#.   30...Qb6  31.Nf6+  Kh8  32.Qh3  Threatening mate on h7.  32...h6  33.Bf3  Creating a threat of Ng4 followed by gxh6!  33...gxf6  34.gxf6  With Rg1 followed by Qg4 ➼ White has a powerful initiative. }
31. Rde1
{ Threatening Bxf5 followed by Nh6+!   31.d5!?  was another promising alternative. }
31... g6 32. Bxf5 { Eliminating Black's main defender. } 32... exf5 33. Rxe7
{ After this exchange sacrifice Black is in trouble because the knight will land on f6. }
33... Qxe7 34. Nf6+ Kf8
{ 34...Kg7  35.Be5+-  was simply worse compared to what happened in the game because White wins a tempo. }
35. Nxh7+ Ke8 36. Nf6+ Kf8 37. Qh3 { Threatening Qh8# } 37... Qb7+ 38. Kg1 Ke7
{ 38...Ne4  39.Bg3!  Threatening Nxe4 followed by Re1 ➼ creating a mating net.  39...Nxg3  40.hxg3+-  With a deadly attack. }
39. d5
{ Being a correspondence game, Black resignes since the computer is indicating a HUGE advantage for White already. To sum things up we can say that White has a big threat of going Re1+ with a decisive advantage. }
*

