1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Bf4 c5 4. e3 Nc6 5. Nbd2 Qb6 6. dxc5 Qxb2 7. Rb1 Qc3 8.
Bb5 g6 9. e4 dxe4 10. Be5 Qa5 11. O-O exf3 12. Nc4 Qd8 13. Bxc6+ bxc6 14. Qxf3
Qd5
{ The losing mistake! ➼ this happened because it's very easy to miss White's next move.   14...Bg4! =  This was the only move to hold ➼ as shown in the Theory Chapter. }
15. Nd6+ { After this tactical blow, White gets a deadly initiative. } 15...
Kd7
{ 15...exd6  16.Qxf6  Attacking the h8-rook.  16...Rg8   16...Qxe5?  17.Rfe1!  +- Wins the queen because of the pin.  17.cxd6  Threatening to play Rfe1.  17...Qe6  18.Qf3!  Of course, we should keep queens on the board in order to keep the initiative going.  18...Qc4  Defending the c6-pawn.  19.Rfe1  Threatening to play Bg3+.  19...Be6  20.Rb7+-  Threatening to play Qf6 and Re7+ ➼ White has a mating attack. }
16. Qc3
{ Keeping queens on, attacking the f6-knight and threatening to play Rfd1! }
16... Bg7
{ 16...exd6  17.Bxf6  Attacking the rook.  17...Rg8  18.cxd6+-  We can continue with Rbd1-Rfe1 with a powerful initiative.   16...Qe6  Threatening ...Nd5!  17.Nxc8  Rxc8  18.Rfe1!  Threatening Bxf6 followed by Rbd1+!  18...Nd5   18...Bg7  19.Bg3+-  With Rb7+ coming on the next move, Black's king is close to getting mated.  19.Qd4  Attacking the h8-rook and threatening to push c4!  19...f6  20.Bd6!  +-  With Rb7+ followed by c4 coming on the next move ➼ White has a decisive attack. }
17. Rfd1 { Attacking Black's queen. } 17... Rb8
{ Setting up a small trap.   17...Qe6  18.Nf5++-  Collecting the g7-bishop next with a winning position. }
18. Ra1
{ Keeping good control over the first rank and reinforcing the Rxd5 threat.   18.Rxb8??  It was not too late to mess things up!  18...Qxd1  for a funny checkmate. }
18... exd6
{ At this point this has to be played because moving the queen allows at least Nf5-Nxh7 with an easy win for White. }
19. Bxf6
{ This is super important, but from now on White has a pretty smooth sailing.   19.Rxd5??  This would have lost on the spot!  19...Nxd5-+  Black gets a rook and three minor pieces for the queen ➼ which is way too much. }
19... Bxf6 20. Qxf6
{ Attacking the h8-rook and the d5-queen. Black is losing material. } 20...
Qxc5 21. Qxf7+ { Stealing a pawn before cashing in the exchange. } 21... Kd8
22. Qf6+ { Time to collect the rook now. } 22... Kc7 23. Qxh8
{ With an easy win thanks to the extra exchange and Black's king being very weak. The rest is simple. }
23... Bd7 24. Qxh7 Rf8 25. Qh4 Qxc2 26. Rac1 Qb2 27. Rb1 Qxa2 28. Ra1
{ Black resigned because Rxa7+ was coming on the next move. } *

