1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Bf4 c5 4. e3 Nc6 5. Nbd2 Qb6 6. dxc5 Qxb2 7. Rb1 Qc3 8.
Bb5 e6 9. O-O Be7 10. e4 O-O 11. e5 Nd7 12. Nb3 Qb4 13. Nfd4 Nxd4 14. Nxd4 Qxc5
15. Re1 Rd8 16. h4
{ This is a typical resource for such positions! We have a structure that is very similar to the French Defense. }
16... Bxh4
{ This is the principled approach.   16...Nf8  After the last move ➼ ...Ng6 becomes an important idea for Black.  17.h5!  Stopping Black from playing ...Ng6! From this point, I think Black has two main plans ➼ to play or not to play ...h6!  17...Bd7   17...h6  18.Re3  Preparing to play Rg3.  18...Nh7  19.Bd3  Bringing the bishop back into the action and setting up a small trap.   19...Qxd4  loses the queen after  20.Bxh7+  Kxh7  21.Qxd4!  19...Ng5  20.Rg3  Activating the rook.  20...f5  This is always a critical move that we need to be aware of.   20...b6  This is the slow approach that gives White a very dangerous initiative.  21.Qd2  Threatening Bxg5!  21...Ne4  22.Bxe4  dxe4  23.c3  Protecting the d4-knight and threatening Bxh6!  23...Bf8  24.Qe3!  This is even more precise than the direct 24.Bxh6 @@StartBracket@@which was also fine@@EndBracket@@. Black lacks a good continuation.  24...Kh8  25.Bxh6!  gxh6  26.Qxe4  Attacking the a8-rook.  26...Rb8  27.Qg4+-  There is no way to stop mate on the g-file.  21.Be3  Threatening Nxe6!  21...Qc7  22.Nf3  Protecting the e5-pawn and putting pressure on the g5-knight.  22...Ne4  Threatening ...Nxg3!  23.Rg6  Threatening Bxh6!  23...Kh7  24.Qc1  Reinforcing the Bxh6 idea.  24...Bf8  25.Bd4  White is threatening to open up the position with g4 next ➼ with good attacking prospects on the kingside.  18.Re3  Preparing to play g3.  18...Bxb5  19.Rxb5  Qc7  20.Qg4  With Rg3 followed by Bh6 ➼ White has more than enough compensation for the pawn. }
17. Rb3 { Preparing to bring the rook over the kingside with Rh3! } 17... Nf8
{ The knight is well placed on this square ➼ defending the h7-pawn. } 18. Rh3
Be7 19. Bd3 { Threatening Bxh7+ followed by Qh5! } 19... g6
{ Threatening ...Qxd4 now that there is no Bxh7+ motif.   19...f5!  This would have been the best way to react. White has a choice between two interesting plans: 20.c3 & 20.exf6.  20.exf6  This is the most principled approach ➼ fighting for the e5-square and activating the d3-bishop.   20.c3!?  This might be the best practical try ➼ Preparing Ree3-Reg3.  20...Bd7   20...Qxc3??  This is never really an option.  21.Bxf5+-  and White just wins.  21.Ree3  Preparing Reg3.  21...Rac8  22.Reg3  Threatening to play Qh5!  22...g6  23.Bh6  White is threatening to play Qh5 followed by Bxf8 with a very dangerous initiative.  20...Bxf6  21.Be5!  Securing control over the e5-square!  21...Qe7  22.Qh5  Threatening Bxh7+!  22...g6!   22...h6  Typically, this move gets Black in trouble.  23.Bxf6  Qxf6  24.Rf3!  +-  After this strong move, White has a crushing initiative. A good example is the following line:  24...Qxd4??  25.Qf7+  Kh8  26.Qxf8+!  Forcing a surprising checkmate.  26...Rxf8  27.Rxf8#  23.Rg3  Pinning the g6-pawn and preparing to bring the knight over with Nf3.  23...Bg7  24.Bxg7  Qxg7   24...gxh5  This leads to a slightly better endgame for White after a forcing sequence.  25.Bf6+  Kf7  26.Bxe7  Kxe7  27.Rh3  With  Rxh5  coming on the next move ➼ White keeps a slightly better position thanks to the more active pieces.  25.Qh4  Attacking the d8-rook.  25...Bd7  26.Nf3  With Ne5 coming on the next move ➼ White has enough compensation for the sacrificed material. The question is whether we can hope for more or not.   19...h6??  This allows White to win on the spot.  20.Bxh6!  Opening up lines for the heavy pieces.  20...gxh6  21.Qg4+!  Bringing the queen over with tempo!  21...Ng6  22.Rxh6+-  With Bxg6 coming on the next move ➼ White has a crushing attack. }
20. Nf3
{ Sidestepping Black's threat and preparing to trade off the dark squared bishops with Bg5! }
20... Bd7 21. Bg5
{ The human move. White is trading the bishops so we can exploit the f6-h6-squares easier.   21.Nh2!?  Preparing to play Ng4 ➼ this is the computer's favorite move.  21...Bb5  Trading the bad bishop.   21...h5  Stopping White from playing Ng4.  22.Rxh5!!  White wins thanks to this brutal tactic.  22...gxh5  23.Re3!  +-  With Rg3+ followed by Qxh5 ➼ White has a mating attack.  22.Ng4  Bxd3  23.Nh6+!  This is a nice intermezzo because the knight is very annoying for Black on h6.  23...Kg7  24.cxd3  Threatening to push d4 followed by Qf3 ➼ Black is struggling to defend the f7-square. }
21... Bxg5 22. Nxg5 Qb4
{ Black goes for a questionable queen maneuver.   22...Bb5!  Trading the bad bishop looks more logical, but White keeps the initiative regardless.  23.Bxb5  Qxb5  24.Qf3  Threatening Qxf7+!  24...Qd7?!   24...Rd7!  This is the best defense.  25.Qf6  With the simple plan to go Ree3-Ref3 ➼ White has good attacking prospects on the kingside.  25.Qf6  White has a deadly threat to take twice on h7 followed by Re3-Rh3, and Black is defenseless. }
23. Ree3
{ Threatening to play Qf3 because there will no longer be a hanging rook on e1. }
23... Qf4 24. Rhg3
{ Protecting the knight and threatening to trap Black's queen with Rg4! } 24...
Qh4 25. Qf3 Be8 26. Bb5
{ Deflecting Black's bishop from defending the f7-square. } 26... Bxb5
{ The losing mistake.   26...Rd7!  The exchange sac was more resilient.  27.Qf6  Threatening to play Rh3.  27...Qh6  28.Bxd7  Nxd7  29.Qf4  With good attacking prospects on the kingside and an extra exchange. }
27. Qxf7+ Kh8 28. Qf6+ { Protecting the g5-knight so we can play Rh3! } 28...
Kg8 29. Rh3 Qxh3
{ 29...Qg4  allowed a forced mate.  30.Qf7+  Kh8  31.Rxh7+  Nxh7  32.Qxh7# }
30. Rxh3 Rd7 31. Rf3
{ Black resigned because there is no way to stop Nf7-Nh6! } *

