1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. Bf4 b6 4. e3 Bb7 5. h3 Be7 6. Bd3 O-O 7. O-O c5 8. c3
Nc6 9. Nbd2 d5 10. Qe2 Bd6 11. Rfe1 Ne7 12. Rad1 Ng6 13. Bxg6
{ Opening up the h-file! After this move Black's king will always be a bit vulnerable. }
13... hxg6 14. Bxd6 { Preparing to play Ne5 followed by the typical f4. } 14...
Qxd6 15. Ne5
{ Centralizing and preparing to support the knight with f4 ➼ setting up the ''Reversed Stonewall''. }
15... g5
{ This is an interesting try ➼ mainly played against White's idea to push f4.   15...Rac8  16.f4  Qe7   16...cxd4  This is usually meant to continue with ...Ne4!  17.exd4  Ne4  18.Nxe4!  Getting rid of Black's annoying knight.  18...dxe4  19.h4!  Threatening to push h5 next ➼ with good attacking prospects on the kingside.  17.g4  Threatening to push h4-h5 with pressure on the kingside.   15...Nd7  16.f4  Black's position is very unpleasant. White has a simple plan to bring the queen over with Qg4-Qh4 followed by Nf3-Ng5 ➼ and Black has problems on the h-file. }
16. f4
{ Magnus is going for the standard move, but with a tricky idea in mind. }
16... gxf4 17. Rf1
{ Threatening Rxf4! This stunning idea gives White a very promising initiative.   17.exf4  This would have allowed Black to get a comfortable position.  17...cxd4  18.cxd4  Rac8=  White has no targets while Black can double up on the c-file followed by ...Ne4 with a solid position. }
17... Nd7
{ 17...fxe3  18.Rxf6!  This was the main point behind 17.Rf1!  18...gxf6  This allows a forced mate.   18...exd2  19.Qxd2  gxf6   19...cxd4  20.Qg5!  +-  Threatening Rd4-Rg4! and  20...Qe7  can be met by  21.Ng4!  20.Ng4!  +-  Winning on the spot with Qh6 next followed by Nf6#.  19.Qg4+  Kh7  20.Rf1!  Bringing the rook over is the key idea to getting a mating attack.  20...fxe5  21.Qh5+!  The next moves are forced.  21...Kg7  22.Qg5+!  Kh7  23.Rf6+-  With Rh6# coming on the next move. }
18. Qh5
{ 18.Nxd7  This was a good alternative.  18...Qxd7  19.Rxf4  f6  White is still better, but it seems much trickier to make progress. }
18... Nf6
{ Black's position is very difficult to play because the b7-bishop is struggling to participate in the main fight which takes place on the kingside.   18...cxd4!  This would have been a better try, but Black's position was already difficult.  19.exd4  Threatening Rxf4.  19...Nxe5  20.dxe5  Qc5+  21.Rf2!   This is the best way to react against the check since  21.Kh2  Qe3!  would have given Black very decent counterplay.  21...f6  22.Nf3  Threatening to play Nd4 and establish a typical position with the good knight against the bad bishop.  22...d4!  The computer finds this super precise defense ➼ sacrificing the pawn to get a somewhat defendable endgame.   22...Qc7?!  This would have been clearly worse.  23.Re1  With Nd4 coming on the next move ➼ and White's knight is much more active than the enemy bishop.  23.cxd4  Bxf3!  24.Qxf3  Qd5  Forcing the queen trade.  25.Qxd5  exd5  26.Rxf4  White is definitely pressing with the extra pawn, but Black has chances to hold in the rook endgame.   18...fxe3??  This was losing on the spot.  19.Nxf7  Attacking Black's queen and threatening Qh8#.  19...Nf6  20.Rxf6!  +- After this important move, Black can resign. }
19. Qh4 Qd8
{ This move is connected with ...Ne4 ideas ➼ looking to exchange queens.   19...Nh7!?  This would have been an interesting try for Black.  20.Rxf4!  This is the most precise! Threatening Qh5 followed by Rh4.   20.exf4  Capturing with the pawn was reasonable here because Black is not in time with ...Ne4 ideas.  20...g5!  The point of Black's previous move.  21.Rg4  Pinning the g5-pawn.  21...f6   21...Qe7  22.Qh6  With Ndf3 coming next ➼ White has a large advantage.  22.Ndf3!  Introducing Nxg5 ideas in case of ...fxe5!  22...Qc7  23.Qg3  We are going to push h4 next ➼ breaking Black's fortress.   19...fxe3??  This was still not working.  20.Rxf6!  White wins with similar ideas.  20...exd2   20...gxf6  21.Ng4+-  With Qh6 next followed by Nf6 ➼ with a crushing attack.  21.Rxd2  Threatening Rd3-Rg3!  21...gxf6  22.Rd3+-  Black gets checkmated with Rg3 next. }
20. Rxf4
{ With a simple threat of playing Rdf1 followed by Rxf6! ➼ with a decisive attack on the kingside.   20.exf4  Ne4  would have been very unclear. }
20... Ne4
{ This turns out to be the decisive mistake ➼ allowing White to get a much better endgame.   20...cxd4  This would have been a better try but still suffering.  21.exd4  Ne4  Threatening to trade queens in a better version compared to what happened in the game.  22.Qe1!  The key move to play for an advantage. White's threat is to play Nxe4 followed by Qg3!   22.Nxe4?!  Would have led to an equal endgame.  22...Qxh4  23.Rxh4  dxe4=  Black is quite comfortable.  22...f5   a@@EndBracket@@  22...Nd6  23.Qe2  Nf5  24.Qh5  With Re1 followed by Ndf3-Ng5 ➼ White has good attacking prospects on the kingside.   b@@EndBracket@@  22...g5!?  This can't be very good for Black, but it requires a bit of unorthodox play from us.  23.Rg4  f5  Attacking the g4-rook.  24.Rg3!  We can simply sacrifice the exchange and make the argument that Black has overextended on the kingside.  24...Nxg3   24...Kh7  25.Nxe4  dxe4  26.Qe2  With Qh5 ideas, Black's king is vulnerable.  25.Qxg3+-  We can continue with Ndf3 followed by h4 with an interesting play on the kingside while the enemy bishop is struggling to enter the game.  23.Nxe4  fxe4  24.Rg4+-  White is winning thanks to the strong knight against the bad bishop. }
21. Nxe4 { Magnus never misses such opportunities. } 21... Qxh4 22. Rxh4 dxe4
23. dxc5 { This is why it was important for Black to start with 20. ..cxd4! }
23... bxc5 24. Rd7 { Activating the rook and attacking the b7-bishop. } 24...
Rab8
{ 24...Ba6  25.c4+-  Threatening Rxe4 ➼ White is strategically winning because Black is unable to activate his bishop. }
25. b3
{ This is a classy move ➼ making sure there is no action on the b-file. } 25...
a5 26. Rc7 { Threatening Rxc5. } 26... a4
{ Trying to create some confusion.   26...Rfc8  This was not really an alternative.  27.Rxf7+-  White is able to collect this very important pawn thanks to the super active e5-knight. }
27. bxa4 Ba8 28. a5
{ White managed to get a dangerous outside passer simply by having more active pieces. }
28... Rb7 29. Rxc5 { Collecting another pawn. } 29... Ra7 30. Nc4
{ Black resigned because White is up two pawns while threatening to win on the spot with Rch5! }
