1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 c5 3. d5 g6 4. Nc3 Bg7 5. e4 d6 6. Bc4 O-O 7. O-O Bg4 8. h3
Bxf3 9. Qxf3 Nbd7 10. Qd1 Ne8 11. a4 Nc7 12. Re1 Rb8 13. Bg5 a6
{ This is a typical position coming from the 1...c5 Benoni. These positions are not really that much about concrete moves, but more so about understanding the main plans and ideas. }
14. a5 { Making Black's ...b5-break less effective. } 14... b5
{ This is the standard plan and what I expect you to face the most.   14...h6  15.Bf4  Ne5  Attacking the c4-bishop.   15...f5?  This is another ''typical'' break for the Benoni, but it's pretty terrible here.  16.exf5  gxf5   16...Rxf5  17.Qd2  Protecting the f4-bishop and attacking the h6-pawn.  17...Kh7  18.Bd3  Attacking the f5-rook and keeping an eye on the soft g6-pawn.  18...Rf8  19.Ra4!+-  Threatening Bxh6 followed by Rh4! ➼ with a winning attack.  17.Na4!+-  Keeping an eye on the b6-square and making room for Ra3-Rg3 ➼ with good attacking prospects on the kingside.  16.Bf1  g5!?  This is another typical idea that can sometimes be interesting for Black, but the main drawback is that it weakens the f5-square.  17.Bg3  Ng6  18.Qd2!  White is slightly better because we can bring the knight over with Nd1-Ne3-Nf5! }
15. axb6 Rxb6
{ Attacking the b2-pawn and preparing ...Nb5 ideas.   15...Nxb6  This is also playable, but White has a precise way of getting a significant advantage.  16.Bxa6  Nxa6  17.Rxa6  Nc4  Winning back the pawn.  18.Qe2!  Attacking the c4-knight.  18...Nxb2  19.Nb5  White is much better because the enemy b2-knight is caught offside, and we can play Na7-Nc6 ➼ with pressure on the e7-pawn. }
16. Qc1
{ Protecting the b2-pawn and preparing to maneuver around with Nd1-c3 followed by Bf1-Ne3-Nc4. }
16... Nb5
{ This is Black's main idea ➼ putting pressure on White's queenside. Generally this plan can be very annoying if you don't know how to counter it, but once you understand the main concept, I expect you to have an astronomic winrate against this opening. }
17. Nd1
{ This is the key idea to get a large advantage. We are ready to play c3 on the next move ➼ shutting down both the b5-knight and the g7-bishop. After that we are going to maneuver the knight with Bf1 followed by Ne3-Nc4 and Black has issues with the isolated a6-pawn. }
17... Nd4 18. Ra3
{ This is perfectly fine, my guess is that White wanted to avoid ...Nb3 ideas after pushing the typical c3.   18.c3  This was an alternative.  18...Nb3  19.Bxb3  Rxb3  20.Rxa6  Black has a bit of compensation, but it shouldn't be enough. }
18... Re8
{ Overprotecting the e7-pawn.   18...Ne5!?  This would have been Black's best chance to complicate the game.  19.Bf1  This is the safest, preparing to push f4.   19.Bxa6  Taking the pawn opens up the door for some tactical ideas.  19...Ndf3+!?  20.gxf3  Rxa6!  Deflecting White's rook from protecting the f3-square.  21.Rxa6  Nxf3+  22.Kf1  Qc8!  Attacking both the a6-rook and the h3-pawn ➼ with very decent counterplay for Black.  19...f5 20.f4  Taking space and attacking the e5-knight.  20...Nf7  21.c3  Attacking the d4-knight.  21...Nxg5  22.fxg5  Nb5  Attacking the a3-rook.  23.Ra1  f4  24.Nf2  We can continue with Bc4-Nd3, and White has a slightly better position. }
19. c3 { Getting rid of the annoying knight. } 19... Nb5 20. Ra2
{ Sidestepping Black's threat and keeping ideas to double up on the a-file. }
20... Qc7 21. Ne3 { Activating the knight and preparing to play Bf1-Nc4. }
21... Ne5 22. Bf1
{ Threatening to push f4 followed by Nc4 ➼ winning the a6-pawn. } 22... c4
{ Seeking active counterplay. } 23. Qc2
{ Controlling the d3-square and preparing Rea1!   23.f4?!  This is a good move in general, but it would have allowed some unnecessary counterplay.  23...Nd3!  24.Bxd3  cxd3  With a pretty messy position. The game is close to equal, but things can go really wrong for White quickly.  25.Qd2?  This natural move is simply a horrific blunder!  25...Nxc3!  26.bxc3  Bxc3  27.Qd1  Qc5  With a much better position for Black. }
23... Reb8 24. Bf4
{ Threatening Bxe5 followed by Nxc4. There is no way for Black to save the pawn at this point. }
24... Nd3 25. Bxd3 cxd3 26. Qxd3 { Threatening Nc4! } 26... Qc5 27. Qc4
{ Being a blitz game, White went for the simple move.   27.Nc4!  This would have been even stronger.  27...R6b7  28.Na5+-  With the knight landing on c6 next, White has a crushing position. }
27... Rc8 28. Qxc5 Rxc5 29. Ra4
{ Threatening to play Nc4!   29.Rea1?!  This would've also been fine, but it would've allowed an interesting sacrifice.  29...Bxc3!?  30.bxc3  Nxc3  31.Rc2  Nxe4  32.Rxc5  Nxc5+-  White is objectively winning, but Black gets some hopes to hold. }
29... Nc7 { Protecting the a6-pawn. } 30. Nc4 Rb7 31. Be3
{ Attacking the c5-rook. } 31... Rcb5 32. Rc1
{ Protecting the c3-pawn ➼ preparing to push b4.   32.Na5  This was another solid alternative.  32...f5  33.f3  Protecting the e4-pawn.  33...Kf7  34.Na5  Rxb2  34...Rb8 35.Nc6 Attacking the b8-rook.  35...Ra8  36.b4+-  White is threatening to push c4 followed by b5 with a close to winning position. }
32... f5 33. f3 { Protecting the e4-pawn. } 33... Kf7 34. Na5 Rxb2 35. Nxb7
Rxb7 36. Rb4
{ With the extra exchange, White has a technically winning position. The rest is simple so I will leave the rest of the game without annotations. }
36... Rb5 37. Rxb5 axb5 38. Kf2 Na6 39. Rb1 Bxc3 40. Rxb5 Nc7 41. Rb7 Ne8 42.
Bg5 Nf6 43. Bxf6 Kxf6 44. g4 f4 45. h4 h6 46. Kg2 Kf7 47. Rc7 Be1 48. Kh3 Bg3
49. Rb7 Be1 50. h5 gxh5
{ 50...g5  This was also not helping.  51.e5!  White wins after this little trick.  51...dxe5  52.d6+-  Winning the e7-pawn. }
51. gxh5 Bc3 52. Kg4 Be5 53. Kf5
{ Black resigned because they either drop the f4-pawn or the king is infiltrating. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Carlsen, Magnus vs. Caruana, Fabiano, Lichess Rapid 2020"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4 d5 3. e3 c5 4. Nf3 Nc6 5. Nbd2 Nh5 6. dxc5 Nxf4 7. exf4 Qa5 8.
Bd3 Qxc5 9. O-O g6 10. Nb3 Qd6 11. Qd2 Bg7 12. c3 O-O 13. Rfe1 Bg4 14. Qe3 Bxf3
15. Qxf3 e6 16. h4
{ This move can be played immediately after you understand that the key factor of the position is ➼ the presence of the opposite coloured bishops in the middlegame which tells us the following golden rule: The attacking side is always favored by the presence of the opposite couloured bishops, and in some books they even go as far as saying that ''it feels like the attacking side is playing with an extra piece''. By understanding this basic concept, you can easily come up with 16. h4! ➼ taking the initiative right off the bat. }
16... h5
{ This is generally the automatic reply. Black could have gone for other moves as well, with a position that is close to equal, but that's not really the point of our discussion. We want to mainly focus on how to build up the pressure in this structure @@StartBracket@@even though on many occasions, Black had a better defense to keep equality@@EndBracket@@. }
17. g3
{ Slowly improving the position and then we can start building up the pressure. You don't want to rush with 17.g4 because that would have been too fast, creating a bunch of weaknesses. }
17... Rfe8 18. Rad1
{ Centralizing the rook and setting up tactical motifs against the enemy queen. }
18... a6 19. Nd2
{ Preparing to bring the knight over the kingside. White wants to play Qe2 followed by Nf3-Ng5 and the knight becomes a very annoying piece for the enemy king. }
19... b5
{ Going for the typical queenside play ➼ preparing to push ...b4! which is lengthening the diagonal of the g7-bishop.   19...e5!=  This was a good time for Black to open up the position despite allowing the isolated queen's pawn ➼ Black is getting very active, which fully compensates for the IQP. }
20. Ne4
{ This stunning move must have been missed by Caruana. Unfortunately, Magnus is the kind of guy who never misses such golden opportunities. This move is exploiting the fact that after pushing ...b5 ➼ the c6-knight becomes vulnerable. }
20... Qd7
{ ''Playing it cool'' ➼ but allowing White to get a free initiative after the knight lands on g5.   20...dxe4!  Surprisingly, this was the way to go because Black has a counter trick.  21.Bxe4  Nd4!!  This was the key move to stay in the game, which Caruana failed to spot, still being shocked by White's 20.Ne4!!   21...Qc5??  22.Bxc6+-  Wins the exchange.  22.cxd4  Rad8  With very good compensation for the pawn. }
21. Ng5 { White already has ideas to break with g4. } 21... Rad8
{ 21...b4  Speeding up the queenside play.  22.g4!  It's a race, so there's no time to waste.  22...hxg4  23.Qxg4  Threatening to push h5!  23...bxc3  24.bxc3  Bxc3  Attacking the e1-rook.  25.Re3  White is going to play Rg3 followed by h5 with a dangerous initiative, to say the least.   21...e5  Breaking in the center was no longer that effective.  22.Bc2!  Threatening Rxd5!  22...Rad8  23.Bb3!  Attacking the d5-pawn.  23...e4  24.Qe3  Threatening Rxd5.  24...Ne7  25.Nxe4!  With an extra pawn for White. Keep in mind that  25...Nf5  can easily be met by  26.Qd3! }
22. Bc2
{ White makes a useful waiting move.   22.Bxg6!?  This was the more direct alternative.  22...fxg6  23.Qd3  Threatening Qxg6.  23...Ne7  24.Rxe6  Attacking the a6-pawn and keeping ideas to play for compensation with Rde1. The position should be close to equal. }
22... b4
{ Black is seeking active counterplay which is very natural.   22...Bf6!  This is a very tough move to play because it's meant to give up the precious fianchetto bishop for the g5-knight. However, it was Black's best bet.  23.g4  hxg4  24.Qxg4  Threatening to push h5!  24...Bxg5!  25.fxg5  Kg7!  Preparing to play ...Rh8 next ➼ making Black's kingside safe.  26.Kg2  Rh8  27.Qf4  Kg8  28.Rh1=  with an equal position. }
23. Ba4
{ Spotting a very unpleasant pin.   23.g4!  This was another promising alternative. }
23... bxc3 24. bxc3 Qc8
{ Unpinning the queen, but allowing a brilliant idea.   24...Re7  25.g4!  Breaking the iceberg.  25...hxg4  26.Qxg4  Threatening to push h5.  26...Qc7  27.h5!  Opening up Black's kingside.  27...gxh5  28.Qxh5  Rd6  After this final touch, White is ready to play Rg1 ➼ with good attacking prospects on the kingside.  29.Kh1! }
25. f5
{ This stunning pawn push can easily be missed. Pretty often the deadly strike happens on ''the most protected square''. It's not really a rule, but something to keep in mind because the most protected square sometimes turns out to be the most vulnerable spot as in our case. After 25.f5 ➼ White is undermining both the d5 and h5-pawns.   25.g4!  This was a solid alternative. }
25... gxf5
{ 25...Ne5  This might be tempting, but it's losing in style.  26.Rxe5!  Bxe5  27.fxg6  Threatening Qf7+  27...f5  28.Bxe8  Regaining the exchange.  28...Rxe8  29.Qxh5+-  White has two extra pawns and a winning attack.   25...exf5  26.Rxe8+  Rxe8  27.Qxd5+-  With a deadly double attack against the f7-square and the c6-knight. }
26. c4
{ Threatening cxd5 and Black has problems both in the center + the c6-knight becomes vulnerable.   26.Qxh5  This would have been a bit inaccurate.  26...Re7  Defending the f7-square.  27.Qh7+  Kf8  Suddenly, there is not an obvious way to make progress, and the game becomes quite unclear. }
26... Nd4
{ 26...Ne5  This would have allowed a similar motif.  27.Rxe5!  Bxe5  28.Bxe8  Collecting back the exchange.  28...Rxe8  29.Qxh5+-  with a winning position because Black's king is too weak. }
27. Rxd4
{ Getting rid of the annoying knight because we can win back the exchange on the next move. }
27... Bxd4 28. Bxe8 Rxe8 29. Qxh5 { Threatening both Qf7+ and Qh7+ } 29... Qc7
30. cxd5
{ After this move White is up a pawn + the initiative is on our side. } 30...
Re7
{ 30...e5  This would not have helped.  31.d6!  Trying to deflect Black's queen because  31...Qxd6  allows a forced checkmate after  32.Qxf7+!  31...Qd7  32.Qh7+!  Kf8  33.Qh8#  This is mating because the d6-pawn is taking away the escape e7-square. }
31. dxe6 { Winning another pawn. } 31... f6
{ Attacking the knight, but weakening the g6-square.   31...fxe6  This was losing the e6-pawn.  32.Qg6+  Kh8  33.Nxe6+-  With two extra pawns and a mating attack. }
32. Qg6+ { This move works well because 32...Rg7 allows 33.Qe8# } 32... Kf8 33.
Nf3 { White is simply winning slowly with the two extra pawns. } 33... Bc3 34.
Rc1 { Pinning the bishop. } 34... Rxe6 35. Nd4 { Using the pin! } 35... Rb6 36.
Qh6+ Kg8 37. Qe3 { Winning the c3-bishop. } 37... Bxd4 38. Qe8+
{ The final touch.   38.Qxd4??  It was not too late to mess up the game!  38...Qxc1+-+  Black wins with the extra rook. }
38... Kg7 39. Rxc7+
{ Black had to resign in the game between Carlsen,M @@StartBracket@@2863@@EndBracket@@ -Caruana,F @@StartBracket@@2835@@EndBracket@@ Lichess.org INT 2020. }
*

