1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 Nf6 3. e3 e6 4. Nf3 Be7 5. Bd3 b6 6. Nbd2 Bb7 7. Ne5 a6 8. O-O
Nbd7 9. c3 O-O { This is a typical position coming from the ...Be7-lines. } 10.
Qf3
{ Preparing to bring the queen over the kingside with Qh3 ➼ this is one of the simplest and most effective plans after we play Ne5 with the London-bishop on f4. }
10... Ne8
{ Preparing to meet Qh3 with ...f5!   10...c5  This is another typical move for Black.  11.Qh3  Putting pressure on the h7-square.  11...g6  This is a common way for Black to restrict the d3-bishop.   11...Re8  12.Ndf3  Creating a direct threat of going Nxf7 followed by Ng5 combined with Qxe6!  12...Nxe5  13.Nxe5  We can continue with g4-g5, and White has good attacking prospects on the kingside.   11...h6  This allows a typical deadly sacrifice.  12.Bxh6!  gxh6  13.Qxh6+-  White has a winning attack with f4 followed by Rf3-Rg3.  12.Bh6!  Attacking the f8-rook and preparing to push f4.  12...Re8  13.f4  White has a simple plan to play Ndf3-Ng5 with a much better position.  13...Ne4  According to the Lichess database, this move is very common for Black.  14.Nxe4  dxe4  15.Bc4!  Threatening Nxf7 followed by Qxe6#  15...Bf6  16.f5!!  This stunning move gives White a winning attack.  16...gxf5   16...exf5  This move weakens the f7-square.  17.Bxf7+  Kh8  18.Nxg6+!  is the most precise, getting a mating attack.  18...hxg6  19.Bxg6+-  With Rxf5 coming next, White has a winning attack.   16...Nxe5  17.dxe5  Attacking the f6-bishop.  17...Bxe5  18.fxe6+-  With a winning attack.  17.Qg3++-  Winning on the spot because  17...Kh8  allows  18.Nxf7 }
11. Qh3 { Threatening mate on h7. } 11... f5
{ 11...g6  12.Bh6  Attacking the f8-rook and making room for f4.  12...Ng7  13.f4  We can continue with Ndf3-Ng5, and White has pressure on the kingside. }
12. Ndf3 { With the simple plan to go Nxd7 followed by Ne5. } 12... Nxe5
{ 12...g5  This might look scary, but it doesn't really work.  13.Nxd7!  Attacking the f8-rook.  13...Qxd7   13...g4  14.Qh6!  Keeping an eye on the e6-pawn.  14...Qxd7  15.Ne5  Centralizing and attacking the enemy queen.  15...Qc8  16.f3!+-  Opening up Black's kingside with a completely winning position.  14.Nxg5+-  With a winning position thanks to the extra pawn. }
13. Nxe5 Nd6
{ 13...g5?  This still doesn't work well.  14.Bg3  Threatening to push f4 since ...g4 allows Nxg4! ➼ because Black has problems with the h7-square.  14...Nd6   14...g4  15.Nxg4!+-  With a winning position for White because  15...fxg4??  allows  16.Qxh7  15.f4!  With fxg5 coming on the next move and White has a much better position. }
14. g4 { The key move to break the ...f5 structure. } 14... c5 15. Kh1
{ Making room for Rg1. } 15... Bg5
{ It's pretty tough to come up with anything else for Black because the position is already simply terrible.   15...Ne4  This looks good, but White can easily get rid of Black's knight.  16.f3!+-  The knight has to go back, and we can continue with Rg1, and White has a deadly attack. }
16. Bxg5 Qxg5 17. gxf5 { Opening up the g-file for the rook. } 17... Nxf5
{ 17...exf5  This would've allowed something similar to what happened in the game.  18.Rg1  Qe7  19.Rxg7++-  With Rg1 next ➼ regaining the queen with a winning position thanks to the strong e5-knight. }
18. Rg1 { Activating the rook and attacking Black's queen. } 18... Qe7
{ 18...Qf6?  19.Nd7+-  Winning the exchange.   18...Qh6??  19.Bxf5!+-  Winning a piece because the f5-bishop defends the h3-queen. }
19. Rxg7+ { This stunning move gives White a winning position. } 19... Qxg7
{ 19...Kxg7  This would have allowed a mating attack.  20.Rg1+  Kf6  21.Bxf5!  After this move ➼ Qh6 becomes a deadly threat.  21...exf5  22.Qh6   19...Nxg7  This allows a direct checkmate.  20.Qxh7 }
20. Rg1
{ Gaining the queen with a winning position because the e5-knight is too powerful and the enemy king is vulnerable. }
20... cxd4
{ 20...Qxg1+  This wouldn't have helped either  21.Kxg1  Rae8  22.Bxf5  Rxf5  23.f3+-  With a completely winning endgame because of the good knight against the bad bishop and the enemy king being vulnerable. }
21. Rxg7+ Kxg7 22. Qg4+
{ White found a more direct win even tho 22.exd4 was completely fine too. }
22... Kh8 { 22...Kf6  23.Nd7++-  Winning the exchange. } 23. Bxf5
{ This is precise ➼ planning to recapture on d4 with the queen. } 23... dxe3
{ 23...exf5  24.Qxd4+-  Winning the b6-pawn.   23...Rxf5  24.Qxd4  Kg8  25.Ng4+-  Threatening Nh6 and Qxb6 with a winning position. }
24. Qd4 { Threatening to mate with Nf7-Nh6! } 24... Rxf5 25. Nf7+ Kg8 26. Nh6+
{ Winning the exchange. } 26... Kf8 27. Nxf5 exf5 28. fxe3
{ Black resigned because the b7-bishop was about to drop. } *

