1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 g6 3. Bf4 d6 4. c3 Bg7 5. h3 O-O 6. Nbd2 Nbd7 7. Bh2 b6 8. e4
Bb7 9. Bd3 e5 10. O-O Re8 11. Re1 a5 12. Qc2
{ The queen is well placed here in this structure ➼ overprotecting the e4-pawn and connecting the rooks. }
12... Ba6
{ This plan is a bit inferior, but Black's position was already quite unpleasant with less space. }
13. Bxa6 Rxa6 14. Rad1
{ This move is very natural, but missing out on a good chance.   14.dxe5!  This would have been more precise!  14...Nxe5   14...dxe5  15.Nc4  Attacking the e5-pawn.  15...Nh5  16.Rad1  White has a direct threat to play Ncxe5 ➼ exploiting the pin, plus having a positional plan to go Ne3 followed by Nd5, with a better position thanks to the active knight.  15.Nd4!  After this important move, we can continue with Rad1 followed by f4 with a slightly better position thanks to the extra space. }
14... b5 15. a4 c6
{ This natural-looking move might actually be the losing mistake!   15...Qb8!  This was the only way to get a playable game.  16.Qd3  Attacking the b5-pawn.  16...Rb6  17.axb5  Rxb5  18.b3  We can continue with Ra1 ➼ White has a slightly better position with pressure on the isolated a5-pawn. }
16. c4 { Undermining Black's queenside. } 16... Qb8
{ 16...b4  17.c5!  Thanks to this move, White has a large advantage!  17...exd4   17...dxc5  18.dxe5  Attacking the f6-knight.  18...Nh5  19.g4+-  Trapping Black's h5-knight.  18.Bxd6+-  We can continue with Nb3-Nbxd4 with an extra pawn and a winning position.   16...bxa4  17.c5!  White is much better with the usual play. }
17. c5 { The key move to get a big advantage! We are undermining the e5-pawn. }
17... Bf8
{ 17...dxc5??  This would have lost on the spot.  18.dxe5  , with e6 coming on the next move ➼ winning the d7-knight. }
18. axb5 cxb5
{ 18...Qxb5  This wouldn't have helped.  19.cxd6  Bxd6  20.Nc4  , with dxe5 coming on the next move ➼ winning at least an exchange. }
19. c6 { Attacking the d7-knight. } 19... Rc8 { Threatening ...Rxc6! } 20. d5
{ After this move White is strategically winning with the protected passer on c6. }
20... Nb6 21. Qb3 { Attacking the b5-pawn. } 21... Na4
{ Threatening to play ...Nc5!   21...b4  This move would have weakened the c4-square.  22.Nc4!  Threatening Nfxe5!  22...Nxc4  23.Qxc4  Attacking the a6-rook.  23...Qb6  24.Nd2  We can continue with Kh1 followed by f4 ➼ with an overwhelming strategical advantage. }
22. Rc1
{ Improving the rook and setting up a small trap in case Black goes for ...Nc5! }
22... Bh6
{ 22...Nc5??  This would have lost material.  23.Rxc5!  dxc5  24.Bxe5+-  Collecting the f6-knight on the next move with a crushing position. }
23. Rc2 { Unpinning and overprotecting the b2-pawn. } 23... Ne8 24. g4
{ Threatening to squeeze Black on the kingside with g5. } 24... Nc5
{ 24...f6  25.g5!  Using a tactical idea!  25...fxg5   25...Bxg5  26.Nxg5  Eliminating Black's bishop and weakening the e5-square.  26...fxg5  27.Nf3+-  Threatening both Nxg5 and Nxe5! with a winning position.   25...Bg7  26.gxf6  Bxf6  27.Nxe5!  Sticking to our main idea ➼ playing for the connected passers.  27...dxe5  28.d6+  Kg7  29.d7+-  Winning back the piece while keeping a much better position.  26.Nxe5!  The key idea to making the connected passers roll.  26...dxe5  27.d6++-  White's pawns are crushing.   24...Bf4  This was also not helping.  25.Bxf4  exf4  26.e5!  With the c6-pawn restricting all of Black's pieces, opening up the position will truly benefit us because the enemy pieces are stuck on the queenside.  26...dxe5  27.Rxe5  Nd6  28.Ne4+-  Threatening Nxd6 followed by Qxb5 with a winning position for White. }
25. Qc3
{ White is going for the simple move ➼ threatening Nxe5!   25.Rxc5!?  This would have been a promising sacrifice.  25...dxc5  26.g5  Bg7  27.Qc3  Attacking both the c5 and the e5 pawns.  27...Qa7  28.Bxe5+-  With a winning position for White thanks to the connected passers. }
25... b4 26. Qc4 { Threatening to play Nb3. } 26... b3 27. Rc3
{ Winning a pawn. } 27... Rb6
{ Protecting the b3-pawn.   27...a4  28.Bxe5!+-  White is completely winning thanks to this move. }
28. Bxe5 { Thanks to this small trick, White manages to pick up a pawn. } 28...
dxe5
{ 28...Rb4  This looks tempting, but White has everything under control.  29.Qxc5!  dxc5  30.Bxb8+-  With a winning endgame because of the connected passers. }
29. Qxc5 { Threatening Qxa5. } 29... Bf8
{ Played with the idea to meet 30.Qxa5 with 30...Bb4! winning the exchange. }
30. Qe3 { Staying away from Black's tricks and threatening to play Nc4! } 30...
a4 { Protecting the b3-pawn. } 31. Nxe5
{ Taking advantage of the overloaded queen. } 31... Ra6
{ 31...Qxe5  This would drop the rook.  32.Qxb6+-  Winning the exchange. } 32.
Nd7 Qb5 33. Nxf8 Kxf8 34. Qd4
