1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Bf4 c5 4. e3 cxd4 5. exd4 Bf5 6. c3 Nc6 7. Qb3 Qc8 8.
Be2 h6 9. O-O e6 10. Nbd2 Be7 11. Rfe1 O-O 12. h3 Ne4 13. Nxe4 Bxe4 14. Nd2 Bg6
{ This is a typical position coming from the ...Bf5-lines. Objectively speaking Black should be okay, but White keeps the easier game. }
15. a4
{ Going for the typical queenside play ➼ preparing to grab more space with a5! }
15... Rd8
{ Preparing to trade off the dark squared bishops with ...Bd6 next. Another way to implement this idea was 15...Bd8 with the idea to play ...Bc7 ➼ with similar ideas. }
16. a5 { Taking space on the queenside. } 16... Bd6
{ Going for the bishop trade. Pretty tough to find an alternative for Black honestly.   16...a6  Stopping White from advancing further with a6, but weakening some critical squares on the queenside @@StartBracket@@b6 and c5@@EndBracket@@.  17.Bf1  Improving the bishop and preparing to play Qd1 followed by the queenside expansion with b4 followed by Nb3-Nc5!  17...Bd6  It's not easy at all to come up with another plan for Black.  18.Bxd6  Rxd6  19.Qa3  Attacking the d6-rook.  19...Rd8  20.Nb3  We are going to play Nc5 next, followed by b4 with a dominating position. We can double up the rooks on the e-file with Re3-Rae1 and potentially expand on the kingside with f4-g4! }
17. Bxd6 Rxd6 18. Qa3
{ I think delaying a6 works best because we can use the Nb3-Nc5 plan exactly like Kamsky did in the game.   18.a6!?  This was also interesting.  18...b6  19.Bb5  But I agree it's not so easy to make progress. }
18... Qc7 { Protecting the rook. } 19. Nb3
{ Preparing to bring the knight over with Nc5! } 19... Rad8 20. Bb5
{ Threatening to play Nc5 followed by a6! } 20... f6
{ Black is trying to seek active play in the center with ...e5, but this plan is creating a lot of weaknesses and it's pretty slow.   20...a6  21.Bxc6!  This is a very good trade for us because we remain with a strong knight against the 'useless' bishop.  21...Qxc6  22.Nc5!  Activating the knight and preparing to support it with b4.  22...Qc7  23.b4  We can bring the queen over with Qc1-Qe3, and White has a slightly better position.   20...b6  Stopping White from playing Nc5.  21.axb6  Opening up the a-file.  21...axb6  22.Nd2  We can maneuver the knight with Nf3-Ne5, and White has pressure both in the center and on the queenside. }
21. Nc5 { Attacking the e6-pawn. } 21... Bf7
{ 21...e5  This doesn't really help.  22.a6!  Threatening to win the exchange with Nb7!  22...bxa6  23.Bxa6  Threatening to play Nb7 ➼ forking Black's rooks.  23...Re8  24.Bb5  ,  with a simple threat to play Bxc6 followed by Qxa7 ➼ winning a pawn. }
22. a6
{ This move works really well after we managed to get the knight to c5! White is threatening to win the exchange with Nb7! }
22... bxa6 23. Bxa6 { Threatening to play Nb7! } 23... Rb8 24. Bf1
{ Creating a threat of Na6! } 24... Ra8 25. b4
{ Threatening to expand on the queenside with b5. } 25... Nd8 26. Qa5
{ Offering the queen trade because the endgames are very juicy against Black's isolated a7-pawn. }
26... Rb6
{ 26...Qxa5  27.Rxa5  With Rea1 next and White is enjoying a risk-free initiative. }
27. Na4 { Forcing the endgame. } 27... Rc6 28. Qxc7 Rxc7 29. Nc5
{ Activating the knight and preparing to double up with Ra6-Rea1! ➼ targeting the a7-pawn. }
29... Nb7 30. Ra6 { Preparing to play Rea1. } 30... e5
{ Seeking for active play. } 31. Rea1 { Attacking the a7-pawn. } 31... Nxc5
{ 31...exd4  doesn't help either.  32.cxd4  Nd8  33.b5+-  Threatening to play b6 next ➼ winning the a7-pawn. }
32. dxc5
{ Normally we prefer to capture ''towards the center'', but in this case the connected passers are more valuable. }
32... d4
{ 32...Be8  33.Rd6  Attacking the d5-pawn.  33...Bf7  34.Ra5+-  We can continue with g3-Bg2, with a winning endgame because Black's position is full of weaknesses @@StartBracket@@mainly the d5 and a7 pawns@@EndBracket@@. }
33. cxd4 exd4 34. Bd3
{ This move is super precise because it's not only threatening Be4 ➼ winning the a7-pawn, but also trapping Black's king in a mating net! }
34... Rb8 35. Rxa7 { Black has problems with the backrank. } 35... Rxa7 36.
Rxa7 Be8
{ 36...Rxb4??  37.Ra8++-  Winning the bishop because the h7-square is covered by the d3-bishop! }
37. Ra6 { Preparing to push c6! } 37... Rxb4 38. c6
{ There is no way to stop the c-pawn. } 38... Kf7 39. c7 Bd7 40. Ra8
{ Black resigned because the endgame is easily winning with the extra piece. This was a marvellous display by Kamsky ➼ against a giant of dynamic chess. Alexei Shirov is a brilliant attacking player, but after a very clever opening choice by White, going for the London System, he was unable to show his main quiality and had to defend a passive position. This is a powerful strategy that you can use against dynamic players. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Berkes, Ferenc vs. McShane, Luke, Heraklion 2017"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Bf4 c5 4. e3 Nc6 5. Nbd2 Bg4 6. c3 cxd4 7. exd4 e6 8.
Qb3 Qc8 9. Bd3 Be7 10. O-O O-O 11. Qc2 Bh5 12. Ne5 a6 13. Rae1 Bg6 14. Nxg6
{ Eliminating the bishop pair and making room for the other knight to e5. White is better in this structure because we have good play on the kingside and ideas to rook lift with Re3-Rh3!   14.Bxg6  This move would've been less effective.  14...hxg6  threatening @@StartFEN@@r1q2rk1/1p2bpp1/p1n1pnp1/3pN3/3P1B2/2P5/PPQN1PPP/4RRK1 b - - 0 15@@EndFEN@@  ...Nxd4!  15.Qd3  b5  , with a double-edged fight. }
14... hxg6 15. Nf3 { Preparing to play Ne5. } 15... b5
{ Going for the minority attack ➼ threatening to push ...b4! } 16. a3
{ As a general rule ''We should not be moving the pawns on the side where opponent is attacking'', but in this particular case 16.a3! is the best move because we are slowing down Black's queenside play quite dramatically. }
16... Ra7
{ My guess is that Black played this with the idea to go ...Rb7 followed by ...a5-b4 ➼ and realized too late that White has Ba6!   16...Na5  With the idea to play ...Nc4 followed by ...a5-b4!  17.h4  Going for the typical kingside play.  17...Nc4  18.g3  Preparing to play the standard Kg2-Rh1.  18...a5  19.Qe2!  Improving the queen and preparing to use the c-file if Black opens up the queenside with ...b4!  19...b4  20.cxb4!  This is a very interesting way to deal with Black's minority attack. The point is to play Rc1 next ➼ exploiting the poor placement of the c8-queen.  20...axb4  21.Rc1!  Threatening to push b3 and win the c4-knight because of the pin.  21...Qe8  22.b3!  Sacrificing the a3-pawn because the knight will be restricted on a3.  22...Nxa3  23.Kg2  The enemy knight is caught offside on a3 while we can push on the kingside with the typical Ne5 followed by Rh1-h5!   16...Qb7  Protecting the b5-pawn and threatening to play ...a5 ➼ going for the minority attack.  17.Qe2!  Improving the queen and making it harder for Black to push on the queenside because the b5-pawn is vulnerable.  17...Nh5  Attacking the f4-bishop.  18.Bc1!  Nf6  19.Ng5!  Making room for the f4-push. This works best because it gives Black no counterplay.   19.Ne5?!  This is decent but allows Black to get some chances.  19...Nxe5  20.dxe5  Attacking the f6-knight.  20...Ne4!?  This is usually a good practical try.  21.Bxe4  dxe4  22.Qxe4  Rfb8  Even though White is still better, Black has some hopes on the queenside with ...a5-b4!  19...Qd7  20.f4!  Preparing to bring the rook over with Rf3-Rh3!  20...Rae8  21.Rf3  Preparing to play Rh3!  21...Bd6  22.Rh3  Qe7  23.Qf3  Creating a threat of going Rh4 followed by Qh3 ➼ with a deadly attack on the h-file.  23...Nh5  The position was already lost, but this allowed a typical tactic.  24.Rxh5!  Black had to resign because the checkmate was unstoppable after  24...gxh5  25.Qxh5  with the mate on h7 next. This was the game between Kassay,K - Csukerda,A Hungary 2014.   16...Nd7  This is meant to make Ne5 less effective.  17.h4!  Initiating the typical kingside play! We will follow the only game that I was able to find in the database because it's quite well played, even though White made a few inaccuracies here and there. Overall the main ideas have been executed correctly.  17...Re8  18.Re2  Nf8  19.g3  Preparing the standard Kg2-Rh1.  19...Qb7  20.Kg2  Preparing to play Rh1 followed by the h5-push.  20...a5  Going for the minority attack.  21.b4!?  This is an interesting way to stop Black's counterplay on the queenside, but focus on the kingside play with 21.Rh1 was also playable.  21...axb4  22.axb4  Ra3  23.Bc1  Getting rid of Black's rook that was keeping an eye on the c3-pawn.  23...Ra1  24.Rh1  Threatening to push h5.  24...Bf6  25.Qb2!  Keeping an eye on Black's counterplay.   25.h5?!  This would have allowed a lot of counterplay.  25...gxh5  26.Rxh5  g6  27.Rh1  e5  White is still slightly better, but the position becomes quite messy.  25...Raa8  26.Bf4!  Stopping Black's counterplay connected with the ...e5-break.  26...Nd7  27.Rhe1!  Controlling the e5-square.  27...Qa6  28.g4!  Now that Black has no moves, we can easily go for the kill on the kingside.  28...Nb6  29.h5!?  Going for an instructive trick.  29...gxh5  30.g5!  This move will take a lot of your opponents by surprise!  30...Bd8  31.g6!  This was the point! Black's king becomes vulnerable.  31...Bf6  32.gxf7+  Kxf7  33.Qb1  Threatening  Bg6+!  33...Kg8  34.Bh7+  Kh8  35.Qg6  Black had to resign because Qxh5 was coming on the next move. This was the game played between Meczynski,W - Miszczak,M Poland 2012. }
17. Qe2
{ Improving the queen. This is usually a good square because it's keeping an eye on the b5-pawn @@StartBracket@@making it harder for Black to initiative the minority attack with ...a5-b4@@EndBracket@@ and the queen can easily join the kingside after we push the typical h4-h5. }
17... Re8 18. h4
{ Starting the typical kingside play. The point is to continue with g3-Kg2-Rh1 followed by the h5-break. }
18... Bd8
{ Preparing to play ... Bc7 ➼ trying to exchange the dark squared bishops. }
19. g3 { Preparing to play Kg2-Rh1. } 19... Ne7
{ 19...Bc7  It would be nice for Black to trade bishops, but White is not forced to allow it @@StartBracket@@like it happened a bit later in the game@@EndBracket@@.  20.Ne5!  , with similar play to what happened in the game. }
20. Kg2 { Preparing to play Rh1 and break with h5! } 20... Nf5 21. Rh1
{ Already threatening to push h5 because ...Nxh5 could potentially be met by Rxh5! with Bxf5 ➼ taking advantage of the undefended e8-rook. }
21... Bc7 22. Ne5
{ This is best! Trading bishops was not a disaster, but it was significantly reducing White's advantage. }
22... Bb8
{ Opening up the seventh rank for the a7-rook.   22...Bxe5  This wouldn't have helped Black either.  23.dxe5!  Attacking the f6-knight.  23...Ne4  24.g4!  Focusing on the initiative.   24.Bxe4  This was also playable but would've reduced White's advantage.  24...dxe4  25.Qxe4  White is up a pawn, but it will take some time and effort to convert ➼ this is why we generally prefer the kingside play.  24...Ne7  25.f3!  Getting rid of the annoying knight.  25...Nc5  Threatening ...Nxd3!  26.Bb1  Keeping the powerful bishop and preparing to push h5 on the next move. White has very good attacking prospects. }
23. g4
{ Simple and strong.   23.h5!?  This was more complicated, but it's a nice idea to be aware of @@StartBracket@@when simple play doesn't work so well@@EndBracket@@.  23...Nxh5   23...gxh5  24.Bg5!  Threatening Bxf6 followed by Qxh5!  24...Kf8  25.Bxf5  exf5  26.Bxf6  gxf6  27.Qxh5!  Sacrificing the knight and focusing on the attack.  27...fxe5  28.Qg5!+-  Controlling the key escape e7-square and threatening to play h8# Black is getting mated.  24.Bc1!  Threatening to push g4 ➼ forking Black's knights.  24...Nf6  25.g4  Attacking the f5-knight.  25...Nd6  26.Qf3  ,  with Qh3 coming on the next move ➼ for a deadly attack on the h-file. }
23... Nd6 24. h5
{ This is connected with a small trick if Black plays 24...gxh5. } 24... Nfe4
{ Black tries to complicate the game, but the position is already objectively losing. White is simply too fast on the kingside while Black has no counterplay.   24...gxh5  This would only speed up White's attack.  25.g5!  This is the key trick to remember. We are getting rid of the f6-knight so we can collect the h5-pawn with a piece.  25...Nd7  26.Qxh5  , with a mating attack.   25...Ng4  26.Rxh5  Nxe5  27.Bxe5  ,  with Rdh1 next and a deadly attack. }
25. hxg6 f6 26. Qf3
{ Threatening to play Qh3! Berkes has a very good feeling for the initiative.   26.Nf3  This was still objectively winning, but you would have to calculate unnecessary complications.  26...e5  Black is threatening ...Qxg4+ and the position becomes quite messy. }
26... Kf8
{ Trying to run away with ...Ke7!   26...fxe5  Taking the piece was losing in a lot of ways.  27.Bxe5  Threatening to play Qh3.  27...Qb7   27...Ng5  28.Qg3+-  Threatening with both Bxd6 and Qh4 for a deadly attack.  28.Qh3  Threatening Qh8#  28...Kf8  29.Qh8+  Ke7  30.Qxg7+  The simplest!  30...Kd8  31.Qxb7  Going for a winning endgame.  31...Rxb7  32.f3+-  Collecting the e4-knight with a winning endgame. }
27. Rh7
{ Catching Black's king in a mating net because we are stopping ...Ke7! } 27...
Rb7 28. Bc1
{ Keeping it very simple ➼ threatening to push g5!   28.Qh3  ,  with the idea to push f3 ➼ this was also winning. }
28... Rd8 29. g5 Nf5
{ Threatening ... fxe5!   29...f5  doesn't save Black.  30.Qh5  Threatening to push f3 ➼ trapping the e4-knight.  30...Nc4  Making a square on d6 for the e4-knight.  31.Nf7  Attacking the d8-rook.  31...Re8  32.Rxg7!+-  Black is getting mated because  32...Kxg7  allows  33.Qh6+  g8  34.Qh8 }
30. Nf7 { Simply attacking the d8-rook. } 30... Rxf7
{ Sacrificing the exchange in order to avoid immediate disaster, but Black's position remains lost.   30...Re8  This loses material.  31.gxf6  Nxf6  32.Bxf5!  The simplest.  32...exf5  33.Rh8+  Ng8  34.Rxg8+!  After this cute trick ➼ Black is getting mated.  34...Kxg8  35.Qh5+-  There is no way to stop the checkmate.   30...Rdd7  This doesn't help  31.Rh8+  , winning the queen. }
31. gxf7 { Threatening to push g6. } 31... fxg5
{ 31...Nxg5  This would allow a forced checkmate.  32.Bxg5!  fxg5  33.Bxf5  exf5  34.Qh5  ,  with Rh8# coming on the next move. }
32. Bxe4 { Eliminating Black's most active piece. } 32... dxe4 33. Rxe4
{ Threatening the simple Bxg5. } 33... Bf4
{ 33...Nh4+  This might seem appealing, but White can simply sacrifice the exchange and eliminate Black's threat.  34.Rexh4  gxh4  35.Bg5+-  Taking away the e7-square and threatening to mate with Rh8 on the next move. }
34. Bxf4 gxf4 35. Qh5
{ Every move was winning at this point, but this is quite precise. White is threatening to play Rh8+ next. }
35... f3+ 36. Kxf3
{ Black resigned because a nice finish with Rh8+ followed by Re8! was about to appear on the board. }
