[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Berkes, Ferenc vs. Nguyen, Thai Dai Van, Zalakaros 2016"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 d5 3. Bf4 c5 4. e3 Nc6 5. Nbd2 cxd4 6. exd4 Bf5 7. c3 e6 8.
Qb3 Qc8 9. Nh4 Bg4 10. h3 Bh5 11. g4 Bg6 12. Nxg6 hxg6 13. Be2 Be7 14. h4 Qd7
15. O-O-O O-O-O 16. Kb1 Bd6
{ This is a very common position arising from the ...c5 & ...Bg4/Bf5-lines. }
17. Be3
{ Keeping the dark squared bishops on the board is one of the most important nuances about this structure.   17.Bxd6?!  This would have been a positional mistake.  17...Qxd6=  Black is very comfortable with good control over the f4-square. This is why we need to avoid trading the dark-squared bishops! }
17... Qc7 { Fighting for the f4-square. } 18. Rc1
{ Preparing to break with c4! This is the key idea to keep pressure on both sides. We are putting pressure on the queenside with c4 and on the kingside with h5! }
18... Kb8
{ 18...Bf4  19.c4  Threatening cxd5 followed by Bb5!  19...dxc4  20.Rxc4!  Although the typical 20.Nxc4 is also good, this works better because we are creating a direct threat of xBf4 followed by d5!  20...Nd5  21.Rhc1!  Focusing on the queenside play.  21...Rxh4  22.Rc5  With Ba6/Bb5 ideas ➼ White has the initiative.   18...Na5  19.Qa4  Sidestepping Black's threat and preparing to push c4!  19...Kb8  20.g5  Attacking the f6-knight.  20...Nd7  21.c4!  Going for the typical queenside play.  21...Nc6  22.c5!  Grabbing space and preparing to expand even further with b4.  22...Bf4  23.Nf3!  This is important to start with because the direct  23.b4  Nxd4!  wins for Black. Next up, we are ready to advance on the queenside with  b4  , and White is enjoying a powerful initiative. }
19. c4 { Threatening cxd5 followed by Bb5! } 19... dxc4 20. Nxc4
{ Creating a concrete threat of going Ne5! } 20... Nd5 21. h5
{ Threatening hxg6 ➼ messing up Black's structure. } 21... gxh5 22. gxh5
{ After this move White is getting pressure on the g7-pawn with Rhg1 ideas. }
22... Na5
{ Exchanging White's powerful knight.   22...Bf4  23.Bf3  We can continue with Rhg1 with pressure on both sides.   22...Qe7  23.Nd2  Threatening Rxc6! ➼ exploiting the pin.  23...Ka8  24.Ne4  With Rg1 next ➼ White is in control with pressure on the g7-pawn.   22...f5  Threatening to push ...f4 followed by ...Nxd4!  23.Bg5!  This move works well ➼ avoiding Black's ...f4 idea.  23...Nxd4!?  Sacrificing the exchange.   23...Rc8  24.Nxd6  Qxd6  25.Rhd1  We can continue with Bf3 followed by Rc5 with pressure on the queenside.  24.Bxd8  Rxd8  25.Qd1  Protecting the e2-bishop.  25...Bc5  26.Bf1  We can continue with Qe1 followed by Ne3, and we can slowly take over the initiative after we push h6! }
23. Nxa5 Qxa5 24. Rhg1
{ Attacking the g7-pawn. Here you can notice why going h5 earlier was important! }
24... Rc8
{ This natural move turns out to be a significant mistake.   24...Nxe3!  This would have been Black's best bet.  25.fxe3  Rc8  26.Bf3  Threatening mate on b7.  26...Rxc1+  27.Rxc1  Qb4!  Offering a relatively equal endgame.  28.Qxb4  I think White keeps some pressure, but if you are in a more fighting mood 28.Qc2 was a decent alternative.  28...Bxb4  29.Rg1  With pressure on the g7-pawn and ideas to bring the king over by playing Kc2-Kd3.   24...Nf4  Attacking the e2-bishop.  25.Bf3  Threatening mate on b7.  25...Qf5+  26.Ka1  Nd5   26...b6  This move is really weakening Black's king.  27.Bxf4!  Entering the opposite colored bishop middlegame because we have the initiative.  27...Bxf4  28.Rc6  With Rxb6+ ideas, White has a powerful initiative.  27.Bxd5  exd5  28.Rg5  Attacking Black's queen and putting pressure on the d5-pawn.  28...Qf6  29.Rxd5  With an extra pawn for White.   24...Bf4??  This was losing on the spot.  25.Rc5!  Qb6  26.Rxd5!+-  Thanks to this move, White wins material. }
25. Bf3
{ Threatening Rxg7 because Black can no longer get the ...Nxe3 counterplay since that will allow Qxb7#   25.Rxc8+  The greedy alternative isn't effective.  25...Rxc8  26.Rxg7?!  Nxe3  27.fxe3  Qd2!=  Black has enough activity to hold. }
25... Rxc1+ 26. Bxc1 { Keeping pressure on the g7-pawn. } 26... Rc8
{ Going for tricks.   26...Rh7  27.Rg5!  Winning a pawn. } 27. Rxg7
{ White correctly assessed that Black should not get enough play. } 27... Nc3+
28. Ka1
{ This is the most precise!  28.bxc3?!  Qf5+  Winning the f3-bishop ➼ this would have given Black chances to survive. }
28... Nb5 29. Rg1
{ Keeping a small advantage, but missing a direct win.  29.Be3!!  This stunning move wins because there are no actual back rank problems.  29...Qe1+  30.Qd1  Qxd1+  31.Bxd1  Nxd4  This move looks annoying at the beginning, but then you realize Black has no actual threat!  32.Rxf7!  , with a completely winning endgame thanks to the outside passed pawn combined with the bishop pair. }
29... Qc7 30. Qd1 Nxd4 31. Be4
{ The only move to keep an advantage.  31.Qxd4??  Allows a direct mate.  31...Qxc1+  32.Rxc1  Rxc1#  This was Black's main point behind 30...Nxd4! }
31... Be5 32. h6 f5 { Attacking the e4-bishop. } 33. Bd3 Qa5
{ Threatening ...Rxc1+ followed by ...Nb3+! ➼ winning the queen. } 34. Kb1
{ Sidestepping ...Nb3 ideas. } 34... Qc7 35. Be3 { Threatening to play Qa4. }
35... Qd7 36. Bf1
{ 36.a3  This would have been a bit more precise according to the computer, but both sides were already in severe time trouble. }
36... Rd8 37. f4 { After this strong move White is in full control. } 37... Bf6
38. Bg2
{ 38.Rg2!  This would have been really strong ➼ threatening to play Rd2! }
38... Qb5 { Creating a HUGE threat of going ...Ne2! } 39. a4
{ Getting rid of Black's queen. } 39... Qd7
{ 39...Qb4  This would have been more resilient. } 40. Rh1
{ Reaching time control with a good position. White is much better thanks to the outside passer on h6. }
40... e5 41. h7 Qg7 42. Bd5
{ The bishop is untouchable because the h7-pawn is about to promote. White has a direct threat of going fxe5 followed by Rg1-Rg8! }
42... Qg3 43. Qg1 { This move is forcing a winning endgame. } 43... Qxg1+ 44.
Rxg1 { Threatening fxe5 followed by Rg8! } 44... Rxd5 45. fxe5 Rxe5
{ 45...Bxe5  46.Bf4!!+-  Deflecting Black's bishop in order to promote. } 46.
Bxd4 Re7 47. Bxf6 Rxh7 48. Rg5
{ White has an easily winning endgame with the extra piece. } 48... Rh1+ 49.
Kc2 Rf1 50. Rg7 a5 51. Bd8 Rf2+ 52. Kb3 Rf3+ 53. Ka2
{ Black resigned because the a5-pawn was dropping. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Kamsky, Gata vs. Fedorowicz, John, Los Angeles 1991"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 g6 3. Bg5 Bg7 4. Nbd2 O-O 5. c3 d6 6. e4 Nc6 7. Be2 h6 8. Bh4
e5 9. O-O Qe8 10. dxe5 dxe5 11. b4 Nh5 12. Re1 Kh8 13. Qc2 f6 14. Nc4 Nd8 15.
Nfd2 Nf4 16. Bf1 Nde6 17. f3 Bd7 18. a4 Rd8 19. Bf2 a6
{ In this game Kamsky played the Torre Attack against the King's Indian Defense ➼ which is one of his pet lines vs the KID. However I picked this game for our ''Model Games'' section because we ended up in a very similar structure for our King's Indian Repertoire! We basically get into these positions after Black goes ... e5 and we meet it with dxe5 followed by Be3. }
20. Na5 { This is a very annoying move for Black ➼ we are threatening Nxb7! }
20... Bc8
{ Protecting the b7-square without creating additional weaknesses.   20...b6  21.Nac4  Threatening to push a5.  21...Bc6!   The point of this move is to meet  22.a5  with  22...b5!  23.Ne3  f5!  , with very decent counterplay.  22.Ne3  Threatening Bxa6!  22...Bb7  23.a5  Threatening axb6.  23...b5  24.Nb3!  Heading towards the c5-square.  24...Qf7  25.Rad1  Threatening to push c4!  25...Rxd1   25...Kh7  26.c4  , with pressure on the queenside.  26.Nxd1  Opening up bishop's path towards the c5-square.  26...f5  27.Nc5  Nxc5  28.Bxc5  Threatening Bxf8.  28...Re8  29.c4  , with pressure on the queenside. }
21. b5 { Threatening to push b6. } 21... axb5 22. axb5 Ng5
{ Setting up a small trap with ...Nfh3+ followed by ...Rxd2! with a deadly fork coming on f3.   22...f5  23.Nac4!  Preparing the b6-push while keeping an eye on the e5-square.  23...Qxb5   23...fxe4  24.Nxe4  Qxb5  25.Ra5!  After this important move, White picks up the e5-pawn.  25...Qe8  26.Nxe5  With a better position for White because  26...b6  allows  27.Bb5!  , with a winning position for White.  24.exf5  gxf5  25.Nxe5  Collecting the pawn and creating a discovery against the enemy queen.  25...Qe8  26.g3  Attacking the f4-knight.  26...Ng6  27.Ndc4  We can continue with f4 followed by Bg2 with a much better position. }
23. Kh1
{ Sidestepping Black's trick.   23.b6??  This is a typical move, but it would have allowed a deadly tactic here.  23...Nfh3+!  24.gxh3  Rxd2!  25.Qxd2  Nxf3+-+  This combination is the point behind 22...Ng5! }
23... f5 24. b6 { This is the key idea to open up Black's queenside. } 24...
fxe4
{ 24...cxb6  25.Bxb6  Attacking the d8-rook.  25...Rd7  26.Nac4  Threatening exf5 followed by Bc5 with Nd6 ideas.   26.Bb5??  This skewerk seems tempting, but it's actually a big blunder!  26...Rxd2!-+  Suddenly Black wins material.  26...Qe6  27.Rab1  We can continue with Bc5, followed by Rb6 with pressure on both sides of the board. }
25. Nxe4
{ Avoiding all the tricks.  25.bxc7?!  This would have allowed a powerful exchange sacrifice.  25...Rxd2!  26.Qxd2  exf3  and Black is taking over the initiative on the kingside. }
25... Nxe4 26. Qxe4 { Threatening bxc7! } 26... cxb6 27. Nc4
{ Threatening Nxe5!  27.Bxb6?!  This would have allowed a lot of counterplay.  27...Bf5!  28.Qxb7  Rb8  29.Qa6  Rf6  The position is very dangerous because it's not easy to unpin. }
27... Qc6
{ Black fails to spot the right time to go for active play and instead goes for a worse endgame.   27...Bf5!  This would have been Black's best bet, but not an easy find!  28.Qxb7  b5!  After this move, the position should be close to equal. }
28. Qxc6 bxc6 29. Bxb6
{ After this simple sequence, White is enjoying a much better endgame thanks to the isolated e5-pawn. }
29... Rd5 { Protecting the e5-pawn. } 30. Bc7 { Threatening Bxe5. } 30... Nd3
{ Black was hoping to save himself in the opposite colored bishop endgame, but in reality, the position is hopeless because White is too active.   30...Bf5!  This would have been a better try.  31.Bxe5  Bd3  With chances to survive even though White is still better.  32.Bxg7+  Kxg7  33.Bxd3  Nxd3  34.Re6  We can push for a long time with the extra pawn. }
31. Bxd3 { Eliminating the annoying knight. } 31... Rxd3 32. Nxe5
{ Kamsky shows very good understanding of the endgame ➼ not being afraid of the general rule that ''the opposite coloured bishop endgames are very drawish'' because he clearly assesed that the activity turns out to be decisive. }
32... Bxe5 33. Bxe5+ Kg8 34. Bd4
{ Threatening to play Re7/Ra7! After this move White is objectively winning because the enemy king is vulnerable. }
34... Rd8 35. Ra7 { Threatening Rg7+ ➼ picking up the g6-pawn. } 35... Rd7 36.
Ra8 { Pinning the c8-bishop. } 36... Rd8 { Threatening to push ...c5! } 37. h4
{ Taking space and making a luft. } 37... c5 38. Bf6
{ Attacking the d8-rook.  38.Bxc5  Taking the pawn was much riskier, but still winning with precise play.  38...Rxc3  39.Bb6!!+-  Only winning move, but still not very obvious. }
38... Rf8 39. Re7 { Activating the rook because we don't mind ...Rxf6! } 39...
Rd7
{ 39...Rxf6  This would have lost another pawn.  40.Rxc8+  Rf8  41.Rxc5+-  With two extra pawns and threatening to play Rcc7 ➼ White is completely winning. }
40. Kh2
{ This move is very clever ➼ creating a threat of going Rxc8!   40.Rxc8  This doesn't work yet because Black can go for the intermezzo.  40...Rd1+!=  After this move, Black wins the exchange with an equal endgame @@StartBracket@@because White is very active@@EndBracket@@. }
40... Rxe7 41. Bxe7 { Winning the c5-pawn. } 41... Re8 42. Bxc5
{ With two extra pawns the position is objectively winning, but it's still very interesting to see how Kamsky converts. }
42... Kf7 43. Ra7+ Ke6 44. Bd4 { Threatening to play Rg7! } 44... Re7 45. Ra8
{ White goes for the practical choice! The endgame is easily winning with rooks on the board.   45.Rxe7+  Kxe7  46.Kg3+-  This endgame is also winning, but harder to evaluate OTB. }
45... Rc7 46. Kg3 { Activating the king. } 46... Kd5 47. Rb8
{ Preparing to play Rb6. } 47... Kc4
{ 47...Rc6  48.Kf4+-  Followed by g4 with a winning endgame, slowly but surely. }
48. Rb6 { Attacking the g6-pawn. } 48... Bf5 49. h5
{ After this move White has an easy win. } 49... gxh5 50. Rxh6
{ Threatening to collect the h5-pawn. } 50... Rh7 51. Rxh7 Bxh7 52. Kh4
{ Black resigned because White has an easy book win with the two extra pawns. Just remember that if the pawns are separated by at least two files, the position is winning. }
