[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Moroni, Luca Jr vs. Batsiashvili, Nino, Titled Tuesday 2022"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 e6 3. e3 Bd6 4. Nf3 Bxf4 5. exf4 c5 6. dxc5 Qc7 7. g3 Qxc5 8.
Nbd2 Nf6 9. Bd3 O-O 10. O-O b6 11. Qe2 a5 12. Nb3 Qe7 13. Nbd4 Ba6 14. Ne5 Nfd7
15. Bxa6 Nxa6 16. Nxd7 Qxd7 17. Rad1 Rfc8 18. Rfe1 Nc5
{ This is a typical position arising from the Berkes structure. Objectively speaking Black should be fine because they managed to trade off the bad bishop, but White's position remains easier to play. }
19. c3
{ This is a very typical move for our structure ➼ supporting the d4-knight. }
19... g6
{ 19...Ne4  This would have been a bit more precise.  20.h4!  Going for the typical kingside play.  20...Rab8  Preparing to start the queenside counterplay with ...b5-b4!  21.Qg4  Threatening to push f5!  21...Nf6  22.Qf3  With f5 ideas, White has an easier play on the kingside. }
20. h4
{ White has a simple plan: We are planning to take advantage of the g6-hook by going h5-hxg6 with Kg2-Rh1 and White has good attacking prospects on the kingside. }
20... h5
{ This is usually the standard answer to h4. Most of the times it slows down White's initiative for a bit, but this structure is now vulnerable to g4 ideas in the long run. }
21. Kg2
{ This is a very useful move ➼ making room for Rh1 which makes the g4-break really powerful. }
21... a4 { Threatening to push ...a3! } 22. a3 Qb7 23. Qe5
{ This is a good positional move, but the direct play was working even better.   23.g4!  Using brute force!  23...hxg4  24.Qxg4  Threatening to push h5!  24...Kh7  Played with the idea to meet h5 with ...Rg8!  25.Kf3!+-  The king is very safe on this square, and we can continue with h5-Rh1 ideas ➼ with a HUGE attack. }
23... Ne4
{ Centralizing the knight, but the problem is that White can easily get rid of it. A ''small'' inaccuracy like this turns out to be the decisive mistake in this game.   23...Re8!  This would have been a much better try.  24.f3  Preparing the g4-break.  24...Qb8  Offering a queen trade.  25.Qe3!  Keeping queens on the board will give you the best chances on the kingside mainly because we are gonna be using the g4-break to create pressure against the enemy king. }
24. f3 { Getting rid of the annoying knight. } 24... Nc5 25. Qg5
{ White has a deadly threat to push f5! Notice how all of Black's pieces are stuck on the queenside which makes our kingside play really effective. }
25... Qd7
{ 25...Kh7  This doesn't help.  26.f5+-  The same motif works because  26...exf5  allows  27.Re7! }
26. f5
{ By using simple tactics White is able to get a crushing initiative. The main point is that 26...exf5 allows 27.Re7! }
26... exf5
{ 26...Kh7  27.Qf6!  This is the most precise ➼ threatening to win an important pawn with fxe6!  27...Re8   27...gxf5??  28.Nxf5!  This simple sacrifice is just deadly.  28...exf5  29.Re7+-  Black has to give up the queen in order to stop a brutal checkmate.  28.Re5!  The rook is very useful on this square ➼ keeping an eye on the h5-square.  28...Rad8   28...exf5  29.Nxf5!  This knight sacrifice works well again ➼ this time because the rook is able to go to the 5th rank.  29...gxf5  30.Rxf5  Threatening Rxh5+!  30...Re2+  31.Kg1!+-  Avoiding all the checks, and Black has no way to stop Rxh5+ with a crushing attack.  29.Nxe6!  Using a subtle trick.  29...fxe6   29...Nxe6  30.Rdxd5!  Attacking Black's queen and taking over the 5th rank.  30...Qc7  31.fxg6+  Threatening a forced checkmate with Rxh5-Rh8#  31...Kg8  32.Rxh5  Threatening h8#  32...Ng7  33.gxf7+  Qxf7  34.Rh8+!  Using the magnet sacrifice ➼ deflecting Black's king.  34...Kxh8  35.Qxf7+-  White has an easily winning position with the extra queen.  30.Qxg6+  Kh8  31.f6+-  With Rxh5+ coming on the next move ➼ White has a winning position. }
27. Re7
{ Activating the rook while getting rid of the only defender from Black's camp. }
27... Qd8 28. Nxf5
{ The material is even, but White is completely winning with so many pieces around the enemy king. }
28... Rc7 29. Rde1
{ Good enough.  29.Qf6!+-  This would have won on the spot, but what happened in the game was also sufficient to secure the victory. }
29... Rac8 30. Qf6 { Threatening Qxf7+! } 30... Qf8 31. Nh6+
{ The final touch! } 31... Qxh6
{ 31...Kh7  32.Nxf7  , with an easy win for White. } 32. Qxf7+ Kh8 33. Re8+
{ With a forced checkmate. } 33... Rxe8 34. Rxe8+ Qf8 35. Rxf8#
{ Impressive display of the Berkes structure by the talented italian GM Luca Moroni ➼ highlighting the power of an easy position by playing solid, natural moves. }
