1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Bf4 c5 4. e3 Nc6 5. Nbd2 e6 6. c3 Bd6 7. Bg3 O-O 8. Bd3
b6 9. Qe2 Bb7 10. Rd1 Re8 11. e4 Be7 12. e5 Nh5
{ This is a super theoretical line coming from the ''QGD With 5...e6''. } 13.
O-O
{ This is a more positional alternative to our aggressive main line with  13.h4!?  ➼ as shown in the Theory Chapter. }
13... g6 14. Rfe1
{ Improving the rook and preparing the typical maneuver with Nf1-Ne3-Ng4. }
14... Rc8
{ 14...cxd4  15.cxd4  Nb4  Threatening  ...Nxd3!  16.Bb1  Ba6  17.Qe3  We can continue with a3-b4, and White has pressure on both sides. }
15. a3
{ Controlling the critical b4-square ➼ because Black had ...cxd4-Nb4 ideas. }
15... a5 16. Nf1
{ This is a typical maneuver preparing to bring the knight over the kingside with Nf1-Ne3-Ng4! }
16... a4 { Trying to create counterplay on the queenside with ... Na5-Nc4. }
17. Bb5 { Attacking the a4-pawn. } 17... Ra8 18. Ne3 { Preparing to play Ng4. }
18... Rf8 19. Bxc6 { Avoiding any ...Na5-Nc4 ideas. } 19... Bxc6 20. Ng4
{ Preparing to play Qe3-Qh6. } 20... Nxg3 21. fxg3
{ Creating a square for the knight on f2 and threatening to push h4-h5.   21.hxg3  This would have been less precise.  21...h5!  22.Ne3  Kg7  Black is going to play ...Rh8 next, and it's not easy to break through. }
21... h5 22. Nf2 { Threatening to play h4 followed by Nh3-Nfg5! } 22... g5
{ Avoiding White's bind with h4.  22...Kg7  This would no longer hold.  23.h4!  Fixing the weak square on g5.  23...Rh8  24.Nh3  We could continue with Nfg5 followed by Rf1 and then break with g4. }
23. g4
{ 23.Nd2!  Attacking the h5-pawn ➼ this would have been even more precise.  23...g4  24.h3!  Breaking Black's kingside.  24...gxh3  25.Qxh5!  , with a winning attack for White. }
23... hxg4
{ 23...h4  24.Nh3  Keeping an eye on the g5-pawn.  24...Kg7  25.Qd2  Threatening xg5.  25...Kg6  26.Rf1  With a direct threat of taking twice on g5 followed by Rf6+ ➼ picking up Black's queen. }
24. Nxg4 Bb7 25. Qe3 { Preparing to bring the queen over the kingside. } 25...
Bc8 26. h4 { Undermining the g5-pawn so we can get acces to Black's king. }
26... gxh4 27. Qh6 { Threatening Nf6+! } 27... f5 28. exf6 Bxf6 29. Qg6+ Kh8
30. Nfe5
{ Black resigned because there is no way to deal with Rf1 @@StartBracket@@among other things@@EndBracket@@. }
