1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Bf4 c5 4. e3 Nc6 5. Nbd2 Qb6 6. dxc5 Qxb2 7. Rb1 Qc3 8.
Bb5 { So far this has been super mainstream theory. } 8... Bd7
{ This is a bit of a sideline, but it's occasionally seen both in OTB and in online chess. The main alternatives were 8...e6 and 8...g6 ➼ as explained in the Theory Chapter. }
9. O-O Qxc5 10. c4 a6
{ 10...e6  This is our main focus in the Theory Chapter. } 11. Ba4
{ Creating a very unpleasant threat of Rxb7. } 11... b5
{ Black is trying to sacrifice a pawn in order to avoid immediate disaster, but this still proves to be a difficult if not impossible task.   11...Qa7  Protecting the b7-pawn, but losing control over the center.  12.e4!!  This move is very logical because Black is underdeveloped, so we need to open up the position in order to take advantage of it.  12...dxe4  13.Ng5  Black can't hang on to the e4-pawn for too long.  13...e6  14.Ngxe4  With Nd6+ ideas in the air, Black's king is getting caught in the center with a very promising position for White. }
12. cxb5 axb5 13. Bxb5
{ At this point White has a simple plan to play Qe2 followed by Rfc1 with pressure on the c6-knight. }
13... e5
{ This is an attempt to speed up development.  13...e6  Simple development doesn't work ➼ this is Black's biggest issue.  14.Qe2!  Simple and strong! White is preparing Rfc1.  14...Be7  15.Rfc1  ,  winning the c6-knight. }
14. Bxc6
{ Simple and strong! Black is unable to play 14...exf4 because of 15.Bxa8 with an extra rook for White. }
14... Bxc6 15. Bxe5 Bb5
{ The losing mistake. The position was already very difficult mainly because Black couldn't get a decent position from the opening.   15...Be7  would have been a better try.  16.Nd4!  Threatening Rc1!  16...Bd7  17.Rb7  White keeps a very promising position with Qb1-Rc1 ideas. }
16. Bxf6 { Spoiling Black's structure. } 16... gxf6
{ 16...Bxf1?  This also doesn't help because White has a deadly intermezzo.  17.Bd4!+-  Attacking Black's queen and collecting the f1-bishop on the next move with a winning position. }
17. Re1
{ Just sidestepping Black's threat. There is no need to complicate things. }
17... Bd3
{ At this point Black had other alternatives, but none of them seemed to give any saving chances, so we'll just focus on what happened in the game. }
18. Rc1 { Sidestepping Black's threat and attacking the enemy queen. } 18...
Qb5 19. Nd4 Qd7 20. Qb3
{ Finishing development while gaining a tempo against the d3-bishop. } 20...
Ba6 21. e4
{ Opening up the position against the enemy king which is stuck in the center forced resignation. This is a very good example of how dangerous this line can actually be @@StartBracket@@remember that with the Black pieces we had a very experienced Grandmaster@@EndBracket@@. }
