[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 d5 3. Bf4 e6 4. Nbd2 c5 5. e3 Be7 6. c3 O-O 7. Bd3 Nbd7 8. h4
b6 9. Ne5
{ This is a typical position coming from the ...Be7-lines after White decided to use the h4-plan @@StartBracket@@Qf3-Qh3 is usually a decent alternative@@EndBracket@@. }
9... Nxe5
{ The losing mistake! This is a very common motif because the e5-knight is very annoying, and most players are not aware of White's potential in this structure.   9...Bb7  Black is not forced to take on e5, so this is a solid alternative.  10.Qf3  Controlling the e4-square so Black is unable to play ...e4!  10...Rc8  11.h5  Not really going to push h6 but mainly preparing to play Qg3 without allowing ...Nh5 ideas.  11...h6  12.Qg3  Threatening Bxh6.  12...Kh8  13.Ndf3  Preparing to play Nxd7, followed by Ne5.  13...Ne4  Attacking the g3-queen.  14.Qh3  We can continue with Rd1, O-O followed by Nxd7-Ne5, with a slightly better position for White. }
10. dxe5 { The key way to recapture ➼ attacking the f6-knight. } 10... Nd7 11.
Bxh7+
{ This stunning sacrifice made me fall in love with the London System. This motif is actually very common and easy to execute while still remaining unexpected. The reason why nobody really sees this in advance, is because the standard Greek Gift happens when the knight is on f3, so White typically play with Ng5+ followed by Qh5. Whenever someone says that the ''London System is boring'' they probably haven't seen this game! }
11... Kxh7 12. Qh5+
{ This is important ➼ forcing the enemy king to g8.   12.Nf3??  This would allow Black to escape.  12...Rh8!  13.Ng5+  Kg8-+  There is no way to continue the attack, and Black keeps the extra piece. }
12... Kg8 13. Nf3
{ Creating a deadly threat of Ng5 and the main point is that we can meet ...Bxg5 with hxg5! }
13... f6
{ With the idea to discourage White from playing Ng5.  13...Ba6!  This is a rare case when Black could have actually saved the game after the deadly sacrifice. The point is to meet 14. Ng5 with 14... Bd3!  14.Rd1!  Controlling the d3-square.  14...Re8!  15.Ng5  Threatening Qh7+!  15...Nf8!  After this move, White has nothing better than to go for the perpetual.  16.Qxf7+  Kh8  17.Qh5+=  With a forced draw. }
14. Ng5
{ This stunning move works anyways because opening up the h-file fully compensates for the sacrificed material because we are getting a deadly initiative. }
14... fxg5 15. hxg5
{ Creating a big threat of pushing g6 ➼ taking away the main scape f7-square. }
15... Rf5 { Stopping White from pushing g6. } 16. Qh7+ Kf7
{ 16...Kf8  was also not saving Black.  17.Qg6!  Threatening Rh8#  17...Kg8  18.Rh7  Threatening Qxg7#  18...Bf8  19.Qh5!+-  Threatening h8# because the h5-queen is taking away the f7-square. }
17. g6+ Ke8 18. Qxg7 { Threatening to play Rh8+! } 18... Bf8 19. Qh8
{ At this point White wins with a lot of moves, so we'll just stick to the game. The point of the last move is to make room for the g-pawn to advance. }
19... Rg5
{ 19...Qe7  20.Rh7!+-  With g7 coming on the next move and White has a completely winning position. }
20. Qg8 { Threatening Qf7# } 20... Nxe5 21. Bxe5
{ Eliminating the knight and reinforcing the Qf7 threat. } 21... Kd7 22. Rh8
{ Threatening to push g7. } 22... Bb7 23. Qh7+
{ Black resigned because g7 was coming on the next move with a completely winning position. }
