1. d4 Nf6 2. c3 d5 3. Bf4 e6 4. Nd2 c5 5. e3 Nc6 6. Ngf3 Bd6 7. Bg3 O-O 8. Bd3
Qe7 9. Ne5 cxd4 10. exd4 Nd7
{ This is a common middlegame arising after Black decided to meet Ne5 with ...Nd7 followed by ...f6/f5 ideas. }
11. f4 { Supporting the e5-knight. } 11... f5
{ This is an interesting plan ➼ preparing ... Nf6-Ne4!   11...f6  This was an alternative.  12.Nxd7  Bxd7  13.O-O  With Qf3 followed by Rae1 ➼ White keeps a slightly better position because of the backward e6-pawn. }
12. O-O Nf6 { Preparing to play ...Ne4! } 13. Bh4
{ Activating the bishop because it was restricted by the f4-pawn. } 13... Qc7
14. Qe2
{ This is the perfect square for the queen because it's keeping the d2-protected after Black goes ...Ne4! For this reason we prefer it over 14.Qf3! }
14... Ne4 15. Kh1 { Preparing the g4-break. } 15... Bd7 16. g4 Be8
{ 16...fxg4??  This was losing on the spot.  17.Nxd7!  Qxd7  18.Nxe4  dxe4  19.Qxe4  Threatening Qxh7+!  19...g6  20.Rae1+-  We can continue with Bc4-Bxe6+ ➼ and White has a winning position.   16...Rae8  This was a solid alternative for Black.  17.gxf5  exf5  18.Rg1  I prefer White with the potential of an attack on the g-file.   16...Ne7  Played with the idea to recapture on f5 with the knight.  17.Bxe7!  Bxe7  18.Rg1  We can continue with Rg2-Rag1, and White has good attacking prospects on the kingside. }
17. gxf5 { Opening up the file for the rook. } 17... exf5 18. Rg1
{ Activating the rook. } 18... Be7
{ 18...Nxe5  This move is generally helping us.  19.fxe5  Be7  20.Bxe7  Qxe7  21.Rg2  With Rag1 next and White has good attacking prospects. }
19. Bxe7 Qxe7 20. Rg2
{ Simple chess! White is preparing to double up on the g-file. } 20... Qh4 21.
Rag1 { Threatening Rxg7+! } 21... Bh5
{ The losing mistake.  21...Kh8!  This would have been Black's best try!   The point is that  22.Rxg7  Nf2+!  wins for Black.  22.Qe3  Threatening to play Ndf3.  22...Bh5  23.Be2!  Trading Black's annoying bishop.  23...Bxe2  24.Rxe2  Rae8  25.Reg2  Attacking the g7-pawn.  25...Re7  26.Ndf3  Activating the knight and attacking Black's queen.  26...Qh3  27.Qe2  We can continue with Ng5 next, and White has good attacking chances on the kingside. }
22. Bxe4
{ This stunning move wins on the spot.  22.Rxg7+  Kh8  Black was hoping to reach this position with ...Nf2+ ideas. }
22... fxe4
{ 22...Bxe2  Taking the queen allows a classy mate.  23.Rxg7+  Kh8  24.Rg8+!  Deflecting Black's rook from protecting the f7-square.  24...Rxg8  25.Nf7#  for a nice smothered mate. }
23. Rxg7+ Kh8 24. Qg2 { Threatening Rxh7+ combined with Qg7# } 24... Bg6 25.
Nxg6+ hxg6 26. Rxg6
{ Black resigned because there was no way to stop Rg3-Rh3! } *

[Event "?"]
