[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Kovacevic, Aleksandar vs. Pap, Misa, Valjevo 2018"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. Bf4 c5 4. e3 d5 5. c3 Nc6 6. Nbd2 Bd6 7. Bg3 O-O 8. Bd3
Qe7 9. Ne5 Bxe5 10. dxe5 Nd7 11. f4 f5
{ This is a super common structure which is arising after White plays Ne5 and Black goes .. .Bxe5. }
12. Nf3
{ This is a very decent alternative to our main move. White is preparing to activate the dark squared bishop with Bh4 followed by Rg1-g4.   12.h4!?  This is our main move in the Theory Chapter @@StartBracket@@going for h5 followed by Bh4@@EndBracket@@. }
12... c4 { Attacking the d3-bishop and making room for ...Nc5. } 13. Bc2
{ Keeping the bishop on the critical diagonal ➼ eyeballing the enemy kingisde. }
13... Nc5 14. Bh4 { Activating the bishop and making room for the g-pawn. }
14... Qe8
{ After this move Black can hardly generate any counterplay.  14...Qc7  This was required ➼ playing for ...Qb6 ideas.  15.g4!  This is the most accurate move because 15. Rg1 Qb6! gives Black very decent counterplay.  15...fxg4   15...Qb6  This is no longer effective.  16.gxf5  Qxb2  17.O-O!+-  Threatening fxe6 followed by Ng5 and Black is doomed.  16.Ng5  We can meet  16...h6  with  17.Nh7  and White has good attacking prospects on the kingside. }
15. Rg1
{ This is the key idea that you want to remember while going against the ...f5 structure. White is preparing to break with g4! }
15... b5 16. g4
{ Threatening gxf5 and Black is unable to play ...exf5 because the d5-pawn drops. }
16... Nd3+
{ Trying to make a mess, but Black's position is simply hopeless.  16...Ne4  doesn't help Black either.  17.gxf5  Rxf5  18.Bxe4!  Eliminating the strong knight.  18...dxe4  19.Bf6!  Creating a deadly threat of Rxg7+!  19...g6  20.Nh4+-  Winning the exchange. }
17. Bxd3 cxd3 18. gxf5
{ The most precise, even though White had many promising moves. } 18... Rxf5
19. Bf6 { Threatening Rxg7+! There is no need to rush with Qxd3. } 19... g6 20.
Nh4 { Winning the exchange. } 20... Na5 21. Qxd3
{ Collecting the rook was also fine, but there is no rush. } 21... Nc4
{ 21...Rh5  leads to a mating attack.  22.Nxg6!  hxg6  23.Rxg6+  Kf8  24.O-O-O+-  With Rdg1 next and Black is getting mated on the g-file.   21...Bb7  This also doesn't save Black.  22.Nxf5  exf5  23.h4+-  White is winning with the extra exchange and a deadly attack. }
22. Nxf5 exf5 23. Qxd5+ Be6 24. Qb7 { Threatening Qg7# } 24... Bf7 25. e6
{ The final touch. White is winning a piece because  25...Qxe6  allows  26.Qxa8+  and  25...Bxe6  26.Qg7  is leading to a checkmate, so Black had to resign. This was simply a beautiful display of White's main idea in the typical structure arising after ...Bxe5 dxe5. What makes it even more impressive is that with the Black pieces we had an experienced Grandmaster which was completely defenceless against White's simple and powerful ideas. }
