1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 e6 3. e3 f5 4. c4 Nf6 5. Nc3 Bd6 6. Bxd6 Qxd6 7. Nf3 O-O 8. Bd3
c6 9. O-O Ne4 10. Qb3 Kh8 11. a4 Nd7 12. a5 Rb8
{ This is a typical position coming from the Stonewall variation of the Dutch Defense. }
13. Qa3
{ The endgames are favourable for White because without queens, Black is unable to generate the typical kingside play. }
13... Ndf6 14. Ne5 { Centralizing the knight. } 14... Qxa3
{ Black doesn't have much of a choice. } 15. Rxa3 Nd6 16. Rb3
{ Creating a direct threat of Nxc6! ➼ exploiting the pin along the b-file. }
16... dxc4
{ 16...Ra8  17.cxd5  exd5  18.a6  After this move, White is much better with a simple plan to go axb7, followed by Na4-Nc5, and Black has issues with the c6-pawn.   16...Bd7  17.c5  Attacking the d6-knight and Black has no good retreating square.  17...Nf7  18.a6+-  White wins because  18...bxa6  19.Rxb8  Rxb8  20.Nxf7+  wins a piece. }
17. Bxc4 { Threatening Na4-Nc5. } 17... Nxc4 18. Nxc4
{ White has a simple plan ➼ Na4-Nc5 with pressure on the queenside. } 18... b6
{ Black is setting up a clever trap.  18...Bd7  This doesn't really help.  19.Na4!  Threatening to play Nc5!  19...Ne4  20.Nc5  Attacking the d7-bishop.  20...Nxc5  21.dxc5  Be8  22.Rd1+-  We can continue with Rd6, followed by Ne5-f4, and Black's position is very passive. }
19. Ne5
{ White is of course well aware of Black's counterplay and avoids it!  19.axb6?!  This would let most of the advantage slip away.  19...Ba6!  Activating the bad bishop and pinning the knight.  20.Rb4  axb6  Threatening to play ...Nd5!  21.Ra1  Attacking the a6-bishop.  21...Bxc4  22.Rxc4  c5!=  Black is very close to equal. }
19... c5 20. dxc5 Ba6 { Attacking the f1-rook. } 21. Rd1
{ Occupying the open file. } 21... bxc5 22. Rxb8 Rxb8 23. Rd6
{ Attacking both the a6-bishop and the e6-pawn. } 23... Bb7 24. Rxe6
{ Collecting the free pawn. Black was unable to protect it with 24...Bc8 because of 25.Rd8+! }
24... h6 25. f3 { Shutting down Black's bishop. } 25... Bd5 26. Rd6
{ Attacking the d5-bishop. } 26... Bg8 27. Rc6 { Threatening Rxc5. } 27... Rxb2
28. Rxc5 Rc2
{ Black could have defended better, but the positional would have been lost regardless. }
29. Ne4 { Forcing a winning endgame. } 29... Rxc5 30. Nxc5
{ The rest is simple because with an extra pawn, White has an easy win. } 30...
Bd5 31. Kf2 { Activating the king. } 31... Kg8 32. Ke2 Kf8 33. Kd3 Ke7 34. Kd4
Kd6 35. Ncd3 Ne8 36. Nb4 { Attacking the d5-bishop. } 36... Bb7 37. Nc4+
{ After this move White is able to infiltrate. } 37... Ke6 38. Nd3
{ Threatening Nc5+ } 38... Ba8 39. Nf4+ Kf6 40. Nd5+ Ke6 41. e4
{ Supporting the d5-knight. } 41... g5 42. Kc5 Kd7
{ Black blundered the pawn, but the position was losing anyway.  42...fxe4  43.fxe4  Bb7  44.Nc3+-  With Kd4 followed by Na4-Nc5 ➼ White has a comfortable win. }
43. exf5
{ Black resigned because there is no hope left ➼ being down two pawns. } *

