1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 Nf6 3. e3 Bf5 4. Bd3 Bxd3 5. cxd3 e6 6. Qb3 Qc8 7. Nc3 c6 8.
Rc1 Na6 9. Nf3 Be7 10. O-O O-O
{ This is a common position arising from the ...Bf5-lines @@StartBracket@@usually seen from the ''CopyCat/Slav Defense@@EndBracket@@. }
11. e4
{ After this move White is simply slightly better thanks to the extra space in the center. }
11... Nb4 { Attacking the d3-pawn. } 12. Qd1
{ Protecting the d3-pawn and preparing to get rid of the enemy b4-knight by pushing a3. }
12... dxe4
{ This is definitely something that we are glad to see.  12...a5  This would have been a small improvement for Black ➼ keeping the tension.  13.a3  Na6  14.e5  Grabbing space and attacking the f6-knight.  14...Nd7  15.h4  We can continue with g3-Kg2-Rh1, followed by h5 to press on the kingside. }
13. dxe4
{ This is how the ideal center looks after we manage to undouble the pawns. }
13... Qd8 14. Qe2 { Developing the queen and preparing Rfd1. } 14... Qa5 15. a3
{ Attacking the b4-knight. } 15... Na6 16. Ne5
{ Activating the knight and introducing Nc4 ideas. } 16... Nb8
{ Preparing to bring the knight back in the game with ...Nbd7! } 17. b4
{ This is an interesting pawn sacrifice.  17.Nc4!  This would have been the same, except we don't allow Black to grab the a3-pawn.  17...Qd8  18.b4  Transposing to the game. }
17... Qd8
{ The ''safer'' choice.  17...Qxa3  Black could have grabbed the pawn, but it looks incredibly risky.  18.Nc4  Qxb4  19.Bd2  With Nd5/Rb1 ideas, White's position looks very promising. }
18. Nc4
{ Not allowing any counterplay!  18.Rfd1?!  This would have given Black a chance for counterplay.  18...a5!  With some hopes for activity. }
18... Ne8
{ Hard to suggest anything else since Black's position is already difficult.  18...Qxd4??  19.Rfd1+-  Trapping Black's queen.   18...Nbd7  This would have been a better try.  19.Na5!  Attacking the b7-pawn.  19...Qc8  20.d5!  With a much better position for White because Black lacks coordination. }
19. Rfd1
{ Threatening to push d5! ➼ White's play is very simple and effective. } 19...
Nd6 20. Bxd6 Bxd6 21. d5
{ After this move Black is simply getting stomped on the d-file. } 21... exd5
22. exd5 { Threatening dxc6! } 22... Qc7 23. Nxd6
{ The simplest! ➼ luring Black's queen on a mined square. } 23... Qxd6 24. dxc6
{ Attacking the enemy queen. } 24... Qxc6 25. Nd5 Qh6 26. Nc7
{ Winning the exchange! The rest is simple. } 26... Nc6 27. Nxa8 Rxa8 28. Qe3
Qh5 29. Qc5 Qh4 30. b5 Nd8 31. Qd4 Qg5 32. h4 Qe7 33. Qd7 Qf8 34. Rc8
{ Forcing a winning endgame, so Black decided to resign. } *

