1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 c5 3. c3 b6 4. Bf4 Bb7 5. e3 e6 6. h3 Be7 7. Bd3 O-O 8. O-O
Nc6 9. Qe2 Rc8 10. Nbd2 d6 11. Rad1 Qc7 12. Bg3 Rfd8 13. Rfe1 g6 14. a3 Nb8 15.
e4 cxd4 16. cxd4 Nbd7
{ This is a typical middlegame arising from the Queen's Indian Defense. White has a slightly better position with the extra space, but it's not easy at all to make progress because Black's position is very compact in this ''Hedgehog structure''. The key in these positions is not to rush and maneuver around with patience. }
17. Nb1
{ Preparing to play Nc3 ➼ improving the knight. This is a typical maneuver that you can use to fulfill the potential of your knight. }
17... Qb8 18. Nc3 Qa8 19. Bf4
{ Improving the bishop, but 19.Bh4 would have been perfectly fine too. } 19...
a6 20. Bg5 { Pinning the knight and introducing e5 ideas. } 20... Kg7 21. Qe3
{ Threatening to push e5. } 21... Ng8
{ Avoiding e5.  21...b5  22.e5!  Taking space and attacking the f6-knight.  22...dxe5  23.dxe5  Ng8  24.Bxe7  Nxe7  25.Be4!  This move is extremely important ➼ trading Black's powerful bishop. White has a free hand on the kingside, with pressure against the enemy king. }
22. Bxe7 Nxe7 23. Ne2
{ Bringing the knight over the kingside. This is a typical maneuver when we have the strong center of pawns. }
23... h6 24. Ng3 Qb8 25. h4
{ Threatening to push h5! This is the key idea to make progress on the kingside. }
25... h5
{ 25...b5  26.h5!  Threatening hxg6.  26...g5  This move usually allows the thematic piece sacrifice on g5.   26...Rf8  27.Bb1!  This is a powerful regrouping ➼ preparing to play Ba2 and then threatening to play hxg6 because the e6-pawn is vulnerable.  27.Nxg5!  hxg5  28.Qxg5+  Forcing ...Kf8 because the e7-knight is under attack.  28...Kf8  29.h6+-  White is completely winning because  29...Ng6  runs into  30.e5! }
26. Qg5 { Attacking the e7-knight and threatening Nxh5+! } 26... Nf6
{ 26...Kf8  doesn't help Black.  27.Qh6+  Kg8  28.Ng5  Threatening h7+!  28...Nf8  29.e5!+-  Threatening xh5! with a winning attack. }
27. e5 { Removing the f6-knight so we can collect the h5-pawn. } 27... dxe5 28.
dxe5 Nfg8 29. Nxh5+ { Collecting the free pawn. } 29... Kf8 30. Nf6
{ With a completely winning position for White! The rest is simple, and not really relevant for our topic ➼ so I will leave the rest without annotations. }
30... Bxf3 31. gxf3 Rd4 32. h5 Rcd8 33. Be2 Rxd1 34. Bxd1 gxh5 35. Nh7+ Ke8 36.
Qg7 Qc7 37. Nf6+ Nxf6 38. exf6 b5 39. fxe7 Qxe7 40. Bc2
{ With the extra piece for White, Black's position is hopeless. } 40... Rd5 41.
Qg8+ Kd7 42. Rd1 Rxd1+ 43. Bxd1 Qf6 44. Kg2 Ke7 45. b4 h4 46. Qg4 Qh6 47. Kh3
Qc1 48. Qxh4+ Ke8 49. Qh8+ Ke7 50. Qh4+ Ke8 51. Qd4 Qxa3 52. Be2 *

