[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 d5 3. Bf4 c5 4. e3 Nc6 5. Nbd2 Qb6 6. dxc5 Qxb2 7. Rb1 Qc3 8.
Bb5 e6 9. O-O
{ This is a typical position arising from the complex 5. Nbd2 Qb6 6.dxc5! line. }
9... Qxc5
{ This is less precise than the main move, but quite common for both OTB and online chess.  9...Be7  is the main move.  10.e4!  With interesting play for White after the Alpha Zero pawn sacrifice ➼ as explained in the Theory Chapter. }
10. c4
{ Immediately seizing the initiative. We are down a pawn, but we have a small lead in development so we need to act quick ➼ otherwise Black will have time to coordinate. }
10... Be7 11. Nb3 Qa3
{ This is the only reasonable square for the queen.  11...Qb4??  loses on the spot.  12.a3!  Qxa3  13.Ra1!  This is really strong because 13... Qb2 allows 14. Be5! ➼ trapping Black's queen.  13...Qb4  14.Ra4+-  Winning Black's queen.   11...Qb6  12.Nbd4!  Threatening Bxc6+ and Black's queen is vulnerable.  12...Qc5  13.cxd5  Opening up the c-file in order to play c1.  13...Nxd5  14.Rc1  Attacking the queen and introducing Rxc6 ideas!  14...Qb6   14...Nc3  This looks active, but the knight is lacking support on this square.  15.Qd3+-  White is picking up the c3-knight next.  15.Rxc6!  This trick wins a piece.  15...bxc6  16.Bxc6++-  Collecting the a8-rook next, with a winning position for White. }
12. Ne5
{ Threatening Nxc6.  12.Nbd4!  This would have been even more precise! } 12...
a6
{ 12...O-O!!  This could be an interesting line for Black but quite risky.  13.Nxc6  bxc6  14.Bxc6  Trapping the a8-rook.  14...Ba6!  This is important.  15.Bxa8  Rxa8  16.Qc2  The computer evaluates this position as close to equal, but it seems pretty tricky to play for Black. White managed to win in the game between Sturt, R - Valderrama Quiceno, E Sitges 2019. }
13. Bxc6+ bxc6 14. Nxc6
{ White sticks to simple and natural moves.  14.Nd4!  This would have been even more precise, but what White played in the game is also fine. }
14... Bd7 { Attacking the c6-knight. } 15. Nxe7 Qxe7
{ Threatening to push ...e5! } 16. Be5
{ Stopping Black from pushing ...e5 and also threatening Bxf6 followed by cxd5 ➼ winning a pawn. }
16... O-O
{ 16...dxc4??  This would have been a major mistake.  17.Bd6!  Qd8  18.Nc5+-  Threatening Nb7 followed by Ba3 with d6+ and Black is lost with the king stuck in the center. }
17. cxd5 Nxd5
{ This is the decisive mistake because it drops the exchange.  17...exd5!  This was required with a slightly better endgame for White.  18.Qd4  Threatening Bxf6!  18...Bf5  Attacking the b1-rook.  19.Rbc1  Rfc8  20.Bxf6  Qxf6  21.Rxc8+!  This is played with the idea of exchanging everything on the c-file.  21...Rxc8  22.Qxf6  Ruining Black's pawn structure.  22...gxf6  23.Rc1!  Forcing a better knight vs. bishop endgame because Black's pawn structure is compromised. }
18. e4
{ Forcing Black's knight to move away so we can play Bd6 ➼ winning the exchange. }
18... f6
{ 18...Nf6  19.Bd6+-  Winning the exchange.   18...Bb5  Attacking the f1-rook.  19.Re1  f6  20.Bd4!  This is important because we need to control the c3-square so Black doesn't fork us with ...Nc3 while also keeping ideas to play Bc5 ➼ winning the exchange.  20...Nf4  21.Bc5+-  Picking up the exchange on the next move. }
19. Bd4
{ Keeping the c3-square under control and threatening to win the exchange with Bc5. }
19... Nf4 20. Bc5 { Winning the exchange. } 20... Qf7 21. Bxf8 Rxf8
{ Threatening to play ...Bb5 followed by ...Nd3 with annoying counterplay. }
22. Re1 { Defending in advance against ...Bb5! } 22... e5 23. Nc5
{ Attacking the d7-bishop. } 23... Bh3 { Setting up a small trap. } 24. Rb7
{ White has everything under control.  24.gxh3??  Qg6+  25.Qg4  Nxh3+-+  Winning the queen. }
24... Qxa2
{ 24...Qg6  25.Qb3+!  This is the key idea to bring the queen over to the kingside.  25...Kh8  26.Qg3!+-  Forcing queens off with a winning position for White thanks to the extra exchange. }
25. gxh3 Nxh3+ 26. Kg2 Nf4+ 27. Kh1
{ The king is safe on this square, and we don't care about the f2-pawn. } 27...
Qxf2 28. Qb3+ { The key idea to bring the queen over into defense. } 28... Kh8
29. Qg3 { Forcing queens off with an extra rook, so Black had to resign. } *

