1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 Nf6 3. e3 c5 4. Nf3 Nc6 5. Nbd2 Qb6 6. dxc5 Qxb2 7. Rb1 Qc3 8.
Bb5 e6 9. O-O Qxc5 10. c4
{ This is a typical position coming from the complex 5.Nbd2 Qb6 6.dxc5! lines. We have a common case where Black did not go for the main line with 9...Be7 and went for the common inaccurate line with 9.. .Qxc5. }
10... Bd7
{ Breaking the pin ➼ this is meant against our Nb3 followed by Ne5 plan @@StartBracket@@which happened in Naiditch-Wells, 2017@@EndBracket@@. The problem with this line in general, is that it weakens the b7-pawn.   10...Be7  This was featured in the other model game between Naiditsch-Wells, 2017. }
11. Ba4 { Targeting the b7-pawn. } 11... Nd8 12. Ne5
{ Putting pressure on the d7-bishop. } 12... Be7
{ 12...Bxa4  This would have been a better try, but still much worse for Black.  13.Qxa4+  b5!  This is an important resource, not to resign immediately.  14.cxb5  Qa3  15.Qc2!  With even material, but an important lead in development for White. }
13. Ne4
{ According to the computer this is a huge mistake because it's missing a large advantage if Black defends properly. However I decided to mark it as interesting because the idea is quite unique, and I think Black's defensive task is quite difficult @@StartBracket@@as a result, Black failed to spot it@@EndBracket@@.   13.Nxd7!  Simpler and stronger.  13...Nxd7  14.cxd5  exd5  15.Nf3+-  With a winning position for White because Black's king is stuck in the center. }
13... Nxe4
{ Missing the chance to fight back.  13...Bxa4!  14.Qxa4+  b5!!  This was probably missed by White. This would have been the only move to hold for Black.  15.Rxb5  Qa3!  White is still slightly better, but Black is back in the game. }
14. Nxd7 { Attacking the c5-queen and threatening a nasty discovery. } 14...
Qa3 15. Nf6+
{ Eliminating Black's e4-knight so there will be no ...Nc3 ideas.   15.Nb6+  This was a solid alternative, picking up the exchange.  15...Kf8  16.Nxa8  Nc3  17.Qc2+-  With a winning position for White. }
15... Kf8 16. Nxe4 dxe4 17. Qd7 { Threatening Qe8# } 17... g5 18. Be5
{ Black resigned here. To be honest it feels a bit early, but White was simply winning with slow play. I will add some sample lines to prove it. }
18... f6 19. Bb2
{ After this move Black has a choice between ... Qd6 and ...Qc5. } 19... Qc5
{ 19...Qd6  This loses the pawn.  20.Qxd6  Bxd6  21.Bxf6  Collecting the free pawn.  21...Rg8  22.f3  With a deadly attack despite the fact that there are no queens on the board and White is also threatening Bxd8 followed by Rxb7 ideas. }
20. Bd4 { Improving the bishop with tempo. } 20... Qa3 21. f4
{ With a decisive attack for White after opening up the f-file. } *

