[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 Nf6 3. e3 c5 4. Nf3 Nc6 5. Nbd2 e6 6. c3 Bd6 7. Bg3 O-O 8. Bd3
b6 9. Qe2 Bb7 10. Rd1 Re8 11. e4 Be7 12. e5 Nh5
{ This is a theoretical position coming from the ...Bd6 main line. } 13. a3
{ This could be an alternative to our main line, together with 13.O-O!? What I really like about the London System in general, is that often times we have a variety of options and you can pick the one that suits you better.   13.O-O!?  This was featured in another model game between Sedlak-Szabo 2018.   13.h4!  This is our main move ➼ as explained in the Theory Chapter. }
13... c4
{ This is an inaccuracy, but I find this type of idea really common for club level players @@StartBracket@@despite having a strong Grandmaster with the Black pieces@@EndBracket@@.   13...g6  This is the main move, but we are not going to dive into a theoretical discussion since this is not our main line. The goal of this game is to get familiar with the typical plans and maneuvers. }
14. Bb1 g6
{ Restricting the b1-bishop and making a square for the knight on g7. } 15. Nf1
{ Going for the standard maneuver with Nf1-Ne3-Ng4!  15.h4!?  This was an alternative, similar to our main lines. }
15... b5
{ While White is pressing on the kingside ➼ Black is trying to organize counterplay with ...a5-b4! }
16. Ne3 { Preparing to play Ng4. } 16... a5 17. Ng4 b4 18. Qe3
{ Preparing Qh6 ideas, or the typical Bf4-Bg5. } 18... bxc3 19. bxc3 Rb8
{ 19...Bxa3?  This also doesn't help Black.  20.Bh4  Activating the bishop and attacking Black's queen.  20...Qc7  21.Nh6+  Kf8  22.g4!  Attacking the h5-knight.  22...Ng7  23.Bf6+-  With Ng5 coming on the next move ➼ White has a mating attack. }
20. Bf4
{ Preparing to play Bg5 ➼ trading the dark squared bishops so we can attack Black on the kingside. }
20... Bc8
{ 20...Nxf4  This would have made it easier for White to advance the h-pawn.  21.Qxf4  Rf8  22.h4  Threatening to push h5 on the next move ➼ with good attacking prospects on the kingside. }
21. Bg5
{ Trading off the dark squared bishops. This is a typical idea to weaken the enemy kingside after Black has commited with ...g6! }
21... Rb3
{ This natural move turns out to be the losing mistake.  21...f6  Good or bad, this had to be played.  22.exf6  Nxf6  23.Nh6+  Kg7  24.h4  We can play Bxf6, followed by Ng4-Nge5, with good control over the center and pressure against the enemy king. }
22. h4 { Threatening to play Nh6+ followed by g4! } 22... Qb6 23. Bc2
{ Threatening to win the exchange. } 23... Rxa3
{ 23...Rb2  24.Ba4+-  With Nh6+, followed by g4 with a big initiative. } 24.
Bxe7 Nxe7
{ 24...Rxe7  25.Qh6+-  With a winning position because Nf6+ is coming next. }
25. Qh6 { Creating a deadly threat of Nf6+! } 25... Nf5 26. Bxf5
{ Eliminating the annoying knight. } 26... exf5 27. Ng5
{ Threatening Qxh7 followed by mate. } 27... Nf6 28. Ne3
{ This is the most precise ➼ breaking the pin @@StartBracket@@threatening exf6@@EndBracket@@ while also threatening Nxd5 which is deflecting Black's knight form defending the h7-square.   28.Nxf6+?!  This would have been pretty unclear.  28...Qxf6  I couldn't find an obvious way to continue here. }
28... f4 29. Nxd5
{ Using a small trick because Black is unable to capture back the d5-knight. }
29... Qd8 30. O-O
{ The classiest finish I've ever seen. Black resigned because we are going to elimiante the f6-knight with checkmate to follow. }
*

