1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 d5 3. c3 e6 4. Bf4 Bd6 5. e3 O-O 6. Nbd2 Bxf4 7. exf4 b6 8. h4
c5 9. h5 Qd6 10. h6 g6 11. g3 a5 12. a3 Nc6 13. Bd3 Ba6 14. Qe2 Bxd3 15. Qxd3
{ This is a typical position for the modern ''Berkes structure''. } 15... cxd4
{ This move feels like an inaccuracy to me, even though the engine is somewhat indifferent. I feel like White is getting additional ideas to use the d4-square for the queen ➼ with good attacking prospects on the kingside.   15...c4  This might have given Black more chances for counterplay.  16.Qe2  b5  Taking space on the queenside and preparing the ...b4-break!  17.Kf1!  After this typical move, we are going to play Kg2, followed by Ne5 with a4 ideas. The position remains close to equal, but White always keeps good attacking prospects on the kingside thanks to the h6-pawn. }
16. Nxd4 Ne7
{ Preparing to play ...Nf5.  16...Rac8  This was an alternative.  17.Nxc6!  Qxc6  18.Qd4  White has very annoying pressure on the kingside.   16...Nd7  17.N2f3  Nc5  Attacking the d3-queen.  18.Qe3!  This is important so we can meet ...Nxd4 with Qxd4!  18...Rfe8  19.Kf1  With Kg2 on the next move ➼ White keeps a slightly better position with Nxc6, followed by Qd4 ideas. }
17. Kf1
{ This move works much better than O-O because the h1-rook is already useful ➼ protecting the h6-pawn.   17.O-O?!  After this move, the h6-pawn becomes a target!  17...Ng4!  Winning the h6-pawn. }
17... Nf5 18. Nxf5 exf5
{ The only reasonable way to recapture.  18...gxf5  This would have been too weakening.  19.Qd4  Attacking the f6-knight.  19...Ne8  20.Rg1  We are going to break with g4 next ➼ and White has a powerful initiative on the kingside. }
19. Qd4 { Centralizing the queen, and keeping an eye on the g7-square. } 19...
b5
{ This is the losing mistake. Black was mainly afraid of Nc4 ideas I think.  19...Rfe8  This would have been a better try but still leading to a worse position.  20.Nc4!  Taking advantage of the pin! White is attacking both the d6-queen and the b6-pawn.  20...Qe6  21.Ne5!  The most precise ➼ creating a huge threat of Nd7!   21.Nxb6?  This was a tempting alternative, but Black could take over the initiative with precise play.  21...Ra6!  22.Na4  Qe2+  23.Kg2  Re4!  Black is getting very active.  21...Rac8?  This is a natural move ➼ placing the rook on the semi-open file.   21...Ne4!  Avoiding the immediate disaster with Nd7.  22.Kg2  f6  23.Nf3  We can continue with Rad1 next ➼ and White has pressure against the isolated d5-pawn.  22.Nd7!!  This is a typical tactic ➼ made possible by the h6-pawn.  22...Nxd7  23.Qg7   22...Qxd7  23.Qxf6+- }
20. g4
{ Nihal doesn't miss such opportunities ➼ which makes him one of the deadliest London System players of all time! }
20... Rfd8
{ 20...fxg4  This would have allowed a stunning motif.  21.Ne4!!+-  This wins on the spot because Black is pinned everywhere.  21...dxe4   21...Nxe4  22.Qg7#  With a typical checkmate.  22.Qxd6+-  Winning the queen.   20...Nxg4  21.Qg7  With a standard checkmate thanks to the h6-pawn. }
21. gxf5
{ Going for the simple approach because Black is unable to win back the pawn.  21.g5!  This would have been even more precise according to the computer ➼ going for the squeeze.  21...Ne8  22.Re1  Creating a direct threat of Rxe8+, followed by Qg7#  22...Qf8  23.Rh3+-  With an easy win for White because Black is very passive. We can continue with Rhe3-Re7, followed by Nb3-Nc5. }
21... Ra6
{ Protecting the sixth rank.  21...gxf5  22.Re1+-  With Re5-Rxf5 ideas ➼ White has a winning position.   22.fxg6  fxg6   22...hxg6  This would have been a better defense.  23.Nf3  However, White keeps a much better position with Ng5 ideas. }
22. fxg6 fxg6 23. Re1 { Activating the rook. } 23... Qf8
{ 23...b4!?  This could have been a better try ➼ looking for active counterplay on the queenside.  24.Nf3!  Focusing on the kingside with Ng5 ideas.  24...bxa3  25.bxa3  Rc8   25...Qxa3?  26.Ng5+-  With Ne6 next, White has a winning position.  26.f5!  With excellent attacking prospects on the kingside. }
24. Nf3 { Preparing to play Ng5 followed by Ne6! } 24... Nh5 25. Ng5
{ Threatening to play Rxh5 followed by Ne6! } 25... Nxf4
{ 25...Qxf4  The endgames are also hopeless for Black.  26.Qxf4  Nxf4  27.Re7+-  With Rg7+ next and White is collecting the important h7-pawn. }
26. Rh4 { Attacking the f4-knight. } 26... Nh5
{ 26...Rf6  This would've lost to a brilliant move.  27.Qa7!!+-  Black is defenseless against Qxh7! }
27. Rxh5
{ Very precise! Avoiding Black's counterplay.  27.Ne6?  This would have allowed Black to fight back.  27...Ng3+  28.Kg2  Nf5  With a messy position. }
27... gxh5 28. Ne6 { Attacking both the d8-rook and the f8-queen. } 28... Rxe6
29. Rxe6 Qf7 30. Qe3 { The rest is simple because Black's king is too weak. }
30... Rf8 31. Re7 Qf4 32. Rg7+ Kh8 33. Qxf4
{ Going for a winning rook endgame. } 33... Rxf4 34. Rb7
{ Attacking the b5-pawn and threatening Rb8# } 34... Kg8 35. Rxb5 d4 36. cxd4
a4 37. Rxh5 Rxd4 38. Rg5+
{ With two extra pawns, White has an easily winning endgame mainly because Black's king is unable to enter the game. This is why Black resigned in this position. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Malakhatko, Vadim vs. Meyssonnier, Patrick, Corsica Rapid 2008"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nc6 2. Nf3 d5 3. Bf4 Bf5 4. e3 e6 5. c4 Nf6 6. Nc3 Bd6 7. Bg5 Be7 8. Rc1
O-O 9. a3 Ne4 10. Bf4 a6 11. cxd5 exd5 12. Be2 Be6 13. O-O Bd6
{ This is a typical structure arising from the Chigorin Defense/Ragozin @@StartBracket@@via transposition@@EndBracket@@. }
14. Bxd6
{ The idea was right, but the execution was a bit inaccurate.  14.Nxe4!  This would have been the most precise!  14...dxe4  15.Bxd6!  exf3   15...Qxd6  16.Nd2  Transposing to the game.  16.Bxf3  Qxd6  17.d5!  Regaining the piece with a better position. }
14... Qxd6
{ This is natural, but allows White to get what they wanted.  14...Nxd6!  This would have given Black better chances to get a reasonable position. The plan is to go ...Ne7 followed by ...c6 with a solid game. }
15. Nxe4 { Creating a weak pawn for Black. } 15... dxe4 16. Nd2
{ Attacking the weak e4-pawn.  16.Ng5!?  This was a solid alternative but more complicated. }
16... f5 17. Qc2
{ Preparing to play Nb3 without allowing ...b6 ➼ because the c6-knight is under attack.   17.Bc4!  This would have been even more precise.  17...Nd8  18.Bxe6+  Nxe6  19.Qb3  Attacking the b7-pawn.  19...b6  20.Rc2  With Rfc1 next and White has pressure on the c-file. }
17... Rac8 18. Nb3
{ Preparing to play Nc5 ➼ putting pressure on the queenside. } 18... Ne7 19.
Nc5 { Attacking the b7-pawn. } 19... Bd5
{ Centralizing the bishop and protecting the b7-pawn.  19...b5  20.a4!  Black has problems holding everything together because  20...c6  allows  21.Nxa6! }
20. Bc4 { Creating a direct threat of Nxb7 because the d5-bishop is pinned. }
20... Qc6
{ 20...Rb8!  This would have been the best defense ➼ avoiding any additional weaknesses.  21.f3!  Opening up the f-file. This is one of the key pawn breaks against the e4-pawn in the Ragozin structure.  21...exf3  22.Rxf3  c6  23.Rcf1  With pressure on the f-file even though Black's position remains pretty solid. }
21. Qb3 { Threatening Qxb7! After this move Black is losing a pawn by force. }
21... b5
{ Losing the a6-pawn, but the position was already difficult.  21...Rb8  This would be the desired move, but it's simply not working.  22.Bxd5+  Qxd5   22...Nxd5  23.Nxe4+-  Collecting the free pawn.  23.Qxd5+  Nxd5  24.Nd7+-  Winning the exchange.   21...Bxc4  22.Rxc4  Qd5  23.Rc3!  After this precise move, Black is unable to protect the b7-pawn. The main issue is that whenever they try to push ...b6 ➼ the a6-pawn drops. }
22. Bxd5+ Qxd5
{ 22...Nxd5  23.Nxe4!+-  This simply wins for White because of the discovery against Black's queen. }
23. Qxd5+ Nxd5 24. Nxa6
{ White should be objectively winning with the extra pawn and pressure on the c-file. }
24... Rf6 25. Nb4
{ I think this is a good decision because we are eliminating Black's active knight. }
25... Nxb4 26. axb4 { Preparing to play Rc5. } 26... Ra6
{ Not the most resilient defense, but the endgame was probably lost already.  26...c6  This would have been more stubborn.  27.Rc3!  Played with the idea of meeting...Ra8 with Ra3!  27...Ra8  28.Ra3!+-  After this move, White is in full control ➼ with a winning rook endgame. }
27. Rc5 { Attacking both the b5 and the f5-pawns. } 27... Ra2 28. Rxf5
{ This is important so that we can collect the b5-pawn while defending our b4-pawn. }
28... Rxb2 29. Rxb5 { Just in time to protect b4. } 29... Ra8 30. g4
{ This is a nice techinal move, making a luft and grabbing space on the kingside. }
30... Ra4 31. Rc1 { Attacking the c7-pawn. } 31... Raxb4
{ 31...Raa2  32.Rf5+-  This is generally the way to stop Black's counterplay, even though in this particular case, White could have gone for  32.Rb8+  with a forced mate. }
32. Rxb4 Rxb4 33. Rxc7
{ Black resigned because being down two was already too much @@StartBracket@@while White was going to win the e4-pawn soon as well@@EndBracket@@. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Landa, Konstantin vs. Balducchi, Francois, Ajaccio Blitz 2007"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3 Nc6 2. d4 d5 3. Bf4 Nf6 4. e3 Bf5 5. Bb5
{ This is a very common position for games below 1500 blitz @@StartBracket@@on chess.com@@EndBracket@@. This has been covered in great depth in the ''Chigorin Defense'' chapter. }
5... Bd7
{ This move is not common at all ➼ after Black develops with ...Bf5! @@StartBracket@@aprox 1/10 games you will face this move@@EndBracket@@. }
6. O-O e6 7. c4
{ This is the way to go because the Ne5 plan was no longer a choice. Usually we play with c3 and Ne5, but when that is not effective, usually pushing more aggressive on the queenside with c4 is a solid alternative. }
7... a6
{ 7...dxc4  8.Bxc4  With a typical Ragozin structure, but Black's bishop is passive on d7. }
8. Bxc6 { This is usually the way to go after having played Bb5. } 8... Bxc6 9.
Ne5
{ This is the key move to get an advantage. White has a big positional threat of playing Nxc6 ➼ ruining Black's pawn structure. }
9... Bd6
{ 9...Bd7  Avoiding the doubled pawns but losing a lot of time.  10.Nc3  Be7  11.Qf3!  Attacking the d5-pawn.  11...c6  12.c5  White is pushing on the queenside in the typical fashion with b4-a4 followed by Rab1-b5! }
10. Nxc6 bxc6 11. Bg5
{ This is by far the best mainly because the alternatives are not great. White has a direct threat of playing Qa4!  11.Bxd6?!  This would have been a pretty big inaccuracy.  11...cxd6=  All of a sudden Black's pawns are very compact, controlling the critical e5/c5 squares.   11.Bg3!?  This was playable but softer. }
11... Be7 12. Nc3 O-O 13. Qc2
{ This is a fine positional move.  13.Qa4!?  This would have been even more aggressive. }
13... Rb8 14. Rfd1 { Bringing the rook on central file. } 14... h6
{ 14...dxc4  15.Bxf6  Bxf6  16.Na4  With Rac1 followed by Qxc4 ➼ White is regaining the pawn while keeping a better pawn structure. }
15. Bxf6
{ Keeping the tension with 15. Bh4 was also fine, but I like White's approach. The plan is to put pressure on the c-file. }
15... Bxf6 16. cxd5 { 16.Rac1!  would have been slightly more precise. } 16...
cxd5 17. Na4 { Controlling the c5-square and preparing to play Rac1. } 17...
Qd7 18. Rac1 { Attacking the c7-pawn and threatening to play Qc6. } 18... Rfc8
19. Qc6 { This is the key move to force a much better endgame! } 19... Qxc6
{ 19...Qd6! This would have been more resilient. 20.Rc5  With Rdc1 next, White keeps a slightly better position thanks to the queenside pressure. }
20. Rxc6 { Attacking the a6-pawn. } 20... a5 21. Rdc1 { Threatening Rxc7! }
21... Rb7 22. b3
{ Solidifying the queenside.  22.Ra6!?  This was a solid alternative, avoiding ...Ra7 ideas. }
22... Be7
{ 22...Ra7  This would have been more stubborn ➼ stopping Ra6 ideas.  23.g4!  White can continue with Kg2, followed by f4-f5 with pressure on the e6-pawn. }
23. Ra6
{ Here Black resigned/lost on time, but the position was very difficult already. I will attach a sample line to illustrate Black's problems. }
23... Bb4 { Protecting the a5-pawn. } 24. Rcc6 { Threatening to play Nc5. }
24... Rb5 25. Kf1 { Bringing the king closer to the center. } 25... Kh7 26. Nc5
{ There is no way for Black to stop Ra7 ➼ winning the c7-pawn. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Kravtsiv, Martyn vs. Mchedlishvili, Mikheil, Turkey 2019"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4 d5 3. e3 c5 4. Nf3 Nc6 5. Nbd2 Bg4 6. c3 e6 7. Qb3 Qc8 8. Nh4
Be7 9. h3 Bh5 10. g4 Bg6 11. Nxg6 hxg6 12. Be2
{ This is a typical position arising from the ...c5 followed by Bf5/Bg4 main lines. White has grabbed the bishop pair and has a bit of pressure on the kingside with h4-h5 @@StartBracket@@taking advantage of the g6-hook@@EndBracket@@, however Black's position remains quite solid, and not easy to break. }
12... a6
{ Staying flexible by making a useful non committal move while setting up a small trap.   12...cxd4  This was an alternative.  13.exd4  Qd7  14.O-O-O  O-O-O  ∞  To see how this structure plays out, make sure to check out the model game between Berkes-Nguyen, 2016. }
13. Kf1
{ Preparing to play Kg2 and keeping the h1-rook very active. Black will have a hard time castling short because White usually gets a crushing attack after h4-h5!   13.h4  This is a solid alternative which was recently tried in a high profile game between Aronian,L @@StartBracket@@2781@@EndBracket@@-So,W @@StartBracket@@2770@@EndBracket@@ chess24.com INT 2021.   13.O-O-O ??  This is literally the only thing we need to avoid!  13...cxd4  14.exd4  Nxd4∓  Black wins a free pawn by taking advantage of the pin along the c-file. }
13... Qd7 14. Kg2
{ Now Black has a big decision to make, but none of the options seem very appealing. }
14... Rc8
{ 14...Bd6  Trading the dark squared bishops is generally a good idea for Black, but it's losing a pawn here.  15.Bxd6  Qxd6  16.Qxb7±  With an extra pawn for White because 16...Rb8 will be met by 17.Qxa6   14...O-O  This would have been Black's ideal move, but the problem is that White gets a huge initiative on the kingside.  15.h4!  Threatening to push h5 next.  15...b5  16.h5!  Threatening hxg6.  16...gxh5  17.g5±  After this strong intermezzo we are going to play Rxh5 followed by Rah1 with a deadly attack.   14...O-O-O ?  This would have also not secured Black's king.  15.Qb6!  Threatening to play dxc5 ➼ winning a pawn.  15...cxd4  16.cxd4+-  This move works very well because we are opening up the c-file with big threats such as Rac1 and Bxa6 ➼ White has a completely winning position.   14...c4  Taking space on the queenside.  15.Qc2  b5   15...O-O-O  This is still likely to fall under a huge attack.  16.b3!  Threatening bxc4 ➼ opening up the b-file for the rook.  16...cxb3  17.axb3±  We can continue with b4-b5 ➼ taking advantage of the a6-hook with a powerful initiative on the queenside.  16.h4⩲  Threatening to push h5 on the next move, with the main idea to meet ...gxh5 by going g5! ➼ with good play on the kingside. }
15. h4
{ Threatening to push h5 and the main idea is to meet ...gxh5 with g5! followed by Bxh5! }
15... Na5
{ 15...b5  This would have not stopped White's main plan.  16.h5!  Threatening hxg6.  16...gxh5  17.g5!  Getting rid of the f6-knight so we can recapture with Bxh5!  17...Ne4  18.Nxe4  Getting rid of Black's active knight.  18...dxe4  19.Bxh5⩲  Threatening to play Bg4 next with pressure on the h-file.   15...cxd4  This would have been probably the best try, but Black's position remains difficult to play.  16.exd4  Going for the standard recapture ➼ entering the Carlsbad structure. After this move Black has a choice between ...O-O or going for the slower ...Kf8-Kg8.  16...O-O   16...Bd6  Inviting a bishop trade. This would generally be an amazing trade for Black because the f4-square will become vulnerable.  17.Bg5!  Of course we are keeping the bishops! We never trade unless we can win something.  17...Kf8  Preparing to play ... Kg8!? This could be a clever idea in some positions, keeping the h8-rook as a defensive piece against White's attack.  18.Rae1  Kg8  19.Bf3⩲  We can continue to improve our position with Qd1 followed by Nb3-Nc1-Nd3 and finally playing Ne5!  17.Rae1  Placing the rook on the semi-open file.  17...Bd6  Inviting a bishop trade. This would generally be an amazing trade for Black because the f4-square will become vulnerable.  18.Bg5!  Of course we are keeping the bishops! We never trade unless we can win something.  18...Rfe8  19.h5!  Threatening hxg6!  19...gxh5  20.Bd3→  Threatening Bxf6 followed by Rxh5, this position seems very difficult for Black. Going for the direct 20.Bxf6 gxf6 21.Rxh5 Kg7 would have allowed Black to escape because ...Rh8 is coming with a safe position. }
16. Qd1
{ Sidestepping Black's threat and we could play dxc5 next followed by b4 ➼ with a nasty fork. }
16... cxd4 17. exd4 Bd6
{ Inviting a bishop trade. This would generally be an amazing trade for Black because the f4-square will become vulnerable. }
18. Be3
{ Of course we are keeping the bishops! We never trade unless we can win something. White has a pretty simple plan to go Bf3 followed by Qe2 and break with h5!   18.Bxd6?!  This is a pretty big strategical mistake because it's weakening the f4-square.  18...Qxd6=  Black could easily take over the intiative because of the weak f4-square.   18.Bg5!?  This would have been a solid alternative. }
18... Bb8
{ Preparing to set-up the battery with ...Qd6!? This is a pretty interesting idea because it makes White's h5 push less effective as there will be ...Rh2+ ideas to get counterplay.   18...Ne4!?  This would have been a possible alternative, but I still like White's chances.  19.Nxe4  Getting rid of Black's strong knight.  19...dxe4  20.h5!  Threatening hxg6.  20...gxh5  21.Rxh5!  This works quite well because we can bring the queen next.  21...Rxh5  22.gxh5  Nc6  Bringing back the knight.  23.Qh1⩲  Threatening to play Qh4 next ➼ attacking the e4-pawn and keeping h6-ideas. After this move White has a promising position with the bishop pair. }
19. Bf3 { Preparing to play Qe2. } 19... Qd6 20. Qe2 Nc4
{ 20...Kf8  21.Rae1  Kg8  22.a4  Threatening to expand on the queenside with b4.  22...Nc6  23.Nb3!  Threatening to play Nc5 followed by Nd3.  23...Nd7  24.Nc1⩲  After this important move White is going to play Nd3 followed by Bf4 and g5 ideas. }
21. Nxc4 { Eliminating Black's annoying knight. } 21... Rxc4
{ 21...dxc4??  22.Bxb7+-  Winning a free pawn. } 22. Rac1
{ Overprotecting the c3-pawn because we are preparing to push in the center with b3-c4! }
22... Rc7 23. Bd2
{ Preparing to play b3 and in case of ...b5 White will have a better version after going a4.   23.b3  White probably didn't like the following line.  23...b5  24.a4?!  24.Bd2 would have transposed to the game.  24...bxa4  25.bxa4  Rc4∞  With enough counterplay to hold. }
23... Rd7 24. b3 { Preparing the c4-break. } 24... Ng8
{ Black wants to play ...Ne7-Nc6 followed by the ...e5-break if there is enough time.   24...O-O  Black's main issue is that this move never works!  25.h5!  gxh5  26.g5!  26...Nh7  27.Rxh5+-  With a crushing attack for White.   24...b5  This would have invited another pawn break.  25.a4!  bxa4  26.bxa4⩲  With Rb1 next and White has pressure on the b-file. }
25. c4 { Of course, White strikes immediately in the center. } 25... Ne7
{ 25...dxc4  Taking the pawn was possible, but dangerous.  26.bxc4  Qxd4  27.Rcd1±  With Bg5/Ba5 ideas, White has a dangerous initiative along the b-file because Black's king is stuck in the center. }
26. c5 { Attacking Black's queen and taking space on the queenside. } 26... Qc7
27. b4 { Preparing to expand with a4-b5. } 27... Nc6 28. Bc3
{ Protecting the d4-pawn. } 28... Re7 29. Rce1
{ Keeping an eye on the e5-square. } 29... e5
{ Good or bad, this has to be tried, otherwise Black might never get counterplay if White grabs more space on the queenside with a4-b5. }
30. dxe5 d4
{ Complicating the game.   30...Nxe5?  This would have led to a winning endgame for White after the following forced sequence.  31.Bxe5  Rxe5  32.Qxe5+  Qxe5  33.Rxe5+  Bxe5  34.Bxd5+-  With a winning position for White because the enemy queenside is collapsing. }
31. Bd2 { Keeping the b4-pawn protected. } 31... O-O
{ Finally Black manages to castle relatively safely on move 31!   31...Nxe5  This would have given White a risk free advatange.  32.Bf4  Pinning the e5-knight.  32...Qd7  33.Bxe5  Bxe5  34.c6!  Undermining the a6-pawn!  34...bxc6  35.Qxa6+-  We are going to collect the c6-pawn next, with a winning endgame. }
32. Bf4
{ This keeps a solid advantage, but there was something even stronger.   32.h5!  This would have been the most precise.  32...Nxe5  33.hxg6  Nxg6  34.Be4±  After this important move White is going to play Qf3 followed by Qh3 with a very promising position. }
32... Rd8
{ Missing the chance!   32...Qd7!  Would have been more stubborn.  33.Qc4  Bxe5  34.Bd2⩲  White keeps pressure on the queenside with a4-b5. }
33. Bxc6
{ Approaching a time scramble, White decided to play it safe.   33.h5!  This would have been crushing with precise play, but not easy at all to find/evaluate during the game.  33...d3!  34.Qd2  Nd4  Threatening ...Nxf3 followed by ...Qc6+!  35.Bd1!  This retreating move is giving White a crushing advantage!  35...Qc6+  36.f3±  We can play hxg6 next followed by Re4 and in case the d4-knight leaves, we can activate with Bb3! }
33... Qxc6+ 34. Qf3 d3
{ This is just a time scramble misscalculation.   34...f6!  Would have given reasonable chances for survival, but White was still pushing.  35.Bd2!  Preparing to push f4 after the queen trade.  35...Rxe5  36.Qxc6  bxc6  37.Rxe5  Bxe5  38.f4!  Taking space with tempo!  38...Bc7  39.Kf2⩲  The computer is quite optimistic about Black's chances for survival, but I still like White. We have an interesting idea to play Rh3-Ra3 followed by Ke2-Kd3 and the d4-pawn will be a constant target. }
35. Qxc6 bxc6 36. Bg5 { Forcing a winning endgame! } 36... f6 37. exf6 Rxe1 38.
Rxe1 d2
{ 38...gxf6  39.Bxf6  Rf8  40.g5+-  Winning the d3-pawn with Rd1 coming on the next move. }
39. Bxd2 { Using a small tactical trick before reaching the time control. }
39... gxf6
{ 39...Rxd2  Would have led to a losing rook endgame.  40.Re8+  40...Kf7  41.fxg7!  Not the only move, but a cute intermezzo!  41...Kxg7  42.Rxb8+-  With Rb6 next, White has a completely winning endgame because of the two extra pawns. }
40. Bc3 Kf7 41. Re3 { Preparing to play Rf3. } 41... Rd5 42. Rf3 f5 43. Kf1
{ Bringing the king towards the center. } 43... a5 44. a3
{ Keeping it simple, even tho going 44.bxa5 was also playable. } 44... axb4 45.
axb4 Ke6 46. Ke2 Bc7
{ Black resigned in this position because h5 was coming next. } *

